column6: Severity Level
column7: Including Ascending Severity Levels
column8: Only events with annotation

column6: cleared
column7: TRUE
column8: FALSE

column6: Description
column7: Long Text
column8: Repair Text

column6: unique constraint (%s.%s) violated
column7: An UPDATE or INSERT statement attempted to insert a duplicate key. For Trusted Oracle configured in DBMS MAC mode, you may see this message if a duplicate entry exists at a different level.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either remove the unique restriction or do not insert the key.

column6: session requested to set trace event
column7: The current session was requested to set a trace event by another session.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is used internally; no action is required.

column6: maximum number of sessions exceeded
column7: All session state objects are in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the SESSIONS initialization parameter.

column6: maximum number of session licenses exceeded
column7: All licenses are in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the LICENSE MAX SESSIONS initialization parameter.

column6: maximum number of processes (%s) exceeded
column7: All process state objects are in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the PROCESSES initialization parameter.

column6: session attached to some other process; cannot switch session
column7: The user session is currently used by others.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not switch to a session attached to some other process.

column6: invalid session ID; access denied
column7: Either the session specified does not exist or the caller does not have the privilege to access it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid session ID that you have privilege to access, that is either you own it or you have the CHANGE_USER privilege.

column6: session references process private memory; cannot detach session
column7: An attempt was made to detach the current session when it contains references to process private memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: A session may contain references to process memory (PGA) if it has an open network connection, a very large context area, or operating system privileges. To allow the detach, it may be necessary to close the session's database links and/or cursors. Detaching a session with operating system privileges is always disallowed.

column6: logins from more than one process not allowed in single-process mode
column7: An attempt was made to log in more than once from different processes for Oracle started in single-process mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log off from the other process.

column6: failed to allocate %s
column7: An application failed because Oracle ran out of memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart Oracle with a larger SGA heap.

column6: missing or invalid session ID
column7: The session ID string specified in the ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION command was invalid, or no string was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command with a valid session ID.

column6: cannot kill current session
column7: An attempt was made to use ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION to kill the current session.
column8: From Oracle doc: If it is necessary to kill the current session, do so from another session.

column6: your session has been killed
column7: A privileged user killed the session and it is no longer logged in to the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the database administrator. The administrator may be attempting to perform an operation that requires users to be logged out. When the database administrator announces that the database is available, log in and resume work.

column6: session is not a user session
column7: The session ID specified in an ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION command was not a user session. For example, the session may be recursively started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command with a valid session ID.

column6: User session ID does not exist.
column7: The user session ID no longer exists, probably because the session was logged out.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid session ID.

column6: session marked for kill
column7: The session specified in an ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION command cannot be killed immediately because the session is involved in a non-interruptible operation (for example, rolling back a transaction or being blocked by a network operation). The session has been marked to be killed as soon as possible after the current operation is done.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required for the session to be killed, but further executions of the ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION command on this session may cause the session to be killed sooner.

column6: invalid session migration password
column7: The session migration password specified in a session creation call was invalid (probably too long).
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry with a valid password (less than 30 characters).

column6: current session has empty migration password
column7: An attempt was made to detach or clone the current session and it has an empty migration password. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the session with a non-empty migration password.

column6: cannot %s in current PL/SQL session
column7: An attempt was made to issue a commit or rollback from a PL/SQL object (procedure, function, package) in a session that has this disabled by a ALTER SESSION DISABLE COMMIT IN PROCEDURE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable commits from PL/SQL in this session, or do not attempt to use commit or rollback in PL/SQL when they are disabled in the current session.

column6: LICENSE_MAX_USERS cannot be less than current number of users
column7: Specified values for LICENSE_MAX_USERS is less than the current number of users.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the license limit and drop extra users or purchase more licenses.

column6: maximum number of recursive SQL levels (%s) exceeded
column7: An attempt was made to go more than the specified number of recursive SQL levels.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the recursive SQL, possibly a recursive trigger.

column6: cannot switch to a session belonging to a different server group
column7: An attempt was made to switch to a session in a different server group. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the server switches to a session that belongs to its server group.

column6: Cannot create session: server group belongs to another user
column7: An attempt was made to create a non-migratable session in a server group that is owned by a different user.
column8: From Oracle doc: A server group is owned by the first user who logs into a server in the server group in non-migratable mode. All subsequent non-migratable mode logins must be made by the user who owns the server group. To have a different user log in in non-migratable mode, the ownership of the server group will have to be changed. This can be done by logging off all current sessions and detaching from all existing servers in the server group and then having the new user login to become the new owner.

column6: operating system error occurred while obtaining an enqueue
column7: Could not obtain the operating system resources necessary to cover an Oracle enqueue. This is normally the result of an operating system user quota that is too low.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look up the operating system error in your system documentation and perform the needed action.

column6: timeout occurred while waiting for a resource
column7: This message is usually caused by an instance that has terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart any non-recovered instances.

column6: maximum number of enqueue resources (%s) exceeded
column7: Ran out of enqueue resources.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the ENQUEUE_RESOURCES initialization parameter.

column6: maximum number of enqueues exceeded
column7: Ran out of enqueue state objects.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the ENQUEUES initialization parameter.

column6: resource busy and acquire with NOWAIT specified
column7: The NOWAIT keyword forced a return to the command prompt because a resource was unavailable for a LOCK TABLE or SELECT FOR UPDATE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try the command after a few minutes or enter the command without the NOWAIT keyword.

column6: maximum number of DML locks exceeded
column7: Ran out of DML lock state objects.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the DML_LOCKS initialization parameter and restart Oracle.

column6: DDL lock on object '%s.%s' is already held in an incompatible mode
column7: The attempted lock is incompatible with the DDL lock already held on the object. This happens if you attempt to drop a table that has parse locks.
column8: From Oracle doc: Before attempting to drop a table, check that it has no parse locks. Wait a few minutes before retrying the operation.

column6: maximum number of temporary table locks exceeded
column7: The number of temporary tables equals or exceeds the number of temporary table locks. Temporary tables are often created by large sorts.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the TEMPORARY_TABLE_LOCKS initialization parameter and restart Oracle.

column6: DB_BLOCK_SIZE must be %s to mount this database (not %s)
column7:
The value of the DB_BLOCK_SIZE initialization parameter used to start this database does not match the value used when that database was created. Potential reasons for this mismatch are:

mounting the wrong database 

using the wrong initialization parameter file 

the value of the DB_BLOCK_SIZE parameter was changed
column8:
From Oracle doc: For one of the above causes, either:

mount the correct database 

use the correct initialization parameter file 

correct the value of the DB_BLOCK_SIZE parameter

column6: maximum number of DB_FILES exceeded
column7: The value of the DB_FILES initialization parameter was exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the DB_FILES parameter and restart Oracle.

column6: deadlock detected while waiting for resource
column7: Your session and another session are waiting for a resource locked by the other. This condition is known as a deadlock. To resolve the deadlock, one or more statements were rolled back for the other session to continue work.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Either:

Enter a ROLLBACK statement and re-execute all statements since the last commit or 

Wait until the lock is released, possibly a few minutes, and then re-execute the rolled back statements.

column6: another instance has a different DML_LOCKS setting
column7: The shared instance being started is using DML locks, and the running instances are not, or vice-versa.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Either:

Do not use DML_LOCKS by setting DML_LOCKS to zero at all instances or 

Use DML_LOCKS by setting DML_LOCKS to a positive integer at all instances.

column6: DML full-table lock cannot be acquired; DML_LOCKS is 0
column7: The instance was started with the value of DML_LOCKS set to zero, and the statement being executed needs a full-table lock (S, X, or SSX).
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance with DML_LOCKS not equal to zero, and re-execute the statement.

column6: maximum number of LOG_FILES exceeded
column7: The value of the LOG_FILES initialization parameter was exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the LOG_FILES initialization parameter and restart Oracle. The value of the parameter needs to be as large as the highest number of log files that currently exist rather than just the count of logs that exist.

column6: object is too large to allocate on this O/S (%s,%s)
column7: An initialization parameter was set to a value that required allocating more contiguous space than can be allocated on this operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the value of the initialization parameter.

column6: initialization of FIXED_DATE failed
column7: The FIXED_DATE string was not in date format yyyy-mm-dd:hh24:mi:ss.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the initialization parameter is in the correct date format.

column6: LOG_FILES is %s but needs to be %s to be compatible
column7: The maximum number of log files supported by this instance is not the same as for the other instances. All instances must be able to open all the files any instance can open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of the LOG_FILES initialization parameter to be compatible.

column6: invalid value %s for parameter %s; must be at least %s
column7: The value for the initialization parameter is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a value as indicated by the message.

column6: invalid value %s for parameter %s, must be between %s and %s
column7: The value for the initialization parameter is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a value as indicated by the message.

column6: cannot acquire lock -- table locks disabled for %s
column7: A command was issued that tried to lock the table indicated in the message. Examples of commands that can lock tables are: LOCK TABLE, ALTER TABLE... ADD (...), and so on.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the ALTER TABLE... ENABLE TABLE LOCK command, and retry the command.

column6: command %s is not valid
column7: An invalid debugger command was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Type HELP to see the list of available commands.

column6: process number must be between 1 and %s
column7: An invalid process number was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid process number.

column6: process "%s" is not active
column7: An invalid process was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid process.

column6: command %s takes between %s and %s argument(s)
column7: An incorrect number of arguments was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct number of arguments. Type HELP to see the list of commands and their syntax.

column6: no process has been specified
column7: No debug process has been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid process.

column6: process "%s" not found in this instance
column7: The specified process was not logged on to the current instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid process.

column6: dump %s not found
column7: An attempt was made to invoke a dump that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Type DUMPLIST to see the list of available dumps.

column6: dump %s is not valid
column7: An attempt was made to invoke an invalid dump.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try another dump.

column6: cannot dump variables by name
column7: An attempt was made to dump a variable by name on a system that does not support this feature.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try the PEEK command.

column6: variable %s not found
column7: An attempt was made to dump a variable that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid variable name.

column6: invalid global area specified by level %s
column7: An attempt was made to dump an invalid global area.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use level 1 for the PGA, 2 for the SGA, and 3 for the UGA. Use extra + level to dump global area level as well as extra bytes for every pointer; extra must be a multiple of 4.

column6: address range [%s, %s) is not readable
column7: An attempt was made to read/write an invalid memory address range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try another address or length.

column6: memory size of %s is not in valid set of [1], [2], [4]stringstringstringstring%s
column7: An invalid length was specified for the POKE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid length (either 1, 2, 4, or possibly 8).

column6: warning: possibly corrupt SGA mapped
column7: Even though there may be SGA corruptions, the SGA was mapped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the DUMPSGA command to dump the SGA.

column6: global area must be PGA, SGA, or UGA
column7: An attempt was made to dump an invalid global area.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either PGA, SGA, or UGA.

column6: current call does not exist
column7: An invalid attempt was made to dump the current call heap.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the process starts a call.

column6: user call does not exist
column7: An invalid attempt was made to dump the user call heap.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the process starts a call.

column6: command cannot be executed on remote instance
column7: An OPS command was issued for a non-OPS ORADEBUG command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue the command without the OPS syntax.

column6: command cannot be executed by MTS server
column7: A debug command was issued on an MTS server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the command using a dedicated server.

column6: invalid instance number in ORADEBUG command
column7: An invalid instance number was specified in an OPS ORADEBUG command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the command with valid instance numbers.

column6: failed to allocate memory for OPS ORADEBUG command
column7: Could not allocate the memory needed to execute parallel ORADEBUG.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the command on each instance with single-instance ORADEBUG.

column6: LARGE_POOL_SIZE must be at least %s
column7: The value of LARGE_POOL_SIZE is below the minimum size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of LARGE_POOL_SIZE past the minimum size.

column6: LARGE_POOL_SIZE must be greater than LARGE_POOL_MIN_ALLOC
column7: The value of LARGE_POOL_SIZE is less than the value of LARGE_POOL_MIN_ALLOC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of LARGE_POOL_SIZE past the value of LARGE_POOL_MIN_ALLOC.

column6: %s must be between %s and %s
column7: The parameter value is not in a valid range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the parameter value to be within the specified range.

column6: %s requires an integer value
column7: The parameter value is not an integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the parameter value to be an integer.

column6: invalid value %s for parameter %s, must be from among %s
column7: The value for the initialization parameter is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a value as indicated by the message.

column6: use of Oracle SQL feature not in SQL92 %s Level
column7: An attempt was made to use an Oracle SQL feature that is not compliant with the SQL92 standard.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the feature or use the ALTER SESSION SET FLAGGER command to set the appropriate level of SQL92 compliance.

column6: timed out while waiting for resource, potential PDML deadlock
column7: The resource needed by the transaction was busy. The PDML transaction could not acquire the resource within the specified amount of time. This indicates potential deadlock involving this PDML transaction and other transactions currently running in the system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the PARALLEL_TRANSACTION_RESOURCE_TIMEOUT parameter; then retry the operation.

column6: no data found
column7: An application made a reference to unknown or inaccessible data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Handle this condition within the application or make appropriate modifications to the application code.

column6: invalid specification for system parameter MTS_DISPATCHERS
column7: The syntax for the MTS_DISPATCHERS parameter is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter the MTS_DISPATCHERS parameter into the initialization parameter file with the correct syntax and then shut down and restart the instance.

column6: network protocol %s cannot be used by dispatchers
column7: The network specified in MTS_DISPATCHERS does not have the functionality required by the dispatchers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to your Oracle operating system-specific documentation for network protocols supported by the dispatchers.

column6: invalid network protocol; reserved for use by dispatchers
column7: The network specified in the Net8 connect string is reserved for use by the dispatchers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify other network protocols in the connection string.

column6: deadlock detected; all public servers blocked waiting for resources
column7: All available public servers are servicing requests that require resources locked by a client which is unable to get a public server to release the resources.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the limit for the system parameter MTS_MAX_SERVERS as the system will automatically start new servers to break the deadlock until the number of servers reaches the value specified in MTS_MAX_SERVERS.

column6: dispatching mechanism not configured for network protocol %s
column7: An attempt was made to alter the dispatcher's configuration for a network protocol that was not specified in the INIT.ORA file.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Do one of the following:

Include the network protocol in the definition for the MTS_DISPATCHERS initialization parameter and restart the system. 

Use the ALTER SYSTEM SET MTS_DISPATCHERS command with a network protocol that exists in the initialization parameter file.

column6: cannot startup/shutdown database when connected to a dispatcher
column7: An attempt was made to start or shut down an instance while connected to a shared server via a dispatcher.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reconnect as user INTERNAL without going through the dispatcher. For most cases, this can be done by connect to INTERNAL without specifying a network connect string.

column6: failed to connect to ORACLE listener process
column7: Most likely due to the fact that the network listener process has not been started.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Check for the following:

The network configuration file is not set up correctly. 

The client side address is not specified correctly. 

The listener initialization parameter file is not set up correctly.

column6: failed to set up dispatcher to accept connection asynchronously
column7: The network protocol used by the dispatcher does not support asynchronous operations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: no servers started because number of servers is limited to %s
column7: An attempt was made to start more servers than the maximum number specified by the system parameter MTS_MAX_SERVERS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the MTS_MAX_SERVERS initialization parameter as needed or re-issue the ALTER SYSTEM SET MTS_SERVERS command with an appropriate number of servers.

column6: only created up to %s (maximum specified) dispatchers
column7: An attempt was made to start more dispatchers than the maximum number specified by the system parameter MTS_MAX_DISPATCHERS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the MTS_MAX_DISPATCHERS initialization parameter as needed.

column6: protocol name %s is too long
column7: A protocol name specified in the MTS_DISPATCHERS initialization parameter is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid protocol name for the MTS_DISPATCHERS value.

column6: missing value for system parameter MTS_SERVICE
column7: No value was specified for the MTS_SERVICE initialization parameter, nor for the DB_NAME parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add an MTS_SERVICE or DB_NAME definition to the initialization file. By default, MTS_SERVICE is the value of DB_NAME unless MTS_SERVICE is explicitly specified.

column6: connection refused; dispatcher connection table is full
column7: A connection request was refused by a dispatcher because the dispatcher cannot support any more connections.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect to a different dispatcher or use a dedicated server.

column6: MTS_SERVICE name is too long
column7: The service name specified in the MTS_SERVICE initialization parameter is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a shorter name for the MTS_SERVICE value (less than or equal to 255 characters).

column6: value out of range for system parameter MTS_SERVERS
column7: The specified value of the MTS_SERVERS parameter is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: MTS_SERVERS must be greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to the value of MTS_MAX_SERVERS.

column6: value out of range for system parameter MTS_DISPATCHERS
column7: The value of the MTS_DISPATCHERS parameter is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: The sum of all MTS_DISPATCHERS values must be greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to the value of MTS_MAX_DISPATCHERS.

column6: invalid specification for system parameter MTS_LISTENER_ADDRESS
column7: The syntax for the MTS_LISTENER_ADDRESS parameter is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the Oracle8i Reference manual for the correct syntax.

column6: dispatching mechanism not enabled or installed
column7: Either the dispatching mechanism was not enabled or the Oracle executable image was not installed with the dispatching mechanism.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide and your operating system-specific documentation for procedures for starting and configuration the dispatcher process.

column6: MTS_SERVERS specified without MTS_DISPATCHERS
column7: A definition for MTS_SERVERS was specified in the INIT.ORA file, but no definition for MTS_DISPATCHERS was specified. Without a value for MTS_DISPATCHERS, shared servers will never be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add a definition for MTS_DISPATCHERS in the INIT.ORA file (or take out the definition for MTS_SERVERS, if MTS is not being used).

column6: cannot initialize network configuration
column7: Oracle could not initialize Net8.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying messages.

column6: idle public server terminating
column7: Too many idle servers were waiting on the common queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error is used internally, no action is required.

column6: MTS_DISPATCHERS specified without MTS_MAX_SERVERS
column7: A definition for MTS_DISPATCHERS was specified in the INIT.ORA file, but MTS_MAX_SERVERS was specified as zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify MTS_MAX_SERVERS to be greater than zero.

column6: connection refused; invalid presentation
column7: The PRESENTATION in the CONNECT_DATA of the TNS address DESCRIPTION is not correct or is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the PRESENTATION specified in the TNS address.

column6: connection refused; invalid duplicity
column7: The DUPLICITY in the CONNECT_DATA of the TNS address DESCRIPTION is not correct or is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the DUPLICITY specified in the TNS address.

column6: dispatcher %s does not exist
column7: There is currently no dispatcher running with the specified name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry with a name of the form "D###" denoting an existing dispatcher process.

column6: this command requires a dispatcher name
column7: Wrong syntax for ALTER SYSTEM SHUTDOWN.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Use correct syntax:

ALTER SYSTEM SHUTDOWN [ IMMEDIATE ] 'dispatcher name'

column6: duplicate transaction ID
column7: An attempt was made to start a new transaction with an ID already in use by an existing transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your application.

column6: invalid transaction ID
column7: The specified transaction ID does not correspond to an existing valid transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your application.

column6: current session does not match requested session
column7: The current session is not the same as the session that was passed into a UPIXADO() call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your application.

column6: internal error in XA library
column7: The XA library could not access thread-specific pointers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: protocol error in transaction monitor
column7: The transaction monitor returned TMJOIN on an AX_REG call but the transaction was locally suspended.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the transaction monitor customer support.

column6: cannot perform work outside of global transaction
column7: The application tried to perform some work on an Oracle 7.3 server outside of a global transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if the application is connected to an Oracle 7.3 server. The Transaction monitor must not return a NULL XID on an AX_REG call when the resource manager is Oracle 7.3.

column6: global transaction length %s is greater than maximum (%s)
column7: An external global transaction ID with a too large length field was passed in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the problem to your external transaction coordinator vendor.

column6: transaction branch length %s is illegal (maximum allowed %s)
column7: An external transaction branch ID with a length either too large or 0 was passed in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the problem to your external transaction coordinator vendor.

column6: external dbid length %s is greater than maximum (%s)
column7: An external database name with too large a length field was passed in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the problem to your external transaction coordinator vendor.

column6: internal database name length %s is greater than maximum (%s)
column7: An internal database name with a too large length field was passed in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the problem to your external transaction coordinator vendor.

column6: controlfile could not be created
column7: It was not possible to create the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that there is sufficient disk space and no conflicts in file names and try to create the control file again.

column6: controlfile version %s incompatible with ORACLE version %s
column7: The control file was created by incompatible software.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either restart with a compatible software release or use CREATE CONTROLFILE to create a new control file that is compatible with this release.

column6: controlfile: '%s'
column7: This message reports the name file involved in other messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: See associated error messages for a description of the problem.

column6: using the wrong controlfiles
column7: The mount ID in the control file is not the same as the mount ID in the control file used by the first instance to mount this database. The control files are for the same database but they are not the same files. Most likely one instance is using a backup control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the correct control files were specified.

column6: error in reading (block %s, # blocks %s) of controlfile
column7: A disk I/O failure was detected on reading the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the disk is online. If it is not, bring it online and shut down and restart Oracle. If it is online, then look for operating system reasons for Oracle's inability to read the disk or control file. See the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for information on recovering from the loss of a control file. See also your operation system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: error in identifying controlfile, check alert log for more info
column7: The system could not find a control file of the specified name and size.
column8:
From Oracle doc: One of the following:

Check that the proper control file name is referenced in the CONTROL_FILES initialization parameter in the initialization parameter file and try again. 

When using mirrored control files, that is, more than one control file is referenced in the initialization parameter file, remove the control file name listed in the message from the initialization parameter file and restart the instance. If the message does not recur, remove the problem control file from the initialization parameter file and create another copy of the control file with a new file name in the initialization parameter file.

column6: error in writing (block %s, # blocks %s) of controlfile
column7: A disk I/O failure was detected on writing to the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the disk is online. If it is not, bring it online and shut down and restart Oracle. If it is online, then look for operating system reasons for Oracle's inability to write to the disk or control file. See the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for information on recovering from the loss of a control file. See also your operation system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: controlfiles are not for the same database
column7: The database ID in the control file is not the same as the database ID in the control file used by the first instance to mount this database. Most likely one of the mounts used the wrong control file or there are two databases with the same name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the control file is for the correct database and is not an old version. When using multiplexed control files, that is, more than one control file is referenced in the initialization parameter file, remove the control file name listed in the message from the initialization parameter file and restart the instance. If the message does not recur, remove the problem control file from the initialization parameter file and create another copy of the control file using a new file name in the initialization parameter file.

column6: number of controlfile names exceeds limit of %s
column7: An attempt was made to use more control files than Oracle supports.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down Oracle. Reduce the number of control files specified in the CONTROL_FILES parameter in the initialization parameter file, and restart Oracle. Delete unused files.

column6: control file blocksize mismatch, check alert log for more info
column7: The block size in the control file header does not match the size specified in the DB_BLOCK_SIZE parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the block size to the amount specified in the message and try again.

column6: cannot open the specified controlfile
column7: Cannot open the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure the control file exists and is not locked by some other program.

column6: controlfile does not match previous controlfiles
column7: A control file was specified that belongs to another database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find and install the correct control file.

column6: block size %s below minimum required size of %s bytes
column7: The block size specified was too small. Space for the system overhead is required.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a larger block size and retry the operation.

column6: cannot reuse controlfile; old file size %s, %s required
column7: To reuse a control file, it must be the same size as the one previously used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either do not specify REUSE, or specify a matching combination of MAXDATAFILES, MAXLOGFILES, MAXLOGMEMBERS, MAXLOGHISTORY, and MAXINSTANCES clauses in the CREATE DATABASE or CREATE CONTROLFILE statement.

column6: controlfile '%s' version %s inconsistent with file '%s' version %s
column7: An inconsistent set of control files, datafiles, and redo log files was used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a consistent set of control files, datafiles, and redo log files. That is, all the files must be for the same database and from the same time period.

column6: must be at least one controlfile
column7: No control file is specified or the control file specified does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify at least one valid control file and retry the operation.

column6: controlfile could not be resized for migration from 8.0.2
column7: Control files created by release 8.0.2 were missing some records. These records are automatically added by resizing the control file when attempting to run a later release. The resize failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look in the alert log for the reason that the resize failed. If it can be fixed by giving the control file more space, then do that. Otherwise, use the CREATE CONTROLFILE script dumped to the trace file to create a new control file.

column6: block size %s of controlfile does not match DB_BLOCK_SIZE (%s)
column7: The block size as stored in the control file header is different from the value of the initialization parameter DB_BLOCK_SIZE. This might be due to an incorrect setting of DB_BLOCK_SIZE, or else might indicate that the control file has either been corrupted or belongs to a different database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a good copy of the control file.

column6: required controlfile size %s exceeds maximum allowable size %s
column7: An invocation of CREATE DATABASE, CREATE CONTROLFILE, cfileCalcSizeList, or cfileCalcSizeArray was executed specifying a combination of parameters that would require the control file size in blocks to exceed the maximum allowable value.
column8: From Oracle doc: In the case of CREATE DATABASE or CREATE CONTROLFILE, use a different combination of MAXDATAFILES, MAXLOGFILES, MAXLOGMEMBERS, MAXLOGHISTORY, and MAXINSTANCES clauses. In the case of cfileCalcSizeList() or cfileCalcSizeArray(), use a different combination of record type counts.

column6: controlfile not mounted by first instance, check alert log for more info
column7: The specified control file has a different mount ID than the other control files that are being mounted. This means that the first instance to mount the database did not use this control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find and install the correct control file.

column6: error on write to controlfile
column7: An error occurred when writing to one or more of the control files.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying messages.

column6: operation would reuse name of a currently mounted controlfile
column7: The file name supplied as a parameter to the ALTER DATABASE BACKUP CONTROLFILE command or to cfileSetSnapshotName matches the name of the specified currently mounted control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation with a different file name.

column6: convert file is invalid or incorrect version
column7: An Oracle7 to Oracle8 convert file contains invalid data or was created with an different version of the migration utility. This error can also be caused by incorrect ORACLE_HOME environment variable when the ALTER DATABASE CONVERT command is issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a correct version of the convert file or regenerate it with the migration utility. Make sure that the migration utility is the same version as the Oracle8 RDBMS executable and that the ORACLE_HOME environment variable is properly set.

column6: controlfile resize attempted with illegal record type (%s)
column7: An attempt was made to expand or shrink the control file by calling cfileResizeSection using an invalid value for the RECORD_TYPE parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a value for the RECORD_TYPE parameter that specifies a valid record type other than type 0 (valid range is 1 to 16).

column6: expected size %s of controlfile differs from actual size %s
column7: The expected size of the control file as stored in its header was different than the actual operating system file size. This usually indicates that the control file was corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a good copy of the control file.

column6: operation disallowed while alternate controlfile open
column7: The attempted operation could not be executed at this time because this process had an alternate control file open for fixed table access.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation after calling cfileUseCurrent.

column6: corrupt block detected in controlfile: (block %s, # blocks %s)
column7: A block header corruption or checksum error was detected on reading the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the CREATE CONTROLFILE or RECOVER DATABASE USING BACKUP CONTROLFILE command.

column6: length of alternate controlfile name exceeds maximum of %s
column7: The specified file name, which was supplied as a parameter to cfileSetSnapshotName or cfileUseCopy, exceeds the maximum file name length for this operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation with a shorter file name.

column6: operation disallowed: already hold snapshot controlfile enqueue
column7: The attempted operation cannot be executed at this time because this process currently holds the snapshot control file enqueue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation after calling cfileUseCurrent to release the snapshot control file enqueue.

column6: operation disallowed: snapshot controlfile enqueue unavailable
column7: The attempted operation cannot be executed at this time because another process currently holds the snapshot control file enqueue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation after the concurrent operation that is holding the snapshot control file enqueue terminates.

column6: snapshot controlfile has not been named
column7: During an invocation of cfileMakeAndUseSnapshot or cfileUseSnapshot, it was detected that no file name for the snapshot control file had previously been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a name for the snapshot control file by calling cfileSetSnapshotName.

column6: snapshot controlfile is nonexistent, corrupt, or unreadable
column7: The snapshot control file was found to be non-existent, corrupt, or unreadable during an invocation of cfileUseSnapshot.
column8: From Oracle doc: Call cfileMakeAndUseSnapshot again (or for the first time).

column6: copy controlfile is corrupt or unreadable
column7: The specified copy control file was found to be corrupt or unreadable during an invocation of cfileUseCopy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Before retrying cfileUseCopy, use the ALTER DATABASE BACKUP CONTROLFILE command and specify the same file name that was specified for cfileUseCopy.

column6: error in identifying or opening snapshot or copy controlfile
column7: A snapshot or copy control file of the specified name could not be found or opened during an invocation of cfileUseSnapshot, cfileMakeAndUseSnapshot, or cfileUseCopy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the snapshot or copy control file using cfileMakeAndUseSnapshot or ALTER DATABASE BACKUP CONTROLFILE, respectively.

column6: controlfile fixed table inconsistent due to concurrent update
column7: Concurrent update activity on a control file caused a query on a control file fixed table to read inconsistent information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation.

column6: snapshot operation disallowed: mounted controlfile is a backup
column7: Attempting to invoke cfileSetSnapshotName, cfileMakeAndUseSnapshot, or cfileUseSnapshot when the currently mounted control file is a backup control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount a current control file and retry the operation.

column6: snapshot operation disallowed: controlfile newly created
column7: An attempt to invoke cfileMakeAndUseSnapshot with a currently mounted control file that was newly created with CREATE CONTROLFILE was made.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount a current control file and retry the operation.

column6: operation would reuse a filename that is part of the database
column7: The file name supplied as a parameter to the ALTER DATABASE BACKUP CONTROLFILE command or to cfileSetSnapshotName matches the name of a file that is currently part of the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation with a different file name.

column6: archiver not started
column7: An attempt was made to stop automatic archiving, but the archiver process was not running.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST cannot be the same destination as %s %s
column7: The destination specified by the LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST parameter is the same as the destination specified by an ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG START TO command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different destination for parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST, or specify a different destination with the ALTER SYSTEM command.

column6: log %s of thread %s is empty, cannot archive
column7: A log must be used for redo generation before it can be archived. The specified redo log was not been used since it was introduced to the database. However, it is possible that the instance died during a log switch and the log was empty.
column8: From Oracle doc: Empty logs do not need to be archived. Do not attempt to archive the redo log file.

column6: character limit %s exceeded by archive destination %s %s
column7: The destination specified by an ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG START TO command was too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the ALTER SYSTEM command using a string shorter than the limit specified in the error message.

column6: error in archive control %s '%s'
column7: The specified archive log location is invalid in the archive command or the LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST initialization parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the archive string used to make sure it refers to a valid online device.

column6: error archiving log %s of thread %s, sequence # %s
column7: An error occurred during archiving.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying message stack for more detailed information. If the online log is corrupted, then the log can be cleared using the UNARCHIVED option. This will make any existing backups useless for recovery to any time after the log was created, but will allow the database to generate redo.

column6: cannot translate archive destination %s %s
column7: The destination specified by an ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG START TO command could not be translated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying message stack for more detailed information. Then, retry the ALTER SYSTEM command using a different string.

column6: archiver error. Connect internal only, until freed.
column7: The archiver process received an error while trying to archive a redo log. If the problem is not resolved soon, the database will stop executing transactions. The most likely cause of this message is the destination device is out of space to store the redo log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the archiver trace file for a detailed description of the problem. Also, verify that the device specified in the initialization parameter ARCHIVE_LOG_DEST is set up properly for archiving.

column6: manual archiving in NOARCHIVELOG mode must identify log
column7: The database is in NOARCHIVELOG mode and a command to manually archive a log did not specify the log explicitly by sequence number, group number or file name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the log by file name, by group number or by thread and sequence number.

column6: log %s of open thread %s is the current log, cannot archive
column7: An attempt was made to archive the current log of an open thread. This is not allowed because the redo log file may still be in use for the generation of redo entries.
column8: From Oracle doc: Force a log switch in the instance where the thread is open. If no instances are open, open the database so that instance recovery can recover the thread.

column6: cannot find online log sequence %s for thread %s
column7:
The log sequence number supplied in the ARCHIVE statement does not match any of the online logs for the thread. This can result from any of the following situations:

The log might have been reused for another sequence number. 

The log might have been dropped. 

The sequence number might be greater than the current log sequence number. 

The thread might not have any logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the ARCHIVE statement, then specify a valid log sequence number. Specify a valid log sequence number.

column6: log %s of thread %s is being archived or modified
column7: The log is either being archived by another process or an administrative command is modifying the log. Operations that modify the log include clearing, adding a member, dropping a member, renaming a member, and dropping the log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the current operation to complete and try again.

column6: current log %s of closed thread %s cannot switch
column7: The log cannot be cleared or manually archived because it is the current log of a closed thread, and it is not possible to switch logs so another log is current. All other logs for the thread need to be archived, or cleared, and cannot be reused.
column8: From Oracle doc: Archive another log in the same thread first, or complete the clearing. See attached errors for the reason the switch cannot be completed.

column6: there are no logs that need archiving for thread %s
column7: An attempt was made to manually archive the unarchived logs in this thread but no logs needed archiving.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: no recovery required
column7: An attempt was made to perform media recovery on files that do not need any type of recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to perform media recovery on the selected files. Check to see that the file names were entered properly. If not, retry the command with the proper file names.

column6: instance recovery required, cannot set ARCHIVELOG mode
column7: The database either crashed or was shut down with the ABORT option. Media recovery cannot be enabled because the online logs may not be sufficient to recover the current datafiles.
column8: From Oracle doc: Open the database and then enter the SHUTDOWN command with the NORMAL or IMMEDIATE option.

column6: name of archived log file needed
column7: During media recovery, the name of an archived redo log file was requested, but no name was entered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount the correct redo log file and enter its name when it is requested.

column6: name of archived log file not needed
column7: During media recovery, the name of an archived redo log file was entered, but no name was requested.
column8: From Oracle doc: Continue media recovery, but do not enter a new log name.

column6: specified log file does not exist '%s'
column7: The given redo log file does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling and capitalization of the file name and retry the command.

column6: specified log file is part of thread %s not %s
column7: The given redo log file is not part of the given thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the thread of the redo log file matches the thread on the command line. If not, use a redo log file from the appropriate thread. Retry the command after correcting the error.

column6: error creating archive log %s
column7: An error was encountered when either creating or opening the destination file for archiving.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the archive destination is valid and that there is sufficient space on the destination device.

column6: there are no logs that need archiving
column7: An attempt was made to archive the unarchived redo log files manually, but there are no files that need to be archived.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: error writing archive log %s
column7: An I/O error occurred while archiving a redo log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the output device is still available and correct any device errors that may have occurred. Also, make certain that sufficient space for archiving is available on the output device.

column6: media recovery of direct load data that was not logged
column7: A media recovery session encountered a table that was loaded by the direct loader without logging any redo information. Some or all of the blocks in this table are now marked as corrupt.
column8: From Oracle doc: The table must be dropped or truncated so that the corrupted blocks can be reused. If a more recent backup of the file is available, try to recover this file to eliminate this error.

column6: illegal recovery option %s
column7: An illegal option was specified for a recovery command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax and retry the command.

column6: media recovery has already been started
column7: An attempt was made to start a second media recovery operation in the same session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete or cancel the first media recovery session or start another session to perform media recovery.

column6: CHANGE keyword specified but no change number given
column7: The CHANGE keyword was specified on the command line, but no change number was given.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command using a valid change number after the CHANGE keyword.

column6: illegal option to the UNTIL recovery flag %s
column7: Only CANCEL, CHANGE and TIME can be used with the UNTIL keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: log file '%s' no longer needed for this recovery
column7: The specified redo log file is no longer needed for the current recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required. The archived redo log file may be removed from its current location to conserve disk space, if needed. However, the redo log file may still be required for another recovery session in the future.

column6: change %s generated at %s needed for thread %s
column7: The requested log is required to proceed with recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the requested log with ALTER DATABASE RECOVER LOGFILE filename or cancel recovery with ALTER DATABASE RECOVER CANCEL.

column6: change %s for thread %s is in sequence #%s
column7: This message helps to locate the redo log file with the specified change number requested by other messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the information provided in this message to specify the required archived redo log files for other errors.

column6: media recovery may not be performed using dispatcher
column7: An attempt was made to use a dispatcher process for media recovery. Memory requirements disallow this recovery method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect to the instance via a dedicated server process to perform media recovery.

column6: UPI %s call not supported, use ALTER DATABASE RECOVER
column7: The given UPI call is no longer supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the ALTER DATABASE RECOVER command for all recovery actions.

column6: recovery session canceled due to errors
column7: An error during recovery was determined to be fatal enough to end the current recovery session.
column8: From Oracle doc: More specific messages will accompany this message. Refer to the other messages for the appropriate action.

column6: recovery session still in progress
column7: An error during recovery was determined to be minor enough to allow the current recovery session to continue.
column8: From Oracle doc: More specific messages will accompany this message. Refer to the other messages for the appropriate action.

column6: TIME not given as a %s constant
column7: UNTIL TIME was not followed by a string constant for the time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter the time enclosed in single quotation marks.

column6: no members available, or no member contains valid data
column7: None of the members of a redo log file group are available, or the available members do not contain complete data.
column8: From Oracle doc: If a member is temporarily offline, attempt to make it available. Make sure that the correct file names are being used, especially if the redo log file is being accessed from a remote location.

column6: specified change number %s not found in thread %s
column7: The given change number does not appear in any of the online redo logs for the given thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement to make certain a valid change number is given. Perhaps try to use the NEXT option for archiving logs.

column6: to continue recovery type ALTER DATABASE RECOVER CONTINUE
column7: During media recovery, a new log is not required but the continuation command is necessary to do a checkpoint and report errors.
column8: From Oracle doc: Type ALTER DATABASE RECOVER CONTINUE and recovery will resume.

column6: suggestion : %s
column7: This message reports the next redo log file name that is needed, according to the initialization parameters LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST and LOG_ARCHIVE_FORMAT. This message assumes that LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST and LOG_ARCHIVE_FORMAT are the same now as when the required redo log file was archived.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consider using this file name for the next log needed for recovery.

column6: operating system archival error occurred. See error below
column7: While attempting to archive to a redo log file, the server encountered an unexpected operating system error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the operating system error given in the messages and retry the operation. See also your operating system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: numeric value required for PARALLEL option
column7: A recovery command was specified incorrectly. The PARALLEL option must be followed by a numeric argument that specifies the degree of parallelism.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-enter the command with a numeric argument specifying the degree of parallelism desired.

column6: parallel recovery feature not installed
column7: A parallel recovery was requested when the parallel recovery option is not installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Delete the PARALLEL clause from the RECOVER command. Also, delete the RECOVERY_PARALLELISM parameter in the initialization file.

column6: controlfile out of sync with redo log
column7: The redo log file and control file are out of sync because a non-current control file was specified when the instance was started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the RECOVER command using the current control file, or retry the RECOVER command using the USING BACKUP CONTROLFILE clause.

column6: invalid archivelog format specifier '%s'
column7: An invalid format specifier was found in the LOG_ARCHIVE_FORMAT initialization parameter. The only characters permitted for string are s, S, t, and T.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the initialization file and restart the instance.

column6: datafile number %s is invalid, must be between 1 and %s
column7: An invalid file number was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a correct datafile number and retry the operation.

column6: maximum number of files (%s) exceeded for RECOVER DATAFILE LIST
column7: The RECOVER DATAFILE LIST command specified more datafiles than are allowed by the DB_FILES initialization parameter. This error occurs when doing recovery with Recovery Manager, and the instance has been started with a DB_FILES parameter specifying fewer datafiles than Recovery Manager needs to recover to satisfy the user's RECOVER command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance with a higher value for DB_FILES.

column6: must specify RECOVER DATAFILE LIST before RECOVER DATAFILE START
column7: The RECOVER DATAFILE START command was issued, but no RECOVER DATAFILE LIST commands had been issued. This only happens when doing recovery with Recovery Manager, and is an internal error in Recovery Manager, because Recovery Manager should always issue RECOVER DATAFILE LIST before RECOVER DATAFILE START.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Missing or invalid TIMEOUT interval
column7: A non-zero integer timeout interval (in minutes) must be specified after the TIMEOUT keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax and retry the command.

column6: illegal redo log block size %s specified - exceeds limit of %s
column7: The specified block size of the redo log is greater than the maximum block size for the operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the redo log on a device with a smaller block size.

column6: error in adding log file '%s' - file cannot be created
column7: The creation of the redo log file failed
column8:
From Oracle doc: Check whether:

There is enough storage space on the device 

The name of the file is valid 

The device is online 

An I/O error occurred 

Also, it is possible REUSE was specified on the command line and a file of the incorrect size exists. Either do not specify REUSE or use a file of the correct size.

column6: limit of %s logs exceeded
column7: The maximum number of redo log files has been exceeded. There is a limit, set at database creation, on the number of redo log files (typically 16).
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the CREATE CONTROLFILE command with a larger value for MAXLOGFILES.

column6: requested INSTANCE_NUMBER is busy
column7: An instance tried to start by using a value of the initialization parameter INSTANCE_NUMBER that is already in use.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Either:

Specify another INSTANCE_NUMBER, 

Shut down the running instance with this number, or 

Wait for instance recovery to complete on the instance with this number.

column6: log %s of thread %s inconsistent; belongs to another database
column7: The database ID in the redo log file does not match the database ID in the control file. This redo log file is not from the current database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct redo log file, and then retry the operation.

column6: limit of %s instances in this database
column7: Starting this instance would exceed the maximum number of instances allowed for this database. This message occurs only with STARTUP shared and multiple instances.
column8:
From Oracle doc: You cannot start more than the lower of:

the operating system-specific maximum or 

the number of instances specified by the MAXINSTANCES option specified in the CREATE DATABASE statement

column6: requested INSTANCE_NUMBER out of range, maximum is %s
column7: The initialization parameter INSTANCE_NUMBER specified a number that was out of range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of INSTANCE_NUMBER to a valid range and restart the instance. The minimum value is 1 and the maximum value is the lower of the operating system-specific maximum or the value of the MAXINSTANCES option specified in the CREATE DATABASE statement. See also your operating system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: cannot open archived log '%s'
column7: The system cannot access a required archived redo log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the offline log exists, the storage device is online, and the archived file is in the correct location. Then attempt to continue recovery or restart the recovery session.

column6: log belongs to wrong database
column7: The system cannot access the archived redo log because it belongs to another database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct redo log file and then retry the operation.

column6: archived log contains sequence %s; sequence %s required
column7: The archived log is out of sequence, probably because it is corrupted or the wrong redo log file name was specified during recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct redo log file and then retry the operation.

column6: cannot read header from archived log
column7: An I/O error occurred when attempting to read the log file header from the specified archived redo log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Other messages will accompany this message. See the associated messages for the appropriate action to take.

column6: online log %s thread %s: '%s'
column7: This message reports the file name for details of another message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Other messages will accompany this message. See the associated messages for the appropriate action to take.

column6: open failed for members of log group %s of thread %s
column7: The online log cannot be opened. The file may not be in the expected location.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct redo log file or make the log available, if necessary. Also, see the accompanying messages.

column6: log %s of thread %s, expected sequence# %s doesn't match %s
column7: The online log is corrupted or is an old version.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find and install the correct version of the log or reset the logs. Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for recovery procedures.

column6: log %s of thread %s, wrong thread # %s in header
column7: The online log is corrupted or is an old version.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find and install the correct version of the log or reset the logs. Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for recovery procedures.

column6: log %s of thread %s, type %s in header is not log file
column7: The online log is corrupted or is an old version.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find and install the correct version of the log or reset the logs. Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for recovery procedures.

column6: file type %s in header is not log file
column7: This is not an archived log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct file and try again. Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for recovery procedures.

column6: log %s of thread %s, expected file size %s doesn't match %s
column7: The file size indicated in the control file did not match the file size contained in the log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the correct file or reset the logs. Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for recovery procedures.

column6: log %s of thread %s has incorrect log reset status
column7: An online redo log has log reset data that is different from the log reset data in the control file. The log is probably an incorrectly restored backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the correct file or reset the logs. Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for recovery procedures.

column6: cannot read file header from log %s of thread %s
column7: The file is not available.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the log file.

column6: log %s of thread %s, cannot update log file header
column7: Cannot write to the log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore access to the file.

column6: log %s of thread %s is not current copy
column7: An online log appears to be an incorrectly restored backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the correct file or reset the logs. Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for recovery procedures.

column6: Current log of thread %s not useable and all others need archiving
column7: An attempt to open the thread failed because it is necessary to switch redo generation to another online log, but all the other logs need to be archived before they can be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Archive the logs for the thread and then retry the open.

column6: log file '%s' translated name '%s' too long, %s characters exceeds %s limit
column7: The translated name for a log file is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose an untranslated name that yields a shorter translated name.

column6: archived log for thread %s, wrong thread # %s in header
column7: The archived log is corrupted or for another thread. Cannot use the log for applying the redo.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct archived log.

column6: log begins at change %s, need earlier change %s
column7: The archived log supplied for recovery was generated after the log that is needed. Cannot yet use the log for applying redo.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct archived log.

column6: log %s of thread %s, physical size %s less than needed %s
column7: A log file has shrunk in size. This is likely to have been caused by a computer operator's mistake or an operating system error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the log file from backup. If a backup is not available, drop this log and re-create it. If the database was shut down cleanly, no further action should be required; otherwise, incomplete recovery may be required.

column6: archived log ends at change %s, need later change %s
column7: The archived log supplied for recovery was generated before the log that is needed. Cannot use the log for applying redo.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct archived log.

column6: archived log begins at change %s, need change %s
column7: The archived log is not the correct log. An earlier log is needed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the correct log file.

column6: archived log ends at change %s, need change %s
column7: The archived log is not the correct log. A later log is needed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the correct log file.

column6: log version %s incompatible with ORACLE version %s
column7: The log was written by an incompatible version of Oracle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recover the database with the compatible software, shut it down cleanly, and then restart Oracle with the current software.

column6: archived log is too small - may be incompletely archived
column7: The log is smaller than the space allocated in it. May be the result of a SHUTDOWN ABORT while it was being written by the archiver.
column8: From Oracle doc: Get a complete version of this log and use it for recovery. There should either be an online version of it or a copy that was successfully archived.

column6: redo log read error block %s count %s
column7: An I/O error occurred while reading the log described in the accompanying error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore accessibility to file, or get another copy of the file.

column6: archived log: '%s'
column7: This message reports the file name involved with other errors.
column8: From Oracle doc: See associated error messages.

column6: online log %s: No log with this number, log does not exist
column7: This message reports the file name involved with other errors.
column8: From Oracle doc: See associated error messages.

column6: log file size %s blocks is less than minimum %s blocks
column7: The log file size as specified in the CREATE DATABASE statement is too small.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the log file size.

column6: log file '%s' does not exist and no size specified
column7: An attempt to add a log found neither an existing file nor a size for creating the file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a size for the log file.

column6: log %s of thread %s is more recent than controlfile
column7: The control file change sequence number in the log file is greater than the number in the control file. This implies that the wrong control file is being used. Note that repeatedly causing this error can make it stop happening without correcting the real problem. Every attempt to open the database will advance the control file change sequence number until it is great enough.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the current control file or do backup control file recovery to make the control file current. Be sure to follow all restrictions on doing a backup control file recovery.

column6: archived log does not contain any redo
column7: The archived log is not the correct log. It is a copy of a log file that has never been used for redo generation, or was an online log being prepared to be the current log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the correct log file.

column6: IO error processing online log %s of thread %s
column7: An I/O error occurred on the named online log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore accessibility to the file or restore the file from backup.

column6: log %s of thread %s, wrong log # %s in header
column7: The internal information in an online log file does not match the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the correct file or reset the logs. Refer to the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for recovery procedures.

column6: archived log was created before last RESETLOGS
column7: Recovery was given a log that was created before the last ALTER DATABASE OPEN RESETLOGS command. There should be another log created since then that contains the correct redo.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the correct log file.

column6: too many errors, log member closed
column7: The maximum number of errors on this log member has been exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the underlying problem by referring to the other error messages found with this one.

column6: unable to re-create online log '%s'
column7: An I/O failure occurred when attempting to re-create an online log as part of either an ALTER DATABASE OPEN RESETLOGS or ALTER DATABASE CLEAR LOGFILE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the file/device as indicated by accompanying errors.

column6: redo log write error block %s count %s
column7: An I/O error occurred while writing the log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the cause of the error, and then restart the system. If the log is lost, apply media/incomplete recovery.

column6: log member marked as STALE
column7: A log file member no longer is complete.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the underlying problem by referring to the other error messages found with this one.

column6: log %s of thread %s, expected block size %s doesn't match %s
column7: During online recovery, the block size specified in the control file did not match the block size contained in the redo log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the correct redo file from a backup or reset the online redo log files.

column6: single-process redo failure. Must abort instance
column7: A failure occurred during a critical portion of the log code during single process operation. This error does not occur during normal multi-process operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: SHUTDOWN ABORT and restart the database.

column6: failure obtaining block size for '%s'
column7: The operating system was unable to determine the block size for the given file name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult the accompanying error message, and correct the device or specify another file name.

column6: log %s of thread %s needs to be archived
column7: The command cannot be done because the log has not been archived, and media recovery has been enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Archive the log or disable media recovery. If the command supports an UNARCHIVED option, then it can be used. However, this may result in making backups unusable, and forcing the drop of some offline files.

column6: recover-to time invalid
column7: The time specified in a recover-until statement must be after January 1st 1988.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a time after January 1st 1988.

column6: all logs for thread %s need to be archived - cannot enable
column7: An attempt was made to enable a thread with all logs needing to be archived, and media recovery has been enabled. There is no log that can be made the new current log for the thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Archive a log for the thread or disable media recovery.

column6: log corruption near block %s change %s time %s
column7: Some type of redo log corruption has been discovered. This error describes the location of the corruption. Accompanying errors describe the type of corruption.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform recovery with a good version of the redo log or do incomplete recovery up to the indicated change or time.

column6: corrupt redo log block header
column7: The block header on the redo block indicated by the accompanying error is not valid. The block number and time-stamp are given in an accompanying message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform recovery with a good version of the redo log or perform cancel-based recovery up to, but not including, the corrupted redo log file. If this happens when archiving, archiving of the problem log can be skipped by clearing the log with the UNARCHIVED option. This must be followed by a backup of every datafile to insure recoverability of the database.

column6: change numbers out of order
column7: A change number found in the redo log is lower than a previously encountered change number. The log is corrupted in some way. The corruption may be at the earlier change or at this one.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform recovery with a good version of the log or perform time-based recovery up to the indicated time.

column6: inconsistent lengths in change description
column7: A change record in the redo log contains lengths that do not add up to a consistent value. The log is corrupted in some way.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform recovery with a good version of the log or do time-based recovery up to the indicated time.

column6: too many members specified for log file, the maximum is %s
column7: An ADD LOGFILE or ADD LOGFILE MEMBER command would result in a log with too many members. The number of members is set when the database is created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use fewer log file members.

column6: Too many file members specified, the maximum is %s
column7: A CREATE or ALTER statement specified too many members in a parenthesised file list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a number of file members that is within the port-defined limit.

column6: logfile group %s does not exist
column7: An ADD LOGFILE MEMBER or DROP LOGFILE request specified a log file group number that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the configuration of the log files and reissue the command.

column6: not a logfile member: %s
column7: A file name was given to DROP LOGFILE MEMBER command that is not a part of the database, or which is a datafile.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a valid log file member name.

column6: cannot remove last log member %s for group %s
column7: An attempt has been made to remove the last member of a log file group.
column8: From Oracle doc: If desired, delete the entire log, by using DROP LOGFILE.

column6: member is required to form a valid logfile in group %s
column7: A request to drop a log file member was denied because it would remove data required to form a complete log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: If desired, delete the entire log (after archiving if required), by using DROP LOGFILE.

column6: log is not the archived version
column7: The log given to recovery is a backup of the online version from the time it was the current log. The archived version of the log would not be marked as end of thread. This error can also be caused by failing to list the current log of an enabled thread in a CREATE CONTROLFILE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the archived version of the log and supply its name. If this is media recovery immediately following a CREATE CONTROLFILE, be sure the current log for this thread was included.

column6: cannot write header to new log member
column7: An I/O error occurred when attempting to write the header to a log member that is being added to an existing group.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying errors. Fix the problem or use another file.

column6: the specified log is not the correct next log
column7: The specified log failed to pass checks to ensure it corresponds to the log that was just applied. This is probably the result of using a log that was generated against a cold backup image of the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the log that was generated by this copy of the database and give that file name to recovery.

column6: log %s of thread %s, checksum error in the file header
column7: The file header for the redo log contains a checksum that does not match the value calculated from the file header as read from disk. This means the file header is corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find and install correct version of the log or reset the logs.

column6: checksum error in log file header
column7: The file header for the redo log contains a checksum that does not match the value calculated from the file header as read from disk. This means the file header is corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct file and try again.

column6: checksum error in redo log block
column7: The redo block indicated by the accompanying error, is not valid. It has a checksum that does not match the block contents.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform recovery with a good version of the log or do time-based recovery up to the indicated time. If this happens when archiving, archiving of the problem log can be skipped by clearing the log with the UNARCHIVED option. This must be followed by a backup of every datafile to insure recoverability of the database. Restore the correct file or reset logs.

column6: Current log of thread %s not useable and other log being cleared
column7: An attempt to open the thread failed because it is necessary to switch redo generation to another online log, but all the other logs are being cleared or need to be archived before they can be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the ALTER DATABASE CLEAR LOGFILE command is still active, then wait for it to complete. Otherwise, reissue the CLEAR command. If there are other online logs for the thread that are not being cleared, then archive the logs.

column6: no free buffer handles available
