column7: There is not enough memory to proceed with the operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Raise the value of the SHARED_POOL_SIZE initialization parameter and try again.

column6: file %s cannot be modified at this time
column7: An attempt was made to modify the contents of a file that cannot be modified. The file is most likely part of a read-only tablespace but may be in the process of going offline, or the database may be in the process of closing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the status of the file and its tablespace.

column6: online log version %s incompatible with ORACLE version %s
column7: The online log was written by an incompatible version of Oracle. This can occur when the log file was created by either a new or older version of Oracle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recover the database with the compatible software, shut it down cleanly, and then restart with current software.

column6: parameter db_block_size = %s invalid, valid range [%s..%s]
column7: An invalid value was specified for the DB_BLOCK_SIZE parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust the value of the parameter and restart the instance.

column6: unable to get default db_block_size
column7: The system was unable to determine the default value for DB_BLOCK_SIZE.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the accompanying system-specific error. As a workaround, specify the block size in the INIT.ORA file.

column6: file %s cannot be read at this time
column7: An attempt was made to read from a file that is not readable. Most likely the file is offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the state of the file. Bring it online.

column6: Frequent backups of file %s causing write operation to stall
column7: Backups are occurring too frequently on this file. Each time a new backup is started for a file, any writes which have been previously issued (but not completed) have to be re-issued. If hot backups are started very, very frequently, it is possible that some writes will be re-issued repeatedly and never complete.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the interval between begin hot-backup commands for this file.

column6: buffer pools cannot be created as specified
column7: The number of buffers or the number of LRU latches is too small to satisfy the specified buffer pool configuration.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either increase the number of buffers and/or number of LRU latches or configure smaller buffer pools.

column6: no free buffers available in buffer pool %s
column7: All buffers in the specified buffer pool are in use and no free buffers are available.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the number of buffers in the specified pool.

column6: log %s of thread %s is being cleared, cannot become current log
column7: An attempt to switch to a new online log for the redo thread failed because no reusable log could be found. This log is being cleared and will be usable when the clearing completes. The command that began the clearing may have terminated without completing the clearing.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the clear command is still executing, then wait for its completion. If it terminated, then reissue the clear command, or drop the log.

column6: All threads must switch to new log format at the same time
column7: An attempt to switch the current log of a single thread is not allowed because the compatibility requirements force a new log format version number. When changing log formats, all threads must switch to the new format at the same time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Open the database to cause the coordinated log switch. If that is not possible, then return to the same software version and compatibility setting last used to open the database.

column6: log %s of thread %s is being cleared, operation not allowed
column7: An operation encountered this online log in the middle of being cleared. The command that began the clearing may have terminated without completing the clearing.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the clear command is still executing, then wait for its completion. If it terminated, then reissue the clear command or drop the log.

column6: log %s of thread %s is needed for recovery of offline datafiles
column7: Log cannot be cleared because the redo in it is needed to recover offline datafiles. It has not been archived so there is no other copy available. If the log is cleared, the tablespaces containing the files will have to be dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Archive the log and then repeat the clear command. If archiving is not possible, and dropping the tablespaces is acceptable, then add the clause UNRECOVERABLE DATAFILE at the end of the clear command.

column6: online log reused while attempting to archive it
column7: An attempt was made to reuse an online log file that is being archived.
column8: From Oracle doc: The online log file has been overwritten; it cannot be archived.

column6: online logs for the clone database must be renamed
column7: A clone database open forces log file renaming to avoid overwriting the primary log files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rename the log files manually or using the LOG_FILE_NAME_CONVERT initialization parameter.

column6: invalid release value %s for parameter %s
column7: The release level given for the specified initialization parameter is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the parameter value in the parameter file and retry.

column6: the value for parameter %s is not supported by this release
column7: The value specified cannot be supported by this release of the software.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose an appropriate value, or remove the parameter value to use the default value.

column6: database changes by release %s cannot be used by release %s
column7: Changes have been made to the database that require a newer software release or that violate the compatibility parameters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a version of the software that can understand the changes or relax the compatibility requirements in the initialization file.

column6: %s (%s) is not the same as other instances (%s)
column7: Another instance has set the COMPATIBLE or COMPATIBLE NO RECOVERY parameters differently than this instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the parameters of the current instance to match other instances already running.

column6: Convert file not found: '%s'
column7: The file used for converting the database from V7 to V8 could not be found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the migration process has been started on this database and that the convert file name is accessible.

column6: compatibility type "%s"
column7: Reporting a type associated with another error.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the accompanying error.

column6: COMPATIBLE parameter needs to be %s or greater
column7: The value of the COMPATIBLE initialization parameter is not high enough to allow the operation. Allowing the command would make the database incompatible with the release specified by the current COMPATIBLE parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down and restart with a higher compatibility setting.

column6: rolling upgrade from release %s.%s to %s.%s is not allowed
column7: Another instance executing software at a different point release already has the database mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down all instances then restart with the new software.

column6: parameter %s is set to TRUE
column7: Reporting the parameter that resulted in the compatibility error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down and restart with a higher compatibility setting.

column6: ORACLE is not licensed. Contact Oracle Corp. for assistance
column7: This installed Oracle software is not licensed to run on this CPU. This can also occur if Oracle software has been installed incorrectly, for example, with the wrong licensing codes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that Oracle is installed correctly. Then contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: ORACLE feature is not licensed. Contact Oracle Corp. for assistance
column7: This installed Oracle feature is not licensed to run on this CPU. This can also occur if Oracle software has been installed incorrectly, for example, with the wrong licensing codes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that Oracle is installed correctly. Then contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: %s Option not installed
column7: The specified option is not installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either avoid calling the option, or purchase and install the option.

column6: feature not enabled: %s
column7: The specified feature is not enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to use this feature.

column6: background process "%s" did not start
column7: The specified process did not start.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the executable image is in the correct place with the correct protections, and that there is enough memory.

column6: background process "%s" failed while starting
column7: Usually due to a bad (or non-existent) background process image.
column8: From Oracle doc: Get a good background process image.

column6: background process "%s" did not start after %s seconds
column7: The specified process did not start after the specified time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the background did not die and leave a trace file.

column6: background process started when not expected
column7: The background process specified started after Oracle was already running.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying messages, if any, and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the other messages. If no user on site started the process, report the message to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: fatal error in background process
column7: One of the background processes died unexpectedly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the system. Check and, if necessary, correct the problem indicated by the background trace file in BACKGROUND_DUMP_DEST.

column6: normal completion of background process
column7: One of the background processes completed normally as requested by the user.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you are solving a problem, check for other messages and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the other messages. Then shut down and restart Oracle.

column6: background process '%s' unexpectedly terminated with error %s
column7: A foreground process needing service from a background process has discovered the process died.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the message code given in the message and the trace file for the foreground and the background processes.

column6: LGWR process terminated with error
column7: The Log Writer process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying messages, and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the messages. Then shut down and restart the instance. If the trace file mentions any other background process messages, check the trace file for the mentioned process until the root message is found.

column6: DBWR process terminated with error
column7: The Database Writer process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying messages, and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the messages. Then shut down and restart the instance. If the trace file mentions any other background process messages, check the trace file for the mentioned process until the root message is found.

column6: PMON process terminated with error
column7: The Process Monitor process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying messages, and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the messages. Then shut down and restart the instance. If the trace file mentions any other background process messages, check the trace file for the mentioned process until the root message is found.

column6: ARCH process terminated with error
column7: The Archiver process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying messages, if any, and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the messages. Then shut down and restart the instance. If the trace file mentions any other background process messages, check the trace file for the mentioned process until the root message is found.

column6: SMON process terminated with error
column7: The System Monitor process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying messages, if any, and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the messages. Then shut down and restart the instance. If the trace file mentions any other background process messages, check the trace file for the mentioned process until the root message is found.

column6: TRWR process terminated with error
column7: The system tracing process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance.

column6: RECO process terminated with error
column7: The distributed transaction (two-phase commit) recovery process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance.

column6: SNP* process terminated with error
column7: A snapshot refresh process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance.

column6: LCK* process terminated with error
column7: One Lock process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying messages, if any, and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the messages. Then shut down and restart the instance. If the trace file mentions any other background process messages, check the trace file for the mentioned process until the root message is found.

column6: LMON process terminated with error
column7: The Lock Manager monitor process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance.

column6: LMD* process terminated with error
column7: A Lock Manager daemon process terminated abnormally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance.

column6: During shutdown a process abnormally terminated
column7: One of the background processes did not exit normally at or near the time of shutdown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the SHUTDOWN ABORT command. Check the accompanying messages, if any, and the background process trace file. Correct the problem mentioned in the messages. Then shut down and restart the instance. If the trace file mentions any other background process messages, check the trace file for the mentioned process until the root message is found.

column6: Maximum number of interrupt handlers exceeded
column7: The number of registered interrupt handling routines for when the break key is entered exceeds the maximum allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of registered interrupt handlers.

column6: internal error code, arguments: [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s]
column7:
This is the generic internal error number for Oracle program exceptions. It indicates that a process has encountered a low-level, unexpected condition. Causes of this message include:

timeouts 

file corruption 

failed data checks in memory 

hardware, memory, or I/O errors 

incorrectly restored files 

The first argument is the internal message number. Other arguments are various numbers, names, and character strings. The numbers may change meanings between different versions of Oracle.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Report this error to Oracle Customer Support after gathering the following information:

events that led up to the error 

the operations that were attempted that led to the error 

the conditions of the operating system and databases at the time of the error 

any unusual circumstances that occurred before receiving the ORA-00600 message 

contents of any trace files generated by the error 

the relevant portions of the Alter files 

Note: The cause of this message may manifest itself as different errors at different times. Be aware of the history of errors that occurred before this internal error.

column6: cleanup lock conflict
column7: The Process Monitor encountered a lock conflict while trying to recover processes. This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: internal programming exception
column7: Internal programming exception occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report this error as a program bug to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: ORACLE server session terminated by fatal error
column7: An Oracle Server session is in an unrecoverable state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log in to Oracle again so a new server session will be created automatically. Examine the session trace file for more information.

column6: error occurred at recursive SQL level %s
column7: An error occurred while processing a recursive SQL statement (a statement applying to internal dictionary tables).
column8: From Oracle doc: If the situation described in the next error on the stack can be corrected, do so; otherwise contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Internal error code
column7: A call to deferred UPI functions was made in non-deferred mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: object necessary for warmstarting database cannot be altered
column7: An attempt was made to alter or drop a database object (table, cluster, or index) defined in the control file's bootstrap segment and needed to warm start the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the spelling of the object name or remove it from the ALTER or DROP statement.

column6: bootstrap verison '%s' inconsistent with version '%s'
column7: The version of the bootstrap data is incompatible with the current version of the software.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a version of the software that is compatible with the datafiles.

column6: maximum number of row cache instance locks exceeded
column7: There are not enough row cache enqueues.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the ROW CACHE ENQUEUE parameter and restart the system.

column6: bootstrap process failure
column7: Failure in processing bootstrap data. Refer to the accompanying messages for more information about the cause of the problem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the problems mentioned in the other messages. If the problem persists, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: inconsistent state during start up; shut down the instance, then restart it
column7: A previous attempt to start an instance was terminated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the instance completely and then restart it.

column6: error message translation failed
column7: There is an internal error where a routine was unable to translate a message code.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid SQL statement
column7: The statement is not recognized as a valid SQL statement. This error can occur if the Procedural Option is not installed and a SQL statement is issued that requires this option (for example, a CREATE PROCEDURE statement). You can determine if the Procedural Option is installed by starting SQL*Plus. If the PL/SQL banner is not displayed, then the option is not installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax or install the Procedural Option.

column6: invalid CREATE command
column7: The CREATE command was not followed by a valid CREATE option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: invalid datatype
column7: The datatype entered in the CREATE or ALTER TABLE statement is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: invalid table name
column7: A table or cluster name is invalid or does not exist. This message is also issued if an invalid cluster name or no cluster name is specified in an ALTER CLUSTER or DROP CLUSTER statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check spelling. A valid table name or cluster name must begin with a letter and may contain only alphanumeric characters and the special characters $, _, and #. The name must be less than or equal to 30 characters and cannot be a reserved word.

column6: invalid column name
column7: The column name entered is either missing or invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid column name. A valid column name must begin with a letter, be less than or equal to 30 characters, and consist of only alphanumeric characters and the special characters $, _, and #. If it contains other characters, it must be enclosed in double quotation marks. It may not be a reserved word.

column6: missing keyword
column7: A required keyword is missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: missing left parenthesis
column7: A required left parenthesis has been omitted. Certain commands, such as CREATE TABLE, CREATE CLUSTER, and INSERT, require a list of items enclosed in parentheses. Parentheses also are required around subqueries in WHERE clauses and in UPDATE table SET column = (SELECT...) statements.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax, inserting a left parenthesis where required, and retry the statement.

column6: missing right parenthesis
column7: A left parenthesis has been entered without a closing right parenthesis, or extra information was contained in the parentheses. All parentheses must be entered in pairs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax and retry the statement.

column6: missing NULL keyword
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: invalid number of arguments
column7: An Oracle function was referenced with an incorrect number of arguments. All Oracle functions, except for SYSDATE, require at least one argument.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax of the function by entering the required number of arguments.

column6: specified length too long for its datatype
column7: No size was specified for a character field or the size was invalid. A maximum length must be specified for each character column. The maximum value for this length varies for each character datatype, such as CHAR or VARCHAR2.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a maximum length for the field.

column6: invalid character
column7: Special characters are valid only in certain places. If special characters other than $, _, and # are used in a name and the name is not enclosed in double quotation marks ("), this message will be issued. One exception to this rule is for database names; in this case, double quotes are stripped out and ignored.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid character from the statement or enclose the object name in double quotation marks.

column6: too many values
column7: The SQL statement requires two sets of values equal in number. This error occurs when the second set contains more items than the first set. For example, the subquery in a WHERE or HAVING clause may return too many columns, or a VALUES or SELECT clause may return more columns than are listed in the INSERT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the number of items in each set and change the SQL statement to make them equal.

column6: missing ADD keyword
column7:
The keyword ADD does not precede one of the following: 

The keyword log file in an ALTER DATABASE statement 

A column element or table constraint in an ALTER TABLE statement 

The keyword DATAFILE in an ALTER TABLESPACE statement
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the keyword ADD in the ALTER statement.

column6: network access of dictionary table not currently allowed
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: missing comma
column7: A required comma has been omitted from a list of columns or values in an INSERT statement or a list of the form ((C,D),(E,F), ...).
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: column ambiguously defined
column7: A column name used in a join exists in more than one table and is thus referenced ambiguously. In a join, any column name that occurs in more than one of the tables must be prefixed by its table name when referenced. The column should be referenced as TABLE.COLUMN or TABLE_ALIAS.COLUMN. For example, if tables EMP and DEPT are being joined and both contain the column DEPTNO, then all references to DEPTNO should be prefixed with the table name, as in EMP.DEPTNO or E.DEPTNO.
column8: From Oracle doc: Prefix references to column names that exist in multiple tables with either the table name or a table alias and a period (.), as in the examples above.

column6: invalid function
column7: An entry was formatted like a function call, but it is not recognizable as an Oracle function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: invalid relational operator
column7: A search condition was entered with an invalid or missing relational operator.
column8: From Oracle doc: Include a valid relational operator such as =, !=, ^=, , >, =, <=, ALL, ANY, [NOT] BETWEEN, EXISTS, [NOT] IN, IS [NOT] NULL, or [NOT] LIKE in the condition.

column6: unexpected end of SQL command
column7: The SQL command was not complete. Part of a valid command was entered, but at least one major component was omitted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: missing or invalid option
column7: An invalid option was specified in defining a column or storage clause. The valid option in specifying a column is NOT NULL to specify that the column cannot contain any NULL values. Only constraints may follow the datatype. Specifying a maximum length on a DATE or LONG datatype also causes this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax. Remove the erroneous option or length specification from the column or storage specification.

column6: FROM keyword not found where expected
column7: In a SELECT or REVOKE statement, the keyword FROM was either missing, misplaced, or misspelled. The keyword FROM must follow the last selected item in a SELECT statement or the privileges in a REVOKE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax. Insert the keyword FROM where appropriate. The SELECT list itself also may be in error. If quotation marks were used in an alias, check that double quotation marks enclose the alias. Also, check to see if a reserved word was used as an alias.

column6: missing BY keyword
column7: The keyword BY was omitted in a GROUP BY, ORDER BY, or CONNECT BY clause. In a GRANT statement, the keyword IDENTIFIED must also be followed by the keyword BY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax. Insert the keyword BY where required and then retry the statement.

column6: missing INTO keyword
column7: An INSERT statement has been entered without the keyword INTO.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax. Insert the keyword INTO where required and then retry the statement.

column6: missing VALUES keyword
column7: An INSERT statement has been entered without the keyword VALUES or SELECT. Either a VALUES clause or a SELECT subquery must follow the INSERT INTO clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax. Enter either a VALUES clause or a subquery after the INSERT INTO clause.

column6: missing equal sign
column7:
An equal sign has been omitted in one of the following places: 

In the SET clause of an UPDATE statement 

Following "!" in a search condition to signify not equal
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax. Insert the equal sign where required and retry the statement.

column6: missing SELECT keyword
column7: A SELECT subquery must be included in a CREATE VIEW statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax. Insert the required SELECT clause after the CREATE VIEW clause and then retry the statement.

column6: missing period
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: missing asterisk
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: missing identifier
column7: The specified string does not contain an identifier.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the string argument.

column6: inconsistent datatypes
column7:
One of the following:

An attempt was made to perform an operation on incompatible datatypes. For example, adding a character field to a date field (dates may only be added to numeric fields) or concatenating a character field with a long field. 

An attempt was made to perform an operation on a database object (such as a table or view) that is not intended for normal use. For example, system tables cannot be modified by a user. Note that on rare occasions this error occurs because a misspelled object name matched a restricted object's name. 

An attempt was made to use an undocumented view.
column8:
From Oracle doc: If the cause is 

different datatypes, then use consistent datatypes. For example, convert the character field to a numeric field with the TO_NUMBER function before adding it to the date field. Functions may not be used with long fields. 

an object not intended for normal use, then do not access the restricted object.

column6: SQL command not properly ended
column7: The SQL statement ends with an inappropriate clause. For example, an ORDER BY clause may have been included in a CREATE VIEW or INSERT statement. ORDER BY cannot be used to create an ordered view or to insert in a certain order. Also, an improper SQL ending occurs if IN clause is used with only one argument (IN(X), for example). An IN clause must have two or more arguments.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax by removing the inappropriate clauses. It may be possible to duplicate the removed clause with another SQL statement. For example, to order the rows of a view, do so when querying the view and not when creating it. This error can also occur in SQL*Forms applications if a continuation line is indented. Check for indented lines and delete these spaces.

column6: group function is not allowed here
column7: One of the group functions, such as AVG, COUNT, MAX, MIN, SUM, STDDEV, or VARIANCE, was used in a WHERE or GROUP BY clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the group function from the WHERE or GROUP BY clause. The desired result may be achieved by including the function in a subquery or HAVING clause.

column6: group function is nested too deeply
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: missing expression
column7: A required part of a clause or expression has been omitted. For example, a SELECT statement may have been entered without a list of columns or expressions or with an incomplete expression. This message is also issued in cases where a reserved word is misused, as in SELECT TABLE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement syntax and specify the missing component.

column6: not a single-group group function
column7: A SELECT list cannot include both a group function, such as AVG, COUNT, MAX, MIN, SUM, STDDEV, or VARIANCE, and an individual column expression, unless the individual column expression is included in a GROUP BY clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop either the group function or the individual column expression from the SELECT list or add a GROUP BY clause that includes all individual column expressions listed.

column6: not enough arguments for function
column7: The function was referenced with too few arguments.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the function syntax and specify the required number of arguments.

column6: too many arguments for function
column7: The function was referenced with too many arguments.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the function syntax and specify only the required number of arguments.

column6: invalid ALTER command
column7: An invalid ALTER option was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: missing cluster name
column7: The cluster name was either missing or invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid cluster name. A valid cluster name must start with a letter, be less than or equal to 30 characters, and contain only alphanumeric characters or the special characters $, _, and #. It may not be a reserved word. The name must be specified immediately following the keywords CREATE CLUSTER.

column6: table or view does not exist
column7: The table or view entered does not exist, a synonym that is not allowed here was used, or a view was referenced where a table is required. Existing user tables and views can be listed by querying the data dictionary. Certain privileges may be required to access the table. If an application returned this message, the table the application tried to access does not exist in the database, or the application does not have access to it.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Check each of the following: 

the spelling of the table or view name. 

that a view is not specified where a table is required. 

that an existing table or view name exists. 

Contact the database administrator if the table needs to be created or if user or application privileges are required to access the table. 

Also, if attempting to access a table or view in another schema, make certain the correct schema is referenced and that access to the object is granted.

column6: cluster does not exist
column7: The current user owns no cluster by the specified name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid cluster name following the keyword CLUSTER, then retry the statement.

column6: insufficient number of clustered columns
column7: An attempt was made to create a table with fewer cluster columns than were specified in the CREATE CLUSTER statement. The CLUSTER clause of a CREATE TABLE statement must specify all cluster columns that were defined when the cluster was created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify all cluster columns in the CREATE TABLE statement, then retry it.

column6: specified clustered column does not exist
column7: A column specified in the cluster clause of a CREATE TABLE statement is not a column in this table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-execute the statement, using the names of columns defined for the table.

column6: missing TO keyword
column7: A GRANT statement was specified without the keyword TO, or an invalid form of the GRANT command was entered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax for the GRANT command, insert the keyword TO where required, and retry the statement.

column6: not enough values
column7:
This error occurs when a SQL statement requires two sets of values equal in number, but the second set contains fewer items than the first set. This can occur in a WHERE or HAVING clause in which a nested SELECT returns too few columns as in: 

WHERE (A,B) IN (SELECT C FROM ...) 


Another common cause of this error is an INSERT statement in which the VALUES or SELECT clause does not contain enough values needed for the INSERT, as in 

INSERT INTO EMP(EMPNO,ENAME) VALUES('JONES')
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the number of items in each set and change the SQL statement to make them equal.

column6: ALTER CLUSTER statement no longer supported
column7: The ALTER CLUSTER statement has been withdrawn.

column6: illegal reference to remote database
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid DROP option
column7: A DROP command was not followed by a valid DROP option, such as CLUSTER, DATABASE LINK, INDEX, ROLLBACK SEGMENT, SEQUENCE, SYNONYM, TABLE, TABLESPACE, or VIEW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the command syntax, specify a valid DROP option, then retry the statement.

column6: cluster not empty
column7: A DROP CLUSTER statement specified a cluster that is not empty. A cluster may not be dropped if it contains any tables, unless the optional INCLUDING TABLES clause is specified. Tables may also be removed from a cluster by using the DROP TABLE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify the INCLUDING TABLES clause in the DROP CLUSTER statement or remove all tables from the cluster with the DROP TABLE command before issuing the DROP CLUSTER command.

column6: missing GROUP keyword
column7: Groups are not currently implemented.
column8: From Oracle doc: No user action required.

column6: missing or invalid index name
column7: In a CREATE INDEX, DROP INDEX, or VALIDATE INDEX statement, the index name was missing or invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid index name after the keyword INDEX. To drop or validate an existing index, check the name by querying the data dictionary. To create a new index, check the syntax before retrying.

column6: missing IDENTIFIED keyword
column7: A GRANT CONNECT statement was issued without the keyword IDENTIFIED.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Check the syntax and insert the keyword IDENTIFIED after the last username. The format is 

GRANT CONNECT TO user-list IDENTIFIED BY password-list;

column6: name is already used by an existing object
column7: An attempt was made to create a database object (such as a table, view, cluster, index, or synonym) that already exists. A user's database objects must have distinct names.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a unique name for the database object or modify or drop the existing object so it can be reused.

column6: missing or invalid auditing option
column7: An AUDIT or NOAUDIT command was not followed by a valid option or the keyword ALL. For example, when AUDITing tables an option such as ALTER, AUDIT, COMMENT, DELETE, GRANT, INDEX, INSERT, LOCK, RENAME, SELECT, or UPDATE must be specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: duplicate column name
column7: A column name was specified twice in a CREATE or INSERT statement. Column names must be unique within a table, view, or cluster.
column8: From Oracle doc: In a CREATE statement, change one of the column names to a new, unique column name. In an INSERT statement, remove one of the duplicate names.

column6: missing CHECK keyword
column7: The keyword CHECK should follow the keyword WITH in the WITH OPTION clause of the CREATE VIEW statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement syntax and insert the keyword CHECK where required. Then retry the statement.

column6: tablespace '%s' does not exist
column7: A statement specified the name of a tablespace that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter the name of an existing tablespace. For a list of tablespace names, query the data dictionary.

column6: ambiguous column naming in select list
column7: A column name in the order-by list matches more than one select list columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove duplicate column naming in select list.

column6: bad datetime/interval value
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: too many group-by / order-by expressions
column7: The group-by or order-by column list contain more than 1000 expressions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use no more than 1000 expressions in the group-by or order-by list.

column6: unsupported interval type
column7: An unsupported interval type was encountered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid interval type.

column6: table name not in FROM list
column7: A table specified in a query's SELECT list is not named in the FROM clause list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check spelling of the table names, check that each table name in the SELECT list matches a table name in the FROM list, and then retry the statement.

column6: column aliases not allowed for '*'
column7:
An alias was used with the return-all-columns function (*) in the SELECT list. For example: 

SELECT * COL_ALIAS FROM EMP;
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify individual columns or do not specify an alias with a "*".

column6: missing TABLE keyword
column7: A LOCK statement was specified and the keyword TABLE was missing, misspelled, or misplaced. A LOCK statement must begin with LOCK TABLE tablename.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: missing WHERE keyword
column7: The keyword WHERE in a SELECT statement was missing, misspelled, or misplaced.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: missing INDEX keyword
column7: The keyword INDEX in a CREATE UNIQUE INDEX or VALIDATE INDEX statement was missing, misspelled, or misplaced.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: missing ON keyword
column7: The keyword ON in a GRANT, REVOKE, or CREATE INDEX statement was missing, misspelled, or misplaced.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check syntax and spelling, and use the keyword ON where required.

column6: missing WITH keyword
column7: The keyword START was specified without the keyword WITH. Both keywords are necessary if a START WITH clause is desired in a tree-structured query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the keyword START to the keywords START WITH. Then retry the statement.

column6: missing SET keyword
column7: The keyword SET in an UPDATE statement is missing, misspelled, or misplaced.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check syntax and spelling, and use the keyword SET after the name of the table to be updated.

column6: identifier is too long
column7: The name of a schema object exceeds 30 characters. Schema objects are tables, clusters, views, indexes, synonyms, tablespaces, and usernames.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shorten the name to 30 characters or less.

column6: invalid row count estimate
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: invalid PCTFREE value (percentage)
column7: The percentage of free space specified in a CREATE INDEX statement is not between 0 and 100. A PCTFREE value of 0 means the entire block is available. The value 100 is not useful because it means that no data may be inserted. The default is 10.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a PCTFREE value between 0 and 100. Then retry the statement.

column6: date + date not allowed
column7: An attempt was made to add two date fields together. Dates may be added only to numeric fields, not to other dates.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the Oracle function TO_NUMBER to convert one of the date fields to a numeric field before adding it to the other date field.

column6: LEVEL, PRIOR, or ROWNUM not allowed here
column7: The use of the PRIOR clause, the pseudo-column LEVEL, or ROWNUM is incorrect in this context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax for the SQL statement. Then remove or relocate the keyword PRIOR, LEVEL, or ROWNUM.

column6: duplicate auditing option
column7: An AUDIT or NOAUDIT statement specified the same option more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify ALL without other auditing options or remove the duplicate auditing specifications.

column6: nested group function without GROUP BY
column7: A group function, such as AVG, COUNT, MAX, MIN, SUM, STDDEV, or VARIANCE, was used within another group function, as in MAX(COUNT(*)), without a corresponding GROUP BY clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either add a GROUP BY clause or remove the extra level of nesting.

column6: not a GROUP BY expression
column7: The GROUP BY clause does not contain all the expressions in the SELECT clause. SELECT expressions that are not included in a group function, such as AVG, COUNT, MAX, MIN, SUM, STDDEV, or VARIANCE, must be listed in the GROUP BY clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Include in the GROUP BY clause all SELECT expressions that are not group function arguments.

column6: synonym translation is no longer valid
column7: The synonym used is based on a table, view, or synonym that no longer exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the synonym with the name of the object it references or re-create the synonym so that it refers to a valid table, view, or synonym.

column6: cannot mix table and system auditing options
column7: Both table-wide and system-wide options were specified within a single AUDIT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the AUDIT command syntax. Then retry one or more AUDIT statements.

column6: missing plus sign
column7: A left parenthesis appeared in a join condition, but a plus sign (+) did not follow. A left parenthesis in a join condition usually signals an outer-join specification and so a plus sign is expected to follow. To specify an outer join on a column in a join operation, follow the column reference in the join condition with a plus sign (+) enclosed in parentheses.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the SQL syntax and retry the statement.

column6: column not allowed here
column7: A column name was used in an expression where it is not permitted, such as in the VALUES clause of an INSERT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the statement and use column names only where appropriate.

column6: invalid program name
column7: Probably a syntax error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct syntax.

column6: missing or invalid group name(s)
column7: Probably a syntax error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct syntax.

column6: missing or invalid username(s)
column7: No username was specified in a GRANT statement or one of the specified usernames is invalid. Valid usernames must be specified following the keyword TO in a GRANT statement to define a user. A username must begin with a letter, consist only of alphanumeric characters and the special characters $, _, and #, and be less than or equal to 30 characters. If it contains other characters, it must be enclosed in double quotation marks. It may not be a reserved word.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid username, or list of usernames, following the keyword TO in the GRANT statement.

column6: missing or invalid password(s)
column7: More usernames than passwords were specified in a GRANT statement. A valid password must be specified for each username listed in the GRANT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid password for each username.

column6: too many passwords for usernames given
column7: More passwords than usernames were specified in a GRANT statement. Only one password may be entered for each username listed in the GRANT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter an equal number of usernames and passwords.

column6: missing or invalid privilege
column7: No privileges were specified in a GRANT privilege statement, or one of the specified privileges is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter one or more valid privileges such as SELECT, INSERT, DELETE, UPDATE, ALTER, INDEX, REFERENCES, or ALL. More than one privilege may be granted by entering the privileges in a list separated by commas (,) or by specifying the keyword ALL to grant all privileges.

column6: only MAC privileges may be granted to procedures
column7: Object privileges or non-MAC system privileges were granted to the procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only grant MAC privileges using the PROCEDURE clause.

column6: invalid format for REVOKE command
column7: An invalid form of the REVOKE command was entered. There are two forms of the REVOKE command. The first form is used to revoke a user's database access privileges. The second form is used to revoke a user's object privileges.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the command syntax and retry the statement.

column6: missing GRANT keyword
column7: The keyword WITH was specified at the end of a GRANT statement without the keyword GRANT. To grant privileges to a user and the permission to grant those privileges to another user, you must specify the keywords WITH GRANT OPTION at the end of the GRANT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the keyword WITH to the keywords WITH GRANT OPTION, then retry the statement.

column6: missing OPTION keyword
column7: The keywords WITH GRANT were specified at the end of a GRANT statement without the keyword OPTION.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the keywords WITH GRANT to the keywords WITH GRANT OPTION. Then retry the statement.

column6: missing or invalid synonym identifier
column7: In a CREATE or DROP SYNONYM statement, the synonym name was either missing or invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check syntax and spelling. A valid synonym name must be specified immediately following the keyword SYNONYM in both statements. Valid synonym names must begin with a letter, consist of alphanumeric characters and the special characters $, _, and #, and be less than or equal to 30 characters. They may not be reserved words.

column6: the concatenate operator is ||, not |
column7: A single bar (|) was interpreted as an attempt to specify concatenation, but the concatenation operator is a double bar (||).
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a double bar (||) for concatenation or remove the single bar (|) if concatenation was not intended.

column6: illegal use of LONG datatype
column7: A value of datatype LONG was used in a function or in a DISTINCT, WHERE, CONNECT BY, GROUP BY, or ORDER BY clause. A LONG value can only be used in a SELECT clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the LONG value from the function or clause.

column6: must name this expression with a column alias
column7: An expression or function was used in a CREATE VIEW statement, but no corresponding column name was specified. When expressions or functions are used in a view, all column names for the view must be explicitly specified in the CREATE VIEW statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a column name for each column in the view in parentheses after the view name.

column6: invalid view name
column7: In a CREATE VIEW statement, the view name was missing or invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid view name following CREATE VIEW. Valid view names must begin with a letter, consist of only alphanumeric characters and the special characters $, _, and #, be less than or equal to 30 characters, and may not be reserved words. If the view name contains other characters, it must be enclosed in double quotation marks.

column6: maximum open cursors exceeded
column7: A host language program attempted to open too many cursors. The initialization parameter OPEN_CURSORS determines the maximum number of cursors per user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the program to use fewer cursors. If this error occurs often, shut down Oracle, increase the value of OPEN_CURSORS, and then restart Oracle.

column6: invalid cursor
column7: Either a host language program call specified an invalid cursor or the values of the AREASIZE and MAXOPENCURSORS options in the precompiler command were too small. All cursors must be opened using the OOPEN call before being referenced in any of the following calls: SQL, DESCRIBE, NAME, DEFINE, BIND, EXEC, FETCH, and CLOSE. The Logon Data Area (LDA) must be defined by using OLON or OLOGON. If the LDA is not defined, this message is issued for the following calls: OPEN, COM, CON, ROL, and LOGOFF.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the erroneous call statement. Specify a correct LDA area or open the cursor as required. If there is no problem with the cursor, it may be necessary to increase the AREASIZE and MAXOPENCURSORS options before precompiling.

column6: fetch out of sequence
column7: In a host language program, a FETCH call was issued out of sequence. A successful parse-and-execute call must be issued before a fetch. This can occur if an attempt was made to FETCH from an active set after all records have been fetched. This may be caused by fetching from a SELECT FOR UPDATE cursor after a commit. A PL/SQL cursor loop implicitly does fetches and may also cause this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Parse and execute a SQL statement before attempting to fetch the data.

column6: no statement parsed
column7: A host language program call referenced a cursor with no associated parsed SQL statement. A SQL call (for example, OSQL3) must be used to pass a SQL statement to Oracle and to associate the statement with an open cursor. A cursor must already have an associated SQL statement if referenced in any of the following calls: DESCRIBE, NAME, DEFINE, BIND, EXECUTE, and FETCH.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do the SQL call, for example, OSQL, to pass the required SQL statement before referencing the cursor.

column6: default username feature not supported; logon denied
column7: An attempt was made to use automatic logon on a system not supporting this feature.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide the complete username and password to log on to Oracle.

column6: null password given; logon denied
column7: An invalid password was given when logging on.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a valid password.

column6: bind variable does not exist
column7: A program issued a BIND call for a variable not listed in the associated SQL statement. Only those variables prefixed by either a colon (:) or ampersand (&) in the SQL statement may be referenced in a BIND call, OBIND or OBINDN. This error may also be caused by a mismatch between a Precompiler program and the related library, SQLLIB.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the BIND call to reference one of the substitute variables specified in the associated SQL statement.

column6: variable not in select list
column7: A reference was made to a variable not listed in the SELECT clause. In OCI, this can occur if the number passed for the position parameter is less than one or greater than the number of variables in the SELECT clause in any of the following calls: DESCRIBE, NAME, or DEFINE. In SQL*Forms or SQL*Report, specifying more variables in an INTO clause than in the SELECT clause also causes this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine which of the problems listed caused the problem and take appropriate action.

column6: not all variables bound
column7: A SQL statement containing substitution variables was executed without all variables bound. All substitution variables must have a substituted value before the SQL statement is executed.
column8: From Oracle doc: In OCI, use an OBIND or OBINDN call to substitute the required values.

column6: missing mandatory parameter
column7: A host language program call did not pass all required parameters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax for the call and enter all required parameters.

column6: invalid OCI operation
column7:
One of the following: 

You attempted an invalid OCI operation. 

You are using an Oracle client application linked version 7.1, or higher libraries, the environment ORA_ENCRYPT_LOGIN is set to TRUE, and you attempted to connect to a version 7.0, or lower, Oracle Server. 

You are connected to a version 7.1, or higher, Oracle Server, the initialization parameter DBLINK_ENCRYPT_LOGIN is set to TRUE, and you attempted to use a database link pointing to a version 7.0, or lower, Oracle Server.
column8:
From Oracle doc: For the above causes: 

Do not use the invalid OCI operation. 

If you do not wish to use encrypted connect passwords in your distributed database, set ORA_ENCRYPT_LOGIN to FALSE. If you wish to use encrypted connect passwords, you must upgrade all Oracle Servers to version 7.1, or higher. 

If you do not wish to use encrypted database links in your distributed database, set DBLINK_ENCRYPT_LOGIN to FALSE. If you wish to use encrypted database links, you must upgrade all Oracle Servers to version 7.1, or higher.

column6: cannot use V7 compatibility mode when talking to V6 server
column7: An attempt was made to use Oracle7 compatibility mode when accessing Oracle Version 6.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use V6 SQL language type. You may need to use the SET COMPATIBILITY V6 command.

column6: not logged on
column7: A host language program issued an Oracle call, other than OLON or OLOGON, without being logged on to Oracle. This can occur when a user process attempts to access the database after the instance it is connected to terminates, forcing the process to disconnect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log on to Oracle, by calling OLON or OLOGON, before issuing any Oracle calls. When the instance has been restarted, retry the action.

column6: user requested cancel of current operation
column7: The user interrupted an Oracle operation by entering CTRL-C, Control-C, or another canceling operation. This forces the current operation to end. This is an informational message only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Continue with the next operation.

column6: ORACLE shutdown in progress
column7: A user tried to log on to Oracle while an instance shutdown was in progress. Oracle logons are disabled while Oracle is being shut down.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until Oracle is brought back up before attempting to log on.

column6: logon called recursively
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: This function can be called only after a fetch
column7: The cursor is in an invalid state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the appropriate OCI/UPI function is called after the fetch and before the offending function.

column6: invalid username/password; logon denied
column7: An invalid username or password was entered in an attempt to log on to Oracle. The username and password must be the same as was specified in a GRANT CONNECT statement. If the username and password are entered together, the format is: username/password.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid username and password combination in the correct format.

column6: column does not have a LONG datatype
column7: An attempt was made to fetch data using the LONG fetch option, but the specified column was not LONG.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-execute the fetch without the LONG fetch option or create the table with a LONG column.

column6: unable to allocate memory in the user side
column7: The user side memory allocator returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the size of the process heap or switch to the old set of calls.

column6: unknown context state
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid context size specified
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: database operation not supported in this configuration
column7: The attempted database operation does not conform to the user programming interface (UPI) for the two communicating Oracle servers.
column8: From Oracle doc: You may need to upgrade one or more of your Oracle servers or re-link your user side application with new libraries. Report the problem to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Cursor context not found (Invalid cursor number)
column7: The cursor number is not a valid open cursor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the cursor is open.

column6: invalid datatype in OCI call
column7: An OCI program call specified an invalid datatype. In OCI calls, Oracle datatypes are specified as numbers between 1 and 7.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the datatype description and enter the correct number for the datatype.

column6: UPI parameter out of range
column7: An integer parameter to a UPI function is out of range.
column8: From Oracle doc: This usually indicates an error in a tool built on top of the Oracle DBMS. Report the error to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: multiple buffers of size > 4000 in the bind list
column7: More than one long buffer in the bind list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the buffer size to be less than 4000 for the bind variable bound to a normal column.

column6: bind variables not allowed for data definition operations
column7: An attempt was made to use a bind variable in a SQL data definition operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Such bind variables are not allowed.

column6: internal two task error
column7: Received send long message but do not have the cursor context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: internal two task error
column7: Received a request to send the long again when there is no long
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: SELECT ... INTO variable does not exist
column7: The SELECT... INTO specified in the bind call does not correspond to a variable in the SQL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: If it is not possible to correct the statement, call Oracle Customer Support.

column6: insufficient privileges
column7: An attempt was made to change the current username or password without the appropriate privilege. This error also occurs if attempting to install a database without the necessary operating system privileges. When Trusted Oracle is configure in DBMS MAC, this error may occur if the user was granted the necessary privilege at a higher label than the current login.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask the database administrator to perform the operation or grant the required privileges. For Trusted Oracle users getting this error although granted the appropriate privilege at a higher label, ask the database administrator to regrant the privilege at the appropriate label.

column6: no such userid
column7: This is an internal error message related to Export/Import.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: ORACLE initialization or shutdown in progress
column7: An attempt was made to log on while Oracle is being started or shut down.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait a few minutes. Then retry the operation.

column6: ORACLE not available
column7:
Oracle was not started. Possible causes include the following:

The SGA requires more space than was allocated for it. 

The operating-system variable pointing to the instance is improperly defined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to accompanying messages for possible causes and correct the problem mentioned in the other messages. If Oracle has been initialized, then on some operating systems, verify that Oracle was linked correctly. See the platform-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: ORACLE only available to users with RESTRICTED SESSION privilege
column7: Logins are disallowed because an instance started in restricted mode. Only users with RESTRICTED SESSION system privilege can log on.
column8: From Oracle doc: Request that Oracle be restarted without the restricted option or obtain the RESTRICTED SESSION system privilege.

column6: illegal variable name/number
column7: Unable to find bind context on user side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the variable being bound is in the SQL statement.

column6: maximum cursor memory exceeded
column7: An attempt was made to process a complex SQL statement which consumed all available memory of the cursor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Simplify the complex SQL statement. Alternatively, you can use the NO_EXPAND hint which prevents the cost-based optimizer from considering OR-expansion for queries having OR conditions or INLISTS in the WHERE clause. Usually, the optimizer considers using OR expansion and uses this method if it decides the cost is lower than not using it. Refer to Oracle8i Designing and Tuning for Performance for information about using hints.

column6: cannot write database file version %s with ORACLE version %s
column7: An attempt was made to write datafile headers in an old format. The new format cannot be used until after the database has been verified as being compatible with this software version.
column8: From Oracle doc: Open the database to advance to the new file formats, then repeat the operation. If the operation is required before the database can be opened, then use the previous software release to do the operation.

column6: insufficient privileges on underlying objects of the view
column7: An attempt was made to explain plan on other people's view without the necessary privileges on the underlying objects of the view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Get necessary privileges or do not perform the offending operation.

column6: invalid character in password; logon denied
column7: There are multibyte characters in the password or some characters in the password are not in US7ASCII range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit the password with valid characters.

column6: internal error. hostdef extension doesn't exist
column7: Pointer to HSTDEF extension in HSTDEF is null.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: detaching a session with open cursors not allowed
column7: An attempt was made to detach a session which had open cursors.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close all the cursors before detaching the session.

column6: user side memory corruption [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s]
column7: The application code corrupted some of the user memory used by Oracle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the application code is not overwriting memory.

column6: size %s of buffer bound to variable %s exceeds maximum %s
column7:
An attempt was made to bind a buffer whose total size would exceed the maximum size allowed. Total array size for arrays is calculated as:

(element_size)*(number of elements)
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the buffer size.

column6: user %s lacks CREATE SESSION privilege; logon denied
column7: A connect was attempted to a userid which does not have create session privilege.
column8: From Oracle doc: Grant the user CREATE SESSION privilege.

column6: cannot acquire space to extend context area
column7: Oracle could not extend the current area any further because the operating system would not supply any more space. A system-specific message should appear following this message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close some cursors and try again or check operating system quotas to use more virtual memory. See your operating system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: The above error occurred in schema=%s, package=%s, procedure=%s
column7: This message is displayed after a previous message to provide more specific information.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the cause and action for the previous message.

column6: Couldn't find the specified procedure in the given context
column7: The procedure user specified in deferred RPC does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure that the procedure exists and is visible to the replication process.

column6: Bind by name is not spupportted in streamed RPC
column7: This error occurs when a newer server version requests from an older server version an operation that is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: You may need to upgrade one or more of your Oracle servers or relink your user application with new libraries.

column6: cannot acquire space to open context area
column7: Oracle could not open a new context area because the operating system would not supply any more space. A system-specific message should appear following this message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close some cursors and try again or check operating system quotas to use more virtual memory. See your operating system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: deferred rpc buffer format invalid
column7: The deferred RPC data in SYS.DEF$_CALL is corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: required destination LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST is not specified
column7: A valid destination for parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST was not specified when parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST was set to 2.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify a value for parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST, or reduce the value for parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST to 1.

column6: user storage address cannot be read
column7: A bind variable or other user area could not be read by Oracle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that binds are done correctly on valid user buffers, then retry the operation.

column6: user storage address cannot be written
column7: A define, FETCH... INTO or SELECT... INTO, variable or other user area could not be written to by Oracle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that INTO variables and indicators are correctly specified. Then retry the operation.

column6: invalid or ambiguous block.field reference in user exit
column7: The reference to a block.field identifier in a user exit is incorrect or ambiguous, probably because it is misspelled or incomplete.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check syntax and identifier spelling. Then correct the reference.

column6: internal New Upi interface error
column7: Attempt to delete non-existent HSTDEF extension.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: parse expected before a bind or execute
column7: The client application attempted to bind a variable or execute a cursor opened in a PL/SQL block before the statement was parsed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the statement is parsed before a bind or execute.

column6: array binds or executes not allowed
column7: The client application attempted to bind an array of cursors or attempted to repeatedly execute against a PL/SQL block with a bind variable of type cursor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bind a single cursor or execute the PL/SQL block once.

column6: cannot start up a V8 server using a V7 client application
column7: You are using an Oracle client application linked with version 7 (or lower) libraries and you attempted to start up a V8 (or higher) server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a client application linked with V8 (or higher) libraries.

column6: Using an old version of Oracle for the server
column7: An attempt was made to run an older, obsolete Oracle Server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the server.

column6: cannot perform operation without starting up ORACLE
column7: An attempt was made to perform an operation before Oracle was started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Start Oracle. Then retry the operation.

column6: cannot stop ORACLE; ORACLE not running
column7: An attempt was made to stop Oracle, but Oracle was not running.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: fatal connection error: unrecognized call type
column7: An illegal internal operation was attempted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot shut down ORACLE; inside a login session - log off first
column7: An attempt was made to shut down Oracle inside a logon session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log off before shutting down Oracle.

column6: you are currently logged on
column7: An attempt was made to log on while already logged on.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: multiple logons per process not yet supported
column7: Oracle does not support multiple logons per process.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: background process initialization failure
column7: A failure occurred during initialization of the background processes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the diagnostic information in the accompanying message stack or in the trace file and take appropriate action.

column6: failure in processing system parameters
column7: Failure during processing of initialization parameters during system startup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Further diagnostic information should be in the error stack.

column6: ORACLE database was not properly created, operation aborted
column7: There was an error when the database or control file was created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check what error was signaled when the database was first created or when the control file was re-created. Take appropriate actions to re-create the database or a new control file.

column6: error in shutting down ORACLE
column7: A failure occurred during system shutdown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the diagnostic information in the accompanying message stack and take appropriate action.

column6: cannot start already-running ORACLE - shut it down first
column7: An attempt was made to start Oracle while it was already running.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down Oracle first, if you want to restart it.

column6: 'row_locking = always' requires the transaction processing option
column7: "row_locking = always" is specified in the INIT.ORA file. This feature is not supported by ORACLE without the transaction processing option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove it from INIT.ORA file or set it to "default" or "intent".

column6: value of parameter "%s" is inconsistent with that of other servers
column7: The value of the given initialization parameter is required to be the same for all servers in the parallel configuration.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value in the initialization parameter file to match that of the other control files.

column6: invalid argument in OCI call
column7: The failing OCI call contains an argument with an invalid value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use valid argument values. For more information, see the Oracle Call Interface Programmer's Guide and the appropriate programming language supplement.

column6: preceding errors in deferred rpc to "%s.%s.%s"
column7: Errors were encountered when the named procedure was executed as a deferred remote procedure call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the cause of the preceding errors.

column6: savepoint '%s' never established
column7: An attempt was made to roll back to a savepoint that was never established.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: cannot start up ORACLE - currently logged on
column7: An attempt was made to start up Oracle by a user who is currently logged on.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log off. Then issue the STARTUP command.

column6: cannot shut down ORACLE while active processes exist
column7: Users are still logged into the instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either wait for all users to logoff or use SHUTDOWN IMMEDIATE.

column6: immediate shutdown in progress - no operations are permitted
column7: The SHUTDOWN IMMEDIATE command was used to shut down a running Oracle instance, terminating any active operations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the instance to be restarted or contact the database administrator.

column6: shutdown in progress - connection is not permitted
column7: The SHUTDOWN command was used to shut down a running Oracle instance, disallowing any connects to Oracle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the instance to restart or contact the database administrator.

column6: failure during startup force
column7: Unable to destroy the old SGA.
column8: From Oracle doc: Manually remove the old SGA. See your operating system-specific Oracle documentation for instructions. Then retry the STARTUP command.

column6: ORACLE instance terminated. Disconnection forced
column7: The instance connected to was terminated abnormally, probably due to a SHUTDOWN ABORT. The current process was forced to disconnect from the instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the database administrator to determine when the instance is restarted. Attempt to reconnect after the instance is running again.

column6: ALTER DATABASE CLOSE only permitted with no sessions connected
column7: There is at lease one more session, other than the current one, logged in to the instance. ALTER DATABASE CLOSE is not permitted when other sessions are active.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the other sessions and disconnect them. Then retry the ALTER DATABASE CLOSE command. Also, issue the SHUTDOWN IMMEDIATE command to force users off the system, or issue the SHUTDOWN ABORT command to shut down the database without waiting for users to be forced off.

column6: ALTER DATABASE CLOSE in progress. Connections not permitted
column7: An attempt was made to connect while the database is being closed with the ALTER DATABASE CLOSE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt to connect again when the database is open. Contact the database administrator to find out when the database will be open.

column6: DML statement processed zero rows
column7: A DML cursor from the OTEX() call processed 0 rows when executed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Caller can either do a rollback or ignore the message and execute the rest of the cursors in the cursor array.

column6: program version (%s) incompatible with instance (%s)
column7: The program was linked with a different version of the server than the instance to which it is attempting to connect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Relink the program against the same version of Oracle as the instance or restart (startup force) the database using the program's version of the SERVER.

column6: cannot shutdown while in a transaction - commit or rollback first
column7: An attempt was made to shut down the database while a transaction was in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either commit or rollback the current transaction and then attempt to shut down the database.

column6: program Interface error during Long Insert
column7: The application program interface could not insert or update a LONG column because of an internal error when a TTCGETV call fails. For example, a network read error or one of the parameters passed to the call is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the insert or update.

column6: cannot mount database in SHARED mode if started in single process mode
column7: An attempt was made to mount a database in parallel mode with the initialization parameter SINGLE_PROCESS set to TRUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either mount the database in EXCLUSIVE mode or set the initialization parameter SINGLE_PROCESS to FALSE before starting the instance in parallel (shared) mode.

column6: database already mounted
column7: An attempt was made to mount a database with the name of a currently mounted database.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: database being created currently mounted by some other instance
column7: Some other instance has the database of same name currently mounted and you are trying to create it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either change the database name or shut down the other instance.

column6: cannot mount database in EXCLUSIVE mode
column7: Some other instance has the database mounted exclusive or shared.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the other instance or mount in a compatible mode.

column6: database name '%s' in controlfile is not '%s'
column7: The database name in the control file does not match your database name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either find the correct control file or change your database name.

column6: number of controlfiles (%s) does not equal %s
column7: The number of control files used by this instance disagrees with the number of control files in an existing instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure that all control files are listed.

column6: mount is incompatible with mounts by other instances
column7: An attempt to mount the database discovered that another instance mounted a database by the same name, but the mount is not compatible. Additional errors are reported explaining why.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying errors.

column6: database must be closed before dismounting
column7: An attempt was made to dismount a database before it was closed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close the database, then retry the operation.

column6: database must be mounted for media recovery
column7: An attempt to perform media recovery was made but the database is not mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount the database.

column6: file %s is in backup or media recovery"
column7: Either media recovery is actively being applied to the file, or it is being backed up while the database is in NOARCHIVELOG mode. It cannot be used for normal database access or crash recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete or cancel the media recovery session or backup.

column6: database not open
column7: A command was attempted that requires the database to be open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Open the database and try the command again.

column6: data file %s: '%s'
column7: This message reports the file name involved with other messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the associated messages for a description of the problem.

column6: name for data file %s is unknown - rename to correct file
column7: The datafile was missing from a CREATE CONTROLFILE command or BACKUP CONTROLFILE RECOVERY was done with a control file that was saved before the file was created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rename the MISSING file to the name of the real file.

column6: media recovery not started
