column7: An attempt to continue media recovery is being made but media recovery was not started.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: file %s needs media recovery
column7: An attempt was made to open a datafile that is in need of media recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: First apply media recovery to the datafile identified in the message, then retry the operation.

column6: IO error writing block to file %s (block # %s)
column7: The device on which the file resides is probably off line.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore access to the device, then retry the operation.

column6: IO error reading block from file %s (block # %s)
column7: The device on which the file resides is probably off line.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore access to the device, then retry the operation.

column6: error in opening database file %s
column7: Usually the file is not accessible.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the datafile is in the expected location and can be accessed properly, then retry the operation.

column6: adding file '%s' with illegal block size: %s; limit is %s
column7: An attempt was made to add a datafile with a block size that is greater than the maximum block size allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation with a smaller block size.

column6: cannot add any more database files: limit of %s exceeded
column7: An attempt to add a datafile failed because the limit for such files had already been reached.
column8: From Oracle doc: If more database space is required, export the database and re-create it with a higher limit for datafiles and perhaps increased file size.

column6: error in creating database file '%s'
column7: Insufficient space on device.
column8: From Oracle doc: Decrease the size of the requested file or allocate a file on another device with more available space. If a file size was not specified in the statement, then specify a file size smaller than the available space on the device.

column6: cannot remove online database file %s
column7: An attempt was made to drop a datafile when it is online.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take file offline before dropping.

column6: cannot rename database file %s - file is in use or recovery
column7: An attempt was made to use ALTER DATABASE RENAME to rename a datafile that is online in an open instance or is being recovered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close database in all instances and end all recovery sessions.

column6: database file %s failed verification check
column7: The information in this file is inconsistent with information from the control file. See accompanying message for reason.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make certain that the database files and control files are the correct files for this database.

column6: cannot start online backup; media recovery not enabled
column7: An attempt to start backup of an online tablespace failed because media recovery is not enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable media recovery and retry this operation.

column6: cannot recover data file %s - file is in use or recovery
column7: An attempt to do media recovery found that the file was not available for recovery. Either it is online and the database is open in some instance, or another process is currently doing media recovery on the file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not do media recovery.

column6: cannot disable media recovery - file %s has online backup set
column7: An attempt to disable media recovery found that an online backup is still in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: End the backup of the offending tablespace and retry this command.

column6: database must be mounted EXCLUSIVE and not open for this operation
column7: An operation failed because the database was not mounted in exclusive mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down Oracle and mount the database in exclusive mode.

column6: database name '%s' exceeds size limit of %s characters
column7: The specified database name is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shorten the database name to eight characters or fewer, then retry the operation.

column6: cannot start online backup - file %s is offline
column7: An attempt to start an online backup found that one of the files is offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the offending files online and retry this command or do a cold backup.

column6: user's default or temporary tablespace does not exist
column7: The user's default or temporary tablespace was dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reassign the default or temporary tablespace.

column6: database file version %s incompatible with ORACLE version %s
column7: The named datafile was created under an incompatible version of Oracle, or the file is invalid or non-existent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down and restart the correct version of Oracle or check the references to the datafile and make sure it exists.

column6: DB_FILES system parameter value %s exceeds limit of %s
column7: The specified value of the initialization parameter DB_FILES is too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the value of the DB_FILES parameter and retry the operation.

column6: length of database file name '%s' exceeds limit of %s characters
column7: The specified datafile name is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shorten the file name and retry the operation.

column6: length of log file name '%s' exceeds limit of %s characters
column7: The specified redo log file name is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shorten the file name and retry the operation.

column6: database mounted exclusive by another instance
column7: An attempt to access a database failed because it is mounted in exclusive mode by another instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either shut down the other instance or wait for the other instance to either close the database or mount it in parallel mode, before retrying the operation.

column6: file %s accessed for DML/query is offline
column7: An attempt was made to access a datafile that is offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the datafile back online.

column6: specified size of file %s (%s blocks) is less than original size of %s blocks
column7: A file size was specified in the AS clause of ALTER DATABASE CREATE DATAFILE, and the size was smaller than the size needed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the file with a larger size.

column6: data file %s is still in the middle of going offline
column7: It was not possible to get the lock for a file that is offline when attempting to bring it online. The most likely cause is that the lock is still held by the instance that is took it offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the other instance to release the lock on the file.

column6: database must either be open in this instance or not at all
column7: The requested operation cannot be done when the database is mounted but not open in this instance, and another instance has the database open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute the operation in an open instance, open the database in this instance, or close the database in the other instances.

column6: RESETLOGS option only valid after an incomplete database recovery
column7: The RESETLOGS option was given in ALTER DATABASE OPEN, but there has been no incomplete recovery session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the ALTER DATABASE OPEN without specifying RESETLOGS.

column6: cannot end online backup - all files are offline
column7: All the files were found to be offline when attempting to end an online backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. Online backup does not need to be ended for this tablespace.

column6: error renaming data file %s - new file '%s' not found
column7: An attempt to change a datafile's name in the control file failed because no file was found with the new name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the datafile has been properly renamed by the operating system and retry.

column6: cannot end online backup - none of the files are in backup
column7: None of the files were found to be in online backup when attempting to end an online backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. Online backup does not need to be ended for this tablespace.

column6: cannot disable media recovery - file %s needs media recovery
column7: An attempt to disable media recovery found a file that needs media recovery, thus media recovery cannot be disabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recover the offending file or drop the tablespace it belongs to and retry this command.

column6: File size (%s blocks) exceeds maximum of %s blocks
column7: Specified file size is larger than maximum allowable size value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a smaller size.

column6: offline immediate disallowed unless media recovery enabled
column7: ALTER TABLESPACE ... OFFLINE IMMEDIATE or ALTER DATABASE DATAFILE ... OFFLINE is only allowed if database is in ARCHIVELOG mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the tablespace offline as usual or do a shutdown abort before attempting the required operation. It is worthwhile reconsidering the backup strategy for the database. The attempted operations can be done if ARCHIVEREDO LOG mode is enabled.

column6: cannot start online backup - file %s is already in backup
column7: An attempt was made to start an online backup, but an online backup was already started for one of the datafiles.
column8: From Oracle doc: End the first backup before beginning another.

column6: SYSTEM tablespace file %s is offline
column7: A file belonging to the SYSTEM tablespace has been marked offline by the database administrator. The database cannot be started until all SYSTEM tablespace files are online and can be opened.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the file online.

column6: can not mount database PARALLEL without a lock manager installed
column7: An attempt was made to mount the database PARALLEL without the existence of a Lock Manager.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount the database in EXCLUSIVE mode.

column6: cannot shutdown - file %s has online backup set
column7: An attempt to shut down normally found that an online backup is still in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: End the backup of the offending tablespace and retry this command.

column6: cannot prevent writes - file %s has online backup set
column7: Tablespace cannot be taken offline or made read-only when online backup is running. Ending the backup entails writing the file header, which this operation, were it permitted, would prevent.
column8: From Oracle doc: End the online backup and then take the tablespace offline or make it read-only.

column6: use media recovery to recover block, restore backup if needed
column7: Crash recovery or instance recovery could not apply a change to a block because it was not the next change. This can happen if the block was corrupted and then repaired during recovery. This message is usually accompanied by ORA-01172.
column8: From Oracle doc: There is additional information for ORA-01172. Perform a RECOVER datafile for the file containing the block. If this does not resolve the problem, restore the file from a backup and recover it again.

column6: file %s was not restored from a sufficiently old backup
column7: An incomplete recovery session was started, but an insufficient number of redo logs were applied to make the database consistent. This file is still in the future of the last redo log applied. The most likely cause of this message is forgetting to restore the file from backup before doing incomplete recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Apply additional redo log files until the database is consistent or restore the datafiles from an older backup and repeat recovery.

column6: an incompatible media recovery is active
column7: Attempt to start an incompatible media recovery or open resetlogs during media recovery. Media recovery sessions are incompatible if they attempt to recover the same datafile. Incomplete media recovery or open resetlogs is incompatible with any media recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete or cancel the other media recovery session.

column6: database busy. Open, close, mount, and dismount not allowed now
column7: Some operation is in progress that expects the state of the instance to remain open or mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the operation to complete and try again. If attempting a normal database shutdown, try SHUTDOWN ABORT.

column6: the database is being opened, closed, mounted or dismounted
column7: The attempted operation will not succeed while the instance is in one of the states mentioned in the message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the open, close, mount, or dismount to complete and try again. If attempting a normal database shutdown, try SHUTDOWN ABORT.

column6: recovery in progress may need access to files
column7: Either media or instance recovery is in progress. The recovery may need access to the files that the attempted operation tried to use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the recovery to complete and try again.

column6: cannot identify/lock data file %s - see DBWR trace file
column7: The background process was either unable to find one of the data files or failed to lock it because the file was already in use. The database will prohibit access to this file but other files will be unaffected. However, the first instance to open the database will need to access all online data files. The accompanying error from the operating system describes why the file could not be identified.
column8: From Oracle doc: At the operating system level, make the file available to the database. Then either open the database or do an ALTER SYSTEM CHECK DATAFILES.

column6: database %s already mounted
column7: Another instance has a database by this name mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find which instance is still running. Perhaps you have not lost the control files after all.

column6: file is not from same database as previous files - wrong database id
column7: Not all of the files specified in CREATE CONTROLFILE are from the same database. The database ID of this file does not match that from the first file specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the list of files provided to the CREATE.

column6: file is not a %s
column7: The named file in the DATAFILE or LOGFILE section of the CREATE CONTROLFILE command does not appear to be as stated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the mentioned file.

column6: database name %s in file header does not match given name of %s
column7: The database name given at the command line does not match the database name found in the file header.
column8: From Oracle doc: Chance are good that the database name specified at the command line is incorrect. Resolve the discrepancy, and resubmit the command. If you are attempting to change the database name, be sure to use the SET DATABASE option.

column6: block size %s in file header does not match DB_BLOCK_SIZE (%s)
column7: CREATE CONTROLFILE discovered that the block size for this file is incompatible with the initialization parameter DB_BLOCK_SIZE used to allocate cache buffers. If not the first file then there are a mixture of block sizes, or the file is corrupt.
column8: From Oracle doc: If this is the first file in the command then correct DB_BLOCK_SIZE to match the file and restart the instance. If not the first file find the correct version of the file.

column6: SIZE clause indicates %s (blocks), but should match header %s
column7: The size specified in bytes in the SIZE clause of the CREATE CONTROLFILE statement does not equate to the number of blocks recorded in the header.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct file name and size (in bytes).

column6: MAXLOGFILES may not exceed %s
column7: MAXLOGFILES specified on the command line too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit the command with a smaller value for MAXLOGFILES.

column6: MAXDATAFILES may not exceed %s
column7: MAXDATAFILES specified on the command line too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit the command with a smaller value for MAXDATAFILES.

column6: file number %s is larger than %s (%s)
column7: File mentioned in CREATE CONTROLFILE has a file number which is larger than that specified for MAXDATAFILES or MAXLOGFILES.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the maximum specified on the command line.

column6: two files are the same file/group number or the same file
column7: There is an overlap of file numbers in the files specified on the command line or the same file is specified twice. If they are not the exact same file then one is likely to be a backup of the other. If they are two members of the same log they must be specified together in a group file specification. This message will also appear if the same control file appears more than once in the CONTROL_FILES parameter in the INIT.ORA file. If this happens, check for additional error messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the file mentioned is not a repeat of a file already mentioned in the command. If they are different files then omit the earlier backup. If they are members of the same log, insure they are in the same group file specification. If this message appears because of a duplicate control file, check the CONTROL_FILES parameter in the INIT.ORA file and see if a file is specified more than once. If all files names appear to be unique, check to make sure that the actual control files themselves are unique. For example, in UNIX check for a symbolic or a hard link to another control file in the list.

column6: physical block size %s does not match size %s of other members
column7: The file is located on a device with a different physical block size than the other members in the group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a physical device with matching block size.

column6: DATAFILE number 1 not found. Must be present
column7: Datafile number 1 was not specified in a CREATE CONTROLFILE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Locate datafile number 1 and resubmit the CREATE CONTROLFILE command.

column6: file not found '%s'
column7: A file specified in the CREATE CONTROLFILE statement was not found. All datafiles and all redo log files, if NORESETLOGS was used, must be accessible by the process that issues the CREATE CONTROLFILE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement for a typing mistake in the file name and check for the existence of all files. Then issue the statement again after correcting the file names.

column6: datafile %s going offline due to error advancing checkpoint
column7: The checkpoint in the file header could not be advanced. See accompanying errors for the reason. The datafile will be taken offline the same as for a write error of a data block.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying errors for details. Restore access to the file, do media recovery, and bring it back online.

column6: recovery of thread %s stuck at block %s of file %s
column7: Crash recovery or instance recovery could not apply a change to a block because it was not the next change. This can happen if the block was corrupted and then repaired during recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do a RECOVER DATAFILE for the file containing the block. If this does not resolve the problem, then restore the file from a backup and recover it.

column6: data dictionary indicates missing data file from system tablespace
column7:
One of the following:

The database is recovered to a point in time in the future of the control file. 

A datafile from the system tablespace is omitted from the issued CREATE CONTROLFILE statement.
column8:
From Oracle doc: One of the following:

Recover the database from a more recent control file. 

Re-create the control file, ensuring all datafiles are included for the system tablespace in the command line.

column6: DB_FILES is %s buts needs to be %s to be compatible
column7: The maximum number of database files supported by this instance is not the same as for the other instances. All instances must be able to open all the files any instance can open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of the DB_FILES parameter to be compatible.

column6: data dictionary has more than the %s files allowed by the instance
column7: The data dictionary is found to have more files than that which can be supported by this instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the instance and restart with a larger value for DB_FILES.

column6: data dictionary has more than the %s files allowed by the controlfie
column7: After a CREATE CONTROLFILE, the data dictionary was found to have more datafiles than that supported by the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the control file with a larger value for MAXDATAFILES.

column6: data file does not match dictionary - probably old incarnation
column7: When comparing the control file with the data dictionary after a CREATE CONTROLFILE or OPEN RESETLOGS, it was noted that this datafile was inconsistent with the dictionary. Most likely the file is a backup of a file that was dropped from the database, and the same file number was reused for a new file. It may also be that an incomplete recovery stopped at a time when this file number was used for another datafile.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do a CREATE CONTROLFILE with the correct file or none at all.

column6: file %s created before last CREATE CONTROLFILE, cannot recreate
column7: An attempt was made to use ALTER DATABASE CREATE DATAFILE to re-create a datafile that existed at the last CREATE CONTROL file command. The information needed to re-create the file was lost with the control file that existed when the file was added to the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find a backup of the file, and recover it. Do incomplete recovery to time before file was originally created.

column6: file %s does not exist
column7: During datafile recovery, a file was listed that was not part of the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recheck the file name. Remember to use single quotation marks at the SQL*DBA command line. Remember also that the file name is translated in the operating environment of SQL*DBA.

column6: can not create datafile 1
column7: An attempt was made to create datafile 1 using ALTER DATABASE CREATE DATAFILE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recover file from a backup or re-create the database.

column6: file %s created before last RESETLOGS, cannot recreate
column7: An attempt was made to use ALTER DATABASE CREATE DATAFILE to re-create a datafile that existed at the last RESETLOGS database open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find a backup of the file, and recover it. Do incomplete recovery to time before file was originally created.

column6: cannot create database file %s - file is in use or recovery
column7: An attempt was made to use ALTER DATABASE CREATE DATAFILE to re-create a datafile that is online in an open instance or is being recovered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close database in all instances and end all recovery sessions.

column6: cannot mount database in SHARED mode
column7: Some other instance has the database mounted exclusive.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the other instance and then mount shared.

column6: logfile group %s already exists
column7: An ALTER DATABASE ADD LOGFILE command specified a log number for the new log which is already in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different log file number, or let the database choose an unused value.

column6: logfile group number %s is invalid
column7: An ALTER DATABASE ADD LOGFILE command specified a log number for the new log which is too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a correct log file number.

column6: file %s failed verification tests
column7: The datafile did not pass the checks to insure it is part of the database. See the accompanying error messages for the reason the verification failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the correct file available to the database. Then, either open the database, or execute ALTER SYSTEM CHECK DATAFILES.

column6: cannot read from file %s because it failed verification tests
column7: The datafile did not pass the checks to insure it is part of the database. Reads are not allowed until it is verified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the correct file available to the database. Then, either open the database, or execute ALTER SYSTEM CHECK DATAFILES.

column6: Block size %s in header does not match physical block size %s
column7: A log file member given to CREATE CONTROLFILE is on a physical device that has a different block size than the device originally used to create the log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Move the file to a device with the correct block size or use the RESETLOGS option to CREATE CONTROLFILE.

column6: file is from a different RESETLOGS than previous files
column7: In a CREATE CONTROLFILE command, either this file or all previous files were backups from before the last RESETLOGS. This may also occur if this is a file that is offline and has been offline since before the last RESETLOGS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the file was taken offline normal before the last RESETLOGS, and is still offline, omit it from the CREATE CONTROLFILE command. Rename and online the file after the database is open. Otherwise find the version of the mentioned file consistent with the rest of the datafiles and resubmit the command.

column6: controlfile or data file %s is from before the last RESETLOGS
column7: An attempt was made to use a datafile when the log reset information in the file does not match the control file. Either the datafile or the control file is a backup that was made before the most recent ALTER DATABASE OPEN RESETLOGS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore file from a more recent backup.

column6: file %s is already offline - cannot do a normal offline
column7: When attempting to do a normal tablespace offline, it was discovered that one of the files in the tablespace was already offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either bring the datafile online first, or use another tablespace offline option.

column6: must have at least one enabled thread
column7: At least two redo log files from at least one thread must be specified in the CREATE CONTROLFILE command line.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the missing redo log files and retry the command with the newly found redo log files included in the command line.

column6: file %s is not the same file seen at start of recovery
column7: A different copy of the file was accessed the last time media recovery looked at the file header. A backup of the file was restored or the meaning of the file name changed during recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the correct file is available, and then retry recovery.

column6: file %s needs more recovery to be consistent
column7: An incomplete recovery session was started, but an insufficient number of logs were applied to make the file consistent. The reported file was not closed cleanly when it was last opened by the database. It must be recovered to a time when it was not being updated. The most likely cause of this error is forgetting to restore the file from a backup before doing incomplete recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either apply more logs until the file is consistent or restore the file from an older backup and repeat recovery.

column6: online backup of file %s needs more recovery to be consistent
column7: An incomplete recovery session was started, but an insufficient number of logs were applied to make the file consistent. The reported file is an online backup which must be recovered to the time the backup ended.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either apply more logs until the file is consistent or restore the database files from an older backup and repeat recovery.

column6: file %s is inconsistent due to a failed media recovery session
column7: The file was being recovered but the recovery did not terminate normally. This left the file in an inconsistent state. No more recovery was successfully completed on this file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either apply more logs until the file is consistent or restore the backup again and repeat recovery.

column6: thread %s only contains one log
column7: During CREATE CONTROLFILE all threads represented in the logs must be represented by at least two logs. A "last log" and a second log. The named thread does not contain two such logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either find more logs from the named thread. Or use the RESETLOGS option to CREATE CONTROLFILE.

column6: must specify size for log file if RESETLOGS
column7: File sizes must be given for all log files if doing a CREATE CONTROLFILE with the RESETLOGS option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit the command with the appropriate log file size.

column6: file %s is not in online backup mode
column7: An attempt was made to end an online backup for a file that is not in online backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not enter command since it is not needed.

column6: actual file size of %s is smaller than correct size of %s blocks
column7: The size of the file as returned by the operating system is smaller than the size of the file as indicated in the file header and the control file. Somehow the file has been truncated. Maybe it is the result of a half completed copy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a good copy of the datafile and do recovery as needed.

column6: file %s header failed to write correctly
column7: An I/O error was reported for the file header. The error was trapped and a second attempt will be made.
column8: From Oracle doc: The file probably will require recovery. Further error messages will indicate what is needed.

column6: wrong incarnation of this file - wrong creation time
column7: The creation time in the file header is not the same as the creation time in the control file. This is probably a copy of a file that was dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a current copy of the datafile and do recovery as needed.

column6: wrong incarnation of this file - wrong creation SCN
column7: The creation SCN in the file header is not the same as the creation SCN in the control file. This is probably a copy of a file that was dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a current copy of the datafile and do recovery as needed.

column6: file number is %s rather than %s - wrong file
column7: The file number in the file header is not correct. This is probably a restored backup of the wrong file, but from the same database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a copy of the correct datafile and do recovery as needed.

column6: not a data file - type number in header is %s
column7: The file type in the header is not correct for a datafile. This is probably a log file or control file. If the type is not a small non-zero positive number then the header is corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a copy of the correct datafile and do recovery as needed.

column6: file is not part of this database - wrong database id
column7: The database ID in the file header does not match the database ID in the control file. The file may be from a different database, or it may not be a database file at all. If the database was rebuilt, this may be a file from before the rebuild. Note that if you see this error when the file is supposed to be plugged in from another database via the Transportable Tablespace feature, it means the database ID in the file header does not match the one expected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore a copy of the correct datafile and do recovery as needed.

column6: file is more recent than controlfile - old controlfile
column7: The control file change sequence number in the datafile is greater than the number in the control file. This implies that the wrong control file is being used. Note that repeatedly causing this error can make it stop happening without correcting the real problem. Every attempt to open the database will advance the control file change sequence number until it is great enough.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the current control file or do BACKUP CONTROLFILE RECOVERY to make the control file current. Be sure to follow all restrictions on doing a BACKUP CONTROLFILE RECOVERY.

column6: data file is an old version - not accessing current version
column7: The checkpoint in the file header is less recent than in the control file. If opening a database that is already open by another instance, or if another instance just brought this file online, the file accessed by this instance is probably a different version. Otherwise, a backup of the file probably was restored while the file was in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the correct file available to the database. Then, either open the database, or execute ALTER SYSTEM CHECK DATAFILES.

column6: data file is from before the last RESETLOGS
column7: The reset log data in the file header does not match the control file. If the database is closed or the file is offline, the backup is old because it was taken before the last ALTER DATABASE OPEN RESETLOGS command. If opening a database that is open already by another instance, or if another instance just brought this file online, the file accessed by this instance is probably a different version. Otherwise, a backup of the file probably was restored while the file was in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the correct file available to the database. Then, either open the database or execute ALTER SYSTEM CHECK DATAFILES.

column6: data file header is media corrupt
column7: The file header block is internally inconsistent. The beginning of the block has a header with a checksum and other data for insuring the consistency of the block. It is possible that the last disk write did not operate correctly. The most likely problem is that this is not a datafile for any database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Have operating system make correct file available to database. If the trace file dump indicates that only the checksum is wrong, restore from a backup and do media recovery.

column6: Oracle7 data file is not from migration to Oracle8
column7: The file is not a copy of the file LAST used under Oracle7. This datafile is either a backup taken from before the migration, or the database was opened by Oracle7 after the migration utility was run. When converting a database from Oracle7 to Oracle8, the migration program MUST be the LAST utility to access the database under Oracle7. Only the datafiles that were current when the migration was done may be accessed by Oracle8.
column8: From Oracle doc: Have operating system make correct datafile available to database, or repeat the Oracle7 to Oracle8 migration. Make sure that database is NOT opened after migration utility is run.

column6: MAXLOGMEMBERS may not exceed %s
column7: MAXLOGMEMBERS specified on the command line too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit the command with a smaller value for MAXLOGMEMBERS.

column6: MAXINSTANCES may not exceed %s
column7: MAXINSTANCES specified on the command line too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit the command with a smaller value for MAXINSTANCES.

column6: MAXLOGHISTORY may not exceed %s
column7: MAXLOGHISTORY specified on the command line too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit the command with a smaller value for MAXLOGHISTORY.

column6: enabled thread %s is missing after CREATE CONTROLFILE
column7: A CREATE CONTROLFILE statement was given which did not list all the enabled threads for the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the CREATE CONTROLFILE statement, including all enabled threads.

column6: thread %s is expected to be disabled after CREATE CONTROLFILE
column7: A thread that was given during CREATE CONTROLFILE is enabled, but the datafiles indicate that it should be disabled. This is probably because the logs supplied to the CREATE CONTROLFILE are old (from before the disabling of the thread).
column8: From Oracle doc: This thread is not required to run the database. The CREATE CONTROLFILE statement can be reissued without the problem thread, and, if desired, the thread can be re-created after the database is open.

column6: logfile member belongs to a different logfile group
column7: A member of a multiple-member log file group specified in a CREATE CONTROLFILE is not part of the same group as previous members.
column8: From Oracle doc: Group together the correct members for the CREATE CONTROLFILE command.

column6: logfile member is not from the same point-in-time
column7: A member of a multiple-member log file group is from a different point in time. One of the members specified may be an older (backup) copy of the log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct version of the log, or leave it out of the CREATE CONTROLFILE command.

column6: database not open: queries allowed on fixed tables/views only
column7: A query was issued against an object not recognized as a fixed table or fixed view before the database has been opened.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-phrase the query to include only fixed objects, or open the database.

column6: file based sort illegal before database is open
column7: A query issued against a fixed table or view required a temporary segment for sorting before the database was open. Only in-memory sorts are supported before the database is open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-phrase the query to avoid a large sort, increase the values of the SORT_AREA_SIZE and/or SORT_AREA_RETAINED_SIZE initialization parameters to enable the sort to be done in memory.

column6: data file %s is not the same file to a background process
column7: When the database writer opens the datafile, it is accessing a different physical file than the foreground doing the recovery. The timestamp set in the file header by the foreground was not found by the background. It may be that the background process could not read the file at all.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look in the DBWR trace file for the error it received when attempting to read the file header. Reconfigure the operating system as needed to have the file name successfully access the same file when opened by a background process.

column6: MAXINSTANCES of %s requires MAXLOGFILES be at least %s, not %s
column7: An attempt was made to create a database or control file that does not have room for at least two logs per thread of redo. A thread of redo must have two online logs in order to be enabled. It does not make sense to allow more redo threads than can be supported by the logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either reduce the MAXINSTANCES argument or increase the value of MAXLOGFILES.

column6: RESETLOGS must be specified to set a new database name
column7: The SET database name option was specified to CREATE CONTROLFILE, but RESETLOGS was not specified. The database name can only be changed when opening the database with RESETLOGS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either add the RESETLOGS option or drop the SET option to CREATE CONTROLFILE.

column6: group number in header %s does not match GROUP %s
column7: Group number specified at CREATE CONTROLFILE does not match the group number stored in the header. Most likely the specification is wrong.
column8: From Oracle doc: Omit the GROUP option or give the correct one.

column6: thread number %s is greater than MAXINSTANCES %s
column7: The log is for a thread greater than the MAXINSTANCES argument.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value for MAXINSTANCES and resubmit the command.

column6: file header of log member is inconsistent with other members
column7: The log file member in the accompanying error is for the same group as the previous members, but other fields in the header are different. Either a file header is corrupted, or some file is a member of a deleted log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct log member or omit this member from the command.

column6: log %s is inconsistent with other logs
column7: The log file in the accompanying error is inconsistent with the contents of other logs given in the CREATE CONTROLFILE command. Either a file header is corrupted, or some file is an old copy rather than the current version. The problem may not be with the log listed since all that can be detected is that there is an inconsistency. All log files listed in the command must be the current versions of the online logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct online logs or use the RESETLOGS option.

column6: SET DATABASE option required to install seed database
column7: The SET DATABASE option was not included in the CREATE CONTROLFILE command when installing a seed database. The database does not have a database ID because it is intended to be installed at multiple sites, and each site needs to be a different database with its own database id. Both the SET DATABASE and RESETLOGS options must be specified to create the control file for this database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit command with the SET DATABASE and RESETLOGS options.

column6: data file %s is inconsistent with logs
column7: The datafile in the accompanying error is inconsistent with the contents of the logs given in the CREATE CONTROLFILE command. The most likely cause is that one or more of the online logs was missing from the command. It is also possible that one or more of the logs is an old copy rather than the current version. All online log files must be listed in the command and must be the current versions of the online logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the correct online logs or use the RESETLOGS option.

column6: cannot make read only - file %s is offline
column7: An attempt to make a tablespace read only found that one of its files is offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the file online and retry this command.

column6: cannot make read write - file %s is offline
column7: An attempt to make a tablespace read write found that one of its files is offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the file online and retry this command.

column6: cannot start online backup - file %s is read only
column7: An attempt to start an online backup found that one of the files is marked read only. Read-only files do not need to be set into online backup mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the backup without the begin backup command.

column6: file %s is read only - cannot recover using backup controlfile
column7: An attempt to do media recovery using a backup control file found that one of the files is marked read only. Read-only files do not normally need to be recovered, but recovery with a backup control file must recover all online files.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the file really is read only, take it offline before the recovery, and bring the read-only tablespace online after the database is open. If the file does need recovery use a control file from the time the file was read-write. If the correct control file is not available, use CREATE CONTROLFILE to make one.

column6: cannot end backup of file %s - file is in use or recovery
column7: An attempt was made to end an online backup of file when the file is busy. Some operation such as recovery or rename may be active, or there may still be some instance that has the database open with this file online.
column8: From Oracle doc: If there is an instance with the database open then the backup can be ended there by using the ALTER TABLESPACE command. Otherwise wait for the completion of the other operation.

column6: END BACKUP failed for %s file(s) and succeeded for %s
column7: One or more of the files in an end backup command failed. Some other files given in the same command may have succeeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the accompanying error messages for the reason the backups could not be ended. Any files not listed in the error messages were successful.

column6: Error %s occurred during initialization of file header access
column7: The indicated error occurred while doing initialization processing of file headers.
column8: From Oracle doc: The error indicated should be corrected. An attempt is made to recover from this error by using a slower access algorithm.

column6: cannot extend datafile %s
column7: An operating system error occurred during the resize.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the cause of the operating system error and retry the command.

column6: cannot shrink datafile %s
column7: An operating system error occurred during the resize.
column8: From Oracle doc: The error is ignored, operation continues normally.

column6: database must be in ARCHIVELOG mode to use external cache
column7: An online file uses an external cache, but the database is in NOARCHIVELOG mode. Since an external cache may require media recovery this cannot be allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change database to be in ARCHIVELOG mode or do not use an external cache.

column6: too many data files to add in one command
column7: The command specifies adding more datafiles than can be done in one command. It is necessary to fit all the file names into one log entry, but that would make the entry too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: If this is a CREATE TABLESPACE command, create with fewer files then add the other files later. If this is an ADD DATAFILE command, break it up into multiple commands.

column6: an external cache has died
column7: The external cache may have been restarted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the file mentioned in the error stack offline, perform media recovery, bring the file online, and retry the attempted operation. You may also restart all instances to make sure they access all datafiles through consistent external caches.

column6: data file suffered media failure: database in NOARCHIVELOG mode
column7: The database is in NOARCHIVELOG mode and a database file was detected as inaccessible due to media failure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore accessibility to the file mentioned in the error stack and restart the instance.

column6: system tablespace file suffered media failure
column7: A system tablespace file was detected as inaccessible due to media failure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore accessibility to the file mentioned in the error stack and restart the instance.

column6: unnamed datafile(s) added to controlfile by media recovery
column7: Media recovery with a backup control file or a control file that was rebuilt, encountered the creation of a datafile that was not in the control file. An entry has been added to the control file for the new datafiles, but with the file name UNNAMEDnnnn, where nnnn is the file number. Attached errors describe the file names that were originally used to create the files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rename the files to valid file names and resume recovery. If necessary the command ALTER DATABASE CREATE DATAFILE may be used to create a file suitable for recovery and do the rename. If the file is not going to be recovered then take it offline with the FOR DROP option.

column6: offline file %s will be lost if RESETLOGS is done
column7: An attempt was made to do an OPEN RESETLOGS with a file that will be lost because it is offline. The file was not taken offline with the FOR DROP option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either bring the file online and recover it, or take it offline with the FOR DROP option.

column6: recovering files through TSPITR of tablespace %s
column7: The files named in the accompanying errors are backups that were made before a tablespace point in time recovery of this tablespace. They cannot be recovered to a time after the point in time recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore more recent backups and recover them.

column6: database recovery through TSPITR of tablespace %s
column7: Recovery of the whole database encountered redo indicating there was a point in time recovery of the tablespace. The new version of the files in the tablespace should be included in the recovery, but that was not done.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the tablespace should not be recovered, take its file offline for drop. If it should be recovered, then restore or rename as needed and restart the recovery.

column6: file %s was created in the future of incomplete recovery
column7: An attempt was made to do a RESETLOGS open with a file entry in the control file that was originally created after the UNTIL time of the incomplete recovery. Allowing such an entry may hide the version of the file that is needed at this time. The file number may be in use for a different file which would be lost if the RESETLOGS was allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: If more recovery is desired then apply redo until the creation time of the file is reached. If the file is not wanted and the same file number is not in use at the stop time of the recovery, then the file can be taken offline with the FOR DROP option. Otherwise a different control file is needed to allow the RESETLOGS. Another backup can be restored and recovered, or a control file can be created via CREATE CONTROLFILE.

column6: archiving not allowed in a clone database
column7: An attempt was made to archive an online redo log or enable archiving for a clone database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to archive from a clone. The archive log destination could easily be the same as the primary database destroying its archived logs. If archiving is needed, then re-create the database not as a clone.

column6: Error %s occurred during termination of file header access
column7: The indicated error occurred while terminating the processing of file headers. The error was other than a write error.
column8: From Oracle doc: The indicated error should be corrected.

column6: Unknown File Header Version read for file number %s
column7: Read of the file header returned a record but its version cannot be identified. Either the header has been corrupted, or the file is not a valid database file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Have the operating system make the correct file available to the database, or recover the file.

column6: cannot prevent writes - file %s in recovery manager backup
column7: An attempt to make a tablespace read only or offline normal found that a recovery manager proxy backup is in progress. If the file is made offline or read only, then the file header cannot be updated when the backup is complete.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the Recovery Manager backup to complete and retry this command.

column6: cannot start online backup - file %s in recovery manager backup
column7: The specified file is being backed up by Recovery Manager.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the Recovery Manager proxy backup to complete before starting another backup.

column6: cannot end online backup - file %s in recovery manager backup
column7: The specified file is being backed up by Recovery Manager.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the Recovery Manager proxy backup to complete. Recovery Manager backup mode cannot be initiated or terminated manually.

column6: cannot shutdown - file %s in recovery manager backup
column7: An attempt to shut down normally found that a Recovery Manager backup is still in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the Recovery Manager proxy backup to complete and retry this command.

column6: Fatal LogMiner Error.
column7:
On of the following:

One or more input parameters in the DBMS_LOGMNR.START_LOGMNR() procedure may be invalid. 

The start or the end SCN may not be available in the log files selected. 

The dictionary file specified may be from a different database than the one that generated the log files. 

LogMiner may have encountered an internal error from which it cannot recover.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to see whether the input parameters are valid. The V$LOGMNR_LOG view can be queried to see the SCN ranges that are valid for the set of log files specified, and the DB_ID of the database that generated the log files.

column6: SCN range specified in dbms_logmnr.start_logmnr() is invalid
column7: StartSCN may be greater than EndSCN, or the SCN specified may be invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid SCN range.

column6: date range specified in dbms_logmnr.start_logmnr() is invalid
column7: The specified Date value is invalid for the log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid date range.

column6: Options specified is invalid
column7: The specified Options is invalid for the procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify valid Options.

column6: file %s cannot be opened
column7: The specified file cannot be opened.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure the file or directory exists and is accessible.

column6: error reading file %s
column7: The file or directory may not exist or is inaccessible.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify valid file or directory. Make sure that file and directory are accessible.

column6: cannot add file %s due to DB_ID mismatch
column7: The log file is produced by a different database than other log files already added to the list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a log file produced by the same database.

column6: Reset SCN for file %s does not match that of other logfiles specified for this LogMiner session
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: Reset Count for file %s does not match that of other logfiles specified for this LogMiner session
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: cannot add duplicate logfile %s
column7: The log file specified has already been added to the list of log files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different log file.

column6: cannot remove unlisted logfile %s
column7: The user attempted to remove a log file that is not present in the list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid log file in the DBMS_LOGMNR.ADD_LOGFILE() procedure.

column6: missing logfile
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: no log file has been specified for the current LogMiner session
column7: No log file has been specified for the LogMiner session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify at least one log file.

column6: time or SCN range not fully contained in the listed logfiles
column7: The input date/SCN range is not fully contained within the log files specified for the session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Select out of V$LOGMNR_LOGS view to check the date or SCN range covered by the log files specified for the LogMiner session, and reissue the START_LOGMNR() procedure with appropriate date or SCN range.

column6: error occurred while processing information in dictionary file %s, possible corruption
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: DBID mismatch between dictionary %s and logfiles
column7: The dictionary file is produced by a database that is different from that produced the log files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a compatible dictionary file.

column6: character set mismatch between dictionary %s and logfiles
column7: The character set of the database that produced the dictionary file is different from the character set of the database that produced the log files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a dictionary file with the same character set.

column6: redo version mismatch between dictionary %s and logfiles
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LowSCN mismatch between dictionary %s and the earliest logfile
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: ResetSCN mismatch between dictionary %s and the earliest logfile
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: enabled thread bit vector mismatch between dictionary %s and the earliest logfile
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: dbms_logmnr.USE_COLMAP can only be used with a valid dictionary
column7: DBMS_LOGMNR.USE_COLMAP can only be used with a valid dictionary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the dictionary file in DBMS_LOGMNR.START_LOGMNR().

column6: syntax error in logmnr.opt file
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: schema %s, specified in logmnr.opt file, does not exist
column7: The schema specified does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a correct schema or a compatible dictionary file.

column6: table %s, schema %s, specified in logmnr.opt file, does not exist
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: column %s, specified in logmnr.opt file, does not exist in table %s, schema %s
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: dbms_logmnr.start_logmnr() must be invoked before selecting from v$logmnr_contents
column7: A select was issued from V$LOGMNR_CONTENTS without first invoking the DBMS_LOGMNR.START_LOGMNR() procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke the DBMS_LOGMNR.START_LOGMNR() procedure before issuing a select from the V$LOGMNR_CONTENTS view.

column6: no LogMiner session is currently active
column7: A select was issued from V$LOGMNR_CONTENTS without first invoking the DBMS_LOGMNR.START_LOGMNR() procedure. Otherwise, DBMS_LOGMNR.END_LOGMNR() was called without a prior call to DBMS_LOGMNR.START_LOGMNR() or DBMS_LOGMNR.ADD_LOGFILE()
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke the DBMS_LOGMNR.START_LOGMNR() procedure before issuing a select from the V$LOGMNR_CONTENTS view.

column6: primary key or mandatory (NOT NULL) column is missing or NULL during insert
column7: When inserting or updating rows, a value for a column defined as NOT NULL was not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a value for each NOT NULL column or modify the table definition to allow NULL values in columns now defined as NOT NULL.

column6: inserted value too large for column
column7: The value entered is larger than the maximum width defined for the column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a value smaller than the column width or use the MODIFY option with ALTER TABLE to expand the column width.

column6: view WITH CHECK OPTION where-clause violation
column7: An INSERT or UPDATE statement was attempted on a view created with the CHECK OPTION. This would have resulted in the creation of a row that would not satisfy the view's WHERE clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the view's WHERE clause in the dictionary table VIEWS. If the current view does not have the CHECK OPTION, then its FROM clause must reference a second view that is defined using the CHECK OPTION. The second view's WHERE clause must also be satisfied by any INSERT or UPDATE statements. To insert the row, it may be necessary to insert it directly into the underlying table, rather than through the view.

column6: no data found
column7: In a host language program, all records have been fetched. The return code from the fetch was +4, indicating that all records have been returned from the SQL query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Terminate processing for the SELECT statement.

column6: ALTER COLUMN will make an index too large
column7: Increasing the length of a column would cause the combined length of the columns specified in a previous CREATE INDEX statement to exceed the maximum index length (255). The total index length is computed as the sum of the width of all indexed columns plus the number of indexed columns. Date fields are calculated as a length of 7, character fields are calculated at their defined width, and numeric fields are length 22.
column8: From Oracle doc: The only way to alter the column is to drop the affected index. The index cannot be re-created if to do so would exceed the maximum index width.

column6: fetched column value is NULL
column7: The INTO clause of a FETCH operation contained a NULL value, and no indicator was used. The column buffer in the program remained unchanged, and the cursor return code was +2. This is an error unless you are running Oracle with DBMS=6, emulating version 6, in which case it is only a warning.
column8:
From Oracle doc: You may do any of the following: 

Use the NVL function to convert the retrieved NULL to another value, such as zero or blank. This is the simplest solution. 

Use an indicator to record the presence of the NULL. You probably should use this option when you want a specific action to be taken when a NULL arises. 

Revise the cursor definition so that no columns possibly containing NULL values are retrieved.

column6: fetched column value was truncated
column7: In a host language program, a FETCH operation was forced to truncate a character string. The program buffer area for this column was not large enough to contain the entire string. The cursor return code from the fetch was +3.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the column buffer area to hold the largest column value or perform other appropriate processing.

column6: cannot update mandatory NOT NULL column to NULL
column7: An attempt was made to update data in a NOT NULL column to a NULL value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a value for the column or modify the table definition to accept NULL values in that column.

column6: such column list already indexed
column7: A CREATE INDEX statement specified a column that is already indexed. A single column may be indexed only once. Additional indexes may be created on the column if it is used as a portion of a concatenated index, that is, if the index consists of multiple columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to re-index the column, as it is unnecessary. To create a concatenated key, specify one or more additional columns in the CREATE INDEX statement.

column6: NOSORT option may not be used; rows are not in ascending order
column7:
Creation of index with NOSORT option when rows were not ascending. The NOSORT option may only be used for indexes on groups of rows that already are in ascending order. 

For non-unique indexes the ROWID is considered part of the index key. This means that two rows that appear to be stored in ascending order may not be. If you create an index NOSORT, and two of the rows in the table have the same index values, but get split across two extents, the data block address of the first block in the second extent can be less than the data block address of the last block in the first extent. If these addresses are not in ascending order, the ROWIDs are not either. Since these ROWIDs are considered part of the index key, the index key is not in ascending order, and the create index NOSORT fails.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the index without the NOSORT option or ensure that the table is stored in one extent.

column6: invalid ROWID
column7: A ROWID was entered incorrectly. ROWIDs must be entered as formatted hexadecimal strings using only numbers and the characters A through F. A typical ROWID format is '000001F8.0001.0006'.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the format, then enter the ROWID using the correct format. ROWID format: block ID, row in block, file ID.

column6: cannot store the length of column in the indicator
column7: An attempt was made to fetch a column of size more than 64K and could not store the length of the column in the given indicator of size 2 bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the new bind type with call backs to fetch the long column.

column6: zero length not allowed for this datatype
column7: The length for type 97 is 0.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct length.

column6: illegal value in packed decimal number buffer
column7: The user buffer bound by the user as packed decimal number contained an illegal value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a legal value.

column6: invalid array length when trying to bind array
column7: An attempt was made to bind an array without either a current array length pointer or a zero maximum array length.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid length.

column6: too many distinct aggregate functions
column7: The query contains more distinct aggregates than can be processed. The current limit is 255.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of distinct aggregate functions in the query.

column6: two tables cannot be outer-joined to each other
column7: Two tables in a join operation specified an outer join with respect to each other. If an outer join is specified on one of the tables in a join condition, it may not be specified on the other table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the outer join specification (+) from one of the tables, then retry the operation.

column6: a table may be outer joined to at most one other table
column7: a.b (+) = b.b and a.c (+) = c.c is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that this is really what you want, then join b and c first in a view.

column6: specified index does not exist
column7: An ALTER INDEX, DROP INDEX, or VALIDATE INDEX statement specified the name of an index that does not exist. Only existing indexes can be altered, dropped, or validated. Existing indexes may be listed by querying the data dictionary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the name of an existing index in the ALTER INDEX, DROP INDEX, or VALIDATE INDEX statement.

column6: datdts: illegal format code
column7: An attempt was made to use an incorrect format.
column8: From Oracle doc: Inspect the format, correct it if necessary, then retry the operation.

column6: datstd: illegal format code
column7: An attempt was made to use an invalid format.
column8: From Oracle doc: Inspect the format, correct it if necessary, then retry the operation.

column6: datrnd/dattrn: illegal precision specifier
column7: An attempt was made to use an invalid precision specifier.
column8: From Oracle doc: Inspect the precision specifier, correct it if necessary, then retry the operation.

column6: exact fetch returns more than requested number of rows
column7: The number specified in exact fetch is less than the rows returned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the query or change number of rows requested.

column6: error encountered while checking for extra rows in exact fetch
column7: An error was encountered during the execution of an exact fetch. This message will be followed by more descriptive messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the accompanying messages and take appropriate action.

column6: missing or illegal character following the escape character
column7: The character following the escape character in LIKE pattern is missing or not one of the escape character, '%', or '_'.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the escape character or specify the missing character.

column6: escape character must be character %s of length 1
column7: Given escape character for LIKE is not a character string of length 1.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change it to a character string of length 1.

column6: numeric overflow
column7: Evaluation of an value expression causes an overflow/underflow.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the operands.

column6: single-row subquery returns more than one row
column7: The outer query must use one of the keywords ANY, ALL, IN, or NOT IN to specify values to compare because the subquery returned more than one row.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ANY, ALL, IN, or NOT IN to specify which values to compare or reword the query so only one row is retrieved.

column6: argument '%s' is out of range
column7:
An illegal value for a mathematical function argument was specified. For example 

SELECT SQRT(-1) "Square Root" FROM DUAL;
column8: From Oracle doc: See the Oracle8i SQL Reference manual for valid input and ranges of the mathematical functions.

column6: Index-Organized Table: no data segment to store overflow row-pieces
column7: No overflow segment defined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add overflow segment.

column6: column being added already exists in table
column7: An ALTER TABLE ADD statement specified the name of a column that is already in the table. All column names must be unique within a table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a unique name for the new column, then re-execute the statement.

column6: internal inconsistency in GRANT command
column7: An internal error occurred while attempting to execute a GRANT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: public synonym to be dropped does not exist
column7: The synonym specified in DROP PUBLIC SYNONYM is not a valid public synonym. It may be a private synonym.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the synonym name or use DROP SYNONYM if the synonym is not public.

column6: synonym to be created is already defined
column7: A CREATE SYNONYM statement specified a synonym name that is the same as an existing synonym, table, view, or cluster. Synonyms may not have the same name as any other synonym, table, view, or cluster available to the user creating the synonym.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a unique name for the synonym, then re-execute the statement.

column6: private synonym to be dropped does not exist
column7: A DROP SYNONYM statement specified a synonym that does not exist. Existing synonym names may be listed by querying the data dictionary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the name of an existing synonym in the DROP SYNONYM statement.

column6: user does not exist
column7: This message is caused by any reference to a non-existent user. For example, it occurs if a SELECT, GRANT, or REVOKE statement specifies a username that does not exist. Only a GRANT CONNECT statement may specify a new username. All other GRANT and REVOKE statements must specify existing usernames. If specified in a SELECT statement, usernames must already exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only existing usernames in the SELECT, GRANT, or REVOKE statement or ask the database administrator to define the new username.

column6: CONNECT BY loop in user data
column7: The condition specified in a CONNECT BY clause caused a loop in the query, where the next record to be selected is a descendent of itself. When this happens, there can be no end to the query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the CONNECT BY clause and remove the circular reference.

column6: cannot have join with CONNECT BY
column7: A join operation was specified with a CONNECT BY clause. If a CONNECT BY clause is used in a SELECT statement for a tree-structured query, only one table may be referenced in the query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove either the CONNECT BY clause or the join operation from the SQL statement.

column6: value larger than specified precision allows for this column
column7: When inserting or updating records, a numeric value was entered that exceeded the precision defined for the column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a value that complies with the numeric column's precision, or use the MODIFY option with the ALTER TABLE command to expand the precision.

column6: column to be modified must be empty to change datatype
column7: An ALTER TABLE MODIFY statement attempted to change the datatype of a column containing data. A column whose datatype is to be altered must contain only NULL values.
column8: From Oracle doc: To alter the datatype, first set all values in the column to NULL.

column6: column to be modified must be empty to decrease precision or scale
column7: An ALTER TABLE MODIFY statement attempted to decrease the scale or precision of a numeric column containing data. In order to decrease either of these values, the column must contain only NULL values. An attempt to increase the scale without also increasing the precision will also cause this message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set all values in the column to NULL before decreasing the numeric precision or scale. If attempting to increase the scale, increase the precision in accordance with the scale or set all values in the column to NULL first.

column6: column to be modified must be empty to decrease column length
column7: An ALTER TABLE MODIFY statement attempted to decrease the size of a character field containing data. A column whose maximum size is to be decreased must contain only NULL values.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set all values in column to NULL before decreasing the maximum size.

column6: column to be modified to NOT NULL is already NOT NULL
column7: An ALTER TABLE MODIFY statement attempted to change a column specification unnecessarily, from NOT NULL to NOT NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: internal inconsistency; illegal datatype in resultant view column
column7: An internal error occurred in referencing a view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: internal inconsistency; internal datatype maps to invalid external type
column7: This is an internal error message not normally issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot select ROWID from a join view without a key-preserved table
column7: A SELECT statement attempted to select ROWIDs from a view derived from a join operation. Because the rows selected in the view do not correspond to underlying physical records, no ROWIDs can be returned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove ROWID from the view selection clause, then re-execute the statement.

column6: cannot select ROWID from view with DISTINCT, GROUP BY, etc.
column7: A SELECT statement attempted to select ROWIDs from a view containing columns derived from functions or expressions. Because the rows selected in the view do not correspond to underlying physical records, no ROWIDs can be returned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove ROWID from the view selection clause, then re-execute the statement.

column6: ALTER TABLE does not operate on clustered columns
column7: An ALTER TABLE MODIFY statement specified a column used to cluster the table. Clustered columns may not be altered.
column8: From Oracle doc: To alter the column, first re-create the table in non-clustered form. The column's size can be increased at the same time.

column6: index must be dropped before changing to desired type
column7: An ALTER TABLE MODIFY statement attempted to change an indexed character column to a LONG column. Columns with the datatype LONG may not be indexed, so the index must be dropped before the modification.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop all indexes referencing the column before changing its datatype to LONG.

column6: column contains NULL values; cannot alter to NOT NULL
column7: An ALTER TABLE MODIFY statement attempted to change the definition of a column containing NULL values to NOT NULL. The column may not currently contain any NULL values if it is to be altered to NOT NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set all NULL values in the column to values other than NULL before ALTERING the column to NOT NULL.

column6: maximum key length (%s) exceeded
column7: The combined length of all the columns specified in a CREATE INDEX statement exceeded the maximum index length. The maximum index length varies by operating system. The total index length is computed as the sum of the width of all indexed columns plus the number of indexed columns. Date fields have a length of 7, character fields have their defined length, and numeric fields have a length of 22. Numeric length = (precision/2) + 1. If negative, add +1.
column8: From Oracle doc: Select columns to be indexed so the total index length does not exceed the maximum index length for the operating system. See also your operating system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: column to be modified to NULL cannot be modified to NULL
column7: The column may already allow NULL values, the NOT NULL constraint is part of a primary key or check constraint, or an ALTER TABLE MODIFY statement attempted to change a column specification unnecessarily, from NULL to NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: If a primary key or check constraint is enforcing the NOT NULL constraint, then drop that constraint.

column6: cannot CREATE UNIQUE INDEX; duplicate keys found
column7: A CREATE UNIQUE INDEX statement specified one or more columns that currently contain duplicate values. All values in the indexed columns must be unique by row to create a UNIQUE INDEX.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the entries need not be unique, remove the keyword UNIQUE from the CREATE INDEX statement, then re-execute the statement. If the entries must be unique, as in a primary key, then remove duplicate values before creating the UNIQUE index.

column6: SET TRANSACTION must be first statement of transaction
column7: A transaction was not processed properly because the SET TRANSACTION statement was not the first statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Commit or roll back the current transaction before using the statement SET TRANSACTION.

column6: cannot convert column into numeric datatype
column7: A non-numeric value could not be converted into a number value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the value to make sure it contains only numbers, a sign, a decimal point, and the character "E" or "e", then retry the operation.

column6: converting column overflows integer datatype
column7: The converted form of the specified expression was too large for the specified datatype.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define a larger datatype or correct the data.

column6: may not perform insert/delete/update operation inside a READ ONLY transaction
column7: A non-DDL insert/delete/update or select for update operation was attempted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Commit (or roll back) the transaction, and then re-execute.

column6: converting column overflows decimal datatype
column7: The converted form of the specified expression was too large for the specified type. The problem also occurs in COBOL programs when using COMP-3 in the picture clause, which is acceptable to the Pro*COBOL Precompiler and to COBOL but results in this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define a larger datatype or correct the data.

column6: invalid length inside variable character %s
column7: An attempt was made to bind or define a variable character string with a buffer length less than the minimum requirement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the buffer size or use a different type.

column6: invalid length for variable character %s
column7: The buffer length was less than the minimum required or greater than its length at bind time minus two bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the string size is long enough to hold the buffer.

column6: unimplemented or unreasonable conversion requested
column7: The requested format conversion is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the requested conversion from the SQL statement. Check the syntax for the TO_CHAR, TO_DATE, and TO_NUMBER functions to see which conversions are supported.

column6: can bind a LONG value only for insert into a LONG column
column7: An attempt was made to insert a value from a LONG datatype into another datatype. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not try to insert LONG datatypes into other types of columns.

column6: cannot insert %s literals longer than 2000 characters
column7: The longest literal supported by Oracle consists of 2000 characters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of characters in the literal to 2000 characters or fewer or use the VARCHAR2 or LONG datatype to insert strings exceeding 2000 characters.

column6: cannot modify column datatype with current constraint(s)
column7: An attempt was made to modify the datatype of column which has referential constraints; or has check constraints which only allows changing the datatype from CHAR to VARCHAR or vise versa.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the constraint(s) or do not perform the offending operation.

column6: circular grant (granting to grant ancestor) of table or view
column7: The user in the TO clause of the GRANT statement has already been GRANTed privileges on this table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not GRANT privileges on a table to the user who originally GRANTed privileges on that table. The statement in error is probably unnecessary.

column6: invalid hex number
column7: In an UPDATE statement following a SELECT FOR UPDATE, part of the ROWID contains invalid characters. ROWID must be expressed in the proper and expected format for ROWID and within quotes.
