column8: From Oracle doc: Enter the ROWID just as it was returned in the SELECT FOR UPDATE.

column6: unable to read data - table definition has changed
column7:
This is a time-based read consistency error for a database object, such as a table or index. Either of the following may have happened: 

The query was parsed and executed with a snapshot older than the time the object was changed. 

The creation time-stamp of the object is greater than the current system time. This happens, for example, when the system time is set to a time earlier than the creation time of the object.
column8:
From Oracle doc: If the cause is: 

an old snapshot, then commit or rollback the transaction and resume work. 

a creation time-stamp in the future, ensure the system time is set correctly. 

If the object creation time-stamp is still greater than the system time, then export the object's data, drop the object, re-create the object so it has a new creation time-stamp, import the object's data, and resume work.

column6: sort key too long
column7: A DISTINCT, GROUP BY, ORDER BY, or SET operation requires a sort key longer than that supported by Oracle. Either too many columns or too many group functions were specified in the SELECT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of columns or group functions involved in the operation.

column6: a predicate may reference only one outer-joined table
column7: A predicate in the WHERE clause has two columns from different tables with "(+)".
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the WHERE clause so that each predicate has a maximum of one outer-join table.

column6: PRIOR can only be followed by a column name
column7: An invalid column name was specified after the PRIOR keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check syntax, spelling, use a valid column name, and try again.

column6: In-list iteration does not support mixed operators
column7: Constants of different types are specified in an in-list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use constants of same type for in-lists.

column6: cannot create a synonym with same name as object
column7: An attempt was made to create a private synonym with the same name as the object to which it refers. This error typically occurs when a user attempts to create a private synonym with the same name as one of their objects.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different synonym name or create the synonym under a different username.

column6: cannot use CONNECT BY on view with DISTINCT, GROUP BY, etc.
column7: CONNECT BY cannot be used on a view where there is not a correspondence between output rows and rows of the underlying table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the DISTINCT or GROUP BY from the view or move the CONNECT BY clause into the view.

column6: cannot have subqueries in CONNECT BY clause
column7: Subqueries cannot be used in a CONNECT BY clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the subquery or move it to the WHERE clause.

column6: cannot have START WITH or PRIOR without CONNECT BY
column7: START WITH and PRIOR are meaningful only in connection with CONNECT BY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax for the SQL statement and add a CONNECT BY clause, if necessary.

column6: must reparse cursor to change bind variable datatype
column7: After executing a statement, an attempt was made to rebind a bind variable with a datatype different from that of the original bind.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-parse the cursor before rebinding with a different datatype.

column6: divisor is equal to zero
column7: An expression attempted to divide by zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the expression, then retry the operation.

column6: user data area descriptor is too large
column7: This is an internal error message not normally issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: array bind may not include any LONG columns
column7: User is performing an array bind with a bind variable whose maximum size is greater than 2000 bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Such bind variables cannot participate in array binds. Use an ordinary bind operation instead.

column6: last character in the buffer is not Null
column7: A bind variable of type 97 does not contain null at the last position.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the last character null.

column6: trailing null missing from STR bind value
column7: A bind variable of type 5 (null-terminated string) does not contain the terminating null in its buffer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Terminate the string with a null character.

column6: invalid number format model
column7: An invalid format parameter was used with the TO_CHAR or TO_NUMBER function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax, then retry the operation.

column6: unsupported character set
column7: The second or third parameter to the CONVERT function is not a supported character set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use one of the supported character sets.

column6: arrays can only be bound to PL/SQL statements
column7: At attempt was made to bind an array to a non-PL/SQL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the offending code being careful to bind arrays only to PL/SQL statements.

column6: compile bind length different from execute bind length
column7: You bound a buffer of type DTYVCS (VARCHAR with the two byte length in front) and at execute time the length in the first two bytes is more than the maximum buffer length, given in the bind call. The number of elements in the array and the current number of elements in the array cannot be more than the maximum size of the array.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the buffer size is sufficiently large to contain the array plus two bytes for the buffer length.

column6: size of array element is too large
column7: An attempt was made to bind a data value that was either too large for the datatype, for example, NUMBER, or was greater than 2000 bytes, for example, VARCHAR or LONG.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find a way to convert or truncate the data value so that its length is acceptable.

column6: packed decimal number too large for supplied buffer
column7: A conversion request cannot be performed because the buffer is too small to hold the result.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the size of the buffer.

column6: invalid nibble or byte in the input data
column7: A conversion request cannot be performed because a digit was invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the number and retry.

column6: result of %s concatenation is too long
column7: String concatenation result is more than the maximum size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the result is less than the maximum size.

column6: invalid ANALYZE command
column7: The syntax of the ANALYZE command was incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax and enter the command using the correct syntax.

column6: CASCADE option not valid
column7: The CASCADE option should be used only for tables or clusters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the CASCADE option in this manner. Check the syntax of the statement and then retry.

column6: LIST option not valid
column7: The LIST option can be used only for tables or clusters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the LIST option in this manner. Check the syntax of the statement and then retry.

column6: invalid SAMPLE size specified
column7: The specified SAMPLE size is out of range
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a value within the proper range.

column6: invalid SIZE specified
column7: The specified histogram SIZE value was out of range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a value within the proper range.

column6: specified chain row table not found
column7: The specified table either does not exist or user does not have the proper privileges.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct table to use.

column6: specified chain row table form incorrect
column7: The specified table does not have the proper field definitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct table to use.

column6: illegal option for ANALYZE CLUSTER
column7: The FOR COLUMNS column_list clause cannot be used with ANALYZE CLUSTER.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Retry with a legal syntax. 

For more information about ANALYZE CLUSTER, see Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: block check failure - see trace file
column7: An error occurred while checking a block with the ANALYZE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the trace file for more descriptive messages about the problem. Correct these errors. The name of the trace file is operating system-specific, for example, ORAxxxx.TRC. It is found in the directory specified by the initialization parameter USER_DUMP_DEST. If USER_DUMP_DEST is not set, trace files are not created. It may be necessary to re-create the object. See also your operating system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: table/index cross reference failure - see trace file
column7: An error occurred when validating an index or a table using the ANALYZE command. One or more entries does not point to the appropriate cross-reference.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the trace file for more descriptive messages about the problem. Correct these errors. The name of the trace file is operating system-specific, for example, ORAxxxx.TRC. It is found in the directory specified by the initialization parameter USER_DUMP_DEST. If USER_DUMP_DEST is not set, trace files are not created. It may be necessary to re-create the object. See also your operating system-specific Oracle documentation.

column6: failure in getting date/time
column7: During CREATE DATABASE or ALTER TABLESPACE, there was a failure in getting the date and time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CREATE DATABASE failed
column7: An error occurred during CREATE DATABASE.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying errors.

column6: index '%s.%s' or partition of such index is in unusable state
column7: An attempt has been made to access an index or index partition that has been marked unusable by a direct load or by a DDL operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: DROP the specified index, or REBUILD the specified index, or REBUILD the unusable index partition.

column6: CREATE CONTROLFILE failed
column7: An error occurred during CREATE CONTROLFILE.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying errors.

column6: database name '%s' does not match parameter db_name '%s'
column7: The name in a database create or mount does not match the name given in the initialization parameter DB_NAME.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct or omit one of the two names.

column6: error in adding log files
column7: During CREATE or ALTER DATABASE, error(s) occurred when adding new log files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check error stack for detailed error information.

column6: missing or illegal database name
column7: No database name was specified in the CREATE/ALTER DATABASE statement, and no DB_NAME initialization parameter was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either the database name must be given in the statement or in the DB_NAME initialization parameter. Note that the SVRMGR or SQL*PLUS STARTUP command issues an ALTER DATABASE statement using the database name specified as part of STARTUP (if any).

column6: database not mounted
column7: A command was attempted that requires the database to be mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you are using the ALTER DATABASE statement via the SVRMGR or SQL*PLUS STARTUP command, specify the MOUNT option to restart; else if you are directly doing an ALTER DATABASE DISMOUNT, do nothing; else specify the MOUNT option to ALTER DATABASE. If you are doing a backup or copy, you must first mount the desired database.

column6: cannot create database; error in file '%s' at line %s
column7: CREATE DATABASE was unable to process the specified file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the offending line in the specified file.

column6: specified name '%s' does not match actual '%s'
column7: The database name specified in ALTER DATABASE does not match the name of the currently mounted database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the database name spelling or DISMOUNT the mounted database.

column6: error in deleting log files
column7: During ALTER DATABASE, an error occurred while dropping log files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for detailed error information.

column6: error in renaming log/data files
column7: During ALTER DATABASE, an error occurred while renaming log or datafiles.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for detailed error information.

column6: error renaming log file %s - new file %s not found
column7: An attempt to change a log file's name in the control file failed because no file was found with the new name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the log file has been properly renamed by the operating system and retry.

column6: invalid current time returned by operating system
column7: The operating system returned a time that was not between 1988 and 2121.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the time kept by the operating system.

column6: error in log specification: no such log
column7: A log file name, or list of member names, did not correspond to an existing log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an existing log file.

column6: error dropping log group %s: no such log
column7: ALTER DATABASE is attempting to drop a log file which is not known to the database control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the name of an existing log file.

column6: nonexistent log file, datafile or tempfile '%s'
column7: An attempt was made to use ALTER DATABASE to either rename a log file or datafile, or change attributes of a datafile or temporary file. The attempt failed because the specified file is not known to the database's control file or is not a type supported for the request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the name of an existing file of the correct type.

column6: log member: '%s'
column7: This message indicates the filename involved with other messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the accompanying messages and take appropriate action.

column6: CREATE DATABASE must specify more than one log file
column7: Only one log file was specified in the CREATE DATABASE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify at least two log files.

column6: error while processing file '%s' near line %s
column7: CREATE DATABASE encountered a problem while processing specified file. The specified file is bad.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry your system installation procedure or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: number of data files to add (%s) exceeds limit of %s
column7: CREATE TABLESPACE statement specifies more files than is permitted for this database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use fewer files or re-create the database with a larger value of MAXDATAFILES.

column6: error in adding data files
column7: During CREATE or ALTER TABLESPACE, an error was detected while adding datafiles.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for detailed error information.

column6: file '%s' to be renamed does not exist
column7: During ALTER TABLESPACE RENAME, a file to be renamed was not found in the database control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct file name.

column6: cannot rename data file to '%s' - file already part of database
column7: During ALTER DATABASE RENAME or ALTER TABLESPACE RENAME, the new name of a file is already present in the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rename the file to a name not already being used as part of the database.

column6: cannot create data file as '%s' - file already part of database
column7: During ALTER DATABASE CREATE DATAFILE, the new name of a file is already present in the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the file as a name not already being used as part of the database.

column6: error in renaming data files
column7: An error occurred when renaming files as part of ALTER TABLESPACE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for detailed information. All files are renamed except for those mentioned in the error stack.

column6: error in opening file '%s'
column7: CREATE DATABASE was not able to open the specified file. This is probably due to a system installation error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry your system installation procedure or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: error while reading file
column7: CREATE DATABASE was not able to read the specified file. This is probably due to a system installation error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry your system installation procedure or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: EOF while processing SQL statement
column7: CREATE DATABASE unexpectedly hit EOF while reading the specified file. The SQL.BSQ file is bad.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry your system installation procedure or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: error closing file '%s'
column7: CREATE DATABASE was not able to close the specified file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry your system installation procedure or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: a database already mounted by the instance
column7: During ALTER DATABASE MOUNT, an attempt is being made to mount a database on an instance in which a database is or has previously been mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you wish to mount the database, shut down and then restart the instance and retry the operation.

column6: a database already open by the instance
column7: During ALTER DATABASE, an attempt was made to open a database on an instance for which there is already an open database.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you wish to open a new database on the instance, first shut down and then restart the instance and retry the operation.

column6: cannot create database; instance being started elsewhere
column7: During CREATE DATABASE, another user appears to be simultaneously altering the instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure no one else is simultaneously altering the instance. If no one is, contact Oracle Customer Support; otherwise, retry the operation.

column6: cannot rename file '%s'; file does not belong to tablespace
column7: During ALTER TABLESPACE RENAME, a file to be renamed was not found in the argument tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct file name or the correct tablespace name.

column6: rollback segment '%s' doesn't exist
column7: During ALTER or DROP ROLLBACK SEGMENT, the specified rollback segment name is unknown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct rollback segment name.

column6: rollback segment '%s' already exists
column7: Specified rollback segment already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different name.

column6: space quota exceeded for tablespace '%s'
column7: The space quota for the segment owner in the tablespace has been exhausted and the operation attempted the creation of a new segment extent in the tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either drop unnecessary objects in the tablespace to reclaim space or have a privileged user increase the quota on this tablespace for the segment owner.

column6: cannot add data file '%s' - file already part of database
column7: During CREATE or ALTER TABLESPACE, a file being added is already part of the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different file name.

column6: failed to acquire any rollback segment
column7: Failed to acquire any rollback segment during startup in shared mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart in exclusive mode to create one more public segment or specify available private segments in the initialization parameter. ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS_REQUIRED, then start in shared mode

column6: tablespace '%s' is not online
column7: Failed to either make a tablespace read only or offline because it is not online. A tablespace must be online before it can become read only or offline normal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the status of the tablespace. Use IMMEDIATE or TEMPORARY options to force all files offline. Bring the tablespace online before making it read only.

column6: tablespace '%s' is not offline
column7: Failed to bring a tablespace online because it is not offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the status of the tablespace.

column6: system tablespace cannot be brought offline; shut down if necessary
column7: An attempt was made to bring system tablespace offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down if necessary to do recovery.

column6: tablespace '%s' is offline, cannot allocate space in it
column7: An attempt was made to allocate space in an offline tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the tablespace online or create the object in other tablespace.

column6: tablespace '%s' already exists
column7: An attempt was made to create a tablespace which already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different name for the new tablespace.

column6: cannot drop system rollback segment
column7: An attempt was made to drop system rollback segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: rollback segment '%s' specified not available
column7:
One of the following:

An attempt was made to bring a rollback segment online that is unavailable during startup; for example, the rollback segment is in an offline tablespace. 

An attempt was made to bring a rollback segment online that is already online. This is because the rollback segment is specified twice in the ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS parameter in the initialization parameter file or the rollback segment is already online by another instance. 

An attempt was made to drop a rollback segment that is currently online. 

An attempt was made to alter a rollback segment that is currently online to use unlimited extents.
column8:
From Oracle doc: One of the following: 

Make the rollback segment available; for example, bring an offline tablespace online. 

Remove the name from the ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS parameter if the name is a duplicate or if another instance has already acquired the rollback segment. 

Bring the rollback segment offline first. This may involve waiting for the active transactions to finish, or, if the rollback segment needs recovery, discover which errors are holding up the rolling back of the transactions and take appropriate actions. 

Same as 3).

column6: tablespace contains active rollback segment '%s'
column7: An attempt was made to make a tablespace that contains active rollback segment(s) offline or read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down instances that use the active rollback segments in the tablespace and then make the tablespace offline or read only.

column6: warning: RECOVER succeeded but OPEN RESETLOGS would get error below
column7: Media recovery with one of the incomplete recovery options ended without error. However, if the ALTER DATABASE OPEN RESETLOGS command were attempted now, it would fail with the specified error. The most likely cause of this error is forgetting to restore one or more datafiles from a sufficiently old backup before executing the incomplete recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rerun the incomplete media recovery using different datafile backups, a different control file, or different stop criteria.

column6: active rollback segment '%s' found, terminate dropping tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to drop a tablespace that contains active rollback segment(s).
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down instances that use the active rollback segments in the tablespace and then drop the tablespace.

column6: tablespace not empty, use INCLUDING CONTENTS option
column7: An attempt was made to drop a non-empty tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: To drop all the objects in the tablespace, use the INCLUDING CONTENTS option.

column6: cannot drop system tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to drop system tablespace. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: extended rollback segment, pinned blocks released
column7: Doing recursive extent of rollback segment, trapped internally by the system.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: cannot use system rollback segment for non-system tablespace '%s'
column7: An attempt was made to use the system rollback segment for operations involving non-system tablespace. If this is a clone database then this will happen when attempting any data modification outside of the system tablespace. Only the system rollback segment can be online in a clone database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create one or more private/public segment(s), shut down and restart. May need to modify the initialization parameter ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS to acquire private rollback segment. If this is a clone database being used for tablespace point in time recovery then this operation is not allowed.

column6: MAXEXTENTS must be no smaller than the %s extents currently allocated
column7: The number of extents allocated is greater than the MAXEXTENTS specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a larger MAXEXTENTS value.

column6: out of transaction slots in transaction tables
column7: Too many concurrent transactions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the system, modify the initialization parameters TRANSACTIONS, ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS or ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS_REQUIRED, and then restart.

column6: snapshot too old: rollback segment number %s with name "%s" too small
column7: Rollback records needed by a reader for consistent read are overwritten by other writers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use larger rollback segments.

column6: MINEXTENTS for rollback segment must be greater than 1
column7: Specified MINEXTENTS of less than 2 for rollback segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify larger MINEXTENTS.

column6: rollback segment extents must be at least %s blocks
column7: Specified extent of less than minimum size for rollback segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify larger extents.

column6: out of transaction ID's in rollback segment %s
column7: All the available transaction IDs have been used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the instance and restart using other rollback segment(s), then drop the rollback segment that has no more transaction IDs.

column6: MAXEXTENTS for rollback segment must be greater than 1
column7: Specified MAXEXTENTS of less than 2 for rollback segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify larger MAXEXTENTS.

column6: global hash table size mismatch for %s (%s != %s)
column7: The specified "GC_" initialization parameter was incompatible with that of another instance which already has the database mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the "GC_" parameter and restart.

column6: failed to remove all objects in the tablespace specified
column7: Failed to remove all objects when dropping a tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the drop tablespace until all objects are dropped.

column6: failed to extend rollback segment number %s
column7: Failure occurred when trying to extend rollback segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is normally followed by another error message that caused the failure. You may take the rollback segment offline to perform maintenance. Use SELECT SEGMENT_NAME FROM DBA_ROLLBACK_SEGS WHERE SEGMENT_ID=string (where string is the segment number from the message) to determine the rollback segment name. Then use the ALTER ROLLBACK SEGMENT OFFLINE command to take the rollback segment offline.

column6: rollback segment is PUBLIC, need to use the keyword PUBLIC
column7: Did not use the keyword PUBLIC to identified public rollback segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the keyword PUBLIC when identifying public rollback segment.

column6: rollback segment is not PUBLIC
column7: The rollback segment identified is not public.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the keyword PUBLIC when identifying private rollback segment.

column6: error in identifying file '%s'
column7: An error occurred while trying to identify a file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for detailed information.

column6: file specified more than once in DROP LOGFILE
column7: The list of files supplied to DROP LOGFILE contains at least one duplicate.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate file specification and retry.

column6: dropping log %s would leave less than 2 log files in thread %s
column7: Dropping all the logs specified would leave fewer than the required two log files per enabled thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either drop fewer logs or disable the thread before deleting the logs. It may be possible to clear the log rather than drop it.

column6: cannot set space quota on PUBLIC
column7: An attempt was made to set space quota on a tablespace for PUBLIC.
column8: From Oracle doc: If trying to grant system-wide or tablespace-wide space privileges to all users, use GRANT RESOURCE [ON tablespace] TO PUBLIC.

column6: data file too small for system dictionary tables
column7: The datafile specified during creation of the database is too small to hold the system dictionary tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the database by specifying a larger file or more files.

column6: MINEXTENTS must be no larger than the %s extents currently allocated
column7: The number of extents allocated is smaller than the MINEXTENTS specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a smaller MINEXTENTS value.

column6: redo version %s incompatible with ORACLE version %s
column7: This software version cannot read the current redo logs, and either crash recovery is required or there are offline database files that need media recovery. If a file name is listed then it needs media recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down and restart using the compatible software. Do any required media recovery, and open the database. Shut down and restart using the current software. If the file is going to be dropped then take it offline with the DROP option to skip this check.

column6: rollback segment %s cannot be brought online, %s extents exceeded
column7: The number of extents in the rollback segment exceeds the hard limit. It cannot be brought online for writing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop and re-create the rollback segment.

column6: shutting down instance, no further change allowed
column7: Some process tried to make changes while the database was being shut down.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: maximum number of concurrent transactions exceeded
column7: The limit on the number of concurrent transactions has been hit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the system, increase the value of the initialization parameter TRANSACTIONS, and then restart the system.

column6: timeout waiting for space management resource
column7: Failed to acquire necessary resource to do space management.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation.

column6: instance locking protocol version %s incompatible with ORACLE version %s
column7: Current software uses incompatible locking protocol.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade software used to start instances so that they use compatible locking protocol.

column6: cannot add log file '%s' - file already part of database
column7: During CREATE or ALTER DATABASE, a file being added is already part of the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different file name.

column6: ORACLE data block corrupted (file # %s, block # %s)
column7: The data block indicated was corrupted, probably due to program errors.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Determine which object was corrupted using a command like the following:

SELECT SEGMENT_TYPE,OWNER||'.'||SEGMENT_NAME FROM DBA_EXTENTS
WHERE file = FILE_ID AND block BETWEEN BLOCK_ID AND BLOCK_ID+BLOCKS -1;


where values for file and block are from the message. 

Try to restore the segment containing the block indicated. This may involve dropping the segment and re-creating it. If there is a trace file, report the errors in it to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: write error occurred during recovery
column7: A write error occurred during recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult trace files for the nature of the write error, and correct error.

column6: error creating control backup file %s
column7: An operating system error occurred while attempting to create a control file backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for more detailed information.

column6: attempt to use rollback segment (%s) new extent (%s) which is being allocated
column7: Undo generated to extend a rollback segment run out of current undo block space and is attempting to write into the new extent which has not been completely allocated.
column8: From Oracle doc: The rollback segment extending will be rolled back by the system, no more extension will be possible until the next extent is freed up by rolling back or committing other transactions.

column6: unable to open controlfile for backup
column7: An operating system error occurred while attempting to open a control file for backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for more detailed information.

column6: unable to get block size of controlfile to be backed up
column7: An operating system error occurred while attempting to get the block size of a control file for backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for more detailed information.

column6: unable to get file size of controlfile to be backed up
column7: An operating system error occurred while attempting to get the file size of a control file for backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for more detailed information.

column6: error identifying backup file %s
column7: An operating system error occurred when attempting to identify the file to be used for control file backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for more detailed information.

column6: unable to open destination file %s for backup
column7: An operating system error occurred while attempting to open a control file for backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error stack for more detailed information.

column6: error during controlfile backup file copy
column7: An operating system error occurred while attempting to copy a control file for backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the accompanying message stack for detailed information and then take appropriate action.

column6: must use RESETLOGS option for database open
column7: An earlier attempt to open the database with the RESETLOGS option did not complete, or recovery was done with a control file backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the RESETLOGS option when opening the database.

column6: must use RESETLOGS or NORESETLOGS option for database open
column7: Either incomplete or backup control file recovery has been performed. After these types of recovery you must specify either the RESETLOGS option or the NORESETLOGS option to open your database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the appropriate option.

column6: number of segment free list (%s) exceeds maximum of %s
column7: The value of the storage parameter FREELIST GROUPS is too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the value of the storage parameter FREELIST GROUPS.

column6: lock held by in-doubt distributed transaction %s
column7: An attempt was made to access resource that is locked by a dead two-phase commit transaction that is in prepared state.
column8: From Oracle doc: The database administrator should query the PENDING_TRANS$ and related tables, and attempt to repair network connection(s) to coordinator and commit point. If timely repair is not possible, the database administrator should contact the database administrator at the commit point if known or the end user for correct outcome, or use heuristic default if given to issue a heuristic COMMIT or ABORT command to finalize the local portion of the distributed transaction.

column6: error converting Version 7 rollback segment (%s) to Oracle 8 format
column7: Look at the accompanying internal error; Version 7 database may not have shut down cleanly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Investigate the internal error; may have to reload the Version 7 database (from backup) and shut down the database cleanly.

column6: rollback segment optimal size (%s blks) is smaller than the computed initial size (%s blks)
column7: Specified OPTIMAL size is smaller than the cumulative size of the initial extents during create rollback segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a larger OPTIMAL size.

column6: attempt to wrap into rollback segment (%s) extent (%s) which is being freed
column7: Undo generated to free a rollback segment extent is attempting to write into the same extent due to small extents and/or there are too many extents to free.
column8: From Oracle doc: The rollback segment shrinking will be rolled back by the system; increase the optimal size of the rollback segment.

column6: error freeing extent (%s) of rollback segment (%s))
column7: Some error occurred while freeing inactive rollback segment extents.
column8: From Oracle doc: Investigate the accompanying error.

column6: cannot specify system in %s parameter
column7: The system rollback segment is specified in the initialization parameter referred to in the error message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of the initialization parameter.

column6: cannot alter system rollback segment online or offline
column7: An attempt was made to online or offline the system rollback segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: rollback segment '%s' is not online
column7: Could have been taken offline before by the database administrator or cleaned up by SMON.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the status of rollback segment in UNDO$ or DBA_ROLLBACK_SEGS to make sure the rollback segment is actually online.

column6: failed to acquire rollback segment (%s), cache space is full (currently has (%s) entries)
column7: The amount statically allocated is not enough based on the value of the MAX_ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: For now, take another rollback segment offline or increase the value of the parameter MAX_ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS.

column6: at most one "%s" in clause "%s" of %s
column7: The initialization parameter was incorrectly specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the initialization parameter and restart the instance.

column6: illegal bucket size in clause "%s" of %s
column7: The bucket size was invalid for this parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the initialization parameter and restart the instance.

column6: illegal grouping size in clause "%s" of %s
column7: The grouping size was invalid for this parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the initialization parameter and restart the instance.

column6: illegal number range in clause "%s" of %s
column7: The number range was invalid for this parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the initialization parameter and restart the instance.

column6: missing numbers in clause "%s" of %s
column7: The numbers were missing for this parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the initialization parameter and restart the instance.

column6: gc_files_to_locks not identical to that of another mounted instance
column7: The GC_FILES_TO_LOCKS parameters were different on two instances.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the initialization parameter GC_FILES_TO_LOCKS and restart.

column6: gc_lck_procs (%s) is not the same as other instances (%s)
column7: The GC_LCK_PROCS initialization parameter is not the same as in other instances that already have the database open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the GC_LCK_PROCS parameter and restart the instance.

column6: cannot bring rollback segment '%s' online, its status is (%s)
column7: Could have been brought online before by the database administrator or left as a result of process crash.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the status of rollback segment in UNDO$ or DBA_ROLLBACK_SEGS

column6: log %s is the current log for thread %s - cannot drop members
column7: A member of the current log for a thread cannot be dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the thread is opened, request a log switch by the instance that is using it. If it is not open, disable the thread, manually archive the log, or clear it.

column6: recovery using the BACKUP CONTROLFILE option must be done
column7: Either an earlier database recovery session specified BACKUP CONTROLFILE, or the control file was re-created with the RESETLOGS option, or the control file being used is a backup control file. After that only BACKUP CONTROLFILE recovery is allowed and it must be followed by a log reset at the next database open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform recovery using the BACKUP CONTROFILE option.

column6: thread number %s is invalid - must be between 1 and %s
column7: A thread number in a command is greater than the number of threads supported by the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a thread number that is valid, or resize the thread record and/or checkpoint progress record sections of the control file.

column6: thread %s is already enabled
column7: An attempt was made to enable a thread that is already enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either use this thread or enable another thread.

column6: thread %s only has %s logs - at least 2 logs required to enable
column7: The thread cannot be enabled because it only has two online log files associated with it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add logs to the thread or pick another thread to enable.

column6: thread %s is busy - cannot enable
column7: The mount enqueue for the thread could not be acquired when attempting to enable the thread. This probably means that another process has already started enabling this thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait and try again, or find another thread to enable.

column6: thread %s is mounted - cannot disable
column7: Some instance, possibly this one, has allocated the thread for its use. The thread may not be disabled while in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down cleanly the instance using the thread.

column6: thread %s is open - cannot disable
column7: The thread is not closed. The last instance to use the thread died leaving the thread open. A thread cannot be disabled until it is closed. It is still required for crash or instance recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the database is open, instance recovery should close the thread soon; wait a few minutes. Otherwise open the database; crash recovery will close the thread.

column6: cannot mount: %s is not a valid thread number
column7: The value of the initialization parameter THREAD is not between 1 and the number of threads allowed by the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the instance, change the value of the initialization parameter and restart, or resize the thread record and/or checkpoint progress record sections of the control file.

column6: thread %s is not enabled - cannot mount
column7: The value of the initialization parameter THREAD requests a thread that is not enabled. A thread must be enabled before it can be mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the instance, change the value of the initialization parameter and restart, mounting a different thread. If the database is open in another instance, then the thread may be enabled.

column6: thread %s is mounted by another instance
column7: The value of the initialization parameter THREAD requests a thread that has been mounted by another instance. Only one instance may use a thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the instance, change the value of the initialization parameter and restart, mounting a different thread.

column6: no public threads are available for mounting
column7: The value of the initialization parameter THREAD is zero, its default value. There are no threads which have been publicly enabled, and not mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the instance, change the value of the initialization parameter to a thread which is privately enabled and not mounted. If the database is open in another instance, then a thread may be publicly enabled.

column6: cannot rename member of current log if database is open
column7: This is a rename command for a member of the current log for an open thread. If the database is open anywhere, the log may be in use, so the rename cannot be done.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the log is not current, or mount the database exclusively.

column6: thread number must be specified - default not specific
column7: The thread was not specified when adding a log, and the currently mounted thread was chosen by default at mount time. Since the current thread was not specified explicitly the user cannot know which thread the log will be added to.
column8: From Oracle doc: Explicitly specify the thread number either in the initialization parameter THREAD, or in the ADD command.

column6: log %s is current log for thread %s - cannot drop
column7: A thread's current log cannot be dropped even if the thread is closed. A disabled thread usually does not have a current log, but a half completed disable may need to be disabled again.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the database is not open then disable the thread. If the database is open and an instance has the thread open, then the instance can be requested to switch logs. If the database is closed the log can be archived or cleared to force a switch.

column6: log %s needed for crash recovery of thread %s
column7: A log cannot be dropped or cleared until the thread's checkpoint has advanced out of the log.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the database is not open then open it. Crash recovery will advance the checkpoint. If the database is open force a global checkpoint. If the log is corrupted so that the database cannot be opened, it may be necessary to do incomplete recovery until cancel at this log.

column6: rollback segment '%s' does not belong to this instance
column7: An attempt was made to shrink or take a rollback segment offline that does not belong to this instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take only those rollback segments offline that belong to the current instance. To take the rollback segment offline, connect to the instance containing it.

column6: rollback segment number '%s' cannot handle more transactions
column7: Too many transactions in this segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different rollback segment, or reduce the number of concurrent transactions.

column6: rollback segment number '%s' is not online
column7: Could have been taken offline before by the database administrator or cleaned up by SMON.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the status of rollback segment in UNDO$ or DBA_ROLLBACK_SEGS to make sure the rollback segment is actually online.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached for rollback segment %s
column7: An attempt was made to extend a rollback segment that was already at the MAXEXENTS value.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the value of the MAXEXTENTS storage parameter is less than the maximum allowed by the system, raise this value.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached saving undo for tablespace %s
column7: Save undo for the offline tablespace at MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the storage parameters for the system tablespace. The tablespace needs to be brought back online so the undo can be applied.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in temp segment in tablespace %s
column7: A temporary segment tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If MAXEXTENTS for the tablespace is less than the system maximum, you can raise that. Otherwise, raise PCTINCREASE for the tablespace.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in table %s.%s
column7: A table tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If MAXEXTENTS is less than the system maximum, raise it. Otherwise, you must re-create with larger initial, next or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in index %s.%s
column7: An index tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the value of MAXEXTENTS in the index storage clause is less than the maximum (based on your block size), raise it. Otherwise, re-create the index with larger extent sizes so that the total number of extents falls below the maximum.

column6: parallel Server Option needed for this operation
column7: System does not have parallel server configured.
column8: From Oracle doc: Obtain parallel server option.

column6: rollback segment number '%s' is about to go offline
column7: The rollback segment specified was marked to go offline by the database administrator.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the rollback segment online first.

column6: rollback segment #%s specified not available
column7:
One of the following:

You tried to acquire an offline rollback segment during startup. 

You tried to drop a rollback segment that contains active transactions.
column8:
From Oracle doc: For the above, one of the following:

Bring the tablespace containing the rollback segment online or do not specify the rollback segment in the initialization parameter file. 

If the rollback segment is in use, shut down the instance using the rollback segment. Otherwise, if the rollback segment needs recovery, determine which errors are holding back the rolling back of the transactions and take appropriate action.

column6: rollback segment '%s' is already online
column7: A rollback segment can only be used by one instance and an instance is trying to bring a rollback segment online that is already in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the values set in the initialization parameter file for parameters ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS, ROLLBACK_SEGMENT_INITIAL, and ROLLBACK_SEGMENT_COUNT are correctly set for the instance with the problem. Also check that the instance is using the correct initialization parameter file. Make sure you are not confused about the difference between private and public rollback segments. See the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for more information about using rollback segments in parallel mode.

column6: rollback segment '%s' is being used by another instance (#%s)
column7: A rollback segment can only be used by one instance, and an instance is trying to access a rollback segment online that is already in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the values set in the initialization parameter file for parameters ROLLBACK_SEGMENTS, ROLLBACK_SEGMENT_INITIAL, and ROLLBACK_SEGMENT_COUNT are correctly set for the instance with the problem. Also check that the instance is using the correct initialization parameter file. Make sure you are not confused about the difference between private and public rollback segments. See Oracle8i Administrator's Guide for more information about using rollback segments in parallel mode.

column6: parameter %s does not allow ORACLE version %s to mount parallel
column7: The value of the RECOVERY_COMPATIBLE parameter is set too low to allow this software version to do a parallel mount.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either use an earlier software release or advance the RECOVERY_COMPATIBLE parameter. If this happens when no RECOVERY_COMPATIBLE parameter has been specified then set it to the current software release.

column6: database cannot be mounted parallel with no lock processes
column7: The value of GC_LCK_PROCS is 0, and the database is being mounted in parallel mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change GC_LCK_PROCS to a value between 1 and 10, or leave it undefined to use the built-in default.

column6: cannot make tablespace read only with active transactions
column7: An attempt was made to make a tablespace read only while there are active transactions in the database. All transactions must commit or rollback to insure that there is no undo for a tablespace before it can be made read only. This includes in doubt distributed transactions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Prevent any more transactions from being started. Putting the database in restricted mode usually helps. If there are any in doubt transactions they must also be resolved.

column6: tablespace '%s' is not online - cannot add data file
column7: An attempt was made to add a datafile to a tablespace that has been set to read only or offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the tablespace online and read write then add the datafile.

column6: begin backup not needed for read only tablespace '%s'
column7: An attempt was made to begin or end a backup for a tablespace that has been set to read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the backup without any BEGIN or END commands. The files are not being modified so the backup will be consistent.

column6: system tablespace can not be made read only
column7: An attempt was made to set the system tablespace to read only. The system tablespace must remain read write for database operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Leave system tablespace read write.

column6: tablespace '%s' is already read only
column7: An attempt was made to make tablespace read only that is already read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Leave tablespace read only, or make read write then make read only again.

column6: previous attempt to make read write is half complete
column7: A failure while making the tablespace read write left it read only, but the checkpoint was advanced. The tablespace will not be usable after a resetlogs if its files are offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Repeat the command to make the tablespace read write.

column6: tablespace '%s' is not read only - cannot make read write
column7: An attempt was made to make a tablespace read write that is not read only. It may be either online or offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Leave tablespace read write.

column6: tablespace '%s' is read only, cannot allocate space in it
column7: An attempt was made to allocate space in a read-only tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the object in another tablespace.

column6: log %s is the current log of disabled thread %s
column7: An attempt to enable the thread failed after it was half completed. This log was left as the current log even though the thread is still disabled. Since a log switch cannot be done until the thread is enabled, the log cannot be cleared or archived.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the thread enable by issuing the ENABLE command again.

column6: operation not allowed with a backup controlfile
column7: An attempt is being made to perform a command that does not make sense when the control file is a restored backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until after the database has been opened and try again.

column6: unable to extend rollback segment %s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for rollback segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: unable to extend save undo segment by %s for tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for saving undo entries for the indicated offline tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the storage parameters for the SYSTEM tablespace. The tablespace needs to be brought back online so the undo can be applied.

column6: unable to extend temp segment by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for temporary segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: unable to extend table %s.%s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for table segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: unable to extend index %s.%s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for index segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: unable to extend cluster %s.%s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for cluster segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in cluster %s.%s
column7: A cluster tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If MAXEXTENTS is less than the system maximum, raise it. Otherwise, you must re-create with larger initial, next or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: invalid SHRINK option value
column7: The specified value must be an integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose an appropriate integer value.

column6: unable to create INITIAL extent for segment in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to find sufficient contiguous space to allocate INITIAL extent for segment being created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE to add additional space to the tablespace or retry with a smaller value for INITIAL.

column6: unable to allocate MINEXTENTS beyond %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to find sufficient contiguous space to allocate MINEXTENTS for the segment being created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE to add additional space to the tablespace or retry with smaller value for MINEXTENTS, NEXT or PCTINCREASE.

column6: tablespace '%s' is already permanent
column7: An attempt was made to make tablespace permanent that is already permanent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Leave tablespace permanent.

column6: tablespace '%s' is already temporary
column7: An attempt was made to make tablespace temporary that is already temporary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Leave tablespace permanent.

column6: tablespace '%s' is non-empty and cannot be made temporary
column7: An attempt was made to convert a non-empty tablespace to a temporary tablespace
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop all the objects in the tablespace.

column6: the contents of tablespace '%s' is constantly changing
column7: The contents of the tablespace is always changing between PERMANENT and TEMPORARY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Decide what the tablespace contents should be and stay with it.

column6: Transaction which has expanded the Sort Segment has aborted
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: controlfile is not a standby controlfile
column7: An attempt was made to mount, recover or activate a standby database without a standby control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a standby control file before attempting to use the database as a standby database.

column6: controlfile is for a standby database
column7: An attempt was made to mount, recover, or open a standby database without the appropriate command option to designate a standby database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the standby option or appropriate commands, or mount with the primary control file.

column6: cannot add any more tablespaces: limit of %s exceeded
column7: There is no more room in the control file for adding tablespaces.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resize the control file or drop other tablespaces.

column6: standby database requires DROP option for offline of data file
column7: An attempt was made to take a datafile offline in a standby database without specifying the DROP option. Files that are offline in a standby database are not recovered, and are likely to be unusable if the standby is activated. Note that specifying DROP does not prevent bringing the file online later.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the DROP option or leave the file online.

column6: standby database controlfile not consistent
column7: An attempt was made to activate a standby database with a control file that has not been recovered to the same point as the datafiles. Most likely the control file was just copied from the primary database and has not been used for recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recover the standby database until all the files are consistent.

column6: new datafile %s needed for standby database recovery
column7: Standby database recovery noticed that a file was added to the primary database, but is not available on the standby.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either copy the file from the primary database or do an ALTER DATABASE CREATE DATAFILE command on the standby to create a file to recover.

column6: controlfile is a backup, cannot make a standby controlfile
column7: The currently mounted control file is a backup control file, and attempting to create a control file for a standby database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete any needed recovery and open the database with the resetlogs option.

column6: controlfile may be missing files or have extra ones
column7: An attempt was made to create a standby control file, but the control file was either recently created via CREATE CONTROLFILE or an incomplete recovery has been done. Thus the datafiles in the control file and the ones in the data dictionary may not match.
column8: From Oracle doc: Open the database, then retry the operation.

column6: data file %s has not been identified
column7: This datafile was not in the control file after an incomplete recovery or CREATE CONTROLFILE. Since information from its header is needed for standby database recovery, we cannot create a standby control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find the file and bring it online. If desired it may be taken offline again. If you intend to drop this file, then taking it offline with the DROP option will avoid this error.

column6: data file %s is an old incarnation rather than current file
column7: Recovery encountered redo that indicates this file was dropped from the database and another file was added using the same file number. This implies that a CREATE CONTROLFILE command was given the old file which was dropped rather than the latest file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rebuild the control file using CREATE CONTROLFILE, and give the correct file.

column6: max_commit_propagation_delay inconsistent with other instances
column7: The MAX_COMMIT_PROPAGATION_DELAY initialization parameter is inconsistent with those in other instances.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure all instances have the same MAX_COMMIT_PROPAGATION_DELAY.

column6: standby file name convert of '%s' exceeds maximum length of %s
column7: When the given file name is converted to the name used for the standby database, the converted name is bigger than the maximum allowed file name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of the initialization parameter DB_FILE_STANDBY_NAME_CONVERT or LOG_FILE_STANDBY_NAME_CONVERT to convert to a valid file name.

column6: standby file name convert parameters differ from other instance
column7: The DB_FILE_STANDBY_NAME_CONVERT or LOG_FILE_STANDBY_NAME_CONVERT initialization parameters are not the same as in other instances that already have the database mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of the initialization parameters DB_FILE_STANDBY_NAME_CONVERT and LOG_FILE_STANDBY_NAME_CONVERT to match other instances.

column6: parameter %s must be two strings, a pattern and a replacement
column7: The initialization parameter does not have two strings for its value. The first string it a pattern to be found in file names. The second string is used to replace the pattern when found in file names.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify two strings for the parameter, or omit the parameter.

column6: database must be mounted EXCLUSIVE and not open to activate
column7: An attempt to activate a standby database was made when the database was not mounted EXCLUSIVE or was already open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount the database EXCLUSIVE and retry the ACTIVATE command.

column6: unable to extend LOB segment by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for a LOB segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in LOB segment in tablespace %s
column7: A LOB segment tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If MAXEXTENTS for the tablespace is less than the system maximum, you can raise that. Otherwise, raise PCTINCREASE for the tablespace.

column6: read-only DB cannot allocate temporary space in tablespace %s
column7: Temporary space (usually for sorting) could not be allocated in either main storage or a temporary file. An attempt was made to allocate the space from the tablespace named, but the database is opened read only. The database open requires a sort work space.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either allow sufficient workspace in main storage (SORT_AREA_SIZE initialization parameter), or create a temporary tablespace before making the database read only. Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD TEMPFILE statement to add temporary files to the temporary tablespace.

column6: unable to extend index %s.%s partition %s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for index segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in table %s.%s partition %s
column7: A table tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If MAXEXTENTS is less than the system maximum, raise it. Otherwise, you must re-create with larger initial, next or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in index %s.%s partition %s
column7: An index tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If MAXEXTENTS is less than the system max, raise it. Otherwise, you must re-create with larger initial, next or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: max # files (%s) reached for the tablespace %s
column7: The number of files for a given tablespace has reached its maximum value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resize existing files in the tablespace, or partition the objects among multiple tablespaces, or move some objects to a different tablespace.

column6: specified logging attribute for tablespace '%s' is same as the existing
column7: An attempt was made to change the tablespace default logging attribute (LOGGING or NOLOGGING) to be the same as the existing logging attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the specified logging attribute.

column6: unable to extend table %s.%s partition %s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for table segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: syntax error in clause "%s" of %s
column7: There was a syntax in the initialization parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the syntax error and restart the instance.

column6: gc_rollback_locks not identical to that of another mounted instance
column7: The parameter GC_ROLLBACK_LOCKS was different on different instances.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the initialization parameter GC_ROLLBACK_LOCKS and restart.

column6: unable to extend lob segment %s.%s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for LOB segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: unable to extend lob segment %s.%s partition %s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for LOB segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in lob segment %s.%s
column7: A LOB segment tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If MAXEXTENTS is less than the system max, raise it. Otherwise, you must re-create with larger initial, next or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in lob segment %s.%s partition %s
column7: A LOB segment tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If MAXEXTENTS is less than the system max, raise it. Otherwise, you must re-create with larger initial, next or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: error converting rollback segment %s to version 8.0.2
column7: Version 8.0.1 database may not have shut down cleanly.
column8: From Oracle doc: May have to reload the 8.0.1 database and shut down cleanly.

column6: controlfile is not a clone controlfile
column7: An attempt was made to mount, a database as a clone when it is already mounted by another instance not as a clone or attempting to use a current control file for a clone.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount without the clone option or use a backup control file and shut down the other instances before mounting as a clone.

column6: controlfile is for a clone database
column7: An attempt was made to mount a clone database without the appropriate command option to designate a clone database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the clone option or appropriate commands, or mount with the primary control file.

column6: a clone database may only have SYSTEM rollback segment online
column7: An attempt was made to online a rollback segment in a clone database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use this command.

column6: tablespace '%s' is being imported for point in time recovery
column7: An attempt was made to online a tablespace or begin another point in time import while a point in time import is already in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the import completes.

column6: duplicate username in list
column7: A username was listed twice in a GRANT or REVOKE statement. Usernames must be unique and may only be specified once in a GRANT or REVOKE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate username and retry the statement.

column6: a cluster is not appropriate here
column7: The name of a cluster was specified in a statement in which clusters are not permitted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid CLUSTER statement or change the cluster name to the name of a valid object for the statement, such as table, view, index, or synonym.

column6: a view is not appropriate here
column7: The name of a view was specified in a statement in which views are not permitted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter the name of a valid object for the statement, such as table, cluster, synonym, or index.

column6: missing SYNONYM keyword
column7: The keyword SYNONYM is required in this context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement syntax and insert the keyword SYNONYM.

column6: %s literal too long
column7: The string literal is longer than 4000 characters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a string literal of at most 4000 characters. Longer values may only be entered using bind variables.

column6: an outer join cannot be specified on a correlation column
column7: A correlation column, that is, a column in a subquery from a table referenced in the outer query's FROM clause, was followed by an outer-join indicator (+). This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Revise the query. Refer to the syntax for subqueries. The outer-join indicator may follow only columns in the same query block in which their table is included in the FROM clause.

column6: user function result value was too large
column7: The user-written SQL function has generated a result that is larger than the maximum defined in the function table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the maximum in the function table or correct the user-written function.

column6: missing LIST keyword
column7: The keyword LIST is required in this context, for example, when using the ARCHIVE LOG statement to display the set of redo log files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement syntax, insert the keyword LIST where required, and retry the statement.

column6: ACCESS or SESSION expected
column7: An AUDIT or NOAUDIT statement contained the keyword BY followed by something other than ACCESS or SESSION.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement syntax and make sure to follow the keyword BY with ACCESS or SESSION.

column6: program does not exist
column7: This feature is not currently implemented.
column8: From Oracle doc: No user action is required.

column6: missing OF keyword
column7: The keyword OF was not specified in a SELECT FOR UPDATE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check and correct the statement syntax. To specify SELECT FOR UPDATE, add the following clause to the end of the SELECT statement:

column6: duplicate privilege listed
column7: A privilege was listed twice in a GRANT or REVOKE statement. A privilege may be specified only once in these statements.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate privilege from the list and retry the statement.

column6: cannot grant a privilege grantor does not have
column7: The grantor could not grant a privilege to another user because the grantor does not have the privilege. A grantor can grant only privileges that the grantor has or is authorized to grant.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Either 
Specify only authorized privileges in the GRANT statement.
Ask the database administrator to grant the user the required privileges.
Ask the database administrator for the required privileges and then grant the other user the privileges.

column6: GRANT OPTION does not exist for that privilege
column7: A GRANT statement specified a privilege that the granting user has but is not authorized to grant to other users. When the user was granted the privilege, the user was not given the GRANT OPTION needed to grant those privileges to others.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the GRANT statement to specify only authorized privileges or ask the user who granted the privileges to grant the GRANT OPTION also.

column6: error in execution of user function
column7: The user-written SQL function indicated that an error occurred during its execution. The meaning of the message is function-dependent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure proper usage of the function or correct the function.

column6: UNIQUE may not be used with a cluster index
column7: An attempt was made to create a cluster index with the UNIQUE attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove UNIQUE from the CREATE INDEX statement.

column6: NOSORT may not be used with a cluster index
column7: An attempt was made to create a cluster index using the NOSORT option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove NOSORT from the CREATE INDEX statement.

column6: seccta invalid access mode token passed
column7: This is an internal error message not normally issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact customer support.

column6: BY ACCESS | SESSION clause not allowed for NOAUDIT
column7: Attempt to specify BY ACCESS | SESSION in a NOAUDIT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove BY ACCESS | SESSION.

column6: outer join operator (+) not allowed in operand of OR or IN
column7: An outer join appears in an or clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: If A and B are predicates, to get the effect of (A(+) or B), try (select where (A(+) and not B)) union all (select where (B)).

column6: grant option does not exist for '%s.%s'
column7: A grant was being performed on a view and the grant option was not present for an underlying object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Obtain the grant option on all underlying objects of the view.

column6: USERENV(COMMITSCN) invoked more than once in a transaction
column7: The USERENV('COMMITSCN') function can only be used once in a transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-write the transaction to use USERENV('COMMITSCN') only once.

column6: invalid number
column7: The attempted conversion of a character string to a number failed because the character string was not a valid numeric literal. Only numeric fields or character fields containing numeric data may be used in arithmetic functions or expressions. Only numeric fields may be added to or subtracted from dates.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the character strings in the function or expression. Check that they contain only numbers, a sign, a decimal point, and the character "E" or "e" and retry the operation.

column6: zero-length columns are not allowed
column7: During CREATE TABLE, a zero-length column was specified, for example, CHAR(0).
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the column declaration so that the length is at least 1 and try the operation again.

column6: floating point precision is out of range (1 to 126)
column7: Floating point precision is too small or large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct and retry.

column6: USERENV('COMMITSCN') not allowed here
column7: The function USERNEV('COMMMITSCN') is only allowed as a top-level expression in the VALUES clause of an INSERT statements, and on the right hand side of an assignment in an UPDATE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the use of the function.

column6: a table is not appropriate here
column7: A table name was used in a statement in which tables are not permitted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid table statement or use the current statement on the appropriate object.

column6: numeric precision specifier is out of range (1 to 38)
column7: The precision specified for a number column in a CREATE/ALTER TABLE or CREATE CLUSTER statement must be a digit between 1 and 38. If no precision is specified, a default precision of 22 digits is used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify numeric precision between 1 and 38 and retry the statement.

column6: numeric scale specifier is out of range (-84 to 127)
column7: The scale specified for a numeric field in a CREATE/ALTER TABLE or CREATE CLUSTER statement is not in the valid range. It should be between -84 and 127.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a numeric scale between -84 and 127. If a number is not specified, the default scale of the column is 0 decimal places.

column6: database link name expected
column7: A database link name does not follow the at-sign (@) in a reference to a table in a remote database.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Correct the reference and retry the operation. The correct syntax for denoting a table in a remote database follows: 

username.table_name@ database_name 


Spaces before and after the at-sign (@) are optional.

column6: invalid number of column names specified
column7: The number of column names specified in a CREATE VIEW statement did not correspond to the number of columns listed in the SELECT clause. If column names are specified in a CREATE VIEW statement, exactly one name must be specified for each column or expression in the SELECT clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one view column name for each column in the SELECT clause.

column6: circular view definition encountered
column7: Through a series of CREATE and DROP VIEW statements, a view was defined that refers to itself. For example, VIEW1 might include a column from VIEW2 that is defined as a column in VIEW1. View definitions may be seen by querying the data dictionary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the view definitions, remove any circular references, and retry the statements.

column6: data manipulation operation not legal on this view
column7: An attempt was made to use an UPDATE, INSERT, or DELETE statement on a view that contains expressions or functions or was derived from more than one table. If a join operation was used to create the view or the view contains virtual columns derived from functions or expressions, then the view may only be queried.
column8: From Oracle doc: UPDATE, INSERT, or DELETE rows in the base tables instead and restrict the operations on the view to queries.

column6: virtual column not allowed here
column7: An attempt was made to use an INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE statement on an expression in a view.
column8: From Oracle doc: INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE data in the base tables, instead of the view.

column6: illegal parameters - EXTENT MIN higher than EXTENT MAX
column7: An incorrect value is specified for the parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the parameter and reissue the statement.

column6: invalid ALTER TABLE option
column7: An invalid option was specified in an ALTER TABLE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement syntax, specify a valid option, and retry the statement.

column6: [NOT] SUCCESSFUL expected
column7: An AUDIT or NOAUDIT statement contained WHENEVER followed by something other than SUCCESSFUL or NOT SUCCESSFUL.
