column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the WHENEVER clause and retry the statement.

column6: valid modes: [ROW] SHARE, [[SHARE] ROW] EXCLUSIVE, SHARE UPDATE
column7: The lock mode entered was not recognized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter one of the following: SHARE, ROW SHARE, EXCLUSIVE, ROW EXCLUSIVE, SHARE ROW EXCLUSIVE, or SHARE UPDATE.

column6: missing IN keyword
column7: In a LOCK TABLE statement, the keyword IN was missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Place the keyword IN and lock mode directly after the table name in the LOCK TABLE statement and retry the statement.

column6: missing MODE keyword
column7: In a LOCK TABLE statement, the keyword MODE was missing. The keyword MODE must directly follow the specified lock mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement syntax, insert the keyword MODE where required, and retry the statement.

column6: missing double quote in identifier
column7: An initial double quote (") was found without a closing quote. If an identifier contains a blank or special characters other than $, #, or _, it must be enclosed in double quotes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add a closing double quote (") to the end of the identifier.

column6: illegal zero-length identifier
column7: An attempt was made to use two double quotes ("") as an identifier. An identifier must be at least one character long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Insert at least one character between the double quotes in the identifier. If a blank identifier is required, specify a blank space between the double quotes (" ").

column6: comment not terminated properly
column7: The indicated comment or hint begun with the /* token did not have the terminating */.
column8: From Oracle doc: Properly terminate the comment or hint with a */.

column6: only pure functions can be indexed
column7: The indexed function uses SYSDATE or the user environment.
column8: From Oracle doc: PL/SQL functions must be pure (RNDS, RNPS, WNDS, WNPS). SQL expressions must not use SYSDATE, USER, USERENV(), or anything else dependent on the session state. NLS-dependent functions are OK.

column6: inappropriate INTO
column7: The INTO clause may not be used in a subquery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax, place the INTO clause in the top-level query, and retry the statement.

column6: invalid host/bind variable name
column7: A colon in a bind variable or INTO specification was followed by an inappropriate name, perhaps a reserved word.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the variable name and retry the operation.

column6: indicator variable not permitted here
column7: An indicator variable is not permitted in this context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the indicator variable and retry the operation.

column6: invalid user.table.column, table.column, or column specification
column7: A column name was specified improperly in the current SQL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement's syntax, especially references to column names, and retry the statement.

column6: only simple column names allowed here
column7: This SQL statement does not allow a qualified column name, such as username.table.column or table.column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the qualifications from the column and retry the operation.

column6: you may not GRANT/REVOKE privileges to/from yourself
column7: Grantor is not allowed to grant or revoke object or system privileges to self.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue the GRANT or REVOKE of system privileges from another database administrator account.

column6: UPDATE/REFERENCES may only be REVOKEd from the whole table, not by column
column7: Although it is possible to GRANT update privileges on a column-by-column basis, it is only possible to REVOKE them for an entire table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not identify specific columns. To revoke update privileges for certain columns, use REVOKE for the entire table and GRANT the user privileges for specific columns.

column6: Invalid dump undo option
column7: An invalid option is specified in the ALTER DUMP UNDO command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct and reissue the command.

column6: cannot delete from view without exactly one key-preserved table
column7: The deleted table either had no key preserved tables, had more than one key-preserved table, or the key-preserved table was an unmerged view or a table from a read-only view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Redefine the view or delete it from the underlying base tables.

column6: column definition incompatible with clustered column definition
column7: When adding a table to a cluster, the definition of the column in the table was inconsistent with the definition of the column in the cluster.
column8: From Oracle doc: The table cannot be added to the cluster until all cluster column definitions are consistent.

column6: a table may contain only one column of type LONG
column7: An attempt was made to add a LONG column to a table which already had a LONG column. Note that even if the LONG column currently in the table has already been marked unused, another LONG column may not be added until the unused columns are dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the LONG column currently in the table by using the ALTER TABLE command.

column6: Must specify an extent number or block number
column7: Expecting an extent or block number but something else was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the error and reissue the command.

column6: quoted %s not properly terminated
column7: A quoted string must be terminated with a single quote mark (').
column8: From Oracle doc: Insert the closing quote and retry the statement.

column6: Must specify an object number
column7: Expecting an object number but something else was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the error and reissue the command.

column6: table must be empty to add mandatory (NOT NULL) column
column7: It is not possible to define a new column as NOT NULL if rows already exist in the table being modified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the statement without the NOT NULL specification.

column6: user function is incorrectly defined
column7: A user function has been improperly defined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: illegal argument for function
column7: The argument or arguments specified for the function are not valid in this context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the definition of the function and correct the arguments.

column6: DML operation does not map to a unique table in the join
column7: The primary table is the base table against which the update, insert or delete operation is finally being done. For delete either there is no primary table in the join query or there is more than one. For update or insert the columns specified map to more than one base table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the join specification.

column6: vopdrv: view query block not in FROM
column7: This is an internal error message not normally issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: update or delete involves outer joined table
column7: For deletes, the table being deleted from is outer joined to some other table. For updates, either the table being updated is outer- joined to some other table, or some table reachable from the primary table is being outer joined to a table not reachable from the primary table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the join specification.

column6: new update value of join is not guaranteed to be unique
column7: A row of a join query table is being updated using a row of a table that is not guaranteed to have exactly one value for the row being updated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the join specification.

column6: specifying table's owner name is not allowed
column7: A table or view name was specified with a period (.) or identified with an invalid prefix.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the object is identified correctly and if necessary remove the period from the name.

column6: dictionary table not allowed in this context
column7: The name of a data dictionary object was used outside the FROM clause of a SELECT statement. The only operation allowed on a data dictionary object is to SELECT from it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restrict operations on data dictionary objects to queries.

column6: UPDATE ... SET expression must be a subquery
column7: An attempt was made to use a single expression without a subquery to update a list of columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax for using subqueries to update data and add the necessary subquery.

column6: number %s too long
column7: A number entered exceeds the limit of 255 characters, including digits, sign, decimal point, and exponent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shorten the number string, perhaps by expressing it in scientific notation, for example, 1.85E9 instead of 1,850,000,000.

column6: duplicate CLUSTER option specifications
column7: During a CREATE of a clustered table, the user attempted to specify more than one CLUSTER option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the extra CLUSTER option.

column6: CLUSTER option not allowed in CREATE CLUSTER command
column7: An attempt was made to use the CLUSTER option within a CREATE CLUSTER statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the CLUSTER clause and try again.

column6: illegal option for a clustered table
column7: During a CREATE or ALTER of a clustered table, the user attempted to enter one or more of the following options: INITRANS, MAXTRANS, PCTFREE, PCTUSED, STORAGE, TABLESPACE, CACHE, NOCACHE. These options may only be specified for the cluster itself.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option(s).

column6: Must specify a value for LEVEL
column7: Expecting the value of LEVEL but something else was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the error and reissue the command.

column6: may not specify column datatypes in this CREATE TABLE
column7: Column datatypes were specified in a SELECT statement used to create and load a table directly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove column datatypes. The datatypes of the SELECT list expressions are automatically used as the column datatypes.

column6: Dump undo option specified more than once
column7: The same option for ALTER DUMP UNDO was specified twice.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the redundant options and reissue the command.

column6: looping chain of synonyms
column7:
Through a series of CREATE synonym statements, a synonym was defined that referred to itself. For example, the following definitions are circular: 

CREATE SYNONYM s1 for s2 
CREATE SYNONYM s2 for s3 
CREATE SYNONYM s3 for s1
column8: From Oracle doc: Change one synonym definition so that it applies to a base table or view and retry the operation.

column6: cannot modify more than one base table through a join view
column7: Columns belonging to more than one underlying table were either inserted into or updated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Phrase the statement as two or more separate statements.

column6: WITH GRANT OPTION not allowed in this system
column7: This version of Oracle does not support the WITH GRANT OPTION.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the WITH GRANT option.

column6: maximum subquery nesting level exceeded
column7: An attempt was made to use more than 255 levels of nested subqueries.
column8: From Oracle doc: Merge some of the subqueries into their containing queries, until there are less than 255 levels of nesting.

column6: cannot modify a column which maps to a non key-preserved table
column7: An attempt was made to insert or update columns of a join view which map to a non-key-preserved table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the underlying base tables directly.

column6: %s literal required
column7: In a COMMENT statement, the Comment following the keyword IS must be a quoted string literal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the Comment is a string literal.

column6: UNRECOVERABLE cannot be specified without AS SELECT
column7: UNRECOVERABLE was specified in a CREATE TABLE statement without also specifying a populating subquery with an AS clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify UNRECOVERABLE.

column6: UNRECOVERABLE cannot be specified for a cluster or clustered table
column7: A CREATE CLUSTER, or clustered CREATE TABLE statement specified UNRECOVERABLE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify UNRECOVERABLE.

column6: only one RECOVERABLE or UNRECOVERABLE clause may be specified
column7: RECOVERABLE was specified more than once, UNRECOVERABLE was specified more than once, or both RECOVERABLE and UNRECOVERABLE were specified in a CREATE TABLE or CREATE INDEX or ALTER INDEX REBUILD statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the RECOVERABLE or UNRECOVERABLE clauses and reissue the statement.

column6: RECOVERABLE cannot be specified with database media recovery disabled
column7: A CREATE TABLE or CREATE INDEX statement specified RECOVERABLE when the database was running in NOARCHIVELOG mode. Since logs are not being archived, they will be overwritten and the object being created cannot be recovered from a backup taken before the object was created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify RECOVERABLE, or restart the database with media recovery enabled.

column6: ORDER BY item must be the number of a SELECT-list expression
column7: Either an ORDER BY item for a set expression is not a column number, or the ORDER BY item is not the number of a SELECT list column.
column8: From Oracle doc: The ORDER BY item must be a number between 1 and the number of columns in the SELECT list. Check the column number and retry the statement.

column6: FOR UPDATE of this query expression is not allowed
column7: An attempt was made to use a FOR UPDATE clause on the result of a set expression involving GROUP BY, DISTINCT, UNION, INTERSECT, or MINUS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax, remove the FOR UPDATE clause, and retry the statement.

column6: only one clause allowed per query block
column7: An attempt was made to use more than one WHERE, GROUP BY, CONNECT BY, or HAVING clause in the query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Combine the duplicate clauses into a single clause and retry the statement.

column6: CONNECT BY clause required in this query block
column7: A START WITH clause was specified without a CONNECT BY clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax, specify a CONNECT BY clause, and retry the statement.

column6: query block has incorrect number of result columns
column7: All of the queries participating in a set expression do not contain the same number of SELECT list columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that all the queries in the set expression have the same number of SELECT list columns.

column6: expression must have same datatype as corresponding expression
column7: A SELECT list item corresponds to a SELECT list item with a different datatype in another query of the same set expression.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that all corresponding SELECT list items have the same datatypes. Use the TO_NUMBER, TO_CHAR, and TO_DATE functions to do explicit data conversions.

column6: not a SELECTed expression
column7: There is an incorrect ORDER BY item. The query is a SELECT DISTINCT query with an ORDER BY clause. In this context, all ORDER BY items must be constants, SELECT list expressions, or expressions whose operands are constants or SELECT list expressions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the inappropriate ORDER BY item from the SELECT list and retry the statement.

column6: maximum number of columns in a table or view is 1000
column7: While creating a table or view, more than 1000 columns were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove some columns from the table or view definition. If all the information is required, split the columns into two tables or views and join the columns when querying.

column6: maximum number of index columns is 32
column7: While creating an index, more than 32 columns were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove some columns from the index definition. If all the columns indexed are required, split them into two indexes.

column6: maximum number of cluster columns is 32
column7: More than 32 columns were specified in the cluster key.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove some of the columns from the cluster key definition. Consider concatenating multiple character strings into a single column.

column6: maximum number of expressions in a list is 1000
column7: More than 254 columns or expressions were specified in a list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove some of the expressions from the list.

column6: this operator cannot be used with lists
column7: A relational operator is not allowed in this context. When comparing lists, use only an operator that tests for equivalence, such as =, !=, or IN.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Rephrase the query so that it only compares lists for equivalence. For example, the following clause is invalid: 

WHERE (A,B) > ((C,D), (E,F)) 


It may be necessary to compare individual columns separately. For example, to see if A and B are respectively greater than C and D, use WHERE A>B AND C>D instead of WHERE (A,B)>(C,D).

column6: this operator must be followed by ANY or ALL
column7: The keyword ANY or ALL was missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement syntax and add ANY or ALL where appropriate.

column6: missing EXCEPTION keyword
column7: The EXCEPTION keyword is missing from the ENABLE clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: a column may not be outer-joined to a subquery
column7: expression(+) relop (subquery) is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either remove the (+) or make a view out of the subquery. In V6 and before, the (+) was just ignored in this case.

column6: a literal in the date format was too large to process
column7: A literal specified in a date format was too large. If a literal is entered as a date, it must be less than 220 characters long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use only literals less than 220 characters long in the date format.

column6: date format is too long for internal buffer
column7: The date format string was too long to process. This should occur only if several long literals are specified as part of a date.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove long literals from the date format string.

column6: Julian date is out of range
column7: An invalid Julian date was entered. Valid Julian dates run from 1 to 3,442,447.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid Julian date between 1 and 3,442,447.

column6: failure in getting date/time
column7: This is an internal error message that is not likely to occur. It is usually caused by a failure in the system clock.
column8: From Oracle doc: Investigate the system clock and the process that requested the date or time. If necessary, contact customer support.

column6: format code appears twice
column7: A format code was listed twice in a date specification. Each format code may be specified only once in the function TO_DATE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate format code from the date specification, then retry the operation.

column6: Julian date precludes use of day of year
column7: Both a Julian date and a day of the year were specified in the TO_DATE function. If a Julian date is specified, the day of the year (DDD) may not be specified, as it is contained in the Julian date.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the day of the year or the Julian date from the specification, then retry the operation.

column6: year may only be specified once
column7: More than one year format code was listed in a date specification. Only one of the following year format codes may be specified in a date: YYYY, YYY, YY, Y.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one year format from the date specification.

column6: hour may only be specified once
column7: More than one hour format code was listed in a date specification. Only one of the following hour format codes may be specified in a date: HH, HH12, HH24.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one hour format from the date specification.

column6: AM/PM conflicts with use of A.M./P.M.
column7: Both types of meridian indicators, AM and PM, were listed in a date specification. If one of the meridian indicator format masks, such as AM or A.M., is specified in the date, the other may not be specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use one meridian indicator format, with or without periods, consistently.

column6: BC/AD conflicts with use of B.C./A.D.
column7: Both types of BC/AD indicators were listed in a date specification. If one of the BC/AD indicator format masks, such as BC or B.C., is specified in the date, the other may not be specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use one BC/AD indicator format, with or without periods, consistently.

column6: month may only be specified once
column7: More than one month format code was listed in a date specification. Only one of the following month format codes may be specified in a date: MM, MON, MONTH.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one month format from the date specification.

column6: day of week may only be specified once
column7: More than one day-of-the-week format code was listed in a date specification. Only one of the following day-of-the-week format codes may be specified in a date: D, DY, DAY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one day-of-the-week format from the date specification.

column6: 'HH24' precludes use of meridian indicator
column7: A date specification contained both a 24-hour time format code and a meridian indicator code. If hours are specified using the 24-hour time format (HH24), a meridian indicator, AM or PM, may not be specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the meridian indicator format code, AM/PM or A.M./P.M., or the 24-hour time format code, HH24, from the date specification.

column6: signed year precludes use of BC/AD
column7: A date specification contained both a signed year and a B.C./A.D. indicator. If the year is specified with a sign, such as SYYYY, then B.C. or A.D. is implicit in the date and must not be entered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the B.C./A.D. indicator from the date specification.

column6: format code cannot appear in date input format
column7: A date specification contained an invalid format code. Only the following may be specified when entering a date: year, month, day, hours, minutes, seconds, Julian day, A.M./P.M. and B.C./A.D.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid format code from the date specification.

column6: date format not recognized
column7: A date specification contained an invalid format code.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that only valid date format codes are specified.

column6: era format code is not valid with this calendar
column7: An era format code, E or EE, was specified with a calendar which does not use era information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation using a date format mask which does not contain era format codes.

column6: date format picture ends before converting entire input %s
column7: A valid date format picture included extra data. The first part of the format picture was converted into a valid date, but the remaining data was not required.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the specifications for date format pictures and correct the statement.

column6: year conflicts with Julian date
column7: The wrong year was specified with a Julian day. If a year is specified with a Julian date, it must be the year in which the Julian date occurs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the year value from the date specification or enter the correct year for the Julian date.

column6: day of year conflicts with Julian date
column7: A Julian date was specified with the day of the year but the day did not correspond to the Julian date. If the day of the year is specified with a Julian date, it must be the same day as the Julian date.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the day of the year value from the date specification or enter the correct day for the Julian date.

column6: month conflicts with Julian date
column7: The wrong month was specified with a Julian date. If a month is specified with a Julian date, it must be the month in which the Julian date occurs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the month value from the date specification or enter the correct month for the Julian date.

column6: day of month conflicts with Julian date
column7: A Julian date was specified with the day of the month, but the month day did not correspond to the Julian date. If the day of the month is specified with a Julian date, it must be the same day of the month as the Julian date.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the day of the month value from the date specification or enter the correct day of the month for the Julian date.

column6: day of week conflicts with Julian date
column7: A Julian date was specified with the day of the week, but the weekday did not correspond to the Julian date. If the day of the week is specified with a Julian date, it must be the same day of the week as the Julian date.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the day of the week value from the date specification or enter the correct day of the week for the Julian date.

column6: hour conflicts with seconds in day
column7: The wrong hour was specified with seconds in the day. If an hour is specified with seconds past midnight (SSSSS), it must be the hour in which the seconds value falls.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the hour value from the date specification or specify the correct hour for the seconds past midnight.

column6: minutes of hour conflicts with seconds in day
column7: A date specification contained both minutes of the hour and seconds in the day but the values did not correspond. If both minutes in the hour (MI) and seconds past midnight (SSSSS) are specified, the minutes value must be the minute in which the seconds value will occur.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the minutes value from the date specification or enter the correct minute value for the specified seconds value.

column6: seconds of minute conflicts with seconds in day
column7: A date specification contained both seconds of the minute and seconds in the day but the values did not correspond. If both types of seconds are specified, the seconds of the minute value (SS) must be the second in which the seconds past midnight value (SSSSS) will fall.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the seconds of the minute value from the date specification or enter a value that corresponds to the given seconds in the day.

column6: date not valid for month specified
column7: The day of the month specified in the date is invalid for the given month. The day of the month (DD) must be between 1 and the number of days in the month.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid day of the month for the specified month.

column6: input value not long enough for date format
column7: The data to be converted to date format was incomplete; the date format picture was longer than the input data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either add more input or shorten the date picture format, then retry the operation.

column6: (full) year must be between -4713 and +9999, and not be 0
column7: A date specified a year that is not in the valid date range. A valid date is any date between January 1, 4712 B.C. and December 31, 9999 A.D.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid date value between 4712 B.C. and 9999 A.D.

column6: quarter must be between 1 and 4
column7: An invalid value was specified for the quarter of the year in a date. The quarter (Q) must be between 1 and 4.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a value for quarter between 1 and 4.

column6: not a valid month
column7: A date specified an invalid month. Valid months are: January-December, for format code MONTH, and Jan-Dec, for format code MON.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid month value in the correct format.

column6: week of year must be between 1 and 52
column7: An invalid value was specified for the week of the year in a date. Week of the year (WW) must be between 1 and 52.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a week of the year value between 1 and 52.

column6: week of month must be between 1 and 5
column7: An invalid value was specified for the week of the month in a date. Week of the month (W) must be between 1 and 5.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a week of the month value between 1 and 5.

column6: not a valid day of the week
column7:
A date specified an invalid day of the week. Valid days are:

Monday-Sunday, for format code DAY 

Mon-Sun, for format code DY 

1-7, for format code D
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid day of the week value in the correct format.

column6: day of month must be between 1 and last day of month
column7: The day of the month listed in a date is invalid for the specified month. The day of the month (DD) must be between 1 and the number of days in that month.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid day value for the specified month.

column6: day of year must be between 1 and 365 (366 for leap year)
column7: An invalid day of the year was specified in a date. Day of the year (DDD) must be between 1 and 365 for a non-leap year or 1 and 366 for a leap year.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a day of the year value between 1 and 365 (or 366).

column6: hour must be between 1 and 12
column7: An invalid hour was specified for a date using the 12-hour time format. If a 12-hour format code (HH or HH12) is used, the specified hour must be between 1 and 12.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter an hour value between 1 and 12.

column6: hour must be between 0 and 23
column7: An invalid hour was specified for a date using the 24-hour time format. If the 24-hour format code (HH24) is listed, the specified hour must be between 0 and 23.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter an hour value between 0 and 23.

column6: minutes must be between 0 and 59
column7: An invalid minute value was specified in a date. Minutes must be between 0 and 59.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a minute value between 0 and 59.

column6: seconds must be between 0 and 59
column7: An invalid seconds value was specified in a date. Seconds must be between 0 and 59 if the seconds format code (SS) is used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a seconds value between 0 and 59.

column6: seconds in day must be between 0 and 86399
column7: An invalid value for seconds in the day was specified in a date. Seconds must be between 0 and 86399 if the seconds past midnight format code (SSSSS) is used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a seconds value between 0 and 86399.

column6: julian date must be between 1 and 5373484
column7: An invalid Julian date was entered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid Julian date between 1 and 5373484.

column6: AM/A.M. or PM/P.M. required
column7: A date specification contained a meridian indicator format code but a valid meridian indicator was not specified. If a meridian indicator code, A.M./P.M. or AM/PM, is included in a date format, the date must include a valid meridian indicator.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the meridian indicator in the correct format, A.M./AM or P.M./PM.

column6: BC/B.C. or AD/A.D. required
column7: A date specification contained a BC/AD format code but a valid BC/AD indicator was not specified. If one of the BC/AD format codes, BC/AD or B.C./A.D., is specified in a date format, the date must include BC/B.C. or AD/A.D.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the BC/AD indicator in the date using the correct format.

column6: not a valid time zone
column7: An incorrect time zone code was specified for the NEW_TIME function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the invalid time zone code, then retry the operation.

column6: a non-numeric character was found where a numeric was expected
column7: The input data to be converted using a date format model was incorrect. The input data did not contain a number where a number was required by the format model.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the input data or the date format model to make sure the elements match in number and type. Then retry the operation.

column6: a non-alphabetic character was found where an alphabetic was expected
column7: The input data to be converted using a date format model was incorrect. The input data did not contain a letter where a letter was required by the format model.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the input data or the date format model to make sure the elements match in number and type. Then retry the operation.

column6: week of year must be between 1 and 53
column7: A week number outside the range 1 to 53 was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use only a value within the valid range for the week number.

column6: literal does not match format %s
column7: Literals in the input must be the same length as literals in the format string (with the exception of leading white space). If the "FX" modifier has been toggled on, the literal must match exactly, with no extra white space.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the format string to match the literal.

column6: the numeric value does not match the length of the format item
column7: When the FX and FM format codes are specified for an input date, then the number of digits must be exactly the number specified by the format code. For example, 9 will not match the format specifier DD but 09 will.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the input date or turn off the FX or FM format specifier in the format string.

column6: the year is not supported for the current calendar
column7: The year is not supported for the current calendar.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the documentation to find out what years are supported for the current calendar.

column6: the date is out of range for the current calendar
column7: Your calendar does not extend to the specified date.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a date which is legal for this calendar.

column6: not a valid era
column7: Era input does not match a known era.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a valid era on input.

column6: the datetime class is invalid
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: the interval is invalid
column7: The character string you specified is not a valid interval.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid interval.

column6: the leading precision of the interval is too small
column7: The leading precision of the interval is too small to store the specified interval.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the leading precision of the interval or specify an interval with a smaller leading precision.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: Not an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: the intervals or datetimes are not mutually comparable
column7: The intervals or datetimes are not mutually comparable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a pair of intervals or datetimes that are mutually comparable.

column6: the number of seconds must be less than 60
column7: The number of seconds specified was greater than 59.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a value for seconds that is 59 or smaller.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: Not an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: the leading precision of the interval is too small
column7: The leading precision of the interval is too small to store the specified interval.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the leading precision of the interval or specify an interval with a smaller leading precision.

column6: time zone hour must be between -12 and 13
column7: The time zone hour specified was not in the valid range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a time zone hour between -12 and 13.

column6: time zone minute must be between -59 and 59
column7: The time zone minute specified was not in the valid range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a time zone minute between -59 and 59.

column6: year must be at least -4713
column7: The specified year was not in range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a year that is greater than or equal to -4713.

column6: %s is too long for internal buffer
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: specified field not found in datetime or interval
column7: The specified field was not found in the datetime or interval.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the specified field is in the datetime or interval.

column6: the hh25 field must be between 0 and 24
column7: The specified hh25 field was not in the valid range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an hh25 field between 0 and 24.

column6: the fractional seconds must be between 0 and 999999999
column7: The specified fractional seconds were not in the valid range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a value for fractional seconds between 0 and 999999999.

column7: An NLS error was detected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look for additional error messages and take appropriate action. If there are no additional errors, call Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Datetime/Interval internal error
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: too many precision specifiers
column7: While trying to truncate or round dates, extra data was found in the date format picture.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the date format picture and retry.

column6: bad precision specifier
column7: An invalid precision code was specified in a date.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid precision code in the date format. Valid precision types are: century, year, month, day, Julian date, hours, minutes, and seconds.

column7: AUDIT or NOAUDIT on a sequence number specifies an auditing option that is not legal for sequence numbers.
column8: From Oracle doc: The following options may not be used for sequence numbers and should be removed: COMMENT, DELETE, INDEX, INSERT, LOCK, RENAME, UPDATE, REFERENCES, EXECUTE.

column6: invalid auditing option for views
column7: AUDIT or NOAUDIT on a view specifies an auditing option that is not legal for views.
column8: From Oracle doc: The following options may not be used for views and should be removed: ALTER, INDEX, REFERENCES, EXECUTE.

column6: keyword ONLINE, OFFLINE, RESIZE, AUTOEXTEND or END/DROP expected
column7: An expected keyword was not used for DATAFILE/TEMPFILE clause
column8: From Oracle doc: Use correct syntax.

column7: There is not a user or role by that name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-specify the name.

column7: User does not exist in the system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify the user name is correct.

column6: role '%s' does not exist
column7: Role by that name does not exist.

column7: There is already a user or role with that name.

column7: Cascade is required to remove this user from the system. The user own's object which will need to be dropped.

column7: Cannot drop the user's objects; someone has them locked.

column7: Set role can only be performed with roles granted directly to your account (for example, a sub-role cannot be enabled).
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not try to set the role.

column7: The initialization parameter MAX_ENABLED_ROLES has been exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase MAX_ENABLED_ROLES and warm start the database.

column6: cannot GRANT to a role WITH GRANT OPTION
column7: Role cannot have a privilege with the grant option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform the grant without the grant option.

column6: cannot REVOKE privileges you did not grant

column8: From Oracle doc: Do not revoke these privileges.

column6: GRANT option not granted for all privileges
column7: In order to grant a privilege, you must first have the privilege with the grant option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Obtain the privilege with the grant option and try again.

column6: IDENTIFIED EXTERNALLY already specified

column6: no privileges on tablespace '%s'

column8: From Oracle doc: Grant the user the appropriate system privileges or grant the user space resource on the tablespace.

column6: ROLE '%s' not granted to '%s'

column6: system privileges not granted to '%s'

column6: command no longer valid, see ALTER USER

column6: DEFAULT ROLE clause not valid for CREATE USER

column6: DEFAULT ROLE '%s' not granted to user

column8: From Oracle doc: Grant the role to the user.

column6: invalid command when OS_ROLES are being used
column7: This command cannot be used when the initialization parameter OS_ROLES is TRUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Grant the role to the user in the operating system.

column6: Keyword MIN or MAX expected, not found
column7: The keyword MIN or MAX was expected as an argument.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter the keyword MIN or MAX and retry the operation.

column6: Must supply an integer for the LAYER option
column7: An item other than an integer was entered for the LAYER option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter an integer for the LAYER option and retry the operation.

column6: Must supply an integer for the OPCODE option
column7: An item other than an integer was entered for the OPCODE option. The value in ALTER SYSTEM DUMP ... OPCODE value must be an integer.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Enter an integer for the OPCODE option and retry the operation. 

For more information on the OPCODE option, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: Invalid dump logfile option
column7: An invalid option was entered for the ALTER SYSTEM DUMP LOGFILE option command.
column8: From Oracle doc: For a list of valid options for DUMP LOGFILE, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: Invalid dump option
column7: An invalid option was entered for the ALTER SYSTEM DUMP command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid option for ALTER SYSTEM DUMP. Examples of valid options are LOGFILE and UNDO. For more information on the DUMP option, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: Must specify a file number or log sequence number
column7: An invalid file number or log sequence number was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid file number or log sequence number and retry the operation. For more information on valid file and log sequence numbers, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: Must specify a block number
column7: An invalid block number was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid block number and retry the operation. For more information on valid block numbers, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: Must specify a time for the TIME option
column7: A value was entered for the TIME option that could not be interpreted as a date.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid date. For more information on the TIME option, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: Must specify a PERIOD
column7: A period is missing between the file number and the block number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a period between the file number and the block number, then retry the operation. For more information on file numbers and block numbers, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: invalid option for CREATE CONTROLFILE
column7: An invalid CREATE CONTROLFILE option is present.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only valid CREATE CONTROLFILE options.

column6: Only specify RESETLOGS or NORESETLOGS once
column7: The keyword RESETLOGS or NORESETLOGS has appeared more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Be sure to specify RESETLOGS or NORESETLOGS exactly once.

column6: You must specify RESETLOGS or NORESETLOGS
column7: Missing a RESETLOGS or a NORESETLOGS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Be sure to specify RESETLOGS or NORESETLOGS exactly once.

column6: You must specify a database name for CREATE CONTROLFILE
column7: Missing a database name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retype CREATE CONTROLFILE command with the DATABASE keyword.

column6: Illegal ALTER TRACING option
column7: An invalid ALTER TRACING option is present.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only valid ALTER TRACING options. Examples of valid options are ENABLE and DISABLE. For more information, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: Must specify a %s for ALTER TRACING ENABLE or DISABLE
column7: Something other than a valid identifier was specified for ALTER TRACING ENABLE or DISABLE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid identifier for ALTER TRACING ENABLE or DISABLE and retry the operation. For more information on valid identifiers, see the Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: Missing change number
column7: Keyword CHANGE found but change number not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the command line and resubmit.

column6: Illegal archive option
column7: An invalid option to the ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE command was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the command and retry it.

column6: Illegal character in change number %s
column7: An invalid change number was supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit the command with a valid change number.

column6: Missing change number
column7: A change number was required, but not supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the command, supply a change number where needed, then retry the command.

column6: Missing thread number
column7: Keyword THREAD found but thread number not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the command line and resubmit.

column6: Missing sequence number
column7: Keyword SEQUENCE found but sequence number not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the command line and resubmit.

column6: missing or invalid password for role '%s'
column7: An attempt was made to enable a role without giving the proper password.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the IDENTIFIED BY clause in SET ROLE to specify the correct password.

column6: error during OS ROLE initialization
column7: An operating system error occurred while loading a users OS ROLES.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the operating system error.

column6: CASCADE CONSTRAINTS must be specified to perform this revoke
column7: During this revoke some foreign key constraints will be removed. In order to perform this automatically, CASCADE CONSTRAINTS must be specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the constraints or specify CASCADE CONSTRAINTS.

column6: invalid auditing option for tables
column7: AUDIT or NOAUDIT on a table specifies an auditing option that is not legal for tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: The following options may not be used for tables and should be removed: REFERENCES, EXECUTE.

column6: invalid auditing option for DEFAULT
column7: AUDIT or NOAUDIT on a DEFAULT specifies an auditing option that is not legal for DEFAULT.
column8: From Oracle doc: The following options may not be used for DEFAULT and should be removed: REFERENCES.

column6: invalid auditing option for procedures/packages/functions
column7: AUDIT or NOAUDIT on a DEFAULT specifies an auditing option that is not legal for procedures, packages, or functions.
column8: From Oracle doc: The following options may not be used for procedures, packages, and functions and should be removed: all but EXECUTE.

column6: cannot create user as LICENSE_MAX_USERS parameter exceeded
column7: Maximum users in the database license limit exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase license limit.

column6: invalid option for OPTIMIZER_GOAL
column7: An invalid OPTIMIZER_GOAL option is present.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax for OPTIMIZER_GOAL, specify a valid option and re-execute the statement.

column6: client os username is too long
column7: A client's operating system username is too long for the operating system logon to succeed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a shorter operating system username.

column6: remote os logon is not allowed
column7: Remote operating system login attempted when not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a local client, or use the REMOTE_OS_AUTHENT system parameter to turn on remote operating system logon.

column6: role '%s' not authorized by operating system
column7: The operating system role does not exist, is not granted to you, or you did not provide the correct password.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-attempt the SET ROLE with a valid operating system role and password, if necessary.

column6: error opening password file '%s'
column7:
An attempt to open the specified password file failed because of one of the following errors: 

An operating system error occurred. 

ORAPWD is already running, so the password file is locked. 

The environment variables ORA_sid_PWFILE and ORA_PWFILE are not set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for the above causes and correct as necessary.

column6: invalid password file '%s'
column7: The specified password file name is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a correct password file name.

column6: error closing password file '%s'
column7: The password file could not be closed because of an operating system error or because an authentication action failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for the above causes and correct as necessary.

column6: error writing password file '%s'
column7: The password file could not be written to because of an operating system error or because an authentication action failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for the above causes and correct as necessary.

column6: GRANT failed: cannot add users to shared password file
column7: A grant failed because a user could not be added to the password file. This is because the value of the REMOTE_LOGIN_PASSWORDFILE initialization parameter is set to SHARED.
column8: From Oracle doc: To add a user to the password file, shut down the database, change the REMOTE_LOGIN_PASSWORDFILE initialization parameter to EXCLUSIVE, and restart the database.

column6: error reading password file '%s'
column7: An operating system error occurred when trying to read the password file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the operating system error.

column6: GRANT failed: password file '%s' is full
column7: The grant failed when a user could not be added to the password file, because all available slots in it were used already.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Either create a larger password file or free up slots in the password file by revoking the SYSOPER and SYSDBA privileges from some of the remote users. You can determine which remote users are valid and their privileges by issuing the following query in SQL*DBA: 

SELECT * FROM V$REMOTE_USERS;

column6: GRANT failed: user '%s' is identified externally
column7: You cannot grant the SYSOPER or SYSDBA privilege to a user created with the IDENTIFIED EXTERNALLY clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you wish to grant the user the SYSOPER or SYSDBA privileges, drop and re-create the user without the IDENTIFIED EXTERNALLY clause.

column6: REVOKE failed: user SYS always has SYSOPER and SYSDBA
column7: You attempted to revoke one of the necessary privileges, SYSOPER or SYSDBA, from user SYS. These privileges cannot be revoked.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt this operation.

column6: password file mode has changed from '%s' to '%s'
column7: Another instance has started with the FORCE_PASSWORD_FILEMODE initialization parameter, which is incompatible with the startup mode of your instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down your instance and start up later when the password file changes are completed for the other instance.

column6: missing %s keyword
column7: The statement entered requires the missing keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the specified keyword.

column6: user SYS is not permitted to create indexes with freelist groups
column7: An attempt was made to create an index while running with SYS authorization.
column8: From Oracle doc: Indexes cannot be created with SYS authorization. Either do not create the index or switch to USER authorization.

column6: error while writing to audit trail
column7: The auditing facility is unable to write to the AUDIT_TRAIL table. If this error occurs, SQL statements that are currently being audited may also fail. This error will occur if the SYSTEM tablespace runs out of disk space.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add space to the SYSTEM tablespace or delete rows from the AUDIT_TRAIL table. If these operations fail or do not eliminate the problem, shut down and restart Oracle with auditing disabled. This is done by setting the initialization parameter AUDIT_TRAIL to FALSE.

column6: invalid USERENV parameter
column7: An invalid parameter was specified for the USERENV function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of the allowable parameters TERMINAL, SESSIONID, ENTRYID, or NLS_LANG.

column6: security violation
column7: A user is attempting to perform an operation without the proper permission, and this fact is being recorded in the AUDIT_TRAIL table. This message only appears in the AUDIT_TRAIL table's return code column.
column8: From Oracle doc: For auditing information only; no action required.

column6: implicit (-1) length not valid for this bind or define datatype
column7: A negative length for the define variable was passed to a define function.
column8: From Oracle doc: An explicit, non-negative, length parameter must be passed.

column6: invalid packed decimal format %s
column7: A packed decimal datatype was passed to a bind or define function, and the format string parameter was either not present or invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: A valid format string parameter must be passed for a packed decimal variable. Check the programming manual for the definition of a packed decimal format string.

column6: can't use ALLOCATE or DEALLOCATE options with REBUILD
column7: Allocate or deallocate storage and rebuild index are not compatible.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose one or the other.

column6: non-zero scale specified for nonnumeric column
column7: A scale factor was specified for a bind or define of a non-numeric variable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the scale factor to zero, then retry the operation.

column6: the size specified for a file must not be zero
column7: A value of zero was specified in a SIZE or RESIZE clause of a file specification.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use correct syntax, or, if allowed, omit the SIZE or RESIZE clause.

column6: missing host connect %s
column7: A quoted character string does not follow the keyword USING in the USING clause of a CREATE DATABASE LINK statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the host connect string, then retry the operation.

column6: duplicate database link name
column7: The database link name specified in a CREATE DATABASE LINK statement already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify a new name or drop the existing link.

column6: missing USING keyword
column7: The keyword USING does not follow the CONNECT TO clause in a CREATE DATABASE LINK statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the USING clause after the CONNECT TO clause.

column6: missing CONNECT keyword
column7: The keyword CONNECT does not follow the database link name in a CREATE DATABASE LINK statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the CONNECT clause after the database link name.

column6: cannot select FOR UPDATE from view with DISTINCT, GROUP BY, etc.
column7: An attempt was made to SELECT... FOR UPDATE from a view whose defining SELECT statement uses at least one of the following constructs in its outer block: outer join, GROUP BY clause, aggregate functions, SELECT DISTINCT, CONNECT BY clause, or set operation, UNION, INTERSECT, or MINUS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use SELECT... FOR UPDATE on this view.

column6: cannot select FOR UPDATE from remote table
column7: An attempt was made to SELECT... FOR UPDATE from a table in a remote database.
column8: From Oracle doc: It is not currently possible to SELECT... FOR UPDATE from a table in a remote database. Instead, log in or connect directly to the remote database before entering a SELECT... FOR UPDATE on its tables.

column6: cannot use a subquery in a START WITH on a remote database
column7: An attempt was made to use a subquery in a START WITH clause. Such a subquery is not currently permitted if the table in the FROM clause of the tree query is in a remote database.
column8: From Oracle doc: It is necessary to connect directly to the remote database before using a subquery in the START WITH clause.

column6: integer value required
column7: The specified value must be an integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an appropriate integer value, then retry the operation.

column6: database link of same name has an open connection
column7: The user is currently connected to a PUBLIC database link with the same name as the database link name specified in a CREATE or DROP DATABASE LINK statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close the cursors that use the PUBLIC database link.

column6: connection description for remote database not found
column7: An attempt was made to connect or log in to a remote database using a connection description that could not be found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an existing database link. Query the data dictionary to see all existing database links. See your operating system-specific Net8 documentation for valid connection descriptors.

column6: too many database links in use
column7: The current session has exceeded the INIT.ORA OPEN_LINKS maximum.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the OPEN_LINKS limit, or free up some open links by committing or rolling back the transaction and canceling open cursors that reference remote databases.

column6: DDL operations are not allowed on a remote database
column7: An attempt was made to use a DDL operation on a remote database. For example, "CREATE TABLE tablename@remotedbname...".
column8: From Oracle doc: To alter the remote database structure, you must connect to the remote database with the appropriate privileges.

column6: remote statement has unoptimized view with remote object
column7: The local view is unoptimized and contains references to objects at the remote database and the statement must be executed at the remote database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a similar view on the remote database and modify the violating view in the SQL statement with the new view@remote.

column6: START WITH or CONNECT BY predicate cannot be evaluated by remote data base
column7: The statement contains a tree query on a remote database, and the tree query's START WITH or CONNECT BY predicate contains a term that cannot be evaluated at the remote database. Such terms include calls to user functions, calls to USERENV, and references to ROWID.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the disallowed term, directly connect, or log on to the remote database.

column6: database link not found
column7: Database link to be dropped is not found in dictionary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the database link name.

column6: all tables in the SQL statement must be at the remote database
column7: A SQL statement referenced tables from multiple databases, and one or more of the remote databases are not Oracle Servers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remote updates can be performed only if all databases in the SQL statement are Oracle Servers. Update the earlier version databases in a separate statement.

column6: missing LINK keyword
column7: A keyword is missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the missing keyword.

column6: multi-row UPDATE of LONG column is not supported
column7: A bind variable with length greater than 4000 bytes is being used to update a column, and the update statement updates more than one row.
column8: From Oracle doc: You may only update a single row with such a bind variable.

column6: fetching an exact number of rows is not supported by the server
column7: The server does not support UPIALL, so the fetch of an exact number of rows cannot be emulated on the user side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect to a valid server or do not use an exact fetch.

column6: missing FILE keyword
column7: A keyword is missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the missing keyword.

column6: can only select from fixed tables/views
column7: An attempt is being made to perform an operation other than a retrieval from a fixed table/view.
column8: From Oracle doc: You may only select rows from fixed tables/views.

column6: no ROWID for fixed tables or for index-organized tables
column7: An attempt is being made to access ROWID from a fixed table or from a index-organized table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not access ROWID from a fixed table or from a index-organized table.

column6: clustered tables cannot be used before the cluster index is built
column7: User attempted to perform a DML statement on a clustered table for which no cluster index has yet been created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the cluster index.

column6: a cluster index for this cluster already exists
column7: A cluster index already exists for the cluster.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: speed bind not permitted
column7: Speed bind not allowed with supplied bind variables. Trapped internally by the system.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: illegal bundled operation combination
column7: User requested that the UPI bundled execution call perform an illegal combination of operations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a legal combination of operations and retry.

column6: too many variables to describe with automatic cursor open
column7: UPI-bundled execution call tried to perform automatic cursor open and close on a describe operation. There were too many SELECT list items or bind variables to do this.
column8: From Oracle doc: Open and close cursor explicitly.

column6: uninitialized speed bind storage
column7: An attempt was made to perform a speed-execution call on a SQL statement containing host variables without first performing a speed-bind call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform a speed-bind call before performing a speed-execution call.

column6: define is not allowed for array type
column7: A user attempted to define a select list variable of type "array". Arrays may serve only as host bind variables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the offending code.

column6: bind by value is not allowed for array type
column7: User attempted to bind an array host variable by value. Arrays may be bound only by reference.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the offending code.

column6: remote database %s does not support two-phase commit
column7: A distributed update of more than one database was attempted, but the named database does not support the prepare phase of the two-phase commit, as determined by its logon transaction traits. The transaction was rolled back.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to update the named database, unless it is the only database updated in the transaction. Distributed updates of more than one database in a single transaction can be performed only if all databases support the two-phase commit mechanism.

column6: client database did not begin a transaction
column7: An update occurred at a coordinated database without the coordinator beginning a distributed transaction. This may happen if a stored procedure commits and then performs updates, and the stored procedure is invoked remotely. It could also happen if an external transaction monitor violates the XA protocol.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the cause is the former, check that any commit is not followed by an update.

column6: too many distributed transactions
column7: The distributed transaction table is full because too many distributed transactions are active.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the DISTRIBUTED_TRANSACTIONS parameter in the initialization parameter file, shut down and restart Oracle, or run fewer transactions. If it is certain there are not too many concurrent distributed transactions, this may be an internal error. In this case, contact Oracle Customer Support. Shutting down and restarting the instance could be a workaround.

column6: must end current transaction before executing %s
column7: A transaction is in progress and one of the following commands is issued: COMMIT FORCE, ROLLBACK FORCE, or ALTER SYSTEM ENABLE DISTRIBUTED RECOVERY in single process mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: COMMIT or ROLLBACK the current transaction and retry the command.

column6: transaction manager login denied: transaction in progress
column7: A remote transaction manager tried to log in while a distributed transaction is in progress. A protocol error occurred in the remote transaction manager.
column8: From Oracle doc: End the current transaction.

column6: too many local sessions participating in global transaction
column7: There are too many sessions at this site to accommodate this transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use an existing database link so that another session need not be created at the remote site.

column6: distributed transaction already begun
column7: This is an internal error not normally encountered. A server session received a BEGIN_TRAN remote procedure call before finishing with a previous distributed transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot join the distributed transaction in progress
column7:
This can happen only when attempting to update an Oracle Version 6 and an Oracle7 database in the same transaction, because either 

A transaction is in progress against a remote database that does not support two-phase commit. 

Updates are pending and an attempt was made to update a different database that does not support two-phase commit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the current transaction before attempting the action that caused the error.

column6: attempt to begin distributed transaction without logging on
column7: The client program did not issue a distributed transaction login. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: timeout: distributed transaction waiting for lock
column7: Exceeded INIT.ORA DISTRIBUTED_LOCK_TIMEOUT seconds waiting for lock.
column8: From Oracle doc: Treat as a deadlock.

column6: transaction %s rolled back, some remote DBs may be in-doubt
column7: Network or remote failure during a two-phase commit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Notify operations; remote databases will automatically re-sync when the failure is repaired.

column6: another session in same transaction failed
column7: A session at the same site with same global transaction ID failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action necessary; the transaction is automatically recovered.

column6: remote transaction failure at %s
column7: There was some error in a remote transaction at the named database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: More descriptive messages will follow. Correct the problem specified in the following messages and retry the operation.

column6: transaction %s committed, some remote DBs may be in-doubt
column7: There was a network failure or a remote failure during the two-phase commit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Notify the database administrator. The remote databases will resynchronize automatically when the failure is repaired.

column6: transaction %s in-doubt
column7: There was a network failure or a remote failure in the two-phase commit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Notify the database administrator. The remote databases will resynchronize automatically when the failure is repaired. Monitor the DBA_2PC_PENDING table for the outcome and resubmit the transaction, if necessary.

column6: distributed update operation failed; rollback required
column7: A failure during a distributed update operation may not have rolled back all effects of the operation. Since some sites may be inconsistent with others, the transaction must roll back to a savepoint or roll back entirely.
column8: From Oracle doc: Roll back to a savepoint or roll back the entire transaction and resubmit the rolled-back statements.

column6: 2PC: %s: bad two-phase command number %s from %s
column7: There was a two-phase commit protocol error.
column8: From Oracle doc: The transaction may automatically recover. Monitor the DBA_2PC_PENDING table to determine the resolution. Enter the transaction again, if necessary. Contact Oracle Customer Support if necessary.

column6: 2PC: %s: bad two-phase recovery state number %s from %s
column7: An internal error in the two-phase recovery protocol occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: no prepared transaction found with ID %s
column7: No transaction with LOCAL_TRAN_ID or GLOBAL_TRAN_ID found in the PENDING_TRANS$ table in prepared state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the PENDING_TRANS$ table.

column6: ORA-2PC-CRASH-TEST-%s in commit comment
column7: This is a special comment used to test the two-phase commit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use this special comment (string a number 1-10).

column6: select for update specified a join of distributed tables
column7: An attempt was made to join tables in different remote databases in a SELECT... FOR UPDATE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Joined tables in a SELECT statement with the FOR UPDATE clause must reside at the same database. Simplify the SELECT... FOR UPDATE statement so that it joins only tables in the same database.

column6: lock table specified list of distributed tables
column7: Tables in a LOCK TABLE statement must reside at the same database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue multiple LOCK TABLE commands.

column6: distributed recovery received DBID %s, expected %s
column7: A database link at a coordinator no longer points to the expected database. Link may have been redefined, or a different database mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore the link definition or the remote database.

column6: preceding string%s from string%s
column7: An Oracle error was received from a remote database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the preceding error message(s).

column6: distributed operation not supported
column7:
One of the following unsupported operations was attempted:

Array execute of a remote update with a subquery that references a database link, or 

An update of a long column with bind variable and an update of a second column with a subquery that both references a database link and a bind variable, or 

A commit is issued in a coordinated session from an RPC with OUT parameters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Simplify the remote update statement.

column6: illegal option for ALTER SYSTEM
column7: The option specified for ALTER SYSTEM is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the Oracle8i SQL Reference for information about options supported.

column6: missing or invalid MTS_DISPATCHERS text
column7: A character string literal was expected, but not found, following ALTER SYSTEM SET MTS_DISPATCHERS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Place the string literal containing the dispatcher's specification after ALTER SYSTEM SET MTS_DISPATCHERS.

column6: transaction or savepoint rollback required
column7: A failure (typically a trigger or stored procedure with multiple remote updates) occurred such that the all-or-nothing execution of a previous Oracle call cannot be guaranteed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Roll back to a previous savepoint or roll back the transaction and resubmit.

column6: following severe error from string%s
column7: A severe error (disconnect, fatal Oracle error) was received from the indicated database link. See following error text.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the remote system administrator.

column6: global_names parameter must be set to TRUE for this operation
column7: A remote mapping of the statement is required but cannot be achieved because GLOBAL_NAMES should be set to TRUE for it to be achieved.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue ALTER SESSION SET GLOBAL_NAMES = TRUE if possible.

column6: database string%s does not support %s in this context
column7: The remote database does not support the named capability in the context in which it is used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Simplify the SQL statement.

column6: error initializing capabilities for remote database %s
column7: Could not load a remote-specified capability table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support for the remote SQL*Connect product.

column6: distributed database network protocol mismatch
column7: This should never happen between different PRODUCTION releases of ORACLE, but may happen between alpha and beta releases, for example.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the older release.

column6: sequence numbers not supported in remote updates
column7: Sequence numbers may not be used in INSERTS, UPDATES, or DELETES on remote tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform the operation without specifying a sequence number.

column6: cannot %s in a distributed transaction
column7: A commit or rollback was attempted from session other than the parent of a distributed transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only commit or roll back from the parent session.

column6: another instance changed state of transaction %s
column7: A commit force or rollback force was issued from a session in another instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if another Oracle instance is performing recovery of pending transactions. Query DBA_2PC_PENDING to determine the new state of the transaction.

column6: sequence not co-located with updated table or long column
column7: All referenced sequences must be located on the same node as the updated table or the long column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the problem and then reissue the statement.

column6: selects of long columns must be from co-located tables
column7: All tables returning values of long columns in a SELECT statement must be located at the same node.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the problem, then reissue the statement.

column6: invalid setting for ALTER SYSTEM FIXED_DATE
column7: An invalid value was used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a correct value.

column6: no new sessions may join a committing distributed transaction
column7: A call to UPI2BG was issued in a session for a transaction that has begun to commit in a different branch; that is, a call to UPI2EN was issued for a branch of the same transaction in another session. This can only happen when using an external transaction manager.

Contact the local database administrator to determine if network problems have been resolved. Wait until the link is open and try the operation again.

column6: database name has illegal character '%s'

column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid database name.

column6: object locked by another process in same transaction

column8: From Oracle doc: Get the more restrictive lock first. For example, if session 1 gets a share lock and session 2 gets an exclusive lock on the same object, get the exclusive lock first. Or use the same session to access the object.

column6: distributed database option not installed

column6: COMMIT is not allowed in a subordinate session

column6: network error: attempted callback+passthru

column6: transaction rolled back
column7:
The distributed transaction is assigned to the system rollback segment and is trying to get into the prepared state, but the required number of non-PREPARED slots are not available, so the transaction is rolled back. 

If the transaction aborted at a remote site, only ORA-02091 will be seen. If the transaction aborted at the host site, then both ORA-02091 and ORA-02092 will be seen.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the current transaction and then do the operation required.

column6: out of transaction table slots for distributed transaction
column7: The transaction is assigned to the system rollback segment and is trying to get into the PREPARED state, but the required number of non-PREPARED slots are not available, hence the transaction is rolled back.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add a rollback segment and retry the transaction.

column6: missing or invalid value for MAXLOGMEMBERS

column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid number after MAXLOGMEMBERS.

column6: missing or invalid constraint name

column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid identifier name for the constraint name.

column6: subquery not allowed here

column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the subquery from the statement.

column6: check constraint condition not properly ended

column8: From Oracle doc: End the condition properly.

column6: constraint specification not allowed here

column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the constraint specification from the statement.

column6: DEFAULT expression not allowed here
column7: Default value expression is not allowed for the column here in the statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the default value expression from the statement.

column6: NOT NULL not allowed after DEFAULT NULL

column8: From Oracle doc: Remove either the NOT NULL or the DEFAULT NULL specification and try again.

column6: number of referencing columns must match referenced columns

column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the referencing columns match the referenced columns.

column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number columns in the list.

column6: duplicate or conflicting NULL and/or NOT NULL specifications
column7: A duplicate or conflicting NULL and/or NOT NULL was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the conflicting specifications and try again.

column6: duplicate UNIQUE/PRIMARY KEY specifications
column7: A duplicate unique or primary key was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate specification and try again.

column6: table can have only one primary key

column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the extra primary keys and try again.

column6: such unique or primary key already exists in the table

column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the extra key and try again.

column6: ORA-nnnnn occurs while type-checking column default value expression
