column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the default value expression or do not alter the column datatype.

column6: need to specify the datatype for this column
column7: The required datatype for the column is missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the required datatype.

column6: name already used by an existing constraint
column7: The specified constraint name has to be unique.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a unique constraint name for the constraint.

column6: cannot derive the datatype of the referencing column
column7: The datatype of the referenced column is not defined as yet.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the datatype of the referenced column is defined before referencing it.

column6: unique/primary keys in table referenced by enabled foreign keys
column7: An attempt was made to drop or truncate a table with unique or primary keys referenced by foreign keys enabled in another table.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Before dropping or truncating the table, disable the foreign key constraints in other tables. You can see what constraints are referencing a table by issuing the following command: 

select constraint_name, table_name, status
from user_constraints
where r_constraint_name in (
select constraint_name from user_constraints where table_name 
='tabnam');

column6: column type incompatible with referenced column type
column7: The datatype of the referencing column is incompatible with the datatype of the referenced column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Select a compatible datatype for the referencing column.

column6: referenced table does not have a primary key
column7: The referenced table does not have a primary key.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify explicitly the referenced table unique key.

column6: key column cannot be of LONG datatype
column7: An attempt was made to define a key column of datatype LONG. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the datatype of the column or remove the LONG column from the key, and try again.

column6: no matching unique or primary key for this column-list
column7: An attempt was made to reference a unique or primary key in a table with a CREATE or ALTER TABLE statement when no such key exists in the referenced table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add the unique or primary key to the table or find the correct names of the columns with the primary or unique key, and try again.

column6: table does not have such constraint
column7: An attempt was made to reference a table using a constraint that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the constraint name or add the constraint to the table, and try again.

column6: constrained column cannot be of LONG datatype
column7: A constrained column cannot be defined as datatype LONG. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the datatype of the column or remove the constraint on the column, and try again.

column6: this unique/primary key is referenced by some foreign keys
column7: A unique or primary key referenced by foreign keys cannot be dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all references to the key before dropping it.

column6: duplicate referential constraint specifications
column7: A referential constraint was specified more than once. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate specification.

column6: such a referential constraint already exists in the table
column7: An attempt was made to specify a referential constraint that already exists. This would result in duplicate specifications and so is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Be sure to specify a constraint only once.

column6: default value type incompatible with column type
column7: The type of the evaluated default expression is incompatible with the datatype of the column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the type of the column, or modify the default expression.

column6: invalid sequence name
column7: The specified sequence name is not a valid identifier name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid identifier name for the sequence name.

column6: duplicate or conflicting MAXVALUE/NOMAXVALUE specifications
column7: Duplicate or conflicting MAXVALUE and/or NOMAXVALUE specifications.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the conflicting specifications and try again.

column6: duplicate or conflicting MINVALUE/NOMINVALUE specifications
column7: Duplicate or conflicting MINVALUE and/or NOMINVALUE clauses were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the conflicting specifications and try again.

column6: duplicate or conflicting CYCLE/NOCYCLE specifications
column7: Duplicate or conflicting CYCLE and/or NOCYCLE clauses were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the conflicting specifications and try again.

column6: duplicate or conflicting CACHE/NOCACHE specifications
column7: Duplicate or conflicting CACHE and/or NOCACHE clauses were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the conflicting specifications and try again.

column6: duplicate or conflicting ORDER/NOORDER specifications
column7: Duplicate or conflicting ORDER and/or NOORDER clauses were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the conflicting specifications and try again.

column6: cannot alter starting sequence number
column7: An attempt was made to alter a starting sequence number. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not try to alter a starting sequence number.

column6: duplicate INCREMENT BY specifications
column7: A duplicate INCREMENT BY clause was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate specification and try again.

column6: duplicate START WITH specifications
column7: A duplicate START WITH clause was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate specification and try again.

column6: no options specified for ALTER SEQUENCE
column7: No ALTER SEQUENCE option was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax. Then specify at least one ALTER SEQUENCE option.

column6: sequence number not allowed here
column7: The specified sequence number reference, CURRVAL or NEXTVAL, is inappropriate at this point in the statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax. Then remove or relocate the sequence number.

column6: invalid OPEN mode
column7: A mode other than RESETLOGS was specified in an ALTER DATABASE OPEN statement. RESETLOGS is the only valid OPEN mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid mode from the statement or replace it with the keyword RESETLOGS, and try again.

column6: sequence does not exist
column7: The specified sequence does not exist, or the user does not have the required privilege to perform this operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the sequence name is correct, and that you have the right to perform the desired operation on this sequence.

column6: check constraint (%s.%s) violated
column7: The value or values attempted to be entered in a field or fields violate a defined check constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter values that satisfy the constraint.

column6: integrity constraint (%s.%s) violated - parent key not found
column7: A foreign key value has no matching primary key value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Delete the foreign key or add a matching primary key.

column6: integrity constraint (%s.%s) violated - child record found
column7: An attempt was made to delete a row that is referenced by a foreign key.
column8: From Oracle doc: It is necessary to DELETE or UPDATE the foreign key before changing this row.

column6: cannot validate (%s.%s) - check constraint violated
column7: An attempt was made via an ALTERTABLE statement to add a check constraint to a populated table that had no complying values.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the ALTER TABLE statement, specifying a check constraint on a table containing complying values. For more information about ALTER TABLE, see Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: cannot enable (%s.%s) - constraint changed during validation
column7: While one DDL statement was attempting to enable this constraint, another DDL changed this same constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again, with only one DDL changing the constraint this time.

column6: found more than one enable/disable clause for constraint
column7: An attempt was made via a CREATE or ALTER TABLE statement to specify more than one ENABLE and/or DISABLE clause for a given constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only one ENABLE or DISABLE clause may be specified for a given constraint.

column6: cannot enable (%s.%s) - null values found
column7: An ALTER TABLE command with an ENABLE CONSTRAINT clause failed because the table contains values that do not satisfy the constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that all values in the table satisfy the constraint before issuing an ALTER TABLE command with an ENABLE CONSTRAINT clause. For more information about ALTER TABLE and ENABLE CONSTRAINT, see Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: cannot disable constraint (%s.%s) - dependencies exist
column7: An alter table disable constraint failed because the table has foreign keys that are dependent on the constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either disable the foreign key constraints or use a DISABLE CASCADE command.

column6: cannot validate (%s.%s) - parent keys not found
column7: An ALTER TABLE ENABLE CONSTRAINT command failed because the table has orphaned child records.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the table has no orphaned child records before issuing an ALTER TABLE ENABLE CONSTRAINT command. For more information about ALTER TABLE and ENABLE CONSTRAINT, see Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: cannot validate (%s.%s) - duplicate keys found
column7: An ALTER TABLE ENABLE CONSTRAINT command failed because the table has duplicate key values.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the table has no duplicate key values before issuing an ALTER TABLE ENABLE CONSTRAINT command. For more information about ALTER TABLE and ENABLE CONSTRAINT, see Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: invalid value for OIDGENERATORS
column7: A number was not specified for the value of OIDGENERATORS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a number for OIDGENERATORS.

column6: maximum number of OIDGENERATORS is 255
column7: A number greater than 255 was specified for the value of OIDGENERATORS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the number specified for OIDGENERATORS does not exceed 255.

column6: invalid or missing type name
column7: An invalid or missing type name was entered in a statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a valid type name in the statement and retry the operation.

column6: cannot drop or replace a type with type or table dependents
column7: An attempt was made to drop or replace a type that has dependents.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop all type(s) and table(s) depending on the type, then retry the operation, or use the FORCE option.

column6: invalid object identifier literal
column7:
An attempt was made to enter an object identifier literal for CREATE TYPE that is either: 

Not a string of 32 hexadecimal characters 

An object identifier that already identifies an existing object 

An object identifier different from the original object identifier already assigned to the type
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify the object identifier clause or specify a 32 hexadecimal-character object identifier literal that is unique or identical to the originally assigned object identifier. Then retry the operation.

column6: only EXECUTE privilege is valid for types
column7: An attempt was made to GRANT or REVOKE an invalid privilege (not EXECUTE) on a type.
column8: From Oracle doc: GRANT or REVOKE only the EXECUTE privilege on types.

column6: cannot create a type that already has valid dependent(s)
column7: An attempt was made to create a type that already has some valid dependent(s) (these dependents depend on the fact that the type does not exist).
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the dependents first before creating the type, or do not create the type.

column6: cannot alter with REPLACE option a type that is not valid
column7: An attempt was made to ALTER with REPLACE option a type that is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the CREATE OR REPLACE TYPE command to modify the type.

column6: invalid option %s for object type column
column7: An attempt was made to specify an invalid option, such as PACKED or UNPACKED, for the object type column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid option from column specification and retry the operation.

column6: atomic NULL violation
column7: An attempt was made to access the attributes of a NULL object instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the object instance is non-NULL before accessing.

column6: exceeded maximum number of allowable columns in table
column7: The attributes in the object type column exceeded the maximum number of columns allowed in a table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify fewer attributes for the object type and retry the operation.

column6: cannot alter with COMPILE option a valid type with type or table dependents
column7: An attempt was made to ALTER with COMPILE option a type that is valid and has type or table dependents.
column8: From Oracle doc: No need to perform this operation.

column6: cannot create extent table for VALUE ADT
column7: An attempt was made to create extent table for VALUE Object Type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify object type when creating extent table.

column6: object type contains non-queryable type %s attribute

column8: From Oracle doc: Use an object type with queryable attribute types.

column6: cannot create index on object type column or attribute

column8: From Oracle doc: index can only be created on simple, scalar columns or attributes.

column6: incorrect number of arguments for default constructor
column7: The number of arguments specified for the default constructor does not match the number of attributes of the object type.

column6: incorrect number of attributes in object type column

column6: invalid column argument to REF operator

column6: object type's default constructor expected

column6: failure in accessing storage table of the nested table column

column8: From Oracle doc: If the situation described in the following messages can be corrected, do so; otherwise contact Oracle Customer Support.

column8: From Oracle doc: If the situation described in the next error on the stack can be corrected, do so; otherwise contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: REF column cannot be specified on VALUE ADT

column6: column of datatype %s cannot be unique or a primary key
column7: An attempt was made to place a UNIQUE or a PRIMARY KEY constraint on a column of datatype VARRAY, nested table, object, LOB, FILE or REF.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the column datatype or remove the constraint. Then retry the operation.

column6: datatype specification not allowed

column8: From Oracle doc: Remove data type specification and retry the operation.

column6: cannot create constraint on column of datatype %s
column7: An attempt was made to create a constraint on a column possessing a non-constrainable datatype: VARRAY, nested table, object, LOB, FILE, or REF.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the column datatype, or remove the constraint.

column6: cannot create index on attributes of this column
column7: An attempt was made to create an index on an attributes of an object type column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify the index on the attribute.

column6: cannot create constraints on attributes of this column
column7: An attempt was made to create a constraint on an attribute of an object type column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the constraint or change the object type.

column6: cannot infer type for column
column7: A datatype was not declared for this column (in the CREATE TABLE) and an attempt was made to create a constraint on an attribute of this column.

column6: invalid datatype for cluster column
column7: An attempt was made to declare a CLUSTER column of datatype object, REF, nested table, VARRAY, LOB, or FILE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the CLUSTER column or change the datatype of the column.

column6: column attribute cannot be accessed
column7: An attempt was made to extract an attribute of an object type column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the object type for the column and retry the operation.

column6: not an object type column
column7: An attempt was made to use dotted notation on a non-ADT column; that is, "a.b.c" where "a" is not an object type.

column6: missing or invalid column constraint specification

column6: invalid column specification
column7: An attempt was made to specify the PACKED or UNPACKED keyword for a non-object type column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the PACKED or UNPACKED keyword in the column specification and retry the operation.

column6: invalid column specification
column7: An attempt was made to specify an UNPACKED column within a packed table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the UNPACKED keyword in the column specification.

column6: cannot refer to non-queryable type %s in SQL

column6: cannot revoke execute on a type with table dependents
column7: An attempt was made to revoke execute on a type that has dependents.

column6: cannot create a view with column based on CURSOR operator
column7: A CURSOR operator was used as one of the SELECT elements in the subquery of a CREATE VIEW or CREATE TABLE ... AS SELECT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the CURSOR operator and replace it with the CAST operator.

column6: cannot grant privileges on columns of an object table
column7: An attempt was made to grant privileges on the columns of an object table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose another table. Privileges cannot be granted on columns of an object table.

column6: invalid attribute type

column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid attribute from the type.

column6: invalid user-defined type - type is incomplete
column7: An attempt was made to use an incomplete type definition as a column or table datatype.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the type definition and retry the operation.

column6: cannot insert into attributes of a packed typed table
column7: A column list was specified in an INSERT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the column list specification statement.

column6: Record %s: Rejected - Error on table %s, column %s
column7: The record indicated caused an Oracle error on insert.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine the Oracle error and correct the record.

column6: Direct path connection must be homogeneous
column7: The user-side to kernel-side connection is heterogeneous.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the connection between identical hardware and operating systems.

column6: Multibyte character error
column7: Text specified by POSITION or terminated by newlines is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Edit the control file or the datafile to fix alignment of column.

column6: Conversion initialization error occurred on field %s
column7: An error occurred during conversion initialization for a field. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact customer support.

column6: Conversion error occurred on CONSTANT field %s
column7: A CONSTANT field caused an Oracle error; all rows will be rejected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine the Oracle error and correct the record.

column6: The database is out of space. The load cannot continue
column7: The load was discontinued due to space exhaustion in the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add space for the specified table.

column6: Packed Decimal conversion error
column7: The column could not be converted from packed decimal to character.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the column and make it conform to packed decimal format.

column6: Zoned Decimal conversion error
column7: The column could not be converted from packed decimal to character.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the column and make it conform to packed decimal format.

column6: Field in data file exceeded maximum specified length
column7: The field is too long for the specified column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shorten the field so that its length is less than or equal to the column length.

column6: Column not found before end of logical record (use TRAILING NULLCOLS)
column7: A column started after the end of the logical record had been reached.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the TRAILING NULLCOLS option or supply data for the column.

column6: Initial enclosing character not found
column7: The initial enclosing character of an enclosed field was not found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the character before the start of the field.

column6: Logical record ended - second enclosing character not present
column7: The second enclosing character of an enclosed field was not found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the character after the end of the field.

column6: No terminator found after TERMINATED and ENCLOSED field
column7: No terminator was found after a terminated and enclosed field.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the character after the end of the field.

column6: Record %s: Discarded - failed all WHEN clauses
column7: The record was not loaded because it failed the WHEN clauses of all the tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: Index %s was made Index Unusable due to
column7: The index was not loaded. The cause of the error is stated after the message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the cause of the error, then reload.

column6: The following index(es) on table %s were processed:
column7: The indexes listed for the named table were loaded.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: Index %s was loaded.
column7: The index specified in the message was loaded.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: Record %s: Discarded - all columns null.
column7: The record was not loaded because all of the columns in the table were null for that record.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: Warning: Variable length field was truncated.
column7: A variable length field was truncated by the end of the logical record.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is just a warning, but since a variable length field has the length embedded in the data for each row, you may want to check your data.

column6: Record %s - Warning on table %s, column %s
column7: The record indicated caused an warning.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine the warning and correct the record if necessary.

column6: Loader must be at least version %s.%s.%s.%s.%s for direct path
column7: The loader being used is incompatible with this version of the kernel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade your loader to at least the specified version or use the conventional path.

column6: Relative start position > absolute field end position.
column7: A field specified as POSITION(*+n:y) had its relative start occur after the absolute position y.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that you are not missing a delimiter and that the values of n and y are correct.

column6: Error parsing insert statement for table %s.
column7: A parsing error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the message following this parsing error message.

column6: No more slots for read buffer queue.
column7: There are no free read buffers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the READBUFFERS keyword in the loader to increase the number of read buffers.

column6: Record %s: Rejected - Error on table %s
column7: The record indicated caused an Oracle error on insert.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine the Oracle error and correct the record. The offending column(s) are not known.

column6: invalid or redundant resource
column7: A resource that is not defined or that is specified twice appears in the CREATE or ALTER PROFILE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define the resource before issuing a CREATE or ALTER PROFILE command. Also check the statement to see that each resource is listed only once.

column6: invalid resource limit
column7: An invalid resource limit of 0 was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a resource limit greater than 0.

column6: duplicate resource name %s
column7: The same resource was specified twice in a CREATE or ALTER PROFILE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue the statement again, carefully checking that each resource is used only once.

column6: profile %s already exists
column7: An attempt was made to create a profile that already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the profile with a name not already used by another profile.

column6: profile %s does not exist
column7: An attempt was made to assign a user to a non-existent profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: Assign the user to an existing profile.

column6: cannot drop PUBLIC_DEFAULT profile
column7: An attempt was made to drop the PUBLIC_DEFAULT profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: The PUBLIC_DEFAULT profile cannot be dropped.

column6: profile %s has users assigned, cannot drop without CASCADE
column7: An attempt was made to drop a profile that had users assigned to it without using the CASCADE option of the DROP PROFILE statement. A profile that has users assigned to it cannot be dropped, unless the CASCADE option is specified. CASCADE reassigns users to the PUBLIC_DEFAULT profile before dropping the profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: To reassign all users to the PUBLIC_DEFAULT profile, issue the DROP PROFILE statement with the CASCADE option.

column6: illegal cost factor
column7: A negative value or UNLIMITED cost was specified for this resource in the ALTER RESOURCE COST statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only positive integer values can be specified for resources in the ALTER RESOURCE COST statement. Issue the statement again, using a positive integer value for each resource specified.

column6: exceeded COMPOSITE_LIMIT, you are being logged off
column7: The COMPOSITE_LIMIT for the profile is exceeded. That is, the weighted sum of the connection time, logical reads per session, CPU usage per session, and private SGA space used during the session exceeded the limit set by the COMPOSITE_LIMIT clause set in the user profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: If this happens often, ask the database administrator to raise the COMPOSITE_LIMIT of the user profile, or determine which resource is used the most and raise the limit on that resource.

column6: exceeded simultaneous SESSIONS_PER_USER limit
column7: An attempt was made to exceed the maximum number of concurrent sessions allowed by the SESSIONS_PER_USER clause of the user profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: End one or more concurrent sessions or ask the database administrator to increase the SESSIONS_PER_USER limit of the user profile. For more information about SESSIONS_PER_USER and the database administrator's specific tasks of adjusting concurrent sessions, see Oracle8i SQL Reference and the Oracle8i Administrator's Guide

column6: exceeded session limit on CPU usage, you are being logged off
column7: An attempt was made to exceed the maximum CPU usage allowed by the CPU_PER_SESSION clause of the user profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: If this happens often, ask the database administrator to increase the CPU_PER_SESSION limit of the user profile.

column6: exceeded call limit on CPU usage
column7: An attempt was made to exceed the maximum CPU time for a call, a parse, execute, or fetch, allowed by the CPU_PER_CALL clause of the user profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: If this happens often, ask the database administrator to increase the CPU_PER_CALL limit of the user profile.

column6: exceeded session limit on IO usage, you are being logged off
column7: An attempt was made to exceed the maximum I/O allowed by the LOGICAL_READS_PER_SESSION clause of the user profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: If this happens often, ask the database administrator to increase the LOGICAL_READS_PER_SESSION limit of the user profile.

column6: exceeded call limit on IO usage
column7: An attempt was made to exceed the maximum I/O for a call, a parse, execute, or fetch, allowed by the LOGICAL_READS_PER_CALL clause of the user profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: If this happens often, ask the database administrator to increase the LOGICAL_READS_PER_CALL limit of the user profile.

column6: exceeded maximum idle time, please connect again
column7: A user has exceeded the maximum time allowed to remain idle.
column8: From Oracle doc: The user must reconnect to the database.

column6: exceeded PRIVATE_SGA limit, you are being logged off
column7: This error occurs only when using a multi-threaded server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the database administrator to expand the PRIVATE_SGA limit.

column6: exceeded procedure space usage
column7: Stored procedures used up too much space in the SYSTEM tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use fewer stored procedures or add an additional file to the system tablespace.

column6: exceeded maximum connect time, you are being logged off
column7: A user has exceeded the maximum time allowed to be connected to the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: The user must reconnect to the database.

column6: cannot EXPLAIN view owned by another user
column7: The view specified in the SQL statement belongs to another user and cannot be explained.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a view with the same definition that belongs to current user.

column6: PLAN_TABLE not found
column7: The table used by EXPLAIN to store row source information does not exist in the current schema.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a plan table in the current schema or use the INTO clause of the statement to put the results of the explain command in an existing plan table.

column6: plan table does not have correct format
column7: The explicit plan table does not have the appropriate field definitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Redefine the plan table to have the appropriate field definitions.

column6: specified plan table not found
column7: The specified plan table does cannot be found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the specified plan table or use an existing plan table.

column6: missing schema authorization clause
column7: The AUTHORIZATION clause is missing from a create schema statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Proceed the schema authorization identifier with the AUTHORIZATION keyword.

column6: missing or invalid schema authorization identifier
column7:
One of the following:

The schema authorization identifier is not recognized. 

An attempt was made to use a schema authorization identifier for a user while not connected as that user.
column8:
From Oracle doc: If the cause is

an unrecognized identifier, then use an existing identifier. 

connected with a different user name, then disconnect and connect to the correct user name.

column6: missing or invalid schema element
column7: A statement other than a CREATE TABLE, CREATE VIEW, or GRANT appears in a CREATE SCHEMA statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: See Oracle8i SQL Reference or the valid elements of the CREATE SCHEMA statement.

column6: schema name does not match schema authorization identifier
column7: A table definition with a schema name prepended to the table name does not match the schema name provided in the AUTHORIZATION clause of a CREATE SCHEMA STATEMENT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the schema names match the one given in the CREATE SCHEMA statement.

column6: potential circular view references or unknown referenced tables
column7: The CREATE SCHEMA statement contains a view that depends on other views contained in the CREATE SCHEMA statement, or they contain references to non-existing tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the dependent views in a separate CREATE SCHEMA statement and ensure that all referenced tables are either defined in the CREATE SCHEMA statement or exist outside the statement.

column6: create table failed
column7: A CREATE TABLE statement failed in the CREATE SCHEMA statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: The cause for failure will be presented below this message. Follow the appropriate actions as suggested by the subsequent messages.

column6: privilege grant failed
column7: A GRANT statement failed in the CREATE SCHEMA statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: The cause for failure will be presented below this message. Follow appropriate actions, as suggested by the subsequent messages.

column6: create view failed
column7: A CREATE VIEW statement failed in the CREATE SCHEMA statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: The cause for failure will be presented below this message. Follow appropriate actions, as suggested by the subsequent messages.

column6: could not add foreign key reference
column7: Oracle could not add a foreign key reference because of an error in the declaration. Either the referenced table does not exist or the table does not have a unique key.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the referenced table exists and/or has a unique key.

column6: cannot drop index used for enforcement of unique/primary key
column7: An attempt was made to drop an index that is being used as the enforcement mechanism for a unique or primary key.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the integrity constraint instead of dropping the index.

column6: cannot enable constraint (%s) - no such constraint
column7: The named constraint does not exist for this table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that a constraint exists before trying to enable it.

column6: cannot disable constraint (%s) - no such constraint
column7: The named constraint does not exist for this table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that a constraint exists before trying to disable it.

column6: cannot enable primary key - primary key not defined for table
column7: An attempt was made to enable a primary key that is not defined for the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add a primary key definition for the table.

column6: cannot disable primary key - primary key not defined for table
column7: An attempt was made to disable a primary key that is not defined for the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that a primary key exists before trying to disable it.

column6: cannot enable unique(%s) - unique key not defined for table
column7: An attempt was made to enable a unique key that is not defined for the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that a unique key exists before trying to enable it.

column6: cannot disable unique(%s) - unique key not defined for table
column7: An attempt was made to disable a unique key that is not defined for the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that a unique key exists before trying to disable it.

column6: date or system variable wrongly specified in CHECK constraint
column7: An attempt was made to use a date constant or system variable, such as USER, in a check constraint that was not completely specified in a CREATE TABLE or ALTER TABLE statement. For example, a date was specified without the century.
column8: From Oracle doc: Completely specify the date constant or system variable.

column6: cannot validate (%s.%s) - primary key violated
column7: An attempt was made to validate a primary key with duplicate values or null values.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicates and null values before enabling a primary key.

column6: Column check constraint cannot reference other columns
column7: An attempt was made to define a column check constraint that references another column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define it as a table check constraint.

column6: Unique index on a deferrable constraint is not allowed
column7: An attempt was made to enable a deferrable primary key/unique constraint that has an existing unique index on the constraint columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the index on the constraint columns or make the constraint not deferrable.

column6: Create as select with referential constraints not allowed
column7: Integrity constraints on a table cannot be created when creating the table using the CREATE TABLE... AS SELECT... form.
column8: From Oracle doc: First, create the table, and then alter the table to add the desired integrity constraints.

column6: Cannot drop nonexistent primary key
column7: An attempt was made to drop the primary key constraint on a table, but there is no primary key constraint on this table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the correct table name is entered in the statement. Otherwise, no action required.

column6: Cannot drop nonexistent unique key
column7: An attempt was made to drop a unique key constraint for a column that does not have a unique key constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make certain the correct column name was entered. Otherwise, no action required.

column6: Cannot drop constraint - nonexistent constraint
column7: An attempt was made to drop a constraint that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make certain the constraint and table name are correct and attempt the procedure again.

column6: Cannot resolve referenced object in referential constraints
column7: An attempt was made to define a foreign key with a reference to a schema object that cannot be resolved to a base table reference.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define referential constraints only with schema objects resolving to a base table.

column6: Exceptions table not found
column7: The explicitly or implicitly declared exceptions table does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the correct exceptions table name was used, then create the table and retry the enable command.

column6: CREATE TABLE ... AS SELECT failed - check constraint violated
column7: An attempt was made to use a CREATE TABLE ... AS SELECT statement when some rows violated one or more CHECK constraints.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not select rows that violate constraints.

column6: cannot defer a constraint that is not deferrable
column7: An attempt was made to defer a nondeferrable constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the constraint and create a new one that is deferrable.

column6: constraint does not exist
column7: The named constraint does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a constraint that does exist or do not perform this operation.

column6: unique/primary keys in table referenced by foreign keys
column7: An attempt was made to drop a table with unique or primary keys referenced by foreign keys in another table.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Before performing the above operations the table, drop the foreign key constraints in other tables. You can see what constraints are referencing a table by issuing the following command: 

SELECT * FROM USER_CONSTRAINTS WHERE TABLE_NAME = "tabnam";

column6: Invalid hash option - missing keyword IS
column7: Missing IS keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify HASH IS option.

column6: duplicate HASHKEYS specification
column7: The HASHKEYS option is specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only specify the HASHKEYS option once.

column6: invalid HASHKEYS option value
column7: The specified HASHKEYS option must be an integer value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an appropriate value.

column6: duplicate HASH IS specification
column7: The HASH IS option is specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: only specify the HASH IS option once.

column6: Number of hash keys per block (%s) exceeds maximum of %s
column7: The SIZE argument is too small.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the SIZE argument.

column6: The number of cluster key column must be 1
column7: When specifying the HASH IS option, the number of key columns must be 1.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either do not specify the HASH IS option or reduce the number of key columns.

column6: The HASH IS column specification must be NUMBER(*,0)
column7: The column specification must specify an integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the column definition as type NUMBER(precision, 0).

column6: The HASH IS option must specify a valid column
column7: The HASH IS column name is not specified in the cluster definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid column name.

column6: HASHKEYS must be specified for a HASH CLUSTER
column7: The HASHKEYS option must be specified when creating a HASH CLUSTER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the HASHKEYS option.

column6: Hashkey value must be a positive integer
column7: The value of the hash key was not a positive number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a positive integer.

column6: Inappropriate index operation on a hash cluster
column7: An attempt to create a cluster index was issued on a hash cluster.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to create such an index.

column6: Inappropriate use of the INDEX option
column7: This option is only valid for non hash clusters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify this option.

column6: Duplicate INDEX option specified
column7: The INDEX option is specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only specify the INDEX option once.

column6: Duplicate HASH IS option specified
column7: The HASH IS option is specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only specify the HASH IS option once.

column6: Cluster definition can not be both HASH and INDEX
column7: The cluster can either be a hash or indexed cluster, not both.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove either the HASH IS or INDEX options.

column6: Inappropriate use of the HASH IS option
column7: This option is only valid for clusters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify this option.

column6: The SIZE option is not allow to be altered for HASH CLUSTERS
column7: The SIZE cannot be changed once the hash cluster has been created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify this option.

column6: Column referenced in expression not found in cluster definition
column7: A column in the hash is expression was not present in cluster definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the cluster and correct the error in hash expression.

column6: Constant or system variable wrongly specified in expression
column7: A constant or system variable was specified in the hash expression.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the cluster and correct the error in hash expression.

column6: Hash expression does not return an Oracle Number.
column7: Result of evaluating hash expression is not an Oracle Number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the cluster and correct the error in hash expression.

column6: TO_DATE, USERENV, or SYSDATE incorrectly used in hash expression.
column7: TO_DATE, USERENV and SYSDATE are not allowed in hash expressions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the cluster and correct the error in hash expression.

column6: SYSDATE, UID, USER, ROWNUM, or LEVEL incorrectly used in hash expression.
column7: SYSDATE, UID, USER, ROWNUM, or LEVEL are not allowed in hash expressions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the cluster and remove the offending keywords.

column6: PL/SQL functions not allowed in hash expressions
column7: A PL/SQL function was used in the hash expression.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the cluster and remove the PL/SQL function.

column6: Error while evaluating the cluster's hash expression.
column7: An error occurred while evaluating the clusters hash expression.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the query and retry.

column6: Fixed hash area extents used (%s) exceeds maximum allowed (%s)
column7: The number of extents required for creating the fixed hash area exceeds the maximum number allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of extents required by increasing the extent allocation sizes within the STORAGE clause.

column6: maximum cluster chain block count of %s has been exceeded
column7: The number of blocks in a cluster chain exceeds the maximum number allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase SIZE parameter in CREATE CLUSTER statement or reconsider suitability of cluster key.

column6: can not create index due to parallel direct load on table
column7: A parallel direct load is occurring to the specified table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry statement after load is complete.

column6: can not perform parallel direct load on object %s
column7: A parallel direct load is not possible because an index is being created on the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry load after index creation is complete.

column6: merge into base segment would overflow MAXEXTENTS limit
column7: Merge of temporary segment into base segment failed because MAXEXTENTS was larger than the total in the temporary and base segments.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a larger value for MAXEXTENTS on the base segment or make the extents in the temporary segments larger.

column6: error while translating file name for parallel load
column7: An invalid file name was specified to load data into.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid database file.

column6: too many event classes specified for events
column7: Illegal trace enable string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a legal trace enable control string.

column6: too many ID ranges specified for events
column7: Illegal trace enable string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a legal trace enable control string.

column6: Specified an event class but gave no events
column7: Illegal trace enable string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a legal trace enable control string.

column6: Illegal ID value specified for events
column7: Illegal trace enable string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a legal trace enable control string.

column6: Low ID value is greater than high ID value
column7: Bad file name given in TRACE_DEST initialization parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid name in the TRACE_DEST initialization parameter.

column6: Error in file %s. Check trace_dest INIT.ORA parm
column7: Bad file name given in TRACE_DEST initialization parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid name in the TRACE_DEST initialization parameter.

column6: Error in writing file name %s. Check trace_dest INIT.ORA parm
column7: Bad file name given in TRACE_DEST initialization parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid name in the TRACE_DEST initialization parameter.

column6: trace_block_size (%s) must be divisable by %s
column7: The initialization parameter TRACE_BLOCK_SIZE was incorrectly set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the initialization parameter and restart.

column6: missing required file size in RESIZE clause
column7: No value was specified for the RESIZE clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct syntax.

column6: missing required keyword ON or OFF in AUTOEXTEND clause
column7: The keyword ON or OFF was not specified for the AUTOEXTEND clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct syntax.

column6: missing required file block increment size in NEXT clause
column7: No value was specified for the NEXT clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct syntax.

column6: invalid file increment size in NEXT clause
column7: A non-integer value was used for the NEXT clause of the DATAFILE list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct syntax.

column6: invalid or missing maximum file size in MAXSIZE clause
column7: UNLIMITED was not specified, or an invalid integer value was specified, for the MAXSIZE clause in the DATAFILE file list. The MAXSIZE value cannot be smaller than the SIZE value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct syntax.

column6: cannot resize file %s, tablespace %s is read only
column7: An attempt was made to resize a datafile in a tablespace that is read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the tablespace to read/write and retry the resize operation.

column6: osnoraenv: error translating ORACLE_SID
column7: Two-task driver could not find the value of ORACLE_SID in the environment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the ORACLE_SID environment variable has been properly set and exported.

column6: osnoraenv: error translating oracle image name
column7: ORACLE_HOME environment variable not set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the ORACLE_HOME environment variable has been properly set and exported.

column6: osnoraenv: error translating orapop image name
column7: ORACLE_HOME environment variable not set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the ORACLE_HOME environment variable has been properly set and exported.

column6: osnpopipe: pipe creation failed
column7: The pipe driver failed to create pipes for communications with the ORAPOP process.
column8: From Oracle doc: You have probably exceeded the maximum number of open file descriptors per user or the system file table is full. Note the operating system error code and contact your system administrator.

column6: osndopop: fork failed
column7: The two-task driver could not fork ORAPOP.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that there are enough system resources to support another process. The user or system process limit may have been exceeded, or the amount of free memory or swap space may be temporarily insufficient.

column6: osnpol: polling of communication channel failed
column7: The pipe driver failed while polling the communications channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnshs: host name too long
column7: The length of your host-string specified by the TWO_TASK environment variable exceeds the Oracle system-imposed limit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnacx: cannot allocate context area
column7: The invoked UNIX two-task driver could not allocate heap space for the context area.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnrntab: connect to host failed, unknown ORACLE_SID
column7: The invoked UNIX two-task driver failed to find an entry in ORATAB for the SID you supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: First, check whether you have read access to ORATAB, and see if the desired sid is there. Add an entry to ORATAB for the desired SID, if necessary.

column6: osnpop: pipe creation failed
column7: The pipe driver failed to create pipes for two-task communications with the Oracle shadow process.
column8: From Oracle doc: You have probably exceeded the maximum number of open file descriptors per user or the system file table is full. Note the operating system error code and contact your system administrator.

column6: osnpop: fork failed
column7: The pipe driver could not fork the Oracle shadow process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that there are enough system resources to support another process. The user or system process limit may have been exceeded, or the amount of free memory or swap space may be temporarily insufficient.

column6: osnpvalid: write to validation channel failed
column7: The pipe driver failed to write to the ORAPOP process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpop: malloc failed
column7: The pipe driver failed to allocate enough heap space for its context area buffers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnprd: message receive failure
column7: The pipe driver failed to read a message from the communications channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpwr: message send failure
column7: The pipe driver failed to write a message to the communications channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpgetbrkmsg: message from host had incorrect message type
column7: The pipe driver received a message having an unrecognizable message type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpgetdatmsg: message from host had incorrect message type
column7: The Pipe driver received a message having an unrecognizable message type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpfs: incorrect number of bytes written
column7: The Pipe driver sent a message that was apparently successful, but the number of bytes transmitted did not match the number of bytes furnished to the driver.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnprs: reset protocol error
column7: The two-task driver could not reset the connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnfop: fork failed
column7: The fast driver could not fork the Oracle shadow process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that there are enough system resources to support another process. The user or system process limit may have been exceeded, or the amount of free memory or swap space may be temporarily insufficient.

column6: osnfop: shmat failed
column7: When the fast driver was invoked, processes failed to attach to the shared memory buffer. You probably supplied an illegal shared memory attach address, or the system ran out of data space to accommodate the buffer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try invoking the Fast driver later, or use the default attach address.

column6: osnseminit: cannot create semaphore set
column7: The Fast driver failed to get a semaphore set.
column8: From Oracle doc: The system-imposed limit on semaphores or semaphore identifiers may have been exceeded. Read the returned operating system error code and check with your system administrator.

column6: osnpui: cannot send break message to orapop
column7: The Pipe driver could not send a break message to ORAPOP.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpui: cannot send break signal
column7: The Pipe driver could not send a break message to the Oracle shadow process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpbr: cannot send break message to orapop
column7: The Pipe driver could not send a break message to ORAPOP.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpbr: cannot send break signal
column7: The Pipe driver could not send a break message to the Oracle shadow process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Kill system call failed. Check the error code (errno) and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnpop: access error on oracle executable
column7: The Pipe driver could not access the Oracle executable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the permissions on the Oracle executable and each component of the ORACLE_HOME/bin path.

column6: osnpop: access error on orapop executable
column7: The Pipe driver could not access the ORAPOP executable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the permissions on the ORAPOP executable and each component of the ORACLE_HOME/bin path.

column6: osnfop: access error on oracle executable
column7: The Fast driver could not access the Oracle executable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the permissions on the Oracle executable and each component of the ORACLE_HOME/bin path.

column6: osncon: driver not in osntab

column8: From Oracle doc: Check with your database administrator which drivers are supported.

column6: osnrnf: cannot find user logon directory
column7: The driver you have specified could not find your logon directory while searching for your local .SQLNET file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set and export the HOME environment variable to identify your home directory. Check with your system administrator to make sure that your UID and home directory are correct in the /etc/passwd file.

column6: osnrnf: malloc of buffer failed
column7: The specified driver could not find enough heap space to MALLOC a buffer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnrnf: cannot find a matching database alias
column7: Database alias specified was not identified in either $HOME/.sqlnet or /etc/sqlnet.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the alias in a file called .sqlnet in the home directory for personal use, or have system administrator create the alias in /etc/sqlnet for system-wide use.

column6: osnsnf: database %s too long

column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnftt: cannot reset shared memory permission

column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnfpm: cannot create shared memory segment

column8: From Oracle doc: Check whether the system-imposed limit on shared memory identifiers has already been reached for your system.

column6: osnfpm: illegal default shared memory address

column6: osncon: host alias is too long

column6: osnfsmmap: cannot map shared memory file

column6: osnfsmmap: illegal shared memory address

column6: osnfsmmap: cannot close shared memory file
column7: The Fast driver cannot close the shared memory file.

column6: osnfsmmap: cannot change shared memory inheritence

column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: osnfsmcre: cannot create chared memory file ?/dbs/ftt_pid.dbf
