column6: Allocation of internal array failed
column7: The package was unable to allocate memory for an array because the system ran out of memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either reclaim memory by killing other processes or restart the machine with more memory.

column6: Not enough request descriptors available
column7: All of the package's request descriptors are in use performing other requests.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either wait until enough requests are done, or shut the package down and re-initialize it with more request descriptors.

column6: Client close of file failed.
column7: The client was unable to close a file after forking the servers.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is a system problem; contact your System Administrator.

column6: File number to be canceled is negative.
column7: The file number contained with the SFIOV structure is less than zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: This may be a programming error. If it is not, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: file number to be cancelled is greater than the maximum.
column7: The file number contained with the SFIOV structure is greater than the maximum.
column8: From Oracle doc: This may be a programming error. If it is not, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to cancel at least one request
column7: No requests were found that could be cancelled.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error can occur if all the requests dealing with that file number have already been filled.

column6: Invalid package mode
column7: The mode of the package can only be parallel or duplex.
column8: From Oracle doc: See SFA.H for the correct values.

column6: Invalid maximum number of servers
column7: The number of servers given was less than or equal to zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a number greater than zero.

column6: Invalid maximum of request descriptors
column7: The number of request descriptors was less than or equal to zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a number greater than zero.

column6: Less than one request descriptor was allocated per server
column7: The package requires that the number of request descriptors be greater than or equal to the number of servers used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a higher number

column6: Maximum number of files is invalid
column7: The maximum number of files to be used by the package was less than or equal to zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Setting of handler for SIGTERM failed
column7: The package was unable to set up handling by the server for the termination signal. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Total number of blocks is invalid
column7: The total number of blocks to be allocated for use by the package was not greater than zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Illegal request time out value
column7: The number was not a positive number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Invalid maximum server idle time
column7: The time given was not a positive number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Invalid maximum client wait time
column7: The time given was not a positive number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Invalid request list latch time out value
column7: The time given was not a positive number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Invalid request done signal
column7: The signal number was not a positive number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Value for request done signal exceeds maximum
column7: The value sent to the package for use as the "request done" signal exceeds the maximum allowed by the operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: Stat failed on log directory
column7: The package was unable to get information about the directory in which the log files are to reside.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the permissions on the directory or use a different directory name.

column6: Name given for the log directory is invalid
column7: The name given for the directory in which the logs are to be kept does not correspond to a directory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different name.

column6: Stat failed on core dump directory
column7: The package was unable to get information about the directory into which the servers are to dump core in the event of an exception.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the permissions on the directory or use a different directory name.

column6: Name given for the core dump directory is invalid
column7: The name given for the directory in which the server processes are to dump core in the event of an exception does not correspond to a directory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different name.

column6: Invalid value given for the timing wanted flag
column7: The value given was not TRUE or FALSE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify TRUE or FALSE for the timing wanted flag.

column6: Both read and write functions were not specified
column7: To ensure that the functions act symmetrically, pointers to both the read and write functions must be given.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify both functions or specify neither. The package will supply its own functions.

column6: Both post and wait functions were not specified
column7: To ensure that the functions act symmetrically, pointers to both the posting and waiting functions must be given.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify both functions or specify neither. The package will supply its own functions.

column6: Invalid shared memory ID specified
column7: The ID of the segment specified for use as the shared buffer region was invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different ID, or let the package specify its own.

column6: Invalid shared memory buffer size
column7: The size given for the shared memory segment to be used as the shared buffer region was less than or equal to zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Size needed for shared region is greater than segment size
column7: The size of the shared segment that was specified for the shared buffer region is less than the number of bytes required. The first field of the "additional information" field is the size needed. The second is the size of the segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a larger size segment or let the package allocate its own.

column6: Unable to allocate memory for segment list
column7: The package cannot allocate memory for an internal segment list because the system has run out of memory. The "additional information" field is the amount of memory that the package attempted to allocate.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close some processes or contact your system administrator.

column6: Unable to find kernel process pointer in async process array
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Support.

column6: Maximum number of files reached
column7: The maximum number of files that can be used for asynchronous I/O has been reached.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down the servers and re-initialize the package with a higher number.

column6: File name is too long
column7: The length of the name of a file that is being opened for asynchronous I/O is longer than the maximum. The "additional information" field is the maximum length.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a shorter name.

column6: Unable to open file for use with asynchronous I/O
column7: The package could not open file for some reason.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the file name.

column6: Unable to fstat() a file being used for asynchronous I/O.
column7: The fstat(2) call on a file being used for asynchronous I/O failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the file name.

column6: Close of asynchronous I/O failed.
column7: The client was unable to close a file being used for asynchronous I/O.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Client unable to get key for shared memory
column7: The client was unable to get a key so that it obtain shared memory for use with shared memory. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Request list is empty
column7: The client was signalled by a server that it was done with a request but the "done" list was empty. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Done request is not in correct state
column7: A request is not in the right state. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: No requests available
column7: No free request descriptors are available.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until some requests are filled and then retry the request, or shut down the servers and initialize the package with a higher number of requests.

column6: Invalid number of requests
column7: The number of operations sent to either SFARD() or SFAWRITE() is less than zero. This is a user programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling program.

column6: Unable to arm signal handler
column7: The arming of a signal handler for the "done" signal failed. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Requests timed out
column7: Some of the requests for asynchronous input or output were not serviced in the required amount of time.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the load on the system is high, it is possible that the timeout limit is too low. Reset it with SFAINIT(). If the server processes are dying due to unexpected signals, this is an internal error, and Oracle Customer Support should be contacted.

column6: Operations timed out
column7: Some asynchronous operations timed out in kernel mode. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: No idle servers available in parallel mode
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Retrieval of current time failed
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Allocation of memory failed for log file name
column7: The client was unable to allocated a buffer for the name of the log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: Unable to set handler for SIGTPA
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to set handler for SIGALRM
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Allocation of memory for I/O vectors failed.
column7: The client was unable to allocate memory for the array of I/O vectors that the servers are to use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: Allocation of memory of open files array failed.
column7: The client was unable to allocate memory for an array of flags that the servers are to use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: Jump buffer not valid
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to make temporary file name for memory mapped file
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to attach shared memory segment
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Bad attach address
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to make temporary file name in order to get key
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to get shared memory
column7: SHMGET(2) failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX number. If you are unsure about what it means, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to attach shared memory
column7: SHMAT(2) failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX number. If you are unsure about what it means, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to kill a process
column7: A server did not die after being sent a kill signal.
column8: From Oracle doc: The process may be a runaway; contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Read failed
column7: A server could not read a requested amount of data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the call to SFARD(). An incorrect file descriptor may have been sent to SFARD(). The number in the "additional information" field is the starting block number of the data segment being read in.

column6: Less than the number of blocks requested was read in
column7: A server could not read in the request amount of data. The first number in the "additional information" field is the block number being read in. The second is the actual number of bytes that was read in. This is a programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling program.

column6: Write failed
column7: A server was unable to perform a write. The number in the "additional information" field is the starting block number of the data segment being written out. The first number in the "additional information" field is the block number being written out. The second is the actual number of bytes that was written out. The disk may have filled up.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number.

column6: Unable to write the requested number of blocks
column7: A server could not write the requested amount of data out to disk. The disk may have run out of space.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number.

column6: Unable to read the requested number of blocks.
column7: A server could not read the number of blocks that was requested. The end of the file may have been read.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the file on disk.

column6: Invalid block offset
column7: A server was unable to seek to the designated block.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number.

column6: Buffer is not aligned.
column7: The buffer on which an I/O is being done is not on the correct boundary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling program.

column6: Request free list is empty
column7: The list from which the package allocates request descriptors is empty because all of the descriptors is in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until some become free, or initialize the package with a higher number of request descriptors.

column6: Request on free list was not free
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Illegal block size
column7: A negative number was given for the I/O block size to be used by the asynchronous I/O package. This is a programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use either a positive number or zero to get the default value.

column6: Invalid file number
column7: The file number upon which an operation is to done is either less than zero or greater than the maximum number of files than can be open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Since the calling program should not touch this number, this is a programming error.

column6: Segment free list is empty
column7: No segments are available to allocated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Free some segments or shut down the package and re-initialize it with a higher number of segments.

column6: No segment of the proper size is available
column7: No segment of the proper size is ready for use by the caller.
column8: From Oracle doc: Free some segments and try again.

column6: Segment could not be split - no free segments available
column7: A segment that is larger than that desired could not be split because no free segment was available.
column8: From Oracle doc: Free some segments and try again.

column6: Segment deallocation failed - empty segment list
column7: The caller attempted to deallocate a segment but the "in use" list was empty. This is a programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling program.

column6: Segment deallocation failed - segment not on list
column7: The caller attempted to deallocate a segment that was not on the "in use" list. This is a programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling program.

column6: Server was unable to close file
column7: A server was unable to close a file being used for asynchronous I/O.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the UNIX error number for more information.

column6: Server unable to open file
column7: The server was unable to open a file for use with asynchronous I/O.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for more information.

column6: Server unable to send signal to client
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to create temporary key file
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to unlink temporary file
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to arm signal handler for the alarm signal
column7: The arming of a signal handler for the alarm signal failed. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Sync of blocks to disk failed.
column7: The server was unable to flush its writes out to disk.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number.

column6: Open of log file by client failed
column7: The client process was unable to open its log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for more information.

column6: Server died on start up
column7: A server exited during its initialization process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the servers' logs for more information.

column6: Client unable to fork a server
column7: The client could not spawn a server. A possible reason is that the operating system has reached its limit on the number of processes that it can spawn.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either reduce the number of servers that are to be used, or reconfigure the operating system so that it can handle more processes.

column6: Invalid value for kernel flag
column7: An illegal value was given for the kernel flag in the information structure. Only TRUE and FALSE are permitted. This is a programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling routine.

column6: Invalid value for the leave open flag
column7: A value was given for the flag that determines whether a file is to be left open after the client checks it to see if the servers can use it. Only TRUE and FALSE are supported. This is a programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling routine.

column6: Invalid value for the timing wanted flag
column7: A value was given for the flag that indicates that operations are to be timed out. Only TRUE and FALSE are supported. This is a programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling routine.

column6: Unkillable server
column7: A server failed to respond to the termination signal. The first number is the number of the server. The second is its UNIX process number. This is an internal problem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Server did not terminate when posted
column7: A server did not respond to a posted request to shut down. The first number is the number of the server. The second is its UNIX process number. This is an internal problem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Asynchronous I/O package is not running
column7: An operation using the asynchronous I/O package was attempted without first initializing the package using SFAINIT().
column8: From Oracle doc: Call SFAINIT() before using the package.

column6: Read failed because of an error
column7: A server could not read the requested amount of data from disk.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number.

column6: File is closed
column7: A file upon which an asynchronous I/O operation is to be performed has already been closed by the package. This is a programming error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the calling program.

column6: Request list is empty when it should not be
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Invalid critical-section time out value
column7: The time given was not a positive number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Invalid server list latch time out value
column7: The time given was not a positive number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a positive number.

column6: Invalid number of request buffers
column7: The value given for DB_SLAVE_BUFFERS in your INIT.ORA file is less than 0.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a number that is greater than or equal to 0.

column6: Number of requests is less than the number of slaves
column7: The value given for DB_SLAVE_BUFFERS in your INIT.ORA file is less than the number specified for the number of slaves, DB_SLAVES.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a number that is greater than that given for DB_SLAVES Alternatively, specify 0. The kernel will supply the appropriate number.

column6: smpini: Unable to get shared memory for PGA
column7: Stated in error code (errno).
column8: From Oracle doc: Resolve the problem.

column6: smpini: Unable to attach to shared memory for PGA
column7: Stated in error code (errno).
column8: From Oracle doc: Resolve the problem.

column6: smpini: Unable to initialize memory protection
column7: The ADSPCINIT program has not been executed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute the ADSCPINIT program as shown in your Installation and Users' Guide. If the problem persists, try restarting your computer.

column6: sou2o: Variable smpdidini overwritten
column7: The variable SMPDIDINI was overwritten, probably by client code.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify client code (for example, in Pro*C check for illegal memory access). If the problem occurs outside Single Task operation, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: sou2o: Could not gain access to protected memory
column7: This is an internal error, note error code in errno.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restarting your application or your computer may cure the problem. If not, report the error to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: smpini: Could not register PGA for protection
column7: This is an internal error, note error code in errno.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restarting your application or your computer may cure the problem. If not, report the error to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: sou2o: Could not revoke access to protected memory
column7: This is an internal error, note error code in errno.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restarting your application or your computer may cure the problem. If not, report the error to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: sou2o: Could not register SGA for protection
column7: This is an internal error, note error code in errno.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restarting your application or your computer may cure the problem. If not, report the error to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: smscre: Cannot create SGA with Extended Shared Memory feature
column7: The environment variable EXTSHM was set before starting Oracle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Unset the environment variable EXTSHM and restart Oracle.

column6: unimplemented feature
column7: At attempt was made to use a feature that is not currently implemented.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to use this feature at this time.

column6: operator not implemented
column7: At attempt was made to use an operator that is not currently implemented.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to use this operator at this time.

column6: obsolete feature
column7: An attempt was made to use a feature that is no longer supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: parameter COMPATIBLE >= %s needed for %s
column7: An attempt was made to use a feature for a later Oracle version than the setting of the initialization parameter, COMPATIBLE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set COMPATIBLE to the value in the message (or higher), and retry the command, but be aware that this will limit your downgrade options.

column6: communication area cannot be allocated; insufficient memory
column7: An attempt to allocate stack space for communication purposes failed. This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: internal protocol error
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: fatal two-task communication protocol error
column7: The communication path between Oracle and the user task has stopped. This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: oranet buffer underflow
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: oranet: ORACLE does not support this interface version
column7: The version of Oracle connected to via Net8 does not support this version of the Net8 protocol.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the older version of Oracle and try again.

column6: oranet buffer overflow
column7: Data being transferred between the user program and Oracle overflowed the buffer space available. This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: oranet: ORACLE does not support this SQL version
column7: The version of Oracle connected to via Net8 does not support the version of the Net8 protocol.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the older version of Oracle and try again.

column6: break received on communication channel
column7: A break was processed on the communications channel, but was not properly handled by Net8 software. This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: a server linked as single-task cannot use SQL*Net
column7: A statement containing a Net8t connect string was issued to the single-task server. For example, a database link was used in a SQL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use Net8t connect strings in a single-task environment.

column6: end-of-file on communication channel
column7: An unexpected end-of-file was processed on the communication channel. The problem could not be handled by the Net8, two task, software. This message could occur if the shadow two-task process associated with a Net8 connect has terminated abnormally, or if there is a physical failure of the interprocess communication vehicle, that is, the network or server machine went down. In addition, this message could occur when ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION or ALTER SYSTEM DISCONNECT SESSION were issued with the IMMEDIATE qualifier because, in those cases, the client's connection to the database is terminated without waiting for the client to issue a request.
column8: From Oracle doc: If this message occurs during a connection attempt, check the setup files for the appropriate Net8 driver and confirm Net8 software is correctly installed on the server. If the message occurs after a connection is well established, and the error is not due to a physical failure, check if a trace file was generated on the server at failure time. Existence of a trace file may suggest an Oracle internal error that requires the assistance of customer support.

column6: not connected to ORACLE
column7: A call to Oracle was attempted when no connection was established. Usually this happens because a user-written program has not logged on. It may happen if communication trouble causes a disconnection. In addition, this message could occur when ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION or ALTER SYSTEM DISCONNECT SESSION were issued with the IMMEDIATE qualifier because, in those cases, the client's connection to the database is terminated without waiting for the client to issue a request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again. If the message recurs and the program is user written, check the program.

column6: unsupported network datatype or representation
column7: A user bind or define, or an Oracle function, is not supported by this heterogeneous Net8 connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the older version of Oracle and try again.

column6: invalid buffer length passed to a conversion routine
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: two-task save area overflow
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: two-task coroutine has invalid state
column7: This is an internal error message not usually issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: two-task conversion routine: integer overflow
column7: An integer value in an internal Oracle structure overflowed when being sent or received over a heterogeneous connection. This can happen when an invalid buffer length or too great a row count is specified. It usually indicates a bug in the user application.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check parameters to Oracle calls. If the problem recurs, reduce all integer parameters, column values not included, to less than 32767.

column6: no interface driver connected - function not performed
column7: This message occurs usually because the Net8 driver is not loaded into memory or there is a mismatch of the version of the driver. A user program linked with an obsolete library may also cause this message. Only programs provided by Oracle Corporation should use this interface.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the message occurred during use of a program provided by Oracle Corporation, contact customer support. If a user program caused the message, relink the program with current versions of the Oracle libraries.

column6: attempt to close ORACLE-side window on user side
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: operation would block
column7: The attempted operation cannot complete now.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation later.

column6: two-task internal error
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: client-server protocol violation
column7: The application received a bad escape sequence from the server and may indicate a problem with the client application user code.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: network driver does not support non-blocking operations
column7: A non-blocking operation was attempted and the network driver does not support non-blocking operations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use default blocking operations or use a driver supporting non-blocking operations.

column6: no new operations allowed until the active operation ends
column7: An attempt was made to execute a new operation before the active non-blocking operation completed or a new operation was attempted before all the pieces of a column were inserted or fetched.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute the new operation after the non-blocking operation completes. If piecewise binds/defines were done, execute the new operation after all the pieces have been inserted or fetched.

column6: connection is in blocking mode
column7: The OCI test for non-blocking mode on a connection indicates that the connection is in blocking mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: If non-blocking mode is required use appropriate OCI calls to change the mode.

column6: the next piece to be inserted is required
column7: The application performed a piecewise bind on a column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide the next piece of this bind variable.

column6: the buffer for the next piece to be fetched is required
column7: The application performed a piecewise define on the column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide the next buffer for the next piece to be retrieved.

column6: an invalid buffer was provided for the next piece
column7: The application either provided the length of the buffer for the next piece to be zero or provided a null pointer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify if the buffer pointer for the next piece is null or if the length is zero.

column6: connection lost contact
column7: 1) Server unexpectedly terminated or was forced to terminate. 2) Server timed out the connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: 1) Check if the server session was terminated. 2) Check if the timeout parameters are set properly in sqlnet.ora.

column6: WARNING: inbound connection timed out
column7: Connection has timed out because of cluster interconnect failure or User Authentication has failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle customer support

column6: the segment type specification is invalid
column7: The segment type is not TABLE, INDEX, or CLUSTER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a correct segment type.

column6: the group number specification is invalid
column7: The freelist group number is either negative or larger than the number of freelist groups in the segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a correct group number.

column6: the scan limit specification is invalid
column7: The scan limit does not have a positive integer value greater than the number of freelist groups in the segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a correct scan limit.

column6: concurrent update activity makes space analysis impossible
column7: High volume of user updates interfere with the space analysis.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command or lock the underlying objects.

column6: the segment type specification should indicate partitioning
column7: A partition name was specified for the space analysis, but the object type does not indicate partitioning.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify PARTITION in the segment type if the object is partitioned, Otherwise, omit the partition name.

column6: partition name is required when partitioned type is specified
column7: A partition name was not specified for the space analysis, but the object type indicates partitioning.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a partition name if the object is partitioned. Otherwise, specify a non-partitioned type.

column6: maximum file size of (%s) blocks in AUTOEXTEND clause is out of range
column7: The maximum file size for an autoextendable file has exceeded the maximum number of blocks allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the size and retry.

column6: subpartitioned type must be specified for composite object
column7: A partition type is specified for the space analysis, but the object type indicates composite partitioning.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a subpartition name and a subpartition type.

column6: partitioned type must be specified for a non-composite object
column7: A subpartition type is specified for the space analysis, but the object type indicates non-composite partitioning.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a partition name and a partition type.

column6: DBMS_ADMIN_PACKAGE invalid file/block specification
column7: The value of file number or block number is outside of limits or inconsistent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the file number/block number value.

column6: DBMS_ADMIN_PACKAGE invalid option specification
column7: The value of one of the option parameters is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the option value.

column6: The segment does not exist or is not in a valid state
column7: The segment specified in the DBMS_SPACE_ADMIN operation does not or is not an state appropriate for this operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the segment specification, or put the segment in the appropriate state.

column6: Temporary Segment cannot be created in locally-managed tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to create a temporary segment for SORT/HASH/LOBS in a locally-managed permanent tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter temporary tablespace of user to a temporary tablespace or a dictionary-managed permanent tablespace.

column6: Invalid Lob Segment Name for DBMS_SPACE package
column7: The LOB segment specified in the DBMS_SPACE operation does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the segment specification.

column6: File Size specified is smaller than minimum required
column7: File size specified for add/resize datafile/temporary file does not allow for the minimum required of one allocation unit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the specification for the file size.

column6: File Size specified for resize is too small
column7: File size specified for resize datafile/temporary file causes bitmap control structures to overlap.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the specification for the file size.

column6: Tablespace/Segment Verification cannot proceed
column7: Corruption was detected during verification which cannot be dealt with
column8: From Oracle doc: Do manual verification.

column6: invalid option for alter of TEMPORARY TABLESPACE
column7: Invalid option for alter of temporary tablespace was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of the valid options: ADD TEMPFILE.

column6: invalid option for CREATE/ALTER TABLESPACE
column7: Invalid option for create/alter tablespace of type locally-managed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of the valid options.

column6: Applies to locally-managed tablespaces only. Tablespace '%s' is not locally-managed
column7: Operation which is only applicable to locally-managed tablespaces is specified for a dictionary-managed tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue operation for a different tablespace, or do not issue it at all, since it does not apply for the given tablespace.

column6: DBMS_ADMIN_PACKAGE required parameter is NULL or missing
column7: Some of the procedures was called with missing or NULL parameters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the missing parameter.

column6: segment only contains %s blocks of unused space above high water mark
column7: Attempt to preserve too many blocks.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the KEEP amount.

column6: the INITIAL extent may not be deallocated
column7: Attempt to deallocate space from the segment which was truncated prior to the 7.3 release.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the KEEP amount, or truncate the segment, and reissue the command.

column6: unable to allocate an extent of %s blocks from tablespace %s
column7: An attempt was made to specify a HASH_MULTIBLOCK_IO_COUNT value that is greater than the tablespace's NEXT value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of NEXT for the tablespace using ALTER TABLESPACE DEFAULT STORAGE or decrease the value of HASH_MULTIBLOCK_IO_COUNT.

column6: unable to extend table %s.%s subpartition %s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for table subpartition segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: unable to extend index %s.%s subpartition %s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: Failed to allocate an extent for index subpartition segment in tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in table %s.%s subpartition %s
column7: A table subpartition tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the value of MAXEXTENTS is less than the system maximum, raise it. Otherwise, you must re-create with larger initial, next or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: max # extents (%s) reached in index %s.%s subpartition %s
column7: An index subpartition tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the value of MAXEXTENTS is less than the system maximum, raise it. Otherwise, you must re-create with larger initial, next or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: Initial Extent of specified size cannot be allocated
column7: Too large a size for an initial extent due to freelist group specification.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce number of freelist groups specified for the segment.

column6: unable to extend LOB segment %s.%s subpartition %s by %s in tablespace %s
column7: An attempt was made to allocate an extent for LOB subpartition segment in tablespace, but the extent could not be allocated because there is not enough space in the tablespace indicated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the ALTER TABLESPACE ADD DATAFILE statement to add one or more files to the tablespace indicated.

column6: maxextents (%s) reached in LOB segment %s.%s subpartition %s
column7: A LOB subpartition segment tried to extend past MAXEXTENTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the value of MAXEXTENTS is less than the system maximum, raise it. Otherwise, re-create the subpartition with larger INITIAL, NEXT, or PCTINCREASE parameters.

column6: both ALLOCATE EXTENT and DEALLOCATE UNUSED options are specified
column7: The DEALLOCATE option and the ALLOCATE option are specified in the same command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose one of the options or issue two separate commands.

column6: duplicate DEALLOCATE option specification
column7: The DEALLOCATE UNUSED option to ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX is specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the option at most once.

column6: duplicate ALLOCATE EXTENT option specification
column7: The ALLOCATE EXTENT option to ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX is specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the option at most once.

column6: invalid SIZE specified
column7: The specified value must be an integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose an appropriate integer value.

column6: duplicate ALLOCATE EXTENT option specification
column7: An option (DATAFILE, SIZE or INSTANCE) was specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify each option at most once.

column6: invalid INSTANCE specified
column7: The specified value is not recognized as a valid instance name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid name.

column6: invalid DATAFILE filename specified
column7: A character string literal is expected, but not found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify file names using character string literals.

column6: invalid ALLOCATE EXTENT option
column7: An option other than DATAFILE, SIZE or INSTANCE was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove invalid option and retry the command.

column6: missing ALLOCATE EXTENT option
column7: No ALLOCATE EXTENT options were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specified one or more of the following options: DATAFILE, SIZE or INSTANCE.

column6: specified datafile %s does not exist
column7: The datafile does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the option with the correct datafile.

column6: datafile %s is not a member of tablespace %s
column7: The specified datafile does not belong to the tablespace that the object resides in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the option with the correct datafile.

column6: ALLOCATE EXTENT not valid for HASH CLUSTERS
column7: The cluster cannot use the allocate extent option because it is a hash cluster.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use this command on a hash cluster.

column6: invalid FREELIST GROUP specified
column7: The specified FREELIST GROUP number is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a number between 1 and the number of freelist groups for this object.

column6: both FREELIST GROUP and INSTANCE parameters may not be specified
column7: Both FREELIST GROUP and INSTANCE were specified in clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the two parameters.

column6: Invalid truncate command - missing CLUSTER or TABLE keyword
column7: Invalid object specification given.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify TRUNCATE CLUSTER or TRUNCATE TABLE.

column6: Invalid truncate option - missing STORAGE keyword
column7: Expected STORAGE keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify DROP STORAGE or REUSE STORAGE.

column6: Table to be truncated is part of a cluster
column7: The table being truncated is a member of a cluster.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either use TRUNCATE CLUSTER or DROP TABLE.

column6: Cluster to be truncated is a HASH CLUSTER
column7: Only INDEX CLUSTERS can be truncated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop and re-create the HASH CLUSTER instead of using truncate.

column6: cannot resize datafile - file %s not found
column7: The specified datafile is not available for resizing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the datafile name is valid, and if so, ensure the file is accessible.

column6: file contains used data beyond requested RESIZE value
column7: Some portion of the file in the region to be trimmed is currently in use by a database object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop or move segments containing extents in this region prior to resizing the file, or choose a resize value such that only free space is in the trimmed.

column6: cannot shrink datafile - file %s is under hot backup
column7: Attempt to shrink a datafile while it is under hot backup. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry shrinking the file after the hot backup completes.

column6: cannot create dictionary table %s
column7: A dictionary table is created upon the first execution of the command ALTER DATABASE DATAFILE AUTOEXTEND ON for a database. This operation did not succeed. The most probable cause for this is insufficient space in the system tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: See action for next error message in error stack.

column6: the sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE cannot exceed 100
column7: The sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for a cluster or table exceeds 100.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the table/cluster specifying values whose sum is less than or equal to 100.

column6: sequence parameter %s must be an integer
column7: string (a sequence parameter) specified was not an integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the sequence, giving the specified parameter an integer value.

column6: INCREMENT must be a non-zero integer
column7: A sequence increment was specified to be zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the increment to be a non-zero value.

column6: sequence parameter %s exceeds maximum size allowed (%s digits)
column7: string (a sequencer parameter) had too many digits.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the parameter with the allowed number of digits.

column6: MINVALUE must be less than MAXVALUE
column7: MINVALUE was specified to be greater than or equal to MAXVALUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a MINVALUE that is less than MAXVALUE.

column6: INCREMENT must be less than MAXVALUE minus MINVALUE
column7: The INCREMENT specified is greater than or equal to MAXVALUE-MINVALUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an INCREMENT that is less than MAXVALUE-MINVALUE.

column6: START WITH cannot be less than MINVALUE
column7: The given starting value is less than MINVALUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the starting value is greater than or equal to MINVALUE.

column6: MINVALUE cannot be made to exceed the current value
column7: The given MINVALUE would be greater than the current value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Always make sure that MINVALUE is less than or equal to the current value.

column6: START WITH cannot be more than MAXVALUE
column7: The starting value would be larger than MAXVALUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the starting value is less than MAXVALUE.

column6: MAXVALUE cannot be made to be less than the current value
column7: The current value exceeds the given MAXVALUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the new MAXVALUE is larger than the current value.

column6: the number of values to CACHE must be greater than 1
column7: The value in the CACHE clause was one.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify NOCACHE, or a value larger than one.

column6: sequence %s must range between %s and %s
column7: The value specified for one of the sequence parameters exceeds limits.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a parameter within these limits.

column6: object is not a sequence
column7: The object specified cannot have sequence DDLs performed on it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-enter the statement being careful with the spelling of the name.

column6: number to CACHE must be less than one cycle
column7: The number to CACHE specified in a CREATE SEQUENCE statement exceeds the number of values in a cycle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enlarge the cycle or cache fewer values, and try again.

column6: descending sequences that CYCLE must specify MINVALUE
column7: A value was not specified in the CREATE SEQUENCE statement. Sequences that cycle must specify a value at which to begin again.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the sequence, specifying the value at which it is to begin.

column6: ascending sequences that CYCLE must specify MAXVALUE
column7: A value was not specified in the CREATE SEQUENCE statement. Sequences that cycle must specify a value at which to begin again.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recreate the sequence, specifying the value at which it is to begin.

column6: sequence %s no longer exists
column7: Sequence was dropped while processing its next value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the sequence.

column6: invalid value %s (length = %s) for parameter max_dump_file_size
column7: Neither did the string supplied for MAX_DUMP_FILE_SIZE parameter match the "UNLIMITED" string value nor did it represent a base 10 integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reassign a proper value to this parameter.

column6: invalid value %s for parameter _scn_scheme
column7: The value specified for initialization parameter _SCN_SCHEME is not recognized as one of the defined schemes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reassign a proper value.

column6: SCN scheme incompatible with other instances
column7: Either different instances are running incompatible Oracle releases or different values have been assigned to the _SCN_SCHEME initialization parameter on different instances.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the _SCN_SCHEME initialization parameter is set to the same value on all instances.

column6: deadlock detected while trying to lock object stringstringstringstring%s
column7: While trying to lock a library object, a deadlock is detected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation later.

column6: timeout occurred while waiting to lock object stringstringstringstring%s
column7: While waiting to lock a library object, a timeout is occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation later.

column6: nowait requested, but had to wait to lock dictionary object
column7: Had to wait to lock a library object during a nowait request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation later.

column6: cannot generate diana for object stringstringstringstring%s
column7: Cannot generate diana for an object because of lock conflict.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report this error to your support representative.

column6: error ORA-%s occurred when querying stringstring%s
column7: The table or view being queried might be missing. The error number indicates the error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the error.

column6: out of process memory when trying to allocate %s bytes (%s,%s)
column7: Operating system process private memory has been exhausted.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the database administrator or operating system administrator to increase process memory quota. There may be a bug in the application that causes excessive allocations of process memory space.

column6: unable to allocate %s bytes of shared memory ("%s","%s","%s","%s")
column7: More shared memory is needed than was allocated in the shared pool.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the shared pool is out of memory, either use the DBMS_SHARED_POOL package to pin large packages, reduce your use of shared memory, or increase the amount of available shared memory by increasing the value of the initialization parameters SHARED_POOL_RESERVED_SIZE and SHARED_POOL_SIZE. If the large pool is out of memory, increase the initialization parameter LARGE_POOL_SIZE.

column6: package specification must be created first before creating package body
column7: Attempt to create a package body before creating its package specification.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the package specification first before creating the package body.

column6: procedure, function, package, or package body does not exist
column7: Attempt to access a procedure, function, package, or package body that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the name is correct.

column6: object %s does not exist
column7:
An object name was specified that was not recognized by the system. Following are possible causes: 

An invalid name for a table, view, sequence, procedure, function, package, or package body was entered. Since the system could not recognize the invalid name, it responded with the message that the named object does not exist. 

An attempt was made to rename an index or a cluster, or some other object that cannot be renamed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the named object and rerun the code. (Valid names of tables, views, functions, etc. can be listed by querying the data dictionary.)

column6: procedure, function, package, or type is not allowed here
column7: A procedure, function, or package was specified in an inappropriate place in a statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the name is correct or remove it.

column6: errors during recompilation/revalidation of %s.%s
column7: This message indicates the object to which the following errors apply. The errors occurred during implicit recompilation/revalidation of the object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the following errors for more information, and make the necessary corrections to the object.

column6: results of compilation are too large to support
column7: Attempt to compile and store a large stored procedure that results in compilation data that is too large for the system to support or store.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the size of the store procedure by splitting it into smaller stored procedures.

column6: object specified is incompatible with the flag specified
column7: The object type implied by the flag does not match the type of object specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct object, or use the appropriate flag.

column6: invalid or missing procedure, function, or package name
column7: The required procedure, function, or package name is invalid or missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid name.

column6: user %s cannot use database link %s.%s
column7: During forwarding of a remote object access, an attempt was made to use a non-existent database link or one owned by a user other than the logon user or PUBLIC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change your database link structure so that all indirect remote accesses are done from the same userid that originates the request.

column6: error occurred when looking up remote object stringstringstringstring%s
column7: An error has occurred when trying to look up a remote object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the error. Make sure the remote database system has run KGLR.SQL to create necessary views used for querying/looking up objects stored in the database.

column6: error occurred when validating remote object stringstringstringstring%s
column7: An error has occurred when trying to validate a remote object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the error. Make sure the remote database system has run KGLR.SQL to create necessary views used for querying/looking up objects stored in the database.

column6: database link %s does not exist
column7: During compilation of a PL/SQL block, an attempt was made to use a non-existent database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either use a different database link or create the database link.

column6: Aborted: "%s" formed a non-REF mutually-dependent cycle with "%s".
column7:
This compilation was aborted because the library unit that was compiled would have formed a non-REF mutually-dependent cycle with some other library units. This happens when an attempt is made to compile types that have attributes of other types that may participate in a cycle with this type. Example: 

create type t1; create type t2 (a t1); create type t1 (a t2);
column8: From Oracle doc: Break the cycle (possibly by adding a REF or by using another type).

column6: insufficient privileges to execute %s
column7: Attempt to execute a stored procedure without sufficient privileges.
column8: From Oracle doc: Get necessary privileges.

column6: existing state of %s has been invalidated
column7: Attempt to resume the execution of a stored procedure using the existing state which has become invalid or inconsistent with the stored procedure because the procedure has been altered or dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again; this error should have caused the existing state of all packages to be re-initialized.

column6: %s of %s has been changed
column7: Attempt to execute a stored procedure to serve an RPC stub which specifies a timestamp or signature that is different from the current timestamp/signature of the procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recompile the caller in order to pick up the new timestamp.

column6: %s has errors
column7: Attempt to execute a stored procedure or use a view that has errors. For stored procedures, the problem could be syntax errors or references to other, non-existent procedures. For views, the problem could be a reference in the view's defining query to a non-existent table. Can also be a table which has references to non-existent or inaccessible types.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the errors and/or create referenced objects as necessary.

column6: not executed, invalidated %s
column7: Attempt to execute a stored procedure that has been invalidated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recompile the stored procedure.

column6: not executed, altered or dropped %s
column7: Attempt to execute a stored procedure that has been altered or dropped thus making it not callable from the calling procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Recompile its dependents.

column6: non-executable object, %s
column7: Attempt to execute a non-procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that a correct name is given.

column6: not executed, %s does not exist
column7: Attempt to execute a non-existent stored procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that a correct name is given.

column6: existing state of packagesstringstring%s has been discarded
column7: An error occurred when attempting to execute a stored procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the accompanying messages and fix the error mentioned. Try the procedure again after proper reinitialization of any application's state.

column6: invalid trigger name
column7: An invalid trigger name was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that trigger name is not a reserved keyword.

column6: missing BEFORE, AFTER or INSTEAD OF keyword
column7: The trigger statement is missing the BEFORE/AFTER/INSTEAD OF clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either BEFORE, AFTER or INSTEAD OF.

column6: invalid trigger type
column7: An invalid trigger type was given.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE.

column6: column list not valid for this trigger type
column7: A column list was specified for a non-update trigger type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the column list.

column6: invalid REFERENCING name
column7: An invalid name was given in the referencing clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify the referencing name is not a reserved word.

column6: invalid trigger action
column7: An statement was given for the trigger action.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-specify the trigger action.

column6: invalid NEW or OLD specification
column7: An invalid NEW or OLD specification was given for a column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-specify the column using the correct NEW or OLD specification.

column6: WHEN clause cannot be used with table level triggers
column7: The when clause can only be specified for row level triggers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the when clause or specify for each row.

column6: OLD and NEW values cannot be identical
column7: The referencing clause specifies identical values for NEW and OLD.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-specify either the OLD or NEW referencing value.

column6: invalid trigger specification
column7: The create TRIGGER statement is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the statement for correct syntax.

column6: trigger '%s' does not exist
column7: The TRIGGER name is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the trigger name.

column6: trigger '%s' already exists
column7: The TRIGGER name or type already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different trigger name or drop the trigger which is of the same name.

column6: NEW or OLD references not allowed in table level triggers
column7: The trigger is accessing "new" or "old" values in a table trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove any new or old references.

column6: invalid trigger variable '%s'
column7: The variable referenced in the trigger body is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: See Oracle8i SQL Reference for valid trigger variable types.

column6: cannot change NEW values for this trigger type
column7: New trigger variables can only be changed in before row insert or update triggers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the trigger type or remove the variable reference.

column6: cannot change the value of an OLD reference variable
column7: Old values can only be read and not changed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to change an old variable.

column6: trigger description too long, move comments into triggering code
column7: The trigger description is limited to 2000 characters (for dictionary storage reasons). The description does not include the text of the "when" clause or the text of the PL/SQL code executed for the trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the trigger description contains a large comment, move that comment into the PL/SQL code for the trigger.

column6: cannot change the value of ROWID reference variable
column7: ROWIDs can only be read and not changed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to change an ROWID value.

column6: error during execution of trigger '%s.%s'
column7: A runtime error occurred during execution of a trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the triggers which were involved in the operation.

column6: cannot create triggers on objects owned by SYS
column7: An attempt was made to create a trigger on an object owned by SYS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not create triggers on objects owned by SYS.

column6: '%s' specifies same table, event and trigger time as '%s'
column7: Trigger is of duplicate event and trigger time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Combine the triggering information into one trigger which is fired at the given time.

column6: table %s.%s is mutating, trigger/function may not see it
column7: A trigger (or a user defined PL/SQL function that is referenced in this statement) attempted to look at (or modify) a table that was in the middle of being modified by the statement which fired it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the trigger (or function) so it does not read that table.

column6: cannot %s in a trigger
column7: A trigger attempted to commit or roll back.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the trigger so it does not commit or roll back.

column6: references to columns of type LONG are not allowed in triggers
column7: A trigger attempted to reference a long column in the triggering table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not reference the long column.

column6: table %s.%s is constraining, trigger may not modify it
column7: A trigger attempted to modify a table that was constraining for some referential constraint of a parent SQL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the trigger so that it does not modify that table.

column6: trigger '%s' already exists on another table, cannot replace it
column7: Cannot replace a trigger which already exists on a different table than the one being replaced.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the trigger with the same name and re-create it.

column6: trigger '%s' has a WHEN clause which is too large, limit 2K
column7: A trigger's WHEN clause is limited to 2K for dictionary storage reasons. The trigger being created exceeded that size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a smaller WHEN clause. Note, the trigger body could be used to perform the same limiting action as the WHEN clause.

column6: DDL conflict while trying to drop or alter a trigger
column7: An attempt was made to concurrently perform two DDL operations on a trigger or trigger table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Investigate the new state of the trigger and retry the DDL operation, if still appropriate.

column6: trigger '%s.%s' is invalid and failed re-validation
column7: A trigger was attempted to be retrieved for execution and was found to be invalid. This also means that compilation/authorization failed for the trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: Options are to resolve the compilation/authorization errors, disable the trigger, or drop the trigger.

column6: trigger '%s' is valid but not stored in compiled form
column7: A trigger was attempted to be retrieved for execution and was found to be valid, but not stored. This may mean the an upgrade was done improperly from a non-stored trigger release.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter compile the trigger to create the trigger in stored form. Also, you may want to review that a proper upgrade was done.

column6: open sequence number failed or initial state is valid
column7: Either Shared Sequence Number operating system component was not installed properly, or an MC hardware failure may have occurred or a previous instance was not shut down properly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that there are no background or foreground Oracle processes from a previous instance on this node using the operating system command ps -ef|grep instance_name. Verify that there are no shared memory segments belonging to the user which owns the Oracle installation by issuing the ipcs -b operating system command. If there are shared memory segments or processes still on the system, use SVRMGRL to shut down the instance with the abort option. If the instance is not up, verify that the cluster software and/or the hardware is installed and working. Log in as superuser and issue the CNXSHOW command. Are all of the nodes in the cluster listed? Are they members of the cluster? Is the communications between nodes okay? If the answer to any of these questions is false, contact Digital's customer support organization.

column6: unable to set initial sequence number value
column7: A call to the SSN failed to set the sequence number to its initial value, possibly caused by an MC hardware problem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the MC hardware is functioning properly. If it is not, contact Digital's customer support organization. If it is, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: increment or adjust of sequence number failed
column7: A call to the SSN failed to increment the sequence number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the MC hardware is functioning properly. If it is not, contact Digital's customer support organization. If it is, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: initial service identifier is non-zero
column7: A valid service identifier existed before the sequence number service was opened.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the instance is completely shut down.

column6: unable to obtain the current sequence number
column7: A call to the SSN failed to return its current value. Either there are many errors occurring on the MC hardware, or the sequence number has become invalid and cannot be validated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the MC hardware is functioning properly. If it is, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: unable to get/convert SCN recovery lock
column7: A process has timed out trying to get or convert the SCN recovery lock. Another process probably has the lock in EX or SHR mode, but is not releasing it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETASY: port open failure
column7: Autologin unable to open port.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: port set-up failure
column7: Autologin unable to change port attributes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: port read failure
column7: Autologin unable to read from port.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: port write failure
column7: Autologin unable to write to port.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: dialogue file open failure
column7: Autologin unable to open dialogue file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check connect string for accuracy/typos.

column6: NETASY: dialogue file read failure
column7: Autologin unable to read dialogue file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: dialogue execute failure
column7: Expected response never received.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: bad dialogue format
