column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the dialogue file.

column6: NETASY: dialogue filename too long
column7: Full file specification for dialogue file exceeds 64 bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Amend connect string accordingly.

column6: NETASY: dialogue file too long
column7: Dialogue file exceeds 768 bytes in length.
column8: From Oracle doc: Simplify dialogue (e.g. remove comments, redundant white space), or split into two and link with the MORE command.

column6: NETASY: dialogue too long
column7:
One of the following: 

Dialogue contains more than 24 exchange blocks 

Dialogue send string exceeds 84 bytes in length
column8: From Oracle doc: Simplify dialogue or split into two and link with the MORE command.

column6: NETASY: message receive failure
column7: Asynchronous driver gets I/O error while doing network read operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETASY: message send failure
column7: Asynchronous driver gets I/O error while doing network write operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETASY: invalid login (connect) %s
column7: Syntax error in login string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit with correct string.

column6: NETASY: initialisation failure
column7: Asynchronous driver unable to complete initialization.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: connect failed
column7: Asynchronous driver unable to establish connection with partner.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: channel open failure
column7: No free channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETASY: port open failure
column7: Asynchronous driver unable to open port.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: VTM error
column7: Virtual Terminal Manager unable to read/write to port.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: Configuration error
column7: Asynchronous driver generated for server-only, but client service requested.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETASY: port close failure
column7: Asynchronous driver unable to close port.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: channel close failure
column7: Asynchronous driver unable to close channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check log file for operating system-specific error code.

column6: NETASY: unable to intialise for logging
column7: Asynchronous driver unable to initialize for logging I/O.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETASY: port assignment failure
column7: Asynchronous driver unable to assign port to channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed, unrecognized node name
column7: Node name specified in host string is unknown (probably misspelled).
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry with correct node name.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed, unrecognized object name
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry with correct object name or create the required object on host node.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed, access control data rejected
column7: Host string contains invalid username/password.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry with correct username/password.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed, partner rejected connection
column7: Connection with partner was made but was rejected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your network administrator.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed, partner exited unexpectedly
column7: Connection with host node was made but partner aborted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure object (see 06031, above) is working (for VMS run the command file and make sure that the Oracle server process starts up); sometimes happens when the network/node is under stress; in this case, a retry often works.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed, insufficient resources
column7: Insufficient system resources are available to complete the connection; for example, all DECnet channels are in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your network administrator.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed, node unreachable
column7: Host node is down.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your network administrator.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed
column7: Connect failed for unexpected reason (see OSD error).
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETDNT: invalid login (connect) %s
column7: Syntax error in login string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resubmit with correct string.

column6: NETDNT: disconnect failed
column7: Driver gets error while doing network close operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETDNT: message receive failure
column7: Driver gets I/O error while doing network read operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETDNT: message send failure
column7: Driver gets I/O error while doing network write operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETDNT: connect failed, byte count quota exceeded
column7: Connect failed because of insufficient byte count quota.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase byte count quota.

column6: NETTCP: cannot allocate context area
column7: Insufficient dynamic memory available for connection context area.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: remote host is unknown
column7: Host name specified in the login (connect) string is unknown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check spelling; make sure name is in the TCP/IP HOST file.

column6: NETTCP: socket creation failure
column7: Process open file quota probably exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: ORACLE network server not found
column7: No entry in SERVICES file for Oracle server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add (ORASRV) entry to the TCP/IP SERVICES file.

column6: NETTCP: connect to host failed
column7: Connection attempt to remote host has failed. Probably means that the SQL*Net TCP/IP server on the remote host is not up, or the host itself is not up (check the latter by targeting it with Telnet).
column8: From Oracle doc: Start the SQL*Net TCP/IP server process on the remote host.

column6: NETTCP: message receive failure
column7: I/O error occurred while attempting network read operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: message send failure
column7: I/O error occurred while attempting network write operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: disconnect failure
column7: Error occurred while closing a socket.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: invalid buffer size
column7: The buffer size specified in the login string exceeds the allowed maximum (of 4096).
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-submit with valid buffer size.

column6: NETTCP: Too many connections
column7: The maximum no. of concurrently open connections has been reached.
column8: From Oracle doc: Exit an application with an open connection which is no longer required.

column6: NETTCP: SID lookup failure
column7: From the remote host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server: the database SID, specified in the login (connect) string, was not recognized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add the appropriate SID entry to the CONFIG.ORA file on the remote host (and restart the SQL*Net TCP/IP server).

column6: NETTCP: unable to create ORACLE logicals
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to create the necessary logical names required by the Oracle server process. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: NETTCP: unable to create ORASRV process
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to create the Oracle server process. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: NETTCP: unable to create ORASRV: quota exceeded
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to create the Oracle server process because of quota depletion.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase quota allocations to the SQL*Net TCP/IP server process.

column6: NETTCP: unable to complete handshake with ORASRV
column7: The Oracle server process was started but failed to complete its initialization.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: spurious client request
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to recognize this connection request. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: network driver not loaded
column7: The TCP/IP network driver is not loaded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the TCP/IP driver is loaded correctly.

column6: NETTCP: access failure
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to test the accessibility of the SID mapping file (specified in CONFIG.ORA) associated with this connection request. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: setup failure
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to set up the appropriate environment to service this connection request. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: cannot set KEEPALIVE
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to set the socket KEEPLIVE option. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: timeout waiting for ORASRV
column7: The Oracle server process was started but failed to respond after N seconds.
column8: From Oracle doc: For heavily loaded systems this is not an uncommon occurrence. Increase the value of N (the default is 30) by placing the following entry in the CONFIG.ORA file: SQLNET ORASRV_WAIT = no_of_secs which will come into effect the next time the SQL*Net TCP/IP server is started.

column6: NETTCP: ORASRV exited unexpectedly
column7:
The Oracle server process was started but exited unexpectedly. Possible causes: 

Insufficient quotas to run ORASRV 

Oracle is not installed See the ORASRV output file for more details; the file will be in the ORA_SQLNET directory and will have a name of the form: ORA_SRVTnn_sid.OUT
column8: From Oracle doc: If appropriate action is not obvious from the ORASRV output file, then contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: ORASRV unable to open network connection
column7: The Oracle server process was started but was unable to open the socket passed to it by TCPSRV.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: unable to change username
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server could not establish a PROXY LOGIN connection because the client username is unknown (to the host operating system).
column8: From Oracle doc: Create new user account on host.

column6: NETTCP: unable to create mailbox
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to create a mailbox (needed for IPC communication with the Oracle server process). See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: unable to transfer socket ownership to ORASRV
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to transfer the network communication handle to the Oracle server process. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: host access denied
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server rejected this connection request because the client node does not have access privilege - as determined by the contents of the Valid Node Table (VNT), a component of the host's CONFIG.ORA.
column8: From Oracle doc: To grant access, add appropriate entry to the host's VNT.

column6: NETTCP: user access denied
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server rejected this connection request because the client user(name) does not have access privilege, as determined by the contents of the Username Mapping Table (UMT), a component of the host's CONFIG.ORA.
column8: From Oracle doc: To grant access, add appropriate entry to the host's UMT.

column6: NETTCP: access denied, wrong password
column7: The host SQL*Net TCP/IP server rejected this connection request because the client password did not match the host password.
column8: From Oracle doc: To grant access, get passwords in sync.

column6: NETTCP: file not found
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server could not find the SID mapping file (specified in CONFIG.ORA) associated with this connection request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check CONFIG.ORA for spelling; make correct entry.

column6: NETTCP: file access privilege violation
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server did not have READ/ EXECUTE permission for the SID mapping file (specified in CONFIG.ORA) associated with this connection request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change protection on SID mapping file.

column6: NETTCP: connection rejected; server is stopping
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server rejected this connection request because it is in the process of stopping.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart SQL*Net TCP/IP server.

column6: NETTCP: error during connection handshake
column7: Network I/O failure occurred while communicating with the host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: error during connection handshake
column7: Network I/O failure occurred while communicating with the host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: error during connection handshake
column7: Network I/O failure occurred while communicating with the host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: no such user
column7: A proxy login connect attempt failed because the client username has no counterpart on the host.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again with a user that has a counterpart on the host.

column6: NETTCP: no privilege for user
column7: A proxy login connect attempt failed because the SQL*Net TCP/IP server had insufficient privileges to access the proxy account.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change account protection; change server privileges.

column6: NETTCP: error getting user information
column7: A proxy login connect attempt failed because the SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to access the proxy account. See the SQL*Net TCP/IP server log file for more details.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETTCP: maximum connections exceeded
column7: The connect failed because the maximum concurrent connections supported by the host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server has already been reached.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for a short period and retry.

column6: NETTCP: SID (database) is unavailable
column7: The database administrator on the host has varied the SID offline.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for it to be varied back online.

column6: NETTCP: unable to start ORASRV: images not installed
column7: The host's SQL*Net TCP/IP server was unable to start the Oracle server process because the Oracle protected images were not installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Install the images.
