column6: NETNTT: cannot allocate send and receive buffers
column7: Two-task driver could not allocate data buffers.
column8: From Oracle doc: There is insufficient memory to run your program. Kill off other processes to free up memory.

column6: NETNTT: cannot translate address file name
column7: ORACLE_HOME environment variable not set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the ORACLE_HOME environment variable has been properly set and exported.

column6: NETNTT: cannot open address file
column7: The NTT two-task driver could not open a file containing address information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the ORACLE_HOME environment variable has been properly set and exported. Make sure the instance you are attempting to connect to is actually up and running.

column6: NETNTT: cannot read arguments from address file
column7: The NTT two-task driver could not read addressing information from its addressing file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the ORACLE_HOME environment variable has been properly set and exported. Make sure the instance you are attempting to connect to is actually up and running.

column6: NETNTT: cannot share connection to cube
column7: The NTT two-task driver could not share a connection to the cube.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the ORACLE_HOME environment variable has been properly set and exported. Make sure the instance you are attempting to connect to is actually up and running.

column6: NETNTT: cannot read pid of remote process
column7: An error occurred while reading the NTT communications link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: remote fork failed
column7: The Oracle listener process on the cube could not fork off a shadow process.
column8: From Oracle doc: The instance you are trying to connect to probably does not have enough memory to run another shadow process. Ask someone else to log off, or connect to a different instance.

column6: NETNTT: cannot send command line to shadow process
column7: An error occurred while writing the NTT communications link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: cannot allocate context area
column7: Two-task driver could not allocate data buffers.
column8: From Oracle doc: There is insufficient memory to run your program. Kill off other processes to free up memory.

column6: NETNTT: cannot read from remote process
column7: An error occurred while reading the NTT communications link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: cannot write to remote process
column7: An error occurred while writing the NTT communications link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: nrange() failed
column7: The call to NRANGE() failed while attempting to establish a connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: nfconn() failed
column7: The call to NFCONN() failed while attempting to establish a connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: out of memory in pi_connect
column7: Two-task driver could not allocate data buffers.
column8: From Oracle doc: There is insufficient memory to run your program. Kill off other processes to free up memory.

column6: NETNTT: data protocol error
column7: The NTT two-task driver received an unexpected message type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: break protocol error
column7: The NTT two-task driver received an unexpected message type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: bad write length
column7: The NTT two-task driver failed on an internal consistency check.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: bad state
column7: The NTT two-task driver failed on an internal consistency check.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETNTT: cannot read /etc/oratab
column7: The NTT two-task driver could not read configuration information from /etc/oratab.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure /etc/oratab exists and is readable. This error may occur if the file is incorrectly formatted. It also may occur if the driver has run out of memory.

column6: IPA: Disconnect failure
column7: A fatal error occurred during the disconnect from the server. This was probably caused by inaccessible message queues.
column8: From Oracle doc: If there is no message queue, restart the SQL*Net IPA servers using IPACTL. Otherwise contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: IPA: Cannot allocate driver context
column7: The memory pool is exhausted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the circumstances and try to allocate less memory in your program or adjust the parameters in your INIT.ORA file and retry.

column6: IPA: Cannot connect to remote host
column7:
One of the following:

There is no ADI server defined to reflect a connection to the specified host. 

The remote host is not known by the local system. 

The Oracle kernel on the remote host is not generated with the IPA driver
column8: From Oracle doc: Check sequentially for the above causes and eliminate the actual cause found.

column6: IPA: Message send error
column7: The SQL*Net IPA driver could not write the message into the message queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the message queue exists and is accessible. If necessary rerun IPACTL.

column6: IPA: Message receive error
column7: The SQL*Net IPA driver could not read a message from the message queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the message queue exists and is accessible. If necessary rerun IPACTL.

column6: IPA: Illegal message type
column7: The communication between user and Oracle is out of synchronization. This message should not normally be issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: IPA: Message write length error
column7: The IPA driver tried to write a message in the queue that was too big for the queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: IPA: Cannot reset connection
column7: A fatal error occurred during the resetting of the connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: IPA: No more connections available
column7: You have exhausted all your connections.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again when some of the current users have logged off.

column6: IPA: No message queue available
column7: The SQL*Net IPA servers have not been started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Run IPACTL.

column6: IPA: Environment variable(s) not set
column7: Environment variable(s) not set correctly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check and correct.

column6: IPA: Maximum number of servers reached
column7: Maximum number of servers reached.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down and restart with an increased maximum number of servers. Note that database links consume one server per link. Be sure to start enough servers to support database links.

column6: IPA: Incorrect outgoing service name supplied
column7: Incorrect outgoing service name supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check and correct the service name.

column6: IPA: Shared memory failed to initialise
column7: The shared memory has not been set up correctly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: IPA: Event set up failure
column7: Fatal interprocess communication error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: IPA: Invalid connect %s
column7: The connect string is malformed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check and correct.

column6: IPA: Invalid database SID
column7: The SID is unknown at the remote side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either the database does not exist, is not running, or there are no reserved servers for that SID.

column6: IPA: Local maximum number of users exceeded
column7: The maximum number of simultaneous users of SQL*Net IPA has been exceeded on the local side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for free connections to become available. If the problem persists, contact your system administrator.

column6: IPA: Local maximum number of connections exceeded
column7: The maximum number of simultaneous connections that SQL*Net IPA can handle to different hosts has been exceeded on the local side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for free connections to become available. If the problem persists, contact your system administrator.

column6: IPA: Remote maximum number of users exceeded
column7: The maximum number of simultaneous users of SQL*Net IPA has been exceeded on the remote side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for free connections to become available. If the problem persists, contact your system administrator.

column6: IPA: Remote maximum number of connections exceeded
column7: The maximum number of simultaneous connections that SQL*Net IPA can handle from different hosts has been exceeded on the remote side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for free connections to become available. If the problem persists, contact your system administrator.

column6: IPA: Cannot reach the remote side
column7: There has been a timeout on an attempt to connect to a remote server the reason for which is most likely to be the remote SQL*Net IPA software is not running. An alternative reason could be that the remote initiator service name is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check and start the remote SQL*Net software. Check that it is started with the correct service names supplied.

column6: IPA: Fatal shared memory error
column7: An internal error has occurred in the shared memory handling.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: IPA: Cause event error
column7: Fatal interprocess communication error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: NETCMN: No default host %s specified
column7: There was no default host string specified in the configuration and the user did not specify any explicit connect string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either reconfigure the system specifying a default connect string or use an explicit connect string.

column6: NETCMN: invalid driver designator
column7: The login (connect) string contains an invalid driver designator.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the string and re-submit.

column6: NETCMN: error receiving break message
column7: Error occurred while attempting to read a break message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to allocate memory.
column7: System unable to allocate needed virtual memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Configure more memory, reduce load, or try again.

column6: NETCMN: invalid login (connect) %s
column7: Syntax error in login string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct string and re-submit.

column6: NETCMN: reset protocol error
column7: Unable to reset out of break state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETCMN: error sending break message
column7: Error occurred while attempting to send a break message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETCMN: unable to set up break handling environment
column7: Error occurred while attempting to set up asynchronous handlers for in-coming, out-of-band break messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETCMN: incorrect message format
column7: Message from partner contains bad header.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Connection not open.
column7: Unable to establish connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use diagnostic procedures to ascertain exact problem.

column6: NETCMN: error on test
column7: Error occurred while testing I/O status of the network connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: NETCMN: server can not start oracle
column7: The remote server was unable to start an Oracle process on behalf of the client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure permissions on the remote Oracle program are correctly set. Contact your system administrator.

column6: NETCMN: SID lookup failure
column7: From the remote host's server: the database SID, specified in the login (connect) string, was not recognized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add the appropriate SID entry to the CONFIG.ORA or ORATAB file on the remote host (restarting the remote server may be needed).

column6: NETCMN: Error detected in the read-in data
column7: Error found during recomputation of checksum or CRC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Possible hardware failures of communication nodes. Contact system administrator immediately.

column6: NETCMN: Error in sending data
column7: Unable to transmit data to remote host.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try reconnect to remote host, and contact your system administrator.

column6: NETCMN: Error in receiving data
column7: Unable to receive data from remote host.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try reconnect to remote host, and contact your system administrator.

column6: ssaio: Seals do not match
column7: A function was called with an invalid argument.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: ssaio: Invalid Block number
column7: The file block number is out of range of the file. The additional information returns the block number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the block number is correct. Run DBFSIZE and check if the block number is in that range. Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: ssaio: Buffer Not Aligned
column7: The I/O buffer was not aligned on a 2K boundary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: ssaio: LSEEK error, unable to seek to requested block.
column7: The additional information returns the block number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look up the additional information returned in your operating system reference manual. Verify that the block number is correct.

column6: ssaio: read error, unable to read requested block from database file.
column7: The read system call returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the block number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: ssaio: write error, unable to write requested block to database file.
column7: The write system call returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the block number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: ssaio: asynchronous I/O failed due to incorrect parameters.
column7: The Asynchronous I/O system call returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the block number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: ssaio: the asynchronous write was unable to write to the database file.
column7: The Asynchronous I/O system call returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the block number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: ssaio: the asynchronous read was unable to read from the database file.
column7: The Asynchronous I/O system call returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the block number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: ssaio: the asynchronous write returned incorrect number of bytes
column7: This write call may have been truncated. The additional information returns the block number and number of bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the block number and the number of bytes written are correct.

column6: ssaio: the asynchronous read returned incorrect number of bytes
column7: This read call may have been truncated. The additional information returns the block number and number of bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the block number and the number of bytes read are correct.

column6: ssvwatev: Incorrect parameter passed to function call
column7: Either the Oracle process ID, or wait time or event ID is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the process ID, time and event ID.

column6: ssvwatev: Failed with unexpected error number.
column7: Some system problems may exist on your system; check the error logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the error number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: ssvpstev: Incorrect parameter passed to function call
column7: An invalid event ID is passed in to this routine.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the event ID.

column6: ssvpstev: Failed with unexpected error number.
column7: Some system problems may exist on your system; check the error logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the error number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: ssvpstevrg: Incorrect parameters passed to function call
column7: An invalid event ID, or the low and high event ID do not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the error number. It also contains the event ID, low boundary and high boundary.

column6: ssvpstevrg: Failed with unexpected error number.
column7: Some system problems may exist on your system; check the error logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the error number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: ssvpstp: Incorrect parameter passed to function call
column7: Invalid Oracle process ID is passed in to this routine.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the process ID.

column6: ssvpstp: Failed with unexpected error number.
column7: Some system problems may exist on your system; check the error logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: The additional information indicates the error number. Look up the additional information returned in your operating system manual.

column6: The list IO or the sysvendor is not installed.
column7: Oracle tries to use the SYSVENDOR interface (INIT.ORA parameter USE_SYSVENDOR=TRUE) but the UNIX kernel does not have the Oracle SYSVENDOR interface linked in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set USE_SYSVENDOR=FALSE in INIT.ORA, if you do not want to use this interface or link the UNIX kernel with this interface so that Oracle can use it.

column6: PL/SQL: storage error
column7: This is a rare internal error message. Memory has been exhausted or corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: PL/SQL: program error
column7: This is an internal error message. An error has been detected in a PL/SQL program.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: PL/SQL: numeric or value error%s
column7: An arithmetic, numeric, string, conversion, or constraint error occurred. For example, this error occurs if an attempt is made to assign the value NULL to a variable declared NOT NULL, or if an attempt is made to assign an integer larger than 99 to a variable declared NUMBER(2).
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the data, how it is manipulated, or how it is declared so that values do not violate constraints.

column6: PL/SQL: Function returned without value
column7: A call to PL/SQL function completed, but no RETURN statement was executed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite PL/SQL function, making sure that it always returns a value of a proper type.

column6: PL/SQL: Return types of Result Set variables or query do not match
column7: Number and/or types of columns in a query does not match declared return type of a result set variable, or declared types of two Result Set variables do not match.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the program statement or declaration. Verify what query the variable actually refers to during execution.

column6: PL/SQL: variable requires more than 32767 bytes of contiguous memory
column7: A PL/SQL variable was declared with a constraint which required more than 32767 bytes of memory. PL/SQL does not currently support allocations of contiguous memory greater than 32767 bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consider reducing the constraint in the variable declaration. If that is not possible, try changing the database or national character set to such, that requires less memory for the same constraint. Note: changing the character set will impact execution of all PL/SQL code.

column6: PL/SQL: could not find program unit being called
column7: An attempt was made to call a stored program that could not be found. The program may have been dropped or incompatibly modified, or have compiled with errors.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that all referenced programs, including their package bodies, exist and are compatible.

column6: PL/SQL: ICD vector missing for this package
column7: This indicates a version clash between some package distributed with an Oracle product and the product executable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: PL/SQL: unhandled user-defined exception
column7: A user-defined exception was raised by PL/SQL code, but not handled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the problem causing the exception or write an exception handler for this condition. Or you may need to contact your application administrator or database administrator.

column6: PL/SQL: cursor already open
column7: An attempt was made to open a cursor that was already open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close cursor first before reopening.

column6: at stringline %s
column7: Backtrace message as the stack is unwound by unhandled exceptions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the problem causing the exception or write an exception handler for this condition. Or you may need to contact your application administrator or database administrator.

column6: PL/SQL: index for PL/SQL table out of range for host language array
column7: An attempt is being made to copy a PL/SQL table to a host language array. But an index in the table is either less than one or greater than the maximum size of the host language array. When copying PL/SQL tables to host language arrays, the table entry at index 1 is placed in the first element of the array, the entry at index 2 is placed in the second element of the array, etc. If an table entry has not been assigned then the corresponding element in the host language array is set to null.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase size of host language array, or decrease size of PL/SQL table. Also make sure that you do not use index values less than 1.

column6: PL/SQL: The remote call cannot be handled by the server
column7: The remote call has parameters that are cursor variables. This cannot be handled by stored procedures on your server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid using cursor variables as parameters for stored procedures on this server or upgrade your server to a version that supports this.

column6: PL/SQL: unhandled exception %s
column7: An exception was raised by PL/SQL code, but not handled. The exception number is outside the legal range of Oracle errors.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the problem causing the exception or write an exception handler for this condition. Or you may need to contact your application administrator or database administrator.

column6: PL/SQL: the Probe packages do not exist or are invalid
column7: A Probe operation, probably an attempt to initialize the Oracle server to debug PL/SQL, could not be completed because the Probe packages were not loaded or have become invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: DBA should load the Probe packages. This can be done by running the PBLOAD.SQL script supplied with the RDBMS.

column6: PL/SQL: Probe error - %s
column7: An error occurred while passing a Probe operation to the server for execution.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the entry for the embedded error message.

column6: PL/SQL: Probe version %s incompatible with version %s
column7: The current version of Probe is incompatible with the version on the Oracle server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the documentation to ensure that this degree of compatibility is supported.

column6: active autonomous transaction detected and rolled back
column7: Before returning from an autonomous PL/SQL block, all autonomous transactions started within the block must be completed (either committed or rolled back). If not, the active autonomous transaction is implicitly rolled back and this error is raised.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that before returning from an autonomous PL/SQL block, any active autonomous transactions are explicitly committed or rolled back.

column6: PL/SQL: Error loading external library
column7: An error was detected by PL/SQL trying to load the external library dynamically.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the stacked error (if any) for more details.

column6: PL/SQL: Error mapping function
column7: An error was detected by PL/SQL trying to map the mentioned function dynamically.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the stacked error (if any) for more details.

column6: %s
column7: ORA-06520 or ORA-06521could stack this error with a system-specific error string.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error string should give the cause for errors ORA-06520 or ORA-06521

column6: Maximum number of arguments exceeded
column7: There is an upper limit on the number of arguments that one can pass to the external function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the port-specific documentation on how to calculate the upper limit.

column6: Unsupported option : %s
column7: The option specified is an unsupported feature for external procedures.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax in the external specification.

column6: Length Mismatch for CHAR or RAW data
column7: The length specified in the length variable has an illegal value. This can happen if you have requested a PL/SQL INOUT, OUT or RETURN raw variable to be passed as a RAW with no corresponding length variable. This error can also happen if there is a mismatch in the length value set in the length variable and the length in the ORLVSTR or ORLRAW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the external procedure code and set the length variable correctly.

column6: Unable to load PL/SQL library
column7: PL/SQL was unable to instantiate the library referenced by this referenced in the EXTERNAL syntax. This is a serious error and should normally not happen.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report this problem to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: External procedure SQLLIB error: %s
column7: An error occurred in SQLLIB during execution of a Pro* external procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: The message text indicates the actual SQLLIB error that occurred.

column6: Error executing PL/SQL profiler
column7: An error occurred during execution of a PL/SQL profiler procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the stacked errors for more details.

column6: Version mismatch - PL/SQL profiler
column7: The PL/SQL profiler package (DBMSPB.SQL, PRVTPBP.PLB) does not match the version of the code in the server implementing the profiler.
column8: From Oracle doc: Run the package PROFLOAD.SQL in $ORACLE_HOME/rdbms/admin to load the correct version of the PL/SQL profiler packages.

column6: Reference to uninitialized composite
column7: An object, LOB, or other composite was referenced as a left hand side without having been initialized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Initialize the composite with an appropriate constructor or whole-object assignment.

column6: Reference to uninitialized collection
column7: An element or member function of a nested table or VARRAY was referenced (where an initialized collection is needed) without the collection having been initialized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Initialize the collection with an appropriate constructor or whole-object assignment.

column6: Subscript outside of limit
column7: A subscript was greater than the limit of a VARRAY or non-positive for a VARRAY or nested table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the program logic and increase the VARRAY limit if necessary.

column6: Subscript beyond count
column7: An in-limit subscript was greater than the count of a VARRAY or too large for a nested table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the program logic and explicitly extend if necessary.

column6: cannot access Serially Reusable package %s in the context of a trigger
column7: The program attempted to access a Serially Reusable package in the context of a trigger. Such an access is currently unsupported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the program logic and remove any references to Serially Reusable packages (procedure, function or variable references) which might happen in the context of a trigger.

column6: statement %s in %s is NULL or 0 length
column7: The program attempted to use a dynamic statement string that was either NULL or 0 length.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the program logic and ensure that the dynamic statement string is properly initialized.

column6: IN bind variable bound to an OUT position
column7: The program attempted to bind an IN bind variable to a statement that was expecting an OUT bind variable at that position.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that an OUT or IN OUT bind mode is specified for the bind argument.

column6: OUT bind variable bound to an IN position
column7: The program attempted to bind an OUT bind variable to a statement that was expecting an IN bind variable at that position.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that an IN or IN OUT bind mode is specified for the bind argument.

column6: statement violates %s RESTRICT_REFERENCES pragma
column7: The program attempted to execute a dynamic statement which does not meet the purity level specified (in the pragma RESTRICT_REFERENCES directive) for the module executing the statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the dynamic statement meets the purity level specified for the module executing the statement.

column6: target of OPEN must be a query
column7: The program attempted to perform an OPEN cursor operation on a dynamic statement that was not a query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the OPEN cursor operation is done on a dynamic query statement.

column6: PL/SQL: compilation error
column7: A PL/SQL compilation error occurred. However, the user generally will not see this error message. Instead, there will be accompanying PLS-nnnnn error messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying PLS-nnnnn error messages.

column6: PL/SQL: compilation error - compilation aborted
column7: A PL/SQL compilation error occurred and the compilation was aborted; but the compilation unit was written out to the backing store. However, unlike ORA-06545, the user generally will not see this error message. Instead, there will be accompanying PLS-nnnnn error messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying PLS-nnnnn error messages.

column6: DDL statement is executed in an illegal context
column7:
DDL statement is executed dynamically in illegal PL/SQL context:

Dynamic OPEN cursor for a DDL in PL/SQL 

Bind variables used in USING clause to EXECUTE IMMEDIATE a DDL 

Define variables used in INTO clause to EXECUTE IMMEDIATE a DDL
column8: From Oracle doc: Use EXECUTE IMMEDIATE without USING and INTO clauses to execute the DDL statement.

column6: RETURNING clause must be used with INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE statements
column7: EXECUTE IMMEDIATE with a RETURNING clause is used to execute dynamic UPDATE, INSERT, or DELETE statements only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use RETURNING clause in EXECUTE IMMEDIATE for INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE statements only. For other statements, use USING clause instead.

column6: PL/SQL: internal error, arguments: [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s]
column7: A PL/SQL internal error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report as a bug; the first argument is the internal error number.

column6: PL/SQL: compilation error - compilation aborted
column7: A PL/SQL compilation error occurred and the compilation was aborted completely without the compilation unit being written out to the backing store. Unlike ORA-06541, the user will always see this error along with the accompanying PLS-nnnnn error messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: See accompanying PLS-nnnnn error messages.

column6: line %s, column %s:%s
column7: A PL/SQL compilation error has occurred. The numbers given for line and column are the location in the PL/SQL block where the error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the following PL/SQL messages for more information about the error.

column6: PL/SQL: Unhandled exception
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: PL/SQL: %s
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: PLS-%s: %s
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: package DBMS_STANDARD must be created before using PL/SQL
column7: The DBMS-specific extensions to PL/SQL's package STANDARD are in package DBMS_STANDARD. This package must be created before using PL/SQL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create package DBMS_STANDARD. The source for this PL/SQL stored package is provided with the distribution.

column6: this name is currently reserved for use by user SYS
column7: An attempt was made to create a package named STANDARD, DBMS_STANDARD or DEBUG_IO. These are currently reserved for use by user SYS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose another name for your package.

column6: the pipe is empty, cannot fulfill the unpack_message request
column7: There are no more items in the pipe.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the sender and receiver agree on the number and types of items placed on the pipe.

column6: null values are not allowed for any parameters to pipe icd's
column7: Internal error from the DBMS_PIPE package.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: buffer in dbms_pipe package is full. No more items allowed
column7: The pipe buffer size has been exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Inspect the program to analyze the rate of input and output to the pipe. You might need to take items out of the pipe by executing RECEIVE_MESSAGE, or empty the entire pipe by executing PURGE on the pipe.

column6: wrong datatype requested, %s, actual datatype is %s
column7:
The sender put different datatype on the pipe than that being requested (package DBMS_PIPE). The numbers are: 

6 - number 

9 - char 

12 - date
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the sender and receiver agree on the number and types of items placed on the pipe.

column6: pos, %s, is negative or larger than the buffer size, %s
column7: Internal error from the DBMS_PIPE package.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: given statement is not supported by package DBMS_SQL
column7: An attempt was made to parse an unsupported statement using procedure PARSE provided by package DBMS_SQL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only statements which begin with SELECT, DELETE, INSERT, UPDATE, LOCK, BEGIN, DECLARE or << (PL/SQL label delimiter) are supported.

column6: type of out argument must match type of column or bind variable
column7: An attempt was made to get the value of a column or a bind variable by calling procedure COLUMN_VALUE or VARIABLE_VALUE of package DBMS_SQL but the type of the given out argument where to place the value is different from the type of the column or bind variable that was previously defined by calling procedure DEFINE_COLUMN (for defining a column) or BIND_VARIABLE (for binding a bind variable) of package DBMS_SQL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass in an out argument of the correct type when calling procedure COLUMN_VALUE or VARIABLE_VALUE. The right type is the type that was provided when defining the column or binding the bind variable.

column6: top level procedure/function specified, cannot have subparts
column7: The name to be resolved was specified with three parts (a.b.c) but the a.b part resolves to a top level procedure or function (which do not have nested procedures). This can also happen with a two-part name, a.b, where a is a synonym for a top level package or procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a procedure/function within a package, or a top level procedure/function.

column6: object %s does not exist
column7: The named object could not be found. Either it does not exist or you do not have permission to access it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the object or get permission to access it.

column6: cannot execute %s from within stored procedure
column7: The named procedure cannot be executed from within a stored procedure, function or package. This function can only be used from PL/SQL anonymous blocks.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the procedure from the calling stored procedure.

column6: invalid number of rows specified
column7: An invalid number of rows was specified in a call to the procedure DEFINE_COLUMN in the package DBMS_SQL. For a given parsed statement in a given cursor, all columns must be defined to have the same number of rows, so all the calls to DEFINE_COLUMN must specify the same number of rows.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a number that matches that for previously defined columns.

column6: invalid number of values specified
column7: An invalid number of values to be bound was specified in a call to the procedure BIND_VARIABLE in the package DBMS_SQL. In order to execute a given parsed statement in a given cursor, the same number of values must have been bound for all bind variables, so when EXECUTE is called, the latest calls to BIND_VARIABLE must have specified the same number of values to be bound for all bind variables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the same number of values have been bound for all of the bind variables.

column6: obsolete ICD procedure called
column7: An obsolete ICD procedure was called by a PL/SQL program. The PL/SQL program was probably written for an earlier release of RDBMS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that all PL/SQL programs have been upgraded to the latest release of the RDBMS. This can be accomplished by following upgrade instructions in the README file, or by running the CATPROC.SQL script supplied with the RDBMS.

column6: Collection bound by bind_array contains no elements
column7: A collection with zero elements was bound to a bind variable in a call to procedure BIND_ARRAY in the package DBMS_SQL. In order to execute a bind of a collection, the collection must contain at least one element. If no elements are present then at execute time there will be no value for this bind and the statement is meaningless.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fill the collection with the elements you want to bind and try the bind call again.

column6: shared pool object does not exist, cannot be pinned
column7: The specified shared pool shared cursor could not be found, therefore it cannot be pinned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that a correct shared cursor name is given. Names are a string of the form 'HHHHHHHH,SDDDDDDDDDD' where the H's are an 8 digit hex number from the 'address' column of V$SQLAREA, and the D's are a 1 to 10 digit decimal number with an optional leading sign (from the HASH_VALUE column) Remove the procedure from the calling stored procedure.

column6: Function %s does not guarantee not to update database
column7:
One of the following:

A SQL statement references a packaged, PL/SQL function that does not contain a pragma that prevents the database from being updated. 

A SQL statement references a standalone, PL/SQL function that contains an instruction to update the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the referenced function is a packaged, PL/SQL function, re-create the PL/SQL function with the required pragma; be certain to include the 'Write No Database State' (WNDS) argument in the argument list of the pragma. If the referenced function is standalone, PL/SQL function, do not use the function.

column6: Function %s has out arguments
column7: A SQL statement references either a packaged or standalone PL/SQL function that contains an OUT parameter in its argument list. PL/SQL functions referenced by SQL statements must not contain the OUT parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create the PL/SQL function without the OUT parameter in the argument list.

column6: Function %s modifies package state, cannot be used here
column7:
One of the following: 

A SQL statement references a packaged, PL/SQL function that does not contain a pragma containing the 'Write no Package State' (WNPS). 

A SQL statement references a standalone, PL/SQL function that modifies a package state. A standalone, PL/SQL function referenced by a SQL statement cannot modify a package state.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the function is a packaged, PL/SQL function: Re-create the function and include a pragma containing the 'Write no Package State' (WNPS). If the function is standalone PL/SQL function, delete the function from the SQL statement.

column6: Function %s references package state, cannot execute remotely
column7:
One of the following: 

A remote, packaged function or a remote-mapped, local, packaged function that does not contain a pragma with the 'Write no Package State' (WNPS) and 'Read no Package State' (RNPS) arguments references a package state. 

A remote, standalone function or a remote-mapped, local, standalone function contains a reference to a package state (reads or writes a package variable). Only local functions that are referenced in a SELECT list, VALUES clause of an INSERT statement, or SET clause of an UPDATE statement can modify a package state.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the function is a packaged function: Re-create the function and include a pragma containing the 'Write no Package State' (WNPS) and 'Read no Package State' (RNPS) arguments. If the function is a standalone function: Do not call the function.

column6: Package or function %s is in an invalid state
column7: A SQL statement references a PL/SQL function that is in an invalid state. Oracle attempted to compile the function, but detected errors.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the SQL statement and the PL/SQL function for syntax errors or incorrectly assigned, or missing, privileges for a referenced object.

column6: not a function or procedure
column7: Could not find a function (if an INTO clause was present) or a procedure (if the statement did not have an INTO clause) to call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the statement to invoke a function or procedure.

column6: output parameter not a bind variable
column7: The argument corresponding to an IN/OUT or OUT parameter for a function or a procedure or a function return value in a CALL statement must be a bind variable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the argument to a bind variable.

column6: output parameter cannot be a duplicate bind
column7: The bind variable corresponding to an IN/OUT or OUT parameter for a function or a procedure or a function return value in a CALL statement cannot be a duplicate bind variable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the bind variable to be unique.

column6: Hash Join ran out of memory while keeping large rows in memory
column7: Hash Join reserves 3 slots (each slot size = DB_BLOCK_SIZE * HASH_MULTIBLOCK_IO_COUNT) for a row. If a row is larger than that, this error will be raised.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase HASH_MULTIBLOCK_IO_COUNT so that each joined row fits in a slot. HASH_AREA_SIZE may also need to be increased.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: SNA software is not loaded
column7: The SNA software is not running.
column8: From Oracle doc: Start the SNA software and try again.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Invalid database ID %s
column7: The database string in the connect was invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a valid database string, as defined in documentation.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Error allocating context area
column7: Context area failure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Error allocating memory
column7: Operating system refused request for memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Unable to allocate session with remote LU
column7: Allocate system call failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the SNA software is running and that sessions are free. If this is the case, then check your SNA configuration data for errors. You may have entered an incorrect parameter.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Unexpected line turnaround
column7: SNA software switched from send to receive unexpectedly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the SNA configuration data, particularly parameters associated with a session.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Unexpected response from SNA
column7: A parameter in an SNA call returned an unexpected value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt to reproduce problem, debug and record the value of the 'what' data parameter at the time of error. Then contact your service representative.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Reset occurred in send state
column7: A reset was issued while in send state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the SNA LOG data, if relevant, for further information.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Reset occurred in receive state
column7: A reset was received from the partner while in receive state. This may be because the partner deallocated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the SNA LOG data, if relevant, for further information.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Failed during deallocation
column7: LU6.2 driver was unable to deallocate gracefully.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the reason for deallocation. Consult the SNA LOG data.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Request to send error
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Send data error
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Receive and wait error
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Receive Immediate error
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Send error
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Attach to LU failed
column7: The SQL*Net LU6.2 driver was unable to attach to the LU specified in the connect string, or was unable to attach to the default LU.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the LU name specified in the connect string, or the default LU name if no LU was specified, is correctly configured and operational.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Attach to PU failed
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Activation of subnetwork failed
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Unable to activate remote partner
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Invalid remote partner
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Allocation error
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: LU6.2 Driver: Unable to attach to SNA
column7: The SQL*Net LU6.2 driver could not attach to the SNA software on your machine. The most likely cause is that the SNA software is not operational.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the status of the SNA software, ensure that it is operational and then try again.

column6: TLI Driver: incorrect message type from host
column7: TLI received a message with an unrecognizable message type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: incorrect number of bytes written
column7: TLI sent a message that was apparently successful, but the number of bytes transmitted did not match the number of bytes supplied to the driver.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot allocate context area
column7: TLI could not allocate heap space for the context area.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: send break message failed
column7: TLI failed to send a break message across the connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: receive break message failed
column7: TLI failed to receive an expected break message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: remote node is unknown
column7: TLI could not find your remote host information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure you specified the host name correctly on the command line. (Also, check your capitalization and spelling.)

column6: TLI Driver: service not found
column7: TLI could not find service information for the specified service name.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you specified the service name on the command line or with the environment variable TLI_SERVER, make sure you specified it correctly. If the service name is not in the SERVICES file for your protocol, ask your system administrator to add it.

column6: TLI Driver: connection failed
column7: TLI failed to establish the connection to a SQL*Net TCP/IP server due to an error encountered by the remote server, which has supplied a string describing the remote error.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the SQL*Net TCP/IP User's Guide or the Net8 Administrator's Guide for the specific cause and action.

column6: TLI Driver: message receive failure
column7: TLI encountered an error receiving a message from the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: message send failure
column7: TLI encountered an error sending a message across the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: send interrupt break message failed
column7: TLI failed to send a break message while handling an interrupt signal from the user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error on bind
column7: TLI failed to assign a network address to the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error on accept
column7: TLI failed to accept a connection request from the client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error on connect
column7: TLI failed to connect the client to the remote server. The network line to the remote host may be down.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use other network login programs to make sure that the remote host is accessible.

column6: TLI Driver: SID lookup failure
column7: The database SID supplied in the database login string was not recognized by the remote host.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask your system administrator to add the appropriate SID entry to ORATAB on the remote host.

column6: TLI Driver: spurious client req
column7: The remote TLI server received an undefined request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: connection setup failure
column7: The remote TLI server rejected the connection request, and the client was unable to retrieve an error code or message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: unable to open clone device
column7: TLI failed to open the Streams clone device associated with the transport provider.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot alloc t_call
column7: TLI cannot allocate space for the client's connection information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot alloc t_discon
column7: TLI cannot allocate space for the client's disconnection information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: failed to receive disconnect
column7: TLI failed to receive an expected disconnection message during connection release.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot connect
column7: TLI failed to connect the client to the remote server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the remote TLI server is running.

column6: TLI Driver: client failed to close error conn
column7: TLI failed to properly close a connection after an error was received.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: server not running
column7: TLI timed out while attempting to connect to the remote TLI server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the remote TLI server is running with the status utility for the transport provider you are using. If it is not, ask your system administrator to start it.

column6: TLI Driver: connection failed
column7: TLI could not establish a connection to the remote TLI server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the remote TLI server is running with the status utility for the transport provider you are using.

column6: TLI Driver: unable to open protocol device
column7: The TLI server failed to open the Streams device associated with the transport provider.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot alloc t_bind
column7: The TLI server cannot allocate space for its requested network address.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot alloc t_bind
column7: The TLI server cannot allocate space for its actual network address.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: listener cannot bind
column7: The TLI server failed to assign the correct network address on which to listen for connections.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: listener already running
column7: The network address on which the TLI server awaits connection requests is in use, possibly because the server is already running.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the TLI server is not already running. If it is not running and this error message recurs, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot alloc t_call
column7: TLI cannot allocate space for the TLI server's connection information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error in listen
column7: The TLI server encountered an error while listening for connection requests.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot allocate t_discon
column7: TLI cannot allocate space for the TLI server's disconnection information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: option not allowed across network
column7: The requested TLI server command must be issued from the same host on which the server is running.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log in to the remote host and try again.

column6: TLI Driver: sync failed
column7: The Oracle process started by the TLI server was unable to synchronize its inherited connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: bound addresses unequal
column7: The OSN check server address failed. The bound server address was not the same as the requested binding address.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI: error in signal setup
column7: A call to SIGACTION() returned with a system error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: name-to-address mapping failed
column7: For SVR4, the NETDIR_GETBYNAME() call failed for some unknown reason.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: unable to get local host address
column7: The name of the remote host to connect to was not specified, and the name of the local host cannot be retrieved from the HOSTS file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot close transport endpoint
column7: The TLI server was unable to close a connection after passing it to an Oracle process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: cannot open oratab
column7: The TLI server could not open the file used to define the locations of remotely accessible databases.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask your system administrator to check that the file exists and has the correct permissions.

column6: TLI Driver: server got bad command
column7: The TLI server received an invalid command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: timeout reading orderly release
column7: TLI was not able to retrieve an expected disconnect message while closing the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error sending orderly release
column7: TLI encountered an error sending a disconnect message closing the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error reading orderly release
column7: TLI encountered an error receiving an expected disconnect message while closing the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error sending disconnect
column7: TLI encountered an error sending a disconnect message closing the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error reading disconnect
column7: TLI was not able to retrieve an expected disconnect message while closing the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error awaiting orderly release
column7: TLI encountered an error awaiting a disconnect message while closing the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: close failed during release
column7: TLI failed to close the communication channel after receiving a disconnect message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: alloc failed during release
column7: TLI cannot allocate space for disconnection information while closing the communication channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error sending version
column7: TLI encountered an error while sending its version information during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error reading version
column7: TLI encountered an error while awaiting the expected version information during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error sending command
column7: TLI encountered an error while sending a command message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error reading command
column7: TLI encountered an error while awaiting the expected command message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error sending break mode
column7: TLI encountered an error while sending break-mode message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error reading break mode
column7: TLI encountered an error while awaiting the expected break-mode message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error sending parms
column7: TLI encountered an error while sending the connection parameters during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error reading parms
column7: TLI encountered an error while awaiting the expected connection parameter message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error sending ccode
column7: TLI encountered an error while sending the completion status message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error reading ccode
column7: TLI encountered an error while awaiting the expected completion status message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: recv error code failed
column7: TLI encountered an error while awaiting an expected error message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: error reading negotation %s
column7: TLI encountered an error while awaiting the expected negotiation message during connection establishment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: poll failed
column7: TLI was unable to poll the communication channel for possible incoming messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: poll returned error event
column7: TLI received an unexpected event while polling the communication channel for possible incoming messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: server cannot exec oracle
column7: The remote TLI server was unable to start an Oracle process on behalf of the client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Note the operating system error message or number and contact your system administrator. The permissions on the remote Oracle program may be set incorrectly.

column6: TLI Driver: server cannot create new process
column7: The remote TLI server was unable to start an Oracle process on behalf of the client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Note the operating system error message or number and contact your system administrator. The remote host may be unable to create any new processes due to a full process table.

column6: TLI Driver: shadow process could not retrieve protocol info
column7: The Oracle process either failed to allocate memory to store the protocol information record, or the protocol rejected the request for some unknown reason.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: SQL*Net SPX client went away during reconnect
column7: The client process was aborted by the system or the user, and was unable to complete the connection establishment with the server listener process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine the cause of the client exit, and reattempt the connection.

column6: TLI Driver: listen for SPX server reconnect failed
column7: An unknown event occurred on the client's listening socket.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not open the /etc/netware/yellowpages file
column7: The /etc/netware/yellowpages file does not exist, or is not readable by the TLI listener process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Insure the file exists and is readable. Make sure that the server machine's node name, network number, ethernet address, and listening socket number are encoded in the file.

column6: TLI Driver: the IPX device file could not be opened
column7: The /dev/ipx file does not exist, or the driver has not been installed in the kernel correctly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reinvoke the Oracle root installation. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not bind an IPX address at initialization
column7: The IPX driver has not been correctly installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reinvoke the Oracle root installation. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not send datagram SAP packet for SPX
column7: The socket endpoint for sending SAP packet was corrupted for some unknown reason.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not complete protocol initialization for SPX
column7: A step in the SPX/IPX protocol initialization failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the previous error reported, and follow corrective action.

column6: TLI Driver: could not open ethernet device driver file
column7: The file /dev/eth does not exist, or the driver it references could not be opened.
column8: From Oracle doc: The system's real ethernet device file, for example /dev/wd, for the Western Digital ethernet driver, should be linked to the file /dev/eth. If this has been done, insure that the ethernet driver has been installed by completing the TCP/IP installation on your system, and testing a connection. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support for a list of supported ethernet drivers.

column6: TLI Driver: could not link IPX and ethernet streams
column7: Either the ethernet driver has not been installed in the system correctly, or the ethernet driver is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Insure that the ethernet driver has been installed by completing the TCP/IP installation on your system, and testing a connection. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support for a list of supported ethernet drivers.

column6: TLI Driver: could not clear the IPX ethernet SAP at init
column7: The IPX driver has not been correctly installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reinvoke the Oracle root installation. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not set the IPX ethernet SAP at init
column7: The IPX driver has not been correctly installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reinvoke the Oracle root installation. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not set the IPX network number at init
column7: The IPX driver has not been correctly installed, or the network number encoded in the /etc/netware/yellowpages file is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: The network number in the yellowpages file should match the four-byte network number of your Novell file server. If this is configured correctly, reinvoke the Oracle root installation. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not read the ethernet driver's node address
column7: The ethernet driver is not installed correctly, or does not support this operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support for a list of supported ethernet drivers.

column6: TLI Driver: the configured ethernet address is incorrect
column7: The node address read from the ethernet driver does not match the value encoded in the /etc/netware/yellowpages file for this server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm the correct ethernet node address for your LAN card, and enter this value in the yellowpages file.

column6: TLI Driver: the SPX device file could not be opened
column7: The /dev/nspxd file does not exist, or the driver has not been installed in the kernel correctly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reinvoke the Oracle root installation. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not link SPX and IPX streams
column7: The SPX driver has not been correctly installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reinvoke the Oracle root installation. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not set the SPX SAP address
column7: The SPX driver has not been correctly installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reinvoke the Oracle root installation. If problem continues, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: TLI Driver: could not read the Novell network address
column7: The file $ORACLE_HOME/spx/address could not be opened for reading and writing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure ORACLE_HOME is set, and the permissions on the ORACLE_HOME are read, write. If this file has been unintentionally deleted, run SPXCTL (net option) to reset the configured Novell network number for SQL*Net SPX.

column6: CMX: cannot read tns directory
column7: CMX is not started on your system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Install and/or start CMX on your system.

column6: CMX: no local name assigned to local application
column7: Local application ORACMX has no local name assigned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter unique local name for ORACMX in the TNS directory.

column6: CMX: cannot attach to cmx subsystem
column7: CCP-xxxx is not started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Start your CCP software on the communication controller.

column6: CMX: cannot read transport address of remote application
column7: Remote application not entered in TNS directory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter remote application in TNS directory.

column6: CMX: no transport address available for remote application
column7: No local name assigned to remote application.
column8: From Oracle doc: Assign local name to remote application.

column6: CMX: connect error
column7: Remote partner not listening.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure remote node has CMX installed and running make sure ORACMX is running on remote host.

column6: CMX: cannot get maximum packet size from CMX
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error during connect confirmation
column7: Remote partner aborted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error during transfer of ORACLE_SID
column7: Remote partner aborted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error during acknowledge of ORACLE_SID
column7: Remote partner aborted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: Cannot start oracle process on remote machine
column7: Oracle process not found or wrong mode (should be 4751).
column8: From Oracle doc: Change /etc/oratab or set mode to 4751.

column6: CMX: t_event returns ERROR
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: write error in datarq
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error during redirection of connection
column7: ORACMX has been stopped, or user process has been aborted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: unexepected event during start of oracle
column7: Connect sequence out of sync.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: unknown t_event in datarq
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error in data read (t_datain)
column7: Remote partner aborted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error in data read (too many bytes read)
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: T_NOEVENT during wait for read event
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error during write request (unknown event)
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: getbrkmsg illegal datatype
column7: Received packets are corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: getdatmsg illegal datatype
column7: Received packets are corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: bad write length
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: illegal break condition
column7: Break handling out of sync.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: wrong break message length
column7: Received packets are corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: disconnect during connect request
column7: Partner is not responding.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure partner is up and running and reachable.

column6: CMX: T_ERROR during read data
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: T_DATAIN received before all data written
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: wrong ORACLE_SID
column7: ORACLE_SID is not entered in remote ORATAB.
column8: From Oracle doc: add ORACLE_SID to remote ORATAB.

column6: CMX: error when sending ORACLE_SID
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error when checking ORACLE_SID
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error during read_properties for server
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error in local name
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CMX: error during attach
column7: Internal error in CMX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: No error
column7: SQL*Net AppleTalk error codes base. This is not an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: Operating system call error
column7: AppleTalk API received error in VMS system service.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Remote end of the communication issued a forward-reset packet.
column7: Peer program may have aborted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Investigate network problems and try again.

column6: Not enough virtual memory
column7: Not enough memory available.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check VMS process quotas and/or SYSGEN parameters.

column6: Illegal file name
column7: Erroneous file name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check path name for server output file, or SQL*Net Appletalk Logical names and symbols.

column6: Number of database servers exceed limit
column7: Too many database connections.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check ATKSRV_MAXCON parameter in configuration file.

column6: Failed to get local host name
column7: Unable to get Appletalk host name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check Appletalk configuration.

column6: No SID is currently available
column7: Incoming SQL*Net connection specified invalid SID name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify correct SID in connect string and retry.

column6: Failed to access configuration file
column7: Unable to access CONFIG.ATK.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check file protections.

column6: Buffer I/O quota is too small
column7: Buffered I/O quota exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase BIOLM using AUTHORIZE utility and retry.

column6: Failed to access log file
column7: SQL*Net Appletalk listener could not create log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check directory path and protections.

column6: Insufficient privilege for attempted operation
column7: You do not have sufficient privileges for the attempted operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check process privileges and retry.

column6: X.25 Driver: remote host is unknown
column7: Host name specified in the login (connect string) is unknown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check spelling; make sure name is in the X.25 HOST file.

column6: X.25 Driver: error while receiving data
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: X.25 Driver: error while sending data
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: X.25 Driver: invalid buffer size
column7: The buffer size specified in the login string must be between 5 and 4096.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-submit with valid buffer size.

column6: X.25 Driver: SID lookup failure
column7: From the remote host's SQL*Net X.25 server: the database SID, specified in the login (connect) string, was not recognized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add the appropriate SID entry to the CONFIG.ORA file on the remote host (and restart the SQL*Net X.25 server).

column6: X.25 Driver: connect to host failed
column7: Connection attempt to remote host has failed. Probably means that the SQL*Net X.25 server on the remote host is not up, or the host itself is not up.
column8: From Oracle doc: Start the SQL*Net X.25 server process on the remote host.

column6: X.25 Driver: endpoint creation failure
column7: Process open file quota probably exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: X.25 Driver: X.25 Level 2 failure

column8: From Oracle doc: You have probably exceeded the maximum number of open file descriptors per user or the system file table operating system error code and contact your system administrator.
