column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure GETHOSTNAME is successful in other contexts, and if so contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Malloc of scratch buffer failed.
column7: Memory needed for a temporary buffer could not be allocated. The additional information field contains the number of bytes that Oracle attempted to allocate.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number. It is probable that the system has run out of memory. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to find ORACLE password file entry for user.
column7: No entry exists for the user in the Oracle password file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Have the database administrator install a password entry by running ORAPASSWD.

column6: Incorrect user password.
column7: The password entered by the user was incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter the correct password.

column6: Malloc of name buffer(s) failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to allocate memory for one or both of the buffers that are used to hold the name of DBA and the operator users.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number. It is probable that the system has run out of memory. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Malloc of dummy name failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to allocate memory for the user name that is to be used in the encryption of the user's password.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number. It is probable that the system has run out of memory. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to open the ORACLE password file.
column7: Oracle could not open the password file for reading.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number. If the error number indicates that the file does not exist, have the database administrator create the file by running ORAPASSWD. If the error number indicates insufficient permissions, ask the database administrator to change the permissions. Otherwise, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Password encryption failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to encrypt a password. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Required password was not specified.
column7: A user attempted to connect as "internal," but did not specify a password.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect as internal again and specify a password.

column6: Unable to get user privileges from SQL*Net
column7: Oracle was unable to retrieve the user's privilege set from the SQL*Net connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system error. Also check the "additional information" field for the SQL*Net error. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to set label of dedicated server
column7: Oracle was unable to set the label of the dedicated to server to the required value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system error. Also, check the privileges on the Oracle executable. It should have at least ALLOWMACACCESS privilege.

column6: Unable to get sensitivity label from connection
column7: Oracle was unable to retrieve the user's sensitivity label from the SQL*Net connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system error. Also check the "additional information" field for the SQL*Net error. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to get information label from connection
column7: Oracle was unable to retrieve the user's information label from the SQL*Net connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system error. Also check the "additional information" field for the SQL*Net error. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Can't spawn process - background log directory not created properly
column7: Oracle was unable to spawn a background process because the directory that will hold trace files of the background processes was not created properly.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Examine the directory pointed to by the initialization parameter BACKGROUND_DUMP_DEST. Make sure that all of the following is true: 

The directory exists. 

The name indeed points to a directory, and is not a file. 

The directory is accessible and writable to the Oracle user.

column6: Can't spawn process - user log directory not created properly
column7: Oracle was unable to spawn a background process because the directory that holds the trace files of the dedicated server processes was not created properly.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Examine the directory pointed to by the initialization parameter USER_DUMP_DEST. Make sure that all of the following is true: 

The directory exists. 

The name indeed points to a directory, and is not a file. 

The directory is accessible and writable to the Oracle user.

column6: Can't spawn process - core dump directory not created properly
column7: Oracle was unable to spawn a background process because the directory that holds the core dumps produced by Oracle processes in the event of exceptions was not created properly.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Examine the directory pointed to by the initialization parameter CORE_DUMP_DEST. Make sure that all of the following is true: 

The directory exists. 

The name indeed points to a directory, and is not a file. 

The directory is accessible and writable to the Oracle user.

column6: Unable to create audit trail file
column7: Oracle was not able to create the file being used to hold audit trail records.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system error. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to set effective privilege set of the server
column7: A dedicated server was unable to set it's own privilege set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the privileges granted to the Oracle executable. It must have at least ALLOWMACACESS privilege.

column6: Unable to set label of server
column7: Oracle was not able to set the label of a server to a new value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the privileges on $ORACLE_HOME/bin/oracle. Make sure that it has ALLOWMACACCESS privilege.

column6: Unable to restore the label of server
column7: Oracle was unable to restore the label of the server to the value that it had before raising it to database high. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: GLB of two labels is invalid
column7: The result of a greatest lower bound operation on two labels was not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Repeat the operation with two different labels. Consult the system encoding file for the values of valid labels.

column6: LUB of two labels is invalid
column7: The result of a least upper bound operation on two labels was not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Repeat the operation with two different labels. Consult the system encoding file for the values of valid labels.

column6: Unable to open ORACLE password file for reading
column7: An attempt to open a password file for reading failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the permissions on the file have not been changed so that the Oracle user cannot open it.

column6: Close of ORACLE password file failed.
column7: An attempt to close a password file failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for the specific reason.

column6: Deletion of old password file failed.
column7: The removal of the old password file failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for the specific reason.

column6: Link of current password file to old failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to create a link so that the old password file could be saved.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for the specific reason.

column6: Unlink of current password file failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to complete the saving of the current password file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for the specific reason.

column6: Open of ORACLE password file for write failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to create a password file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for the specific reason.

column6: Chmod of ORACLE password file failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to change a password file to be read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for the specific reason.

column6: Save of signal handlers failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to save the previous values of selected signal handlers. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Restoration of signal handlers failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to restore the previous values of selected signal handlers. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: ORACLE password file header is corrupt
column7: The header of one of the password files was not in the format that Oracle expected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the headers of both files. The header should be in the format "FILE VERSION: N.N.N.N.N EXECUTABLE VERSION: N.N.N.N.N" where N is a number. Remove the corrupt file(s) and re-run ORAPASSWD.

column6: Version of orapasswd or installer is older than file.
column7: The version of ORAPASSWD or installer that is being run is older than that of the Oracle password file. Since the file version is only changed when the format is changed, this error means that the executable is using a different format than that with which the file was created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Run a version of the installer or ORAPASSWD whose version is the same or later than that of the file.

column6: Write of ORACLE password file header failed.
column7: The attempt to write out the header of the Oracle password file failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the operating system error number. It is possible that the file system became full.

column6: Allocation of memory for password list component failed.
column7: When it is building a list of password file entries, Oracle allocates memory for various components. One of the allocations failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the operating system error number. The system has probably run out of memory.

column6: Password entry is corrupt.
column7: An entry in an Oracle password file was not in the format that Oracle expected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Removed the corrupt file(s) and re-run ORAPASSWD.

column6: Unable to initialize the audit trail file
column7: Oracle was unable to write header information to the file being used as the audit trail.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system error. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: File name too long for buffer
column7: The buffer that was to be used to hold a file name was determined to be too short for the generated name. This will happen if the translated name for either a trace file or an audit file is longer than the maximum allowed, which on many ports is 256 characters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a shorter file name.

column6: Unable to allocate connection attributes structure
column7: Oracle was not able to allocate the memory needed to hold the attributes of the SQL*Net connection. The "Additional Information" field holds the number of bytes that Oracle attempted to allocate.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number. It is probable that the system has run out of memory. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Process information label retrieval failed.
column7: Oracle was unable to get the information label for a process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system failure. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to get client operating system privileges
column7: Oracle was unable to get the operating system privileges for the client process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system failure. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to get server operating system privileges
column7: Oracle was unable to get its privileges from the operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is an error that should never happen. Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to create file
column7: Oracle was unable to create a file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the UNIX error number for a possible operating system failure. If there is no error, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: scgcmn: lk_open_convert unexpected return: open failed

column8: From Oracle doc: Check for system error message and refer to the Distributed Lock Manager documentation or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: scggc: unexpected return of a lock convert
column7: The Distributed Lock Manager returned an unexpected value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for Lock Manager error messages and refer to the Distributed Lock Manager documentation or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: scgcc: unexpected return status to callback of lock close
column7: The Distributed Lock Manager returned an unexpected value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for Lock Manager error messages and refer to the Distributed Lock Manager documentation or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: scgcan: unexpected return status when canceling a lock
column7: DLM system service x returned an unexpected value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for system error message and refer to the Distributed Lock Manager documentation or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: scgcm: unexpected lock status condition
column7: A global locking system service returned an unexpected value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for system error message (if any) and refer to refer to the Distributed Lock Manager documentation or contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to send termination request to IMON
column7: The attempt to send a termination signal to IMON failed. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: IMON: two processes with the same ORACLE pid are active

column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: IMON: deletion of a process failed.
column7: The IMON process was unable to delete a server process from its process ID array because no entry for the process could be found. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to establish signal handler for termination signal
column7: Oracle was unable to set up a handler for the signal used to notify it that the instance was shutting down. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Unable to restore termination signal handler
column7: Oracle failed to set the handler for the termination signal to its previous value. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: scumnt: translation error while expanding ?/dbs/lk
column7: Failure of SLTLN in SCUMNT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional returned error for more information.

column6: scumnt: unable to create or open file
column7: Open system call returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check errno.

column6: scumnt: unable to lock file
column7: Lock file operating system call returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check errno.

column6: scurls: unable to close lock file
column7: Close system call returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check errno.

column6: skxfidini: Error Initializing SDI Channel
column7: The process was unable to initialize the SDI channel properly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: kxfspini: Error Initializing SDI Process
column7: The process was unable to attach to the SDI channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the SDI process specific limits correctly configured. Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: skxfqdini: Error Creating Port
column7: The process was unable to create a communications endpoint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the SDI port specific limits correctly configured. Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: skxfqhini: Error Connecting
column7: The process was unable to connect to another endpoint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the SDI port specific limits correctly configured. Check that the other node(s) is part of the cluster and operating properly. Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: skxfqhdel: Error Disconnecting from another endpoint.
column7: The process was unable to disconnect cleanly from another endpoint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the other node(s) are part of the cluster and operating properly. Check the instance and processes on the other node(s). Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: skxfqhsnd: Error Sending a message to another endpoint
column7: The process was unable to send a message to an existing endpoint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the other node(s) are part of the cluster and operating properly. Check the instance and processes on the other node(s). Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: skxfqdrcv: Error Receiving a message from another endpoint
column7: The process encountered an error while trying to receive a message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the other node(s) are part of the cluster and operating properly. Check the instance and processes on the other node(s). Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: skxfqdreg: Error Adding a page to the SDI buffer pool
column7: The process was unable to add a page to the SDI buffer pool.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: skxfqddrg: Error Removing a page from the SDI buffer pool
column7: The process was unable to remove a page to the SDI buffer pool.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the operating system error and retry the operation.

column6: skxfidsht: Error shutting down SDI channel
column7: The process was unable to shut down the SDI channel.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the SDI persistent resources using SDI tools. Verify that all processes exited cleanly and the instance is safely shut down. Delete any remaining SDI channel IDs associated with the current instance.

column6: SGA file $ORACLE_HOME/dbs/sgadef$ORACLE_SID.dbf does not exist
column7: File does not exist or is not accessible.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance to create the SGA definition file.

column6: SGA definition file could not be read
column7: UNIX read() operation failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check errno and take appropriate action.

column6: wrong number of bytes read from SGA definition file
column7: Struct SKGMSDEF size differs from the number of bytes read from the SGA file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Compare the two struct definitions and ensure that they are identical in size and structure.

column6: unable to attach to SGA in READ-ONLY mode
column7: The instance is not up, or SGA segments are not read-accessible.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the instance is up and read permissions for the SGA segments are set.

column6: error while detaching SGA
column7: SKGMSDEF struct is corrupted and/or segment addresses are modified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Safely shut down the instance and mount the SGA segments again.

column6: attempt to use invalid skgmsdef struct pointer
column7: Pointer to SKGMSDEF struct used without validating it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Assign a valid address to the SKGMSDEF struct pointer before using it.

column6: %s
column7: This event is sent when a message could not be properly mapped to EVENT:- due to a short text difference in the RtpLogOracle event catalogue. Please, check the details for event EVENT:- using RtpAdmCli or RTP GUI.
column8: From Oracle doc: The RtpLogOracle event catalogue should be updated to correspond the message issued by the OS to assure correct mapping.

column6: a snapshot log already exists on table '%s'
column7: An attempt was made to create a snapshot log on a table that already has a snapshot log. Each master table can have only one snapshot log.
column8: From Oracle doc: All snapshots on a table can use the same snapshot log for that table. To make changes to the existing log, use the ALTER SNAPSHOT LOG command or drop the snapshot log and create it again.

column6: cannot create log: table '%s' already has a trigger
column7: Snapshot logs are filled by a trigger on the master table. That trigger cannot be created.
column8: From Oracle doc: To create a snapshot log, drop the current trigger on the master.

column6: there is no snapshot log on table "%s"."%s"
column7: There is no snapshot log on the master table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the log.

column6: snapshot "%s"."%s" does not exist
column7: The snapshot with the given owner and name does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify inputs or create snapshot.

column6: REFRESH FAST cannot be used for snapshot "%s"."%s"
column7: The snapshot log does not exist or cannot be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use just REFRESH, which will reinstantiate the entire table. If a snapshot log exists and the form of the snapshot allows the use of a snapshot log, REFRESH FAST will be available starting the next time the snapshot is refreshed.

column6: may not schedule automatic refresh for times in the past
column7: An attempt was made to schedule an automated snapshot refresh for a time in the past.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a time in the future instead.

column6: a snapshot with the same user.name already exists
column7: An attempt was made to create a snapshot with the name of an existing snapshot.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the snapshot using a different name or drop the existing snapshot.

column6: snapshot reuse parameters are inconsistent
column7: The CREATE SNAPSHOT .. or CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG .. REUSE command was given inconsistent parameters immediately after the REUSE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the other messages on the stack to find the problem.

column6: error in snapshot refresh path
column7: Table SNAP$_snapshot_name reads rows from the view MVIEW$_snapshot_name, which is a view on the master table (the master may be at a remote site). Any error in this path will cause this error at refresh time. For fast refreshes, the table master_owner.MLOG$_master is also referenced.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the other messages on the stack to find the problem. See if the objects SNAP$_snapshot_name, MVIEW$_snapshot_name, mowner.master@dblink, mowner.MLOG$_master@dblink still exist.

column6: snapshots may not contain long columns
column7: An attempt was made to create a snapshot with a long column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to create snapshot logs with long columns.

column6: cannot create snapshot log on table owned by SYS
column7: CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG attempts to create a trigger on the table, but triggers cannot be created on SYS tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Cannot create snapshot logs on SYS tables.

column6: execution of %s jobs failed
column7: Some kind of error was caught in DBMS_IJOB.RUN. One or more jobs which were due to be run produced errors which they could not handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look at the alert log for details on which jobs failed and why.

column6: error on auto execute of job %s
column7: Some kind of error was caught while doing an automatic execute of a job.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look at the accompanying errors for details on why the execute failed.

column6: updatable snapshots must be simple enough to do fast refresh
column7: The updatable snapshot query has a join, subquery, union, connect by, order by, or group by.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the snapshot simpler. If a join is really needed, make multiple simple snapshots then put a view on top of them.

column6: table '%s' does not contain a primary key constraint
column7: The CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG command was issued with the WITH PRIMARY KEY option and the master table does not contain a primary key constraint or the constraint is disabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the command using only the WITH ROWID option, create a primary key constraint on the master table, or enable an existing primary key constraint.

column6: cannot create a fast refresh snapshot from a complex query
column7: Neither ROWIDs and nor primary key constraints are supported for complex queries.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the command with the REFRESH FORCE or REFRESH COMPLETE option or create a simple snapshot.

column6: snapshot does not include all primary key columns
column7: The query that instantiates the snapshot does not include all of the columns in the master's primary key constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Include all of the master's primary key columns in the snapshot query or create a ROWID snapshot.

column6: cannot alter primary key snapshot '%s' to a rowid snapshot
column7: Conversion of a primary key snapshot to a ROWID snapshot is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a new snapshot or drop and re-create the snapshot.

column6: following error encountered during code generation for "%s"."%s"
column7: The refresh operations for the indicated snapshot could not be regenerated due to errors. See following error text.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the indicated problem and repeat the operation.

column6: master table is a synonym to a remote object
column7: Snapshot of remote synonyms or snapshot logs on remote synonym are not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not create the snapshot or snapshot log on a remote synonym.

column6: snapshot %s is not registered
column7: Attempt to unregister a snapshot that is not registered.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: snapshot "%s"."%s" is corrupt
column7: The snapshot indicated is no longer valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: snapshot log on "%s"."%s" already has rowid
column7: Snapshot log on the indicated table already has ROWID information.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: missing index on snapshot "%s"."%s"
column7: The specified ROWID snapshot does not have the required index on the ROWID column of its underlying table.
column8: From Oracle doc: The snapshot is corrupted. Drop and re-create the snapshot.

column6: snapshot log on "%s"."%s" does not have primary key columns
column7: Snapshot log on the indicated table does not have primary key information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add primary keys to snapshot log using the alter snapshot command.

column6: snapshot log on "%s"."%s" already has primary keys
column7: Snapshot log on the indicated table already has primary key columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: invalid filter column detected
column7: One or more of the specified filter columns does not exist or is a primary key column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that all specified filter columns exist in the master table and ensure that primary key columns are not included in the list of filter columns.

column6: dulicate filter column
column7: One or more of the specified filter columns is already begin recorded in the snapshot log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Describe the snapshot log table and reissue the SQL command with specifying the filter columns that are already begin recorded in the snapshot log.

column6: snapshot type is not supported by master site %s
column7: Pre-Oracle8 master sites are not able to support primary key or subquery snapshots that are able to perform a fast refresh.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a ROWID snapshot or use a master table from an Oracle8 site.

column6: LOB columns may not be used as filter columns
column7: LOB columns may not be used as filter columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove LOB columns from the filter columns list and retry command.

column6: cannot create a fast refresh snapshot
column7: The snapshot log does not exist or does not log the information needed by the snapshot to perform a fast refresh.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the snapshot log exists and logs the necessary information. For ROWID snapshots, the master table's ROWID must be logged. For primary key, snapshots the master table's primary key columns must be logged. For subquery snapshots filter, primary key, and ROWID values must all be logged.

column6: cannot use primary key columns from snapshot log on "%s"."%s"
column7: The snapshot log either does not have primary columns logged, or the timestamp associated with the primary key columns is more recent than the last refresh time.
column8: From Oracle doc: A complete refresh is required before the next fast refresh.

column6: cannot use rowid column from snapshot log on "%s"."%s"
column7: The snapshot log either does not have primary columns logged, or the timestamp associated with the primary key columns is more recent than the last refresh time.
column8: From Oracle doc: A complete refresh is required before the next fast refresh.

column6: cannot use filter columns from snapshot log on "%s"."%s"
column7: The snapshot log either does not have primary columns logged, or the timestamp associated with the primary key columns is more recent than the last refresh time.
column8: From Oracle doc: A complete refresh is required before the next fast refresh.

column6: snapshot log on "%s"."%s" younger than last refresh
column7: The snapshot log is younger than the last refresh.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform a complete refresh of the snapshot before attempting another fast refresh.

column6: could not use snapshot log on "%s"."%s"
column7: The snapshot log does not exist or cannot be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use just REFRESH, which will reinstantiate the entire table. If a snapshot log exists and the form of the snapshot allows the use of a snapshot log, REFRESH FAST will be available starting.

column6: updatable snapshot log is not empty, refresh snapshot
column7: The updatable snapshot log must be empty before an updatable ROWID snapshot can be altered to a primary key snapshot.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that updatable snapshot log is empty by refreshing the snapshot before converting the updatable ROWID snapshot to a primary key snapshot.

column6: unknown export format
column7: An attempt was made to import a snapshot exported by an unknown export version (for example, from a newer release than the importing site)
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-export the file using a version of export known by the importing site.

column6: %s literal has unexpected length
column7: Corrupt or invalid information was detected during import of a snapshot.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the export log file has not been corrupted and that no errors were raised during export. Contact Oracle Customer Support if the problem persists.

column6: unable to use local rollback segment "%s"
column7: A local rollback segment was specified in the CREATE SNAPSHOT command, but automatic refresh parameters were not specified. Therefore a refresh group was not created to automatically refresh the snapshot and the local rollback segment cannot be registered for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either supply the automatic refresh parameters so that a refresh group will be created or do not specify a local rollback segment.

column6: master rollback segment option not support by master site %s
column7: The master site of the current snapshot does not allow users to specify a rollback segment to be used for snapshot operations. This feature is only supported by Oracle8 or later master sites.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify a master rollback segment in the current operation or choose a new master site.

column6: cannot record ROWIDs for index-organized table "%s"."%s"
column7: Index-organized tables do not have ROWIDs. Therefore a snapshot log that records the ROWIDs of an index-organized table cannot be created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not include the WITH ROWID option when using the CREATE SNAPSHOT command and do not include the ADD ROWID option when using the ALTER SNAPSHOT command if the master table is index-organized.

column6: cannot alter job_queue_processes in single process mode
column7: There is no concept of detached processes in single process mode. Therefore altering the value of JOB_QUEUE_PROCESSES parameter is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to set JOB_QUEUE_PROCESSES in single process mode.

column6: invalid CREATE SNAPSHOT option
column7: An invalid option was used in a CREATE SNAPSHOT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: invalid CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG option
column7: An invalid option was used in a CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: invalid ALTER SNAPSHOT LOG option
column7: An invalid option was used in an ALTER SNAPSHOT LOG statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: ON COMMIT attribute is incompatible with other options
column7: The ON COMMIT refresh attribute is not allowed with other refresh options such as automatic periodic refresh.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: cannot fast refresh materialized view %s.%s
column7: This materialized view is not always fast refreshable. Either ROWIDs of certain tables are missing in the definition or the inner table of an outer join does not have UNIQUE constraints on join columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the FORCE or COMPLETE option. If this error occurred during creation, the materialized view definition could be changed. Refer to the documentation on materialized views.

column6: cannot set the ON COMMIT refresh attribute for the materialized view
column7: The materialized view does not satisfy conditions for refresh at commit time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: invalid REFRESH method
column7:
The NEVER REFRESH option may not be used under the following conditions: 

The snapshot is updatable 

The snapshot refreshes ON COMMIT 

Automatic refresh options are specified
column8: From Oracle doc: For updatable snapshots, reissue the SQL command using REFRESH FORCE, REFRESH FAST, or REFRESH COMPLETE. For read-only snapshots, reissue the SQL command using ON DEMAND.

column6: snapshot "%s"."%s" is INVALID and must complete refresh
column7: The status of the snapshot is INVALID and the snapshot may not be fast refreshed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform a complete refresh of the snapshot. Check the value of the STATUS column in DBA_SNAPSHOTS, ALL_SNAPSHOTS, or USER_SNAPSHOTS to verify that the snapshot is VALID after the complete refresh.

column6: snapshot cannot use prebuilt table
column7: The snapshot cannot use the prebuilt table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the SQL command using BUILD IMMEDIATE or BUILD DEFERRED.

column6: prebuilt table "%s"."%s" does not exist
column7: The specified prebuilt table does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the SQL command using BUILD IMMEDIATE, BUILD DEFERRED, or ensure that the prebuilt table exists.

column6: shape of prebuilt table does not match definition query
column7: The number of columns or the type of a column in the prebuilt table does not match the snapshot definition query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reissue the SQL command using BUILD IMMEDIATE, BUILD DEFERRED, or ensure that the prebuilt table matches the snapshot definition query.

column6: invalid ALTER SNAPSHOT option
column7: An invalid option was used in an ALTER SNAPSHOT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: transaction %s received out of sequence from site %s
column7: A transaction from the client site was received out of sequence. This implies that one or more transactions are missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the transaction queue at the client site is valid and has not been corrupted.

column6: unable to apply transaction from site %s
column7: The current transaction from the client site could not be applied to the master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the client site is still valid and that it has not been dropped from the master site.

column6: invalid refresh sequence number: %s
column7: The client site is attempting to perform a refresh with an invalid refresh sequence.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform a complete refresh to synchronize the refresh sequence number.

column6: unknown refresh group identifier %s
column7: The specified refresh group does not exist at the master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the client site is still valid and that it has not been dropped from the master site.

column6: invalid CREATE SNAPSHOT command
column7:
The Replication API does not support the following options and types of snapshot: 

ROWID snapshots 

REFRESH ON COMMIT 

ON PREBUILT TABLE 

BUILD DEFERRED 

NEVER REFRESH 

ENABLE QUERY REWRITE
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a PRIMARY KEY snapshot using REFRESH WITH PRIMARY KEY and/or remove the invalid options.

column6: empty refresh groups are not allowed
column7: The refresh group being instantiated does not contain any snapshots.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the template to include at least one snapshot.

column6: updatable snapshot log for snapshot "%s"."%s" does not exist
column7: The updatable snapshot is missing the updatable snapshot log that is required to track updates made to the snapshot.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the updatable snapshot log.

column6: invalid object for offline instantiation
column7: Only snapshots can be offline instantiated. The object being offline instantiated is not a valid snapshot.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the object from the template or replace the object with a valid snapshot.

column6: cannot offline instantiate snapshot "%s"."%s"
column7:
Offline instantiation does not support snapshots using the following options:

ON PREBUILT TABLE 

BUILD DEFERRED
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid options.

column6: definition query of "%s"."%s" is invalid for offline instantiation
column7:
Offline instantiation requires snapshot definition queries to observe the following constraints: 

"SELECT *" may not be used. The query must explicitly specify each column in the select list. 

The database link that will be used by the snapshot site to connect to the master site must be included with each master table referenced in the query. 

All master tables referenced must be located at the local site. References to other sites are not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the snapshot definition query.

column6: updatable materialized view log data for '%s'.'%s' cannot be created
column7: The updatable materialized view is missing the updatable materialized view log that is required to track updates made to the materialized view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the updatable materialized view log.

column6: request cannot be processed
column7: An out-of-sequence request was made and it cannot be processed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again with a valid request.

column6: invalid memory address
column7: An attempt was made to access an invalid memory region.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reconnect and try the command again.

column6: invalid object or field
column7: ] An attempt was made to access an invalid field or object in the Java Virtual Memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the request.

column6: invalid threshold value
column7: The result set threshold or LOB threshold value is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a threshold value below 64K.

column6: temporary updatable materialized view log does not exist
column7: Temporary updatable materialized view log was not created or was dropped.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Re-create the temporary updatable materialized view log. 

Warning: This will cause a complete refresh of the materialized view.

column6: fast refresh of refresh group ID %s failed
column7: Refresh result set sent through client method REFRESH_REQ_RESULT returns an unknown value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-issue the refresh request.

column6: snapshot options require COMPATIBLE parameter to be %s or greater
column7:
The following snapshot options require 8.1 or higher compatibility setting:

ON COMMIT 

ON PREBUILT TABLE 

BUILD DEFERRED 

NEVER REFRESH 

ENABLE QUERY REWRITE
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down and restart with an appropriate compatibility setting.

column6: , 00000 update operation not allowed on table %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to update a read-only materialized view. Only Oracle is allowed to update a read-only materialized view.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: '%s'.'%s' cannot be index organized
column7: An attempt was made to create an index-organized materialized aggregate view or an index-organized updatable ROWID materialized view. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try to create the materialized view without the index organization clause.

column6: must use DROP MATERIALIZED VIEW to drop %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to drop a materialized view using a command other than DROP MATERIALIZED VIEW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the DROP MATERIALIZED VIEW command.

column6: must use ALTER MATERIALIZED VIEW to alter %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to alter a materialized view using a command other than ALTER MATERIALIZED VIEW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the ALTER MATERIALIZED VIEW command.

column6: TNS:unable to send data
column7: Unable to send data. Connection probably disconnected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-establish connection. If the error is persistent, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation.

column6: TNS:received bad packet type from network layer
column7: Internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:unable to send break message
column7: Unable to send break message. Connection probably disconnected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-establish connection. If the error is persistent, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation.

column6: TNS:not connected
column7: Not currently connected to a remote host.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-establish connection.

column6: TNS:could not resolve service name
column7: The service name specified is not defined correctly in the TNSNAMES.ORA file.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Make the following checks and correct the error: 
- Verify that a TNSNAMES.ORA file exists and is in the proper place and accessible. See the operating system specific manual for details on the required name and location.
- Check to see that the service name exists in one of the TNSNAMES.ORA files and add it if necessary.
- Make sure there are no syntax errors anywhere in the file. Particularly look for unmatched parentheses or stray characters. Any error in a TNSNAMES.ORA file makes it unusable. See Chapter 4 in the SQL*Net V2 Administrator's Guide. If possible, regenerate the configuration files using the Oracle Network Manager.

column6: TNS:received bad datatype in NSWMARKER packet
column7: Internal error during break handling.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:tried to reset line from incorrect state
column7: Internal error during break handling.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:internal network communication error
column7: Internal error during network communication.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:could not initialize parameter subsystem
column7: Unable to locate parameter file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that a valid parameter file exists, and is readable.

column6: TNS:trace file not writeable
column7: The trace file to be generated is not writeable by this user.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the user does not have write permissions in the directory to which the trace file will be written, contact the DBA to get the proper permissions or use TRACE_DIRECTORY_CLIENT in SQLNET.ORA to specify a directory the user can write to.

column6: TNS:internal error: Bad error number
column7: Corrupt error reporting subsystem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:internal error: partial data received
column7: The connection may be terminated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reconnect and try again. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:service name is incorrectly specified
column7: The connect descriptor corresponding to the service name in TNSNAMES.ORA is incorrectly specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure there are no syntax errors in the connect descriptor. Particularly look for unmatched parentheses or stray characters. Any error in a TNSNAMES.ORA file makes it unusable. See Chapter 4 in the SQL*Net V2 Administrator's Guide.

column6: TNS:connect descriptor is too long
column7: The connect descriptor corresponding to the service name in TNSNAMES.ORA is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: The maximum length for a connect descriptor is 512 bytes and this limit has been exceeded. Use a smaller connect descriptor. If this is not possible, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:Sqlnet.fdf file not present
column7: The sqlnet.fdf file doesn't exist in $ORACLE_HOME/network/admin.
column8: From Oracle doc: The sqlnet.fdf file is required for Oracle Tracing to occur. Either install the sqlnet.fdf file in $ORACLE_HOME/network/admin or turn off tracing in your ORA file.

column6: TNS:Trying to write trace file into swap space.
column7: Oracle Trace doesn't allow writing trace information into your swap space.
column8: From Oracle doc: Oracle Trace cannot write trace information into swap space so either disable tracing or redirect trace files to be written to another area of your disk.

column6: TNS:received an error from TNS
column7: The navigation layer received an error from TNS.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the error log file for the specific TNS error.

column6: TNS:keyword-value resolution error
column7: The navigation layer received an error while trying to look up a value for a keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the connect descriptor.

column6: TNS:could not find path to destination
column7: Could not navigate a path through Interchanges to the destination. This error occurs if an invalid community is in the address string, or the address includes a protocol that is not available or the TNSNAV.ORA file does not have a correct CMANAGER address specified or the Interchange is down.
column8: From Oracle doc: Assure that Interchanges necessary to get to the desired destination are up and have available capacity for an additional connection. Also check that the correct community and protocol have been specified in the CMANAGER address used.

column6: TNS:could not allocate memory
column7: Out of memory on machine.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reconfigure machine to have more storage or run fewer applications while the Interchange is running.

column6: TNS:encountered too small a connection buffer
column7: TNS connection buffer supplied by the application was too small to retrieve the data sent back.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a larger connection buffer. If problem persists, call Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:internal navigation error
column7: Internal navigation error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:unable to connect to destination
column7: Invalid TNS address supplied or destination is not listening. This error can also occur because of underlying network transport problems.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the service name you entered on the command line was correct. Ensure that the listener is running at the remote node and that the ADDRESS parameters specified in TNSNAMES.ORA are correct. Finally, check that all Interchanges needed to make the connection are up and running.

column6: TNS: received data refused from an application
column7: The application using the Interchange or Connection Manager refused the connection at the listener.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the application listener at the destination is functioning correctly. If it is and the problem persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:could not get failed addresses
column7: Internal navigation error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:received a TNS error during navigation
column7: Internal navigation error because of an unexpected TNS error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look at the log file to find the TNS error. If necessary, turn on tracing and repeat the operation.

column6: TNS:unable to perform navigation
column7: Improperly configured navigation file TNSNAV.ORA.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the TNSNAV.ORA file on the application`s machine, and verify that it lists the correct communities.

column6: TNS:could not find the TNSNAV.ORA file
column7: Either the ORACLE environment is not set up correctly, or the TNSNAV.ORA file is not present.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the ORACLE environment is set up appropriately on your platform and that a TNSNAV.ORA file is present.

column6: TNS:encountered uninitialized global
column7: Application calling navigation routine has not properly configured the global variables. There are no TNSNAV.ORA files available, or they are defective.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:error in finding Navigator data
column7: Application calling navigation routine has not properly configured the TNSNAV.ORA file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the TNSNAV.ORA file.

column6: TNS:needs PREFERRED_CMANAGERS entry in TNSNAV.ORA
column7: TNSNAV.ORA does not have a PREFERRED_CMANAGERS defined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add a PREFERRED_CMANAGERS entry to the TNSNAV.ORA file.

column6: TNS:incomplete PREFERRED_CMANAGERS binding in TNSNAV.ORA
column7: The PREFERRED_CMANAGERS binding in the client's TNSNAV.ORA file does not have a CMANAGER_NAME specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define the CMANAGER_NAME as part of the PREFERRED_CMANAGERS binding. Use of the Oracle Network Manager should eliminate this error.

column6: TNS:incomplete PREFERRED_CMANAGERS binding in TNSNAV.ORA
column7: The PREFERRED_CMANAGERS binding in the client's TNSNAV.ORA file does not have an ADDRESS specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define the ADDRESS as part of the PREFERRED_CMANAGERS binding.

column6: TNS:missing local communities entry in TNSNAV.ORA
column7: There is no LOCAL_COMMUNITIES entry in TNSNAV.ORA.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define the LOCAL_COMMUNITIES for this node in the TNSNAV.ORA file.

column6: TNS:poorly formed PREFERRED_NAVIGATORS Addresses in TNSNAV.ORA
column7: Address binding for PREFERRED_NAVIGATORS entry is improperly entered. entry.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your PREFERRED_NAVIGATORS entry and fix it in TNSNAV.ORA.

column6: TNS:poorly formed PREFERRED_CMANAGERS addresses in TNSNAV.ORA
column7: Address binding for the PREFERRED_CMANAGERS entry in the client's TNSNAV.ORA file is improperly entered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define the ADDRESS as part of the PREFERRED_CMANAGERS binding.

column6: TNS:could not contact PREFERRED_CMANAGERS in TNSNAV.ORA
column7: There is a syntax error in the PREFERRED_CMANAGERS entry, or addresses specified are wrong, or the intended Connection Managers are unavailable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the PREFERRED_CMANAGERS entries in the client's TNSNAV.ORA file and correct them or talk with your network administrator to determine if the specified Connection Managers are available. Verify that the Interchanges are active by using the INTCTL STATUS command.

column6: TNS:unacceptable network configuration data
column7: Poorly formed network configuration data. For example, a PREFERRED_CMANAGERS entry may have an incorrect CMANAGER_NAME in the client's TNSNAV.ORA file. Or an Interchange downtime parameter (TIMEOUT_INTERVAL) on the Navigator may be set to zero in INTCHG.ORA.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the entries in TNSNAV.ORA and the Interchange configuration files and correct them. If necessary, talk with your network administrator to determine if the specified Interchanges (Connection Managers) are available and properly configured. Use the Oracle Network Manager to generate the configuration files if necessary.

column6: TNS:missing community name from address in ADDRESS_LIST
column7: This error occurs when an ADDRESS_LIST has some ADDRESSes in it that have no COMMUNITY component and others that do have a COMMUNITY component.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that in the connect descriptors you are using either all the ADDRESSes have a COMMUNITY component or all do not.

column6: TNS:illegal ADDRESS parameters
column7: An illegal set of protocol adapter parameters was specified. In some cases, this error is returned when a connection cannot be made to the protocol transport.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the destination can be reached using the specified protocol. Check the parameters within the ADDRESS section of TNSNAMES.ORA. Legal ADDRESS parameter formats may be found in the Oracle operating system specific documentation for your platform. Protocols that resolve names at the transport layer (such as DECnet object names) are vulnerable to this error if not properly configured or names are misspelled.

column6: TNS:no such protocol adapter
column7: The protocol adapter requested (by way of the "(PROTOCOL=..)" keyword-value pair in a TNS address) is unknown. If the supplied address is typographically correct then the protocol adaptor is not installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Install the protocol adapter or correct typographically error, as appropriate. Note: if the supplied address was derived from resolving the service name, check the address in the appropriate file (TNSNAMES.ORA, LISTENER.ORA or TNSNET.ORA).

column6: TNS:internal limit restriction exceeded
column7: Too many TNS connections open simultaneously.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for connections to close and re-try.

column6: TNS:no listener
column7: The connection request could not be completed because the listener is not running.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the supplied destination address matches one of the addresses used by the listener - compare the TNSNAMES.ORA entry with the appropriate LISTENER.ORA file (or TNSNAV.ORA if the connection is to go by way of an Interchange). Start the listener on the remote machine.

column6: TNS:destination host unreachable
column7: Contact can not be made with remote party.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the network driver is functioning and the network is up.

column6: TNS:operating system resource quota exceeded
column7: The current user has exceeded the allotted resource assigned in the operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Acquire more operating system resource, or perform a different function.

column6: TNS:syntax error
column7: The supplied connect descriptor contains illegal syntax.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the connect descriptor in TNSNAMES.ORA.

column6: TNS:protocol adapter not loadable
column7: On some platforms (such as OS/2) protocol adapters are loaded at run-time. If the shared library (or DLL) for the protocol adapter is missing or one of its supporting libraries is missing then this error is returned.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. The trace file will include the name of the shared library (or DLL) that could not be loaded.

column6: TNS:Interchange has no more free connections
column7: One or more Interchanges along the path to the destination desired has no more free connections available to be used for this call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again later when the Interchanges are less busy, or contact your network administrator to have him determine which interchange it is, and increase the number of connections available on that interchange.

column6: TNS:Severe Network error occurred in making this connection
column7: This error is reported by an interchange which fails to make contact with the destination due to a physical network error while calling a destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again later when the network service may have been fixed or report the problem to your Network Administrator so that he may fix the problem.

column6: TNS:No connection possible to destination
column7: This error is reported by an interchange which fails to find a possible connection along the path to the destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the problem to your Network Administrator so that he may fix the problem.

column6: TNS:No path available to destination
column7: This error is reported by an interchange which fails to find a possible path to the destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the problem to your Network Administrator so that he may fix the problem.

column6: TNS:Failure to accept a connection
column7: This error is reported by an interchange which fails to accept a connection due to a redirect failure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the problem to your Network Administrator so that he may isolate the interchange problem.

column6: TNS:Redirect to destination
column7: This error is reported by an interchange which determines that this interchange is not the right gateway and needs to redirect the connection to another gateway along the path to the destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: None.

column6: TNS:Failure to redirect to destination
column7: This error is reported by an interchange which fails to redirect a connection to another interchange along the path to the destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the problem to your Network Administrator so that he may fix the problem.

column6: TNS:protocol adapter not loaded
column7: On some platforms (such as OS/2) protocol adapters are loaded at run-time. If the shared library (or DLL) for the protocol adapter has not been loaded, then this error is returned.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. The trace file will have the name of the shared library (or DLL) that has not been loaded.

column6: database link type is invalid for the ALTER DATABASE statement
column7: The database link name you specified on the ALTER DATABASE statement is not an ROM: link. You must specify an ROM: link when using the ALTER DATABASE statement to mount or open a secondary database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-issue the ALTER DATABASE statement using a valid ROM: link to the database you want to mount or open. If a valid ROM: link does not exist, create one using the CREATE DATABASE LINK command. See your documentation for Oracle security-related products for more information about creating database links using the ROM: link type.

column6: syntax error in database link's connect %s
column7: The connect string in the CREATE DATABASE LINK statement has a syntactical error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the database link and re-create it using valid syntax. See Oracle8i SQL Reference for more information about the connect string portion of the CREATE DATABASE LINK statement.

column6: logon to database (link name %s) denied
column7: There are several possible causes for this error. First, you can get this error if your username (and password, if you are using database instead of operating system authentication) in the secondary database are not identical to your username (and password) in the primary database. Second, you can get this error if your username in the secondary database is invalid (has not been created). Third, you can get this error if the username/password combination specified in the connect string of the database link definition is invalid (either not created or has an invalid password).
column8: From Oracle doc: In the first case, ensure that the secondary database contains a username (and password, if you are using database authentication) identical to the one you are using in the primary database. In general, you should always use operating system authentication in Trusted Oracle (see the your documentation for Oracle security-related products for more information about the advantages of operating system authentication). In the second case, ensure that your username in the secondary database has been created. In the third case, ensure that the username specified in the connect string has been created in the secondary database.

column6: database (link name %s) is already mounted
column7: You are attempting to mount a secondary database that has already been mounted by your instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: The database is already mounted, so you need not take additional action to mount it. To establish access, use the ALTER DATABASE linkname OPEN command to open the database.

column6: database (link name %s) is already open
column7: You are attempting to open a secondary database that is already open.
column8: From Oracle doc: The database is open and you need not take additional action to establish access.

column6: database (link name %s) is not open and AUTO_MOUNTING=FALSE
column7: The secondary database that your instance is attempting to mount is not open and automatic mounting has not been enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Manually mount and open the secondary database using ALTER DATABASE linkname with the OPEN and MOUNT options. Alternately, to allow your instance to automatically mount and open secondary databases, set the AUTO_MOUNTING parameter in the parameter file to TRUE.

column6: unable to mount database (link name %s)
column7: This message should be accompanied by additional error messages that indicate the cause of the problem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Follow the steps outlined in the accompanying error messages to resolve the problem.

column6: unable to open database (link name %s)
column7: This message should be accompanied by additional error messages that indicate the cause of the problem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Follow the steps outlined in the accompanying error messages to resolve the problem.

column6: cannot use the ROM: link type on a private database link
column7: You can only specify the ROM: link type on a public, not a private, database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine if there is an existing public database link to the secondary database. If not, and if you wish to establish public access to the secondary database, create a public database link to the secondary database using the CREATE DATABASE LINK command.

column6: database %s is closing immediately; no operations are permitted
column7: The database you attempted to access is closing, so your operation has been terminated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the database has been reopened, or contact the database administrator.

column6: database %s is closed; no operations are permitted
column7: The database you attempted to access is closed, so your operation has been terminated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the database is reopened, or contact the database administrator.

column6: database (link name %s) is not mounted
column7: An attempt was made to open a database that has not been mounted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount the database with the ALTER DATABASE linkname MOUNT command, then re-attempt to open the database.

column6: database (link name %s) is still open
column7: An attempt was made to dismount a database that is still open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close the database with the ALTER DATABASE linkname CLOSE command, then re-attempt to dismount the database.

column6: database (link name %s) is not open
column7: An attempt was made to close a database that is not open.
column8: From Oracle doc: The database is closed; you can proceed with dismounting it.

column6: cannot login to database (link name %s)
column7: An attempt was made to login while another user is mounting or dismounting the same database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to see if the database is in the middle of being mounted or opened and try your login again once the database is accessible.

column6: maximum number of open mounts exceeded
column7: The number specified on the OPEN_MOUNTS parameter in the parameter file exceeds the maximum allowed (255).
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of this parameter so that it reflects the actual number of possible open mounts to secondary databases. This must be less than 255.

column6: open mounts exceeds limit set on the OPEN_MOUNTS parameter
column7: The number of currently open mounts exceeds the value you specified on the OPEN_MOUNTS parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of the OPEN_MOUNTS parameter so that it accommodates the maximum possible number of open mounts to secondary databases.

column6: user %s lacks CREATE SESSION privilege in database link (linkname %s)
column7: There are several possible causes for this message: First, you will get this message if your username in the second database specified was not granted the CREATE SESSION system privilege. Second, you will get this message if the username specified in the connect string of the database link definition was not granted the CREATE SESSION system privilege.
column8: From Oracle doc: The action you take depends upon the cause of the message: In the first case, ensure that your username in the secondary database was granted the CREATE SESSION system privilege. In the second case, ensure the username specified in the connect string of the database link definition was granted the CREATE SESSION system privilege in the secondary database.

column6: database link being dropped is still mounted
column7: An attempt was made to drop a ROM: database link that was still mounted and/or opened.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close and dismount the database and then re-issue the drop statement.

column6: cannot create view using a remote object which has a remote object reference
column7: An attempt was made to create a view which references a remote object which, in turn, references an object on another database. Since the view that would have been created references a remote object, that object cannot reference an object on another database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different object to reference in your view or change the remote object so that it does not reference another database.

column6: object %s.%s@%s is invalid
column7: An attempt was made to reference (compile against) an object of a secondary database but the object is invalid and the system cannot validate or recompile it because it is in a secondary database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Manually recompile the invalid object in the secondary database.

column6: secondary stored object cannot reference remote object
column7: An attempt was made to either select from a remote view or execute a remote procedure which references an object on another database. Since the remote view or procedure is on a secondary database, an additional reference to another database cannot be done.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different object to reference or change the remote view or procedure so that it does not reference another database.

column6: secondary object being dropped
column7: An attempt was made to access a object (for example, a table or view) on a secondary database that was in the process of being dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Repeat the operation. If you receive this message again, try to access the object from the secondary database. If you receive an internal error or a trace file, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: DBLOW is not a valid operating system label
column7: The operating system label corresponding to DBLOW has become invalid due to a change in operating system label definitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the operating system facilities to restore the definition of this label, or change the value of DBLOW to a valid label. To change the value of DBLOW, you must mount the database and switch to OSMAC mode.

column6: DBHIGH is not a valid operating system label
column7: The operating system label corresponding to DBHIGH has become invalid due to a change in operating system label definitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the operating system facilities to restore the definition of this label, or change the value of DBHIGH to a valid label. To change the value of DBHIGH, you must mount the database and switch to OSMAC mode.

column6: file: %s
column7: Reporting file name for detail of another message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the message stack for additional detail.

column6: file label (%s) must be equal to DBHIGH (%s)
column7: An Oracle file was found to have a label that does not match the operating system equivalent of DBHIGH. This may be caused if DBHIGH has been changed, or if the file has been relabeled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either relabel the file so that its label matches DBHIGH, or alter DBHIGH so that it matches the label on the file.

column6: device low (%s) must be dominated by DBLOW (%s)
column7: A Oracle file was found on a device with an authorized range insufficient to handle the lowest labeled data in the file. DBLOW must always dominate the minimum device label.
column8: From Oracle doc: Lower the authorized minimum device label or move the file to a different device.

column6: device high (%s) must dominate DBHIGH (%s)
column7: An Oracle file was found on a device with an authorized range insufficient to handle the highest labeled data in the file. DBHIGH must always be dominated by the maximum device label.
column8: From Oracle doc: Raise the authorized maximum device label or move the file to a different device.

column6: must be at DBHIGH (%s) in OS to add files to a tablespace
column7: A file was added to a new or existing tablespace by a user whose operating system label was not equal to DBHIGH.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log in to the operating system at DBHIGH to add the file. If you are creating a new tablespace, set your session label to the label at which you want the tablespace to be created, then create the tablespace. If you are adding a file to an existing tablespace, set your session label to match the creation label of the tablespace, then alter the tablespace See the your documentation for Oracle security-related products for more detailed information about creating and altering tablespaces.

column6: cannot insert or update the ROWLABEL column of a view
column7: An attempt was made to insert into or update the ROWLABEL column of a view. Trusted Oracle does not allow you to modify the ROWLABEL column of a view.
column8: From Oracle doc: While you cannot modify the ROWLABEL column of a view, you can modify the ROWLABEL column in the base table(s) of the view. Use the INSERT or UPDATE commands to modify the base tables(s); consequently, this modifies the view.

column6: tablespace previously existed at another label (%s)
column7: A tablespace by this name was previously created and dropped at another label. Part of the dictionary entry for the old tablespace remains, and the new tablespace is attempting to reuse the old entry.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either re-create the tablespace at the original label or choose a new name for this tablespace.

column6: DBLOW cannot be null in DBMS MAC mode
column7: The database was started in DBMS MAC mode before resetting DBLOW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the database in OS MAC mode and supply valid values for both DBHIGH and DBLOW before starting up in DBMS MAC mode.

column6: DBHIGH cannot be null in DBMS MAC mode
column7: The database was started in DBMS MAC mode before resetting DBHIGH.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the database in OS MAC mode and supply valid values for both DBHIGH and DBLOW before starting up in DBMS MAC mode.

column6: DBHIGH must dominate DBLOW
column7: DBHIGH does not dominate DBLOW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the database in OS MAC mode and supply valid values for DBHIGH and DBLOW before starting up in DBMS MAC mode.

column6: Cannot raise DBLOW above %s
column7: You tried raise DBLOW above its current value. DBLOW can only be lowered; it cannot be raised.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to raise DBLOW.

column6: Cannot lower DBHIGH below %s
column7: An attempt was made to lower DBHIGH below its current value. DBHIGH can only be raised.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to lower DBHIGH.

column6: must be DBHIGH (%s) to startup database
column7: An attempt was made to open a database while at an operating system label not equal to DBHIGH.
column8: From Oracle doc: Login at DBHIGH to start the database.

column6: session label must dominate the creation label of role %s
column7: An attempt was made to grant a privilege to a role while at a label that does not dominate the role's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate the role's creation label in order to grant a privilege to the role.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the role and perform the grant while at a label that dominates the creation label of the role.

column6: label of audit must dominate user
column7: An attempt was made to set statement audit options for a user while at a label that does not dominate the user's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate the user's creation label in order to set statement audit options for the user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the user and set the statement audit option while at a label that dominates the creation label of the user.

column6: label of index must equal table
column7: An attempt was made to create an index on a table while at a label that does not match the table's creation label. Your DBMS label must match the table's creation label in order to create an index on the table. If the table was created at DBHIGH or DBLOW, your label must be set to DBHIGH or DBLOW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the table and create the index while at a label that matches the creation label of the table.

column6: label of column must equal table
column7: An attempt was made to add a column to a table while at a label that does not match the table's creation label. Your DBMS label must match the table's creation label in order to add a column to the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the table and add the column while at a label that matches the creation label of the table.

column6: label of stored object must dominate referenced object %s
column7: An attempt was made to create or you issued a statement that tried to create a stored object (view, procedure, function, trigger) which references some object while at a label that does not dominate the referenced object's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate the creation labels of all referenced objects in order to create a stored object. While the referenced object may be visible due to enabled MAC privileges, MAC privileges cannot be used to create the stored object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation labels of the referenced objects and create the stored object while at a label that dominates the creation labels of all referenced objects.

column6: label of grant must dominate object
column7: An attempt was made to grant privileges on an object while at a label that does not dominate the object's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate the object's creation label in order to grant privileges on the object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the object and perform the grant while at a label that dominates the creation label of the object.

column6: label of grant must dominate grantee %s
column7: An attempt was made to grant privileges to a user while at a label that does not dominate the user's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate the user's creation label in order to grant privileges to the user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the user and grant the privileges while at a label that dominates the creation label of the user.

column6: label of constraint must equal table
column7: An attempt was made to add a constraint to a table while at a label that does not match the table's creation label. Your DBMS label must match the creation label of the table in order to add a constraint to the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the table and add the constraint while at a label that matches the creation label of the table.

column6: label of object must dominate tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to create an object in a tablespace while at a label that does not dominate the tablespace's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate the tablespace's creation label in order to create an object in the tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the tablespace and create the object while at a label that dominates the creation label of the tablespace.

column6: label of table must dominate cluster
column7: An attempt was made to create a table in a cluster while at a label that does not dominate the cluster's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate the cluster's creation label in order to create a table in the cluster.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the cluster and create the table while at a label that dominates the creation label of the cluster.

column6: label of user must dominate default or temporary tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to assign a user a default or temporary tablespace when the user's creation label did not dominate the tablespace's creation label. The user's creation label must dominate the tablespace's creation label in order for the default or temporary tablespace to be assigned to the user. Your DBMS label must dominate both the user's and the tablespace's creation labels in order to assign the tablespace to the user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the default or temporary tablespaces and create the user so that the user's creation label dominates the creation label of the tablespaces.

column6: label of object must dominate schema
column7: An attempt was made to create an object in a schema while at a label that does not dominate the schema's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate the schema's creation label in order to create an object in the schema.
