column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the schema and create the object while at a label that dominates the creation label of the schema.

column6: insufficient MAC privileges
column7: An attempt was made to write to an object when you did not have sufficient privileges. You may have sufficient privileges to read the object, but do not have MAC write access to the object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either retry the operation at the label of the object or ask the database administrator for sufficient MAC privileges to write the object. See the your documentation for Oracle security-related products for more information on MAC privileges.

column6: label of comment must equal table or view
column7: An attempt was made to comment a table or view while at a label that does not match the table's or view's creation label. Your DBMS label must match the table's or view's creation label in order to comment the table or view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the table or view and add the comment while at a label that matches the creation label of the table or view.

column6: label of trigger must equal table
column7: An attempt was made to create or you issued a statement that tried to create a trigger on a table while at a label that does not match the table's creation label. Your DBMS label must match the table's creation label in order to create the trigger on the table. While the table may be visible due to enabled MAC privileges, MAC privileges cannot be used to create a trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the table and create the trigger while at a label that matches the creation label of the table.

column6: label of user must dominate default profile
column7: An attempt was made to assign a user a default profile when the user's creation label did not dominate the default profile's creation label. In order to assign a default profile to a user, the user's creation label must dominate the default profile's creation label. Your DBMS label must dominate both the user's and the default profile's creation labels in order to assign the user the default profile.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the default profile and create the user so that the user's creation label dominates the creation label of the default profile.

column6: label of grant must equal label of procedure
column7: An attempt was made to assign MAC privileges to a procedure at a label other than the creation label of the procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Grant MAC privileges to the procedure at the procedure's creation label.

column6: label of default role %s must dominate user
column7: An attempt was made to assign a default role to a user when the default role's creation label did not dominate the user's creation label. The default role's creation label must dominate the user's creation label. Your DBMS label also must dominate both the role's and user's creation label in order to assign a user a role.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation labels of the user and role and assign only those roles whose creation labels dominate the creation label of the user.

column6: label of child record must dominate parent
column7: An attempt was made to insert a child record with a label that does not dominate the corresponding parent record's label or update a parent record such that the child records would not dominate the corresponding parent's label. The label of a child record must always dominate that of its parent record.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the label of the parent record and insert the child record while at a label that dominates the label of the parent record or update the label of the child record before updating the parent record so that the child can still dominate the parent after the update.

column6: label of package body must equal package
column7: An attempt was made to create a package body while at a label that does not match the corresponding package's creation label. Your DBMS label must match the package's creation label in order to create a package body.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the creation label of the package and create the package body while at a label that matches the creation label of the package.

column6: package body must exist to grant MAC privileges
column7: An attempt was made to grant MAC privileges to a package when the package body does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the package body for the package and then re-attempt the grant.

column6: cannot write down to a database at a lower label
column7: An attempt was made to perform a write operation in a secondary database. You can only perform write operations in your primary database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect directly to the secondary database to perform the operation.

column6: insufficient privileges to validate constraint on all rows
column7: You must have access to all rows in a table in order to attempt to enable a constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either enable MAC privileges so that you can read all rows in the table, or downgrade all rows in the table so you can read them. Then enable the constraint.

column6: cannot modify ROWLABEL column
column7: An attempt was made to modify the definition of the ROWLABEL column with the ALTER command. For example, you may have tried to lengthen the ROWLABEL column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Although the value of the ROWLABEL column can be changed, the ROWLABEL column definition cannot be modified.

column6: database has not been mounted in read-compatible mode
column7: The requested secondary database was not started in read-compatible mode. In order for a database to be mounted by a higher level read-secure instance, the database must be mounted by its primary instance in read-compatible mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the DB_MOUNT_MODE parameter to READ_COMPATIBLE in the secondary database and start the secondary database.

column6: grant already exists at a different label
column7: An attempt was made to grant a privilege that was previously granted at a different label.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check USER_SYS_GRANTS or USER_OBJ_GRANTS to identify the label of the privilege's previous grant. If you want to execute the grant at the new label, revoke the old grant and regrant the privilege while at the new label.

column6: must be at same label as user to modify default roles
column7: An attempt was made to modify a user's default roles while at a label that does not match the user's creation label. Your DBMS label must match the user's creation label in order to alter a user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the ALL_USERS view to determine the creation label of the user and modify the user's default roles while at a label that matches the creation label of the user.

column6: audit option already exists at a different label
column7: An attempt was made to audit an event that was previously audited at a different label.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the DBA_STMT_AUDIT_OPTS or DBA_PRIV_AUDIT_OPTS dictionary views to identify the label of the previous audit statement. If you want to audit the event at the new label, stop the old audit (using the NOAUDIT statement) and re-audit the event while at the new label.

column6: file label is lower than instance label
column7: An attempt was made to reuse a file with a label different than the database instance label.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the message stack for the file name. Remove the file or relabel it to match the database instance label.

column6: file label is higher than instance label
column7: An attempt was made to reuse a file with a label different than the database instance label. You can only reuse files labeled at or below the instance label.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the message stack for the file name. Remove the file or relabel it to match the database instance label.

column6: non-secure protocol used; connection denied
column7: An attempt was made to connect to Trusted Oracle7 with a networking protocol that was not secure. You must use a secure networking protocol to connect via a remote location.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either connect to the database with a secure networking protocol or log in directly to the database.

column6: greatest lower bound resulted in an invalid operating system label
column7: An attempt was made to do an operation that generated a greatest lower bound (GLB) label which is not a valid label on your operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the message stack for a more specific messages. See your installation or user's guide for information on invalid label generation. See the your documentation for Oracle security-related products for information on greatest lower bound (GLB) functions.

column6: least upper bound resulted in an invalid operating system label
column7: An attempt was made to do an operation that generated a least upper bound (LUB) label which is not a valid label on your operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the message stack for a more specific messages. See your installation or user's guide for information on invalid label generation. See the your documentation for Oracle security-related products for information on least upper bound (LUB) functions.

column6: internal buffer overflow during label translation
column7: An internal buffer used to translate labels overflowed. A possible cause could be a format mask you specified is too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try using a smaller format mask.

column6: format mask for TO_LABEL or TO_CHAR function is invalid
column7: The format mask that you specified did not contain valid format codes for label conversion.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the your documentation for Oracle security-related products for valid format codes. Correct the format mask and reattempt the operation.

column6: error initializing label context
column7: An internal error occurred that prevented initialization of the label context. This may be caused by internal memory corruption or a software defect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: binary label could not be translated into a %s
column7: The binary label that you specified for conversion is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the source of the binary label. Execute the conversion with a valid binary label.

column6: input %s does not contain expected punctuation or literal
column7: The punctuation you supplied in the label string is inconsistent with the format you specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the punctuation in the label string or format, whichever is appropriate, and reissue the statement.

column6: invalid internal format code found
column7: In performing the requested translation, a format code was invalid. This message may result from memory corruption.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: duplicate format code specified in %s to label conversion
column7: You may not specify duplicate string input when converting to a binary label. For example, 'SEN SENLEV' is an invalid format mask.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the format mask and input string to specify a format code only once.

column6: invalid length for MLSLABEL bind variable
column7: A bind variable of type MLSLABEL is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult your documentation for proper datatype lengths.

column6: the input %s could not be translated into a binary label
column7: The input string you specified is not a valid binary label on your operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the input string, change any components so that they form a valid label, and retry the operation.

column6: maximum number of columns in a Trusted Oracle table is 253
column7: A CREATE or ALTER TABLE statement tried to add more than 253 columns (not counting ROWLABEL) to a table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify no more than 253 columns in your CREATE or ALTER TABLE command.

column6: the value %s for the MLS_LABEL_FORMAT parameter is not valid
column7: The value for the MLS_LABEL_FORMAT parameter you specified does not contain a valid format mask. You must have a valid MLS_LABEL_FORMAT parameter for the database to start.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change this parameter setting in your INIT.ORA file to a correct value.

column6: invalid binary label
column7: You provided a binary label in an OCI program's bind statement that was not a valid operating system label.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the invalid binary label with one that is valid.

column6: process label could not be found
column7: An error was encountered in translating the your operating system process label into a label number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the message stack for a more specific message.

column6: cannot log in below DBLOW (%s)
column7: An attempt was made to log in at a label dominated by DBLOW. You can only log in to Trusted Oracle between DBLOW and DBHIGH, inclusive.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either log in at a higher label, or lower DBLOW.

column6: cannot log in above DBHIGH (%s)
column7: An attempt was made to log in at a label dominating DBHIGH. You can only log in to Trusted Oracle between DBLOW and DBHIGH, inclusive.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either log in at a lower label, or raise DBHIGH.

column6: cannot insert label below DBLOW (%s)
column7: An attempt was made to explicitly insert a value below DBLOW into the ROWLABEL column, or tried to specify a value lower than DBLOW in a column of datatype MLSLABEL. Any label you insert into Trusted Oracle table must fall between DBLOW and DBHIGH, inclusive.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either lower the value of DBLOW, or specify a higher label on the INSERT or UPDATE statement.

column6: cannot insert label above DBHIGH (%s)
column7: An attempt was made to explicitly insert a value above DBHIGH into the ROWLABEL column, or tried to specify a value higher than DBHIGH in a column of datatype MLSLABEL. Any label you insert into a Trusted Oracle table must fall between DBLOW and DBHIGH, inclusive.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either raise the value of DBHIGH, or specify a lower label on the INSERT or UPDATE statement.

column6: secondary database changing between OS MAC and DBMS MAC modes
column7: An attempt was made to access a secondary database while the secondary database was in the process of changing between OS MAC and DBMS MAC modes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-attempt the operation after the change is complete.

column6: cannot find file label for %s
column7: An error was encountered while reading the label of the specified file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the message stack for an operating system message.

column6: insufficient privileges to set label to DBHIGH or DBLOW
column7: You must connect to Trusted Oracle using the INTERNAL keyword in order to set your label to DBHIGH or DBLOW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect to Trusted Oracle using INTERNAL, then set your label to DBHIGH or DBLOW. If you do not have privileges to connect using INTERNAL, contact your database administrator.

column6: session label must be equal to %s
column7: An attempt was made to log in to an OS MAC database at other than the database label.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log in from an OS process at the specified label.

column6: insufficient MAC privileges to alter your session label
column7: An attempt was made to alter your session label without the appropriate MAC privileges. You must have the appropriate MAC privileges in order to dynamically change your session label. Note that MAC privileges are not available in an OS MAC database, only in a DBMS MAC database.
column8:
From Oracle doc: To change your session label, do one of the following: 

Change your operating system label. This is your only alternative in OS MAC mode. This can be done by logging out of the DBMS, changing your operating system label within the operating system, and then logging back into the DBMS. Note that, if you are logging into an OS MAC database, your operating system label must match the label of your primary database. 

Obtain the appropriate MAC privileges that allow you to dynamically change your session label within the DBMS. You need the READUP and WRITEUP MAC privileges to raise your session label, and the WRITEDOWN MAC privilege to lower your label, and all three to alter your label laterally. Note that changing your session label does not effect your operating system label.

column6: cannot alter DBMS label below username creation label (%s)
column7: An attempt was made to alter your DBMS label to a label lower than that at which your username was created. You can only alter your DBMS label between your username's creation label and DBHIGH, within the limits of your clearance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either do not alter your DBMS label below the specified label, or contact the database administrator to re-create your username at lower level.

column6: cannot change MAC mode when mounted in READ_COMPATIBLE mode
column7: An attempt was made to change between OS and DB MAC mode while the database was mounted in READ_COMPATIBLE mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the DB_MOUNT_MODE parameter to NORMAL and restart the database.

column6: cannot mount secondary database labeled above DBLOW
column7: The secondary database that you attempted to mount is labeled above DBLOW in the primary database. You can only mount a secondary database if that DBHIGH in that database (or, in OS MAC mode, the label of the database) is lower than DBLOW in your primary database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine if you really want to establish a read-secure link between the two databases. If so, relabel the secondary database so that DBHIGH in the secondary database is lower than DBLOW in the primary database.

column6: multi-threaded server cannot be used with Trusted Oracle
column7: The MTS_DISPATCHERS parameter is set in the initialization file, which initiated the configuration of the multi-threaded server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the MTS_DISPATCHERS parameter from the initialization file and restart the instance.

column6: TNS:listener failed to start a dedicated server process
column7: The process of starting up a dedicated server process failed. The executable could not be found or the environment may be set up incorrectly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Turn on tracing at the ADMIN level and reexecute the operation. Verify that the ORACLE Server executable is present and has execute permissions enabled. Ensure that the ORACLE environment is specified correctly in LISTENER.ORA. The Oracle Protocol Adapter that is being called may not be installed on the local hard drive. Please check that the correct Protocol Adapter are successfully linked. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:listener received no CONNECT_DATA from client
column7: No CONNECT_DATA was passed to the listener.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the service name resolved from TNSNAMES.ORA has the CONNECT_DATA component of the connect descriptor.

column6: TNS:listener was not given the SID in CONNECT_DATA
column7: The SID was missing from the CONNECT_DATA.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the connect descriptor corresponding to the service name in TNSNAMES.ORA has an SID component in the CONNECT_DATA.

column6: TNS: listener could not resolve SID given in connect descriptor
column7: The SID in the CONNECT_DATA was not found in the listener's tables. This error will be returned if the database instance has not registered with the listener; the instance may need to be started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure that the SID specified is correct. The SIDs that are currently registered with the listener can be obtained by typing "LSNRCTL SERVICES ". These SIDs correspond to SID_NAMEs in TNSNAMES.ORA, or DB_NAMES in the initialization file.

column6: TNS:listener failed to redirect client to service handler
column7: The dispatcher terminated unexpectedly
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt to connect again and if the same error occurs, contact the DBA to check the state of the dispatchers for this SID. If the problem persists, turn on tracing in the listener to determine the TNS error caused by the redirect.

column6: TNS:database lacks resources to handle the request for this SID
column7: The dispatchers are busy handling other requests.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the DBA to increase the number of dispatchers servicing this SID.

column6: TNS:service handler found but it is not accepting connections
column7: The dispatchers are busy handling other requests and they notified the listener that they are temporarily busy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt the connection again. If error persists, ask the DBA to increase the number of dispatchers.

column6: TNS:service handler found but it has not registered a redirect address
column7: The dispatcher just came up and has not had time yet to register the address that a client should be redirected to.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt the connection again. If error persists, ask the DBA to increase the number of dispatchers.

column6: TNS:service handler found but it has registered for a different protocol
column7: The dispatchers registered for this service are connected to the listener by way of a different network protocol than that of the client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the DBA to register a dispatcher on your protocol.

column6: TNS:listener does not currently know of service requested in connect descriptor
column7: The listener received a request to establish a connection to a database or other service. The connect descriptor received by the listener specified a service name for a service (usually a database service) that either has not yet dynamically registered with the listener or has not been statically configured for the listener. This may be a temporary condition such as after the listener has started, but before the database instance has registered with the listener.
column8: - Wait a moment and try to connect a second time.;- Check which services are currently known by the listener by executing: lsnrctl services ;- Check that the SERVICE_NAME parameter in the connect descriptor of the net service name used specifies a service

column6: TNS:listener: all appropriate instances are blocking new connections
column7: All instances supporting the service requested by the client reported that they were blocking the new connections. This condition may be temporary, such as at instance startup.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt the connection again. If error persists, then contact the administrator to check the status of the instances.

column6: TNS:cannot allocate memory
column7: Sufficient memory could not be allocated to perform the desired activity.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either free some resource for TNS, or add more memory to the machine. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation.

column6: TNS:invalid argument
column7: An internal function received an invalid parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:illegal ADDRESS parameters
column7: An illegal set of protocol adapter parameters was specified. In some cases, this error is returned when a connection cannot be made to the protocol transport.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the destination can be reached using the specified protocol. Check the parameters within the ADDRESS section of TNSNAMES.ORA. Legal ADDRESS parameter formats may be found in the Oracle operating system specific documentation for your platform. Protocols that resolve names at the transport layer (such as DECnet object names) are vulnerable to this error if not properly configured or names are misspelled.

column6: TNS:operation not supported
column7: An internal function received a request to perform an operation that is not supported (on this machine).
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:operation timed out
column7: The requested connection could not be completed within the timeout period specified by the CONNECT_TIMEOUT parameter in listener.ora. This error arises from the tnslsnr.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either reconfigure CONNECT_TIMEOUT to be 0, which means wait indefinitely, or reconfigure CONNECT_TIMEOUT to be some higher value. Or, if the timeout is unacceptably long, turn on tracing for further information.

column6: TNS:operation would block
column7: An internal operation did not commence because to do so would block the current process and the user has requested that operations be non-blocking.
column8: From Oracle doc: None needed; this is an information message.

column6: TNS:connection closed
column7: "End of file" condition has been reached; partner has disconnected.
column8: From Oracle doc: None needed; this is an information message.

column6: TNS:no such protocol adapter
column7: The protocol adapter requested (by way of the "(PROTOCOL=..)" keyword-value pair in a TNS address) is unknown. If the supplied address is typographically correct then the protocol adaptor is not installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Install the protocol adapter or correct typographical error, as appropriate. Note: if the supplied address was derived from resolving the service name, check the address in the appropriate file (TNSNAMES.ORA, LISTENER.ORA or TNSNET.ORA).

column6: TNS:buffer over- or under-flow
column7: Buffer too small for incoming data or too large for outgoing data.
column8: From Oracle doc: This restriction (which is associated with CONNECT DATA) is not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation; contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:internal limit restriction exceeded
column7: Too many TNS connections open simultaneously.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for connections to close and re-try.

column6: TNS:no listener
column7: The connection request could not be completed because the listener is not running.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the supplied destination address matches one of the addresses used by the listener - compare the TNSNAMES.ORA entry with the appropriate LISTENER.ORA file (or TNSNAV.ORA if the connection is to go by way of an Interchange). Start the listener on the remote machine.

column6: TNS:address already in use
column7: Specified listener address is already being used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Start your listener with a unique address.

column6: TNS:destination host unreachable
column7: Contact can not be made with remote party.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the network driver is functioning and the network is up.

column6: TNS:contexts have different wait/test functions
column7: Two protocol adapters have conflicting wait/test functions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: Connect failed because target host or object does not exist
column7: The address specified is not valid, or the program being connected to does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the ADDRESS parameters have been entered correctly; the most likely incorrect parameter is the node name. Ensure that the executable for the server exists (perhaps "oracle" is missing.) If the protocol is TCP/IP, edit the TNSNAMES.ORA file to change the host name to a numeric IP address and try again.

column6: TNS:permission denied
column7: User has insufficient privileges to perform the requested operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Acquire necessary privileges and try again.

column6: TNS:lost contact
column7: Partner has unexpectedly gone away, usually during process start-up.
column8: From Oracle doc: Investigate partner application for abnormal termination. On an Interchange, this can happen if the machine is overloaded.

column6: TNS:incomplete read or write
column7: A data send or receive failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:operating system resource quota exceeded
column7: The current user has exceeded the allotted resource assigned in the operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Acquire more operating system resource, or perform a different function.

column6: TNS:syntax error
column7: The supplied connect descriptor contains illegal syntax.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the connect descriptor in TNSNAMES.ORA.

column6: TNS:missing keyword
column7: The supplied connect descriptor is missing one or more TNS keywords.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax, and ensure all required keywords are present.

column6: TNS:operation was interrupted
column7: An internal operation was interrupted and could not complete.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:current operation is still in progress
column7: An internal operation is still in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:permission denied
column7: User has insufficient privileges to perform the requested operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Acquire necessary privileges and try again.

column6: TNS:no caller
column7: TNS detected an incoming connect request but there was no caller.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:protocol adapter not loadable
column7: On some platforms (such as OS/2) protocol adapters are loaded at run-time. If the shared library (or DLL) for the protocol adapter is missing or one of its supporting libraries is missing then this error is returned.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracin and reexecute the operation. The trace file will include the name of the shared library (or DLL) that could not be loaded.

column6: TNS:protocol adapter not loaded
column7: On some platforms (such as OS/2) protocol adapters are loaded at run-time. If the shared library (or DLL) for the protocol adapter has not been loaded, then this error is returned.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. The trace file will have the name of the shared library (or DLL) that has not been loaded.

column6: TNS:protocol adapter error
column7: A generic protocol adapter error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check addresses used for proper protocol specification. Before reporting this error, look at the error stack and check for lower level transport errors.For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. Turn off tracing when the operation is complete.

column6: TNS:unknown error
column7: A generic protocol error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation.

column6: TNS:bad global handle
column7: Internal error - bad 'gbh' argument passed to TNS from caller. System may have been linked with old libraries.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:connection refused
column7: The connect request was denied by the remote user (or TNS software).
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation.

column6: TNS:protocol error
column7: An unexpected TNS protocol error has occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:packet checksum failure
column7: The data received is not the same as the data sent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt the transaction again. If the error is persistent, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation.

column6: TNS:packet reader failure
column7: An error occurred during a data receive.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:packet writer failure
column7: An error occurred during a data send.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:redirection denied
column7: The connect request failed because it would have required redirection and the caller has requested no redirections.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:invalid operation
column7: An internal function received an invalid request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:no reader
column7: A send operation has been requested but partner has already disconnected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:data truncation
column7: A receive operation has completed with insufficient data to satisfy the user's request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:connection not bequeathable
column7: An attempt to hand-off a connection from one process to another has failed because the protocol provider does not support it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:no I/O buffer
column7: An attempt to perform an I/O operation failed because no buffer was available.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:event signal failure
column7: The TNS software is unable to signal an event occurrence.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:bad packet
column7: An ill-formed packet has been detected by the TNS software.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:no registered connection
column7: An attempt to solicit network event activity has failed because no connections are registered for event notification.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:no confirmation
column7: TNS is unable to get requested confirmation acknowledgment from remote partner.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:internal inconsistency
column7: TNS has detected an internal inconsistency.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation and contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:connect descriptor already in use
column7: Internal error - illegal use of connect descriptor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:banner registration failed
column7: The registration of a product banner with the Oracle server failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is an error which is not normally visible externally. Enable tracing and attempt to repeat the error. If it occurs again, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:cryptographic checksum mismatch
column7: The data received is not the same as the data sent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt the transaction again. If error persists, check (and correct) the integrity of your physical connection.

column6: TNS: %s open failed
column7: The creation of a string in ORACLE NLS format failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is an internal error, enable tracing and attempt to repeat the error. If it occurs again, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:information flags check failed
column7: The TNS information flags set by the process prior to connection negotiation were not present after the negotiation was finished.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is an internal error. Enable tracing and attempt to repeat the error. If it occurs again, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:operation is not portable
column7: Attempted operton is not portable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:connection is busy
column7: Attempted operation failed because it conflicts with an ongoing action or status of the connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:preempt error
column7: A request to service an event failed because no event notification has yet been posted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:no event signals
column7: The TNS software is unable to enable event signals.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:bad `what' type
column7: The operation failed because the type of data specified is unknown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:versions are incompatible
column7: The two machines are running incompatible versions of TNS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the version numbers, and upgrade the machine with the smaller one.

column6: TNS:unable to grant requested service
column7: The connect request failed because requested service could not be provided by the local TNS software.
column8: From Oracle doc: If appropriate, reexecute with reduced service requirements.

column6: TNS:requested characteristic not available
column7: The connect request failed because a requested transport characteristic could not be supported by the remote TNS software.
column8: From Oracle doc: If appropriate, reexecute with reduced requirements.

column6: TNS:event notifications are not homogeneous
column7: An attempt to register a connection for event notification failed because the event notification type conflicts with existing registrations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation and contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:operation is illegal in this state
column7: Connection is half-duplex and a full-duplex operation was attempted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation. If error persists, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:connection is already registered
column7: An attempt to register a connection for event notification failed because the connection is already registered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation and contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:missing argument
column7: An operation failed because an argument was missing"
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation and contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:bad event type
column7: An attempt to register a connection for event notification failed because the event type is unknown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation and contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:no event callbacks
column7: An attempt to register a connection for event notification failed because asynchronous callbacks are not available.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation and contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: TNS:no event test
column7: An attempt to register a connection for event notification failed because the ability to test for events is not available.
column8: From Oracle doc: Not normally visible to the user. For further details, turn on tracing and reexecute the operation and contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: Native service operation not supported
column7: An operation requested by a user is not supported by the native services component.
column8: From Oracle doc: This may be an internal error if the operation should have been supported.

column6: Username retrieval failed
column7: The authentication service failed to retrieve the name of a user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine which routine is failing.

column6: Role fetch failed
column7: The authentication service failed to retrieve one of the user's roles.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine which routine is failing.

column6: No shared authentication services
column7: The list of authentication services specified by the user does not match those supported by the process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify another list or relink the executable with the desired services.

column6: Memory allocation failed
column7: Process was unable to allocate memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Terminate other processes in order to reclaim needed memory.

column6: No authentication adapters available
column7: The executable was not linked with any authentication service adapters but the SQLNET.ORA parameter that determines whether or not authentication is required was set to true.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either disable the parameter or relink the executable with service adapters.

column6: Packet send failed
column7: A process was unable to send a packet to another process. Possible causes are: 1. The other process was terminated. 2. The machine on which the other process is running went down. 3. Some other communications error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the cause is not obvious, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: Packet receive failed
column7: A process was unable to receive a packet from another process. Possible causes are: 1. The other process was terminated. 2. The machine on which the other process is running went down. 3. Some other communications error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the cause is not obvious, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: Credential retrieval failed
column7: The authentication service failed to retrieve the credentials of a user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error.

column6: Authentication service negotiation failed
column7: No match was found between the types of authentication services that the client supports and those that the server is using.
column8: From Oracle doc: Possible solutions: 1. Change the entry in SQLNET.ORA that determines which services are to be used. 2. Relink the client with at least one of the authentication service adapters that the server supports. 3. Relink the server with at least one of the authentication service adapters that the client supports. 4. Disable authentication on both the client and server.

column6: Authentication adapter initialization failed
column7: The function specified in the authentication table entry for the service failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error.

column6: Authentication service failed to initialize
column7: The authentication service failed during initialization.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error.

column6: No session key
column7: A process has no session key associated with it because the authentication service being used does not use one.
column8: From Oracle doc: If a session key is required, use another authentication service.

column6: Client received internal error from server
column7: The client process received an error from the server that indicated that an internal SQL*Net native services error had occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing on both processes and attempt to recreate the problem. If successful in recreating the problem, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: Authentication service initialization failed
column7: The routine called to initialize the authentication adapter failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error. A likely cause is that memory is exhausted.

column6: Parameter does not exist.
column7: A SQLNET.ORA parameter from which a value was needed does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the parameter in the parameter file.

column6: Invalid value specified for boolean parameter
column7: The value specified for a parameter was set to a value other than true/false or on/off.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value of the parameter.

column6: Authentication required
column7: The parameter that controls whether authentication is required was set to true, but the executable does not have an authentication service linked in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either re-link the executable with an authentication service adapter or disable the parameter.

column6: Encryption or data integrity algorithm list empty
column7: A SQL*Net list-of-algorithms parameter was empty, e.g. "()".
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the list to contain the name of at least one installed algorithm, or remove the list entirely if every installed algorithm is acceptable.

column6: Unknown encryption or data integrity algorithm
column7: A SQL*Net list-of-algorithms parameter included an algorithm name that was not recognized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either remove that algorithm name, correct it if it was misspelled, or install the driver for the missing algorithm.

column6: No common encryption or data integrity algorithm
column7: The client and server have no algorithm in common for either encryption or data integrity or both.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose sets of algorithms that overlap. In other words, add one of the client's algorithm choices to the server's list or vice versa.

column6: Encryption or data integrity algorithm unacceptable
column7: The algorithm the server chose to use for encryption or data integrity was not one of the choices acceptable to the client. This is either the result of an internal error, of a network data transmission error, or of deliberate tampering with the transmitted data.
column8: From Oracle doc: For further details, turn on tracing, re-execute the operation, and contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: String truncated
column7: Not enough memory was allocated for a string so it had to be truncated
column8: From Oracle doc: If it is OK that the string is truncated, then it is not an error. Otherwise, call the routine that reported the error again with a larger string buffer.

column6: Authentication control function failed
column7: The control function utilized by the authentication service driver failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error.

column6: Authentication conversion failed
column7: The authentication service was unable to convert the credentials of a user from the format specific to the format into the ORACLE format.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error.

column6: Password check failed
column7: The authentication service being used was unable to verify the provided password.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error.

column6: Cryptographic checksum mismatch
column7: The cryptographic checksum received with a packet of incoming data didn't match the checksum computed by the receiving end. This indicates that the packet was tampered with or otherwise corrupted in transit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look for sources of data corruption, perhaps including deliberate tampering.

column6: No algorithms installed
column7: The near side of the connection required the use of a service (either encryption or checksumming) when no algorithms for that service were installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the "ON" requirement for that service.

column6: Native service required but TNS version is incompatible
column7: A process that is running an earlier version of TNS attempted to connect but the connection failed because the server process required that a native service (authentication, encryption, etc.) be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Relink the calling executable and retry the connection or eliminate the requirement that the service be used on the server side.

column6: Error received from other process
column7: An error was received by one or more services from the process on the other side of the connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error(s). The error(s) is (are) not returned directly because an error generated by a server may not make sense on the client side and vice-versa.

column6: Encryption or crypto-checksumming parameters incompatible
column7: One side of the connection specified "REQUIRED" for encryption or crypto-checksumming, while the other side specified "REJECTED".
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the "REQUIRED" side to "REQUESTED" if the you want encryption or crypto-checksumming to be optional, or change the "REJECTED" side to "ACCEPTED" if you do not want the service to be optional.

column6: Protocol authentication to be used
column7: The SQL*Net authentication service has determined that the SQL*Net transport protocol in use is to be utilized to authenticate a user's identity.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error is used solely to communicate information between the authentication service and the SQL*Net session layer and should not be visible to the user. If the error is seen, contact Worldwide customer support.

column6: proxy ticket retrieval failed
column7: The authentication adapter used by SQL*Net failed to retrieve the credentials needed to authenticate a database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error.

column6: Services required by client not available on the server
column7: Service(s) that was (were) required by the client process were not available on the server process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Configure the server with the services required by the client (best solution) or delete the requirement from the configuration file of the client (least secure).

column6: Services required by server not available on the client
column7: Service(s) that was (were) required by the server process were not available on the client process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Configure the client with the services required by the server (best solution) or delete the requirement from the configuration file of the server (least secure).

column6: NLS %s open failed
column7: A native service was unable to make a string available for use by the National Language Support component.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the National Language Support component has been properly. If it has, enable tracing and report the problem to Customer Support.

column6: Dedicated server: outbound transport protocol different from inbound
column7: The protocol specified for an externally-identified outbound connection from a dedicated server (database link) was not the same as that used for the inbound connection. It is not possible for SQL*Net to authenticate a proxy connection that uses a protocol that is different from that which was used for the connection to the dedicated server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the same protocol in the SQL*Net connect string or alias for the outbound connection as that used for the inbound connection

column6: Shared server: outbound transport protocol different from inbound
column7: The protocol specified for an externally-identified outbound connection from a shared server (database link) was not the same as that used for the inbound connection. It is not possible for SQL*Net to authenticate a proxy connection that uses a protocol that is different from that which was used for the connection to the shared server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the same protocol in the SQL*Net connect string or alias for the outbound connection as that used for the inbound connection

column6: Dedicated server: outbound protocol does not support proxies
column7: The protocol specified to perform an externally-identified proxy connection (database link) from a dedicated server does not support proxy connections.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a protocol in the SQL*Net connect string or alias used for the connection that does support externally-authenticated proxy connections. NOTE: Because of a limitation in SQL*Net, the protocol used for the proxy connection must the same as that used for the connection from the client to the server.

column6: Shared server: outbound protocol does not support proxies
column7: The protocol specified to perform an externally-identified proxy connection (database link) from a shared server does not support proxy connections.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a protocol in the SQL*Net connect string or alias used for the connection that does support externally-authenticated proxy connections. NOTE: Because of a limitation in SQL*Net, the protocol used for the proxy connection must the same as that used for the connection from the client to the server.

column6: Incorrect role password
column7: A password supplied for a role could not be validated by the authentication service.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the correct password.

column6: Shared server: adapter failed to save context
column7: The adapter for the authentication service failed when it tried to save the data needed for proxy connections (database links) through the multi-threaded server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error. Contact Worldwide Customer Support if the reason is not obvious.

column6: Database logon failure
column7: The authentication service adapter in use encountered an error it attempted to validate the logon attempt of a user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error encountered by the adapter.

column6: Dedicated server: context not saved
column7: A connection was marked as being a proxy connection (database link) from a dedicated server but no inbound context was present.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error should not normally be visible to the user. Contact Oracle Customer Support

column6: Shared server: proxy context not saved
column7: A connection was marked as being a proxy connection (database link) from a shared server but no inbound context was present.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error should not normally be visible to the user. Contact Oracle Customer Support

column6: External user name not available yet
column7: The authentication service in use was not able to return the external name of a user of the ORACLE server because it is not available to the service yet.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is just an information message and should not normally be visible to the user. If the error does appear, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: Server received internal error from client
column7: The server process received an error from the client which indicated that an internal SQL*Net native services error had occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing on both processes and attempt to recreate the problem. If the problem recurs, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: Authentication service not supported by database link
column7: The authentication service used by the proxy process (database link) was unable to find the adapter being used by the client in its list of authentication mechanisms.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an authentication adapter that is shared by the client and the server being used for the database link.

column6: Authentication disabled but required
column7: The configuration parameters that control whether SQL*Net authentication is disabled or required were both set to TRUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set one or both of the parameters to FALSE.

column6: Native services disabled by other process but required
column7: The remote process has disabled native services but the local process requires them.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable native services on the remote process or disable them locally.

column6: Native services disabled but required
column7: The process has disabled native services but at least one service is required.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable native services or change the configuration file so that none of the available services are required.

column6: Login failed: the SecurID card does not have a pincode yet
column7: The SecurID card that is used to logon to Oracle, does not have a pincode assigned to it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use one of the programs supplied by Security Dynamics to assign a pincode to the card.

column6: Login failed: the SecurID card is in next PRN mode
column7: The SecurID card and the SecurID server are out of sync and the server requires the next cardcode to re-synchronize the card.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use one of the programs supplied by Security Dynamics to re-synchronize the SecurID card.

column6: encryption/crypto-checksumming: no Diffie-Hellman seed
column7: The "sqlnet.crypto_seed" parameter is missing from the SQLNET.ORA parameters file for SQL*Net.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add this line to SQLNET.ORA: sqlnet.crypto_seed = "randomly-chosen text"

column6: encryption/crypto-checksumming: Diffie-Hellman seed too small
column7: The "sqlnet.crypto_seed" parameter in the SQLNET.ORA parameter file for SQL*Net is too small.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add more randomly-chosen text to it, perhaps using Network Manager.

column6: Native service required remotely but disabled locally
column7: A native service is required by the remote process but native services have been disabled locally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable native services locally or change the configuration parameters on the remote host so that no native services are required.

column6: Invalid command specified for a service
column7: An operation which does not exist was specified for a native service.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is a programming error and should not normally be visible to the user. If the error does appear, contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: Database link failed: credentials expired
column7: The credentials that are used to authenticate the user for the requested database link have expired.
column8: From Oracle doc: Renew your credentials. Refer to the documentation specific for your Network Authentication Adapter on how to do this.

column6: Login failed: the SecurID server rejected the new pincode
column7: There are a number of reasons why the SecurID server would refuse a pincode: - The user might not have permission to make up his own pincode. - The pincode was either too short or too long. Valid pincodes consist of minimal four, but no more than eight characters. - The pincode contains any non alpha-numeric characters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reexecute the operation and make sure to use a pincode that satisfies the above requirements. If the problem persists, turn on tracing at the Oracle Server side of the connection and examine the trace file for the exact error.

column6: Server Authentication required, but not supported
column7: Server Authentication is required for this connection, but not supported by both sides of the connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure both sides of the connection have the correct version of Secure Network Services, and that the Authentication Adapter supports Server Authentication.

column6: Server Authentication failed, login cancelled
column7: Server Authentication is required, but the server's credentials were found invalid by the client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the server has a valid set of credentials. Refer to your authentication adapter specific documentation on how to do this.

column6: Native service internal error
column7: An internal error occurred in the native services component.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable tracing to determine the exact error. Contact Worldwide Customer Support.

column6: invalid NLS parameter value (%s)
column7: An invalid NLS initialization parameter was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax and spelling of the parameter. Enter the correct parameter into the initialization parameter file.

column6: CREATE DATABASE character set is not known
column7: The character set specified in the CREATE DATABASE command does not exist on the system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to your Oracle operating system-specific documentation for more information about character sets on the system. Use a valid character set in the CREATE DATABASE command.

column6: invalid NLS parameter %s used in SQL function
column7: An invalid parameter or value was entered in the NLS parameter string in a SQL function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the function and the parameters. Enter the command again using the correct syntax and valid values.

column6: this character set conversion is not supported
column7: An attempt was made to use the CONVERT function to convert between two character sets, and the requested conversion is not possible due to unavailability of one or both character sets.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use character sets available on the system in the CONVERT function.

column6: character set mismatch
column7:
One of the following: 

The string operands (other than an NLSPARAMS argument) to an operator or built-in function do not have the same character set. 

An NLSPARAMS operand is not in the database character set. 

String data with character set other than the database character set is passed to a built-in function not expecting it. 

The second argument to CHR() or CSCONVERT() is not CHAR_CS or NCHAR_CS. 

A string expression in the VALUES clause of an INSERT statement, or the SET clause of an UPDATE statement, does not have the same character set as the column into which the value would be inserted. 

A value provided in a DEFAULT clause when creating a table does not have the same character set as declared for the column. 

An argument to a PL/SQL function does not conform to the character set requirements of the corresponding parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Strings declared with NCHAR or NCHAR VARYING do not interoperate with strings declared with CHAR or VARCHAR2. Use TRANSLATE() function to explicitly convert one to the other.

column6: invalid or unknown NLS parameter value specified
column7: There are two possible causes: Either an attempt was made to issue an ALTER SESSION statement with an invalid NLS parameter or value; or the NLS_LANG environment variable contains an invalid language, territory, or character set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the ALTER SESSION command and the NLS parameter, correct the syntax and retry the statement, or specify correct values in the NLS_LANG environment variable. For more information about the syntax of the ALTER SESSION command, see Oracle8i SQL Reference.

column6: this CREATE DATABASE character set is not allowed
column7: An attempt was made to create a database on an ASCII-based machine using an EBCDIC-based character set or vice versa. This is not permitted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the database using either ASCII-based or EBCDIC-based character sets, depending on what is supported by the hardware. Refer to your Oracle operating system-specific documentation for more information about the type of character set supported.

column6: error while getting create database NLS parameter %s
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: error while loading create database NLS parameter %s
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: error while loading create database character set
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: CREATE CONTROLFILE character set is not known
column7: The character set specified when creating the control file is unknown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a known character set.

column6: this CREATE CONTROLFILE character set is not allowed
column7: It is not allowed to create a control file on a native ASCII-based machine using an EBCDIC-based character set, and vice versa.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the correct control file for machine and character set.

column6: new character set must be a superset of old character set
column7: When you ALTER DATABASE ... CHARACTER SET, the new character set must be a superset of the old character set. For example, WE8ISO8859P1 is not a superset of the WE8DEC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a superset character set.

column6: system appears too busy for parallel query execution
column7: Load on the system is too high to perform parallel queries.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-execute serially or wait until the system load is reduced.

column6: error signaled in parallel query server %s
column7: A parallel query server reached an exception condition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the following error message for the cause.

column6: parallel query server lost contact with coordinator
column7: A parallel query server lost contact with the foreground (coordinator) process/thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your system for anomalies and reissue the statement. If this error persists, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: parallel query server lost contact with another server
column7: A parallel query server lost contact with another server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your system for anomalies and reissue the statement. If this error persists, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: parallel query server appears to have died
column7: Cannot find process information for a parallel query server thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your system for anomalies and reissue the statement. If this error persists, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: parallel query server died unexpectedly
column7: A parallel query server died unexpectedly, PMON cleaning up the process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your system for anomalies and reissue the statement. If this error persists, contact Oracle Customer Support. See trace file for more details.

column6: could not get background process to hold enqueue
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error should not normally occur. If it persists, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: process queue could not receive parallel query message
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error should not normally occur. If it persists, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot set %s_INSTANCES greater than number of instances %s
column7: An attempt was made to set SCAN_INSTANCES or CACHE_INSTANCES using the ALTER SYSTEM command to a value larger than the number of available instances.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the accompanying message for the current allowable maximum value, or set SCAN_INSTANCES / CACHE_INSTANCES to ALL.

column6: cannot set %s_INSTANCES when mounted in exclusive mode
column7: An attempt was made to set SCAN_INSTANCES or CACHE_INSTANCES using the ALTER SYSTEM command while the database was mounted in exclusive mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: SCAN_INSTANCES / CACHE_INSTANCES may not be set unless running Oracle parallel server mounted in SHARED or PARALLEL mode.

column6: PARALLEL_MAX_SERVERS must be less than or equal to %s
column7: An attempt was made to set the PARALLEL_MAX_SERVERS parameter to a value higher than the maximum allowed by the system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set PARALLEL_MAX_SERVERS to a value less than or equal to the maximum specified in the accompanying message and retry.

column6: PARALLEL_MIN_SERVERS must be less than or equal to PARALLEL_MAX_SERVERS, %s
column7: An attempt was made to set the PARALLEL_MIN_SERVERS parameter to a value higher than PARALLEL_MAX_SERVERS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set PARALLEL_MIN_SERVERS to a value less than or equal to PARALLEL_MAX_SERVERS (indicated in the accompanying message) and retry.

column6: only one PARALLEL or NOPARALLEL clause may be specified
column7: PARALLEL was specified more than once, NOPARALLEL was specified more than once, or both PARALLEL and NOPARALLEL were specified in a CREATE TABLE, CLUSTER, or INDEX or in an ALTER TABLE or CLUSTER statement, or in a RECOVER command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the PARALLEL or NOPARALLEL clauses and reissue the statement.

column6: value for PARALLEL or DEGREE must be greater than 0
column7: PARALLEL 0 or DEGREE 0 was specified in a CREATE TABLE, CLUSTER, or INDEX or in an ALTER TABLE or CLUSTER statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a degree of parallelism greater than 0 or specify default parallelism using PARALLEL with no degree or using DEGREE DEFAULT within a PARALLEL clause.

column6: only one CACHE or NOCACHE clause may be specified
column7: CACHE was specified more than once, NOCACHE was specified more than once, or both CACHE and NOCACHE were specified in a CREATE TABLE or CLUSTER, or in an ALTER TABLE or CLUSTER statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the CACHE or NOCACHE clauses and reissue the statement.

column6: value for INSTANCES must be greater than 0
column7: PARALLEL parameter specifying number of instances must be a positive integer or DEFAULT.
column8: From Oracle doc: specify a positive integer or DEFAULT for INSTANCES if parallelism across instances is desired.

column6: parallel create index fastpath operation
column7: The parallel create index fastpath operation event has been set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set this event only under the supervision Oracle development.

column6: parallel query option must be enabled
column7: A parallel query option feature has been invoked but this option has not been enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable the parallel query option.

column6: invalid option in PARALLEL clause
column7: An unrecognized option was used within a PARALLEL clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: specify any combination of DEGREE { n | DEFAULT } and INSTANCES { n | DEFAULT } within the PARALLEL clause.

column6: missing options in PARALLEL clause
column7: PARALLEL clause cannot be empty.
column8: From Oracle doc: specify any combination of DEGREE { n | DEFAULT } and INSTANCES { n | DEFAULT } within the PARALLEL clause.

column6: invalid value for DEGREE
column7: Invalid value for DEGREE was specified within a PARALLEL clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a positive integer or DEFAULT for the DEGREE option within a PARALLEL clause.

column6: invalid value for INSTANCES
column7: An invalid value for INSTANCES was specified within a PARALLEL clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a positive integer or DEFAULT for the INSTANCES option within a PARALLEL clause.

column6: duplicate option in PARALLEL clause
column7: DEGREE or INSTANCES was specified more than once within a PARALLEL clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify each desired PARALLEL clause option only once.

column6: default degree of parallelism may not be specified here
column7: The PARALLEL keyword was used alone or DEGREE DEFAULT was specified in the PARALLEL clause of an ALTER DATABASE RECOVER command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Respecify with an explicit degree of parallelism.

column6: INSTANCES DEFAULT may not be specified here
column7: INSTANCES DEFAULT was specified in the PARALLEL clause of an ALTER DATABASE RECOVER command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Respecify with an explicit value for INSTANCES or omit the INSTANCES option if single instance recovery is desired.

column6: explicit degree of parallelism must be specified here
column7: The DEGREE option was omitted from an ALTER DATABASE RECOVER command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Respecify with an explicit degree of parallelism.

column6: hung parallel query server was killed
column7: The parallel query server was hung and subsequently killed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-execute the query and report suspicious events in the trace file to Oracle Customer Support if the error persists.

column6: insufficient parallel query slaves available
column7: PARALLEL_MIN_PERCENT parameter was specified and fewer than minimum slaves were acquired.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either re-execute query with lower PARALLEL_MIN_PERCENT or wait until some running queries are completed, thus freeing up slaves.

column6: Can't start parallel transaction - distributed transaction in progress
column7: PDML transaction cannot be started because a distributed transaction is in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the DML statement to exclude updates to remote tables and re-execute the statement.

column6: Deadlock - itls occupied by siblings at block %s of file %s
column7: A parallel statement failed because all ITLS in the current block are occupied by siblings of the same transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the value of MAXTRANS of the block or reduce the degree of parallelism for the statement. Re-execute the statement. Report suspicious events in the trace file to Oracle Customer Support if the error persists.

column6: Must COMMIT or ROLLBACK after executing parallel INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE
column7: After executing a parallel INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE statement, a command other than COMMIT or ROLLBACK was issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute COMMIT or ROLLBACK before issuing another SQL command.

column6: Must COMMIT or ROLLBACK after executing INSERT with APPEND hint
column7: After executing an INSERT statement with an APPEND hint, a command other than COMMIT or ROLLBACK was issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute COMMIT or ROLLBACK before issuing another SQL command.

column6: Could not allocate slaves on all specified instances
column7: After executing a query on a global v$ fixed view, one or more instances failed to allocate a slave to process query.
column8: From Oracle doc: To allow results to be returned by successfully allocated slaves, execute ALTER SESSION SET ALLOW_PARTIAL_SN_RESULTS=TRUE statement, or check parameters of instances.

column6: Coordinator's instance not a member of parallel_instance_group
column7: The coordinator's instance must be a member of the PARALLEL_INSTANCE_GROUP in which this operation will be run.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either add the coordinator's instance to the current PARALLEL_INSTANCE_GROUP or change PARALLEL_INSTANCE_GROUP.

column6: Instance group name, '%s', too long, must be less than %s characters
column7: The instance group name is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either shorten the name or get rid of the instance group.

column6: No instances are active in the OPS_ADMIN_GROUP
column7: There must be at least one instance in the OPS_ADMIN_GROUP in order to execute a query on global views.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of OPS_ADMIN_GROUP.

column6: cannot read/modify an object after modifying it in parallel
column7: Within the same transaction, an attempt was made to add read or modification statements on a table after it had been modified in parallel or with direct load. This is not permitted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the transaction, or break it up into two transactions: one containing the initial modification and the second containing the parallel modification operation.

column6: cannot modify an object in parallel after modifying it
column7: Within the same transaction, an attempt was made to perform parallel modification operations on a table after it had been modified. This is not permitted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the transaction or break it up into two transactions: one containing the parallel modification and the second containing the initial modification operation.

column6: cannot access remote table in a parallel transaction
column7: Within a transaction, an attempt was made to perform distributed access after a PDML or insert direct statement had been issued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Commit/roll back the PDML transaction first, and then perform the distributed access, or perform the distributed access before the first PDML statement in the transaction.

column6: Cannot alter the session parallel DML state within a transaction
column7: Transaction in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: Commit or roll back the transaction and then re-execute.

column6: schema modified during parallel execution
column7: Schema modified during the parse phase of parallel processing.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: pdml lock not held properly on the table
column7: The coodinator crashed or released the lock on the partition which the slave is trying to aquire.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if the coordinator or some of the other slaves died. Also check that the lock has not been corrupted. Issue the PDML again.

column6: checkpoint option not allowed with SET UNUSED
column7: An attempt was made to specify checkpoint option with SET UNUSED.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the checkpoint option.

column6: cannot drop column from an object type table
column7: An attempt was made to drop a column from an object type table.
column8: From Oracle doc: This action is not allowed.

column6: cannot drop column from a nested table
column7: An attempt was made to drop a column from a nested table.
column8: From Oracle doc: This action is not allowed.

column6: cannot drop all columns in a table
column7: An attempt was made to drop all columns in a table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure at least one column remains in the table after the drop column operation.

column6: cannot drop partitioning column
column7: An attempt was made to drop a column used as the partitioning key.
column8: From Oracle doc: This action is not allowed.

column6: tablespace '%s' is read only, cannot drop column
column7: An attempt was made to drop column from a partition/subpartition on a read-only tablespace.
