column8: From Oracle doc: Set the tablespace to read write and resubmit statement.

column6: columns in partially dropped state. Submit ALTER TABLE DROP COLUMNS CONTINUE
column7: An attempt was made to access a table with columns in partially dropped state (that is, drop column operation was interrupted).
column8: From Oracle doc: Submit ALTER TABLE DROP COLUMNS CONTINUE to complete the drop column operation before accessing the table.

column6: cannot combine drop column with other operations
column7: An attempt was made to combine drop column with other ALTER TABLE operations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that drop column is the sole operation specified in ALTER TABLE.

column6: cannot drop column from table owned by SYS
column7: An attempt was made to drop a column from a system table.
column8: From Oracle doc: This action is not allowed.

column6: invalid value for checkpoint interval
column7: An invalid checkpoint interval specified in statement. Checkpoint interval must be between 0 and (2^31-1).
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct checkpoint interval and resubmit statement.

column6: duplicate option specified
column7: Duplicate option specified in statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate option and resubmit statement.

column6: column is referenced in a multi-column constraint
column7: An attempt was made to drop a column referenced by some constraints.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop all constraints referencing the dropped column or specify CASCADE CONSTRAINTS in statement.

column6: cannot drop parent key column
column7: An attempt was made to drop a parent key column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop all constraints referencing the parent key column, or specify CASCADE CONSTRAINTS in statement.

column6: tablespace '%s' is offline, cannot drop column
column7: An attempt was made to drop a column from a partition/subpartition on an offline tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the tablespace online and resubmit statement.

column6: drop column option only allowed once in statement
column7: An attempt was made to repeat the drop column option in a single statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Separate drop column options into different statements and resubmit statements.

column6: no columns in partially dropped state
column7: An attempt was made to submit DROP COLUMNS CONTINUE statement while there are no partially dropped columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Cannot submit this statement.

column6: cannot drop system-generated virtual column
column7: An attempt was made to drop a virtual column generated by the system.
column8: From Oracle doc: This action is not allowed.

column6: cannot drop primary key column from an index-organized table
column7: An attempt was made to drop a primary key column from an index- organized table.
column8: From Oracle doc: This action is not allowed.

column6: geometry column %s does not exist in table %s
column7: The specified table does not have a column of type SDO_GEOMETRY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter or re-create the table such that it includes a column of type SDO_GEOMETRY and a column of type NUMBER.

column6: column %s in table %s is not of type SDO_GEOMETRY
column7: The column intended for storing the geometry is not of type SDO_GEOMETRY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter the column definition to be of type SDO_GEOMETRY.

column6: geometry identifier column %s does not exist in table %s
column7: The specified table does not contain a GID column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the GID column name was correctly specified and that it exists in the specified table.

column6: geometry identifier column %s in table %s is not of type NUMBER
column7: GID column is not of type NUMBER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter the table definition such that the column containing the geometry identifier (GID) is of type NUMBER.

column6: error inserting data into table %s
column7: An OCI error occurred or the user has insufficient quota in the active tablespace or the rollback segments are too small.
column8: From Oracle doc: There should be an accompanying error message that indicates the cause of the problem. Take appropriate action to correct the indicated problem.

column6: error reading data from layer table %s
column7: There was an error reading the geometry data from the layer_SDOGEOM table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that layer_SDOGEOM and layer_SDODIM exist. If they do then run VALIDATE_GEOMETRY on the specified layer.

column6: error obtaining dimension information from SDO_GEOM_METADATA
column7: There is no entry in SDO_GEOM_METADATA for the specified geometry table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the table SDO_GEOM_METADATA exists. If it does, insert an entry for the destination geometry table with the dimension information obtained from the source layer_SDODIM table.

column6: internal error [%s] encountered when processing geometry table
column7: An internal error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support with the exact error message text.

column6: OCI error %s
column7: OCI error while processing the layer or geometry tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the appropriate steps to correct the OCI specific error.

column6: error allocating memory for geometry object
column7: There was insufficient memory for the geometry object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make more memory available to the current session/process.

column6: geometric object %s in table %s is invalid
column7: The specified object failed the geometric integrity checks performed by VALIDATE_GEOMETRY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult Oracle Spatial User's Guide and Reference for information on the geometric integrity checks performed by VALIDATE_GEOMETRY and correct the geometry definition if required.

column6: dimension metadata table %s does not exist
column7: The layer_SDODIM table does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the specified layer name is correct and that the layer_SDODIM table exists in the current schema.

column6: invalid MASK
column7: The MASK you passed to RELATE function is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the mask is not NULL. See Oracle Spatial User's Guide and Reference for a list of supported masks.

column6: a point geometry has more than one coordinate
column7: A geometry, specified as being a point, has more than one coordinate in its definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: A point has only one coordinate. If this geometry is intended to represent a point cluster, line, or polygon then set the appropriate SDO_GTYPE or SDO_ETYPE value. If this is a single point object then remove the extraneous coordinates from its definition.

column6: a line geometry has less than two coordinates
column7: A geometry, specified as being a line, has less than two coordinates in its definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: A line must consist of at least two distinct coordinates. Correct the geometric definition or set the appropriate SDO_GTYPE or SDO_ETYPE attribute for this geometry.

column6: an arc geometry has less than three coordinates
column7: A geometry, specified as being an arc, has less than three coordinates in its definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: An arc must consist of at least three distinct coordinates. Correct the geometric definition or set the appropriate SDO_GTYPE or SDO_ETYPE attribute for this geometry.

column6: a polygon geometry has less than four coordinates
column7: A geometry, specified as being a polygon, has less than four coordinates in its definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: A polygon must consist of at least four distinct coordinates. Correct the geometric definition or set the appropriate SDO_GTYPE or SDO_ETYPE attribute for this geometry.

column6: an arcpolygon geometry has less than five coordinates
column7: A geometry, specified as being an arcpolygon, has less than six coordinates in its definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: An arcpolygon must consist of at least five coordinates. An arcpolygon consists of an ordered sequence of arcs, each of which must be described using three coordinates. Since arcs are connected, the end-point of the first is the start of the second and does not have to be repeated. Correct the geometric definition or set the appropriate SDO_GTYPE or SDO_ETYPE attribute for this geometry.

column6: a compound polygon geometry has less than five coordinates
column7: A geometry, specified as being a compound polygon, has less than five coordinates in its definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: A compound polygon must contain at least five coordinates. A compound polygon consists of at least one arc and one line each of which must be described using three and at least two distinct coordinates respectively. Correct the geometric definition or set the appropriate SDO_GTYPE or SDO_ETYPE attribute for this geometry.

column6: the coordinates defining an arc are collinear
column7: Invalid definition of an arc. An arc is defined using three non-collinear coordinates.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter the definition or the arc or set the SDO_ETYPE or SDO_GTYPE to the line type.

column6: the coordinates defining an arc are not distinct
column7: Two or more of the three points defining an arc are the same.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter the definition of the arc ensuring that three distinct coordinate values are used.

column6: polygon boundary is not closed
column7: The boundary of a polygon does not close.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter the coordinate values or the definition of the SDO_GTYPE or SDO_ETYPE attribute of the geometry.

column6: polygon boundary crosses itself
column7: The boundary of a polygon intersects itself.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the geometric definition of the object.

column6: two or more rings of a complex polygon touch
column7: The inner or outer rings of a complex polygon touch.
column8: From Oracle doc: All rings of a complex polygon must be disjoint. Correct the geometric description of the object.

column6: two or more rings of a complex polygon overlap
column7: The inner or outer rings of a complex polygon overlap.
column8: From Oracle doc: All rings of a complex polygon must be disjoint. Correct the geometric description of the object.

column6: the coordinates do not describe a circle
column7: The set of coordinates used to describe a circle are incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the set of coordinates actually represent points on the circumference of a circle.

column6: ELEM_INFO_ARRAY not grouped in threes
column7: The ELEM_INFO_ARRAY in SDO_GEOMETRY has more or fewer elements than expected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the number of elements in ELEM_INFO_ARRAY is divisible by 3.

column6: incorrect offset in ELEM_INFO_ARRAY
column7: The offset field in ELEM_INFO_ARRAY of SDO_GEOMETRY references an invalid array subscript in SDO_ORDINATE_ARRAY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the offset is a valid array subscript in SDO_ORINATE_ARRAY.

column6: SDO_ORDINATE_ARRAY not grouped by number of dimensions specified
column7: The number of elements in SDO_ORDINATE_ARRAY is not a multiple of the number of dimensions supplied by the user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the number of dimensions is consistent with data representation in SDO_ORINATE_ARRAY.

column6: adjacent points in a geometry are redundant
column7: There are repeated points in the sequence of coordinates.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the redundant point.

column6: extent type does not contain 2 points
column7: Extent type should be represented by 2 points: lower left and upper right.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that there are only 2 points for extent type.

column6: circle type does not contain 3 points
column7: Circle type should be represented by 3 distinct points on the circumference.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that there are only 3 points for circle type.

column6: extent does not have an area
column7: The 2 points representing the extent are identical.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the 2 points describing the extent type are distinct.

column6: invalid subtype in a compound type
column7: This subtype is not allowed within the ETYPE specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the Oracle Spatial User's Guide and Reference for type definitions.

column6: not enough sub-elements within a compound ETYPE
column7: The compound type declare more sub-elements than actually defined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the number of sub-elements is consistent with the compound type declaration.

column6: disjoint sub-element in a compound polygon
column7: Compound polygon must describe an enclosed area.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that all sub-elements are connected.

column6: no valid ETYPE in the geometry
column7: None of the ETYPEs within the geometry is supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that there is at least one valid ETYPE.

column6: Oracle GeoImage internal error, arguments: %s, %s, %s, %s, %s
column7: This is an internal Oracle GeoImage error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: unsupported geoimage format
column7: The GeoImage format is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the GeoImage format is valid and supported.

column6: NULL destination
column7: The object specified as the destination is NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the object specified as the destination is not NULL.

column6: NULL source geometry
column7: The source GeoImage has a NULL geometry.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the geometry of the source GeoImage is not NULL.

column6: not a local source
column7: An attempt has been made to modify a GeoImage which is not stored in the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Import the GeoImage in order to modify it.

column6: NULL source
column7: The object specified as the source is NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Confirm that the object specified as the source is not NULL.

column6: unsupported image processing command %s
column7: The image processing command specified is not supported for a GeoImage.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult the Oracle interMedia manual to verify which image processing commands are supported within an Oracle GeoImage method.

column6: unrecognized space type qualifier %s
column7: The GeoImage space type qualifier is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid space type qualifier (RASTER or MODEL).

column6: NULL table name
column7: The table name parameter is NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the parameter used for the table name is not NULL.

column6: Oracle table %s does not exist.
column7: The table specified does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the table name used is valid and the table exists.

column6: NULL column name
column7: The column name parameter is NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the parameter used for the column name is not NULL.

column6: Oracle column %s does not exist.
column7: The column specified does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the column name used is valid and the column exists.

column6: invalid ROWID
column7: The ROWID value used in not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the ROWID value used is valid.

column6: could not select the GeoImage for initialization"
column7: The GeoImage in the table could not be selected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the GeoIMage is present in the table and the supplied parameters are valid.

column6: could not update the table containing the GeoImage
column7: The table containing the GeoImage could not be updated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the table exists and is valid.

column6: invalid domain
column7: The SDO_DIMINFO value used is not valid or the SDO_GEOMETRY supplied is not defined in the domain.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the SDO_DIMINFO value is valid, and that the SDO_GEOMETRY is defined within the domain specified.

column6: invalid geometry, arguments %s
column7: The SDO_GEOMETRY value used is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the SDO_GEOMETRY is valid, consult the Oracle Spatial User's Guide and Reference for a list of valid geometries.

column6: undefined raster to model space transformation
column7: The raster to model space transformation associated with a GeoImage is undefined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the GeoImage format is valid and that the particular operation is supported for that format.

column6: undefined model to raster space transformation
column7: The model to raster space transformation associated with a GeoImage is undefined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the GeoImage format is valid and that the particular operation is supported for that format.

column6: invalid latitude value
column7: A latitude value outside the valid range [-90,90] has been used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the GeoImage geometry definition is within the domain.

column6: invalid model to raster space transformation
column7: The model to raster space transformation associated with a GeoImage is not valid or cannot be calculated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the transformation is supported and that the GeoImage format is valid.

column6: invalid raster to model space transformation
column7: The raster to model space transformation associated with a GeoImage is not valid or cannot be calculated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the transformation is supported and that the GeoImage format is valid.

column6: uninitialized source
column7: The LOB used for the source is not initialized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the source is properly initialized.

column6: empty source
column7: The LOB used for the source is empty.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the source is properly initialized and data has been imported into it.

column6: uninitialized destination
column7: The LOB used for the destination is not initialized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the destination is properly initialized.

column6: empty destination
column7: The LOB used for the destination is empty.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the destination is properly initialized and data has been imported into it.

column6: unsupported raster origin
column7: The raster origin specified is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the origin specified is supported.

column6: unknown raster origin
column7: The value specified for the raster origin is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the value used to specify the raster origin is valid and supported.

column6: source does not exist
column7: The source does not exist or cannot be accessed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the source specification is correct and accessible.

column6: operation %s not supported on GeoImage type %s
column7: The specified operation is not supported on the particular GeoImage type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the operation is supported.

column6: model coordinate system not supported
column7: The model specified for the definition of the coordinate system is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the model value is correct.

column6: NULL crop geometry
column7: The geometry used to crop a GeoImage is NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the geometry used for the crop operation is not NULL.

column6: invalid scaling parameters %s %s
column7: The parameters used in the scale operation are invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the scaling parameters are greater than zero.

column6: unrecognized scale mode %s
column7: The scale mode used in the scale operation is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult the Oracle8i interMedia Audio, Image, and Video User's Guide and Reference for a list of valid scale mode qualifiers.

column6: unsupported conversion format %s
column7: The format specified for conversion is invalid or unsupported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the conversion format specified is valid.

column6: invalid tag/key %s
column7: The tag or key is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the format version is supported or the format is valid.

column6: invalid tie point
column7: One of the tie points is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the tie points used are valid (for example all raster tie points are >= 0).

column6: unsupported GeoTIFF geometry definition
column7: The combination of keys/tags used to define the geometry footprint of the GeoImage is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the GeoTIFF format version is supported and the format is valid.

column6: unsupported conversion
column7: The format specified for conversioin is not supported. In GeoTIFF only a limited number of tags/keys combinations are supported for conversion.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the GeoTIFF format version is supported and conversion to the desired format is available.

column6: %s
column7: This is an internal Spatial Cartridge error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: only one LOCAL clause may be specified
column7: CREATE INDEX statement contained more than one LOCAL clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify LOCAL option at most once.

column6: LOCAL clause contradicts previosly specified GLOBAL clause
column7: CREATE INDEX statement contained a GLOBAL clause and a LOCAL clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify LOCAL or GLOBAL clause, but not both.

column6: only one GLOBAL clause may be specified
column7: CREATE INDEX statement contained more than one GLOBAL clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify GLOBAL option at most once.

column6: GLOBAL clause contradicts previosly specified LOCAL clause
column7: CREATE INDEX statement contained a LOCAL clause and a GLOBAL clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify GLOBAL or LOCAL clause, but not both.

column6: missing PARTITION keyword
column7: Keyword PARTITION missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply missing keyword.

column6: missing RANGE keyword
column7: Keyword RANGE missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply missing keyword.

column6: invalid partition name
column7: A partition name of the form identifier is expected but not present.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter an appropriate partition name.

column6: missing LESS keyword
column7: Keyword LESS missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply missing keyword.

column6: missing THAN keyword
column7: Keyword THAN missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply missing keyword.

column6: partition bound may not be specified for a LOCAL index partition
column7: While parsing a CREATE INDEX statement to create a LOCAL partitioned index, partition_description of one of partitions was found to contain VALUES LESS THAN clause which is illegal since a LOCAL index inherits partition bounds from its base table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all VALUES LESS THAN clauses from descriptions of LOCAL index partitions.

column6: this physical attribute may not be specified for an index partition
column7: Unexpected option was encountered while parsing physical attributes of an index partition; valid options for range or composite range partitions are INITRANS, MAXTRANS, TABLESPACE, STORAGE, PCTFREE; only TABLESPACE may be specified for hash partitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove invalid option(s) from the list of physical attributes of an index partition.

column6: names assigned to resulting partitions must be distinct
column7: Names of partitions resulting from splitting of an existing table or index partition are not distinct.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rename resulting partition(s) to ensure that their names are distinct and different from those of any other partition of the table or index.

column6: resulting partition name conflicts with that of an existing partition
column7: Name of a partition resulting from splitting of an existing table or index partition is identical to that of some other existing partition of that table or index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rename resulting partition(s) to ensure that their names are distinct and different from those of any other partition of the table or index.

column6: duplicate partition name
column7: Name of a partition of a table or index being created is not unique.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rename partition(s) to ensure that their names are unique among partitions of the table or index being created.

column6: maximum number of partitioning columns is 16
column7: Number of columns in a partitioning column list exceeded the legal limit of 16.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify partitioning column list so that it consists of at most 16 columns.

column6: too many partition descriptions
column7: CREATE TABLE or CREATE INDEX contained too many partition descriptions; maximum number of partitions is 65535.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of partitions to not exceed 65535.

column6: underlying table of a LOCAL partitioned index must be partitioned
column7: An attempt was made to create a LOCAL partitioned index on a non-partitioned table which is illegal. Only GLOBAL indices (partitioned or otherwise) may be created on a non-partitioned table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the statement and re-enter it.

column6: partition bound list contains too many elements
column7: Partition bound list contained more elements than there are partitioning columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the number of elements in partition bound list is equal to the number of partitioning columns of the table or index.

column6: partition bound list contains too few elements
column7: Partition bound list contained fewer elements than there are partitioning columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the number of elements in partition bound list is equal to the number of partitioning columns of the table or index.

column6: partition bound element must be one of: %s, datetime or interval literal, number, or MAXVALUE
column7: Partition bound list contained an element of invalid type (that is, not a number, non-empty string, datetime or interval literal, or MAXVALUE).
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that all elements of partition bound list are of valid type.

column6: this physical attribute may not be specified for a table partition
column7: Unexpected option was encountered while parsing physical attributes of a table partition; valid options for range or composite range partitions are INITRANS, MAXTRANS, TABLESPACE, STORAGE, PCTFREE, and PCTUSED; only TABLESPACE may be specified for hash partitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove invalid option(s) from the list of physical attributes of a table partition.

column6: MAXVALUE must be specified for all columns
column7: In the VALUES LESS THAN clause for the highest (last) partition of a GLOBAL index, MAXVALUE must be specified for all columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that VALUES LESS THAN clause for the last partition of a GLOBAL index has MAXVALUE specified for all columns.

column6: creation of LOCAL partitioned cluster indices is not supported
column7: An attempt was made to create a LOCAL partitioned cluster index, which is currently illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove LOCAL along with partition_descriptions, if any, from the CREATE INDEX statement.

column6: creation of GLOBAL partitioned cluster indices is not supported
column7: An attempt was made to create a GLOBAL partitioned cluster index, which is currently illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove PARTITION BY RANGE clause along with partition_descriptions from the CREATE INDEX statement.

column6: number of partitions of LOCAL index must equal that of the underlying table
column7: An attempt was made to create a LOCAL partitioned index with a number of partitions which is different from that of the underlying table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the CREATE INDEX statement to specify a correct number of partitions.

column6: PARTITION may not be specified for a snapshot or a snapshot log
column7: PARTITION option was encountered while parsing a definition of a snapshot or a snapshot log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a definition of a SNAPSHOT does not include invalid options.

column6: PARTITION and CLUSTER clauses are mutually exclusive
column7: Definition of a table contained both PARTITION and CLUSTER clauses which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the conflicting clauses.

column6: only one PARTITION clause may be specified
column7: CREATE TABLE statement contained more than one PARTITION clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify PARTITION option at most once.

column6: missing AT keyword
column7: Keyword AT missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply missing keyword.

column6: GLOBAL partitioned index must be prefixed
column7: The partitioning columns of a global partitioned index did not contain a prefix of the index's key columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the GLOBAL partitioned index being created is prefixed and retry the operation.

column6: non-existent partitioning column in CREATE TABLE statement
column7: Partitioning column specified in CREATE TABLE statement is not one of columns of the table being created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that all columns in the partitioning column list are columns of the table being created.

column6: partitioning column may not be of type LONG or LONG RAW
column7: Partitioning column specified by the user was of type LONG or LONG RAW, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that no partitioning column is of type LONG or LONG RAW.

column6: partition bound of partition number %s is too high
column7: High bound of the partition whose number (partitions are numbered starting with 1) is displayed in this message did not collate lower than that of the following partition, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that high bound of every partition (except for the last one) collates lower than that of a following partition.

column6: partition bound value too large for column
column7: Length of partition bound value is longer than that of the corresponding partitioning column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that lengths of high bound values do not exceed those of corresponding partitioning columns.

column6: partition bound of partition "%s" is too high
column7: High bound of the partition whose name (explicitly specified by the user) is displayed in this message did not collate lower than that of the following partition, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that high bound of every partition (except for the last one) collates lower than that of a following partition.

column6: GLOBAL partitioned index must be prefixed
column7: An attempt was made to create a GLOBAL non-prefixed partitioned index which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: If a non-prefixed index is desired, it must be created as LOCAL; otherwise, correct the list of key and/or partitioning columns to ensure that the index is prefixed. Then retry the operation.

column6: partitioning columns must form a subset of key columns of a UNIQUE index
column7: An attempt was made to create a UNIQUE partitioned index whose partitioning columns do not form a subset of its key columns which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you want to create an index whose partitioning columns do not form a subset of its key columns, it must be created as non-UNIQUE; otherwise, correct the list of key and/or partitioning columns to ensure that the index's partitioning columns form a subset of its key columns.

column6: partition bound may not be specified for resulting partitions
column7: While parsing an ALTER {TABLE|INDEX} SPLIT PARTITION statement, partition_description of a resulting partition was found to contain VALUES LESS THAN clause which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove VALUES LESS THAN clause from the description(s) of partitions resulting from splitting an existing table or index partition.

column6: partition bound may not be specified for a partition being moved, modified or rebuilt
column7: While parsing an ALTER {TABLE|INDEX} MODIFY PARTITION, ALTER TABLE MOVE PARTITION, or ALTER INDEX REBUILD PARTITION statement, description of new physical attributes of the partition being moved, modified, or rebuilt was found to contain VALUES LESS THAN clause which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove VALUES LESS THAN clause from the description of new attributes of the partition being moved, modified, or rebuilt.

column6: only one partition may be added
column7: ALTER TABLE ADD PARTITION contained descriptions of more than one partition to be added.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the statement contains exactly one partition definition and that it does not contain any commas.

column6: only one partition may be moved
column7: ALTER TABLE MOVE PARTITION contained descriptions of more than one partition to be moved.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the statement describes exactly one partition to be moved and that it does not contain any commas.

column6: only one partition may be modified
column7: ALTER TABLE|INDEX MODIFY PARTITION contained descriptions of more than one partition to be modified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the statement describes exactly one partition to be modified and that it does not contain any commas.

column6: a partition may be split into exactly two new partitions
column7: ALTER TABLE|INDEX SPLIT PARTITION did not contain descriptions of exactly two new partitions into which an existing table or index partition was to be split.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the statement describes exactly two partition into which an existing partition is to be split.

column6: ALTER TABLE|INDEX RENAME may not be combined with other operations
column7: ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement attempted to combine a RENAME operation with some other operation which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that RENAME operation is the sole operation specified in ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement.

column6: a partition maintenance operation may not be combined with other operations
column7: The ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement attempted to combine a partition maintenance operation (for example, MOVE PARTITION) with some other operation (for example, ADD PARTITION or PCTFREE) which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a partition maintenance operation is the sole operation specified in an ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement; operations other than those dealing with partitions, default attributes of partitioned tables/indices, or specifying that a table be renamed (ALTER TABLE RENAME) can be combined.

column6: invalid ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION option
column7: An option other than PCTFREE, PCTUSED, INITRANS, MAXTRANS, STORAGE, BACKUP, ALLOCATE EXTENT, or DEALLOCATE UNUSED was specified in an ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION statement for a range or composite range partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: invalid ALTER INDEX MODIFY PARTITION option
column7: An option other than INITRANS, MAXTRANS, STORAGE, or DEALLOCATE UNUSED was specified in an ALTER INDEX MODIFY PARTITION statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: invalid ALTER SNAPSHOT option
column7: An option other than PCTFREE, PCTUSED, INITRANS, MAXTRANS, STORAGE, or BACKUP was specified in an ALTER SNAPSHOT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: partition-extended table name syntax is disallowed in this context
column7: An attempt was made to use partition-extended table name syntax in illegal context (that is, not in FROM-clause or INSERT, DELETE, or UPDATE statement).
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid use of partition-extended table name in contexts other those mentioned above.

column6: illegal attempt to modify %s in %s statement
column7: Certain attributes of objects (for example, tables) may be specified at creation time, but may not be modified using ALTER statement. Unfortunately, user specified one of such attributes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that ALTER statement specifies new values only for attributes which may be changed once an object has been created.

column6: invalid ALTER TABLE TRUNCATE PARTITION option
column7: Name of the partition to be truncated may be followed by DROP STORAGE or REUSE STORAGE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that no options besides DROP STORAGE or REUSE STORAGE are specified with ALTER TABLE TRUNCATE PARTITION.

column6: keyword REBUILD in ALTER INDEX REBUILD must immediately follow index_name
column7: ALTER INDEX statement contained REBUILD keyword following some index attributes (for example, INITRANS).
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that keyword REBUILD immediately follows the name of the index being altered.

column6: partition number %s: sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE may not exceed 100
column7: The sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for a partition whose number (partitions are numbered starting with 1) is displayed in this message exceeds 100. Note that if PCTUSED and/or PCTFREE values for this partition were not specified explicitly, default values for the partitioned table or index would be used. If, in turn, default PCTUSED and/or PCTFREE values for the partitioned table or index were not specified, system defaults would be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for the partition does not exceed 100.

column6: partition "%s": sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE may not exceed 100
column7: The sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for a partition whose name (explicitly specified by the user) is displayed in this message exceeds 100. Note that if PCTUSED and/or PCTFREE values for this partition were not specified explicitly, default values for the partitioned table or index would be used. If, in turn, default PCTUSED and/or PCTFREE values for the partitioned table or index were not specified, system defaults would be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for the partition does not exceed 100.

column6: partition number %s: INITRANS value must be less than MAXTRANS value
column7: Value of INITRANS was found to be greater than that of MAXTRANS for a partition whose number (partitions are numbered starting with 1) is displayed in this message. Note that if INITRANS and/or MAXTRANS values for this partition were not specified explicitly, default values for the partitioned table or index would be used. If, in turn, default INITRANS and/or MAXTRANS values for the partitioned table or index were not specified, system defaults would be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the value of INITRANS (whether specified explicitly or derived from the default value for the partitioned table or index) is no greater than that of MAXTRANS.

column6: partition "%s": INITRANS value must be less than MAXTRANS value
column7: Value of INITRANS was found to be greater than that of MAXTRANS for a partition whose name (explicitly specified by the user) is displayed in this message. Note that if INITRANS and/or MAXTRANS values for this partition were not specified explicitly, default values for the partitioned table or index would be used. If, in turn, default INITRANS and/or MAXTRANS values for the partitioned table or index were not specified, system defaults would be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the value of INITRANS (whether specified explicitly or derived from the default value for the partitioned table or index) is no greater than that of MAXTRANS.

column6: data type or length of a table partitioning column may not be changed
column7: User issued ALTER TABLE statement attempting to modify data type and/or length of a column used to partition the table named in ALTER TABLE statement, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid modifying data type and/or length of table partitioning column(s).

column6: data type or length of an index partitioning column may not be changed
column7: User issued ALTER TABLE statement attempting to modify data type and/or length of a column used to partition some index defined on the table named in ALTER TABLE statement, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid modifying data type and/or length of index partitioning column(s).

column6: one or more of table's partitions reside in a read-only tablespace
column7: User issued ALTER TABLE statement attempting to modify an existing VARCHAR2 (or VARCHAR) column to be of type CHAR (or CHARACTER), increase length of an existing CHAR (or CHARACTER) column, or add a column with user-specified default for a table one or more partitions of which reside in read-only tablespaces, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid performing aforementioned operations on a partitioned table one or more partitions of which reside in read-only tablespaces.

column6: Unusable index exists on unique/primary constraint key
column7: An attempt was made to add or enable a primary key/unique constraint on column(s) of a table on which there exists an index marked Index Unusable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the existing index or rebuild it using ALTER INDEX REBUILD.

column6: Index with Unusable partition exists on unique/primary constraint key
column7: An attempt was made to add or enable a primary key/unique constraint on column(s) of a table on which there exists an index one or more partitions of which are marked Index Unusable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the existing index or rebuild unusable partitions it using ALTER INDEX REBUILD PARTITION.

column6: ALLOCATE STORAGE may not be specified for a partitioned table
column7: User specified ALLOCATE STORAGE clause in ALTER TABLE statement issued against a partitioned table which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option. If it is desired to add storage to individual partitions, ALLOCATE STORAGE clause may be specified with ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION statement.

column6: illegal option for a non-partitioned table
column7: An attempt was made to issue a CREATE TABLE or ALTER TABLE command on a non-partitioned table, but the command contains an option that is legal only for partitioned tables. Such options are: ENABLE ROW MOVEMENT and DISABLE ROW MOVEMENT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option(s) from the command.

column6: duplicate TABLESPACE_NUMBER specification
column7: TABLESPACE_NUMBER clause was specified more than once for a table, an index, or an index partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the code generating text of CREATE INDEX statement sent to the slaves.

column6: TABLESPACE and TABLESPACE_NUMBER may not be both specified
column7: Both TABLESPACE and TABLESPACE_NUMBER clauses were specified for a table, an index, or an index partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the code generating text of CREATE INDEX statement sent to the slaves.

column6: invalid TABLESPACE_NUMBER value
column7: The TABLESPACE_NUMBER value is not an integer between 0 and 0x7FFFFFFF.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the code generating text of CREATE INDEX statement sent to the slaves.

column6: option may be specified only for partitioned indices or with REBUILD
column7: User issued ALTER INDEX statement containing an option which is legal only for partitioned indices or in conjunction with REBUILD against a non-partitioned index. Such options are: PCTFREE, TABLESPACE, [NO]PARALLEL and INITIAL, FREELISTS, and FREELIST GROUPS inside STORAGE clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove illegal option(s).

column6: invalid option for an index used to enforce a constraint
column7: An option other than COMPRESS, NOCOMPRESS, PCTFREE, INITRANS, MAXTRANS, STORAGE, TABLESPACE, PARALLEL, NOPARALLEL, RECOVERABLE, UNRECOVERABLE, LOGGING, NOLOGGING, LOCAL, or GLOBAL was specified for an index used to enforce a constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose one of the valid index options.

column6: fixed table may not be truncated
column7: An attempt was made to truncate a fixed table which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table being truncated is not a fixed table.

column6: bootstrap table or cluster may not be truncated
column7: An attempt was made to truncate a bootstrap table or cluster which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table (or cluster) being truncated is not a bootstrap table (or cluster).

column6: partition bound must collate higher than that of the last partition
column7: Partition bound specified in ALTER TABLE ADD PARTITION statement did not collate higher than that of the table's last partition, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the partition bound of the partition to be added collates higher than that of the table's last partition.

column6: partition maintenance operations may only be performed on partitioned indices
column7: Index named in ALTER INDEX partition maintenance operation is not partitioned, making a partition maintenance operation, at best, meaningless.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the index named in ALTER INDEX statement specifying a partition maintenance operation is, indeed, partitioned.

column6: DROP/SPLIT PARTITION may not be applied to a LOCAL index partition
column7: An attempt was made to drop or split a partition of a LOCAL index which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the index named in such statement is a GLOBAL partitioned index.

column6: you may not drop the highest partition of a GLOBAL index
column7: An attempt was made to drop highest partition of a GLOBAL index, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the partition specified in ALTER INDEX DROP PARTITION statement is not the highest partition of the index.

column6: illegal option for a partition marked Index Unusable
column7: ALTER INDEX MODIFY PARTITION statement against an index partition marked Index Unusable contained STORAGE and/or DEALLOCATE SPACE clauses which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that only valid options are specified.

column6: partition cannot be split along the specified high bound
column7: An attempt was made to split a partition along a bound which either collates higher than that of the partition to be split or lower than that of a partition immediately preceding the one to be split.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the bound along which a partition is to be split collates lower than that of the partition to be split and higher that of a partition immediately preceding the one to be split.

column6: new partition name must differ from the old partition name
column7: User entered ALTER TABLE/INDEX RENAME PARTITION specifying new_partition_name which is identical to the name of the partition being renamed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the new partition name is different from the name of any (including the one being renamed) existing partition of a given table or index.

column6: new partition name must differ from that of any other partition of the object
column7: User entered ALTER TABLE/INDEX RENAME PARTITION specifying new_partition_name which is identical to the name of some existing partition of the object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the new partition name is different from the name of any (including the one being renamed) existing partition of a given table or index.

column6: cannot drop the only partition of a partitioned table
column7: A drop partition command is being executed when there is only one partition in the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that there is at least one partition. Drop table to remove all partitions.

column6: you may specify TABLESPACE DEFAULT only for a LOCAL index
column7: An attempt was made to specify TABLESPACE DEFAULT for an object other than a LOCAL index, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-enter the statement without TABLESPACE DEFAULT clause.

column6: partitioned table cannot have column with LONG datatype
column7: An attempt was made to create a partitioned table with a LONG datatype or tried to add a LONG datatype column to a partitioned table.
column8: From Oracle doc: LONG data types are not supported with partitioned tables. Create table without LONG column or change table to not partitioned. If adding column, do not use LONG datatype. If modifying attributes of a column to change data type to LONG, it has to be a non-partitioned table.

column6: a partitioned index may not be rebuilt as a whole
column7: An attempt was made to rebuild a partitioned index using ALTER INDEX REBUILD statement, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rebuild the index a partition at a time (using ALTER INDEX REBUILD PARTITION) or drop and re-create the entire index.

column6: invalid ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION option
column7: Name of the table to be EXCHANGED has to be followed by [{INCLUDING|EXCLUDING} INDEXES][{WITH|WITHOUT} VALIDATION].
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that no options besides INCLUDING INDEXES or EXCLUDING INDEXES are specified with ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION.

column6: ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE requires a non-partitioned, non-clustered table
column7: The table in the EXCHANGE operation is either clustered or partitioned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table with which the partition is being exchanged for is not partitioned or clustered.

column6: tables in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION must have the same number of columns
column7: The two tables specified in the EXCHANGE have different number of columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables have the same number of columns with the same type and size.

column6: column type or size mismatch in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION
column7: The corresponding columns in the tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION are of different type or size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables have the same number of columns with the same type and size.

column6: index mismatch for tables in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION
column7: The two tables specified in the EXCHANGE have indexes which are not equivalent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the indexes for the two tables have indexes which follow this rule For every non-partitioned index for the non-partitioned table, there has to be an identical LOCAL index on the partitioned table and vice versa. By identical, the column position, type and size have to be the same.

column6: all rows in table do not qualify for specified partition
column7: There is at least one row in the non-partitioned table which does not qualify for the partition specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that all the rows in the segment qualify for the partition. Perform the alter table operation with the NO CHECKING option. Run ANALYZE table VALIDATE on that partition to find out the invalid rows and delete them.

column6: partition extended table name cannot refer to a remote object
column7: An attempt was made to use partition-extended table name syntax in conjunction with remote object name which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the statement and re-enter it.

column6: partition extended table name cannot refer to a synonym
column7: An attempt was made to use partition-extended table name syntax in conjunction with synonym name which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the statement and re-enter it.

column6: only one LOGGING or NOLOGGING clause may be specified
column7: LOGGING was specified more than once, NOLOGGING was specified more than once, or both LOGGING and NOLOGGING were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the LOGGING or NOLOGGING clauses and reissue the statement.

column6: LOGGING/NOLOGGING may not be combined with RECOVERABLE/UNRECOVERABLE
column7: A statement contained both [NO]LOGGING and [UN]RECOVERABLE clauses which is disallowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of the offending clauses. [UN]RECOVERABLE is being deprecated in V8 and will be obsoleted in V9. To duplicate semantics of UNRECOVERABLE clause, create an object with NOLOGGING option and then ALTER it specifying LOGGING. To duplicate semantics of RECOVERABLE clause, create an object with LOGGING option.

column6: RECOVERABLE/UNRECOVERABLE may not be specified for partitioned tables/indices
column7: CREATE TABLE/INDEX statement used to create a partitioned table/index contained RECOVERABLE or UNRECOVERABLE clause which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove offending clause. [UN]RECOVERABLE is being deprecated in V8 and will be obsoleted in V9. To duplicate semantics of UNRECOVERABLE clause, create an object with NOLOGGING option and then ALTER it specifying LOGGING. To duplicate semantics of RECOVERABLE clause, create an object with LOGGING option.

column6: RECOVERABLE/UNRECOVERABLE may not be specified in this context
column7: RECOVERABLE/UNRECOVERABLE clause is not allowed in this context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove offending clause. RECOVERABLE/UNRECOVERABLE may only be specified in CREATE TABLE/INDEX statement describing a non-partitioned table or index and ALTER INDEX REBUILD statement. [UN]RECOVERABLE is being deprecated in V8 and will be obsoleted in V9. To duplicate semantics of UNRECOVERABLE clause, create an object with NOLOGGING option and then ALTER it specifying LOGGING. To duplicate semantics of RECOVERABLE clause, create an object with LOGGING option.

column6: LOGGING/NOLOGGING may not be specified for a clustered table
column7: An attempt was made to specify LOGGING or NOLOGGING clause in CREATE TABLE or ALTER TABLE statement involving a clustered table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove offending clause.

column6: partition specification is required for a partitioned object
column7: parameter which supplies partition name is missing. This parameter is optional for non-partitioned objects, but is required for partitioned objects.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the missing parameter.

column6: illegal partition-extended table name syntax
column7: Partition to be accessed may only be specified using its name. An attempt was made to use a partition number or a bind variable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the statement to refer to a partition using its name.

column6: partition-extended object names may only be used with tables
column7: An attempt was made to use a partition-extended object name with an object which is not a table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid using partition-extended name syntax with objects which are not tables.

column6: partitioning column may not be of type ROWID
column7: Partitioning column specified by the user was of type ROWID, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that no partitioning column is of type ROWID.

column6: creation of GLOBAL partitioned indices on clustered tables is not supported
column7: An attempt was made to create a GLOBAL partitioned index on a clustered table which is currently illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove PARTITION BY RANGE() clause along with (partition_list) to create a GLOBAL non-partitioned index on a clustered table.

column6: RECOVERABLE/UNRECOVERABLE may not be specified for a partition or subpartition
column7: Description of a partition or subpartition found in CREATE TABLE/INDEX statement contained RECOVERABLE or UNRECOVERABLE clause which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove offending clause. Use LOGGING or NOLOGGING instead.

column6: partitioned table cannot have column with LOB datatype
column7: An attempt was made to create a partitioned table with a LOB datatype or tried to add a LOB datatype column to a partitioned table.
column8: From Oracle doc: LOB data types are not supported with partitioned tables. Create table without LOB column or change table to not partitioned. If adding column, do not use LOB datatype. If modifying attributes of a column to change data type to LOB, it has to be a non-partitioned table.

column6: partitioned table cannot have column with object, REF, nested table, array datatype
column7: An attempt was made to create a partitioned table with a object datatype (object, REF, nested table, array) or tried to add a object datatype column to a partitioned table.
column8: From Oracle doc: object data types are not supported with partitioned tables. Create table without object column or change table to not partitioned. If adding column, do not use object datatypes. If modifying attributes of a column to change data type to object, it has to be a non-partitioned table.

column6: partition bound of partition number %s is too long
column7: Length of linear key representation of a high bound of the partition whose number (partitions are numbered starting with 1) is displayed in this message exceeded the legal limit (4K).
column8: From Oracle doc: Change representation of a partition high bound to bring its length within legal limit.

column6: partition bound of partition "%s" is too long
column7: Length of linear key representation of a high bound of the partition whose name (explicitly specified by the user) is displayed in this message exceeded the legal limit (4K).
column8: From Oracle doc: Change representation of a partition high bound to bring its length within legal limit.

column6: partition resides in offlined tablespace
column7: User attempted an operation requiring that we access data in a partition which resides in a tablespace which was taken offline. Such operations include trying to drop a tablespace of a table which has indices defined on it or is referenced by a constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the tablespace online before attempting the operation.

column6: CHECK constraint mismatch in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION
column7: The corresponding columns in the tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION statement have CHECK constraint defined on them.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables do not have CHECK constraint defined on any column.

column6: specified partition bound is too long
column7: Length of a linear key representation of a high bound of a table partition being added or along which an existing table or index partition is being split exceeded the legal limit (4K).
column8: From Oracle doc: Change representation of a partition high bound to bring its length within legal limit.

column6: incompletely specified partition bound for a DATE column
column7: An attempt was made to use a date expression whose format does not fully (that is, day, month, and year (including century)) specify a date as a partition bound for a DATE column. The format may have been specified explicitly (using TO_DATE() function) or implicitly (NLS_DATE_FORMAT).
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that date format used in a partition bound for a DATE column supports complete specification of a date (that is, day, month, and year (including century)). If NLS_DATE_FORMAT does not support complete (that is, including the century) specification of the year, use TO_DATE() (for example, TO_DATE('01-01-1999', 'MM-DD-YYYY') to fully express the desired date.

column6: MODIFY DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES may not be combined with other operations
column7: ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement attempted to combine MODIFY DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES with some other operation (for example, ADD PARTITION or PCTFREE) which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that MODIFY DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES is the sole operation specified in ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement; operations other than those dealing with partitions, default attributes of partitioned tables/indices or specifying that a table be renamed (ALTER TABLE RENAME) may be combined at will.

column6: only one REVERSE or NOREVERSE clause may be specified
column7: Both REVERSE and NOREVERSE were specified in CREATE INDEX statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the REVERSE or NOREVERSE clauses and reissue the statement.

column6: duplicate NOREVERSE clause
column7: NOREVERSE was specified more than once in ALTER INDEX statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the NOREVERSE clauses and reissue the statement.

column6: duplicate REVERSE clause
column7: REVERSE was specified more than once in ALTER INDEX or CREATE INDEX statements.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the REVERSE clauses and reissue the statement.

column6: REVERSE/NOREVERSE may not be specified in this context
column7: REVERSE/NOREVERSE clause is not allowed in this context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove offending clause. REVERSE may be specified as an attribute of an index (not of an individual partition, if creating a partitioned index) in CREATE INDEX statement and ALTER INDEX REBUILD statement. NOREVERSE may be specified only in ALTER INDEX REBUILD statement.

column6: only a parallel_clause may follow description(s) of resulting partitions
column7: Descriptions of partition(s) resulting from splitting of a table or index partition may be followed by an optional parallel_clause which applies to the entire statement and which, in turn, may not be followed by any other clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that all partition attributes appear within the parenthesized list of descriptions of resulting partitions in ALTER TABLE/INDEX SPLIT PARTITION statement.

column6: FOREIGN KEY constraint mismatch in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION
column7: The corresponding columns in the tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION statement have different FOREIGN KEY constraints.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables do not have FOREIGN KEY constraints defined on any column or disable all FOREIGN KEY constraints on both tables. Then retry the operation.

column6: INCLUDING INDEXES must be specified as tables have enabled UNIQUE constraints
column7: Matching UNIQUE constraints in both table are enabled and validated but INCLUDING INDEXES is not specified in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION|SUBPARTITION command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Disable currently enabled matching UNIQUE constraints on both tables or ensure that INCLUDING INDEXES option is used.

column6: UNIQUE constraints mismatch in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION
column7: One of the tables named in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION command has a UNIQUE constraint for which no matching (vis-a-vis key columns) constraint is defined on the other table or a matching constraint is defined on the other table, but it differs from that defined on the first table vis-a-vis being enabled and/or validated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that for every UNIQUE constraint defined on one of the tables named in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION statement there is a matching (vis-a-vis key columns and being enabled and/or validated) UNIQUE constraint defined on the other table. If UNIQUE constrains are enabled, UNIQUE constraints on the partitioned table should be enforced using local indexes.

column6: enabled UNIQUE constraint exists on one of the tables
column7: One of the tables referenced in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION|SUBPARTITION statement has enabled UNIQUE constraint(s) defined on it, which prevents EXCHANGE from proceeding.
column8: From Oracle doc: Disable constraints defined on tables referenced in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION|SUBPARTITION statement and retry the statement.

column6: table cannot be used in EXCHANGE
column7:
An attempt was made to issue an ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION | SUBPARTITION command, but the non-partitioned table cannot be used in the EXCHANGE because one or more of the following apply: 

it is a typed table 

it contains ADT columns 

it contains nested-table columns 

it contains REF columns 

it contains array columns 

it is an index-organized table 

it contains LOB columns 

it is a nested table
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the non-partitioned table does not violate any of the above restrictions for the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION | SUBPARTITION command.

column6: ALTER TABLE MOVE cannot be combined with other operations
column7: An attempt was made to combine an ALTER TABLE MOVE statement with another operation, such as MODIFY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that MOVE is the only operation specified in ALTER TABLE statement.

column6: indexes cannot use both DESC and REVERSE
column7: An attempt was made to make a reverse index with some index columns marked DESC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use DESC in reverse indexes. The rule-based optimizer can scan indexes backwards, which allows a normal reverse index to simulate a reverse index with columns marked DESC.

column6: a LOB column cannot serve as a partitioning column
column7: An attempt was made to specify a column of type BLOB or CLOB as a partitioning or subpartitioning column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that no partitioning or subpartitioning column is of type BLOB or CLOB.

column6: missing SUBPARTITION keyword
column7: Keyword SUBPARTITION missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the missing parameter.

column6: invalid table partitioning method
column7: Invalid partitioning method was specified in CREATE TABLE statement. A table may be partitioned by RANGE, HASH, or composite range/hash (R+H).
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of valid partitioning methods.

column6: invalid number of partitions specified in PARTITIONS clause
column7: number-of-partitions clause contained in CREATE TABLE or CREATE INDEX statement specified a number of partitions outside of legal range (1-65535).
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a number between 1 and 65535 in the number-of-partitions clause.

column6: only one of STORE IN or partition_description clause may be specified
column7: Both STORE IN and partition_description clauses were specified in a CREATE TABLE|INDEX command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of offending clauses.

column6: only one of STORE IN or subpartition_description clause may be specified
column7: Both STORE IN and subpartition_description clauses were specified in a CREATE TABLE|INDEX, or ALTER TABLE ADD|SPLIT PARTITION or ALTER TABLE MERGE PARTITIONS command for a composite range-partitioned object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of offending clauses.

column6: missing PARTITION or SUBPARTITION keyword
column7: Expected either the PARTITION or SUBPARTITION keyword but neither was supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the missing keyword.

column6: invalid number of subpartitions specified in SUBPARTITIONS clause
column7: Number-of-subpartitions clause contained in CREATE TABLE or CREATE INDEX statement specified a number of subpartitions outside of legal range (1-65535).
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a number between 1 and 65535 in the number-of-subpartitions clause.

column6: invalid subpartition name
column7: A subpartition name of the form identifier is expected but not present.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter an appropriate subpartition name.

column6: too many subpartition descriptions
column7: CREATE TABLE or CREATE INDEX contained too many subpartition descriptions; maximum number of subpartitions is 65535.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of subpartitions to not exceed 65535.

column6: duplicate subpartition name
column7: Name of a subpartition of a table or index being created is not unique.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rename the subpartition(s) to ensure that their names are unique among subpartitions of the table or index being created.

column6: this physical attribute may not be specified for a table subpartition
column7: An unexpected option was encountered while parsing physical attributes of a table subpartition; TABLESPACE is the only valid option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid option(s).

column6: subpartition number %s: sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE may not exceed 100
column7: The sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for a subpartition whose number (subpartitions are numbered starting with 1) is displayed in this message exceeds 100. Note that if PCTUSED and/or PCTFREE values for this subpartition were not specified explicitly, default values at partition-level would be used. If, in turn, default PCTUSED and/or PCTFREE values at partition-level were not specified, default values for the partitioned table or index would be used. If those values were also not specified explicitly, system defaults would be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for the subpartition does not exceed 100.

column6: subpartition "%s": sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE may not exceed 100
column7: The sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for a subpartition whose name (explicitly specified by the user) is displayed in this message exceeds 100. Note that if PCTUSED and/or PCTFREE values for this subpartition were not specified explicitly, default values at partition-level would be used. If, in turn, default PCTUSED and/or PCTFREE values at partition-level were not specified, default values for the partitioned table or index would be used. If those values were also not specified explicitly, system defaults would be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a sum of PCTUSED and PCTFREE for the subpartition does not exceed 100.

column6: subpartition number %s: INITRANS value must be less than MAXTRANS value
column7: The value of INITRANS was found to be greater than that of MAXTRANS for a subpartition whose number (subpartitions are numbered starting with 1) is displayed in this message. Note that if INITRANS and/or MAXTRANS values for this subpartition were not specified explicitly, default values at partition-level would be used. If, in turn, default INITRANS and/or MAXTRANS values at partition-level were not specified, default values for the partitioned table or index would be used. If those values were also not specified explicitly, system defaults would be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that value of INITRANS (whether specified explicitly or derived from the default value at partition-level, table-level or index-level) is no greater than that of MAXTRANS.

column6: subpartition "%s": INITRANS value must be less than MAXTRANS value
column7: The value of INITRANS was found to be greater than that of MAXTRANS for a subpartition whose name (explicitly specified by the user) is displayed in this message. Note that if INITRANS and/or MAXTRANS values for this subpartition were not specified explicitly, default values at partition-level would be used. If, in turn, default INITRANS and/or MAXTRANS values at partition-level were not specified, default values for the partitioned table or index would be used. If those values were also not specified explicitly, system defaults would be used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that value of INITRANS (whether specified explicitly or derived from the default value at partition-level, table-level or index-level) is no greater than that of MAXTRANS.

column6: MODIFY DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES FOR PARTITION may not be combined with other operations
column7: An ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement attempted to combine MODIFY DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES OF PARTITION with some other operation (for example, ADD PARTITION or PCTFREE) which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that MODIFY DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES is the sole operation specified in ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement; operations other than those dealing with partitions, default attributes of partitioned tables/indices or specifying that a table be renamed (ALTER TABLE RENAME) may be combined at will.

column6: missing INTO keyword
column7: Keyword INTO missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the missing keyword.

column6: only one subpartition may be moved
column7: ALTER TABLE MOVE SUBPARTITION contained descriptions of more than one subpartition to be moved.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the statement describes exactly one subpartition to be moved and that it does not contain any commas.

column6: only one subpartition may be modified
column7: ALTER TABLE|INDEX MODIFY SUBPARTITION contained descriptions of more than one subpartition to be modified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the statement describes exactly one subpartition to be modified and that it does not contain any commas.

column6: invalid ALTER TABLE MODIFY SUBPARTITION option
column7: An option other than PCTFREE, PCTUSED, INITRANS, MAXTRANS, STORAGE, was specified in an ALTER TABLE MODIFY SUBPARTITION statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: cannot specify partition_description clause in CREATE TABLE|INDEX
column7: User requested to generate default partition description(s) (possibly via PARTITIONS number_of_partitions) while at the same time specified partition_description clause which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of offending clauses.

column6: cannot specify subpartition_description clause in CREATE|ALTER TABLE
column7: User requested to generate default subpartition description(s) (possibly via SUBPARTITIONS) while at the same time specified subpartition_description clause which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove one of offending clauses.

column6: invalid ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION option
column7: Name of the table to be EXCHANGED has to be followed by [{INCLUDING|EXCLUDING} INDEX][{WITH|WITHOUT} VALIDATION].
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that no options besides INCLDING INDEX or EXCLUDING INDEX are specified with ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION.

column6: illegal subpartition-extended table name syntax
column7: Subpartition to be accessed may only be specified using its name. An attempt was made to use a subpartition number or a bind variable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify statement to refer to a subpartition using its name.

column6: only a parallel_clause may follow COALESCE PARTITION|SUBPARTITION
column7: ALTER TABLE COALESCE PARTITION|SUBPARTITION may be followed by an optional parallel_clause. No partition/subpartition attributes may be specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that no partition/subpartition attribute was specified.

column6: a subpartition maintenance operation may not be combined with other operations
column7: An ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement attempted to combine a subpartition maintenance operation (for example, MOVE SUBPARTITION) with some other operation (for example, MODIFY PARTITION ADD SUBPARTITION or PCTFREE) which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a subpartition maintenance operation is the sole operation specified in ALTER TABLE or ALTER INDEX statement; operations other than those dealing with subpartitions, default attributes of partitioned tables/indices or specifying that a table be renamed (ALTER TABLE RENAME) may be combined at will.

column6: this attribute may not be specified for a hash partition
column7: An invalid option was encountered while parsing physical attributes of a partition of a table partitioned using the HASH method. The TABLESPACE option is the only valid option for such partitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid option(s).

column6: TABLESPACE DEFAULT can be specified only for Composite LOCAL index
column7: An attempt was made to specify TABLESPACE DEFAULT for a partition of a range/system/hash-partitioned LOCAL index object, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace TABLESPACE DEFAULT with TABLESPACE ts_name or remove it.

column6: incorrect physical attribute specified for this index partition
column7: An unexpected option was encountered while parsing physical attributes of a local index partition; valid options for range composite range partitions are INITRANS, MAXTRANS, TABLESPACE, STORAGE, PCTFREE, PCTUSED, LOGGING and TABLESPACE; but only TABLESPACE may be specified for hash partitions STORE IN () is also disallowed for all but composite range partitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid option(s) from the list of physical attributes of an index partition.

column6: number of sub-partitions of LOCAL index must equal that of the underlying table
column7: An attempt was made to create a LOCAL partitioned index with a number of subpartitions which is different from that of the underlying table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the CREATE INDEX statement to specify a correct number of subpartitions.

column6: partitioning method for LOCAL index is inconsistent with that of the underlying table
column7: An attempt was made to create a LOCAL partitioned index that is not equipartitioned with the underlying table. The partitioning types are mismatched.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the CREATE INDEX statement to ensure that the index partitioning method is consistent with that of the base table.

column6: sub-partitioning columns must form a subset of key columns of a UNIQUE index
column7: An attempt was made to create a UNIQUE partitioned index whose subpartitioning columns do not form a subset of its key columns which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you want to create an index whose subpartitioning columns do not form a subset of its key columns, it must be created as non-UNIQUE; otherwise, correct the list of key and/or subpartitioning columns to ensure that the index's subpartitioning columns form a subset of its key columns.

column6: this physical attribute may not be specified for an index subpartition
column7: An unexpected option was encountered while parsing physical attributes of an index subpartition; TABLESPACE is the only valid option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid option(s).

column6: only one ENABLE/DISABLE ROW MOVEMENT clause can be specified
column7:
One of the following: 

ENABLE ROW MOVEMENT was specified more than once. 

DISABLE ROW MOVEMENT was specified more than once. 

Both ENABLE ROW MOVEMENT and DISABLE ROW MOVEMENT were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the ENABLE ROW MOVEMENT or DISABLE ROW MOVEMENT clauses and then reissue the command.

column6: ALLOCATE STORAGE may not be specified for Composite Range partitioned object
column7: User specified ALLOCATE STORAGE clause in ALTER TABLE/ALTER INDEX statement issued against a range-partitioned index which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option. If it is desired to add storage to individual partitions, ALLOCATE STORAGE clause may be specified with ALTER TABLE/INDEX MODIFY PARTITION statement.

column6: cannot modify physical index attributes of a Hash index partition
column7: An attempt was made to modify one of INITRANS/MAXTRANS/LOGGING/STORAGE clause for an index partition of a hash-partitioned index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the physical attributes one is trying to modify.

column6: invalid ALTER INDEX MODIFY SUBPARTITION option
column7: An option other than UNUSABLE, ALLOCATE EXTENT, DEALLOCATE UNUSED was specified in an ALTER INDEX MODIFY SUBPARTITION statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.

column6: only one subpartition may be rebuilt
column7: ALTER INDEX REBUILD SUBPARTITION contained descriptions of more than one subpartition to be rebuilt.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the statement describes exactly one subpartition to be rebuilt and that it does not contain any commas.

column6: ALLOCATE STORAGE may not be specified for RANGE partitioned object
column7: User specified ALLOCATE STORAGE clause in ALTER TABLE/ALTER INDEX statement issued against a range-partitioned index which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option. If it is desired to add storage to individual partitions, ALLOCATE STORAGE clause may be specified with ALTER TABLE/INDEX MODIFY PARTITION statement.

column6: Specified subpartition does not exist
column7: Subpartition not found for the object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry with correct subpartition name.

column6: invalid ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION option for a Hash partition
column7: Only ALLOCATE EXTENT and DEALLOCATE UNUSED may be specified in ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION for a hash partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only legal options.
