column6: table is not partitioned by Composite Range method
column7: The table in a subpartition maintenance operation (ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE/MODIFY/MOVE/TRUNCATE SUBPARTITION, or ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION ADD/COALESCE SUBPARTITION command must be partitioned by composite range method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table is partitioned by composite range method.

column6: cannot specify ALLOCATE STORAGE for a (Composite) Range partitioned table
column7: User specified ALLOCATE STORAGE clause in ALTER TABLE statement issued against a range or composite range partitioned table which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option. If it is desired to add storage to individual partitions/subpartitions, ALLOCATE STORAGE clause may be specified with ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION/SUBPARTITION statement. If it is desired to add storage to all subpartitions of a Composite partition, ALLOCATE STORAGE clause may be specified with ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION.

column6: table is not partitioned by Range or Composite Range method
column7: ALTER TABLE SPLIT/DROP PARTITION or ALTER TABLE MERGE PARTITIONS command is only valid for table partitioned by range or composite range method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table is partitioned by range or composite range method.

column6: invalid resulting partition description(s)
column7: User specified STORE-IN clause, SUBPARTITIONS clause, and/or subpartition_description clause in partition description(s) in ALTER TABLE SPLIT PARTITION or ALTER TABLE MERGE PARTITIONS statement but the table in the maintenance operation is not a composite range-partitioned table which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid clause(s), or ensure that the table is partitioned by composite range method.

column6: cannot move partition other than a Range or Hash partition
column7: An attempt was made to move a partition that is not a range or hash partition which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify MOVE PARTITION for a range or hash partition only.

column6: invalid partition description
column7: User specified STORE-IN clause, SUBPARTITIONS clause, and/or subpartition_description clause in ALTER TABLE ADD PARTITION statement but the table in the maintenance operation is not a composite range/hash-partitioned table which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid clause(s), or ensure that the table is partitioned by composite range/hash method.

column6: table is not partitioned by Hash method
column7: ALTER TABLE COALESCE PARTITION is only valid for table partitioned by Hash method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid ALTER TABLE option for the table, or ensure that the table is partitioned by Hash method.

column6: incorrect physical attribute specified for this partition
column7: User specified INITRANS, MAXTRANS, STORAGE, PCTFREE, PCTUSED, and/or [NO]LOGGING option to a hash partition via ALTER TABLE ADD/MOVE PARTITION command which is illegal. Only TABLESPACE may be specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid option(s).

column6: partition bound may not be specified when adding this Hash partition
column7: User specified VALUES LESS THAN clause when adding a partition (via ALTER TABLE ADD PARTITION) to a hash-partitioned table which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the VALUES LESS THAN clause from the description of partition being added.

column6: new subpartition name must differ from the old subpartition name
column7: User entered ALTER TABLE/INDEX RENAME SUBPARTITION specifying new_subpartition_name which is identical to the name of the subpartition being renamed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the new subpartition name is different from the name of any (including the one being renamed) existing subpartition of a given table or index.

column6: new subpartition name must differ from that of any other subpartition of the object
column7: User entered ALTER TABLE/INDEX RENAME SUBPARTITION specifying new_subpartition_name which is identical to the name of some existing subpartition of the object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the new subpartition name is different from the name of any (including the one being renamed) existing subpartition of a given table or index.

column6: table is not partitioned by Composite Range method
column7: The table in the MODIFY DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES FOR PARTITION operation is partitioned by method other than Composite method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table is partitioned by Composite method.

column6: data type or length of a table subpartitioning column may not be changed
column7: User issued ALTER TABLE statement attempting to modify data type and/or length of a column used to subpartition the table named in ALTER TABLE statement, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid modifying data type and/or length of table subpartitioning column(s).

column6: data type or length of an index subpartitioning column may not be changed
column7: User issued ALTER TABLE statement attempting to modify data type and/or length of a column used to subpartition some index defined on the table named in ALTER TABLE statement, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid modifying data type and/or length of index subpartitioning column(s).

column6: cannot specify PARALLEL clause when adding a (Composite) Range partition
column7: User issued ALTER TABLE ADD PARTITION statement with PARALLEL clause for a range or composite range partition which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the PARALLEL clause.

column6: subpartition '%s' of the partition resides in offlined tablespace
column7: User attempted an operation requiring that we access data in a subpartition which resides in a tablespace which was taken offline. Such operations include trying to drop a tablespace of a table which has indices defined on it or is referenced by a constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring tablespace online before attempting the operation.

column6: cannot exchange partition other than a Range or Hash partition
column7: User attempt to exchange a partition with a non-partitioned table but the specified partition is not a range or hash partition which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify EXCHANGE PARTITION for a range or hash partition only.

column6: table is not partitioned by Range or Hash method
column7: The table in ALTER TABLE MODIFY PARTITION {UNUSABLE LOCAL INDEXES | REBUILD UNUSABLE LOCAL INDEXES} statement is not partitioned by range or hash method which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table is partitioned by range or hash method.

column6: table is not partitioned by Composite Range/Hash method
column7: The table in ALTER TABLE MODIFY SUBPARTITION {UNUSABLE LOCAL INDEXES | REBUILD UNUSABLE LOCAL INDEXES} statement is not partitioned by composite range/hash method which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table is partitioned by composite range/hash method.

column6: only a partition with higher bound can be reused
column7: User attempt to reuse a lower-bound partition in ALTER TABLE MERGE PARTITIONS statement as the resulting partition which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the higher-bound partition to be the resulting partition or specify a new partition name.

column6: lower-bound partition must be specified first
column7: User specified higher-bound partition before lower-bound partition in ALTER TABLE MERGE PARTITIONS statement which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify lower-bound partition then higher-bound partition.

column6: partitions being merged are not adjacent
column7: User attempt to merge two partitions that are not adjacent to each other which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify two partitions that are adjacent.

column6: cannot reuse lower-bound partition as resulting partition
column7: User attempt to reuse lower-bound partition of the partitions being merged which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify new resulting partition name or reuse the higher-bound partition only.

column6: EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION requires a non-partitioned, non-clustered table
column7: The table in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION operation is either clustered or partitioned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table with which the subpartition is being exchanged for is not partitioned or clustered.

column6: tables in EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION must have the same number of columns
column7: The two tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION have different number of columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables have the same number of columns with the same type and size.

column6: column type or size mismatch in EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION
column7: The corresponding columns in the tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION are of different type or size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables have the same number of columns with the same type and size.

column6: index mismatch for tables in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION
column7: The two tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION have indexes which are not equivalent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the indexes for the two tables have indexes which follow this rule For every non-partitioned index for the non-partitioned table, there has to be an identical LOCAL index on the partitioned table and vice versa. By identical, the column position, type and size have to be the same.

column6: all rows in table do not qualify for specified subpartition
column7: There is at least one row in the non-partitioned table which does not qualify for the subpartition specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that all the rows in the segment qualify for the subpartition. Perform the alter table operation with the NO CHECKING option. Run ANALYZE table VALIDATE on that subpartition to find out the invalid rows and delete them.

column6: CHECK constraint mismatch in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION
column7: The corresponding columns in the tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION statement have CHECK constraint defined on them.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables do not have CHECK constraint defined on any column.

column6: FOREIGN KEY constraint mismatch in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION
column7: The corresponding columns in the tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION statement have different FOREIGN KEY constraints.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables do not have FOREIGN KEY constraints defined on any column or disable all FOREIGN KEY constraints on both tables. Then retry the operation.

column6: UNIQUE constraints mismatch in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION
column7: One of the tables named in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION command has a UNIQUE constraint for which no matching (vis-a-vis key columns) constraint is defined on the other table or a matching constraint is defined on the other table, but it differs from that defined on the first table vis-a-vis being enabled and/or validated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that for every UNIQUE constraint defined on one of the tables named in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE SUBPARTITION statement there is a matching (vis-a-vis key columns and being enabled and/or validated) UNIQUE constraint defined on the other table. If UNIQUE constrains are enabled, UNIQUE constraints on the partitioned table should be enforced using local indexes.

column6: one or more of table's subpartitions reside in a read-only tablespace
column7: User issued ALTER TABLE statement attempting to modify an existing VARCHAR2 (or VARCHAR) column to be of type CHAR (or CHARACTER), increase length of an existing CHAR (or CHARACTER) column, or add a column with user-specified default for a table one or more subpartitions of which reside in read-only tablespaces, which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid performing aforementioned operations on a partitioned table one or more subpartitions of which reside in read-only tablespaces.

column6: cannot COALESCE the only partition of this partitioned table
column7: A COALESCE PARTITION command was issued when there is only one partition in the table which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that there is at least one partition. Drop table to remove all partitions.

column6: cannot COALESCE the only subpartition of this table partition
column7: A COALESCE SUBPARTITION command was issued when there is only one subpartition in the partition which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that there is at least one subpartition. Drop partition to remove all subpartitions.

column6: cannot REBUILD a partition of a Composite Range partitioned index
column7: An attempt was made to rebuild a partition of a composite range-partitioned index which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: REBUILD the index partition, a subpartition at a time.

column6: index is not partitioned by Composite Range method
column7: The index in a partition or subpartition maintenance operation (ALTER INDEX MODIFY [SUBPARTITION|DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES FOR PARTITION] or ALTER INDEX REBUILD SUBPARTITION command must be partitioned by composite range method.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: cannot make local index partition of Composite Range partitioned table unusable
column7: An attempt was made to rebuild a partition of a composite range partitioned index which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: PRIMARY KEY constraint mismatch in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE [SUB]PARTITION
column7: The corresponding columns in the tables specified in the ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE [SUB]PARTITION statement have different PRIMARY KEY constraints.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the two tables do not have PRIMARY KEY constraints defined on any column or disable all PRIMARY KEY constraints on both tables. Then retry the operation.

column6: cannot EXCHANGE a composite partition with a non-partitioned table
column7: A composite partition can only be exchanged with a partitioned table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the table being exchanged is partitioned or that that the partition being exchanged is non-composite.

column6: Partitioning type of table must match subpartitioning type of composite partition
column7: When exchanging a partitioned table with a composite partition, the partitioning type of the table must match the subpartitioning type of the composite partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the partitioning type of partitioned table is the same as the subpartitioning type of the composite partition.

column6: Number of partitioning columns does not match number of subpartitioning columns
column7: When exchanging a partitioned table with a composite partition, the number of partitioning columns of the table must match the number of subpartitioning columns of the composite partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the number of partitioning columns in the partitioned table is the same as the number of subpartitioning columns in the composite partition.

column6: Number of partitions does not match number of subpartitions
column7: When exchanging a partitioned table with a composite partition, the number of partitions of the table must match the number of subpartitions of the composite partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the number of partitions in the partitioned table is the same as the number of subpartitions in the the composite partition.

column6: column type or size mismatch between partitioning columns and subpartitioning columns
column7: When exchanging a partitioned table with a composite partition, the type and size of the partitioning columns of the table must match the type and size of the subpartitioning columns of the composite partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the type and size of the partitioning columns of the partitioned is the same as the type and size of the subpartitioning columns of the composite partition.

column6: table-level attributes must be specified before partition-level attributes
column7: While processing an ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN statement, table-level attributes of LOB columns were encountered after processing partition-level attributes of LOB columns or while processing CREATE TABLE statement, table-level attributes of LOB columns were encountered after processing partition descriptions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the SQL statement to specify table-level attributes prior to partition-level attributes or partition descriptions; then retry the statement.

column6: only one list of added-LOB-storage-clauses can be specified in a statement
column7: While parsing an ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN statement, one list of added-LOB-storage-clauses was parsed when another list of added-LOB-storage-clauses was encountered. There cannot be more than one list of added-LOB-storage-clauses in a statement; all added-LOB-storage-clauses must be combined into one list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Combine all of the lists of added-LOB-storage-clauses into one list and retry the statement.

column6: partitions or subpartitions are not in the right order
column7: Descriptions of partitions or subpartitions in an ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN statement were ordered differently from the DDL order of partitions or subpartitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-order the partitions or subpartitions in the added LOB storage clause by partition or subpartition DDL order, and retry the statement.

column6: inserted partition key is beyond highest legal partition key
column7: At attempt was made to insert a record with a concatenated partition key that is beyond the concatenated partition bound list of the last partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not insert the key. Or, add a partition capable of accepting the key.

column6: inserted partition key is outside specified partition
column7: The concatenated partition key of an inserted record is outside the ranges of the two concatenated partition bound lists that delimit the partition named in the INSERT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not insert the key or insert it in another partition.

column6: updating partition key column would cause a partition change
column7: An UPDATE statement attempted to change the value of a partition key column causing migration of the row to another partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to update a partition key column or make sure that the new partition key is within the range containing the old partition key.

column6: cursor invalidation detected after getting DML partition lock
column7: Cursor invalidation was detected after acquiring a partition lock during an INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: partitioned table contains partitions in a different tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to drop a tablespace which contains tables whose partitions are not completely contained in this tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find tables with partitions which span the tablespace being dropped and some other tablespace(s). Drop these tables or move partitions to a different tablespace.

column6: partitioned index contains partitions in a different tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to drop a tablespace which contains indexes whose partitions are not completely contained in this tablespace, and which are defined on the tables which are completely contained in this tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find indexes with partitions which span the tablespace being dropped and some other tablespace(s). Drop these indexes, or move the index partitions to a different tablespace, or find the tables on which the indexes are defined, and drop (or move) them.

column6: updated partition key is beyond highest legal partition key
column7: At attempt was made to update a record with a concatenated partition key that is beyond the concatenated partition bound list of the last partition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not update the key. Or, add a partition capable of accepting the key.

column6: partitioned table contains subpartitions in a different tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to drop a tablespace which contains tables whose subpartitions are not completely contained in this tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find tables with subpartitions which span the tablespace being dropped and some other tablespace(s). Drop these tables or move subpartitions to a different tablespace.

column6: partitioned index contains subpartitions in a different tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to drop a tablespace which contains indexes whose subpartitions are not completely contained in this tablespace, and which are defined on the tables which are completely contained in this tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find indexes with subpartitions which span the tablespace being dropped and some other tablespace(s). Drop these indexes, or move the index partitions to a different tablespace, or find the tables on which the indexes are defined, and drop (or move) them.

column6: inserted partition key is outside specified subpartition
column7: The concatenated partition key of an inserted record is outside the ranges of the two concatenated subpartition bound lists that delimit the subpartition named in the INSERT statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not insert the key or insert it in another subpartition.

column6: attempt to access a transactional temp table already in use
column7: An attempt was made to access a transactional temporary table that has been already populated by a concurrent transaction of the same session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to access the temporary table until the concurrent transaction has committed or aborted.

column6: unsupported feature with temporary table
column7: An attempt was made to create an IOT, specify physical attributes, specify partition or parallel clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: attempt to create, alter or drop an index on temporary table already in use
column7: An attempt was made to create, alter or drop an index on temporary table which is already in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: All the sessions using the session-specific temporary table have to truncate table and all the transactions using transaction specific temporary table have to end their transactions.

column6: attempt to use a LOB of a temporary table, whose data has already been purged
column7: An attempt was made to use LOB from a temporary table whose data has been dropped either because table was transaction-specific and transaction has committed or aborted, table was truncated or session which created this LOB has ended.
column8: From Oracle doc: This LOB locator is invalid and cannot be used.

column6: attempt to reference temporary table in a referential integrity constraint
column7: An attempt was made to reference temporary table in a referential integrity constraint. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use triggers.

column6: attempt to create referential integrity constraint on temporary table
column7: An attempt was made to create a referential integrity constraint on a temporary table. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use triggers.

column6: cannot rebuild index on a temporary table
column7: An attempt was made to rebuild an index on a temporary table.
column8: From Oracle doc: The index data is anyway lost at end of session/transaction.

column6: disallowed VARRAY and Nested Table column in a Temporary table
column7: An attempt made to create a VARRAY or Nested Table column in a temporary table. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify these datatypes for temporary tables.

column6: attempt was made to create a temporary table with INDEX organization
column7: An attempt was made to create an Index Organized Temporary table. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the table with HEAP organization and the primary key.

column6: missing GLOBAL keyword
column7: Keyword GLOBAL is missing while creating temporary table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the missing keyword.

column6: LOCAL option not valid without partition name
column7: Incorrect syntax specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command.

column6: object is not partitioned
column7: Table or index is not partitioned. Invalid syntax.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command with correct syntax.

column6: only one partition name can be specified
column7: More than one partition name has been specified for analyze.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one partition name.

column6: syntax not supported for analyze
column7: A partition/subpartition number or bind variable has been used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid partition/subpartition name.

column6: LOCAL option valid only for partitioned indexes
column7: Incorrect syntax specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command.

column6: LOCAL option required for partitioned indexes
column7: Incorrect syntax specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command.

column6: partition corrupt. all rows do not fall within partition bounds
column7: The partition contains rows which should really be in some other partition. Possibly due to an exchange partition without validation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Delete rows in partition which do not qualify.

column6: specified VALIDATE INTO table not found
column7: The specified table either does not exist or user does not have the proper privileges.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct table to use.

column6: specified VALIDATE INTO table form incorrect
column7: The specified table does not have the proper field definitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct table to use. See UTLVALID.SQL for more information.

column6: can specify VALIDATE INTO clause only for partitioned tables
column7: The VALIDATE INTO has been specified for a non-partitioned table or cluster or index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the syntax correctly.

column6: cannot perform operation on a partitioned object
column7: An attempt was made to perform an operation that is not allowed on partitioned tables or indexes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command with correct syntax.

column6: cannot perform operation on a clustered object
column7: An attempt was made to perform an operation that is not allowed on clustered tables or indexes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command with correct syntax.

column6: partitioning column may not be of object datatype
column7: Partitioning column specified by the user was an object datatype (object, REF, nested table, array) which is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that no partitioning column is an object datatype.

column6: LOCAL option not valid without subpartition name
column7: Incorrect syntax specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the command.

column6: only one aubpartition name can be specified
column7: More than one subpartition name has been specified for analyze.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one subpartition name.

column6: subpartition corrupt. all rows do not fall within subpartition bounds
column7: The subpartition contains rows which should really be in some other subpartition. Possibly due to an exchange subpartition without validation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Delete rows in subpartition which do not qualify.

column6: subpartition of index '%s.%s' is in unusable state
column7: An attempt has been made to access an index subpartition that has been marked unusable by a direct load or by a DDL operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: REBUILD the unusable index subpartition.

column6: cannot perform a DML operation inside a query
column7: DML operation like insert, update, delete or select-for-update cannot be performed inside a query or under a PDML slave.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the offending DML operation is not performed or use an autonomous transaction to perform the DML operation within the query or PDML slave.

column6: cannot perform a DDL, commit or rollback inside a query or DML
column7: DDL operations like creation tables, views etc. and transaction control statements such as commit/rollback cannot be performed inside a query or a DML statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the offending operation is not performed or use autonomous transactions to perform the operation within the query/DML operation.

column6: cannot perform a lob write operation inside a query
column7: A LOB write operation cannot be performed inside a query or a PDML slave.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the offending LOB write operation is not performed or use an autonomous transaction to perform the operation within the query or PDML slave.

column6: database open for read-only access
column7: The database has been opened for read-only access. Attempts to modify the database using inappropriate DML or DDL statements generate this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: In order to modify the database, it must first be shut down and reopened for read-write access.

column6: database already open for read-only access by another instance
column7: The database has been opened for read-only access by another instance, and cannot be opened for read-write access by this instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: This instance must be opened for read-write access, or all other instances must first be shut down and reopened for read-only access.

column6: database already open for read-write access by another instance
column7: The database has been opened for read-write access by another instance, and cannot be opened for read-only access by this instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: This instance must be opened for read-only access, or all other instances must first be shut down and reopened for read-write access.

column6: standby database is restricted to read-only access
column7: To ensure its integrity, a standby database can only be opened for read-only access.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-issue the ALTER DATABASE OPEN specifying READ ONLY.

column6: backup database requires recovery
column7: The control file is for a backup database which requires recovery, and cannot be opened for read-only access by this instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform the necessary recovery and re-open for read-only access.

column6: database requires recovery
column7: The database requires recovery, and therefore cannot be opened for read-only access by this instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform the necessary recovery and re-open for read-only access.

column6: audit_trail destination incompatible with database open mode
column7: The AUDIT_TRAIL initialization parameter was set to "DB" (or TRUE), which is incompatible with a database opened for read-only access.
column8: From Oracle doc: When the database is opened for read-only access, the AUDIT_TRAIL initialization parameter can only be set to "OS" or "NONE" (FALSE).

column6: invalid backup controlfile checkpoint
column7: The backup control file being opened for read-only access does not contain a valid control file checkpoint. Therefore the database cannot be opened for read-only access.
column8: From Oracle doc: First open the database for read-write access which will result in valid control file checkpoint. Then re-open the database for read-only access.

column6: indeterminate controlfile checkpoint
column7: The control file for the database being opened for read-only access was created via CREATE CONTROLFILE. Therefore a control file checkpoint could not be calculated and the database cannot be opened for read-only access.
column8: From Oracle doc: First open the database for read-write access which will result in valid control file checkpoint. Then re-open the database for read-only access.

column6: remote archivelog destination must be a STANDBY database
column7: The database associated with the archive log destination service name is other than the required STANDBY type database. Remote archival of redo log files is not allowed to non-STANDBY database instances.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the necessary steps to create the required compatible STANDBY database before retrying the ARCHIVE LOG processing.

column6: remote archivelog destination database is opened for update
column7: The database associated with the archive log destination service name is opened for update access. Remote archival of redo log files to standby databases opened for update access is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shutdown the standby destination instance and re-open for read-only access or simple leave the standby instance mounted and unopened.

column6: Archivelog Remote File Server process in Error state
column7: The archive log remote file server (RFS) process at the specified standby database site has experienced an unrecoverable error and is unable to receive further archive log data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the problem at the standby database site.

column6: Archivelog standby database identifier mismatch
column7: The database identifiers of the Primary and Standby database do not match. Remote archival of redo log files is not allowed to incompatible STANDBY database instances.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the necessary steps to create the required compatible STANDBY database before retrying the ARCHIVE LOG processing.

column6: log %s sequence# %s does not need archiving
column7: An attempt was made to archive the named file manually, but the file did not require archiving. The file had previously been successfully archived.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: log %s sequence# %s not archived, no available destinations
column7: An attempt was made to archive the named log, but the archive was unsuccessful. The archive failed because there were no archive log destinations specified or all destinations experienced debilitating errors.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that archive log destinations are being specified and/or take the necessary step to correct any errors that may have occurred.

column6: log %s sequence# %s not archived, media recovery disabled
column7: An attempt was made to archive the named log, but the archive was unsuccessful. A standby archive log destination was specified and the database was not media recovery enabled. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Disable the standby destination or enable media recovery and retry.

column6: archived log for thread %s sequence# %s unavailable
column7: The sustained standby database recovery operation has timed out waiting for the requested archived log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the primary database is still archiving redo logs to the standby recovery database site and reissue the RECOVER STANDBY DATABASE WAIT command.

column6: cannot use LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST without a primary archive destination
column7: The parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST was set to a non-NULL value when the primary archive destination was set to NULL explicitly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the primary archive destination to a valid non-NULL value.

column6: cannot use %s with LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n
column7:
One of the following events caused an incompatibility: 

Parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST or LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST was in use when a LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5) parameter was encountered while fetching initialization parameters. 

An ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG START TO command was in effect when a LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter was encountered while fetching initialization parameters. 

A LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter was in use when an ALTER SYSTEM command was used to define a value for either the LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST or LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Eliminate any incompatible parameter definitions.

column6: cannot use %s with LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST or LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST
column7:
One of the following events caused an incompatibility: 

Parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST or LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST was in use when the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5) parameter was encountered while fetching initialization parameters. 

Parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST or LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST was in use when an attempt was made to use an ALTER SYSTEM or ALTER SESSION command to define a value for the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter. 

An ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG START TO command was in effect when the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter was encountered while fetching initialization parameters. 

An ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG START TO command was in effect when an attempt was made to use an ALTER SYSTEM or ALTER SESSION command to define a value for the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Eliminate any incompatible parameter definitions.

column6: less destinations available than specified by LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST
column7: With automatic archiving enabled, the number of archive log destinations that could be used for the database was less than the LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST parameter value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either adjust the settings of the log archive destination parameters, or lower the value of LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST.

column6: session %s destination cannot be the same as session %s destination
column7: An attempt was made to change the first specified archive log parameter using ALTER SESSION to have a destination value that duplicates the session-level destination value of the second specified archive log parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different session destination value for one of the LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameters.

column6: LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST cannot be NULL because LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST is non-NULL
column7: An attempt was made to change parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST to NULL when parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST is non-NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either set parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST to a non-NULL value, or set parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST to a NULL value.

column6: system %s destination cannot be the same as session %s destination
column7: An attempt to change the first specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5) parameter produced a destination that duplicates the session destination value of the second specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter. This error can occur when setting a non-NULL value with the ALTER SYSTEM command. Or, this error can occur when setting a NULL value with ALTER SESSION command, because then the associated system destination value may appear as a duplicate.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different destination value for the first specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter.

column6: parameter %s cannot be parsed
column7: The value for the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5) parameter could not be parsed. Common causes for this error are a misplaced equal sign, an unrecognized option, or an option that is missing a required value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value for the LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter.

column6: parameter %s contains repeated or conflicting options
column7: The value for the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5) parameter contained either repeated options or options that conflicted with each other.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value for the LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter.

column6: parameter %s contains an invalid reopen time
column7: The value for the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5) parameter contained a REOPEN option with an invalid numeric value. The valid range is 0-65535.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value for the LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter.

column6: parameter %s is missing a destination option
column7: The value for the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5) parameter failed to include a destination option. Valid destination options are LOCATION or SERVICE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value for the LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n parameter.

column6: new %s causes less destinations than LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST requires
column7: With automatic archiving enabled, an attempt was made to change the specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n or a LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_STATE_n parameter (n = 1...5) to a value that reduces the number of archive log destinations to less than the LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either select different options for the LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n or LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_STATE_n parameters, or reduce the value for parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST.

column6: cannot change LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST, no archive log destinations
column7: An attempt was made to change the LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST parameter when there are no archive log destinations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define one or more log archive destinations using parameters LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST, LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST, or LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5). Then, change the value of parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST.

column6: session specific change requires a LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n destination
column7: The following event caused an incompatibility: Parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST or LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST was in use when an attempt was made to change the LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST parameter with an ALTER SESSION command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace any LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST and LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST parameters with LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n (n = 1...5) parameters.

column6: parameter %s destination %s exceeds %s character limit
column7: The value for the specified parameter contained a destination string that is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the destination value for the specified parameter with a character string that has a length below the limit specified in the error message.

column6: parameter %s destination %s cannot be translated
column7: The value for the specified parameter contained a destination string that could not be translated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid destination string in the specified parameter.

column6: parameter %s destination cannot be the same as parameter %s destination
column7: An attempt was made to change the first specified archive log parameter to have a destination value that duplicates the system-level destination value of the second specified archive log parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different value for one of the archive log parameters.

column6: FROM parameter is incompatible with MANAGED recovery
column7: Use of the FROM 'location' parameter is not allowed when MANAGED recovery has been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax and retry the command.

column6: missing required keyword %s
column7: The keywords STANDBY DATABASE are required when MANAGED recovery has been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax and retry the command.

column6: invalid MANAGED recovery CANCEL option
column7: A mode other than IMMEDIATE follows the CANCEL keyword in RECOVER MANAGED STANDBY DATABASE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either nothing or IMMEDIATE following CANCEL.

column6: user requested cancel of sustained recovery operation
column7: The sustained standby database recovery operation has been canceled per user request.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: log %s sequence# %s cannot be archived
column7: An attempt was made to archive the named file, but the file could not be archived. Examine the secondary error messages to determine the cause of the error.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required.

column6: RFS request version mismatch
column7: A request to archive a redo log to a standby site failed because the request was incompatible with the Remote File Server (RFS) at the standby site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that compatible versions of Oracle are running on the primary and all standby sites.

column6: standby destination archivelog file is locked
column7: The target standby destination archive log file is currently locked. This indicates that the file is being archived to by another Remote File Server (RFS) process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for and eliminate duplicate standby destination archive log service names defined for the primary database.

column6: Remote File Server fatal error
column7: The Remote File Server (RFS) process at the standby destination archive log site has encountered a disabling error and is no longer available. Further archiving to the standby site may not be possible.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the appropriate RFS trace file located at the standby site for details regarding the error encountered and if possible take corrective action.

column6: user requested cancel immediate of sustained recovery operation
column7: The sustained standby database recovery operation has been canceled immediately per user request. Processing of the current archive log file has been interrupted and therefore the database is in an inconsistent state.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: FAL request rejected
column7: FAL server rejects the FAL request from the FAL client. This may be caused by different reasons.
column8: From Oracle doc: to solve the problem.

column6: standby database instance is not mounted
column7: The RFS process on the standby database received an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the standby alert log and RFS trace files for more information.

column6: archivelog rejected by RFS
column7: An attempt was made to re-archive an existing archivelog. This usually happens because either a multiple primary database or standby database(s) or both are trying to archive to this standby database.
column8: From Oracle doc: See alert log and trace file for more details. No action is necessary; this is an informational statement provided to record the event for diagnostic purposes.

column6: the password for %d user(s) is already expired. For user: %s  in databsae %s.
column7: The user's account password has expired and the password needs to be changed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the password or contact the database administrator.

column6: invalid outline name
column7: The parser detected a missing or invalid outline name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-issue the command, specifying a valid outline name.

column6: no options specified for ALTER OUTLINE
column7: The parser detected that no clause was specified on the command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-issue the command, specifying a valid ALTER OUTLINE clause.

column6: the specified outline does not exist
column7: Either the outline did not exist to begin with, or a timing window allowed for another thread to drop or alter the outline midstream.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for the existence of the outline and try again.

column6: an outline already exists with this signature
column7: The signature generation algorithm generates signatures that are 16 bytes in length so it is highly unlikely that any 2 signatures will be identical. This message is raised in such a rare case.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either re-issue the statement that led to the outline being created with some white space added or force the outline to be created in a different category.

column6: outline already exists
column7: An outline already exists, either with the specified name, or for the specified SQL text.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again with another name.

column6: create any outline privilege is required for this operation
column7: Create any outline privilege is required for the attempted operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure you have create any outline privilege and retry the operation.

column6: drop any outline privilege is required for this operation
column7: Drop any outline privilege is required for the attempted operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure you have drop any outline privilege and retry the operation.

column6: alter any outline privilege is required for this operation
column7: Alter any outline privilege is required for the attempted operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure you have alter any outline privilege and retry the operation.

column6: cannot find OUTLN schema
column7: The database creation script that creates this schema must not have been executed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Review the log files to see what happened when the database was created.

column6: one or more outline system tables do not exist
column7: Either the database creation script that creates these tables was not executed or a user accidently deleted the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Review the log files to see what happened when the database was created.

column6: command missing mandatory CATEGORY keyword
column7: User failed to specify the CATEGORY keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-issue the command with the CATEGORY keyword included.

column6: System type conflict with object SYS.%s
column7: The user had an object with the same name as one of the system types. The system types were not initialized properly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the conflicting object and re-run migration.

column6: device block size %s is invalid
column7: The device block size returned by sequential I/O OSD is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the block size was set by using the PARMS option of the Recovery Manager ALLOCATE CHANNEL command, then the specified block size must be changed. If no PARMS option was specified on the ALLOCATE CHANNEL command, then this is an internal error that should be reported to Oracle.

column6: read error on file "%s", blockno %s (blocksize=%s)
column7: Read error on input file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the file.

column6: write error on file "%s", blockno %s (blocksize=%s)
column7: Write error on output file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the file.

column6: cannot obtain information on device, name="%s", type="%s", parms="%s"
column7: Call to get device information returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check device name, type, and parameters.

column6: failed to create file "%s"
column7: Call to create file returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional messages and check access permissions.

column6: failed to identify file "%s"
column7: Call to identify the file returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional messages, and check whether the file exists.

column6: failed to create sequential file, name="%s", parms="%s"
column7: Call to create the sequential file returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional messages, check access permissions.

column6: failed to retrieve sequential file, handle="%s", parms="%s"
column7: Call to retrieve the sequential file returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional messages, and check if the file exists.

column6: failed to delete file "%s"
column7: Call to delete the file returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional messages.

column6: failed to delete sequential file, handle="%s", parms="%s"
column7: Call to delete the sequential file returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional messages.

column6: failed to set size of %s blocks for file "%s" (blocksize=%s)
column7: Call to resize the file returned an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional messages.

column6: %s
column7: An error occurred in the media management software which is linked with the Oracle server to perform backup and restore in cooperation with Recovery Manager.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the text of message 19511 does not provide enough information to resolve the problem, then you should contact the vendor of the media management software.

column6: cannot use backup/restore functions while using dispatcher
column7: An attempt was made to use backup/restore functions while connected to the dispatcher in a multi-threaded server. This is not allowed because the device that is used for backup and restore must remain allocated to a single process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect directly to the instance then re-execute the backup or restore function.

column6: device is busy, device type: %s, device name: %s
column7: The indicated device could not be allocated because it is allocated to another session, or no device was named, or all devices of the requested type are busy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either attempt to allocate another device or wait until the required device is no longer busy.

column6: device type %s is invalid
column7: The device type indicated is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a correct device type and retry the allocation.

column6: device name %s is invalid
column7: The device name indicated is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a correct device name and retry the allocation.

column6: error allocating device, device type: %s, device name: %s
column7: The specified device could not be allocated.
column8: From Oracle doc: One or more other messages should be displayed to help pinpoint the cause of the error. Correct the error and retry the allocation.

column6: invalid LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST parameter value
column7: The value of parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST was not set within the valid range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a correct value for parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST. If the archive log parameters LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST or LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST are in use, set parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_MIN_SUCCEED_DEST to either 1 or 2.

column6: required destination LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST currently is deferred
column7: The destination for parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST was deferred when it was required to be enabled. The destination was deferred automatically when an ALTER SYSTEM command for parameter LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST defined a destination which duplicated an existing LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST parameter destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the destination value for the LOG_ARCHIVE_DUPLEX_DEST parameter.

column6: device error, device type: %s, device name: %s
column7: An error occurred in the platform-specific device code.
column8: From Oracle doc: One or more other messages should be displayed to help pinpoint the cause of the error. Correct the error and retry the allocation.

column6: error de-allocating device
column7: The specified device could not be de-allocated.
column8: From Oracle doc: One or more other messages should be displayed to help pinpoint the cause of the error. Correct the error and retry the allocation.

column6: error sending device command: %s
column7: An error occurred while sending the indicated command to the session device.
column8: From Oracle doc: One or more other messages should be displayed to help pinpoint the cause of the error. Correct the error and retry the allocation.

column6: %s is not a valid device limit
column7: An invalid type of device limit was specified in a call to X$DBMS_BACKUP_RESTORE.SETLIMIT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use one of the documented limits: KBYTES, READRATE, or PARALLEL.

column6: %s requires a DISK channel
column7: The attempted command requires that a DISK device channel be allocated to the session, but a non-DISK device was found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Deallocate the current device and allocate a DISK channel, then retry the command.

column6: file %s is empty
column7: The indicated file, which is an archive log, control file, or datafile was found to be empty during a copy, backup, or scan] operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the correct files are being specified for the copy or backup operation.

column6: %s header validation failed for file %s
column7: When opening the file to be placed in a copy or backup set, to be inspected, or used as the target for an incremental restore, the header was not recognized as a valid file header for a file of the indicated type (datafile, archived log, or control file), belonging to the current database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the correct files are being specified for the copy or backup operation.

column6: error occurred writing %s bytes at block number %s
column7: An error occurred while writing to a file.
column8: From Oracle doc: One or more other messages should be displayed to help pinpoint the cause of the error. Correct the error if possible, then retry the copy, backup, or restore operation.

column6: BACKUP_TAPE_IO_SLAVES not enabled when duplexing to sequential devices
column7: An attempt was made to specify duplexing to sequential devices, but the BACKUP_TAPE_IO_SLAVES initialization parameter was not enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify BACKUP_TAPE_IO_SLAVES=TRUE in the INIT.ORA file, or do not specify duplexing to sequential devices.

column6: exceeded limit of %s corrupt blocks for file %s
column7: The user specified limit of allowable corrupt blocks was exceeded while reading the specified datafile for a datafile copy or backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. The copy or backup operation fails. The session trace file contains detailed information about which blocks were corrupt.

column6: cannot shrink file %s because it is being backed up or copied
column7: An ALTER statement attempted to reduce the size of the indicated file while the same file is being backed up or copied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the resize after the backup or copy is complete.

column6: a device is already allocated to this session
column7: A device cannot be allocated to a session if another device is already allocated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Deallocate the current device.

column6: no device is allocated to this session
column7: An operation was attempted which requires a device to be allocated to the current session, and there is no device allocated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Allocate a device then retry the operation.

column6: file number %s is outside valid range of 1 through %s
column7: A file number used in a copy, backup, or restore operation is not valid for the current database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid file number.

column6: %s recid %s stamp %s not found in controlfile
column7: The input file specified for a copy or backup operation could not be opened because the record describing the file is not found in the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a correct RECID/stamp and retry the copy or backup.

column6: cannot process file %s, file is being being resized
column7: The input file specified for a copy or backup operation could not be opened because the file is being resized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the resize to complete then retry the copy or backup.

column6: cannot obtain %s enqueue for datafile %s
column7: The file access enqueue could not be obtained for a file specified in a backup, copy or restore operation. If the enqueue type shown is SHARED, then the file is the input file for a backup or copy. If the type is EXCLUSIVE, then the file is the output file for a datafile copy or restore which is attempting to overwrite the currently active version of that file. In this case, the file must be offline or the database must be closed. If the type is read-only, then you are attempting to back up or copy this file while the database is in NOARCHIVELOG mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the conflicting operation is complete, then retry the copy or backup. If the database is in NOARCHIVELOG mode, then all files being backed up must be closed cleanly.

column6: output filename must be specified
column7: This type of copy or restore requires an output file name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an output file name and retry the copy.

column6: expected %s blocks in file %s, found %s
column7: During a backup, restore, copy, or scan operation, the indicated file did not contain as many blocks as were indicated in the file header.
column8: From Oracle doc: The input copy or backup piece is probably corrupt. If another backup or copy exists of the file that is being restored, then the corrupt file can be deleted from the recovery catalog and the operation can be restarted.

column6: datafile %s not defined in control file
column7: The specified file number was not found in the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a correct file number and retry the operation.

column6: file %s is MISSING
column7: A copyDataFileCopy, restoreDataFileTo or proxyRestoreDataFile function specified a file number but no output file name, indicating that the output file name should be taken from the control file. However, the control file entry for this file indicates that it was created for a file that was present in the data dictionary but not named during the last CREATE CONTROLFILE statement, so the name in the control file cannot be used for restoration.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify an output file name or issue a SQL RENAME command to enter a valid name for this file in the control file.

column6: end of volume while duplexing to sequential files, backup piece incomplete
column7: An end of volume (EOV) condition was detected while duplexing to sequential files, and this condition cannot be handled currently.
column8: From Oracle doc: Before retrying the backup, make sure the backup pieces will fit in the volume, or disable duplexing.

column6: %s conversation not active
column7: A backup or restore operation was attempted before a conversation was started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Start a conversation then retry the operation.

column6: no files have been named
column7: An attempt was made to proceed from the file naming phase to the piece processing phase of a backup or restore conversation before any files have been specified for backup or restore.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify some files then retry the operation.

column6: conversation terminated due to error
column7: An error occurred which forced the termination of the current backup or restore conversation.
column8: From Oracle doc: There should be other error messages to help identify the cause of the problem. Correct the error and begin another conversation.

column6: file %s already in use
column7: The indicated file, which was specified as the target for a copy, restore, or delete operation is already in use by the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different name and retry the operation.

column6: premature end of volume on piece %s
column7: While creating the indicated backup piece, an end-of-volume condition was encountered before all of the backup set control data was written to the backup piece. This is most likely a media error, because the amount of backup set control data is very small in relation to the total amount of data in a backup set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the piece with a larger piece of output media.

column6: %s k-byte limit is too small to hold piece directory
column7: The user-specified limit of k-bytes per backup piece is not enough to hold the backup set control data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the setLimit procedure to increase the k-byte limit and retry the operation.

column6: error occurred reading %s bytes at block number %s
column7: An error occurred while reading from a file.
column8: From Oracle doc: One or more other messages should be displayed to help pinpoint the cause of the error. Correct the error then retry the copy, backup, or restore operation.

column6: %s recid %s stamp %s is no longer valid
column7: The indicated record has been marked as deleted. This indicates that the corresponding file has either been overwritten by another copy or restore, or that the copy was 'consumed' by a switchToCopy operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you know the name of the file you wish to copy, then inspect it and then retry the copy specifying the new RECID.

column6: %s is not a snapshot or backup controlfile
column7: The control file that is the source for a backup or copy operation is not a snapshot or backup control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the name of a snapshot or backup control file.

column6: conversation already active
column7: An attempt was made to begin a backup or restore conversation, but another conversation is already active in this session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either continue the current conversation, or call backupCancel or restoreCancel to end the current conversation before starting a new one.

column6: wrong %s conversation type
column7: An attempt was made to specify a type of file to be backed-up or restored, but the current conversation cannot process this type of file. For example, you specified an archived log to be included in a datafile backup set. The specified file will not be included in the backup or restore operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. The conversation is still active, and more files can be specified.

column6: datafile number %s already included as %s
column7: This datafile is already specified for inclusion in this backup or restore conversation. A backup or restore conversation may process only a single instance of a datafile.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. The conversation is still active, and more files can be specified.

column6: controlfile already included as %s
column7: The control file is already specified for inclusion in this backup or restore conversation. A backup or restore conversation may process only a single instance of the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. The conversation is still active, and more files can be specified.

column6: archivelog thread %s sequence %s already included as %s
column7: The indicated archive log has already been specified for inclusion in this backup conversation. A backup conversation may process only one copy of any archive log.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. The conversation is still active, and more files can be specified.

column6: snapshot controlfile has not been created
column7: You requested that the snapshot control file be included in the backup set, but no snapshot control file has been created for this instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different control file name, or call cfileMakeAndUseSnapshot to create the snapshot control file.

column6: file %s blocksize %s does not match set blocksize of %s
column7: A file was specified for inclusion in a backup set but it has a logical block size different from the rest of the files in the backup set. All files in a backup set must have the same logical block size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a file that has the same block size as the rest of the files in the backup set. The conversation is still active and more files can be specified.

column6: starting SCN must be specified for incremental backup
column7: No starting SCN was specified to backupDataFile or backupDataFileCopy, but the current backup conversation is for an incremental backup, which requires that a non-zero SCN be specified for all datafiles.
column8: From Oracle doc: The conversation is still active. Respecify the datafile with a non-zero SCN.

column6: block number %s is corrupt in %s %s
column7: A corrupt block was found in a control file, archive log, or backup piece that is being read for a backup or copy. Corruption shall not be tolerated in control files, archive logs, or backup pieces.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. The copy or backup operation fails. Note that in the case of a backup set, the conversation is still active and the piece may be retried.

column6: input file is %s %s (%s)
column7:
This message identifies the input file for a failed copy operation. Both the file number and name (if the name has been determined) are shown. 

For a datafile, the file number refers to the datafile's absolute file number as shown in the DBA_DATA_FILES view. 

For a datafile-copy, the file number refers to the copy's control file record number as shown in the V$DATAFILE_COPY view. 

For a datafile-copy, the file number refers to the copy's control file record number as shown in the RECID column of the V$DATAFILE_COPY view. 

For an archived log, the file number refers to the log's control file record number as shown in the RECID column of the V$ARCHIVED_LOG view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Other messages should display to help pinpoint the cause and the solution.

column6: output file is %s %s (%s)
column7: This message identifies the output file for a failed copy operation. The fields are as described in message 19600. When creating a new datafile copy, its control file record number may not have been determined when the message is printed. In that case, the record number shown is zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: See other error message.

column6: cannot backup or copy active file in NOARCHIVELOG mode
column7: An attempt was made to copy or backup a file that was not closed cleanly, and the database was in NOARCHIVELOG mode. This is not allowed because when restored, the file will require redo application before it is usable, and redo is not currently being saved beyond the contents of the online redo logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the tablespace offline clean or close the database and retry the copy or backup.

column6: conversation file naming phase is over
column7: A call was made to specify a file to be backed up or restored after the first backup piece has been processed.
column8: From Oracle doc: You cannot specify more files to be processed during a backup or restore conversation after the first backup piece has been processed. If more files must be specified, you must begin a new conversation.

column6: input filename must be specified
column7: The input file name was not specified for a control file copy operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an input file name and retry the operation.

column6: Cannot copy or restore to snapshot controlfile
column7: A control file copy or restore operation specified the name of the snapshot control file as the output file. It is not permitted to overwrite the snapshot control file in this manner. Other methods are available to create the snapshot control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different file name and retry the operation. If this is a restore, then the restore conversation remains active and more files may be specified.

column6: %s is an active controlfile
column7: A control file copy, restore, or backup specified the name of a control file named in the INIT.ORA file as the input or output file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different file name and retry the operation. If this is a backup or restore conversation, then the conversation remains active and more files may be specified.

column6: %s is not a backup piece
column7: The specified file is not a backup piece produced by the DBMS_BACKUP_RESTORE package. Either the first block of the backup piece is corrupt or this file is not a backup piece.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different file name and retry the operation.

column6: %s is from different backup set: stamp %s count %s
column7: The specified file is not from the backup set which is currently being processed. It is part of a different backup set. The identification of the set containing this piece is shown.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct backup piece and retry the operation.

column6: directory block %s is corrupt
column7: The indicated directory block failed checksum validation. This backup piece is unusable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply another copy of the same backup piece, or terminate the restore conversation.

column6: backup piece out of order. Expected %s but found %s
column7: This backup piece is out of sequence.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the correct backup piece.

column6: datafile %s not restored due to %s
column7: The indicated file could not be restored, because all of its data blocks were not found in the backup piece.
column8: From Oracle doc: The restore conversation remains active, and the current piece must be reprocessed. If the failure cannot be resolved by reprocessing the current piece, then the restore conversation must be cancelled.

column6: datafile %s not found in backup set
column7: The indicated file could not be restored, because it is not in this backup set. If the file number is zero, then this refers to the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: This message is issued when the directory from the first backup piece is read and one or more files named for restoration were not found. The restore conversation is still active, but no data has been read and you must supply the first backup piece of a backup set that contains all of the requested files.

column6: archivelog thread %s sequence %s not found in backup set
column7: The indicated archived log file was named explicitly for restoration but is not contained in this backup set.
column8: From Oracle doc: This message is issued when the directory from the first backup piece is read and one or more files named for restoration were not found. The restore conversation is still active, but no data has been read and you must supply the first backup piece of a backup set that contains all of the requested files.

column6: some files not found in backup set
column7: Some files that were specified for restoration were not found in the backup set directory. Message 19613 or 19614 is issued for each file that was not found.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the instructions for message 19613.

column6: output filename must be specified if database not mounted
column7: A datafile restore specified no target file name, but the database is not mounted. The database must be mounted when no target file name is specified, so that the target file name can be obtained from the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: The restore conversation remains active. If you wish to restore datafiles without their target file names, then mount the database before continuing. Otherwise, a target file name must be specified on all datafile restoration calls.

column6: file %s contains different resetlogs data
column7: The indicated file contains resetlogs data which is different from the archived log files which are already included in the backup set. All archived log files in a backup set must have the same resetlogs data.
column8: From Oracle doc: The restore conversation remains active, and you may continue to specify archived log files for inclusion in the backup set.

column6: cannot name files after restoreValidate has been called
column7: A call was made to specify a file to restore from a backup set, but a previous call to restoreValidate has already been made.
column8: From Oracle doc: You must cancel and restart the conversation if you wish to specify files to restore.

column6: cannot call restoreValidate after files have been named
column7: restoreValidate was called after some files had already been specified for restoration.
column8: From Oracle doc: You must cancel and restart the conversation if you wish to call restoreValidate.

column6: archivelog range has already been specified
column7: A range of logs has already been specified. Only one SCN range may be specified per conversation.
column8: From Oracle doc: The restore conversation remains active and more logs may be specified by thread and sequence number, if desired.

column6: archivelog thread %s sequence %s not restored due to %s
column7: The indicated file could not be restored, because all of its data blocks were not found in the backup piece.
column8: From Oracle doc: The restore conversation remains active, and the current piece must be reprocessed. If the failure cannot be resolved by reprocessing the current piece, then the restore conversation must be cancelled.

column6: file %s is open
column7: A SwitchToCopy operation specified a datafile copy whose parent datafile is open.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the owning tablespace offline or close the database, then retry the operation.

column6: operation failed, retry possible
column7: A backup, restore or image copy operation failed with an I/O error. If the source of the I/O error can be corrected, then the operation may be retried.
column8: From Oracle doc: This message is used by Recovery Manager to decide whether or not to retry the operation.

column6: error identifying file %s
column7: A file specified as input to a copy or backup operation, or as the target for an incremental restore, could not be identified as an Oracle file. An operating system-specific error accompanies this error to help pinpoint the problem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an different file and retry the operation.

column6: backup set type is %s - can not be processed by this conversation
column7: The data in the backup set is not compatible with the current conversation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either supply the first piece from a backup set that matches the current conversation or start a new restore conversation which can process this backup set.

column6: cannot read backup pieces during controlfile application
column7: This is a control file restore conversation, which is using the offline range information from one or more control files to update datafile checkpoint data. Backup sets are not used during this type of conversation.
column8: From Oracle doc: The conversation is still active and more control files may be applied.

column6: invalid SCN range
column7: The starting SCN for restoreRedoLogRange is greater than the ending SCN.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a starting SCN which is less than or equal to the ending SCN.

column6: no files in specified archivelog SCN range
column7: This backup set contains no files in the specified range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either supply a backup set that contains files in the correct range or start a new conversation and specify a range which will select some files from this backup set.

column6: end of volume encountered while copying backup piece
column7: While copying a backup piece from the operating system native file system to an output device, the output device encountered end-of-volume.
column8: From Oracle doc: The copy fails. This could happen if a tape was used which is not large enough to hold the entire backup piece.

column6: archivelog record contains no file name
column7: This archive log record represents a switch into an active log that took place without archiving its prior contents. The prior contents of the log file are lost.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the RECID of an archive log record that contains a file name. Fixed view V$ARCHIVED_LOG can be used to examine the archived logs.

column6: file name not found in controlfile
column7: The name passed to getFno was not found in the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a valid file name.

column6: controlfile record %s is out of sync with recovery catalog
column7: The control file record describing the file to be deleted in a call to deleteBackupPiece, deleteDataFilecopy, proxyDelete or deleteArchivedLog does not match the validation data supplied by Recovery Manager.
column8: From Oracle doc: contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: filename required for this function
column7: The FNAME or handle parameter was not specified for deletePiece, deleteDataFileCopy, deleteRedoLog or proxyDelete.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the FNAME or handle parameter when calling these functions.

column6: input and output filenames are identical
column7: Identical input and output file names were specified for a datafile copy operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an output file name which is different from the input file name.

column6: archivelog thread %s sequence %s already included
column7: The indicated archive log has already been specified for inclusion in this restore conversation. A restore conversation may process only one copy of any archive log.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. The conversation is still active, and more files can be specified.

column6: backupPieceCreate requires file name when using DISK device
