column7: The session device is currently allocated to disk, and so a file name is required.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a file name and retry the operation.

column6: file %s is not current enough to apply this incremental backup
column7: The checkpoint of the target for this incremental backup is less than the start of the incremental backup. If this backup were applied, then any changes made between the datafile checkpoint and the start of the incremental backup could be lost.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a backup set that can be applied and retry the operation.

column6: file %s is more current than this incremental backup
column7: The checkpoint of the target for this incremental backup is greater than or equal to the checkpoint of the file in the incremental backup set. This backup cannot advance the checkpoint of the target file, so there is no point in applying it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a backup set that can be applied and retry the operation.

column6: datafile checkpoint is SCN %s time %s
column7: This message identifies the datafile checkpoint for a datafile that was too old to take an incremental backup from, or the target of an incremental restore that could not be applied.
column8: From Oracle doc: See other error message.

column6: backup datafile checkpoint is SCN %s time %s
column7: This message identifies the checkpoint of a datafile in an incremental backup set that could not be applied.
column8: From Oracle doc: See other error message.

column6: incremental-start SCN is %s
column7: This message identifies the starting SCN of an incremental backup that could not be applied.
column8: From Oracle doc: See other error message.

column6: datafile %s: incremental-start SCN is too recent
column7: The incremental-start SCN which was specified when starting an incremental datafile backup is greater than the datafile checkpoint SCN, which could cause some blocks to be missed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a smaller incremental-start SCN.

column6: datafile %s: incremental-start SCN is prior to resetlogs SCN %s
column7: The incremental-start SCN which was specified when starting an incremental datafile backup is less than the resetlogs SCN.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a larger incremental-start SCN.

column6: datafile %s: incremental-start SCN is prior to creation SCN %s
column7: The incremental-start SCN which was specified when starting an incremental datafile backup is less than the datafile's creation SCN.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a larger incremental-start SCN.

column6: cannot change size of datafile %s from %s to %s
column7: The indicated file was resized before this incremental backup was taken, but the incremental backup failed to set the file to the new size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the other messages which should be present to indicate the cause of the failure.

column6: non-zero LEVEL cannot be specified when INCREMENTAL is FALSE
column7: BackupSetDataFile was called with a non-zero BACKUP_LEVEL and a FALSE incremental indication.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either set incremental to TRUE or change BACKUP_LEVEL to zero.

column6: datafile %s: incremental-start SCN equals checkpoint SCN
column7: The incremental-start SCN which was specified when starting an incremental datafile backup is equal to the datafile's checkpoint SCN. Since an incremental backup can only be applied to a datafile whose checkpoint SCN is between the backup set incremental-start SCN (inclusive) and the backup set checkpoint SCN (exclusive), there is no datafile that this backup set could ever be applied to.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a smaller incremental-start SCN.

column6: offline-range record recid %s stamp %s not found in file %s
column7: applyOfflineRange was called with a RECID/stamp which was not found in the indicated control file. This probably means that the specified control file is no longer the same control file that Recovery Manager thinks it is.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the RECID/stamp of a record that exists in the control file copy.

column6: Offline-range record recid %s stamp %s in file %s has SCN %s
column7: This messages identifies the offline-clean SCN from the indicated offline-range record in the indicated file.
column8: From Oracle doc: See other error message.

column6: cannot apply offline-range record to datafile %s: SCN mismatch
column7: applyOfflineRange cannot apply an offline-range record to a target datafile unless the datafile's checkpoint SCN exactly matches the offline-clean SCN in the specified offline-range record.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an offline-range record whose offline-clean SCN matches the target datafile's checkpoint.

column6: cannot apply offline-range record to datafile %s: file is fuzzy
column7: The target datafile for an applyOfflineRange call is fuzzy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a target datafile that is closed cleanly.

column6: cannot switch to older file incarnation
column7: SwitchToCopy was called with a datafile copy for a datafile that was dropped prior to the time this control file was backed up.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore and mount an earlier control file. It is acceptable to use a control file that was backed up prior to the creation of the specified datafile.

column6: must use backup controlfile to switch file incarnations
column7: This switchToCopy operation is attempting to switch incarnations of a datafile, but the currently mounted control file is not a backup control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restore and mount a backup control file.

column6: cannot switch to incarnation with different resetlogs data
column7: This switchToCopy operation is attempting to switch to a datafile which comes from a different resetlogs version of the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either restore a backup control file that was taken from the same database version as the target datafile-copy, or switch to a different datafile-copy.

column6: cannot backup, copy, or delete online log %s
column7: The indicated log file is an active log. You can only backup, copy, or delete archived logs.
column8: From Oracle doc: The indicated log file cannot be processed. Select another file.

column6: cannot inspect current datafile %s
column7: The file being inspected is already part of the currently mounted database.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. The file is already part of the database.

column6: cannot inspect %s - file is from different resetlogs
column7: The resetlogs data in the log file being inspected does not match that in the currently mounted control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: The indicated file cannot be processed; inspect another file.

column6: incremental restore would advance file %s past resetlogs
column7: This incremental backup cannot be applied to the specified datafile, because the datafile is from an earlier incarnation of the database, and its checkpoint would be advanced too far to be recoverable in the current incarnation of the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: This incremental cannot be applied to this datafile. If you wish to recover the file to the resetlogs SCN so that the database can be opened with the RESETLOGS option, then you must use redo-log recovery, not incremental restore, to continue recovering this file.

column6: some files in the backup set could not be verified
column7: A restore conversation was made to verify all the files in a backup set, and the files which were printed in messages 19661 or 19662 could not be verified because corrupt blocks for those files were found in the backup set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Unless the damage to the backup set can be repaired, the indicated files cannot be restored from this backup set.

column6: datafile %s could not be verified
column7: Some data blocks for the indicated datafile were corrupt in the backup set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Unless the damage to the backup set can be repaired, the indicated datafile cannot be restored from this backup set.

column6: archived log thread %s sequence %s could not be verified
column7: Some data blocks for the indicated archived log were corrupt in the backup set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Unless the damage to the backup set can be repaired, the indicated archived log cannot be restored from this backup set.

column6: cannot apply current offline range to datafile %s
column7: An attempt was made to apply the current offline range to the specified datafile, but the datafile is either not current enough or is not at the correct SCN to apply the offline range.
column8: From Oracle doc: The datafile remains unchanged.

column6: file type: %s, file name: %s
column7: This message is issued to identify the file which is the subject of an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. This is an informational message. There should be other Oracle messages explaining the cause of the error.

column6: size %s in file header does not match actual file size of %s
column7: The size of the file as indicated in the file header does not match the true size of the file. The two differing sizes are shown in units of logical blocks.
column8: From Oracle doc: This file is not usable; it has most likely been truncated.

column6: cannot do incremental restore of the controlfile
column7: The control file was included in an incremental restore conversation
column8: From Oracle doc: If you wish to restore the control file, you must do a full restore of the control file.

column6: cannot do incremental restore of datafile %s
column7: The backup of the datafile is a full backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you wish to restore the datafile, you must do a full restore of the datafile.

column6: cannot do full restore of datafile %s
column7: The backup of the datafile is an incremental backup.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you wish to restore the datafile, you must do an incremental restore of the datafile.

column6: proxy copy functions cannot be run on DISK channel
column7: A proxy copy procedure was called, but the device which is allocated to the current session has type DISK.
column8: From Oracle doc: Allocate a non-DISK channel and retry the operation. Note that proxy copy requires a third-party media management software product that supports the this backup/restore feature.

column6: file %s already being restored
column7: A proxy restore function has already named this file as a restore destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different file name. If this message occurs during a Recovery Manager job, then this is an internal error in Recovery Manager, and you should contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: media management software returned invalid proxy handle
column7: During a proxy backup or restore, the media management software returned an invalid file handle. This is an internal error in the media management software which is linked with Oracle to provide backup/restore services.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the media management software vendor.

column6: media management software returned invalid file status
column7: During a proxy backup or restore, the media management software returned an invalid file status. This is an internal error in the media management software which is linked with Oracle to provide backup/restore services.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the media management software vendor.

column6: error during proxy copy of file %s
column7: During a proxy backup or restore, an error occurred while copying this file, but other files may have been copied successfully.
column8: From Oracle doc: There should be other errors on the error stack which explain why the file could not be successfully copied.

column6: file %s is already being backed up with proxy copy
column7: Recovery Manager attempted to back up the specified file with proxy copy, but the file is already being backed up by another Recovery Manager job.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the other Recovery Manager backup of this file is complete, then retry the backup.

column6: file %s was modified during proxy copy
column7: A proxy backup of the specified file failed because the file was brought online or otherwise modified while the proxy backup was in progress. This file was offline or read only when the backup began, so the file was not put into hot-backup mode, therefore no modifications are permitted while the backup is in progress.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take another backup of this file.

column6: one or more files failed during proxy backup or restore
column7: During a proxy backup or restore, errors were encountered while processing some files. The files for which no error messages are shown were processed successfully.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the messages regarding the specific files to determine the cause of the problems.

column6: device type exceeds maximum length of %s
column7: The device type indicated is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a correct device type and retry the allocation.

column6: device name exceeds maximum length of %s
column7: The device name indicated is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a correct device name and retry the allocation.

column6: device parameter exceeds maximum length of %s
column7: The device parameter exceeds the port-specific maximum length.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the parameter and retry the operation.

column6: device command %s exceeds maximum length of %s
column7: The device command string exceeds maximum length.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the command and retry the operation.

column6: file name exceeds maximum length of %s
column7: The specified file name, which was a parameter to a copy, backup, or restore operation, exceeds the maximum file name length for this operating system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation with a shorter file name.

column6: tag value exceeds maximum length of %s characters
column7: During a backup or copy operation, the user supplied a tag value too long to fit in the file header.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a shorter tag and retry the operation.

column6: invalid SCN
column7: The input SCN is either not a positive integer or too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the input SCN and make sure it is a valid SCN.

column6: invalid record block number - %s
column7: The input number is either negative or too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the input record block number and make sure it is a valid number clauses in the CREATE DATABASE statement.

column6: log destination exceeds maximum length of %s characters
column7: When starting a restore conversation, the user specified a log restore destination longer than the port-specific maximum.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a shorter destination and retry the operation.

column6: numeric parameter must be non-negative integer
column7: A numeric parameter to an X$DBMS_BACKUP_RESTORE procedure is negative or contains a fractional portion.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a valid numeric parameter.

column6: Error occurred when converting an OCI number into an SCN
column7: This is most likely caused by an invalid SCN number that came from an external file, such as an export file.
column8: From Oracle doc: See other errors on the error stack to look for the source of the problem.

column6: Cannot find datafile with absolute file number %s in tablespace %s
column7: Cannot find one of the data files that should be in the pluggable set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure all datafiles are specified via import command line option or parameter files.

column6: datafile %s is an incorrect version
column7: The datafile is an incorrect version. It contains either less or more changes then the desired version.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the right datafiles are transported. Make sure the datafile is copied while its tablespace is read only.

column6: Cannot recreate plugged in read-only datafile %s
column7: The datafile is plugged in read only. It cannot re-created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER DATABASE RENAME FILE command instead.

column6: snapshot too old: snapshot time is before file %s plug-in time
column7: The snapshot SCN is before the SCN at which the referred datafile is plugged into the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: retry the query.

column6: can not acquire plug-in enqueue
column7: There maybe another ALTER DATABASE RESET COMPATIBILITY command issued concurrently, preventing this process from acquiring the plug-in enqueue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation.

column6: cannot plug data [%s] at level %s into database running at compatibility level %s
column7: Some of the data in the pluggable set requires a compatibility level higher than what is currently allowed by the database. The string in square bracket is the name of the compatibility type associated with the data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Raise the value of the COMPATIBLE initialization parameter and retry the operation.

column6: cannot plug data [%s] at level %s into database running Oracle %s
column7: Some of the data in the pluggable set requires a compatibility level higher than the release level of the Oracle executable. The string in square bracket is the name of the compatibility type associated with the data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade Oracle and retry the operation.

column6: data object number conflict between table %s and partition %s in table %s
column7: The non-partitioned table has the same data object number as one of the partitions in the partitioned table. One cannot exchange the table with the partition in this case.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the ALTER TABLE MOVE PARTITION command to move the offending partition, so that the partition will get a new data object number. Retry the operation then.

column6: File %s is not the initial version of the plugged in datafile
column7: The file is not the initial version of the plugged in datafile.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct initial version of the plugged in datafile.

column6: can not convert offline plugged-in datafile %s
column7: As part of making a tablespace read-write, we need to convert datafiles that are plugged in read only. The file must be online.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the datafile online and retry the operation.

column6: cannot apply change to unverified plugged-in datafile %s
column7: Recovery was not able to verify the referred datafile according to information in the control file. Before encountering this change vector for this file, somehow recovery did not encounter the file conversion redo that is supposed to verify the file. This may happen due to corrupted or incorrect control file used for media recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct control file and continue recovery.

column6: incorrect number of datafiles for tablespace %s
column7: The number of datafiles in the export file for the referred tablespace is not the same as expected. This is most likely caused by a user editing the export file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct export file and retry the operation.

column6: COMPATIBLE parameter needs to be %s or greater
column7: The COMPATIBLE initialization parameter is not high enough to allow the operation. Allowing the command would make the database incompatible with the release specified by the current COMPATIBLE parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shutdown and restart with a higher compatibility setting.

column6: wrong creation SCN - control file expects converted plugged-in datafile
column7: When a tablespace is plugged into a database, the tablespace is initially read only. Oracle converts the header of the plugged-in datafiles (assign them a new creation SCN) when the tablespace is first made read-write. This error occurs when the creation SCN in the file header is different from the creation SCN in the control file, possibly because this is the initial version of plugged-in datafile.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either restore the converted datafile or continue recovering the datafile.

column6: wrong creation SCN - control file expects initial plugged-in datafile
column7: When a tablespace is plugged into a database, the tablespace is initially read only. Oracle converts the header of the plugged-in datafiles (assign them a new creation SCN) when the tablespace is first made read-write. This error occurs when the creation SCN in the file header is different from the creation SCN in the control file, possibly because this is the converted datafile.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either restore the initial version of the plugged-in datafile, or continue database recovery, which will recover the control file.

column6: can not plug a tablespace into a database using a different national character set
column7: Oracle does not support plugging a tablespace into a database using a different national character set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use import/export or unload/load to move data instead.

column6: WARNING: %s of %s bytes is %s used, and has %s remaining bytes available
column7: DB_RECOVERY_FILE_DEST is running out of disk space.
column8: From Oracle doc: Action: One of the following: 1. Add disk space and increase DB_RECOVERY_FILE_DEST_SIZE. 2. Backup files to tertiary device using RMAN. 3. Consider changing RMAN retention policy. 4. Consider changing RMAN archivelog deletion policy. 5. Delete files from recovery area using RMAN.

column6: skip_row procedure was called
column7: The SKIP_ROW procedure was called which raises this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: SKIP_ROW should only be called within a trigger or a procedure called by a trigger.

column6: %s
column7: The stored procedure RAISE_APPLICATION_ERROR was called which causes this error to be generated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the problem as described in the error message or contact the application administrator or database administrator for more information.

column6: error number argument to raise_application_error of string%s is out of range
column7: An attempt was made to specify a number not in the allowed range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use an error number in the range of -20000 to -20999, inclusive.

column6: error number argument to raise_system_error of string%s is out of range
column7: An attempt was made to specify a number not in the allowed range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use an error number in the range of -23300 to -24299, or -29300 to -29399, inclusive.

column6: objects option not installed
column7: The objects option is not installed at this site. object types and other object features are, therefore, unavailable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Install the objects option. The objects option is not part of the Oracle Server product and must be purchased separately. Contact Oracle Customer Support if the objects option needs to be purchased.

column6: not initialized in object mode
column7: This function requires the OCI process to be initialized in object mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify OCI_OBJECT mode when calling OCIInitialize().

column6: internal error code, arguments: [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s], [%s]
column7: This is the generic error number for the OCI environment (client-side) internal errors. This indicates that the OCI environment has encountered an exceptional condition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report to Oracle Customer Support. The first argument is the internal error number.

column6: program could not allocate memory
column7: The operating system has run out of memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take action to make more memory available to the program.

column6: program terminated by fatal error
column7: A program is in an unrecoverable error state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report to Oracle Customer Support.

column6: database server driver not installed
column7: User attempted to access a database server through an object-mode OCI environment but the necessary driver for supporting such access to the database server is not installed or linked in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if the driver corresponding to the database server has been installed/linked in and entered in the server driver table.

column6: exceeded maximum number of connections in OCI (object mode only)
column7: User exceeded the maximum number of connections (255) that can be supported by an OCI environment in object mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close some of existing and unused connections before opening more connections.

column6: attempted to use an invalid connection in OCI (object mode only)
column7: User attempted to use an invalid connection or a connection that has been terminated in an OCI environment (object mode), or user attempted to de-reference a REF obtained from a connection which has been terminated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the connection exists and is still valid.

column6: functionality not supported by the server (object mode only)
column7: User attempted to use a functionality that the server does not support.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the server.

column6: object type mismatch
column7: The object type of the object is different from what is specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the type of the object and correct it.

column6: attribute number or (collection element at index) %s violated its constraints
column7: Attribute value or collection element value violated its constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the value of the attribute or collection element such that it meets its constraints. The constraints are specified as part of the attribute or collection element's schema information.

column6: initialization failed
column7: The initialization sequence failed. This can happen, for example, if an environment variable such as NLS_DATE_FORMAT is set to an invalid value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that all NLS environment variables are well-formed.

column6: argument %s is null, invalid, or out of range
column7: The argument is expecting a non-null, valid value but the argument value passed in is null, invalid, or out of range. Examples include when the LOB/FILE positional or size argument has a value outside the range 1 through (4GB - 1), or when an invalid open mode is used to open a file, and so on.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your program and correct the caller of the routine to not pass a null, invalid or out-of-range argument value.

column6: path expression too long
column7: The path expression that is supplied by the user is too long. The path expression is used to specify the position of an attribute in an object. This error occurs when one of the intermediate elements in the path expression refers to an attribute of a built-in type. Thus, the OCI function cannot proceed on to process the rest of the elements in the path expression.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass in the correct path expression to locate the attribute.

column6: attribute is not an object
column7: The user attempts to perform an operation (that is valid only for an object) to an attribute of a built-in type. An example of such an illegal operation is to dynamically set a null structure to an attribute of a built-in type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid performing such operation to an attribute of built-in type.

column6: operation does not support the specified typecode
column7: The user attempts to perform an operation that does not support the specified type code.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the range of valid type codes that are supported by this operation.

column6: property id [%s] is invalid
column7: The specified property ID is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid property ID. Valid property IDs are enumerated by OCIObjectPropId.

column6: property [%s] is not a property of transient or value instances
column7: An attempt was made to get a property which applies only to persistent objects.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the lifetime and only get this property for persistent objects.

column6: property [%s] is not a property of value instances
column7: An attempt was made to get a property which applies only to persistent and transient objects.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the lifetime and only get this property for persistent and transient objects.

column6: can not free this object
column7: An attempt was made to free an object that is persistent and dirty and the OCI_OBJECTFREE_FORCE flag is not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either flush the persistent object or set the flag to OCI_OBJECTFREE_FORCE

column6: memory cartridge service handle not initialized
column7: Attempt to use the handle without initializing it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Initialize the memory cartridge service handle.

column6: duration is invalid for this function
column7: Attempt to use a duration not valid for this function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid duration: a previously created user duration or OCI_DURATION_STATEMENT or OCI_DURATION_SESSION. For callout duration or external procedure duration, use OCIExtProcAllocCallMemory.

column6: memory being resized without being allocated first
column7: Attempt to resize memory without allocating it first.
column8: From Oracle doc: Allocate the memory first before resizing it.

column6: size [%s] is invalid
column7: Attempt to resize memory with invalid size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass in a valid size (must be a positive integer).

column6: key length [%s] is invalid
column7: Attempt to use an invalid key length.
column8: From Oracle doc: Key length is invalid and valid range is 0 to 64.

column6: key is already being used
column7: Attempt to use a key that is already used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a new key that is not yet being used.

column6: key does not exist
column7: Attempt to use a non-existent key.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a key that already exists.

column6: constraint violation for attribute number %s
column7: Constraints on the attribute were violated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value (of the attribute) so that it satisfies constraints.

column6: copy of an OTS (named or simple) instance failed
column7: See following message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that no attribute value violates constraints.

column6: object does not exist or is marked for delete
column7: User attempted to perform an inappropriate operation to an object that is non-existent or marked for delete. Operations such as pinning, deleting and updating cannot be applied to an object that is non-existent or marked for delete.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-initialize the reference to reference an existent object or unmark the object.

column6: attempt to flush objects to different servers
column7: User attempted to flush objects to different servers in one function call. These objects are obtained by calling a callback functions provided by the program.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid performing this operation.

column6: object is not instantiated or has been de-instantiated in cache
column7: User attempted to perform an inappropriate operation to a transient object that is not instantiated in the object cache. Operations that cannot be applied to a not-instantiated transient object include deleting or pinning such an object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check their code to see if they are performing such an operation without instantiating the object first, or performing such an operation after the allocation duration of the object has expired.

column6: cannot flush an object that is not modified
column7: See the error message.
column8: From Oracle doc: The object should not be flushed.

column6: cannot terminate cache or connection without flushing first
column7: See the error message.
column8: From Oracle doc: The transaction should be aborted or committed before terminating the cache or connection.

column6: service context is invalid
column7: The service context that is supplied by the user is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Establish the service context.

column6: duration does not exist or is invalid
column7: The duration number that is supplied by the user is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Establish the duration or use a correct predefined duration.

column6: pin duration is longer than allocation duration
column7: The pin duration supplied by the user is longer than the allocation duration. This affects operations such as pinning and setting default parameters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a shorter pin duration or use the null duration.

column6: inappropriate operation on a transient object
column7: An attempt was made to perform an inappropriate operation on a transient object. Operations that cannot be applied to a transient object include flushing and locking.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid performing such operations on a transient object.

column6: cannot refresh an object that has been modified
column7: An attempt was made to refresh an object that has been marked for delete, update or insert (new).
column8: From Oracle doc: Unmark the object before refreshing it.

column6: argument is expecting a valid memory address of an object
column7: The object memory address that is supplied by the user is invalid. The user may have passed in a bad memory address to a function that is expecting a valid memory address of an object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass in a valid memory address of an object to the function.

column6: duration not active
column7: An attempt was made to use a duration that has been terminated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Avoid performing such operation.

column6: overflow error
column7: This operation's result is above the range of Oracle number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Decrease the input value(s) so that the result is in the range of Oracle number.

column6: underflow error
column7: This operation's result is below the range of Oracle number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the input value(s) so that the result is in the range of Oracle number.

column6: unknown sign flag value [%s]
column7: Signed flag used is not OCI_NUMBER_SIGNED or OCI_NUMBER_UNSIGNED.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use either OCI_NUMBER_SIGNED or OCI_NUMBER_UNSIGNED as sign flag.

column6: value [%s] is divided by zero
column7: Given value is divided by zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify divisor value to be non-zero.

column6: bad integer length [%s]
column7: The length of the integer (that is, number of bytes) to be converted to or from an Oracle number is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use integer length 1, 2, 4 or 8 bytes only.

column6: buffer size [%s] is too small - [%s] is needed
column7: The buffer to hold the resulting text string is too small.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a buffer of the required size.

column6: argument [%s] is an invalid or uninitialized number
column7: An invalid or uninitialized number is passed in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid number. To initialize number, call OCINumberInit().

column6: invalid format text [%s]
column7: The numeric format string for converting characters to or from an Oracle number is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use valid format string as documented in the Oracle Call Interface Programmer's Guide.

column6: invalid input %s [%s]
column7: The text string for converting to numbers is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid input string as documented in the Oracle Call Interface Programmer's Guide.

column6: reading negative value [%s] as unsigned
column7: An attempt was made to convert a negative number to an unsigned integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the sign flag ORLTSB to convert a signed number.

column6: invalid NLS parameter %s [%s]
column7: The NLS parameter string for converting characters to or from an Oracle number is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use valid format string as documented in the Oracle Call Interface Programmer's Guide.

column6: number to text translation for the given format causes overflow
column7: Rounding done due to the given string format causes overflow.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the string format such that overflow does not occur.

column6: buffer size [%s] is less than the required size [%s]
column7: The size of the buffer into which the hexadecimal REF string is to be written is too small.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a buffer of the required size.

column6: hexadecimal %s length is zero
column7: The given hexadecimal string length must be greater than zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a length greater than zero.

column6: hexadecimal %s does not correspond to a valid REF
column7: The given hexadecimal string is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a valid hexadecimal string which was previously returned by a call to OCIRefToHex().

column6: given size [%s] must be in the range of 0 to [%s]
column7: The given resize size is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the given size is in the required range.

column6: variable-length array has not been initialized
column7: An un-initialized variable-length array is being operated upon.
column8: From Oracle doc: Initialize the variable-length array prior to calling this function.

column6: cannot resize non-zero variable-length array to zero elements
column7: An attempt was made to resize a non-zero variable-length array to 0 elements.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-zero size.

column6: destination variable-length array is not initialized
column7: The variable-length array on the right-hand-side of an assignment or the destination array of an append is not initialized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Initialize the destination variable-length array prior to calling this function.

column6: source variable-length array is not initialized
column7: The variable-length array on the left-hand-side of an assignment or the source array of an append is not initialized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Initialize the destination variable-length array prior to calling this function.

column6: element at index [%s] does not exist
column7: Collection element at the given index does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the index of an element which exists.

column6: type code [%s] is not valid
column7: Given type code is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use one of the type codes enumerated in OCITypeCode.

column6: element at index [%s] has been previously deleted
column7: An attempt was made to delete a non-existent collection element.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for the existence of the element prior to calling this function.

column6: left hand and right hand side collections are not of same type
column7: Left hand and right side collections are not of same type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the same collection type is passed for both left hand and right hand side of this function.

column6: delete element operation is not allowed for variable-length array
column7: An attempt was made to delete an element of a variable-length array.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the collection is not a variable-length array prior to calling this function.

column6: given index [%s] must be in the range of 0 to [%s]
column7: Given index is not in the required range.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the given index is in the required range.

column6: collection is empty
column7: Given collection is empty.
column8: From Oracle doc: Test if collection is empty prior to invoking this function.

column6: given trim size [%s] must be less than or equal to [%s]
column7: Given trim size is greater than the current collection size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the given size is less than or equal to the collection size prior to calling this function.

column6: invalid LOB locator specified
column7:
One of the following: 

The LOB locator was never initialized. 

The locator is for a BFILE and the routine expects a BLOB/CLOB/NCLOB locator. 

The locator is for a BLOB/CLOB/NCLOB and the routine expects a BFILE locator. 

An attempt was made to update the LOB in a trigger body -- LOBs in trigger bodies are read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: For (1), initialize the LOB locator by selecting into the locator variable or by setting the LOB locator to empty. For (2) and (3), pass the correct type of locator into the routine. For (4), remove the trigger body code that updates the LOB value.

column6: invalid locator for LOB buffering
column7:
One of the following:

The locator was never enabled for buffering. 

It is not an updated locator but is being used for a write/flush operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: For (1) enable the locator for buffering; (2) ensure that only an updated locator is used for a LOB update operation.

column6: cannot use two different locators to modify the same LOB
column7: LOB buffering is enabled and an attempt was made to modify the LOB using two different LOB locators.
column8: From Oracle doc: When using LOB buffering, modify the LOB through one LOB locator only.

column6: must update the LOB only through the LOB buffers
column7: LOB buffering is enabled for this LOB and there are buffers for this LOB in the buffer pool. Thus, updating the LOB through means other than the LOB buffers is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Update the LOB through the LOB buffers using the locator that has LOB buffering enabled. If this operation is required, buffers associated with this LOB should either be flushed as necessary or buffering should be disabled. Once this is done, reissue the command.

column6: cannot perform operation with LOB buffering enabled
column7: The operation attempted is not allowed when LOB buffering is enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the operation is required, LOB buffering should not be used. In this case, flush buffers associated with the input LOB locator as necessary, disable buffering on the input LOB locator and reissue the command.

column6: no more buffers available for operation
column7:
One of the following:

All buffers in the buffer pool have been used up by previous operations. 

An attempt was made to flush a LOB without any previous buffered update operations.
column8: From Oracle doc: For (1), flush the LOB(s) through the locator that is being used to update the LOB. For (2), write to the LOB through a locator enabled for buffering before attempting to flush buffers.

column6: cannot perform operation with an updated locator
column7: The input locator has buffering enabled and was used to update the LOB value through the LOB buffering subsystem. The modified buffer has not been flushed since the write that was performed by the input locator; thus, the input locator is considered an updated locator. Updated locators cannot be the source of a copy operation. Only one locator per LOB may be used to modify the LOB value through the LOB buffering subsystem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Depending on whether the modifications made through the input locator to the LOB buffering subsystem should be written to the server, either flush the buffer to write the modifications, or, disable buffering on the locator to discard the modifications. Then, reissue the command.

column6: non-contiguous append to a buffering enabled LOB not allowed
column7: The buffered write operation has an input offset value more than one byte or character past the end of the LOB.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an input offset value which is exactly one character or byte greater than the length of the LOB that you are attempting to update through a buffered write operation.

column6: non-existent directory or file for %s operation
column7: An attempt was made to access a directory that does not exist, or attempted to access a file in a directory that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a system object corresponding to the specified directory exists in the database dictionary, or make sure the name is correct.

column6: insufficient privileges on file or directory to perform %s operation
column7: The user does not have the necessary access privileges on the directory alias and/or the file for the operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask the database/system administrator to grant the required privileges on the directory alias and/or the file.

column6: invalid or modified directory occurred during %s operation
column7: The directory alias used for the current operation is not valid if being accessed for the first time, or has been modified by the database administrator since the last access.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you are accessing this directory for the first time, provide a valid directory name. If you have been already successful in opening a file under this directory before this error occurred, then close the file and retry the operation with a valid directory alias as modified by your database administrator. Oracle recommends that directories should be modified only during quiescent periods.

column6: file or LOB operation %s failed%s
column7: The operation attempted on the file or LOB failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the next error message in the error stack for more detailed information. Also, verify that the file or LOB exists and that the necessary privileges are set for the specified operation. If the error still persists, report the error to the database administrator.

column6: cannot perform %s operation on an unopened file or LOB
column7: The file or LOB is not open for the required operation to be performed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Precede the current operation with a successful open operation on the file or LOB.

column6: operation would exceed the maximum number of opened files or LOBs
column7: The number of open files or LOBs has reached the maximum limit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close some of the opened files or LOBs and retry the operation.

column6: Open LOBs exist at transaction commit time
column7: An attempt was made to commit a transaction with open LOBs at transaction commit time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close the LOBs before committing the transaction.

column6: Cannot open a LOB in read-write mode without a transaction
column7: An attempt was made to open a LOB in read-write mode before a transaction was started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Start a transaction before opening the LOB in read-write mode. Ways to start a transaction include issuing a SQL DML or SELECT FOR UPDATE command. Opening the LOB in read-only mode does not require a transaction.

column6: LOB already opened in the same transaction
column7: An attempt was made to open a LOB that already is open in this transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close the LOB before attempting to reopen it.

column6: cannot update a LOB opened in read-only mode
column7: An attempt was made to write to or update a LOB opened in read-only mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close the LOB and reopen it in read-write mode before attempting to write to or update the LOB.

column6: type "%s"."%s" not found
column7: An attempt was made to obtain information for a type that cannot be found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the schema is correct and that the type has been created correctly.

column6: input type is not an object type
column7: An attempt was made to obtain the supertype information for a non-object type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass in only an object type.

column6: attribute/method/parameter "%s" not found
column7: Type element with the given name is not found in the type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure that the type element exists.

column6: type "%s"."%s" already exists
column7: An attempt was made to create a type that already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure that the type has not been created prior to this.

column6: operation must be on a user-defined type
column7: An attempt was made to perform an operation that is allowed only on a user-defined type, and the type is not a user-defined type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure that only user-defined types are being operated on.

column6: attribute with name "%s" already exists
column7: An attempt was made to create an object type where more than one attributes have the same name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure that all attribute names are unique.

column6: type for attribute "%s" does not exist
column7: The type of the attribute does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: No types were created/modified for this DDL transaction. Redo the DDL transaction and add the creation of the attribute's type in the DDL transaction.

column6: cannot use two versions of the same type "%s"
column7: The version of this type conflicts with the version of this type used by another library that was linked in with the application. An application may only use one version of a type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the libraries being linked with this application and use the same versions of the type.

column6: method information mismatch in ALTER TYPE
column7: The number of methods or the method signature do not match that of the original type declaration. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the method signature stay identical for the previously declared method. Do not drop existing methods.

column6: type "%s" does not contain a map or order function
column7: The input type does not contain a map or order function so one cannot be returned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add a map or order function to the type or catch this error.

column6: input type is not a collection type
column7: An attempt was made to obtain information for collection types on a non-named collection type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a named collection type for the function.

column6: typecode number is not legal as a number type
column7: An attempt was made to use a number type code that is not valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use only OCI_TYPECODE_SMALLINT, OCI_TYPECODE_INTEGER, OCI_TYPECODE_REAL, OCI_TYPECODE_DOUBLE, OCI_TYPECODE_FLOAT, OCI_TYPECODE_NUMBER, or OCI_TYPECODE_DECIMAL.

column6: input type is not an array type
column7: An attempt was made to obtain the number of elements for a non-array type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass in only a named collection type which is an array.

column6: type attribute information altered in ALTER TYPE
column7: The type attribute information does not match that of the original type declaration when altering type. Attributes cannot be altered during ALTER TYPE. Only new methods can be added.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that all type alterations are legal.

column6: method does not return any result
column7: OCITypeResult() was called on a method that does not return any results.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that you are passing in the correct method descriptor, or that your method creation was done correctly.

column6: invalid parameter encountered in method %s
column7: An invalid parameter is being passed to this method of SYS.RowType or SYS.RowSet.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the parameters being passed to this method and make sure that the parameters are allowed.

column6: incorrect usage of method %s
column7: This method of SYS.RowType or SYS.RowSet is being used inappropriately.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the documentation for correct usage.

column6: encountered 8.0.2 (Beta) VARRAY data that cannot be processed
column7: Production Oracle8 (8.0.3 and beyond) encountered some VARRAY data which was created and stored by Oracle8 8.0.2 (Beta 2). Production Oracle8 cannot understand or process such VARRAY data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Delete the VARRAY data from the table by dropping the table, deleting the rows, or nulling out the VARRAY columns, and then reinsert the VARRAY data. There is no provided script or tool to help automate this conversion.

column6: pickler TDS context [%s] is not initialized
column7: An attempt was made to use the pickler TDS context without initializing it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use OCIPicklerTdsCtxInit to initialize the context.

column6: pickler TDS handle [%s] is not well-formed
column7: An attempt was made to use the pickler TDS handle without initializing or constructing it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use OCIPicklerTdsInit to initialize the handle before it is constructed. Use OCIPicklerTdsGenerate to generate the TDS before its attributes can be accessed.

column6: cannot add an attribute to the already generated TDS handle
column7: An attempt was made to add an attribute to the already constructed TDS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a TDS handle that is initialized but not yet constructed.

column6: TDS handle already generated
column7: An attempt was made to generate TDS that is already generated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a TDS handle that is initialized but not yet generated.

column6: FDO handle [%s] is not initialized
column7: An attempt was made to use an uninitialized FDO handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use OCIPicklerFdoInit to initialize FDO handle.

column6: pickler image handle [%s] is not well-formed
column7: An attempt was made to use the image handle without initializing/ constructing it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use OCIPicklerImageInit to initialize the handle before it is constructed. Use OCIPicklerImageGenerate to generate the image before its attributes can be accessed.

column6: image handle already generated
column7: An attempt was made to generate image that is already generated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a image handle that is initialized but not yet generated.

column6: cannot add an attribute to the already generated image handle
column7: An attempt was made to add an attribute to the already constructed image.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a image handle that is initialized but not yet constructed.

column6: error %s during initialization of FDO
column7: An error occurred during FDO initialization.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take an action based on the specified error.

column6: error while adding a scalar to the image handle
column7: An error occurred while adding a scalar attribute to the image handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure image handle is initialized before adding scalar.

column6: TDS version is not recognized
column7: Incorrect TDS handle is passed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure image handle is initialized with the correct TDS.

column6: TDS does not describe a collection TDS
column7: Collection construct/access routines are being on an image but the TDS does not describe that a collection TDS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure a collection TDS is used before invoking collection routines on the image handle.

column6: buflen does not match the size of the scalar
column7: BUFLEN is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure BUFLEN is correct and matches the size of the scalar.

column6: error while construction the collection in the image
column7: An error occurred during the construction of collection.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure image handle is initialized and OCIPicklerImageCollBegin is called to begin collection.

column6: attribute is not a collection
column7: Collection routine is invoked upon a non-collection attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure attribute is a collection.

column6: image is not of Oracle 8.1 format
column7: The function being invoked is applicable only for 8.1 images.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure image is of 8.1 format.

column6: error while accessing the image handle collection
column7: An error occurred while accessing collection in the image handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure image is initialized correctly and the collection is constructed properly.

column6: attribute is a BAD NULL in the image handle
column7: The attribute in question is probably the attribute of a null embedded image.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure attribute number is valid or it is NULL or NOT NULL.

column6: all collection elements have already been accessed
column7: An attempt was made to access a collection element after all the collection elements are already accessed.
column8: From Oracle doc: This function should not be invoked any more.

column6: buffer size too small to hold the value
column7: Buffer size is not enough to hold the value. Most likely while doing the character set conversion, a bigger buffer is needed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass in a bigger buffer. If the client character set format differs from that of server, doing the conversion may result in 4X expansion.

column6: error transfering an object from the agent
column7: An error was returned from the pickler routines on the agent side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid user-defined type
column7: An attempt was made to use an incomplete type as a constructor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the type definition before using it in a query.

column6: invalid object row variable
column7: The specified object row variable is not available in the scope of name resolution.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify the specified object row variable is correct, or use an object row variable visible in scope.

column6: cannot update attributes of packed ADTs in SQL
column7: An attempt was made to update an attribute of a packed ADT column in an UPDATE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use an unpacked ADT column, OR update the entire ADT instead.

column6: object type contains zero attributes
column7: An attempt was made to create or specify a column or constructor of an object type that has no attributes. Only object types that have at least one attribute are allowed in this context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid object type.

column6: remote operations not permitted on object tables or user-defined type columns
column7: An attempt was made to perform queries or DML operations on remote object tables or on remote table columns whose type is one of object, REF, nested table or VARRAY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the reference to remote tables in the statement.

column6: cannot insert NULL object into object tables or nested tables
column7: An attempt was made to insert a NULL object into an object table or a Nested Table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a non-NULL object is inserted into the table or insert an object with attributes whose values are NULL.

column6: not an object or REF
column7: An attempt was made to extract an attribute from an item that is neither an object nor a REF.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use an object type or REF type item and retry the operation.

column6: cannot resolve to a scalar type or a collection type
column7: Invalid use of a non-scalar (for example, object type) item.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the item's data type and retry the operation.

column6: REF dereferencing not allowed
column7: An attempt was made to access an object type's attributes by de-referencing a REF item.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the item an object type instead of a REF to an object type.

column6: nonexistent attribute
column7: An attempt was made to access a non-existent attribute of an object type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the attribute reference to see if it is valid. Then retry the operation.

column6: cannot modify object attributes with REF dereferencing
column7: An attempt was made to modify the attributes an object by de-referencing a REF column in an UPDATE statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Update the table containing the object that the REF points to, or change the REF column to an object type column.

column6: cannot access attributes of packed adts in SQL
column7: Attempt to access an attribute of a packed ADT column/table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use an unpacked ADT or retrieve the entire ADT instead.

column6: cannot reference nested table column's storage table
column7: An attempt to access the nested table column's storage table is not allowed in the given context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue the statement against the parent table containing the nested table column.

column6: operand value exceeds system limits
column7: Object or Collection value was too large. The size of the value might have exceeded 30k in a SORT context, or the size might be too big for available memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose another value and retry the operation.

column6: attribute or element value is larger than specified in type
column7: Value provided for the object type attribute or collection element exceeded the size specified in the type declaration.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose another value and retry the operation.

column6: unsupported feature with RETURNING clause
column7: RETURNING clause is currently not supported for object type columns, LONG columns, remote tables, INSERT with subquery, and dereferencing inside returning clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use separate SELECT statements to get the values.

column6: subquery not allowed in the default clause
column7: An attempt was made to use a subquery in the column default clause expression.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the subquery from the default clause.

column6: subquery expressions not allowed here
column7: An attempt was made to use a subquery expression where these are not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the statement without the subquery expression.

column6: scope of input value does not correspond to the scope of the target
column7: An attempt was made to operate on a REF value scoped to a different table than the expected one.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a REF which is scoped to the expected table and retry the operation.

column6: duplicate LOB storage option specificed
column7: A LOB storage option (CHUNK, PCTVERSION, CACHE, NOCACHE, TABLESPACE, STORAGE, INDEX) was specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify all LOB storage options only once.

column6: invalid CHUNK LOB storage option value
column7: The specified CHUNK LOB storage option value must be an integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose an appropriate integer value and retry the operation.

column6: invalid PCTVERSION LOB storage option value
column7: The specified PCTVERSION LOB storage option value must be an integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose an appropriate integer value and retry the operation.

column6: invalid LOB storage option specification
column7: A LOB storage option was not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of CHUNK, PCTVERSION, CACHE, NOCACHE, TABLESPACE, STORAGE, INDEX as part of the LOB storage clause.

column6: invalid option for LOB storage index
column7: A valid LOB store index option was not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of (INITTRANS, MAXTRANS, TABLESPACE, STORAGE) as part of the LOB storage index.

column6: optional name for LOB storage segment incorrectly specified
column7: The optional name for LOB storage segment was specified with multiple columns in the column list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify each column LOB storage only with optional name(s).

column6: cannot add columns to object tables
column7: An attempt was made to add columns to an object table. Object tables cannot be altered to add columns since its definition is based on an object type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a new type with additional attributes, and use the new type to create an object table. The new object table will have the desired columns.

column6: cannot modify columns of object tables
column7: An attempt was made to alter the object table by modifying existing columns. An object table cannot be altered to modify existing columns since it is based on an object type. The table definition must be in sync with the corresponding type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a new type with the desired attribute types and use it to create an object table. The new object table will have the desired columns.

column6: invalid alteration of datatype
column7: An attempt was made to modify the column type to object, REF, nested table, VARRAY or LOB type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a new column of the desired type and copy the current column data to the new type using the appropriate type constructor.

column6: invalid modification of columns
column7: An attempt was made to modify an object, REF, VARRAY, nested table, or LOB column type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a new column of the desired type and copy the current column data to the new type using the appropriate type constructor.

column6: object type expected
column7: An attempt was made to create an object table using a non- object type, or to create a column that is a REF to a non-object type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid object type in the table or column definition.

column6: invalid user-defined type
column7: An attempt was made to create a column or object table of a non-existent type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid type in the table or column definition.

column6: specified object identifier doesn't match existing object identifier
column7: An attempt was made to specify an object identifier for the type that does not match the existing identifier of the incomplete type of the same name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct object identifier or leave it out of the statement.

column6: synonym for datatype %s.%s not allowed
column7: A synonym specification for a datatype is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the synonym for the datatype.

column6: cannot ALTER or DROP LOB indexes
column7: An attempt was made to ALTER or DROP a LOB index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not operate directly on the system-defined LOB index. Perform operations on the corresponding LOB column.

column6: more than one column specified
column7: An attempt was made to specify multiple columns where only one is allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a single column and retry the operation.

column6: default character set is of varying width
column7: A character LOB was defined but the default character set is not fixed width.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the character set is of fixed width before defining character LOBs.

column6: table with LOBs contains segments in different tablespaces
column7: An attempt was made to drop a tablespace which contains the segment(s) for the LOB columns of a table but does not contain the table segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find table(s) with LOB columns which have non-table segments in this tablespace. Drop these tables and reissue drop tablespace.

column6: depth of type dependency hierarchy exceeds maximum limit
column7: The type dependency hierarchy was structured to have depth greater than 1024.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restructure the type dependency hierarchy to a shorter depth.

column6: ALTER TYPE with REPLACE option a non-object type
column7: An attempt was made to perform ALTER TYPE with REPLACE option a non-object type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the non-object type first, then re-create it as an object type.

column6: ALTER TYPE with REPLACE is not allowed for pure incomplete types
column7: An attempt was made to perform ALTER TYPE with REPLACE option for a pure incomplete type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Completely define the original type, before using the ALTER TYPE with REPLACE option.

column6: OID INDEX clause not allowed on tables with primary key based object identifiers
column7: An attempt was made to create an OID INDEX on a table with primary key-based object identifiers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the OID INDEX clause.

column6: primary key not specified for primary key based object table
column7: An attempt was made to create a primary key based object table without specifying a primary key.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a primary key and retry the operation.

column6: attribute "%s" is not part of the type "%s"
column7: Attribute specified in the USER_DEFINED clause is not an attribute of the REF type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the name specified in the USER_DEFINED clause is the name of a valid attribute of the REF type.

column6: cannot drop primary key of an object table whose object identifier is primary key based
column7: An attempt was made to drop the primary key of an object table which has a primary key based object identifier.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the drop primary key clause.

column6: this user-defined type is not allowed or it cannot be used in this context
column7: An attempt was made to create a kind of user-defined type which is not allowed, or an attempt to create table columns or use default constructor with a type on which these are not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the type is permitted in this context.

column6: invalid option specified for a HASH partition or subpartition of a LOB column
column7: One or more invalid options were encountered while parsing the physical attributes of a LOB partition or subpartition. Either the LOB partition is in a table partitioned using the HASH method, or the LOB subpartition is in a table subpartitioned using the HASH method. TABLESPACE is the only valid option for a HASH partition or subpartition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the invalid option(s).

column6: duplicate LOB partition or subpartition specified
column7: An attempt was made was made to specify a partition or subpartition that has already been specified for the LOB column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate specification.

column6: cannot use the LOB INDEX clause for partitioned tables
column7: An attempt was made to specify a LOB INDEX clause in a CREATE TABLE or ALTER TABLE statement for a partitioned table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the LOB INDEX clause.

column6: invalid REF
column7: An invalid REF was accessed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the REF and retry the operation.

column6: dangling REF
column7: The object corresponding to the REF that was accessed does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the REF value is pointing to an existing object.

column6: object creation failed
column7: The object cannot be created in the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to see if the object table exists and the object size is not too big. Then retry the operation.

column6: object deletion failed
column7: The object could not be deleted from the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to see if the object table exists. Then retry the operation.

column6: object modification failed
column7: The object could not be modified in the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to see if the object table exists and the object size is not too big. Then retry the operation.

column6: cannot get REF to a non-persistent object
column7: An attempt was made to get a REF for something other than an object in an object table. REFs can only be taken for objects in object tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Rewrite the query to obtain REF values from object tables.

column6: scoped table "%s" in schema "%s" is not an object table
column7: The scoped table specified for a REF column is not an object table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the scoped table is an object table. Then retry the operation.

column6: type of REF column is not the same as that of its scoped table
column7: The type specified for the REF column and the type specified for the scope table are different.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the types of a REF column and its scoped table are the same.

column6: duplicate SCOPE clauses for a REF column
column7: Multiple SCOPE clauses were specified for a single REF column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate SCOPE clauses and retry the operation.

column6: REF value does not point to scoped table
column7: An attempt was made to insert a REF value that does not point to the scoped table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the REF values point to the scoped table.

column6: cannot specify name for REF column constraint
column7: An attempt was made to specify a constraint name for a constraint on a REF column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the constraint name and retry the operation.

column6: cannot have multiple columns in REF constraint
column7: An attempt was made to specify multiple columns in a single REF constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify separate constraints for each column and retry the operation.

column6: scoped table "%s" does not exist in schema "%s"
column7: The scoped table specified for a REF column does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the scoped table exists and retry the operation.

column6: constraint can be specified only for REF columns
column7: The constraint specified does not apply to non-REF columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the constraint and retry the operation.

column6: cannot add constraint on existing unscoped REF columns of non-empty tables
column7: An attempt was made to add a constraint to existing unscoped REF columns of a table which contains one or more rows.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the constraint specification or add the constraint after emptying the table.

column6: referenced table "%s" in schema "%s" is not an object table
column7: The referenced table specified for a REF column is not an object table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the referenced table is an object table. Then retry the operation.

column6: cannot have both scope and referential constraint on REF column "%s"
column7: REF column has both a referential and a scope constraint. A referential constraint implies a scope constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove either the referential or scope constraint and then retry the operation.

column6: no scope clause specified for user-defined REF column "%s"
column7: User-defined REF column does not have a scope constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a scope constraint for the user-defined REF column and retry the operation.

column6: existing scope clause on "%s" points to a table other than the one mentioned in the referential constraint
column7: Table mentioned in the referential integrity constraint is different from the scope table of the REF column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the scope table of the REF column in the referential integrity constraint and then retry the operation.

column6: cannot specify both scope and rowid constraint on ref column
column7: An attempt was made to specify both a scope and a ROWID constraint on a REF column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove either the ROWID or scope constraint and then retry the operation.

column6: the SELECT list item of THE subquery is not a collection type
column7: The THE subquery must SELECT a nested table or VARRAY item.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the subquery to SELECT a nested table or VARRAY item.

column6: cannot compare nested table or VARRAY or LOB attributes of an object type
column7: Comparison of nested table or VARRAY or LOB attributes of an object type was attempted in the absence of a MAP or ORDER method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define a MAP or ORDER method for the object type.

column6: CURSOR expression not allowed
column7: CURSOR on a subquery is allowed only in the top-level SELECT list of a query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the CURSOR expression and retry the operation.

column6: MULTISET expression not allowed
column7: MULTISET expressions are allowed only inside a CAST to a nested table or VARRAY type.
column8: From Oracle doc: put the MULTISET (subquery) expression inside a CAST to a nested table or VARRAY type.

column6: invalid reference to a nested table column
column7: An invalid reference was made to a nested table column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove invalid reference to the nested table column and retry the operation.

column6: cannot access rows from a non-nested table item
column7: An attempt was made to access rows of an item whose type is not known at parse time or that is not of a nested table type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use CAST to cast the item to a nested table type.

column6: cannot perform DML on expression or on nested table view column
column7: An attempt was made to perform a DML on an expression or on a nested table view column where a nested table column of a base table is expected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only nested table column of a base table is allowed in the DML.

column6: invalid CAST to a type that is not a nested table or VARRAY
column7: An attempt was made to CAST to a type that is not a nested table or VARRAY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Respecify CAST to a nested table or VARRAY type.

column6: reference to NULL table value
column7: The evaluation of the THE subquery or nested table column resulted in a NULL value implying a NULL table instance. The THE subquery or nested table column must identify a single non-NULL table instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the evaluation of the THE subquery or nested table column results in a single non-null table instance. If happening in the context of an INSERT statement where the THE subquery is the target of an insert, then ensure that an empty nested table instance is created by updating the nested table column of the parent table's row specifying an empty nested table constructor.

column6: exceeded maximum VARRAY limit
column7: The total number of elements used in VARRAY construction exceeds the specified VARRAY limit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the more than the specified limit of elements for VARRAY construction.

column6: cannot specify schema name for nested tables
column7: Table name was qualified with schema name in the nested table column's (or attribute's) storage clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Respecify the nested table item's storage clause without the schema name qualification. By default, the storage table for the nested table item is created in the same schema as the containing table.

column6: duplicate storage specification for the nested table item
column7: The storage clause is specified more than once for the NESTED TABLE column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate storage specification.

column6: specified column or attribute is not a nested table type
column7: The storage clause is specified for a column or attribute that is not a nested table column or attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid nested table column or attribute.

column6: must specify table name for nested table column or attribute
column7: The storage clause is not specified for a nested table column or attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the nested table storage clause for the nested table column or attribute.

column6: DROP of nested tables not supported
column7: An attempt was made to DROP a nested table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Nested tables cannot be explicitly dropped. nested tables can only be dropped by dropping their containing parent table.

column6: cannot ALTER nested tables to ADD/MODIFY columns
column7: An attempt was made to ADD or MODIFY columns of a nested table. Columns cannot be added or modified for a nested table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Instead, alter the parent table's nested table column to cause any such change.

column6: cannot do an exact FETCH on a query with Nested cursors
column7: Exact FETCH on a query was specified which is not allowed if the query returns any cursors.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use an exact FETCH.

column6: use VARRAY to define the storage clause for this column or attribute
column7: Not using VARRAY to define storage clause for VARRAY column or attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify VARRAY before the column storage clause and resubmit the statement.

column6: specified column or attribute is not a VARRAY type
column7: An attempt was made to define a VARRAY storage clause for a column or attribute which is not VARRAY type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify VARRAY storage clause for a VARRAY column or attribute.

column6: dangling REF error or lock object failed for no wait request
column7: The error could be one of the following: the object corresponding to the REF does not exist or the object was locked by another user and the lock with nowait request failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the REF value is pointing to an existing object or issue a lock request without the nowait option.
