column6: row containing the LOB value is not locked
column7: The row containing the LOB value must be locked before updating the LOB value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Lock the row containing the LOB value before updating the LOB value.

column6: length of input buffer is smaller than amount requested
column7: The buffer length is not big enough to hold the amount of data requested.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the number of bytes/characters specified in the input amount parameter is not bigger than the number of bytes specified in the input buffer length parameter. Allocate more space for the input buffer if necessary.

column6: nonexistent LOB value
column7: The LOB value associated with the input locator does not exist. The information in the locator does not refer to an existing LOB.
column8: From Oracle doc: Repopulate the locator by issuing a SELECT statement and retry the operation.

column6: amount of data specified in streaming LOB write is 0
column7: An attempt was made to write LOB value via the streaming mechanism (that is, unlimited write) but the input amount of data to stream was specified as 0. Thus, the user is trying to write 0 bytes to the LOB value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Write more than 0 bytes to the LOB value.

column6: snapshot too old
column7: The version of the LOB value needed for the consistent read was already overwritten by another writer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a larger version pool.

column6: operation would exceed maximum size allowed for a LOB value
column7: An attempt was made to write too much data to the LOB value. LOB size is limited to 4 gigabytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either start writing at a smaller LOB offset or write less data to the LOB value.

column6: specified trim length is greater than current LOB value's length
column7: The input length for which to trim the LOB value to is greater than the current length of the LOB value.
column8: From Oracle doc: May not need to trim the LOB value because it's already smaller than the trim length specified. Or, if trimming the LOB value really is required, use a smaller trim length.

column6: invalid LOB locator specified
column7:
One of the following: 

The LOB locator was never initialized. 

The locator is for a BFILE and the routine expects a BLOB/CLOB/NCLOB locator. 

The locator is for a BLOB/CLOB/NCLOB and the routine expects a BFILE locator. 

An attempt was made to update the LOB in a trigger body -- LOBs in trigger bodies are read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: For (1), initialize the LOB locator by selecting into the locator variable or by setting the LOB locator to empty. For (2) and (3), pass the correct type of locator into the routine. For (4), remove the trigger body code that updates the LOB value.

column6: invalid privilege on directories
column7: An attempt was made to grant or revoke an invalid privilege on a directory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only CREATE, DELETE, READ and WRITE privileges can be granted or revoked on directories. Do not grant or revoke other privileges.

column6: invalid or missing directory name
column7: The required directory name is invalid or missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid name.

column6: directory does not exist
column7: An attempt was made to access a directory that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the name is correct.

column6: cannot ORDER objects without MAP or ORDER method
column7: An object type must have a MAP or ORDER method defined for all comparisons other than equality and inequality comparisons.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define a MAP or ORDER method for the object type.

column6: NULL returned by ORDER method
column7: ORDER method used to compare two object values returned NULL which is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Redefine the ORDER method to not return a NULL.

column6: name does not correspond to an object view
column7: Either the expression is not a view name or the name specified does not correspond to an object view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the expression with the name of an object view.

column6: invalid datatype for PRIMARY KEY-based object identifier
column7: When creating an object view, the datatype of an expression in the WITH OBJECT OID clause is not allowed for PRIMARY KEY-based OID.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the expression with one of appropriate scalar datatype.

column6: NULL value not allowed in PRIMARY KEY-based object identifier
column7: A value constituting the PRIMARY KEY-based object identifier is NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the expressions in MAKE_REF system function or attributes in the WITH OBJECT OID clause of an object view do not evaluate to NULL.

column6: size of object identifier exceeds maximum size allowed
column7: Size of the PRIMARY KEY-based object identifier of an object view exceeded the maximum size of 65535 bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify fewer or smaller PRIMARY KEY attributes in the WITH object OID clause when creating the object view.

column6: missing WITH OBJECT OID clause
column7: WITH OBJECT OID clause was not specified when creating an object view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the WITH OBJECT OID clause.

column6: cannot create a PRIMARY KEY-based REF to this object view
column7: The object view specified in the MAKE_REF function does not have a PRIMARY KEY-based object identifier. A PRIMARY KEY-based REF cannot be created for such a view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an object view that has a PRIMARY KEY-based object identifier in the MAKE_REF function.

column6: incorrect number of arguments to MAKE_REF
column7: Number of arguments for MAKE_REF is different from the number of PRIMARY KEY attributes of the object view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify all the necessary arguments for MAKE_REF.

column6: missing or invalid attribute
column7: Either the attribute name is missing in the WITH OBJECT OID clause or it is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid attribute of the object type of the object view.

column6: only simple attribute name is allowed in the WITH OBJECT OID clause
column7: An attempt was made to specify a Nested attribute in the WITH OBJECT OID clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a top-level attribute of the object type of the object view.

column6: cannot INSERT object view REF or user-defined REF
column7: An attempt was made to insert an object view REF or user-defined REF in a REF column created to store system generated REF values.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the REF to be inserted is not from an object view or from a user-defined REF column

column6: must specify a set of attributes for the WITH OBJECT OID clause
column7: The WITH OBJECT OID DEFAULT clause was used, but the underlying view or table does not have a OID.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify attributes for the WITH OBJECT OID clause to create a primary key based object identifier for the object view.

column6: LOB locators cannot span transactions
column7: A LOB locator selected in one transaction cannot be used in a different transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reselect the LOB locator and retry the operation.

column6: insufficient space allocated for argument %s
column7: The data to be returned in the argument is greater than the amount of space allocated for the argument.
column8: From Oracle doc: Allocate more space for the argument.

column6: cannot use LOB locators selected from remote tables
column7: A remote LOB column cannot be referenced.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove references to LOBs in remote tables.

column6: specified input amount is greater than actual source amount
column7:
For LOB write, the amount of data received is different from the amount that was indicated would be sent. 

For LOB copy and load from file, the end of the source LOB/FILE value was reached before the specified input amount was copied/loaded.
column8: From Oracle doc: (1) will happen when using OCI's piecewise mechanism with polling or with a callback function. Modify the code either to send the amount specified or to pass 0 as the input amount so that any amount of data can be sent. (2) will happen if the specified input amount is too large for the source LOB/FILE given the starting source offset. Either decrease the starting source offset, or decrease the amount to copy/load.

column6: source offset is beyond the end of the source LOB
column7: The source offset for a LOB COPY or LOB LOADFROMFILE is beyond the end of the source LOB.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the length of the LOB and then adjust the source offset.

column6: TABLESPACE DEFAULT option is invalid in this context
column7:
TABLESPACE DEFAULT option can be specified for LOB columns only in the following contexts: 

at the table level for a partitioned table 

at the partition level for a composite partition 

An attempt was made to use the TABLESPACE DEFAULT option in a different context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the TABLESPACE DEFAULT option.

column6: NEXT extent size is smaller than LOB chunksize
column7: An attempt was made to create or alter a LOB segment so that its NEXT extent size was less than the LOB chunk size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a NEXT extent size that is greater than or equal to the LOB chunk size.

column6: VARRAY stored as LOB is not specified at the table level
column7: An attempt was made to specify a VARRAY column to be stored as LOB at the partition/subpartition level in a partition maintenance or a move table statement. However, the VARRAY column was not specified to be stored as LOB at the table level when the table was created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the VARRAY column to be stored as LOB at the table level when the table is created. Alternatively, do not specify the VARRAY column to be stored as LOB at the partition/subpartition level if it is not specified at the table level when the table is created.

column6: %s
column7: The stored procedure RAISE_SYSTEM_ERROR was called which causes this error to be generated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the problem as described in the error message or contact the application administrator or database administrator for more information.

column6: mixed use of deferred rpc destination modes
column7: Replication catalog determined deferred RPC destinations were mixed with destination determined by other mechanisms in the same transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not mix destination types in the same transaction.

column6: application raised communication failure during deferred RPC
column7: An application declared a communication failure during a deferred RPC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the application when communication is restored.

column6: application raised generic exception during deferred RPC
column7: An application declared a generic failure during a deferred RPC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determined by the application.

column6: malformed deferred rpc at arg %s of %s in call %s, in tid %s
column7: A deferred RPC call was issued without the correct number of arguments as determined by the count parameter to DBMS_DEFER.CALL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Be sure the number of arguments matches the count.

column6: internal deferred RPC error: %s
column7: An internal error occurred in deferred RPC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Report the error and other information to support.

column6: schema %s does not exist
column7: The schema name was null or misspelled, or the schema does not exist locally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the schema correctly, or create it with CREATE USER.

column6: replicated schema %s already exists
column7: The given database already replicates the given schema.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different schema or a different database.

column6: object %s.%s does not exist or is invalid
column7: The given name was null or misspelled, the given type was wrong, the object does not exist as a valid database object, or the object does not exist as a replicated object with the appropriate status.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the object is valid in the database, is visible to the user, and, if appropriate, is a valid object in ALL_REPOBJECT.

column6: object %s.%s of type %s exists
column7: An object in the same name space exists, perhaps with a different type or shape, or the same object has already been registered as an REPOBJECT in another object group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the offending object with the SQL DROP command, unregister the offending object with DBMS_REPCAT.DROP_MASTER_REPOBJECT(), or reinvoke the request using TRUE for a boolean parameter such as retry or USE_EXISTING_OBJECT.

column6: object group %s.%s is not quiesced
column7: The requested operation requires the object group to be suspended.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke SUSPEND_MASTER_ACTIVITY at the REPGROUP's MASTERDEF, wait until the status has changed to quiesced, and then retry the original request.

column6: not the masterdef according to %s
column7: The group name is null, the group name is misspelled, the invocation or given database is not the MASTERDEF, or one of the masters does not believe the invocation database is the MASTERDEF.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the given group name and MASTERDEF were both correct, connect to the MASTERDEF and retry the request, or relocate the MASTERDEF at the (errant) databases using RELOCATE_MASTERDEF.

column6: object group %s.%s is not mastered at %s
column7: The group name is null, the group name is misspelled, the invocation database is not a master, or the invocation database does not believe the given database is a master.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the given group name was correct, connect to a current master and retry the request, make the invocation database a master with ADD_MASTER_DATABASE, or use SWITCH_SNAPSHOT_MASTER if the invocation database is a snapshot site.

column6: database is not a snapshot site for %s.%s
column7: The invocation database is not a snapshot database for the given object group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect to the desired snapshot database and retry the request, or make the invocation database a snapshot site with CREATE_SNAPSHOT_REPSCHEMA or CREATE_SNAPSHOT_REPGROUP.

column6: repcatlog version or request %s is not supported by version %s
column7: Either incompatible REPCAT versions are used, or a REPCATLOG record has been corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Convert the master to a compatible version of REPCAT or retry the request.

column6: the masterdef is %s
column7: The requested operation is not permitted on a MASTERDEF site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Relocate the MASTERDEF to another master and retry the operation.

column6: a communication failure has occurred
column7: The remote database is inaccessible.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the remote database is running, the communications network is functioning, and the appropriate database links are present.

column6: a ddl failure has occurred
column7: User-supplied or system-generated DDL did not execute successfully.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine DDL, database state, REPCATLOG, and ALL_ERRORS to determine why the failure occurred.

column6: parameter value %s is not appropriate
column7: The given value of a parameter is either null, misspelled, or not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the documentation and use parameter values that are appropriate for the given situation.

column6: the request failed because of values %s and %s
column7: A missing DDL record for a REPCATLOG record, or inconsistency in REPCAT views.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the request, or make the views consistent.

column6: Pipename may not be null
column7: You called DBMS_PIPE with a null pipe name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find out the name of the pipe and call function with non-null pipe name.

column6: Privilege error accessing pipe
column7: You either tried to create a pipe that already existed and belonged to someone else, or remove a pipe that you were not authorized to use, or put a message into a pipe that you were not authorized for, or get a message from a pipe that you were not authorized for.
column8: From Oracle doc: You may have to use a different pipe name.

column6: parameter length exceeds deferred RPC limits
column7: A deferred RPC parameter was longer than the deferred RPC limits of 4000 bytes for char/varchar2 parameters and 2000 bytes for raw parameters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use smaller parameters.

column6: error %s, while creating deferror entry at "%s" with error %s
column7: The given error was encountered while attempting to create a DEFERROR entry for the give error code and the give database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the cause of the given error.

column6: parameter type is not %s
column7: A conflict resolution priority function was given a type different than the type assigned to the priority group; or the priority group has no type assigned or a function; or DBMS_DEFER_SYS_QUERY was called to retrieve a deferred RPC parameter from the deferred RPC queue, but the type of the parameter does not match the return type of the function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the function corresponding to the parameter type.

column6: object group %s.%s is quiesced
column7: Either SUSPEND_MASTER_ACTIVITY has been called before the object group has resumed normal operation or a (deferred) RPC operation was attempted while the object group was quiesced.
column8: From Oracle doc: If SUSPEND_MASTER_ACTIVITY has been called and a RESUME_MASTER_ACTIVITY request is pending, wait until it completes, and then reinvoke SUSPEND_MASTER_ACTIVITY. Otherwise, resume database activity with the RESUME_MASTER_ACTIVITY call.

column6: imported deferred rpc data does not match %s of importing db
column7: Deferred RPC queues were imported from a database with a different global name or operating system than importing database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Deferred RPC data should only be imported into a database with the same global name and hardware and operating system.

column6: snapshot base table "%s"."%s" differs from master table "%s"."%s"
column7: When creating a snapshot through REPCAT, the snapshot base table name did not match a replicated table name at the master.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the snapshot DDL to use the same base table as the replicated table name at the master.

column6: successful user-provided ddl but no snapshot "%s"."%s"
column7: The DDL provided by the user to create a snapshot was executed without error, but snapshot does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Manually back-out the DDL, and reregister with matching DDL and snapshot.

column6: column group %s already exists
column7: The column group was already registered in the object group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a column group name not yet registered in the replicated object group.

column6: column group %s does not exist
column7: The given column group is either null, misspelled or not registered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a registered column group.

column6: group %s is in use; cannot drop
column7: The given column group or priority group is being used to resolve conflicts.
column8: From Oracle doc: Call DBMS_REPCAT procedures DROP_UPDATE_RESOLUTION, DROP_DELETE_RESOLUTION, DROP_UNIQUE_RESOLUTION so that the column group or priority group is no longer in use before dropping.

column6: column "%s" is already part of a column group
column7: An attempt was made to add a column to a column group when the column was already a member of a column group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the column from its existing column group before trying to add it to another.

column6: column "%s" does not exist in table or column group
column7: The given column is either null, misspelled or is not part of the given table or column group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a column that is a member of the table or column group.

column6: priority group %s already exists
column7: The priority group was already registered in the object group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a column group name not yet registered in the object group.

column6: priority group %s does not exist
column7: The priority group was already registered in the object group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a priority group name not yet registered in the object group.

column6: priority or value not in priority group %s
column7: The specified value or priority has not been registered as part of the priority group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify a different value or priority that is already part of the priority group, or add the value to the priority group.

column6: priority or value already in priority group %s
column7: The specified value or priority has already been registered as part of the priority group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify a different value or priority that not already part of the priority group, or drop the value to the priority group.

column6: duplicate conflict resolution information
column7: The specified combination of column group, sequence, conflict type and/or parameter table name, parameter column name, and parameter sequence number has already been registered.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that additional conflict resolution information needs to be added and provide a new sequence number. If modifying existing information, the existing information must be dropped first.

column6: incorrect resolution method %s
column7: User function is specified when conflict resolution method was not "USER FUNCTION" or specified resolution method is not one of the predefined methods.
column8: From Oracle doc: If user function is specified when conflict resolution method was not "USER FUNCTION", either reregister function with method as "USER FUNCTION" or specify a NULL user function. Otherwise, specify one of the documented supported conflict resolution methods.

column6: user function required
column7: A NULL user function was specified for the "USER FUNCTION" method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide user function name (for example, "schema"."package"."function") that conforms to the documented user function specifications or specify one of the documented supported conflict resolution methods.

column6: invalid parameter column "%s"
column7: The parameter column name is null or misspelled, the invocation database is not a master, or is of the wrong type for the specified conflict resolution method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a parameter column from the specified column group that has a correct type for the conflict resolution method.

column6: no match for specified conflict resolution information
column7: The specified combination of column group, sequence, conflict type has not been registered (for example, for adding a comment).
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a combination of column group, sequence, conflict type has been registered.

column6: constraint (%s.%s) does not exist
column7: A null, misspelled or non-existent constraint was specified when registering a uniqueness conflict.
column8: From Oracle doc: Register a named constraint for the specified table.

column6: table "%s"."%s" not registered to collect statistics
column7: A procedure that deals with conflict resolution statistics-gathering was called for a table that was not registered to collect statistics.
column8: From Oracle doc: Call DBMS_REPCAT.REGISTER_STATISTICS to register the table.

column6: primary key is undefined for table or snapshot %s
column7: An attempt was made to generate replication support for a table or snapshot without a primary key as defined by a constraint or DBMS_REPCAT.SET_COLUMNS.
column8: From Oracle doc: For a table, add a primary key constraint or define a primary key using DBMS_REPCAT.SET_COLUMNS. For a ROWID snapshot, set MIN_COMMUNICATION to false or use a primary key snapshot.

column6: datatype %s for column "%s" table %s not supported
column7: The table has a column whose datatype is not supported by REPCAT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the column from the table, or alter the column to have one of the supported datatypes.

column6: cannot replicate procedure %s; only IN parameters supported
column7: An attempt was made to generate replication support for a package that has a procedure with OUT or IN OUT parameters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the procedure from the package, or remove the OUT or IN OUT parameters from the procedure.

column6: cannot generate replication support for functions
column7: An attempt was made to generate replication support for a package that has a public function, or for a standalone function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the public function from the package, or alter the function to be a procedure.

column6: maximum number of recursive calls exceeded
column7: This usually occurs when trying to resolve conflicts in a table while concurrent updates to the same row create more conflicts.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-execute the deferred transaction from DefError using DBMS_DEFER_SYS.EXECUTE_ERROR.

column6: parameter datatype %s for procedure %s not supported
column7: The procedure has a parameter whose datatype is not supported by REPCAT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the parameter from the procedure, or alter the parameter to have one of the supported datatypes.

column6: duplicate destination for deferred transaction
column7: A duplicate destination was specified for a deferred transaction either in a DBMS_DEFER.CALL call or an earlier DBMS_DEFER.TRANSACTION call or a dbms_defer_sys.add_default_dest call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate entry.

column6: deferred RPC queue has entries for object group %s.%s
column7: The requested action cannot be performed until the queue is empty for the given object group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use DBMS_DEFER_SYS.EXECUTE or DBMS_DEFER_SYS.DELETE_TRAN to empty the queue.

column6: deferred RPC execution disabled for "%s"
column7: Deferred RPC cannot be executed at the destination because their propagation has been disabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable deferred RPC execution with the DBMS_DEFER_SYS.ENABLE call.

column6: object %s.%s does not exist or is invalid at master site
column7: The given name was null or misspelled, the given type was wrong, the object does not exist as a valid database object at the master site, or the object does not exist as a replicated object with the appropriate status.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the object is valid in the master database, and is visible to the user, and, if appropriate, is a valid object in ALL_REPOBJECT.

column6: masterdef recognizes a master which does not recognize the masterdef
column7: Possibly DROP_MASTER_REPGROUP was run at a master site but REMOVE_MASTER_DATABASES was not run at master definition site for that master.
column8: From Oracle doc: Run REMOVE_MASTER_DATABASES from master definition site to remove the appropriate master (see associated error messages).

column6: the propagator does not exist
column7: The propagator does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Register a new propagator.

column6: invalid remote user
column7: The local user does not match the remote user connected via a database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop and re-create the identified database link with the connect-to user identical to the owner of the database link.

column6: error on creating a ddl record for a repcatlog record
column7: The USERID in the REPCATLOG record does not match the USERID of the connected user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation with a different user.

column6: only one snapshot for master table "%s" can be created
column7: An attempt was made to create more than one snapshot on a given master table in the same rep group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create these other snapshots in a different rep group at another site.

column6: snapshot "%s" does not exist at master site
column7: The snapshot does not exist at the master site for offline instantiation of the snapshot.
column8: From Oracle doc: The correct procedure is to create the snapshot in a different schema at the master site, and then follow the instructions for offline instantiation of snapshots.

column6: invalid user
column7: The given user does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter the name of a valid user and retry the operation.

column6: mismatch of snap base table "%s" at master and snap site
column7: The name of the base table of the snapshot at the master site is different from the base table at the snapshot site. This error may arise during offline instantiation of snapshots.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry offline instantiation with a snapshot name less than 24 bytes

column6: Feature not enabled: Advanced replication
column7: The Advanced Replication feature is not enabled at this site. Updatable snapshots, deferred RPCs, and other replication features are, therefore, unavailable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to use this feature. Contact Oracle Customer Support if the Advanced Replication feature has been purchased but not enabled.

column6: site %s does not exist
column7: site specified in argument REFERENCE_SITE or argument COMPARISON_SITE in call to DIFFERENCES() routine or RECTIFY() routine does not name an existing site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that database sites specified really do exist, and rerun the routine.

column6: integer value %s is less than 1
column7: Value of argument MAX_MISSING to routine DIFFERENCES() cannot be less than 1. Value of argument COMMIT_ROWS to routines DIFFERENCES() and RECTIFY() cannot be less than 1.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose an integer value for those arguments to be 1 or greater.

column6: table %s is missing the primary key
column7: Table specified in argument "oname1" or "oname2" in call to "differences()" routine does not contain either a primary key or a virtual primary key (defined through DBMS_REPCAT package under symmetric replication).
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the tables specified have a primary key defined.

column6: name %s cannot be null or the empty %s
column7: Argument SNAME1, SNAME2, ONAME1, ONAME2, MISSING_ROWS_SNAME, MISSING_ROWS_ONAME1, MISSING_ROWS_ONAME2 to DIFFERENCES() or RECTIFY() cannot be NULL or '' (empty string).
column8: From Oracle doc: Change argument to non-null or non-empty string.

column6: value of "%s" argument cannot be null
column7: Argument MAX_MISSING to DIFFERENCES() routine cannot be NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Legal values for MAX_MISSING are integers 1 or greater.

column6: table %s and table %s are not shape equivalent (%s)
column7: The tables specified are not shape equivalent, which means intuitively that the number of columns, the names, their datatypes and lengths are not the same. Specifically, problem is in the parentheses and is one of the following: the number of columns are not equal, datatypes of columns with same name in different tables are different, lengths of varchar2 and char columns are not equal, precision and scale of number datatypes are not equal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the two tables being compared have the same number of columns, same column names, and same datatypes.

column6: column %s unknown in table %s
column7: Some column in ARRAY_COLUMNS argument (or COLUMN_LIST argument) to DIFFERENCES() routine does not correspond to a column in the specified table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that all the columns in either ARRAY_COLUMNS or COLUMN_LIST are present in the specified table.

column6: type %s in table %s is unsupported
column7: Certain types in the table comparison utility are not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the types of columns in the tables to be compared are the ones supported by symmetric replication.

column6: object group %s.%s does not exist
column7: The group name was null or misspelled, or the group does not exist locally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the group correctly, or create it with DBMS_REPCAT.CREATE_MASTER_REPGROUP().

column6: object group %s.%s already exists
column7: The given database already replicates the given object group. A snapshot repgroup cannot be created at a given site where a master repgroup with the same name already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different group or a different database.

column6: feature is incompatible with database version at %s
column7: A feature not compatible with the specified database was used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set or raise the value of the COMPATIBLE initialization parameter to match the necessary compatibility level.

column6: node %s is not compatible with replication version "%s"
column7: A feature not compatible with the remote database was used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the remote database and retry the operation.

column6: bad name %s for missing_rows_oname1 argument
column7: An attempt was made to use the name of the reference site table as the name of the missing_rows_oname1 argument.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a separately created table with a different name for MISSING_ROWS_ONAME1 argument. The separately created table will contain the differences between the tables being compared.

column6: connection qualifier "%s" is not valid for object group %s.%s
column7: The connection qualifier used in the database link for the specified object group does not match the qualifier specified for the group in CREATE_MASTER_REPGROUP.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use or create a database link which contains the correct connection qualifier.

column6: connection qualifier "%s" is too long
column7: The maximum length of a database link, including the connection qualifier, is 128 bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a shorter connection qualifier, or shorten the name of the database link

column6: propagation mode "%s" is not valid
column7: The specified propagation is misspelled, or is not supported. For snapshot sites, all snapshot object groups at the same snapshot site with the same master object group must all have the same propagation method.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to Oracle8i Replication for valid propagation modes. For snapshot sites, also ensure that the propagation modes of all snapshot object groups with the same master object group are the same.

column6: generated object for base object %s.%s@%s does not exist
column7: The system generated object(s) for the specified base object do not exist at the specified site. The current operation requires the base object to have generated replication support.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the generated replication object(s) for the base object exist and are valid at the specified site. If the generated object(s) do not exist, then the procedure DBMS_REPCAT.GENERATE_REPLICATION_SUPPORT() needs to be called from the master definition site for the base object. missing_rows_oname1 argument. The separately created table will contain the differences between the tables being compared.

column6: snapshot repgroup %s.%s is not registered at site %s
column7: The snapshot REPGROUP is not currently registered at the master and so cannot be unregistered.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: registration for snapshot repgroup %s.%s failed at site %s
column7: Insertion into local REPSCHEMA table failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: replication parallel push %s argument out of range
column7: Specified numeric argument to DBMS_DEFER_SYS.PUSH is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the argument value and try again.

column6: replication parallel push %s argument not valid
column7: Specified string argument to DBMS_DEFER_SYS.PUSH is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the argument value and try again.

column6: replication parallel push cannot create slave processes
column7: An error was occurred while creating slave processes for parallel push.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the PARALLEL_MAX_SERVERS initialization parameter is zero, reconfigure the parameter to be greater than zero. Otherwise, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: replication parallel push dequeue error
column7: An attempt to dequeue a deferred transaction failed while trying to assign a new queue batch number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: replication parallel push watermark error
column7: An error occurred during parallel push while trying to update the high-water-mark information in SYSTEM.DEF$_DESTINATION.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: obsolete procedure; drop objects and recreate using new master
column7: DBMS_REPCAT.SWITCH_SNAPSHOT_MASTER is no longer supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the objects in the object group and re-create them using the new master.

column6: could not find snapshot to be associated with "%s"."%s"
column7: Could not find snapshot associated with a trigger or index that is being pulled from the master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that snapshot, master, and master index or trigger is registered as replicated objects.

column6: the user is already the propagator
column7: The given user is already the current propagator.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: duplicate propagator
column7: More than one valid propagator exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Unregister any duplicate propagator.

column6: object "%s"."%s" of type "%s" does not exist or is invalid
column7: The given name was null or misspelled, the given type was wrong, the object does not exist as a valid database object, or the object does not exist as a replicated object with the appropriate status.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure the object is valid in the database, is visible to the user, and, if appropriate, is a valid object in ALL_REPOBJECT.

column6: database link "%s" does not exist or has not been scheduled
column7: The database link does not exist in the schema of the replication propagator or has not been scheduled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the database link exists in the database, is accessible and is scheduled for execution.

column6: global name "%s" does not match database link name "%s"
column7: The database link name at the local node does not match the global name of the database that the link accesses.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that global names is set to true and the link name matches the global name.

column6: user name "%s" at database link "%s" does not match local user name "%s"
column7: The user name of the replication administration user at the local node and the user name at the node corresponding to the database link are not the same. Symmetric replication expects the two users to be the same.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the user ID of the replication administration user at the local node and the user ID at the node corresponding to the database link are the same.

column6: generation of replication support for "%s"."%s" is not complete
column7: Replication support for the specified object has not been generated or the generation process is not yet complete.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that replication support has been generated for the object. Use DBMS_REPCAT.GENERATE_REPLICATION_SUPPORT() to generate replication support for the object.

column6: invalid snapshot name "%s"
column7: A null, misspelled, or badly formed snapshot name was given to DBMS_SNAPSHOT.REFRESH.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a valid snapshot name to DBMS_SNAPSHOT.REFRESH.

column6: snapshot "%s"."%s" does not exist
column7: A snapshot name was given to DBMS_SNAPSHOT.REFRESH that is not in SYS.SNAP$ or its associated views.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a snapshot name that is in SYS.SNAP$, ALL_SNAPSHOTS or USER_SNAPSHOTS.

column6: refresh was aborted because of conflicts caused by deferred txns
column7: There are outstanding conflicts logged in the DefError table at the snapshot's master.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resolve the conflicts in the master DefError table and refresh again after the table is empty. Alternatively, refresh with REFRESH_AFTER_ERRORS set to TRUE, which will proceed with the refresh even if there are conflicts in the master's DefError table. Proceeding despite conflicts can result with an updatable snapshot's changes appearing to be temporarily lost (until a refresh succeeds after the conflicts are resolved).

column6: refresh group "%s"."%s" already exists
column7: Making a new refresh group when there is already a group of the same name in SYS.RGROUP$.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different refresh group name.

column6: refresh group "%s"."%s" does not exist
column7: A refresh group name was given that is not in SYS.RGROUP$.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a refresh group name that is in SYS.RGROUP$ or DBS_RGROUP.

column6: refresh group number %s does not exist
column7: A refresh group number was given that is not in SYS.RGROUP$.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a refresh group number that is in SYS.RGROUP$ or DBS_RGROUP.

column6: insufficient privileges on user "%s"
column7: The caller is not the owner of the snapshot and does not have ALTER ANY SNAPSHOT privileges.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform the operation as the owner of the snapshot or as a user with ALTER ANY SNAPSHOT privileges.

column6: object name %s must be shaped like "schema"."object" or "object"
column7: The object name (for example, the rollback segment, the snapshot name, the refresh group) was incorrectly specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation with the object name properly specified (like "schema"."object" or "object").

column6: this replication operation is not supported in a mixed configuration
column7: Operation is not supported if the object group is replicated at a pre-V8 node.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that all nodes of the replicated object group are V8.

column6: could not find an unused refresh group number
column7: 1000 consecutive refresh group numbers, as defined by the RGROUPSEQ number, were already used by rows in SYS.RGROUP$.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter the sequence number to be within a legal unused range and destroy unneeded refresh groups.

column6: snapshot "%s"."%s" is already in a refresh group
column7: A snapshot of the same name is already in a refresh group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Subtract the snapshot from the current refresh group and add it to its new refresh group, or combine the two refresh groups into a single refresh group.

column6: snapshot "%s"."%s" is not in refresh group "%s"."%s"
column7: The specified snapshot is not in the specified refresh group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again with the proper snapshot and refresh group names.

column6: master table's primary key columns have changed
column7: The master table's primary key constraint was modified after the primary key snapshot was created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop and re-create the primary key snapshot.

column6: table "%s"."%s" does not have a snapshot log
column7: The fast refresh cannot be performed because the master table does not contain a snapshot log.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG command to create a snapshot log on the master table.

column6: snapshot log for "%s"."%s" does not record rowid values
column7: A ROWID snapshot is being fast refreshed, but the snapshot log does not record ROWID information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG...ADD ROWID command to begin recording ROWID information in the snapshot log.

column6: snapshot log for "%s"."%s" does not record the primary key
column7: A primary key snapshot is being fast refreshed, but the snapshot log does not record primary key information.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG...ADD PRIMARY KEY command to begin recording primary key information in the snapshot log.

column6: table "%s"."%s" does not contain a primary key constraint
column7: The master table does not contain a primary key constraint or the primary key constraint has been disabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a primary key constraint on the master table or enable the existing constraint.

column6: unknown snapshot type: %s
column7: A fast refresh is being performed on a snapshot of an unknown or unsupported type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check ALL_SNAPSHOTS and ensure that the snapshot being refreshed is a valid snapshot.

column6: cannot unregister the propagator who is currently in use
column7: The propagator is currently used in propagating replication RPCs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again later when there is no transaction active in propagating replication RPCs.

column6: regenerate replication support before resuming master activity
column7: There are tables in the object group that require regeneration of replication support.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the GENERATION_STATUS column in the ALL_REPOBJECTS view. Regenerate replication support for any table in the object group with a 'NEEDSGEN' status. Resume master activity.

column6: interval must evaluate to a time in the future
column7: The parameter INTERVAL evaluates to a time earlier than SYSDATE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose an expression that evaluates to a time later than SYSDATE.

column6: job number %s is not a job in the job queue
column7: There is no job visible to the caller with the given job number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose the number of a job visible to the caller.

column6: Oracle Server could not generate an unused job number
column7: Oracle Server could not generate a job number that was not used to identify another job.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation.

column6: job number %s is not positive
column7: The given job number is less than 1.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a positive integer.

column6: snapshot "%s"."%s" at %s not registered
column7: The specified snapshot has not be successfully registered at this site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Register the snapshot manually at either the master site or the snapshot site.

column6: invalid snapshot identifier %s
column7: The argument provided to DBMS_SNAPSHOT.PURGE_SNAPSHOT_FROM_LOG is an invalid snapshot identifier or it does not identify an Oracle 8 fast refreshable snapshot or the snapshot has been already purged.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the snapshot is an Oracle 8 fast refreshable snapshot then provide PURGE_SNAPSHOT_FROM_LOG with its valid snapshot identifier.

column6: deferred RPC queue has entries for %s
column7: The requested action cannot be performed until the queue is empty for the given site/database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use DBMS_DEFER_SYS.PUSH, DBMS_DEFER_SYS.PURGE_QUEUE or DBMS_DEFER_SYS.DELETE_TRAN to empty the queue.

column6: deferred purge queue argument %s out of range
column7: Specified numeric argument to DBMS_DEFER_SYS.PURGE_QUEUE is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the argument value and try again.

column6: job associated instance number %s is not valid
column7: A job is associated with an instance that is not running.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a running instance for job affinity, or set force parameter to TRUE.

column6: argument "%s" cannot be NULL or empty %s
column7: The caller has provided an argument whose value cannot be NULL or the empty string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the varchar2 value provided is not NULL or the empty string, and retry the call.

column6: wrong state: %s
column7: The routine was executed against a replicated object group that was in the wrong state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the replicated object group is in the state given in the error message.

column6: master site %s already exists
column7: An attempt was made to instantiate a replicated object group at a master site that was already a part of the object group.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you were trying to add this site, do nothing because it already exists; otherwise, pick the name of another site, and rerun the routine.

column6: executing against wrong master site %s
column7: An attempt was made to execute the routine at a site that is different from the site specified in the argument of the routine.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide an argument to the routine that correctly indicates the site against which the routine should be executing.

column6: master site %s not known for object group
column7: The site name given as an argument to a routine was not already known to the replicated object group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute the DBMS_OFFLINE_OG.BEGIN_INSTANTIATION() routine to add a new site to the replicated object group.

column6: cannot create an updatable ROWID snapshot with LOB columns
column7: The propagation of LOB data from snapshot sites to the master site requires a primary key on the replicated table. Thus updatable ROWID snapshots that contain LOB columns are not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a primary key snapshot instead of a ROWID snapshot. If the snapshot already exists, it can be converted to a primary key snapshot using the ALTER SNAPSHOT DDL command.

column6: missing template authorization for user
column7: The specified template authorization does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the values for user name, refresh template name or AUTH_TEMPLATE_ID to ensure a valid row exists in the DBA_REPCAT_USER_AUTHORIZATIONS view.

column6: template authorization already exists for user
column7: The specified user already has been authorized to use the specified refresh group template.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the values for user name and refresh template name or query the DBA_REPCAT_USER_AUTHORIZATIONS view to ensure that the correct values were passed as parameters.

column6: missing refresh group template
column7: The specified refresh group template does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the refresh group template does not exist by querying the DBA_REPCAT_REFRESH_TEMPLATES view.

column6: refresh group template already exists
column7: The specified refresh group template already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the refresh group template exists by querying the DBA_REPCAT_REFRESH_TEMPLATES view.

column6: incorrect public template value
column7: The public template parameter is not 'Y', 'N' or NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value of the public template parameter. It must be 'Y','N' or NULL.

column6: object does not exist for refresh group template
column7: The specified object does not exist in the refresh group template.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the object name and object type parameters. Check the DBA_REPCAT_TEMPLATE_OBJECTS view to verify the correct name and type of the object.

column6: object already exists for the refresh group template
column7: The specified object already exists in the refresh group template.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the object name and object type parameters. Query the DBA_REPCAT_REMPLATE_OBJECTS view to verify the correct name and type of the object.

column6: missing template parameter
column7: The specified template parameter does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the template parameter value and execute the procedure again. Use the DBA_REPCAT_TEMPLATE_PARMS view to verify the name of the refresh group template and parameter name.

column6: duplicate template parameter
column7: The template parameter already exists for the specified refresh group template.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the template parameter value and execute the procedure again. Use the DBA_REPCAT_TEMPLATE_PARMS view to verify the name of the refresh group template and parameter name.

column6: missing template site
column7: The template site specified by the site name, user name and refresh group template name does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the invalid parameter and execute the procedure again. Use the DBA_REPCAT_TEMPLATE_SITES view to query the existing template sites.

column6: duplicate template site
column7: The template site specified by the site name, user name and refresh group template name already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the invalid parameter and execute the procedure again. Use the DBA_REPCAT_TEMPLATE_SITES view to query the existing template sites.

column6: missing user parameter value
column7: The user parameter value specified by the user name, parameter name and refresh group template name does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the invalid parameter and execute the procedure again. Use the DBA_REPCAT_USER_PARM_VALUES view to query the existing user parameters.

column6: duplicate user parameter value
column7: The user parameter value specified by the user name, parameter name and refresh group template name already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the invalid parameter and execute the procedure again. Use the DBA_REPCAT_USER_PARM_VALUES view to query the existing user parameters.

column6: missing user name
column7: The user specified by the user name parameter does not exist in the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct an invalid user name or create the user in the master database. Use the DBA_USERS view to select the valid database users.

column6: flavor already contains object "%s"."%s"
column7: The flavor already contains the specified object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the specified object is correct. To add all columns of a table object, delete the object from the flavor and then add it again.

column6: flavor %s already defined for object group %s.%s
column7: The given object group already contains a (possibly unpublished) definition of the specified flavor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the flavor name. Check for an unpublished flavor of the desired name.

column6: flavor %s of object group %s.%s is already published
column7: The given object group already contains a (published) definition of the specified flavor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the flavor name.

column6: requested operation is not supported on top flavor
column7: The TOP flavor has a NULL name and may not be directly defined or deleted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the name of a flavor other than the TOP flavor or use DBMS_REPCAT routines to implicitly change the TOP flavor.

column6: flavor %s not defined for object group %s.%s
column7: The given object group does not contain a (published) definition of the specified flavor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the flavor name. Ensure the flavor has been defined (and published) for the object group.

column6: flavor %s contains object "%s"
column7: The given flavor contains the object to be dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Purge the flavor or choose another object to drop.

column6: flavor %s does not contain "%s"
column7: The flavor does not contain the given object, column, or attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either drop the flavor or choose a different object, column, or attribute.

column6: invalid flavor ID %s
column7: The given flavor ID is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure this flavor has been instantiated. If the flavor ID is outside the range (-2147483647, 2147483647), contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: inappropriate flavor %s at %s
column7: The given flavor at the given database prevents the operation from succeeding.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either change the database flavor or choose a different operation.

column6: flavor %s must contain "%s"
column7: The flavor must contain the given object, column, or attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either choose a different database flavor or ensure the object, column, or attribute is available.

column6: missing value for column %s in resolution method "%s" for "%s"."%s"."%s"
column7: Before resolving conflicts, some values necessary for resolving conflicts are not available; or, after resolving conflicts, some values necessary for retrying the SQL are not available.
column8: From Oracle doc: define appropriate flavors, provide necessary values through availability vector in USER FLAVOR FUNCTION for conflict resolution.

column6: fail to resolve conflict for "%s"."%s"."%s"
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: flavor %s in use at site %s
column7: The given flavor cannot be deleted because it is being used at the given site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the flavor of the site, or unregister it if it is a snapshot site.

column6: flavor incompatible with object "%s"."%s"
column7: An existing flavor includes the specified object with an incompatible type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the type of the object, or delete the flavor if it is not in use.

column6: flavor lacks column %s of "%s"."%s"
column7: The flavor includes some columns of an object group but not all the required columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the flavor definition to include all required columns.

column6: flavor already includes column %s of "%s"."%s"
column7: The flavor includes the specified column which is being added.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the specified column is correct.

column6: flavor requires missing object "%s"."%s"
column7: The flavor includes the specified object which does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the specified object name is correct, and create the object if appropriate.

column6: flavor lacks object "%s"."%s"
column7: The flavor does not include the specified object which is being dropped.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the specified object is correct.

column6: missing %s %s
column7: The template is missing the object with the specified key.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add the object to the template.

column6: %s is different between templates
column7: The values for the specified columns are different in each template for the same key values.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the column values to make the templates the same.

column6: invalid status
column7: The status should be DELETED, INSTALLING or INSTALLED. Any other status is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the specified status value is correct.

column6: template not authorized for user
column7: The refresh template is private and the user has not been authorized to instantiate the template.
column8: From Oracle doc: Authorize the user to use the template.

column6: snapshot "%s"."%s" must be atomically refreshed
column7: Non-atomic refresh is not supported for the specified snapshot.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the value of the ATOMIC parameter to FALSE in the refresh procedure being used or remove the specified snapshot from the set of snapshots being refreshed.

column6: replication RPC processing for "%s"."%s" is disabled
column7: The processing of replication RPCs for the object group that contains this object is disabled. This includes RPCs in the error queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Processing of replication RPCs is disabled when the object group is being offline instantiated. Wait until offline instantiation is finished.

column6: definition of "%s"."%s" has changed since generation of replication support
column7: The current columns in the specified table and their column types do not match the columns and column types when replication support was last generated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Regenerate replication support for the affected table. All flavors that include the specified table should also be checked for validity.

column6: key column "%s" must be sent and compared
column7: The specified column is a key column and must be sent and compared during replication propagation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure every key column is sent and compared.

column6: cannot import from %s to %s
column7: This object was imported from a database with a different global name than the importing database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only import this object into a database with the same global name.

column6: unable to alter propagation mode for object group %s.%s
column7: The propagation method of a snapshot object group can only be altered when no other object groups with the same master object group are sharing the snapshot site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that there are no other snapshot object groups at the local site with the same master object group.

column6: object group %s is already mastered at %s
column7: There is at least one other snapshot repgroup at the local site with the same group name but a different master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that all snapshot repgroups at the local site with the same group name have the same master.

column6: invalid value %s, %s should be of the form [SCHEMA.]NAME
column7: An invalid value was specified for the parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a string of the form [SCHEMA.]NAME.

column6: cannot create QUEUE_TABLE, %s already exists
column7: The queue table already exists in the queueing system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the table first using the DROP_QUEUE_TABLE() command or specify another table.

column6: QUEUE_TABLE %s does not exist
column7: QUEUE_TABLE does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Query on the user view USER_QUEUE_TABLES to find out existing queue tables.

column6: Queue table index %s inconsistent with queue table %s
column7: The queue table index has not yet been successfully imported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Import the queue table index before attempting to use the queue table. If the import failed, correct the problem and try to import the queue table index again.

column6: invalid column name %s in SORT_LIST, should be ENQ_TIME or PRIORITY
column7: Invalid column name was specified in the SORT_LIST.
column8: From Oracle doc: The valid column names are ENQ_TIME and PRIORITY.

column6: must use DBMS_AQADM.DROP_QUEUE_TABLE to drop queue tables
column7: An attempt was made to use the SQL command DROP TABLE for queue tables, but DROP TABLE is not supported for queue tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the DBMS_AQADM.DROP_QUEUE_TABLE procedure instead of the DROP TABLE command.

column6: cannot create QUEUE, %s already exists
column7: The queue requested to be created already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify another queue name. Query USER_QUEUES for all the existing queues in the users's schema.

column6: invalid value %s, MAX_RETRIES should be non-negative integer
column7: An invalid value was specified for MAX_RETRIES.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-negative integer.

column6: queue table %s.%s must be dropped first
column7: An error was detected when dropping a queue table in a cluster, tablespace, or schema.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the DBMS_AQADM.DROP_QUEUE_TABLE procedure to drop the specified queue table first; then, retry the operation.

column6: invalid value %s, QUEUE_TYPE should be NORMAL_QUEUE or EXCEPTION_QUEUE
column7: Invalid queue type parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Valid values are NORMAL_QUEUE for normal queue and EXCEPTION_QUEUE for exception queue.

column6: QUEUE %s does not exist
column7: The specified queue does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid queue. Query USER_QUEUES for all the valid queues.

column6: cannot drop QUEUE, %s should be stopped first
column7: The queue has not been stopped. That is, either enqueue or dequeue is still enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Stop the queue first using the STOP_QUEUE command and disable it from both enqueueing and dequeueing.

column6: cannot drop QUEUE_TABLE, some queues in %s have not been dropped
column7: A queue exists in the queue table which has not been dropped. All queues need to be dropped first.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop all queues belonging to this queue table using the DROP_QUEUE() command. Be sure to stop the queues appropriately before dropping them. Alternately, use the force option in DROP_QUEUETABLE.

column6: invalid value %s, RETRY_DELAY should be non-negative
column7: A negative value was specified for RETRY_DELAY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-negative value for RETRY_DELAY.

column6: invalid value %s, RETENTION_TIME should be FOREVER or non-negative
column7: Queue retention was specified, but the retention time was specified to be less than zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the retention time to be non-negative or FOREVER. Alternately do not specify retention.

column6: cannot create QUEUE_TABLE, QUEUE_PAYLOAD_TYPE %s.%s does not exist
column7: An invalid QUEUE_PAYLOAD_TYPE specified during CREATE_QUEUE_TABLE.
column8: From Oracle doc: The QUEUE_PAYLOAD_TYPE should be RAW or an object type that already exists in the database.

column6: cannot create QUEUE_TABLE, user %s does not have execute privileges on QUEUE_PAYLOAD_TYPE %s.%s
column7: An invalid object type specified for QUEUE_PAYLOAD_TYPE during CREATE_QUEUE_TABLE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure you have execute privileges on the object type specified for the queue.

column6: cannot enable enqueue on QUEUE, %s is an exception queue
column7: An attempt was made to enable enqueueing to an exception queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: STOP_QUEUE on %s failed, outstanding transactions found
column7: There were outstanding transactions on the queue, and WAIT was set to false, so STOP_QUEUE was unsuccessful in stopping the queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set WAIT to TRUE and try STOP_QUEUE again. It will hang till all outstanding transactions are completed.

column6: identifier for %s too long, should not be greater than %s characters
column7: The identifier specified is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again with a shorter identifier.

column6: Internal error in DBMS_AQ_IMPORT_INTERNAL, %s
column7: An internal error occurred in the package. DBMS_AQ_IMPORT_INTERNAL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: queue table definition not imported for %s.%s
column7: The queue definition is not updated because the queue table was not imported properly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Import the queue table again.

column6: the specified parameters has no effect on the queue
column7: The parameter combination will not cause the queue to be started or stopped.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. This is a warning.

column6: Internal error in DBMS_AQ_EXP_INTERNAL.%s [%s] [%s]
column7: An internal error occurred in the package DBMS_AQ_EXP_INTERNAL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Internal error in DBMS_AQ_IMP_INTERNAL.%s [%s] [%s]
column7: An internal error occurred in the package DBMS_AQ_IMP_INTERNAL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid value %s, QUEUE_PAYLOAD_TYPE should be RAW or an object type
column7: Parameter QUEUE_PAYLOAD_TYPE has invalid value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid object type or RAW.

column6: invalid value, %s should be non-NULL
column7: Parameter is NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-NULL value for the parameter.

column6: object %s exists, index could not be created for queue table %s
column7: Oracle AQ tried to create an index with the name specified in the error message. The index could not be created for the specified queue table because a object exists with the same name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the object specified in the error message and retry the command. You can also choose a different name for the queue table.

column6: no recipients for message
column7: An enqueue was performed on a queue that has been set up for multiple dequeuers but there were neither explicit recipients specified in the call nor were any queue subscribers determined to be recipients for this message.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either pass a list of recipients in the enqueue call or add subscribers to the queue for receiving this message.

column6: application %s is already a subscriber for queue %s
column7: An application name that was already a subscriber for the queue was specified in the DBMS_AQ.SUBSCRIBE call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose another application name and retry the call.

column6: AQ agent %s is not a subscriber for queue %s
column7: An AQ agent that was not a subscriber for the queue was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the name and/or address of the agent and retry the call.

column6: invalid SORT_ORDER column %s specified for queue table
column7: The CREATE QUEUE TABLE command was issued with MESSAGE_GROUPING set to TRANSACTIONAL and a sort order column other than priority. Only the priority column can be specified in the sort order for queue tables with transactional grouping.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the sort order list in the CREATE QUEUE TABLE command and retry the call.

column6: schema %s in QUEUE_NAME is not same as schema %s in QUEUE_TABLE
column7: The schema specified in the QUEUE_NAME parameter of CREATE_QUEUE is not the same as the schema specified in the QUEUE_TABLE parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the same schema name for both the QUEUE_NAME and QUEUE_TABLE parameters and retry the command.

column6: RETRY_DELAY and MAX_RETRIES cannot be used for a 8.0 compatible multiple consumer queue
column7: The CREATE_QUEUE or ALTER_QUEUE command was issued with a non-zero RETRY_DELAY and a QUEUE_TABLE that was created for multiple consumers and with COMPATIBLE parameter set to '8.0'.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either set the RETRY_DELAY to zero or upgrade the queue table to 8.1 compatible using the DBMS_AQADM.MIGRATE_QUEUE_TABLE procedure.

column6: Queue %s not created in queue table for multiple consumers
column7: Either an ADD_SUBSCRIBER, ALTER_SUBSCRIBER, or REMOVE_SUBSCRIBER procedure, or an ENQUEUE with a non-empty recipient list, was issued on a queue that was not created for multiple consumers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the queue in a queue table that was created for multiple consumers and retry the call.

column6: propagation schedule exists for QUEUE %s and DESTINATION %s
column7: A SCHEDULE_PROPAGATION was issued for a queue and destination pair which has an existing propagation schedule.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue UNSCHEDULE_PROPAGATION to remove the existing schedule and then reissue the SCHEDULE_PROPAGATION call.

column6: no propagation schedule exists for QUEUE %s and DESTINATION %s
column7: AN UNSCHEDULE_PROPAGATION was issued for a queue and destination pair which has no existing propagation schedule.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify the spelling of the specified QUEUE and DESTINATION and then reissue the call with the correct spelling.

column6: destination %s uses a reserved name, names with AQ$_ prefix are not valid
column7: An attempt was made to specify a reserved name for a destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a different value or NULL for the local destination. Then retry the operation.

column6: source %s and destination %s object types do not match
column7: A message recipient's queue has a different object structure than the sender's queue. The message cannot be propagated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either remove the recipient from the subscriber's list for the sender's queue or create the destination queue with an object type that matches the source queue's object type.

column6: invalid agent address %s, agent address should be of the form [SCHEMA.]NAME[@DATABASE LINK]
column7: An invalid value was specified for the agent address parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a string of the form [SCHEMA.]NAME[@DATABASE LINK].

column6: protocol attribute reserved for future use
column7: The protocol attribute of the AQ agent object type is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify the protocol attribute in the agent object type.

column6: invalid agent name %s, agent name should be of the form NAME
column7: An invalid value was specified for the agent name parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a string of the form NAME. Then retry the operation.

column6: cannot create QUEUE_TABLE, user does not have access to AQ object types
column7: An attempt was made to issue the CREATE_QUEUE_TABLE command, but the user who issued the command does not have access to internal AQ object types.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the DBMS_AQADM.GRANT_TYPE_ACCESS procedure to grant the user access to the AQ object types.

column6: invalid agent name %s, names with AQ$_ prefix are not valid
column7: An attempt was made to use a reserved prefix in the agent name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a different value for the agent name. Then, retry the operation.

column6: subscribers are not supported for exception queue %s
column7: An ADD_SUBSCRIBER, ALTER_SUBSCRIBER, or REMOVE_SUBSCRIBER procedure was issued on a queue that was created as an EXCEPTION_QUEUE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a NORMAL_QUEUE in the procedure.

column6: cannot propagate object type payloads that have a REF or BFILE attribute
column7: An ADD_SUBSCRIBER or ENQUEUE procedure with a non-NULL address field in the agent type was issued on a queue whose payload has a REF or BFILE attribute. Propagation of object type payloads that have a REF or BFILE attribute currently is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an agent with a NULL address field so that the agent can dequeue from the same queue. Or, change the object type definition to one that does not use REF or BFILE attributes.

column6: cannot propagate object type payloads with LOB attributes to an 8.0 release
column7: The recipient of a message with LOB attributes was using an Oracle 8.0 release. Propagation of LOB attributes is supported only in Oracle 8.1 and higher releases.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the target release to Oracle 8.1 and retry. Or, change the object type definition to one that does not use LOBs.

column6: PRIMARY_INSTANCE and SECONDARY_INSTANCE must be non-negative
column7: One of PRIMARY_INSTANCE or SECONDARY_INSTANCE was negative.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify non-negative integers for PRIMARY_INSTANCE and SECONDARY_INSTANCE.

column6: cannot propagate to an Oracle 8.0.3 release or lower release
column7: The recipient of a message was using an Oracle 8.0.3 release or lower release. Propagation is supported only in Oracle 8.0.4 and higher releases.
column8: From Oracle doc: Upgrade the target release to Oracle 8.0.4 or higher and retry.

column6: cannot delete propagation status rows that are in prepared state
column7: An attempt was made to use the internal administration procedure to delete status rows from the SYS.AQ$_PROPAGATION_STATUS table that were in the prepared state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the propagation to complete successfully before retrying the operation.

column6: internal inconsistency for QUEUE %s and destination %s
column7: The sequence numbers used in the SYS.AQ$_PROPAGATION_STATUS table were inconsistent for the given queue and destination.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot define subscriber with rule for queue %s
column7: An ADD_SUBSCRIBER or ALTER_SUBSCRIBER procedure with a rule was issued on a queue for which rule based subscribers are not supported. Rule based subscribers currently are supported only for NORMAL (persistent) multi-consumer queues created using an Oracle release 8.1.0 or higher compatible queue table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a NORMAL multi-consumer queue in an Oracle release 8.1.0 or higher compatible queue table, and retry the call. Or, if the queue is a normal (persistent) multi-consumer queue, convert the queue table to Oracle 8.1.0 or higher compatibility and retry.

column6: cannot downgrade QUEUE_TABLE that has propagation in a prepared state
column7: An attempt was made to downgrade the queue table when there were messages being propagated that were in the prepared state.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for the propagation to complete before retrying the operation.

column6: invalid COMPATIBLE parameter setting %s specified in DBMS_AQADM.%s
column7: An invalid compatible parameter was specified in the DBMS_AQADM procedure. The parameter setting must be of the form '8.x.y' where x is the release number and y is the update number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid COMPATIBLE parameter setting, and retry the operation.

column6: cannot convert QUEUE_TABLE, %s already is compatible with release %s
column7: The source queue table in the DBMS_AQADM procedure is compatible with the specified COMPATIBLE parameter setting.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different COMPATIBLE parameter setting to convert the queue table to the desired compatibility.

column6: cannot specify non-zero SECONDARY_INSTANCE if PRIMARY_INSTANCE was zero
column7: A non-zero value was specified for SECONDARY_INSTANCE when PRIMARY_INSTANCE was zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-zero primary instance before you specify a non-zero secondary instance.

column6: Subscriber table %s inconsistent with queue table %s
column7: The subscriber table has not yet been successfully imported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Import the subscriber table before attempting to use the queue table. If the import failed, correct the problem and try to import the subscriber table again.

column6: cannot downgrade QUEUE_TABLE that has queues with rule-based subscribers
column7: An attempt was made to downgrade the queue table when there were queues on which rule-based subscribers are defined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the rule-based subscribers for all queues in this queue table and retry.

column6: propagation for QUEUE %s and DESTINATION %s already enabled
column7: An ENABLE_SCHEDULE_PROPAGATION command was issued for a queue and destination pair whose propagation schedule already was enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the QUEUE and DESTINATION are correct when you issue the ENABLE_SCHEDULE_PROPAGATION command.

column6: propagation for QUEUE %s and DESTINATION %s already disabled
column7: A DISABLE_SCHEDULE_PROPAGATION command was issued for a queue and destination pair whose propagation schedule already was disabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the QUEUE and DESTINATION are correct when you issue the DISABLE_SCHEDULE_PROPAGATION command.

column6: invalid privilege specified
column7: An invalid privilege is specified for granting or revoking privilege.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid privilege.

column6: exceeded maximum number of subscribers for queue %s
column7: An attempt was made to add new subscribers to the specified, but the number of subscribers for this queue has exceeded the maximum number (1024) of subscribers allowed per queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove existing subscribers before trying to add new subscribers.

column6: cannot start queue %s, queue table %s is being migrated
column7: An attempt was made to start a queue in a queue table that is being migrated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the queue table migration, and retry the operation.

column6: cannot downgrade queue table %s while it is being upgraded
column7: An attempt was made to downgrade a queue table, but a previous command to upgrade the queue table has not yet completed successfully.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the upgrade of the queue table by re-executing the DBMS_AQADM.MIGRATE_QUEUE_TABLE procedure. Then, downgrade the queue table.

column6: cannot upgrade queue table %s while it is being downgraded
column7: An attempt was made to upgrade a queue table, but a previous command to downgrade the queue table has not yet completed successfully.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the downgrade of the queue table by re-executing the DBMS_AQADM.MIGRATE_QUEUE_TABLE procedure. Then, upgrade the queue table.

column6: cannot perform operation %s, queue table %s is being migrated
column7: An attempt was made to perform an operation on a queue in a queue table that is being migrated.
column8: From Oracle doc: Complete the queue table migration, and retry the operation.

column6: cannot execute MIGRATE_QUEUE_TABLE procedure; must own queue table
