column7: An attempt was made to upgrade or downgrade a queue table using the DBMS_AQADM.MIGRATE_QUEUE_TABLE procedure, but the user who executed the procedure does not own the queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reconnect as the owner of the queue table, and then execute the DBMS_AQADM.MIGRATE_QUEUE_TABLE procedure.

column6: cannot specify RETENTION_TIME on exception queue %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to create or alter an exception queue by specifying a non-zero RETENTION_TIME.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the default RETENTION_TIME parameter value for exception queues.

column6: RETRY_DELAY and MAX_RETRIES cannot be used for exception queue %s
column7: The CREATE_QUEUE or ALTER_QUEUE command was issued with a non-zero RETRY_DELAY and an exception queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify RETRY_DELAY or MAX_RETRIES for exception queues.

column6: cannot specify agent with NULL address and non-NULL protocol
column7: An ADD_SUBSCRIBER or enqueue was attempted with an agent that had a NULL address and a non-NULL protocol.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify a non-NULL address or set the protocol to NULL.

column6: cannot perform operation %s for NON_PERSISTENT queue %s.%s
column7: One of the operations, SCHEDULE_PROPAGATION, ALTER_QUEUE, LISTEN, DEQUEUE was issued for a NON_PERSISTENT queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify a NON_PERSISTENT queue for these operations.

column6: cannot create propagation schedule for EXCEPTION queue %s.%s
column7: A SCHEDULE_PROPAGATION was issued for an EXCEPTION queue. Propagation schedules can be created only for NORMAL queues.
column8: From Oracle doc: To propagate messages from a queue, specify the queue type as NORMAL.

column6: cannot specify a non-NULL SECONDARY_INSTANCE if PRIMARY_INSTANCE was NULL
column7: A non-NULL value was specified for SECONDARY_INSTANCE when PRIMARY_INSTANCE was NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-NULL primary instance before you specify a non-NULL secondary instance.

column6: invalid name %s, names with AQ$_ prefix are not valid for %s
column7: An attempt was made to use a reserved prefix for the object name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a different name for this object. Then, retry the operation.

column6: unschedule_propagation pending for QUEUE %s and DESTINATION %s
column7: A propagation administration command was issued for a queue and destination pair whose propagation is being unscheduled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not issue propagation administration commands for a propagation schedule on which there is a pending unschedule request.

column6: compatible parameter needs to be %s or greater
column7: The value of the COMPATIBLE parameter was not high enough to allow the operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down and restart with a higher compatibility setting.

column6: propagation may still be happening for the schedule for QUEUE %s and DESTINATION %s
column7: The snapshot process executing the propagation schedule did not respond to the disable propagation command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the job for the propagation schedule has been ended.

column6: cannot specify remote subscribers for %s QUEUE %s
column7: An ADD_SUBSCRIBER call with a non-null address field was issued on a queue which does not support remote subscribers. Remote subscribers are not supported for NON_PERSISTENT QUEUES.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a null address field and retry the call.

column6: DBLINK name in address field of agent %s is not unique within the first 24 bytes"
column7: Advanced Queuing requires that the agent's DBLINK name should be unique within the first 24 bytes (for 8.0 compatible queue tables)
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a DBLINK name that is unique within the first 24 bytes or migrate to 8.1 compatible queue tables where this restriction is not there.

column6: error in ktz testing layer
column7: There is an error in the Transaction layer test ICDs.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: invalid %s parameter passed to DBMS_REPAIR.%s procedure
column7: An invalid parameter was passed to the specified DBMS_REPAIR procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid parameter value or use the parameter's default.

column6: both cascade and a block range passed to DBMS_REPAIR.CHECK_OBJECT procedure
column7: Both cascade and a block range were specified in a call to DBMS_REPAIR.CHECK_OBJECT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use either cascade or a block range, or do not use either one.

column6: invalid block range specification
column7: An incorrect block range was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify correct values for the BLOCK_START and BLOCK_END parameters.

column6: feature %s is not yet implemented
column7: An attempt was made to use the specified feature, but the feature is not yet implemented.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to use the feature.

column6: invalid ACTION parameter passed to DBMS_REPAIR.%s procedure
column7: An invalid ACTION parameter was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify CREATE_ACTION, PURGE_ACTION or DROP_ACTION for the ACTION parameter.

column6: Object %s.%s has changed
column7: An attempt was made to fix corrupt blocks on an object that has been dropped or truncated since DBMS_REPAIR.CHECK_OBJECT was run.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use DBMS_REPAIR.ADMIN_TABLES to purge the repair table and run DBMS_REPAIR.CHECK_OBJECT to determine whether there are any corrupt blocks to be fixed.

column6: invalid CASCADE_FLAG passed to DBMS_REPAIR.%s procedure
column7: CASCADE_FLAG was specified for an object that is not a table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use CASCADE_FLAG only for tables.

column6: TABLESPACE parameter specified with an ACTION other than CREATE_ACTION
column7: The TABLESPACE parameter can only be used with CREATE_ACTION.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify TABLESPACE when performing actions other than CREATE_ACTION.

column6: partition name specified for a non-partitioned object
column7: A partition name was specified for an object that is not partitioned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a partition name only if the object is partitioned.

column6: table name %s does not start with %s prefix
column7: An attempt was made to pass a table name parameter without the specified prefix.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass a valid table name parameter.

column6: table %s does not exist
column7: An attempt was made to specify a map, repair, or sync table that does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid table name parameter.

column6: table %s has incorrect columns
column7: An attempt was made to specify a map, repair, or sync table that does not have a correct definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a table name that refers to a properly created table.

column6: table name %s is too long
column7: An attempt was made to specify a table name is greater than 30 characters long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid table name parameter.

column6: ruleset specified does not exist
column7: An attempt to access or modify a ruleset was made, which failed because the ruleset does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only access or modify existing rulesets.

column6: invalid ruleset name
column7: An attempt to create a ruleset with an invalid name was made. The ruleset name cannot be NULL, and cannot be more than 26 characters, unless a RULES_TABLE_NAME is also specified, in which case the ruleset name may be up to 30 characters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the create with a valid ruleset name.

column6: invalid table name
column7: An attempt to create a ruleset on an invalid table name was made. The DATA_TABLE name cannot be NULL, and cannot be more than 30 characters. The table with the name specified must exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the create with a valid table name.

column6: rules engine internal error, arguments: [%s], [%s]
column7: An internal error occurred in the rules engine. This indicates that the rules engine has encountered an exception condition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support. The first argument is the error and the second argument is the package.

column6: a row already exists in the %s table for these parameters
column7: A call was made to create a new row in the specified table. A row already exists in the table with the specified values.
column8: From Oracle doc: Delete the existing row using the appropriate API or check the parameters used to create the row.

column6: translation type must be either T, S or M
column7: The translation type parameter is not a T, S or an M. A value other than T, S or M was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the translation type and re-execute the API call.

column6: initialization value must be either F or T
column7: The initialization value must be either F or T. A value other than F or T was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the initialization value and re-execute the API call.

column6: translation text is required if translation type is T or S
column7: If a translation type of T or S is specified, translation text must be supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide translation text and re-execute the API call.

column6: no row exists in the %s table for these parameters
column7: A call was made to update a row that does not exist or a foreign key value supplied to create a table does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the row using the appropriate API or check the parameters used to create the new row to ensure that all specified values exist.

column6: function '%s' parameter '%s' missing or invalid
column7: The function pkgname.funcname was called with a parameter parmname that was null, 0 length, or had an invalid value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the parameter to supply values that comply with its datatype and limits as specified in the documentation.

column6: function '%s' output '%s' maximum value exceeded
column7: The function pkgname.funcname computed a value for the output parmname that exceeded the maximum allowed. This can occur when multiple input parameters, each valid separately, combine to specify an invalid result. For example, when a length parameter multiplied by a copies parameter yields a total length exceeding the maximum for the output datatype.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the input values to produce a result that will comply with the limits as specified in the documentation.

column6: insufficient privileges to execute %s
column7: The access to the named procedure is limited to users with certain privileges, which the invoker does not have.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your documentation to verify the privileges needed to execute the named procedure.

column6: privilege type mismatch
column7: Privileges can be granted to a user on an object like execute rights or just to a user like create library rights. Those are different types of privileges. One cannot insert an object privilege into the user privileges table and vice versa.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the privilege type is correct.

column6: insufficient privileges to create library
column7: The user tried to create a remote library without having the remote create library privilege.
column8: From Oracle doc: A local database administrator must grant the remote user the create library privilege by invoking DBMS_HS_EXTPROC.GRANT_CREATE_LIBRARY().

column6: invalid input value for parameter %s
column7: The parameter has been provided a negative, out of range, or NULL input value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the input value such that it is valid, and is within the range as specified in the documentation.

column6: invalid access past the maximum size of LOB parameter %s
column7: The value of positional or size parameters exceeds the maximum allowed LOB size of 4 Gigabytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the input values for amount and offset such that their sum is less than or equal to 4 Gigabytes. If error occurs in a read or write loop, check the looping conditions and/or offset increments.

column6: bad value for mode
column7: An undefined mode value was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the correct mode is selected and that an allowed value for that mode is specified.

column6: null host specified in thread-safe logon
column7: An HDA was not specified in the logon call while running in a thread safe environment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that HDA is not NULL when calling the logon routine.

column6: host connection in use by another thread
column7: An attempt was made to use the host connection while it was in use by another thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for another thread to finish before using this connection.

column6: call not supported in non-deferred linkage
column7: One of the calls that is supported in deferred mode linkage exclusively was invoked when the client was linked non-deferred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use this call in deferred mode of linkage.

column6: datatype not allowed for this call
column7: Data of this datatype cannot be sent or fetched in pieces.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use other bind or define calls for this datatype.

column6: bad bind or define context
column7: The call was executed on a cursor for which this is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that this call is valid for this cursor. For example, Get piece information and set piece information are valid on a cursor if appropriate binds and defines have been done on this cursor.

column6: bad buffer for piece
column7: A zero length buffer or a null buffer pointer was provided.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the buffer pointing to this piece or its length is non-zero. The buffer pointer for the next piece or its length can be zero if it is the last piece to be inserted and there are no more data for the column.

column6: invalid length for piece
column7: The length of the piece exceeded the maximum possible size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the length of this piece and the cumulative length of all the previous pieces is not more than the desired value supplied by the application.

column6: illegal define position
column7: Call to modify attributes was done for a non-existent position.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that a define has been done for this position.

column6: already connected to a server
column7: This server handle is already attached to a server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Disconnect from the server and then retry the call to establish a connection.

column6: length specified for null connect %s
column7: The connect string is null, but a length was specified for it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set length to zero if connect string is null.

column6: memory initialization failed
column7: Cannot initialize user memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: illegal parameters specified for allocating user memory
column7: An illegal size or null pointer was specified for user memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a legal size and a valid pointer for user memory.

column6: user already authenticated
column7: A user has already been authenticated on this service handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Terminate the service context before using it for another user.

column6: service handle not initialized
column7: The server context does not done exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Establish the server context in the service context.

column6: illegal attribute type
column7: An illegal attribute type was specified for the handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult the Oracle Call Interface Programmer's Guide. to specify an attribute valid for this handle.

column6: illegal handle type
column7: An illegal handle type was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult the Oracle Call Interface Programmer's Guide. to specify a valid handle type.

column6: define handle used in a different position
column7: A define was done with an existing handle on a different position.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the same position as before on a redefine.

column6: call not allowed for scalar data types
column7: This call is valid only for object types.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the data-type for this variable is an object type.

column6: unable to allocate memory
column7: Process was unable to allocate memory to store diagnostics.
column8: From Oracle doc: Terminate other processes in order to reclaim needed memory.

column6: unable to initialize a mutex
column7: An attempt to initialize a MUTEX failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: inconsistent parameters passed
column7: One of the three memory function pointers is null or non-null.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that either all the memory functions are null or non-null.

column6: unable to delete an initialized mutex
column7: An attempt to delete an initialized MUTEX failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: value not allowed
column7: A null or invalid value was passed in for a mandatory parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that all mandatory parameters are properly initialized.

column6: service handle not initialized
column7: An attempt was made to use an improper service context handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the service context handle has all the parameters initialized prior to this call.

column6: this OCI operation is not currently allowed
column7: An attempt was made to use a context handle outside its scope.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the context handle is set to a service context handle that has been converted to a logon data area for other OCI calls. The logon data area must be converted back to a service context before it can be used.

column6: handle passed in is already initialized
column7: An attempt was made to pass an initialized handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the parameter passed in to retrieve a handle does not already point to a handle.

column6: need explicit attach before authenticating a user
column7: A server context must be initialized before creating a session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create and initialize a server handle.

column6: illegal attribute value
column7: The attribute value passed in is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult the Oracle Call Interface Programmer's Guide. and specify a legal attribute value for the handle.

column6: invalid character set identifier
column7: The character set identifier specified is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid character set identifier in the OCI call.

column6: internal OCI error
column7: An internal OCI error has occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: user buffer too small
column7: The user buffer to contain the output data is too small.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a bigger buffer.

column6: invalid object type
column7: An invalid object type is requested for the describe call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid object type to the describe call.

column6: zero iteration count
column7: An iteration count of zero was specified for the statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the number of times this statement must be executed.

column6: no descriptor for this position
column7: The application is trying to get a descriptor from a handle for an illegal position.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the position number.

column6: cannot support more than 1000 columns
column7: The number of columns exceeds the maximum number supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a number of columns less than 1000.

column6: invalid result set descriptor
column7: The result set descriptor should have valid data fetched into it before it can be converted to a statement handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fetch valid data into the descriptor before attempting to convert it into a statement handle.

column6: statement handle not prepared
column7: A statement cannot be executed before making preparing a request.
column8: From Oracle doc: Prepare a statement before attempting to execute it.

column6: statement handle not executed
column7: A fetch or describe was attempted before executing a statement handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute a statement and then fetch or describe the data.

column6: cannot set server group name after connecting to server
column7: An attempt was made to set the server group in a server handle after connecting to the server. However, once the connection is established to a server, the server group name cannot be set anymore.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attach to the server after setting the server group name in the server handle.

column6: cannot support more than 255 columns
column7: The number of columns exceeds maximum supported by the server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Limit your operation to 255 columns.

column6: bad mode specified
column7: OCI_ENV_NO_MUTEX mode was specified for a non-threaded client.
column8: From Oracle doc: OCI_ENV_NO_MUTEX may be specified when OCI_THREADED had been specified at process initialization.

column6: unable to destroy a mutex
column7: An attempt to destroy a MUTEX failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: user defined callback error
column7: The only valid return value for a user defined callback function is OCI_CONTINUE. Any other value will cause this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that OCI_CONTINUE is returned from the user-defined callback function.

column6: success with compilation error
column7: A SQL or PL/SQL compilation error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Return OCI_SUCCESS_WITH_INFO along with the error code.

column6: A Truncation or null fetch error occurred
column7: A truncation or a null fetch error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the buffer size is long enough to store the returned data.

column6: cannot execute without binding variables
column7: None of the bind variables in the SQL statement are bound.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bind all the variables before the execute is done.

column6: Warning of a NULL column in an aggregate function
column7: A null column was processed by an aggregate function.
column8: From Oracle doc: An OCI_SUCCESS_WITH_INFO is returned.

column6: Update or Delete without Where
column7: An UPDATE or DELETE was executed without a WHERE clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: An OCI_SUCCESS_WITH_INFO is returned.

column6: OCI call not allowed
column7: OCI used is not permitted from external procedures.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the Oracle Call Interface Programmer's Guide. for usage restrictions.

column6: invalid date passed into OCI call
column7: A bad date was passed into one of the OCI calls.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your date bind values and correct them.

column6: invalid COBOL display type passed into OCI call
column7: A bad COBOL display type was passed into one of the OCI calls.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your COBOL display type bind values and correct them.

column6: user buffer too small to accommodate COBOL display type
column7: User supplied buffer for a COBOL display type was too small to accommodate fetched number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the allocation for COBOL display type buffer.

column6: number fetched too large to fit in COBOL display type buffer.
column7: The number fetched was beyond the range that can be displayed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the number in the database.

column6: attempt to store a negative number in an Unsigned Display type.
column7: An attempt was made to convert a negative number into an unsigned display type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the number in the database or change the defined datatype.

column6: internal error while converting from to COBOL display type.
column7: An internal error was encountered during conversion to COBOL display type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: internal error while converting from to OCIDate.
column7: An internal error was encountered during conversion to OCIDate type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: OCIBindObject not invoked for a Object type or Reference
column7: OCIBindObject was not invoked resulting in an incomplete bind specification for a Object Type or Reference.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke the OCIBindObject call for all Object Types and References.

column6: OCIDefineObject not invoked for a Object type or Reference
column7: OCIDefineObject was not invoked resulting in an incomplete bind specification for a Object Type or Reference.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke the OCIDefineObject call for all Object Types and References.

column6: Type Descriptor Object not specified for Object Bind/Define
column7: Type Descriptor Object is a mandatory parameter for Object Types Binds and Defines.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke the OCIBindObject() or OCIDefineObject() call with a valid Type Descriptor Object.

column6: basic bind call not invoked before invoking advanced bind call
column7: One of the basic bind calls was not invoked on this bind handle before performing an advanced bind call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke the advanced bind call on this bind handle only after performing a basic bind call.

column6: improper use of the character count flag
column7: When the character count flag is set, then the maximum size of the buffer in the server should be specified as a non-zero value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a non-zero value for the maximum size of the buffer in the server.

column6: measurements in characters illegal here
column7: Measurements in characters instead of bytes are illegal if either the server's or client's character set is varying width.
column8: From Oracle doc: If either the client's or server's character set is varying width then do not use the OCI_ATTR_CHAR_COUNT attribute for the bind handle. Use OCI_ATTR_MAXDATA_SIZE instead.

column6: internal error while padding blanks
column7: An internal error has occurred while attempting to blank pad string data. This error should not occur normally.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: error in character conversion
column7: This usually occurs during conversion of a multibyte character data when the source data is abnormally terminated in the middle of a multibyte character.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that all multibyte character data is properly terminated.

column6: migratable user handle is set in service handle
column7: This occurs during user authentication, a migratable user handle has been set in the service handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Service handle must not be set with migratable user handle when it is used to authenticate another user.

column6: user handle has not been set in service handle
column7: This occurs during authentication of a migratable user. the service handle has not been set with non-migratable user handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Service handle must be set with non-migratable user handle when it is used to authenticate a migratable user.

column6: OCI mutex counter non-zero when freeing a handle
column7: This is an internal OCI error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: required callbacks not registered for one or more bind handles
column7: No callbacks have been registered for one or more of the bind handles which are part of the RETURNING clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: The bind handles which are to receive data in a DML statement with a RETURNING clause must have their mode set as DATA_AT_EXEC and callback functions must be registered for these bind handles using OCIBindDynamic.

column6: illegal piecewise operation attempted
column7: Data of a certain datatype that does not support piecewise operation is being sent or fetched in pieces.
column8: From Oracle doc: Always set the piece value to OCI_ONE_PIECE for datatypes that does not support piecewise operation.

column6: data would not fit in current prefetch buffer
column7: An internal OCI error has occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid object for describe
column7: The object to be described is not valid. It either has compilation or authorization errors.
column8: From Oracle doc: The object to be described must be valid.

column6: invalid length specified for statement
column7: The length specified for the statement is either 0 or too large.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid length for the statement.

column6: define not done before fetch or execute and fetch
column7: The application did not define output variables for data being fetched before issuing a fetch call or invoking a fetch by specifying a non-zero row count in an execute call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue OCI define calls for the columns to be fetched.

column6: Cannot use V6 syntax when talking to a V8 server
column7: V6 syntax is no longer supported in V8 server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change syntax to V7 syntax or higher.

column6: cannot register/get user callback for non-environment handle
column7: A user callback registration or get was attempted on a handle which is not an environment handle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass the environment handle to register/get user callback.

column6: invalid OCI function code
column7: An invalid function code was used to register or get user callback.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid OCI function code.

column6: user callbacks not allowed for this call
column7: An attempt was made to register a user callback for an OCI call for which it not allowed to register user callbacks.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not register user callback for this OCI call.

column6: invalid user callback type
column7: An invalid type of user callback was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid user callback type.

column6: invalid mode specification
column7: The mode parameter in an OCIU* call is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use only a valid mode parameter.

column6: error(s) in array DML
column7: One or more rows failed in the DML.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the error stack in the error handle.

column6: statement handled already executed or described
column7: The statement handle was executed or described successfully before.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform a OCIStmtPrepare again before OCI_PARSE_ONLY.

column6: Overflow segment of an IOT cannot be described
column7: The name specified in the OCIDescribeAny call referred to an IOT overflow segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use OCIDescribeAny to describe only documented objects.

column6: incorrect size of attribute
column7: Transaction ID attribute size is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the size parameter is correct.

column6: OCI_TRANS_NEW flag must be specified for local transactions
column7: Application attempted to start a local transaction without using OCI_TRANS_NEW.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use OCI_TRANS_NEW when starting local transactions.

column6: local transactions cannot be detached
column7: An attempt to detach a local transaction was made.
column8: From Oracle doc: Local transactions may only be committed or rolled back.

column6: cannot start new transaction with an active transaction
column7: An attempt to start a new transaction was made when there was an active transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Commit, rollback or detach the existing transaction before starting a new transaction.

column6: OCI_TRANS_NOMIGRATE, OCI_TRANS_JOIN options are not supported
column7: These flags are currently not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: transaction does not exist
column7: An invalid transaction identifier or context was used or the transaction has completed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply a valid identifier if the transaction has not completed and retry the call.

column6: duplicate transaction identifier
column7: An attempt was made to start a new transaction with an identifier already in use by an existing transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the identifier is not in use.

column6: not attached to the requested transaction
column7: An attempt was made to detach or complete a transaction that is not the current transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the transaction context refers to the current transaction.

column6: invalid transaction start flags
column7: An invalid transaction start flag was passed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that one of the values OCI_TRANS_NEW, OCI_TRANS_JOIN, or OCI_TRANS_RESUME was specified.

column6: invalid isolation level flags
column7: An invalid isolation level flag was passed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that only one of following values - OCI_TRANS_READONLY, OCI_TRANS_READWRITE, OCI_TRANS_SERIALIZABLE is used.

column6: transaction rolled back
column7: The application tried to commit a transaction and the server rolled it back.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: server failed due to unspecified error
column7: An internal error has occurred in the server commit protocol.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: transaction operation cannot be completed now
column7: The commit or rollback cannot be performed now because the session cannot switch to the specified transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation later.

column6: transaction branch has been heuristically committed
column7: This is an informational message.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: transaction branch has been heuristically rolled back
column7: This is an informational message.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: transaction branch has been partly committed and aborted
column7: This is an informational message.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: transaction was read-only and has been committed
column7: This is an informational message.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: commit protocol error occured in the server
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot forget an active transaction
column7: Transaction identifier refers to an active transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the identifier of an active transaction was not passed as an argument.

column6: cannot forget a prepared transaction
column7: Transaction identifier refers to a prepared transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the identifier of a prepared transaction was not passed as an argument.

column6: cannot detach, prepare or forget a local transaction
column7: Service handle contains a local transaction context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the transaction context does not refer to a local transaction.

column6: Cannot mix tightly-coupled and loosely-coupled branches
column7: Application attempted to start a transaction with a global transaction identifier and a wrong option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that all branches of a global transaction are started with either OCI_TRANS_TIGHT or OCI_TRANS_LOOSE option. If the application is correct and uses distributed updates, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid transaction type flags
column7: OCI_TRANS_TIGHT or OCI_TRANS_LOOSE mode was not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the right parameters are being used.

column6: cannot switch to specified transaction
column7: The transaction specified in the call refers to a transaction created by a different user.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create transactions with the same authentication so that they can be switched.

column6: cannot prepare or commit transaction with non-zero lock value
column7: An attempt was made to detach the transaction with a non-zero lock value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Detach the transaction with lock value set to zero and then try to prepare or commit the transaction.

column6: cannot start a new transaction
column7: An attempt was made to start a new transaction when session was already attached to an existing transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: End the current transaction before creating a new transaction.

column6: use of non-migratable database link not allowed
column7: The transaction, which needs to be migratable between sessions, tried to access a remote database from a non-multithreaded server process.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform the work in the local database or open a connection to the remote database from the client. If the multithreaded server option is installed, connect to the Oracle instance through the dispatcher.

column6: cannot open connections
column7: The migratable transaction tried to access a remote database when the session itself had opened connections to remote database(s).
column8: From Oracle doc: Close the connection(s) in the session and then try to access the remote database from the migratable transaction. If the error still occurs, contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: detach not allowed with open remote cursor
column7: The migratable transaction tried to detach from the current session while an open remote cursor exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close any open remote cursor prior to detach.

column6: cannot recover a transaction while in an existing transaction
column7: An attempt was made to commit or roll back a transaction while in a different transaction, and the transaction for which the action is requested is in a recovery state (this happens if it is idle too long).
column8: From Oracle doc: Detach from the current transaction and retry the operation.

column6: branches don't belong to the same global transaction
column7: The list of xids passed into kpotxmp() do not have the same gtrid
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: illegal parameter value in OCI lob function
column7: One of the parameter values in the OCI LOB function is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check every parameter in the OCI Lob function call to make sure they are correct. Offsets should be greater than or equal to one.

column6: user defined lob read callback error
column7: The only valid return value for a user defined LOB read callback function is OCI_CONTINUE. Any other value will cause this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that OCI_CONTINUE is returned from the user defined LOB read callback function.

column6: illegal parameter value in lob read function
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error should not normally occur. If it persists, contact your Oracle Customer Support.

column6: illegal parameter value in lob write function
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error should not normally occur. If it persists, contact your Oracle Customer Support.

column6: LOB type mismatch
column7: When copying or appending LOB locators, both source and destination LOB locators should be of the same type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass the same type of LOB locators for copying or appending.

column6: LOB form mismatch
column7: When reading from or writing into LOBs, the character set form of the user buffer should be same as that of the LOB.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the buffer you are using to read or write has the same form as that of the LOB.

column6: LOB form mismatch
column7: When copying or appending LOBs, both source and destination LOB locators should have the same character set form.
column8: From Oracle doc: Pass locators of the same character set form for copying or appending LOBs.

column6: streaming of lob data is not allowed when using lob buffering
column7: An attempt was made to stream LOB data via the polling mode or a callback when LOB buffering was enabled for the input LOB locator.
column8: From Oracle doc: Lob buffering is useful when reading/writing small amounts of LOB data so streaming should not be necessary. Rewrite the OCILobRead/OCILobWrite call so that it does not use streaming. If streaming of data is required, LOB buffering should not be used. In this case, flush buffers associated with the input LOB locator as necessary, disable buffering on the input LOB locator and reissue the OCILobRead/OCILobWrite call.

column6: amount specified will not fit in the lob buffers
column7: LOB buffering is enabled for the input LOB locator so buffering will be used. However, the amount of LOB data to read or write is larger than what the LOB buffers can hold.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either disable buffering on the input LOB locator and reissue the command or pass a smaller amount.

column6: attempting to write more data than indicated
column7: While writing into a LOB, more data was supplied than indicated.
column8: From Oracle doc: If data is written in pieces, then make sure that you do not provide more data in the pieces (cumulatively), than you indicated.

column6: less data provided for writing than indicated
column7: While writing into a LOB, less data was provided than indicated.
column8: From Oracle doc: If writing data in single pieces, then make sure that the buffer length specified is big enough to accommodate the data being provided. If data is written in pieces, then make sure that all the data has been provided before specifying OCI_LAST_PIECE.

column6: character set conversion to or from UCS2 failed
column7: If the database character set is varying-width, the CLOB/NCLOB value is implicitly converted to or from UCS2. This implicit conversion failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot send or receive an unsupported LOB
column7: An attempt was made to send a LOB across the network, but either the server does not support the LOB sent by the client, or the client does not support the LOB sent by the server. This error usually occurs when the client and server are running different versions of Oracle.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a version of the Oracle that supports the LOB on both the client and the server.

column6: failed to startup shared subsystem
column7: While attempting to initialize OCI in shared mode, a problem was encountered in starting the shared subsystem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: failed to connect to shared subsystem
column7: While attempting to initialize OCI in shared mode, a problem was encountered in connecting the process to the shared subsystem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: protocol error during statement execution
column7: An internal protocol error occurred while receiving describe data from the server during execution of a statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: failed to connect thread to shared subsystem
column7: While attempting to initialize OCI in shared mode, a problem was encountered in connecting the thread to the shared subsystem.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid or unsupported mode paramater passed in call
column7: The mode parameter passed into the OCI Client Notification call is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the mode parameter passed into OCI.

column6: handles belonging to different environments passed into an OCI call
column7: All handles passed into an OCI call should belong to the same environment. In the call that returned this error, handles belonging to different environments were passed in.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the handle parameters in the call to come from the same OCI Environment.

column6: invalid subscription name or name-length in subscription handle
column7: The subscription handle passed into the OCI call does not have a proper name or name-length attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the name and name-length attributes using the OCIAttrSet() call.

column6: invalid namespace attribute passed into OCI call
column7: The subscription handle passed into the OCI call does not have a proper NAMESPACE attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the NAMESPACE attribute using the OCIAttrSet() call.

column6: invalid callback attribute passed into OCI call
column7: The subscription handle passed into the OCI call does not have a proper callback attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the callback attribute using the OCIAttrSet() call.

column6: invalid use of bind variable in trigger WHEN clause
column7: A bind variable was used in the when clause of a trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the bind variable. To access the table columns use (new/old).column_name.

column6: cannot create this trigger type on views
column7: Only INSTEAD OF triggers can be created on a view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the trigger type to INSTEAD OF.

column6: cannot create INSTEAD OF triggers on tables
column7: Only BEFORE or AFTER triggers can be created on a table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the trigger type to BEFORE or AFTER.

column6: cannot change NEW values for this column type in trigger
column7: Attempt to change NEW trigger variables of datatype object, REF, nested table, VARRAY or LOB datatype which is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not change the NEW trigger variables in the trigger body.

column6: WHEN clause is not allowed in INSTEAD OF triggers
column7: WHEN clause is specified in an INSTEAD OF trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the WHEN clause when creating an INSTEAD OF trigger.

column6: cannot CREATE INSTEAD OF trigger on a read-only view
column7: Attempt to create an INSTEAD OF trigger on a view created with read-only option. The view cannot be updated using INSTEAD OF triggers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not create the trigger.

column6: cannot specify this column in UPDATE OF clause
column7: Attempt to create a trigger on update of a column whose datatype is disallowed in the clause, such as LOB and nested table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the UPDATE OF clause.

column6: functions or methods not allowed in WHEN clause
column7: PL/SQL function call or method invocation is not allowed in the WHEN clause when creating a trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the function call or method invocation from the WHEN clause.

column6: no implicit conversion to LOB datatype in instead-of trigger
column7: When inserting or updating a view using instead-of trigger, the new value for a LOB view column is of a different datatype.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specified a LOB value as the new value for the LOB view column.

column6: Nested table clause allowed only for INSTEAD OF triggers
column7: Triggers on nested tables can only be created on view columns using INSTEAD OF triggers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use view nested table columns for defining nested table triggers.

column6: Invalid nested table column name in nested table clause
column7: The column name specified in the nested table clause of an INSTEAD OF trigger does not correspond to a nested table column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a nested table column on which the trigger is to be defined.

column6: PARENT and NEW values cannot be identical
column7: The referencing clause specifies identical values for PARENT and OLD.
column8: From Oracle doc: Respecify either the PARENT or NEW referencing value.

column6: OLD and PARENT values cannot be identical
column7: The referencing clause specifies identical values for OLD and PARENT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Respecify either the OLD or PARENT referencing value.

column6: cannot change the value of a PARENT reference variable
column7: Parent values can only be read and not changed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to change a Parent variable.

column6: cannot perform DML on this nested table view column
column7: DML cannot be performed on a nested table view column except through an INSTEAD OF trigger.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create an INSTEAD OF trigger over the nested table view column and then perform the DML.

column6: cannot specify column list for insert into nested table view column
column7: A column list cannot be specified for inserts into the nested table view column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify all the columns for insert into the nested table.

column6: cannot reference NEW ROWID for movable rows in before triggers
column7: NEW ROWID was referenced in a before row trigger which is defined on an index-organized table, or a partitioned table with enabled movement of rows. The ROWID cannot be computed in a before row update trigger because it depends on the actual values of the row.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove references to NEW ROWID from the trigger definition.

column6: TABLESPACE option can only be used with ALTER INDEX REBUILD
column7: The TABLESPACE option to ALTER INDEX was used without the REBUILD option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER INDEX REBUILD TABLESPACE tablespace name.

column6: duplicate REBUILD option specification
column7: The REBUILD option to ALTER INDEX is specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the option at most once.

column6: PARALLEL option can only be used with ALTER INDEX REBUILD
column7: The PARALLEL option to ALTER INDEX was used without the REBUILD option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER INDEX REBUILD.

column6: NOPARALLEL option can only be used with ALTER INDEX REBUILD
column7: The NOPARALLEL option to ALTER INDEX was used without the REBUILD option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER INDEX REBUILD.

column6: UNRECOVERABLE option can only be used with ALTER INDEX REBUILD
column7: The UNRECOVERABLE option to ALTER INDEX was used without the REBUILD option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER INDEX REBUILD.

column6: RECOVERABLE option can only be used with ALTER INDEX REBUILD
column7: The RECOVERABLE option to ALTER INDEX was used without the REBUILD option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER INDEX REBUILD.

column6: only one of PARALLEL or NOPARALLEL clause may be specified
column7: PARALLEL was specified more than once, NOPARALLEL was specified more than once, or both PARALLEL and NOPARALLEL were specified in an ALTER INDEX REBUILD statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the PARALLEL or NOPARALLEL clauses.

column6: duplicate TABLESPACE option specification
column7: the TABLESPACE was specified more than once in an ALTER INDEX REBUILD statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the TABLESPACE clauses.

column6: standby lock name space exceeds size limit of %s characters
column7: The lock name space for the standby database exceeded the maximum string length.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change initialization parameter _STANDBY_LOCK_NAME_SPACE to a character string of less than the specified characters.

column6: standby lock name space has illegal character '%s'
column7: An invalid lock name space was specified for the standby database. The lock name space for the standby database can only contain A-Z, 0-9, '_', '#', '$', '.' and '@' characters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change initialization parameter _STANDBY_LOCK_NAME_SPACE to a valid character string.

column6: NOSORT may not be used with a bitmap index
column7: An attempt was made to create a bitmap index using the NOSORT option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove NOSORT from the CREATE BITMAP INDEX statement.

column6: creation of BITMAP cluster indices is not supported
column7: An attempt was made to create a cluster index with the BITMAP attribute.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove BITMAP from the CREATE INDEX statement.

column6: maximum number of BITMAP index columns is 30
column7: Too many columns were specified for the index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create an index on fewer columns.

column6: GLOBAL may not be used with a bitmap index
column7: An attempt was made to create a bitmap index using the GLOBAL option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove GLOBAL from the CREATE BITMAP INDEX statement, and/or add a LOCAL partition descriptor if the table is partitioned.

column6: invalid file number specified in the DUMP DATAFILE/TEMPFILE command
column7: An invalid file number was used in dumping a datafile or temporary file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid file number.

column6: duplicate BLOCK option specification
column7: BLOCK (MIN/MAX) was specified more than once in the DUMP DATAFILE/TEMPFILE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only one BLOCK option.

column6: invalid block number specified in the DUMP DATAFILE/TEMPFILE command
column7: An invalid block number was used in dumping a datafile or temporary file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid block number.

column6: MIN/MAX/Block Number expected
column7: A value other than MIN/MAX, or a block number was entered in the DUMP DATAFILE/TEMPFILE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: invalid DUMP DATAFILE/TEMPFILE option
column7: An invalid option was specified for the DUMP DATAFILE/TEMPFILE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the syntax.

column6: LOGGING/NOLOGGING option already specified
column7: In CREATE TABLESPACE, the LOGGING and/or NOLOGGING options were specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the logging specifications.

column6: MINIMUM EXTENT option already specified
column7: In CREATE TABLESPACE, the MINIMUM EXTENT option was specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the MINIMUM EXTENT specifications.

column6: MINIMUM EXTENT value greater than maximum extent size
column7: In CREATE/ALTER TABLESPACE, the value specified for the MINIMUM EXTENT option was greater than the maximum extent size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a lower value for the MINIMUM EXTENT option.

column6: Only LOCAL bitmap indexes are permitted on partitioned tables
column7: An attempt was made to create a global bitmap index on a partitioned table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a local bitmap index instead.

column6: Too many components specified in the name.
column7: More components per name than is allowed were specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the name specified for the operation.

column6: Database link name not allowed.
column7: A database link name was specified when it is not permitted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the name specified for the operation.

column6: BUFFER_POOL storage option not allowed
column7: An attempt was made to specify the BUFFER_POOL storage option. This option may only be specified during CREATE/ALTER TABLE/CLUSTER/INDEX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove this option and retry the statement.

column6: Invalid name specified for BUFFER_POOL
column7: The name of the buffer pool specified by the user is invalid. The only valid names are KEEP, RECYCLE and DEFAULT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a valid name or remove the BUFFER_POOL clause.

column6: RELY not allowed in NOT NULL constraint
column7: An attempt was made to set RELY on for NOT NULL constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Only NORELY may be specified for a NOT NULL constraint.

column6: No insert/update/delete on table with constraint (%s.%s) disabled and validated
column7: An attempt was made to insert/update/delete on table with DISABLE VALIDATE constraint.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the constraint's states.

column6: cannot modify constraint (%s) - no such constraint
column7: The named constraint does not exist for this table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again with a constraint that does exist for this table.

column6: cannot modify primary key - primary key not defined for table
column7: An attempt was made to modify a primary key that is not defined for the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: cannot modify unique(%s) - unique key not defined for table
column7: An attempt was made to modify a unique key that is not defined for the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: UNIQUE constraint (%s.%s) disabled and validated in ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION
column7: Cannot ALTER TABLE EXCHANGE PARTITION when the partition and the table have a disabled and validated unique constraints AND the unique keys in the partition is not mutually exclusive from the rest of the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the constraint's status.

column6: duplicate SINGLE TABLE option specified
column7: The SINGLE TABLE option was specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the SINGLE TABLE option only once.

column6: keyword TABLE expected
column7: The keyword TABLE is missing from the SINGLE TABLE option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Place the keyword TABLE after the keyword SINGLE in the command.

column6: cannot use the SINGLE TABLE option
column7: The SINGLE TABLE option is only valid for hash clusters.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify the SINGLE TABLE option.

column6: this cluster can contain only one table
column7: An attempt was made to store more than one table in a cluster that was created with the SINGLE TABLE option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to store more than one table in the cluster.

column6: Data value out of range
column7: Value from cast operand is larger than cast target size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase size of cast target.

column6: %s initialization parameter has been made obsolete
column7: An obsolete initialization parameter has been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: The system will come up, but parameters must be examined.

column6: invalid option for CREATE TEMPORARY TABLESPACE
column7: An invalid option appears.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of the valid options: TEMPFILE, EXTENT MANAGEMENT LOCAL, UNIFORM.

column6: %s space policy cannot be specified for the %s extent management
column7: An invalid option appears.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that for LOCAL extent management UNIFORM or AUTOALLOCATE is specified, and for DICTIONARY extent management UNIFORM or AUTOALLOCATE are not specified

column6: invalid EXTENT MANAGEMENT clause
column7: An invalid option appears for EXTENT MANAGEMENT clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of the valid options: UNIFORM SIZE, AUTOALLOCATE.

column6: default storage clause specified twice
column7: Default storage clause was specified twice for create tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify it once.

column6: default storage clause is not compatible with allocation policy
column7: Default storage clause was specified for a tablespace with AUTOALLOCATE or UNIFORM policy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Omit the storage clause.

column6: invalid option for CREATE TABLESPACE with TEMPORARY contents
column7: An invalid option appears.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify one of the valid options: EXTENT MANAGEMENT DICTIONARY, USER.

column6: allocation policy already specified
column7: In CREATE TABLESPACE, the allocation policy was specified more than once, for example, AUTOALLOCATE and UNIFORM.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the allocation policy specifications.

column6: EXTENT MANAGEMENT option already specified
column7: In CREATE TABLESPACE, the EXTENT MANAGEMENT option was specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all but one of the EXTENT MANAGEMENT specifications.

column6: UNIFORM SIZE value greater than maximum extent size
column7: In CREATE/ALTER TABLESPACE, the value specified for the UNIFORM SIZE option was greater than the maximum extent size.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a lower value for the UNIFORM SIZE option.

column6: ONLINE option not permitted
column7: An attempt was made to specify ONLINE for ALTER TABLE MOVE on a table that is not index-organized. The ONLINE option is currently supported only for index-organized tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the ONLINE option from the command.

column6: Columns of UROWID type may not be indexed
column7: An attempt was made to create an index on a column of UROWID type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the column from the list of indexed columns.

column6: ALTERING of extent parameters not permitted
column7: An attempt was made to alter the extent parameters for a segment in a tablespace with autoallocate or uniform extent allocation policy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the appropriate extent parameters from the command.

column6: Rollback Segment cannot be created in this tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to create a rollback segment in a tablespace with autoallocate extent allocation policy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different tablespace for the rollback segment.

column6: TEMPFILE cannot be dropped at this time
column7: An attempt was made to drop a TEMPFILE being used by online users.
column8: From Oracle doc: The TEMPFILE has been taken offline. Try again later.

column6: Temporary Tablespace is Empty
column7: An attempt was made to use space in a temporary tablespace with no files.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add files to the tablespace using ADD TEMPFILE command.

column6: no PRIMARY KEY constraint found
column7: A PRIMARY KEY constraint must be defined for a table with this organization.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define a PRIMARY KEY.

column6: storage specification not permitted for primary key
column7: Storage parameters cannot be defined for a PRIMARY KEY constraint for a table with this organization.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove storage specification for primary key.

column6: UNRECOVERABLE option not permitted
column7: The UNRECOVERABLE option may not be specified for a primary key for a table with this organization.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove UNRECOVERABLE option for primary key.

column6: duplicate PCTTHRESHOLD storage option specification
column7: The storage option PCTTHRESHOLD is specified more than once.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify storage options at most once.

column6: invalid PCTTHRESHOLD storage option value
column7: The specified value must be a positive integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an appropriate value.

column6: PCTTHRESHOLD only valid for certain table organizations
column7: PCTTHRESHOLD can only be specified for tables with certain organizations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the PCTTHRESHOLD option.

column6: missing ON keyword for NESTED INDEX
column7: The ON keyword is required to specify nested index column nest.
column8: From Oracle doc: Add ON keyword.

column6: feature not currently available for index-organized tables
column7:
An attempt was made to use one or more of the following feature(s) not currently supported for index-organized tables: 

CREATE TABLE with LOB/BFILE/VARRAY columns 

partitioning/PARALLEL/CREATE TABLE AS SELECT options 

ALTER TABLE with ADD/MODIFY column options 

CREATE INDEX
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the disallowed feature(s) in this release.

column6: index-organized table top index segment is in a different tablespace
column7: An attempt was made to drop a tablespace which contains an index only table's overflow segment but not the top index segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Find index-organized tables which span the tablespace being dropped and some other tablespace(s). Drop these tables.

column6: column name expected
column7: A column name is not present where required by the CREATE TABLE for specifying last column to be included in the index segment of the index-organized table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a column name where required by the syntax.

column6: index column other than last can not be specified for INCLUDE clause
column7: An index column name other than the last was specified as including column.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either a column name which is not part of index-organized table primary key index, or the last key column of the primary key for the INCLUDING clause.

column6: INCLUDING clause specified for index-organized table without OVERFLOW
column7: INCLUDING clause of a CREATE TABLE is an valid option only for index-organized tables with OVERFLOW clause (at creation time) or if an OVERFLOW segment already exists (at ALTER time).
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify OVERFLOW clause for the index-organized table: For ALTER, perform ADD OVERFLOW first.

column6: specified exceptions table form incorrect
column7: The specified table does not have the proper field definitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct table to use.

column6: cannot drop/disable/defer the primary key constraint for index-organized tables
column7: An attempt was made to DROP, DISABLE, or DEFER the primary key constraint for an index-only table. This is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not DROP, DISABLE, or DEFER the primary key constraint for an index-only table.

column6: illegal ALTER TABLE option for an index-organized table
column7: During ALTER of a index-organized table, the user attempted to enter one or more of the following options: TABLESPACE, ALLOCATE/DEALLOCATE EXTENT, PCTFREE/PCTUSED for IOT top index segment
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option(s).

column6: an index-organized table maintenance operation may not be combined with other operations
column7: ALTER TABLE statement attempted to combine an index-organized table maintenance operation (for example, changing physical attributes) with some other operation (for example, ADD constraint) which is illegal
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that a index-organized table maintenance operation is the sole operation specified in ALTER TABLE statement.

column6: cannot reference overflow table of an index-organized table
column7: An attempt was made to directly access the overflow table of an index-organized table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue the statement against the parent index-organized table containing the specified overflow table.

column6: invalid option for an index-organized table
column7: An attempt was made to specify one or more of the following options for an index-organized table: [NO]CACHE, NO LOGGING, CLUSTER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option(s).

column6: cannot use COMPRESS option for a single column key
column7: An attempt was made to use COMPRESS option on single column key.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the COMPRESS option.

column6: invalid COMPRESS prefix length value
column7: The specified value must be a positive integer less than the number of key columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an appropriate value.

column6: invalid option for index on an index-organized table
column7: An attempt was made to specify one or more of the following options for index on an IOT: BITMAP, REVERSE, PCTUSED.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an appropriate option.

column6: keyword MOVE in ALTER TABLE MOVE must immediately follow table_name
column7: MOVE specified after one/more other ALTER options.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change order of options, MOVE should be first or remove the illegal option(s).

column6: an overflow segment already exists for the indexed-organized table
column7: An attempt was made to ADD OVERFLOW segment on an index-organized table that already has an overflow segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: only range partitioning is supported for index-organized table
column7: Hash, system, or composite partitioning schemes are not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Select a different partitioning scheme.

column6: partitioning key of a index-organized table must be a subset of the primary key
column7: An attempt was made to specify a partitioning key which is not a prefix of the primary key of the index-organized table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Select a different partitioning key.

column6: invalid value %s, QUEUE_NAME should be [SCHEMA.]NAME
column7: A NULL parameter was specified for QUEUE_NAME.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-NULL queue name.

column6: invalid value, VISIBILITY should be ON_COMMIT or IMMEDIATE
column7: An invalid value specified for parameter VISIBILITY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either ON_COMMIT or IMMEDIATE.

column6: invalid value NULL, %s should be non-NULL
column7: A NULL value was specified for the parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-NULL value.

column6: invalid value %s, DELAY should be non-negative
column7: A negative value or NULL was specified for DELAY.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-negative integer for DELAY.

column6: invalid value, SEQUENCE_DEVIATION should be BEFORE or TOP
column7: An invalid SEQUENCE_DEVIATION was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either the option 'BEFORE' or 'TOP'.

column6: the QUEUE %s.%s does not exist
column7: The specified queue does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the queue first before specifying it for enqueue or dequeue.

column6: enqueue failed, enqueue to exception queue %s.%s not permitted
column7: An attempt was made to enqueue to an exception queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try enqueueing to another queue.

column6: enqueue failed, queue %s.%s is disabled from enqueueing
column7: The queue has been stopped to prevent any further enqueueing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable the queue first by using an administrative operation.

column6: RELATIVE_MSGID must be specified if SEQUENCE_DEVIATION is BEFORE
column7: A relative message identifier should be specified if sequence deviation is specified as BEFORE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify an existing relative message identifier or do not specify sequence deviation as BEFORE.

column6: invalid value %s, EXPIRATION should be non-negative or NEVER
column7: The expiration is less than zero or NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid value for EXPIRE_AFTER which should be greater than or equal to zero or NEVER.

column6: invalid value for RELATIVE_MSGID, no message in queue with that msgid
column7: No message in the queue with the MSGID equal to the specified RELATIVE_MSGID.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try again with a valid RELATIVE_MSGID.

column6: invalid DELAY specified when using sequence deviation
column7: The DELAY specified in the enqueue is greater than the delay of the message with the given relative message ID.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the DELAY to be less than or equal to the delay of the message with the given relative message ID. If the TOP option is used the delay must be less than or equal to the delay of all the messages in the queue.

column6: invalid PRIORITY specified when using sequence deviation
column7: The PRIORITY specified in the enqueue is less than the priority of the message with the given relative message ID.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the PRIORITY to be less than the delay of the message with the given relative message ID. If the TOP option is used the priority must be greater than or equal to the priority of all the messages in the queue.

column6: message with specified RELATIVE_MSGID has been dequeued
column7: The message specified by the RELATIVE_MSGID field in the sequence deviation BEFORE option has been dequeued.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. This is an informational message only.

column6: user_data type and queue type do not match
column7: A user tries to enqueue an object to a queue that was created for objects of different type.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try enqueue again with an object of the right type.

column6: invalid recipient, either NAME or ADDRESS must be specified
column7: Both attributes, NAME and ADDRESS, were specified null for one of the recipients in the recipient list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-null NAME or ADDRESS for the recipient.

column6: enqueue failed, visibility must be IMMEDIATE for queue %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to enqueue to a non-persistent queue without setting visibility to IMMEDIATE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set visibility to IMMEDIATE.

column6: enqueue failed, delay must be zero for queue %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to enqueue to a non-persistent queue with delay greater than zero seconds.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set delay to zero.

column6: enqueue failed, sequence deviation not allowed for queue %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to enqueue to a non-persistent queue with sequence deviation specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify sequence deviation.

column6: invalid value %s, DEQUEUE_MODE should be REMOVE or BROWSE or LOCKED
column7: An invalid parameter has been specified for DEQUEUE_MODE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either REMOVE, BROWSE or LOCKED.

column6: dequeue failed, queue %s.%s is not enabled for dequeue
column7: The queue has not been enabled for dequeue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable the queue using START_QUEUE.

column6: timeout or end-of-fetch during message dequeue from %s.%s
column7: User-specified dequeue wait time has passed or the end of the queue has been reached but no message has been retrieved.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try dequeue again with the appropriate WAIT_TIME or the FIRST_MESSAGE option.

column6: invalid value %s, WAIT should be non-negative
column7: A negative value has been specified for WAIT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-negative value or FOREVER.

column6: cannot dequeue because CONSUMER_NAME not specified
column7: A user tried to dequeue from a queue that has been created for multiple consumers but a CONSUMER_NAME was not been specified in the dequeue options.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the CONSUMER_NAME in the dequeue options.

column6: duplicate recipients specified for message
column7: An enqueue was performed with duplicate queue agents in the recipients parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate queue agent and retry the call.

column6: invalid parameter specified for NAVIGATION
column7: An invalid parameter has been specified for NAVIGATION.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose one of FIRST_MESSAGE, NEXT_MESSAGE or NEXT_TRANSACTION. Use FIRST_MESSAGE for dequeuing the first message that satisfies the criterion, NEXT_MESSAGE for dequeuing the next message that satisfies the criterion and NEXT_TRANSACTION for moving to a set of messages enqueued by another transaction.

column6: NEXT_TRANSACTION navigation option invalid for queue table %s.%s
column7: The NEXT_TRANSACTION navigation option was used in a dequeue from a queue in a queue table that was not created for transactional grouping.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify either FIRST_MESSAGE or NEXT_MESSAGE as the navigation option. If you want to dequeue messages using transactional grouping create the queue in a queue table that has transactional grouping enabled.

column6: fetched all messages in current transaction
column7: The NEXT_TRANSACTION navigation option was used in a dequeue when there were no more messages that belong to the same transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the NEXT_TRANSACTION navigation option to move to the next also use the FIRST_MESSAGE option to start from the head of the queue again.

column6: buffer too small for user data
column7: The variable or buffer used for the out parameter payload is too small for the user data dequeued.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the size of the buffer or the size of the variable. Maximum size allowed is 32K.

column6: navigation option used out of sequence
column7: The NEXT_MESSAGE or NEXT_TRANSACTION option was specified after dequeuing all the messages.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reset the dequeuing position using the FIRST_MESSAGE navigation option and then specify the NEXT_MESSAGE or NEXT_TRANSACTION option.

column6: too many recipients specified for message destination %s
column7: An ENQUEUE was performed with more than 32 recipients for the given destination (address).
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of recipients to 32 or less, and retry the call.

column6: message ID not supplied when dequeuing from exception queue %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to dequeue from a release 8.0-compatible exception queue without including a message ID in the dequeue options.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the application to ensure that the queue name has been specified correctly. If the queue name is correct supply a message ID when dequeuing from a release 8.0-compatible exception queue. Otherwise, upgrade the QUEUE_TABLE containing the queue to release 8.1-compatible using the DBMS_AQADM.MIGRATE_QUEUE_TABLE procedure.

column6: message ID and correlation ID specified in dequeue options
column7: An attempt was made to dequeue by including both a message ID and a correlation ID in the dequeue options. In the dequeue options, you are permitted to specify either one of message ID or correlation ID, or neither ID.
column8: From Oracle doc: To dequeue a message, specify a message ID or a correlation ID in the dequeue options, but do not specify both. If you want to dequeue in the queue's sort order, then do not specify either the message ID or correlation ID in the dequeue options.

column6: cannot change correlation ID from %s to %s without FIRST_MESSAGE option
column7: An attempt was made to change the correlation ID while using the NEXT_MESSAGE or NEXT_TRANSACTION option for dequeuing.
column8: From Oracle doc: To use a correlation ID that is different from the previous dequeue call, reset the dequeuing position by using the FIRST_MESSAGE navigation option.

column6: cannot change subscriber name from %s to %s without FIRST_MESSAGE option
column7: An attempt was made to change the subscriber name while using the NEXT_MESSAGE or NEXT_TRANSACTION option for dequeuing.
column8: From Oracle doc: To use a subscriber name that is different from the previous dequeue call, reset the dequeuing position by using the FIRST_MESSAGE navigation option.

column6: CONSUMER_NAME cannot be specified when dequeuing from exception queue %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to dequeue from an exception queue by specifying the CONSUMER_NAME in the dequeue options. CONSUMER_NAME can only be specified when dequeuing from a normal queue created for multiple consumers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify only the message ID in the dequeue options to dequeue a message from an exception queue.

column6: dequeue index key not found, QUEUE %s, rowid %s
column7: An internal error was encountered. There may be an inconsistency in the queue table index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support. You may need to provide the trace file and information about reproducing the error.

column6: agent name cannot be specified if address is a single-consumer queue or an exception queue
column7: The agent name for the agent in the LISTEN call was specified when the agent address was a single-consumer queue or an exception queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify the agent name.

column6: listen failed, the address %s is an 8.0 style exception queue
column7: An 8.0 style exception queue was specified in the agent-list for the LISTEN call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a normal 8.0 style queue or an 8.1 style queue in the agent-list.

column6: %s is not a recipient of specified message
column7: The consumer name specified in the dequeue options is not a recipient of the message specified by the message ID.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the agent specified by the consumer name is a recipient of the message specified by the message ID.

column6: duplicate agent specified in the agent list
column7: An agent was specified more than once in the agent list of the LISTEN call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate agent specification(s), and retry the call.

column6: dequeue failed, dequeue not allowed for queue %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to dequeue from a non-persistent queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Dequeue from a different queue.

column6: Cannot specify a remote recipient for the message
column7: A recipient for the message enqueued to a non-persistent queue had a non-local address.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify the address field or specify the queue which is the target of the enqueue

column6: exceeded maximum number of recipients for message
column7: An attempt was made to issue an ENQUEUE call that exceeded the maximum number (1024) of recipients per message.
