column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the number of recipients to 1024 or less, and retry the call.

column6: listen failed, the address %s is a non-persistent queue
column7: A non-persistent queue was specified as an address for an agent in the LISTEN call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a normal queue as address for the agent, and retry the LISTEN call.

column6: listen failed, queue %s.%s is not enabled for dequeue
column7: An attempt was made to specify a queue that is not enabled for dequeue in a LISTEN call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enable the queue for dequeue using START_QUEUE, and retry the LISTEN call.

column6: time-out in LISTEN while waiting for a message
column7: The specified wait time has elapsed and there were no messages for any of the agents in the agent-list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try the LISTEN call with an appropriate time-out.

column6: incorrect subscription %s %s
column7: An incorrect subscription string was specified with OCIRegister.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a subscription string using the [CONSUMER:]SCHEMA.QUEUE form.

column6: consumer cannot be specified with a single-consumer queue or an exception queue
column7: An attempt was made to specify a consumer in the subscription string when registering for notification on a single-consumer queue or an exception queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify the consumer in the subscription string.

column6: consumer must be specified with a multi-consumer queue
column7: An attempt was made to register on a multi-consumer queue without specifying a consumer in the subscription string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a consumer in the subscription string.

column6: cannot register for notifications on an 8.0 style exception queue
column7: An attempt was made to specify an 8.0 style exception queue in the subscription string of OCIRegister.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a normal queue or a non-persistent queue.

column6: cannot specify protocol for agent
column7: The user specified the protocol attribute for an agent in the agent list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify the protocol attribute of the agent object type.

column6: JOB_QUEUE_PROCESSES must be at least 2 for AQ propagation
column7: AQ Propagator encountered a setting for JOB_QUEUE_PROCESSES that is insufficient for AQ propagation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the number of JOB_QUEUE_PROCESSES to at least 2 for AQ propagation.

column6: agent name cannot be NULL if address is a multi-consumer queue
column7: The name for the agent in the LISTEN call was not specified when the agent address was a multi-consumer queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-NULL name for the agent.

column6: no message in queue %s.%s with message ID %s
column7: An attempt was made to dequeue a message with a specific message ID, but no such message exists in the queue.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try dequeue again with a valid message ID.

column6: table specified is not a queue table
column7: An invalid queue table name is specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the dictionary views to see if the table is a queue table.

column6: cannot grant or revoke object privilege on release 8.0 compatible queues
column7: An attempt was made to grant or revoke object privilege on release 8.0 style queues.
column8: From Oracle doc: Convert the release 8.0 compatible queue table to release 8.1 compatible using DBMS_AQADM.MIGRATE_QUEUE_TABLE before granting or revoking object privilege.

column6: grantee name cannot be NULL
column7: An attempt was made to specify NULL for the grantee parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid grantee parameter.

column6: maximum number of concurrent transaction branches exceeded
column7: The limit on the number of concurrent transaction branches has been reached.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the initialization parameter TRANSACTIONS and restart the system.

column6: transaction is currently in use
column7: The transaction is currently used by a different session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not switch to a transaction attached to some other session.

column6: no current transaction
column7: The user session is not attached to any transaction.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to detach when there is no current transaction.

column6: branch marked for deletion
column7: The branch specified cannot be killed immediately because another session is using the branch, but it has been marked for kill. This means it will be deleted as soon as possible after the current uninterruptable operation is completed.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action is required for the branch to be deleted.

column6: must replay fetch
column7: A failure occurred since the last fetch on this statement. Failover was able to bring the statement to its original state to allow continued fetches.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is an internally used error message and should not be seen by the user.

column6: can not continue fetches
column7: A failure occurred since the last fetch on this statement. Failover was unable to bring the statement to its original state to allow continued fetches.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-execute the statement and start fetching from the beginning.

column6: transaction must roll back
column7: A failure occurred while a transaction was active on this connection.
column8: From Oracle doc: The client must roll back.

column6: could not reconnect
column7: The connection to the database has been lost, and attempts to reconnect have failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Manually reconnect.

column6: lost instance
column7: The primary instance has died.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is an internally used error message and should not be seen by the user.

column6: transaction status unknown
column7: A failure occurred while a transaction was attempting to commit. Failover could not automatically determine instance status.
column8: From Oracle doc: The user must determine the transaction's status manually.

column6: could not generate a connect address
column7: Failover was unable to generate an address for a backup instance.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: connection terminated
column7: The connection was lost while doing a fetch.
column8: From Oracle doc: This is an internally used error message and should not be seen by the user.

column6: can not safely replay call
column7: The connection was lost while doing this call. It may not be safe to replay it after failover.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to see if the results of the call have taken place, and then replay it if desired.

column6: connection lost during rollback
column7: The connection was lost while issuing a rollback.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the transaction is not externally coordinated, then Oracle implicitly rolled back, so no action is required. Otherwise examine PENDING_TRANS$ to determine if ROLLBACK FORCE is required.

column6: remote instance does not support shared dblinks
column7: A shared database link is being used to connect to a remote instance that does not support this feature because it is an older version.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a normal database link if you need to connect to this instance.

column6: ruleset specified does not exist
column7: An attempt to access a ruleset was made, but the ruleset referenced does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look up the correct name of the ruleset in USER_RULESETS.

column6: rule %s does not exist
column7: An attempt to access a rule was made, which failed because the rule does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Look up the rule in the rules storage table, which can be found from USER_RULESETS.

column6: table specified does not exist
column7: An attempt to define a ruleset on a table was made, which failed because the rule does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define rulesets only on existing tables.

column6: duplicate ruleset
column7: An attempt to define a ruleset was made, which failed because a ruleset with the same name exists in the same schema.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define a ruleset with a different name.

column6: duplicate rule %s
column7: An attempt to define a rule was made, which failed because a rule with the same name already exists in the same ruleset.
column8: From Oracle doc: Define a rule with a different name.

column6: partition load specified but table %s is not partitioned
column7: The Loader control file contains a PARTITION clause but the table being loaded is not partitioned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the partition specification from the SQL*Loader control file and retry the load.

column6: Index %s specified in SORTED INDEXES does not exist on table %s
column7: A non-existent index was specified in the SORTED INDEXES clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify as a SORTED INDEX.

column6: Table %s has index defined upon it.
column7: Parallel load was specified into a table which has index defined upon it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop index(es) defined upon table, or do not use parallel load, or use SKIP_INDEX_MAINTENANCE option.

column6: parallel load not supported for index-organized table %s
column7: Parallel load is not supported for index-organized tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Load the index-organized table without the PARALLEL option.

column6: Tables loaded through the direct path may not be clustered
column7: An attempt was made to load a clustered table via the direct path.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the conventional path.

column6: For INSERT option, table must be empty. Error on table %s
column7: The user tried to use the INSERT option on a non-empty table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Empty the table from SQL*Plus, or use the REPLACE option.

column6: NOT NULL column %s has a nullif clause
column7: A column which is NOT NULL in the database has a SQL*Loader NULLIF clause on it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the NULLIF clause in the SQL*Loader control file.

column6: NOT NULL column %s has a defaultif clause which may evaluate to null
column7: A column which is NOT NULL in the database has a SQL*Loader DEFAULTIF clause which may evaluate to null.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the DEFAULTIF clause in the SQL*Loader control file.

column6: Column %s in table %s is NOT NULL and is not being loaded
column7: A column which is NOT NULL in the database is not being loaded and will cause every row to be rejected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Load the column by specifying the NOT NULL column in the INTO TABLE clause in the SQL*Loader control file.

column6: Tables loaded through the direct path may not be object tables
column7: An attempt was made to load an object table via the direct path.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the conventional path.

column6: Tables loaded through the direct path may not have object columns
column7: An attempt was made to load a table with an object column via the direct path.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the conventional path.

column6: Tables loaded through the direct path may not be nested
column7: An attempt was made to load a nested table via the direct path.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the conventional path.

column6: Tables loaded through the direct path may not have REF columns
column7: An attempt was made to load a table with a REF column via the direct path.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the conventional path.

column6: Tables loaded through the direct path may not have array columns
column7: An attempt was made to load a table with an array column via the direct path.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the conventional path.

column6: Record %s: Rejected - Error on table %s, partition %s
column7: The record indicated caused an Oracle error on insert.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine the Oracle error and correct the record. The offending column(s) are not known.

column6: Global indexes not allowed on direct path partition load, table %s
column7: Global indexes are defined on a table when direct path loading a single partition of the table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the global index from the named table and retry the operation.

column6: Column %s in table %s does not exist
column7: Column specified in the loader control file does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the column exists and that you have privileges on it. Correct the loader control file if it is wrong.

column6: Column %s in table %s of type %s not supported by direct path
column7: The specified column of SQL column type string is not supported by the direct path loader.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the column is NULLable, remove it from the control file description. Then it will be loaded as a NULL.

column6: index %s.%s loaded successfully with %s keys
column7: Non-partitioned index information put to loader log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. This is an informational message.

column6: index %s.%s partition %s loaded successfully with %s keys
column7: Partitioned index information put to loader log file.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required. This is an informational message.

column6: index %s.%s was made unusable due to:
column7: A non-partitioned index was made index unusable due to the error displayed below this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Depending on the error, either rebuild the index, or drop and re-create it.

column6: index %s.%s partition %s was made unusable due to:
column7: A partition of a partitioned index was made index unusable due to error displayed below this error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Depending on the error, either rebuild the index partition, or drop and re-create the entire index.

column6: SKIP_UNUSABLE_INDEXES requested and index segment was initially unusable
column7: User requested SKIP_UNUSABLE_INDEXES option, and the index segment was in unusable state prior to the beginning of the load.
column8: From Oracle doc: Informational only. User will need to either rebuild the index or index partition, or re-create the index.

column6: SKIP_INDEX_MAINTENANCE option requested
column7: A request was made that index maintenance be skipped on a direct path load.
column8: From Oracle doc: The listed index was put into Index Unusable state due to the user requesting that index maintenance be skipped. Either rebuild the index or index partitions, or drop and re-create the index.

column6: unique index %s.%s initially in unusable state
column7: A unique index is in IU state (a unique index cannot have index maintenance skipped via SKIP_UNUSABLE_INDEXES).
column8: From Oracle doc: Either rebuild the index or index partition, or use SKIP_INDEX_MAINTENANCE if the client is SQL*Loader.

column6: unique index %s.%s partition %s initially in unusable state
column7: A partition of a unique index is in IU state (a unique index cannot have index maintenance skipped via SKIP_UNUSABLE_INDEXES).
column8: From Oracle doc: Either rebuild the index or index partition, or use SKIP_INDEX_MAINTENANCE if the client is SQL*Loader.

column6: index %s.%s initially in unusable state
column7: An index is in IU state prior to the beginning of a direct path load, it cannot be maintained by the loader.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either rebuild the index, re-create the index, or use either SKIP_UNUSABLE_INDEXES or SKIP_INDEX_MAINTENANCE (SQL*Loader only).

column6: index %s.%s partition %s initially in unusable state
column7: A partition of an index is in IU state prior to the beginning of a direct path load, it cannot be maintained by the loader.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either rebuild index partition, re-create the index, or use either SKIP_UNUSABLE_INDEXES or SKIP_INDEX_MAINTENANCE (SQL*Loader only).

column6: index %s.%s had %s partitions made unusable due to:
column7: A logical index error occurred on a partitioned index which affected one or more index partitions, which are listed below this message.
column8: From Oracle doc: The affected index partitions will have to be rebuilt, or, the entire index dropped and re-created.

column6: index maintenance error, the load cannot continue
column7: A index error occurred during the index maintenance phase of a direct path load. The load cannot continue. See error message below this message.
column8: From Oracle doc: See action for the error message which follows this one.

column6: index %s.%s loading aborted after %s keys
column7: An index error occurred during direct-load of an index-organized table. Loading had to be aborted. No rows were loaded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the key just following the number of keys mentioned above. This key caused the index problem mentioned in an earlier message.

column6: error while evaluating index %s.%s, row %s due to:
column7: An index error occurred while attempting to evaluate an expression on a functional index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the input data is valid for the functional index.

column6: end of logical record found when reading length of varying length field
column7: While attempting to read the length portion of a varying length field, then end of the logical record was reached.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the control file describes the data correctly and that the data in the datafile matches the description in the control file

column6: Record %s: Rejected - Error on table %s, subpartition %s
column7: The record indicated caused an Oracle error on insert.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine the Oracle error and correct the record. The offending column(s) are not known.

column6: subpartition load specified but table %s is not subpartitioned
column7: The Loader control file contains a PARTITION clause but the table being loaded is not subpartitioned.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the subpartition specification from the SQL*Loader control file and retry the load.

column6: Record %s: Rejected - Error on table %s, subpartition %s
column7: The record indicated caused an Oracle error on insert.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine the Oracle error and correct the record. The offending column(s) are not known.

column6: error converting character length field to a number
column7: An error occurred while attempting to convert the characters containing the count portion of a VARCHARC or VARRAWC field.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the count portion for the field has the correct value.

column6: Table %s has domain index defined upon it
column7: Direct path load was specified for a table which has a domain index defined upon it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop domain index(es) defined on the table or use the conventional path.

column6: Data block was loaded using the NOLOGGING option
column7: An attempt was made to access data in a block that was loaded without redo generation using the NOLOGGING/UNRECOVERABLE option.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the object containing the block.

column6: DATETIME/INTERVAL datatype conversion error
column7: The column could not be converted from DATETIME datatype to internal DATETIME/CHARACTER datatype.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: unable to convert format %s into internal form
column7: An attempt to convert a DATETIME format string into internal format in preparation for DATETIME datatype processing failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: unable to convert time zone for DATETIME/INTERVAL processing
column7: An attempt to convert the time zone specified by the ORA_STDZ environment variable to internal format failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the setting for ORA_STDZ is valid.

column6: unable to to get DATETIME/INTERVAL reference date
column7: An attempt to retrieve the system reference date for DATETIME/INTERVAL datatypes failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: file %s is not part of database being loaded
column7: A parallel load file was specified which is not part of the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check filename and pathname for correctness.

column6: file %s is not part of table %s.%s
column7: A parallel load file was specified which is not in the tablespace of the table being loaded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check to make sure that the specified parallel load file is in the tablespace of the table being loaded.

column6: file %s is not part of table %s.%s partition %s
column7: A parallel load file was specified which is not in the tablespace of the table (partition, subpartition) being loaded. When a partitioned table is being loaded, the file must be in the tablespace of every partition or subpartition (that is, each (sub)partition must be in the same tablespace).
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different parallel load file, or no file at all.

column6: load stream synchronization error
column7: The row header flag byte contains an unexpected value, this indicates that an error has occurred in either the generation of, or the pushing of the load stream from the client to the server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Usually due to an application programming error when dealing with error handling, or not resetting the stream state.

column6: load of overlapping segments on table %s.%s is not allowed
column7: Client application is attempting to do multiple direct path load operations on the same table, but the segments overlap.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the partition names (subname attribute of the direct path context) being loaded. Make sure you are not loading a table and a partition of the same table. Make sure you are not loading a partition, and a sub-partition within the same partition.

column6: direct path context already finished
column7: An OCIDirPathLoadStream operation was attempted after OCIDirPathFinish was called. Once a direct path operation has been finished, no more data can be loaded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check program logic to make sure OCIDirPathLoadStream is not called after OCIDirPathFinish.

column6: direct path operation must start its own transaction
column7: A direct path operation is being attempted within a transaction that has already been started.
column8: From Oracle doc: Commit the transaction and Prepare the direct path operation again.

column6: direct path does not support triggers
column7: A direct path operation is being attempted on a table which has enabled triggers.
column8: From Oracle doc: Disable the triggers on the table and try again.

column6: direct path does not support referential or check constraints
column7: A direct path operation is being attempted on a table which has enabled referential integrity or enabled check constraints.
column8: From Oracle doc: Disable the referential integrity and/or check constraints on the table and try again.

column6: scalar column '%s' must be specified prior to LOB columns
column7: All scalar columns (that is, non-LOB and non-LONG columns) must be specified by the client of the direct path API prior to specifying any LOB columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify all scalar columns prior to specifying any LOB columns.

column6: LONG column '%s' must be specified last
column7: A client of the direct path API specified a LONG column to be loaded, but the LONG column was not the last column to be specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the LONG column last.

column6: row is in partial state
column7: A direct path operation is being finished or a data save request has been made, but the table for which the request is being made on has a row in partial state. The row must be completed before the segment high water marks can be moved.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either complete the row, or abort the direct path operation.

column6: requested direct path operation not supported
column7: A direct path operation was requested that is not supported
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use that operation. Currently, UNLOAD is not supported.

column6: only LONG or LOB types can be partial
column7: A column which is not a LONG or LOB had the OCI_DIRPATH_COL_PARTIAL flag associated with it. Only LONG or LOB type columns can be loaded in pieces.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the OCI_DIRPATH_COL_PARTIAL flag for the column.

column6: stream offset does not map to a column array
column7: The ROW_COUNT attribute was being read from a direct path stream handle and it was found that the stream offset for the last processed row did not map to a column array offset.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the stream was sourced from a column array.

column6: stream format error: input column overflow
column7: An input stream contained data for more input columns than specified by the client of the direct path API.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the stream being loaded is for the correct table. Check initialization sequence.

column6: unprocessed stream data exists
column7: Either a OCIDirPathLoadStream call was made which provided more stream data prior to the server being able to fully process the stream data that it already has, or a OCIDirPathFinish call was made when the server had unprocessed stream data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Most likely an application misuse of the direct path API. Make sure that the stream is not being reset inadvertently prior to any previous stream data being processed, or, that OCIDirPathFinish is not being called prematurely (that is, stream pushed, error encountered and LoadStream not called to process the remainder of the stream before Finish is called).

column6: transfer size too small for row data (number bytes required)
column7: Either the transfer buffer size specified, or the default transfer buffer size (if you did not specify a size), is too small to contain a single row of the converted row data.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set the transfer buffer size attribute of the direct path context to be larger.

column6: unsupported conversion for column %s (from type number to type number)
column7: The direct path API does not support the required conversion.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the types are correct.

column6: direct path context is not prepared
column7: A direct path API function was called with a direct path context which has not been prepared.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure all necessary attributes in the direct path context have been set, and the context is prepared via OCIDirPathPrepare.

column6: direct path context is already prepared
column7: OCIDirPathPrepare was called with a context that has already been prepared.
column8: From Oracle doc: Free the direct path context, set necessary attributes, and call OCIDirPathPrepare.

column6: unused error
column7: This error is not used.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: tablespace # in file header is %s rather than %s for file %s
column7: The tablespace number in the file header is inconsistent with that in the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if the control file has been migrated correctly. Retry with the correct control file and datafile.

column6: relative file # in file header is %s rather than %s for file %s
column7: The relative file number in the file header is inconsistent with that in the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if the control file has been migrated correctly. Retry with the correct control file and datafile.

column6: V6 or V7 data file used to create control file
column7: The file header of the referenced file is in V6 or V7 format.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either remove the file from the create control file command, or somehow migrate the file header to V8 format.

column6: error on caching "%s"."%s"
column7: Attempt to cache the replication information which is unavailable in the catalog for the object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use DBMS_REPUTIL.SYNC_UP_REP to validate the replication catalog, or use DBMS_REPUTIL.MAKE_INTERNAL_PKG to validate internal package.

column6: RepAPI operation failure
column7: An external RepAPI operation failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult detail error message.

column6: error resignal
column7: An internal service failed and signalled an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult detail error message.

column6: internal RepAPI operation failure on object %s.%s
column7: An unexpected internal RepAPI failure was detected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: operation not implemented
column7: The caller requested a RepAPI operation that was not implemented.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not issue this call.

column6: unexpected internal null
column7: An internal buffer control structure was NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that sufficient memory resources are available to RepAPI.

column6: null global context
column7: An internal buffer control structure was NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that sufficient memory resources are available to RepAPI.

column6: null master connection
column7: The master connection handle was or became invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the master connection is valid.

column6: null snapshot connection
column7: The client connection handle was or became invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the client connection is valid.

column6: null snapshot control structure
column7: An internal snapshot control structure could not be obtained.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the owner and users provided are correct.

column6: snapshot name: '%s' is greater than max. allowed length of %s bytes
column7: The specified snapshot name was too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shorten the snapshot name.

column6: master table '%s.%s' not found
column7: A RepAPI operation was attempted against a non-existent or invalid master table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the master table object exists.

column6: error pushing transaction to def$error
column7: An unexpected error occurred while sending an DEF$ERROR RPC to the master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the DBMS_DEFER package is valid and executable by the RepAPI client. Contact the local or master site administrator, if necessary.

column6: push error: master proc. %s$RP.%s failed for trans:%s seq:%s
column7: A conflict/error occurred at the master site while executing a $RP.rep_insert(), rep_update(), or rep_delete() function which was not handled by conflict resolution logic at the master.
column8: From Oracle doc: Notify master site system administrator or database administrator.

column6: object '%s.%s' not found
column7: The specified object was expected but not found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the specified object exists and is valid.

column6: no master log available for '%s.%s'
column7: The specified master log was not found or available for the named table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the master log at the master site or correct any problems that may exist with the log.

column6: no push transaction acknowledgement
column7: RepAPI was unable to confirm that the last pushed transaction was successfully committed by the master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the communications link between the local site and the master site is still valid. If the transaction has not been committed at the master, repush the transaction.

column6: snapshot control entry for '%s.%s' was not found
column7: The specified snapshot catalog control record was not found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the local snapshot catalog is valid and that the local snapshot is properly defined.

column6: push queue synchronization error detected
column7: Client tried to repush a transaction has already been committed at the master site. A common cause of this problem is an error at the local site in initializing or updating the local site transaction sequence mechanism.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that transaction data that RepAPI was attempting to repushed to the master site exists at the master table and is valid and consistent with the local site. If this error occurs, redundantly identified transactions are ignored and then purged from the local updatable snapshot logs. Check that the local site is correctly assigning new transaction IDs and is not accidently generating non-unique values.

column6: no memory available to allocate
column7: There was no memory left for the RepAPI process. This error may occur when RepAPI is trying to allocate a new table buffer area.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down one or more local applications to attempt to free heap memory and retry the RepAPI operation.

column6: internal memory failure
column7: An internal memory error was detected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if other errors have occurred or determine if any local application may have corrupted the memory subsystem.

column6: rpc initialization error
column7: An error occurred during the initialization of a PL/SQL RPC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the procedure to be invoked exists and is valid at the master site and is executable by the RepAPI user.

column6: rpc execution error
column7: An error occurred during the execution of a PL/SQL RPC.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the error messages from the remote procedure and fix any remote site problems that may be preventing the execution of the invoked RPC.

column6: rpc termination error
column7: An error occurred during the termination of a PL/SQL RPC. This is usually caused by master site being unable to close an opened cursor or if RepAPI cannot deallocate internal memory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix any server side problems first, determine if the RepAPI memory subsystem has been corrupted.

column6: nls subsystem initialization failure for product=%s, facility=%s
column7: The NLS product/facility error message file could not be located or properly initialized.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the error message directory and file(s) have been properly installed.

column6: session connection attempt failed for %s (@%s)
column7: A connection could not be established to the specified database using the provided connection string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that the user, password, connect string, names services, network, and any remote site listener process are properly installed and working.

column6: snapshot sql ddl parse/expansion failed for %s.%s
column7: The client SQL snapshot definition query could not be properly parsed by the master Oracle site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check that snapshot DDL SQL is compatible with the currently connected version of Oracle and does not violate any of the RepAPI SQL limitations or restrictions.

column6: local store callback init phase failed for '%s.%s'
column7: The client callback failed during its INIT phase for the named object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the objects referenced by the client callback exist and are valid. Refer to the vendor-specific callback error code reference to diagnose the local problem. Record all error states and notify Oracle Customer Support.

column6: local store callback proc phase failed for '%s.%s'
column7: The client callback failed during its PROC phase for the named object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the vendor-specific callback error code reference to diagnose the local problem. Record all error states and notify Oracle Customer Support.

column6: local store callback term phase failed for '%s.%s'
column7: The client callback failed during its TERM phase for the named object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to the vendor-specific callback error code reference to diagnose the local problem. Record all error states and notify Oracle Customer Support.

column6: unable to build snapshot refresh control list
column7: The snapshot control list could not be constructed. This is generally the result of an error while accessing the local snapshot catalog.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the named snapshot(s) are properly defined and valid.

column6: replication parallel push simulated site failure
column7: A parallel push executed with event 26531 enabled raises this error to simulation failure of network or destination site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not enable the event for normal operation.

column6: collision: tranID number ignored and purged
column7: A transaction that was pushed had a transaction ID that collided with a transaction that was previously pushed and committed at the master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the action section for E_QUEUESYNC (26518).

column6: number byte row cache insufficient for table with rowsize=number
column7: A transaction that was pushed had a transaction ID that collided with a transaction that was previously pushed and committed at the master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the RepAPI row buffer size or reduce the width of the replicated tables.

column6: refresh was aborted because of conflicts caused by deferred transactions
column7: There are outstanding conflicts logged in the DEFERROR table at the snapshot's master site.
column8: From Oracle doc: Resolve the conflicts in the master DEFERROR table and refresh again after the table is empty. Alternatively, refresh with REFRESH_AFTER_ERRORS, even if there are conflicts in the master's DEFERROR table. Proceeding despite conflicts can result in an updatable snapshot's changes appearing to be temporarily lost, until a refresh succeeds after the conflicts are resolved.

column6: renaming this table is not allowed
column7: Attempt to rename a replicated table, an updatable snapshot table or the master table of a snapshot for which a snapshot log has been created.
column8: From Oracle doc: If desired, unregister the replicated table with DBMS_REPCAT.DROP_MASTER_REPOBJECT, or use the recommended procedure to rename the master table of a snapshot.

column6: %s argument is not of specified type
column7: User passed type of the given argument number does not match with the type of the argument in the stored arguments.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke correct type procedure (that is, get_XXX_arg).

column6: Call to type_arg made before calling dbms_defer.call
column7: User invoked type_arg procedure before starting a deferred call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke various procedures in the correct order.

column6: Couldn't open connect to %s
column7: Failed to open connection using given database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the database link is valid and remote m/c is up.

column6: %s.%s.%s: number of arguments (%s) does not match replication catalog
column7: The number of arguments does not match the replication catalog.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine the total number of arguments for the RPC call.

column6: %s.%s.%s: argument %s does not match replication catalog
column7: The (RPC) call is corrupted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Examine total number of arguments and each argument for the RPC call.

column6: remote database does not support replication parallel propagation
column7: The remote database has a version lower than Oracle 8.0 and hence does not understand replication parallel propagation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use serial propagation or upgrade the remote database to Oracle 8.0 or above.

column6: skgfqsbi: failed to initialize storage subsystem (SBT) layer
column7: SBTINIT returned an error, additional information indicates error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that vendor's storage subsystem product is operating correctly.

column6: unsupported device type
column7: The specified device type is supported on this platform.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check V$BACKUP_DEVICE for supported device types.

column6: function called with invalid device structure
column7: An internal error occurred. Additional information indicates which function encountered error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for a trace file and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot open file on device allocated with NOIO option
column7: An internal error occurred. A file is being created/retrieved on a device allocated with NOIO option, additional information indicates which function encountered error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for a trace file and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid blocksize specified
column7: An internal error occurred. The block size specified is incorrect for the device on which file is being created, additional information indicates block size specified, and the function that encountered the error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for a trace file and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot open file for async I/O on device not supporting async
column7: An internal error occurred. A file is being opened for asynchronous I/O on a device that does not support asynchronous I/O, additional information indicates which function encountered error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for a trace file and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: sbtremove returned error
column7: Additional information indicates error returned by SBTREMOVE, and the function that encountered the error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the vendor's storage subsystem product is operating correctly.

column6: failed to open file
column7: SBTOPEN returned error, additional information indicates error returned from SBTOPEN, and the function that encountered the error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the vendor's storage subsystem product is operating correctly.

column6: function called with invalid file structure
column7: An internal error occurred. Additional information indicates which function encountered error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for a trace file and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: skgfwrt: cannot write to file opened for read
column7: An internal error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for a trace file and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: skgfwrt: write to file failed
column7: SBTWRITE returned error, additional information indicates error returned from SBTWRITE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the vendor's storage subsystem product is operating correctly.

column6: skgfrd: cannot read from file opened for write
column7: An internal error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for a trace file and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: skgfrd: read from file failed
column7: SBTREAD returned error, additional information indicates error returned from SBTREAD.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the vendor's storage subsystem product is operating correctly.

column6: skgfqdel: cannot delete an open file
column7: An internal error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for a trace file and contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: skgfqpini: translation error while expanding SS_UDMPDIR
column7: Failure of SLTLN in SKGFQPINI.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check additional return error for more information.

column6: skgfcls: failed to close the file
column7: SBTCLOSE returned an error. Additional information indicates error returned from SBTCLOSE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the vendor's storage subsystem product is operating correctly.

column6: skgfcls: sbtinfo returned error
column7: Additional information indicates error returned from SBTINFO.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the vendor's storage subsystem product is operating correctly.

column6: skgfcls: media handle returned by sbtinfo exceeds max length(SSTMXQMH)
column7: Media handle string length exceeds SSTMXQMH.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the vendor's storage subsystem product is operating correctly, and that the platform limit (SSTMXQMH) is at least 64 (the limit specified for SBTINFO). additional information indicates the media handle string length returned by SBTINFO, and the limit (SSTMXQMH).

column6: BLKSIZE is not a multiple of the minimum physical block size
column7: User-specified BLKSIZE (blocking factor) is not a multiple of the minimum block size that is permitted on this platform.
column8: From Oracle doc: Two ADDITIONAL INFORMATION messages are displayed which show the blocking factor provided by the user and the minimum physical block size. Specify a BLKSIZE that is an integral multiple of the minimum block size.

column6: tape filename length exceeds limit (SBTOPMXF)
column7: The length of the tape file name provided to sequential I/O OSD functions is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Additional information indicates in which function this error is encountered, the length of file name provided, and the limit on file name.

column6: named devices not supported
column7: The platform or the specified device type does not support named devices.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify device name or use a device type that supports named devices. Use V$BACKUP_DEVICE view to see what device types and names (if any) are available.

column6: sequential file handle must be specified
column7: The file name which will be passed to SBTOPEN was not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a file name and continue. If this is a backup set being created via Recovery Manager, use the 'format' option to specify the backup piece handle name.

column6: skgfqsbi: could not allocate memory for media manager
column7: Oracle could not allocate memory required by the media management software which is linked with Oracle to provide backup/restore services.
column8: From Oracle doc: Increase the amount of memory available to the Oracle process and retry the backup/restore.

column6: skgfqsbi: media manager protocol error
column7: The media management software which is linked with Oracle to provide backup/restore services did not provide its function pointer structure to Oracle. This is an internal error in the media management product.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the media management vendor.

column6: skgfqsbi: sbtinit2 returned error
column7: SBTINIT2 returned an error. This happens during a backup or restore operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: This error is returned from the media management software which is linked with Oracle. There should be additional messages which explain the cause of the error. This error usually requires contacting the media management vendor.

column6: skgfqsbi: invalid media manager context area size
column7: The media management software requested a context area size which is greater than the maximum allowable size. This is an internal error in the media management product.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the media management vendor.

column6: skgfrls: sbtend returned error

column8: From Oracle doc: This error is returned from the media management software which is linked with Oracle. There should be additional messages which explain the cause of the error. This error usually requires contacting the media management vendor.

column6: sbtremove2 returned error

column6: skgfqcre: sbtbackup returned error

column6: logical block size is invalid
column7: Logical block size for Oracle files must be a multiple of the physical block size, and less than the maximum.
column8: From Oracle doc: Block size specified is returned as additional information, check initialization parameters, additional information also indicates which function encountered the error.

column6: translation error, unable to expand file name

column8: From Oracle doc: Raise the file size limit.

column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the file has not been overwritten or truncated.

column8: From Oracle doc: Check errno.

column6: cannot allocate zero sized communication buffers

column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to KGXP.H for usage of KGXPVALO().

column6: IPC global name service is not supported

column8: From Oracle doc: Either use a different name service, of abort the current process/thread.

column6: trying to destroy invalid connection identifier

column6: cannot send unaligned message

column6: exceeded the maximum vectored message size

column8: From Oracle doc: Use a smaller vector size.

column6: multicast message is not aligned on the correct boundary
column7: The message to multicast is not aligned on the proper boundary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Align the message appropriately.

column6: cannot receive messages into unaligned buffers
column7: The message being posted for receive is not aligned on the required boundary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the KGXPALSZ() macro to get the alignment size of messages, and align all messages on this boundary.

column6: failed to added accept handle to the free pool

column8: From Oracle doc: Exit the process.

column6: accept handle free pool is empty. Cannot accept new connections

column8: From Oracle doc: Add accept handles to the free pool.

column6: no more communication channels can be created for process/thread. already at maximum.
column7: The maximum communication channels are already in use for this process/thread.
column8: From Oracle doc: Destroy connections which are not needed.

column6: fatal error trying to connect to remote port
column7: Either the remote address is not valid, or the process is in bad shape.
column8: From Oracle doc: Destroy all connections, and try to re-establish them.

column6: failed trying to queue up accept handles
column7: The OSD would not allow KGXP to queue up the storage necessary to accept new incoming connections.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the parameters; if they are okay, abort the process.

column6: cannot cancel an outstanding request
column7: The OSD cannot cancel an outstanding request immediately.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shut down all connections and abort the process.

column6: memory mapped communication is not supported
column7: The platform does not support memory communication.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the default send/receive.

column6: the account is locked
column7: The user has entered wrong password consequently for maximum number of times specified by the user's profile parameter FAILED_LOGIN_ATTEMPTS, or the database administrator has locked the account.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait for PASSWORD_LOCK_TIME or contact the database administrator.

column6: the password has expired
column7: The user's account has expired and the password needs to be changed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the password or contact the database administrator.

column6: the password will expire within %s days
column7: The user's account is about to about to expire and the password needs to be changed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the password or contact the database administrator.

column6: password verification for the specified password failed
column7: The new password did not meet the necessary complexity specifications and the PASSWORD_VERIFY_FUNCTION failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enter a different password. Contact the database administrator to find out the rules for choosing the new password.

column6: invalid argument for function specified in PASSWORD_VERIFY_FUNCTION %s
column7: The password verification function does not have the required number and type of input/output arguments and/or the return argument.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the Oracle Security Server Guide to find out the format of the password verification function.

column6: invalid logon flags
column7: The flags are not properly set or conflicting flags are set in making calls.
column8: From Oracle doc: Call the function with appropriate flags set.

column6: conflicting values for parameters %s and %s
column7: The parameters PASSWORD_REUSE_TIME and PASSWORD_REUSE_MAX cannot both be set. One parameter should be unlimited while other is set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Set one value to UNLIMITED explicitly.

column6: the password cannot be reused
column7: The password cannot be reused for the specified number of days or for the specified number of password changes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try the password that you have not used for the specified number of days or the specified number of password changes Refer to the password parameters in the CREATE PROFILE statement.

column6: invalid old password
column7: Old password supplied is wrong; Hence user cannot be authenticated using old password.
column8: From Oracle doc: Supply the correct old password for authentication.

column6: connection to sys should be as sysdba or sysoper
column7: Connect sys/password is no longer a valid syntax.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try connect sys/password as sysdba or connect sys/password as sysoper.

column6: cannot expire external or global accounts
column7: If a user account is created as IDENTIFIED EXTERNALLY, or IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY, this account cannot be expired.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try to expire the password of the user that has database password.

column6: IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY already specified
column7: The IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY clause was specified twice.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use only one IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY clause.

column6: cannot grant global roles
column7: A role granted was IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY. Global roles can only be granted via a central authority for the domain.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER ROLE to change the type of role (from IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY to other, such as IDENTIFIED BY password), or allocate it to a global user via the central authority.

column6: cannot grant external roles to global user or role
column7: A role granted was IDENTIFIED EXTERNALLY. External roles cannot be granted to global users or global roles.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use ALTER ROLE to change the type of the role being granted (from IDENTIFIED EXTERNALLY to other, such as IDENTIFIED BY password), or use ALTER ROLE or ALTER USER to change the type of the user or role that is the grantee.

column6: must revoke grants of this role to other user(s) first
column7: The role altered to IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY was granted to one or more other users and/or roles. Global roles cannot be granted to any user or role.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use REVOKE to revoke the role from other users or roles first.

column6: must revoke grants of external roles to this role/user
column7: The user or role altered to IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY has external roles directly granted; these must be revoked, since external roles cannot be granted to global users or roles.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use REVOKE to revoke the external roles from the user or role to be ALTERed.

column6: missing or null external name
column7: The IDENTIFIED EXTERNALLY AS or IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY AS clause was specified with a valid external name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide a valid external name.

column6: user with same external name already exists
column7: The external name specified for the user being created or altered already exists for another user.
column8: From Oracle doc: External names must be unique among users. Specify another.

column6: privileged database links may be used by global users
column7: Only users IDENTIFIED GLOBALLY may use a privileged database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either change the user to a global user or try to use a different database link.

column6: could not authenticate remote server
column7: During the course of opening a privileged database link, the remote server was not securely identified using the network security service. Additional errors should follow.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consult the network security service documentation on how to properly configure the remote server.

column6: could not authorize remote server for user %s
column7: During the course of opening a privileged database link, the remote server was found to lack the necessary authorizations to connect as the current global user. This may be because the server was not authorized by the network security service. Or it may be because the local server is restricting access by the remote server using the DBMS_SECURITY_DOMAINS_ADMIN package.
column8: From Oracle doc: Grant the remote server the proper authorization to connect as the given global user, and check that the local server is not restricting access.

column6: Server encountered problems accessing LDAP directory service
column7: Unable to access LDAP directory service.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: Cannot Get Session Key for Authentication

column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your system administrator.

column6: policy function schema %s is invalid
column7: The schema was dropped after the policy associated with the function had been added to the object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the policy and re-create it with a policy function owned by a valid user. Or re-create the user and the policy function under the new user.

column6: policy already exists
column7: A policy with the same name for the same object already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if the policy has already been added or use a different policy name.

column6: policy does not exist

column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the policy name argument.

column6: adding a policy to an object owned by SYS is not allowed

column8: From Oracle doc: You cannot perform this operation.

column6: policy function or package is invalid

column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the function or package.

column6: input value for argument #%s is not valid
column7: Input values for the argument is missing or invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the input values.

column6: policy was disabled
column7: Try to flush a disabled policy.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the policy is supposed to be enforced, it must be enabled.

column6: circular row level security policies detected
column7: Policies for the same object reference each other.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the policies.

column6: the number of related policies has exceeded the limit of 16
column7: Too many policies are involved in the same objects.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop one or more policies. Or combine a few of them into one.

column6: policy function or package %s.%s has error
column7: The policy function may have been dropped, or is no longer valid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the status of the function and correct the problem. Or re-create the policy with a valid function.

column6: insufficient privilege to evaluate policy predicate

column8: From Oracle doc: Grant appropriate privileges to the policy function owner.

column6: failed to execute policy function
column7: The policy function has one or more error during execution.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the trace file and correct the errors.

column6: policy predicate has error
column7: Policy function generates invalid predicate.
column8: From Oracle doc: Review the trace file for detailed error information.

column6: policy with check option violation
column7: Policy predicate was evaluated to FALSE with the updated values.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the trace file and correct the errors.

column6: insufficient privileges to do direct path access
column7: Users with insufficient privileges attempting to do direct path access of tables with fine grain access control policies.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask the database administrator to do the operation. Note that users can work with security administrator to temporarily drop/disable the policies at time of export, import, or load, but this has security implication, and thus access of the database must be controlled carefully.

column6: proxy not authorized to connect as client
column7: A proxy user attempted to connect as a client, but the proxy was not authorized to act on behalf of the client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Grant the proxy user permission to perform actions on behalf of the client by using the ALTER USER... GRANT CONNECT command.

column6: more than one user name specified for command
column7: More than one user name was specified for an ALTER USER command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try the command again with only one user name.

column6: proxy user '%s' may not specify initial role '%s' on behalf of client '%s'
column7: A proxy user attempted to specify an initial role for a client, but the client does not possess the role.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the proxy user so that it does not specify the role or grant the role to the client.

column6: Invalid client initial role specified: '%s'
column7: A role specified by a proxy user as an initial role to be activated upon connecting on behalf of a client is invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Connect again as the client specifying a valid role.

column6: Proxy user may not act as client '%s'
column7: A proxy user cannot assume the identity of a privileged user in order to limit the privileges that a proxy can possess.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute the statement again, specifying a client other than a privileged user.

column6: user '%s' specified as a proxy is actually a role
column7: A user specified in an AUDIT operation BY proxy ON BEHALF OF client is actually a role.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute the statement again with a valid proxy user.

column6: Proxy user '%s' not authorized to set role '%s' for client '%s'
column7: A proxy user has not been granted the right to use a role on behalf of a client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute the command ALTER USER client GRANT CONNECT THROUGH PROXY proxy to grant the needed role.

column6: Proxy user '%s' forbidden to set role '%s' for client '%s'
column7: A proxy user was forbidden to use a role on behalf of a client through the command ALTER USER client GRANT CONNECT THROUGH proxy WITH ALL ROLES EXCEPT role.
column8: From Oracle doc: Execute the command ALTER USER client GRANT CONNECT THROUGH PROXY proxy to grant the needed role.
