column7: Keyword missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide missing keyword.

column6: missing BEHALF keyword
column7: Keyword missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide missing keyword.

column6: missing EXCEPT keyword
column7: Keyword missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide missing keyword.

column6: missing ROLES keyword
column7: Keyword missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide missing keyword.

column6: missing THROUGH keyword
column7: Keyword missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Provide missing keyword.

column6: GRANT already specified
column7: The GRANT clause was specified twice.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use only one GRANT clause.

column6: REVOKE already specified
column7: The REVOKE clause was specified twice.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use only one REVOKE clause.

column6: proxy '%s' may not specify password-protected role '%s' for client '%s'
column7: A proxy user attempted to activate a role on behalf of a client which has a password associated with it. Since the proxy does not have a password, this activation cannot be allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Attempt to activate a different role or change the role administratively so that there is no password.

column6: duplicate rolename in list
column7: The name of a role was specified more than once in a list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Repeat the command specifying the role once.

column6: attempted to grant password-protected role
column7: An ALTER USER ... GRANT CONNECT command was attempted specifying a role that is protected by a password as a role which the proxy may execute on behalf of a client.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify a role that does not have a password or alter the role so that a password is not required.

column6: Invalid input to Obfuscation toolkit
column7: An empty input was given to the obfuscation toolkit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the input corresponding to the PL/SQL function is not empty.

column6: Invalid input size for Obfuscation toolkit
column7: Input to DES encryption/decryption routine not a multiple of 8 bytes.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the input corresponding to the PL/SQL function is a multiple of 8 bytes.

column6: connection from ORACLE to a non-Oracle system returned this message:
column7: The cause is explained in the forwarded message.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the non-Oracle system's documentation of the forwarded message.

column6: communication error on heterogeneous database link
column7: An unexpected communication failure occurred on a heterogeneous database link to a non-Oracle system. The message above will be followed by a second message generated by the connected non-Oracle system.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the documentation for the non-Oracle system for an explanation of the second error message.

column6: internal communication error on heterogeneous database link
column7: A communication error internal to Oracle's heterogeneous services has occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: bind value cannot be translated into SQL text for non-Oracle system
column7: A SQL statement used bind variables on a Heterogeneous Services database link to a non-Oracle system, but the non-Oracle system does not support bind variables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change your SQL statement so that it does not use bind variables.

column6: ROWID not found in ROWID cache for heterogeneous database link
column7: The ROWID cache for Heterogeneous Services held no entry that corresponds to the specified ROWID. The ROWID entry may have been overwritten in the ROWID cache.
column8: From Oracle doc: Enlarge the Heterogeneous Services ROWID cache size by increasing the value of the initialization parameter ROWID_CACHE_SIZE in the server data dictionary by using the DBMS_HS PL/SQL package.

column6: cannot get non-Oracle system capabilities from %s
column7: Oracle was unable to retrieve capability information for the non-Oracle system connected through a heterogeneous database link. This capability information should be stored in data dictionary tables viewable with the HS_CLASS_CAPS or HS_INST_CAPS data dictionary views.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the database administrator to check the server data dictionary table named in the error message. If table contents are incorrect, the database administrator should restore all data dictionary content for this FDS_CLASS_NAME and/or FDS_INST_NAME. It usually is sufficient to delete all current data dictionary content for this class and/or instance and initiate a new connection to let the connected agent upload new data dictionary content to the server.

column6: parse error in data dictionary translation for %s stored in %s
column7: A reference to an Oracle data dictionary table or view name on a heterogeneous database link to a non-Oracle system could not be translated. The Oracle data dictionary tables shown with view HS_CLASS_DD contain invalid SQL for the data dictionary translation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: error in data dictionary view %s
column7: The initialization parameter table for the Heterogeneous Services was not available, or its structure (number of columns or column types) was incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify correct installation of the following Heterogeneous Services' initialization parameter views: HS_CLASS_INIT and HS_INST_INIT. If these views are not available, make sure you ran the script CATHS.SQL in the $ORACLE_HOME/rdbms/admin directory.

column6: invalid value %s for Heterogeneous Services initialization parameter %s
column7: The specified Heterogeneous Services initialization parameter had an invalid value when attempting to connect to a non-Oracle system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the Heterogeneous Services documentation to determine acceptable values, and update that parameter in HS_INST_INIT using a PL/SQL procedure in the DBMS_HS package.

column6: unable to establish a connection to non-Oracle system
column7: Initialization of a database link to a non-Oracle system failed to connect to the Heterogeneous Services agent process for this non-Oracle system.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Check the Net8 service name definition in the following places: 

the USING clause of the CREATE DATABASE LINK statement 

the TNSNAMES.ORA file 

the Oracle Names Server 

The following are possible reasons for name mismatches: 

The USING clause in the CREATE DATABASE LINK statement has to match the service name defined in the TNSNAMES.ORA file or in the Oracle Names Server. 

The protocol-specific information in the service name definition must match the protocol-specific definition of the responding listener. 

The SID=name in the service name definition (in the TNSNAMES.ORA file or in Oracle Names Server) must match the value in the LISTENER.ORA file for the responding listener.

column6: heterogeneous database link initialization failed
column7: Initialization of a heterogeneous database link to a non-Oracle system failed due to an error identified by the agent for this non-Oracle system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the non-Oracle system is up and running and that all of the environment and initialization values for the agent are set correctly.

column6: lost RPC connection to heterogeneous remote agent using SID=%s
column7:
A fatal error occurred in one of the following places: 

the connection between the Oracle server and the agent 

the heterogeneous services remote agent itself 

the connection to the non-Oracle system 

This error occurred after communication had been established successfully.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check for network problems and remote host crashes. The problem is probably in the agent software. If so, contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: cannot get data dictionary translations from %s
column7: Oracle was unable to retrieve data dictionary translation information for the non-Oracle system connected through a heterogeneous database link. This data dictionary translation information should be stored in data dictionary tables viewable with the HS_CLASS_DD or HS_INST_DD data dictionary views.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask your database administrator to check the server data dictionary table named in the error message. If table contents are incorrect, the database administrator should restore all data dictionary content for this FDS_CLASS_NAME and/or FDS_INST_NAME. It usually is sufficient to delete all current data dictionary content for this class and/or instance and initiate a new connection to let the connected agent upload new data dictionary content to the server.

column6: internal error in heterogeneous remote agent
column7: An internal error has occurred in the Oracle remote agent supporting a heterogeneous database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make a note of how the error was produced and contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: heterogeneous database link initialization could not convert system date
column7: The system date was not retrievable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the Oracle server's host machine and operating system are operational. This error should not occur unless low level system functions are failing.

column6: cannot get external object definitions from %s
column7: Oracle was unable to retrieve definitions of distributed external procedures or remote libraries registered for the non-Oracle system instance, probably because the underlying data dictionary table does not exist or is malformed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the Oracle server's Heterogeneous Services data dictionary was installed correctly. If the Heterogeneous Services data dictionary is not installed, execute the CATHS.SQL script in the $ORACLE_HOME/rdbms/admin directory.

column6: data dictionary translation has illegal translation type
column7: A data dictionary translation definition, either in the Oracle server data dictionary or in data dictionary content uploaded from a Heterogeneous Services agent, specified an illegal translation type code. Legal values are 'T' or 't' for 'translate', 'M' or 'm' for 'mimic'. Information on the exact data dictionary translation causing the error is written to a trace (*.TRC) file for the Oracle instance and to the Oracle instance's alert log. This error occurs when a Heterogeneous Services agent uploads data dictionary content to an Oracle server on the first connection from the server to the agent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: no heterogeneous data dictionary translations available
column7: The Oracle server's data dictionary did not define data dictionary translations for the connected non-Oracle system, and automatic self-registration (data dictionary upload) was disabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask a database administrator to resolve this problem. The easiest solution is to enable automatic self-registration by setting the Oracle server's HS_AUTO_REGISTER initialization parameter to TRUE. An alternative is to load the Heterogeneous Services data dictionary with information specific for the non-Oracle system by executing a SQL script supplied by the agent vendor. If the script is run and the error persists, contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: error initializing heterogeneous data dictionary translations
column7: Oracle was unable to retrieve data dictionary translations for the non-Oracle system instance, probably because the underlying data dictionary table does not exist or is formed incorrectly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the Oracle server's Heterogeneous Services data dictionary was installed correctly. If the Heterogeneous Services data dictionary is not installed, execute the CATHS.SQL script in the $ORACLE_HOME/rdbms/admin directory. If the connected agent, identified by FDS_CLASS_NAME, requires a custom installation script for the Oracle server, verify that the script has been run. If both scripts were executed and the error persists, contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: no heterogeneous capability information available
column7: The Oracle server's data dictionary did not contain capability definitions for the connected non-Oracle system, and automatic self-registration (data dictionary upload) was disabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask a database administrator to resolve this problem. The easiest resolution is to enable automatic self-registration by setting the Oracle server's HS_AUTO_REGISTER initialization parameter to TRUE. An alternative is to load the Heterogeneous Services data dictionary with information specific for the non-Oracle system by executing a SQL script supplied by the agent vendor. If the script is run and the error persists, contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: error initializing heterogeneous capabilities
column7: Oracle was unable to retrieve capability definitions for the non-Oracle system instance, probably because the underlying data dictionary table does not exist or is formed incorrectly.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the Oracle server's Heterogeneous Services data dictionary was installed correctly. If the Heterogeneous Services data dictionary is not installed, execute the CATHS.SQL script in the $ORACLE_HOME/rdbms/admin directory. If the connected agent, identified by FDS_CLASS_NAME, requires a custom installation script for the Oracle server, verify that the script has been run. If both scripts were executed and the error persists, contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: ORACLE and heterogeneous agent are incompatible versions
column7: An operation on a database link attempted to connect to a non-Oracle system, but the Oracle instance and the agent process for the non-Oracle system are incompatible.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask your database administrator to confirm configuration of both the Oracle instance and the agent. Additional information on the version incompatibility is logged in trace (*.TRC) files, the Oracle instance and the agent, and in the Oracle instance's alert log. Check the documentation for your agent to find out which releases of the Oracle Server are supported.

column6: unable to create Heterogeneous Services error message text
column7: Incorrect arguments were passed into the error message creation routine.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid describe information returned to Heterogeneous Services
column7: The Heterogeneous Services received invalid describe information for a select list, bind list, or stored procedure from the Heterogeneous Services agent. This indicates a problem with the Heterogeneous Services' non-Oracle system agent.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: Heterogeneous Services datatype mapping error
column7: Either an Oracle datatype could not be mapped to a non-Oracle datatype, or a non-Oracle datatype could not be mapped to an Oracle datatype. These mappings are defined as capability definitions in the Oracle server's data dictionary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the Oracle server's data dictionary has been initialized with correct capability definitions for the connected FDS_CLASS_NAME and FDS_INST_NAME. If table contents are incorrect, a database administrator should restore all data dictionary content for this FDS_CLASS_NAME and/or FDS_INST_NAME. It usually is sufficient to delete all current data dictionary content for this class and/or instance and initiate a new connection to let the connected agent upload new data dictionary content to the server. If the error persists contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: Heterogeneous Services datatype conversion error
column7:
Either an Oracle datatype could not be converted to a non-Oracle datatype, or a non-Oracle datatype could not be converted to an Oracle datatype. The following are possible reasons for the conversion failure: 

overflow problems (in the case of numbers) 

length limitations (in the case of character strings) 

invalid values passed into the conversion routines
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact customer support of the agent vendor. If the problem is due to size discrepancies between Oracle and the non-Oracle system, it may not be possible to convert the value.

column6: invalid or missing parameter in Net8 service name definition
column7: There was an invalid or missing Heterogeneous Services parameter in the Net8 service name definition stored in either the TNSNAMES.ORA file or in the Oracle Names Server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ask your database administrator to make sure the information in the Net8 service definition is correct and complete. The correct information that should be included in the Net8 service definition can be found in the agent's documentation.

column6: Heterogeneous Services initialization error in NLS language ID
column7: Heterogeneous Services was unable to initialize an NLS language ID. Both the Oracle server and the Heterogeneous Services agent for the connected non-Oracle system must have language IDs.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Heterogeneous Services coercion handling error
column7: The Heterogeneous Services encountered an error in coercion handling. The HS can, if the agent vendor so chooses, perform extra processing on SQL statements that contain implicit coercions or that contain coercion functions such as TO_CHAR, TO_NUMBER or TO_DATE. This functionality is controlled by coercion-related capabilities. HS logic reports this error when it encounters an error in one of these capability definitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: The capability table settings are controlled by the agent vendor and can be modified by the database administrator. Contact your database administrator and agent vendor and get the correct set of capabilities installed.

column6: Heterogeneous Services preprocessing error
column7: One of the things that the Heterogeneous Services can do is to preprocess parts of SQL statements that contain implicit coercions or calls to explicit coercion functions like TO_CHAR TO_NUMBER or TO_DATE. For example, it could convert a call to TO_DATE to a bind variable, pre-evaluate the TO_DATE function call and pass the resulting value to the non-Oracle system as the bind value. This behavior is controlled by some coercion related capabilities. If the capabilities are set incorrectly, the HS could encounter errors when it attempts to do the preprocessing. If it does then this error will be signaled.
column8: From Oracle doc: The capability table settings are controlled by the agent vendor and can be modified by the database administrator. Contact your database administrator and agent vendor and get the correct set of capabilities installed.

column6: invalid Heterogeneous Services context
column7: A Heterogeneous Services agent's driver module called an HS service routine with an invalid HS context value. This probably is a logic error in the driver.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact customer support of the agent vendor.

column6: error in processing Heterogeneous Services initialization parameters
column7: An error described by a subsequent error message prevented successful processing of Heterogeneous Services initialization parameters from the Oracle server data dictionary.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check server data dictionary views HS_CLASS_INIT, HS_INST_INIT, and HS_ALL_INITS. Look for conditions which could produce the error identified in the error message immediately following this one.

column6: pass-through SQL: cursor not found
column7: A value passed to a pass-through SQL function or procedure call as a cursor does not identify a currently open cursor.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a cursor number returned by the pass-through SQL OPEN_CURSOR call.

column6: pass-through SQL: SQL parse error
column7: A non-Oracle system rejected text supplied as a pass-through SQL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the SQL supplied to the pass-through SQL PARSE call is legal for the non-Oracle system.

column6: pass-through SQL: call flow error
column7: A pass-through SQL function was called in an invalid order.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct program flow by changing the order of API calls to match the flow described in the manual.

column6: pass-through SQL: invalid bind-variable position
column7: A pass-through SQL function referring to the position of a bind variable in the currently-parsed SQL statement supplied an invalid bind-variable position. Valid values are 1 through n, where n is the number of bind-variable place-holders in the SQL text.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the bind-variable position parameter is in the correct range to represent a place-holder in the SQL text. Confirm that the SQL text uses the correct syntax for a bind-variable place-holder, as required by the non-Oracle system.

column6: pass-through SQL: out of cursors
column7: The maximum number of open cursors has been exceeded.
column8: From Oracle doc: Close open cursors by using the pass-through SQL CLOSE_CURSOR function.

column6: pass-through SQL: required parameter missing or NULL
column7: An attempt was made to pass a NULL value to a non-NULL parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a non-NULL value for the parameter.

column6: authorization insufficient to access table
column7: A query attempted to access a table in the non-Oracle system that is either privileged or has privileged columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the database administrator for the non-Oracle system. The database administrator can grant permission to access the privileged table or columns.

column6: unknown %s for database link to non-Oracle system
column7: When attempting to connect to a non-Oracle system through a Heterogeneous Services database link, the agent supporting this non-Oracle system failed to return FDS_CLASS_NAME and/or FDS_INST_NAME. Oracle requires these names to configure the heterogeneous database link.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact the database administrator to check setup of the connection and the Heterogeneous Services agent.

column6: HS_FDS_CONNECT_STRING undefined for non-Oracle system
column7: A database link to a non-Oracle system had no HS_FDS_CONNECT_STRING initialization parameter in the Oracle server's data dictionary for Heterogeneous Services. Without this parameter, the connection could not be completed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your database administrator to verify correct setup of an HS_FDS_CONNECT_STRING entry in the Oracle Heterogeneous Services data dictionary (see HS_INST_INITS view in the Oracle8 Reference book). It may be necessary to use PL/SQL procedures in the SYS.DBMS_HS package to create or replace an entry for the connection's FDS_CLASS_NAME and FDS_INST_NAME.

column6: FDS_CLASS_NAME is %s, FDS_INST_NAME is %s
column7: An associated error was reported in another message, and this message supplies supplementary information to assist diagnosis of that error. FDS_CLASS_NAME and FDS_INST_NAME are used to access information in tables and views of the Oracle data dictionary that direct operation of Heterogeneous Services on a database link to a non-Oracle data store.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the FDS_CLASS_NAME and FDS_INST_NAME values to check Oracle data dictionary contents when necessary to diagnose the cause of the associated error.

column6: error in configuration of agent process
column7: An Oracle server invoked a function not supported by the connected agent (Heterogeneous Services or external procedures). The most probable cause is incorrect Net8 setup, resulting in use of the wrong agent executable.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Check Net8 administration in the following ways: 

When using TNSNAMES.ORA or an Oracle Names server, make sure that the connection from the Oracle server uses the correct SID. 

Check LISTENER.ORA on the agent's host machine to assure that this SID refers to the correct agent executable in its (PROGRAM=...) clause.

column6: unable to set date format on non-Oracle system
column7: Initialization of a Heterogeneous Services connection to set the date format to be used on the connected non-Oracle system.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the Oracle data dictionary supplies a value for the HS_NLS_DATE_FORMAT parameter, confirm that this value is formatted correctly by the rules of the non-Oracle system. Also check for additional information in log and trace files generated by the Heterogeneous Services agent.

column6: unable to open RPC connection to external procedure agent
column7: Initialization of a network connection to the external procedure agent did not succeed. This problem can be caused by network problems, incorrect listener configuration, or incorrect transfer code.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check listener configuration in LISTENER.ORA and TNSNAMES.ORA, or check Oracle Names Server.

column6: lost RPC connection to external procedure agent
column7: A fatal error occurred in either an RPC network connection, the external procedure agent, or the invoked 3GL after communication had been established successfully.
column8: From Oracle doc: First check the 3GL code you are invoking; the most likely cause of this error is abnormal termination of the invoked "C" routine. If this is not the case, check for network problems. Correct the problem if you find it. If all components appear to be normal but the problem persists, the problem could be an internal logic error in the RPC transfer code. Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: argument %s of external procedure %s has unsupported datatype %s
column7: While transferring external procedure arguments to the agent, an unsupported datatype was detected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your documentation for the supported datatypes of external procedure arguments.

column6: protocol error during callback from an external procedure
column7: An internal protocol error occurred while trying to execute a callback to the Oracle server from the user's 3GL routine.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: network error during callback from external procedure agent
column7: An internal network error occurred while trying to execute a callback to the Oracle server from the user's 3GL routine.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: recursive external procedures are not supported
column7: A callback from within a user's 3GL routine resulted in the invocation of another external procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the SQL code executed in a callback does not directly call another external procedure, or indirectly results in another external procedure, such as triggers calling external procedures, PL/SQL procedures calling external procedures, and so on.

column6: protocol error while executing recursive external procedure
column7: An internal protocol error occurred while trying to execute an external procedure resulting from a callback in another external procedure.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: a direct connection to this agent is not allowed
column7: A user or a tool tried to establish a direct connection to either an external procedure agent or a Heterogeneous Services agent, for example: "SVRMGR> CONNECT SCOTT/TIGER@NETWORK_ALIAS". This type of connection is not allowed.
column8: From Oracle doc: When executing the CONNECT statement, make sure your database link or network alias is not pointing to a Heterogeneous Option agent or an external procedure agent.

column6: agent control utility: illegal or badly formed command
column7: The user has issued an unrecognized or syntactically incorrect command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to documentation and correct the syntax of the command.

column6: agent control utility: unable to access parameter file
column7: The agent control utility was unable to access its parameter file. This could be because it could not find its ADMIN directory or because permissions on directory were not correctly set.
column8: From Oracle doc: The agent control utility puts its parameter file in either the directory pointed to by the environment variable AGTCTL_ADMIN or in the directory pointed to by the environment variable TNS_ADMIN. Make sure that at least one of these environment variables is set and that it points to a directory that the agent has access to.

column6: agent control utility: agent SID not set
column7: The agent needs to know the value of the AGENT_SID parameter before it can process any commands. If it does not have a value for AGENT_SID then all commands will fail.
column8: From Oracle doc: Issue the command SET AGENT_SID value and then retry the command that failed.

column6: agent control utility: command terminated with error
column7: An error occurred during the processing of the command. There could be several causes. A SET or an UNSET command could have been issued after the agent was started. This is illegal. The user may have attempted to start two agents with the same SID value or the user could have attempted to shut down an agent that is no longer running.
column8: From Oracle doc: If the user wishes to issue a SET or an UNSET command, he should make sure the agent is shut down first by issuing the SHUTDOWN command.

column6: agent control utility: invalid parameter name
column7: The user tried to set or unset an invalid agent parameter.
column8: From Oracle doc: Refer to documentation and correct the parameter name.

column6: invalid [no]MINIMIZE option
column7: User did not type this alter table table_name MINIMIZE RECORDS_PER_BLOCK or alter table table_name NOMINIMIZE RECORDS_PER_BLOCK.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-enter correct SQL command.

column6: statement not permitted on tables containing bitmap indexes
column7: Table has bitmap indexes and user is minimizing or nominalizing RECORDS_PER_BLOCK.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop all bitmap indexes before changing RECORDS_PER_BLOCK.

column6: statement not permitted on empty tables
column7: Table is empty and statement does not work on empty tables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try statement after loading your data.

column6: bitmap indexes cannot be reversed
column7: An attempt was made to create reverse bitmap index. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: bitmap index is corrupted - see trace file for diagnostics
column7: Validate Index detected bitmap corruption in its argument index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop this bitmap index and create a new one.

column6: Primary index on an IOT cannot be rebuilt
column7: An attempt was made to issue alter index rebuild on IOT-TOP.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use Alter table MOVE to reorganize the table(IOT).

column6: Primary index on IOTs can not be marked unusable
column7: An attempt was made to mark IOT-TOP unusable through ALTER INDEX.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the option UNUSABLE.

column6: overflow segment attributes cannot be specified
column7: During ALTER MOVE ONLINE of a index-organized table, the user attempted to enter one or more of the following options: OVERFLOW, PCTTHRESHOLD,INCLUDING.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the illegal option(s).

column6: tables must both be index-organized
column7: An attempt was made to exchange a non-IOT table/partition with a partition/table respectively.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that non-partitioned and partitioned tables are both index-organized.

column6: table and partition not overflow compatible
column7: If one of the tables (partitioned/non-partitioned) has overflow data segment and the other one does not.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that non-partitioned and partitioned tables both have overflow data segment or neither one does.

column6: Alter table add overflow syntax error
column7: Syntax error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax.

column6: incomplete attribute specification
column7: The attribute specification is not done for all partitions.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the storage attributes either for ALL partitions or NONE.

column6: This operation is supported only for Index-Organized tables
column7: Attempt to perform some IOT specific operation on a non-IOT. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: COMPRESS must be specified at object level first
column7: An attempt was made to specify COMPRESS at the partition level without first specifying it at the table level.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify COMPRESS at the table level. Use ALTER TABLE xxx MODIFY DEFAULT ATTRIBUTES COMPRESS ...

column6: Partitioned Index-Organized table may not be MOVEd as a whole
column7: An attempt was made to MOVE a partitioned index-organized table as a whole. This is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not try to MOVE a partitioned index-organized table as a whole.

column6: Object already has COMPRESS clause specified
column7: An attempt was made to specify COMPRESS for an index-organized table/index which already has a compression clause. This attribute can only be specified at creation time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify COMPRESS for an index-organized table/index which already has a compression clause.

column6: IOT index and overflow segments must share the same LOGGING attribute
column7: An attempt was made to specify LOGGING for one segment and NOLOGGING for the other segment.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the same attribute value for both segments.

column6: Logging/Nologging attribute can not be specified in the statement ALTER TABLE ADD OVERFLOW
column7: An attempt was made to specify LOGGING for an ALTER TABLE ADD OVERFLOW statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not specify LOGGING in this context.

column6: Invalid index specifed in call to dbms_sql.bind_array
column7: An invalid index was specified in a call to BIND_ARRAY of DBMS_SQL. The index may have been null or of an improper value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the index value by modifying your PL/SQL program and try the BIND_ARRAY call again.

column6: Index1 is greater than Index2 in call to dbms_sql.bind_array
column7: The value of index1 was greater than the value for index2 in the call to BIND_ARRAY. This is illegal since the elements of the table that will be bound are those with indexes greater than or equal to index1 and less than or equal to index2.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value of the two indexes and try the call to again BIND_ARRAY.

column6: collection does not contain elements at index locations in call to dbms_sql.bind_array
column7: The bound table does not contain elements at both index locations in call to BIND_ARRAY of DBMS_SQL. This is illegal. Both index locations must contain elements. In other words tab.exists(index1) and tab.exists(index2) must both return true.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either modify the two indexes or the contents of the table and try the call again.

column6: Invalid count argument passed to procedure dbms_sql.define_array
column7: The count argument specified in the call to procedure DEFINE_ARRAY of package DBMS_SQL had an invalid value. Invalid values are negative numbers and nulls. The argument must be a positive integer.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct your PL/SQL program so that only valid arguments are passed to DEFINE_ARRAY and try again.

column6: Invalid lower_bound argument passed to procedure dbms_sql.define_array
column7: The LOWER_BOUND argument specified in the call to procedure DEFINE_ARRAY had an invalid value. Legal values are all integers (both positive and negative) including zero. The null value is illegal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct your PL/SQL program so that only valid arguments are passed to DEFINE_ARRAY and try again.

column6: Cursor contains both bind and define arrays which is not permissible
column7: Both DEFINE_ARRAY and BIND_ARRAY have been called on this cursor. This is illegal. It is not possible for a cursor to both contain array binds and array defines. The semantics of this setting are nonsensical. Array defines are used to move data from select queries into PL/SQL tables and array binds to bind PL/SQL tables to non-select queries.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify your PL/SQL program to only perform calls to one of the two functions depending on the kind of cursor at hand.

column6: Cursor contains both regular and array defines which is illegal
column7: Both DEFINE_ARRAY and DEFINE_COLUMN have been called on this cursor. This is illegal. It is not possible for a cursor to both contain regular and array defines. The semantics of this setting are nonsensical. Array defines are used to move data from select queries into PL/SQL tables and regular defines to move data from select queries into PL/SQL variables.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify your PL/SQL program to only perform calls to one of the two functions depending on the situation at hand.

column6: ORACLE error, tablespace point-in-time recovery
column7: Another Oracle error occurred in the DBMS_PITR package.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the text of the error message for a description of the error.

column6: wrong DBMS_PITR package function/procedure order
column7: The DBMS_PITR package function/procedure was called in an incorrect order.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart tablespace point-in-time recovery with a correct procedure.

column6: database is not open clone
column7: The database was not opened as a clone database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mount the database clone and open the database.

column6: user does not login as SYS
column7: The user did not log in as SYS to perform tablespace point-in-time recovery in a clone database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Log in as SYS and restart tablespace point-in-time recovery.

column6: tablespace '%s' does not exist
column7: The selected tablespace does not exist in the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the list of tablespaces in V$TABLESPACE and select a valid tablespace.

column6: cannot point-in-time recover tablespace '%s'
column7: An attempt was made to ALTER the tablespace to be read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if the tablespace is SYSTEM or with online rollback segment.

column6: datafile %s is not online
column7: The selected datafile was not online.
column8: From Oracle doc: Bring the datafile online and rename it if necessary.

column6: datafile %s error, %s
column7: The datafile is not ready for tablespace point-in-time recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the correct tablespace point-in-time recovery procedure.

column6: view TS_PITR_CHECK failure
column7: Some objects which crossed the boundary of the recovery set were not allowed in the tablespace point-in-time recovery.
column8: From Oracle doc: Query TS_PITR_CHECK and resolve the boundary crossing objects.

column6: export dump file was generated by different version of DBMS_PITR package
column7: The version of DBMS_PITR is different from the version of the cloned database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Load the version of DBMS_PITR which matches the version of the cloned database.

column6: database is not open, or opened as a clone
column7: Either the database was not open, or an attempt was made to open it as a cloned database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Open the production database instead.

column6: export dump file was not generated by this database, %s does not match
column7: The export dump files were imported to an incorrect database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Open the correct production database and try the import again.

column6: database not compatible, %s %s
column7: A point-in-time tablespace was chosen to perform the recovery, but the current database is not compatible with the database that was used to create the point-in-time tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a point-in-time and retry the operation.

column6: tablespace '%s' cannot be imported twice
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your database administrator.

column6: tablespace '%s' is not OFFLINE FOR RECOVER nor READ ONLY
column7: Tablespace clean SCN is either 0 or invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: ALTER the tablespace OFFLINE FOR RECOVER.

column6: tablespace '%s' has been recreated
column7: An attempt was made to recover a tablespace to a point-in-time before it was re-created.
column8: From Oracle doc: Choose a different point in time for recovery.

column6: datafile %s been imported twice
column7: This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact your database administrator.

column6: datafile %s does not exist
column7: The specified datafile could not be found in the production database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Copy the datafile from the clone database.

column6: datafile %s is online
column7: The datafile is online.
column8: From Oracle doc: Take the datafile offline.

column6: datafile %s is not correct
column7: An incorrect datafile was copied to the production database. The datafile information in the export dump file differs with the information in the datafile in the production database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Copy the datafile from the clone database to the production database.

column6: datafile header error
column7: An error occurred during reading datafile header.
column8: From Oracle doc: Copy the correct datafile from the clone database to the production database, then retry the operation.

column6: too many datafiles added since the point-in-time
column7: Too many datafiles were added to the recovery set since the point-in-time recovery. It is assumed that no more than 100 datafiles were added since the point-in-time.
column8: From Oracle doc: Divide the recovery set into smaller subsets and retry.

column6: SCN %s size too long -- maximum size 58 bytes/characters
column7: Too many characters in specifying the SCN string
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all unnecessary characters. Only 15 characters are required for both the hex and decimal representation of the 48 bit SCN.

column6: SET COMPATIBILITY command cannot be used for releases before 8.0.0
column7: The rolling release feature was first implemented in 8.0.3.
column8: From Oracle doc: Try 8.0.3 or later.

column6: SET COMPATIBILITY release %s format is wrong
column7: It should be of the form 8.x.x.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct format.

column6: SET COMPATIBILITY release number mismatches compatibility release number
column7: In 8.0.3, it should be the same as compatibility release number.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the same as the COMPATIBLE initialization parameter. Note that this cannot be a release number less than 8.0.0.

column6: specified SET COMPATIBILITY release number reduced to %s.%s.%s.%s.%s
column7: One or more instances had a lower release number.
column8: From Oracle doc: To roll the release to the specified number, all instances will need to migrate to the same release number or higher.

column6: unsupported client compatibility mode used when talking to the server
column7: The client compatibility mode is higher than the version of the server.
column8: From Oracle doc: Using SET COMPATIBILITY command, specify the same release number as the server.

column6: tablespace '%s' is not read only
column7: The tablespace is not read only.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make the tablespace read only and retry the operation.

column6: Internal error [%s] [%s] from DBMS_PLUGTS
column7: Internal error from package DBMS_PLUGTS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Call Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Failed to validate the file header of datafile %s
column7: The system failed to validate the file header of the referred datafile. The datafile maybe missing. The content in the datafile header may be inconsistent with that in the control file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the referred datafile exists. Make sure it is in a valid state.

column6: datafile %s is in an undesired state (%s, %s)
column7: The referred datafile is not in a state ready for tablespace copy operation. For example, the datafile may be offline. The datafile needs to be ONLINE, and either READ ONLY or READ WRITE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Put the datafile into the desired state.

column6: tablespace block size %s does not match database block size %s
column7: The block size of the tablespace to be plugged in does not match the block size of the database. Plugging a tablespace into a database with a different block size is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a different way to move data.

column6: export file appears to be corrupted: [%s] [%s] [%s]
column7: This is caused either by a corrupted export file or by an Oracle internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the export file used for transportable tablespace is not corrupted. If the error still occurs, call Oracle Customer Support.

column6: The transportable set is not self-contained
column7: The set of objects in the set of tablespaces selected are not self-contained.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consider using different export options, or removing some of the pointers that caused the violation, or selecting a different set of tablespaces.

column6: user %s does not exist in the database
column7: The referred user is one of the owners of data in the pluggable set. This user does not exist in the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consider either creating the user in the database or map the user to a different user via FROM_USER and TO_USER import options.

column6: user %s (mapped from user %s) does not exist in the database
column7: The referred user is one of the owners of data in the pluggable set. This user does not exist in the database.
column8: From Oracle doc: Consider either creating the user or map the original user to a different user.

column6: Owner validation failed - failed to match owner '%s'
column7:
The system failed to match the referenced owner. There are two cases in which this may occur:

This user owns data in the transportable set, but this user is not specified in the TTS_OWNERS list of the import command line option, assuming that TTS_OWNERS is specified. 

This user is specified in the TTS_OWNER list, but this user does not own any data in the transportable set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the import with a different OWNER list.

column6: can not plug a tablespace into a database using a different character set
column7: Oracle does not support plugging a tablespace into a database using a different character set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use import/export or unload/load to move data instead.

column6: invalid tablespace list
column7: The tablespace list supplied to DBMS_TTS.TRANSPORT_SET_CHECK. PL/SQL routine is in an incorrect format.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check PL/SQL User's Guide and Reference and use the correct format.

column6: Tablespace name validation failed - failed to match tablespace '%s'
column7:
The system failed to match the referenced tablespace. There are two case in which this may happen:

This tablespace is in the transportable set, but it is not specified in the TABLESPACES list of the import command line option, assuming that TABLESPACES is specified. 

This tablespace is in the TABLESPACES list, but it is not in the transportable set.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation with the correct TABLESPACES list.

column6: You must specify the datafiles to be plugged in
column7: The datafiles to be plugged in are not specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the datafiles via the import DATAFILES command line option.

column6: tablespace '%s' already exists
column7: An attempt was made to plug-in a tablespace which already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the offending tablespace if possible. Otherwise use a different method (for example, import/export) to move data.

column6: server version %s incompatible with package %s version %s
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: can not transport system or temporary tablespace '%s'
column7: The referenced tablespace is either the system tablespace or a temporary tablespace.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not include this tablespace in the transportable set.

column6: NULL or invalid %s argument specified
column7: The named argument was either invalid or specified as a NULL.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify non-null, valid arguments.

column6: MAX_ACTIVE_SESS_TARGET_P1 and PARALLEL_DEGREE_LIMIT_P1 can be specified only for directives that refer to consumer groups
column7: The above parameters were specified as an argument to procedure CREATE_PLAN_DIRECTIVE or UPDATE_PLAN_DIRECTIVE of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER where the GROUP_OR_SUBPLAN argument is a resource plan.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify these parameters only for consumer group directives.

column6: object %s already exists
column7: The name specified as argument to procedure CREATE_PLAN, CREATE_CONSUMER_GROUP of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER was already in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an unused name.

column6: resource plan %s does not exist
column7: An invalid plan name was specified as an argument to procedure UPDATE_PLAN of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an existing plan name.

column6: invalid method name %s specified for resource plan %s
column7: An invalid method was specified as an argument to procedure CREATE_PLAN or UPDATE_PLAN of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid method name.

column6: retry operation. Too much concurrent activity
column7: An attempt was made to revoke the switch consumer group privilege from a user for his/her initial consumer group but someone is modifying the user in another session.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the operation later.

column6: percentage %s is outside valid range of 0 to 100
column7: An invalid percentage value was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a percentage value between 0 and 100 inclusive.

column6: plan directive %s, %s does not exist
column7: A non-existent plan directive was specified for procedure UPDATE_PLAN_DIRECTIVE of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an existing plan directive for update.

column6: plan directive %s, %s is mandatory and cannot be modified or deleted
column7: An attempt was made to modify a mandatory plan directive.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to modify mandatory plan directives because they are required by the Resource Manager and cannot be modified.

column6: plan directive %s, %s already exists
column7: An attempt was made to create a plan directive that already exists.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the create operation using different values.

column6: NULL or invalid GROUP_OR_SUBPLAN argument specified
column7: A NULL or invalid GROUP_OR_SUBPLAN was specified as an argument to procedure CREATE_PLAN_DIRECTIVE or UPDATE_PLAN_DIRECTIVE of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-NULL, valid argument.

column6: invalid CONSUMER_GROUP argument specified
column7: An invalid consumer group name was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a non-NULL, valid consumer group name.

column6: object %s does not exist
column7: A non-existent object name was specified as an argument to procedure CREATE_PLAN_DIRECTIVE of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid plan or consumer group name.

column6: consumer group %s does not exist
column7: An non-existent consumer group was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify an existing consumer group.

column6: invalid method name %s specified for consumer group %s
column7: An invalid method name was specified as an argument to procedure CREATE_CONSUMER_GROUP or UPDATE_CONSUMER_GROUP of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid method name.

column6: pending area is already active
column7: An attempt was made to activate a pending area that is already active.
column8: From Oracle doc: Wait until the pending area is no longer active; then, retry the operation.

column6: pending area is not active
column7: An attempt was made to make changes without creating a pending area.
column8: From Oracle doc: Invoke procedure CREATE_PENDING_AREA before making any changes.

column6: identifier %s is too long; it must be less than %s characters
column7: An attempt was made to specify an identifier that is more than 30 characters long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use an identifier that is 30 characters or less in length.

column6: resource manager is not on
column7: An attempt was made to execute an operation that cannot be executed with the resource manager being off.
column8: From Oracle doc: Turn on the resource manager and try again.

column6: resource plan %s in top-plan %s has no plan directives
column7: A plan was created in the pending area that is an orphan or standalone.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create plan directives if needed. Otherwise, delete the plan.

column6: sum of percentages %s for level %s, plan %s exceeds %s
column7: The sum of percentages for the specified plan, level exceeds 100.
column8: From Oracle doc: Alter the percentages for the level so that they sum to 100.

column6: number of consumer groups %s in top-plan %s exceeds %s
column7: The number of consumer groups in the specified top-plan is more than 32.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the top-plan to have no more than 32 consumer groups.

column6: consumer group %s is not part of top-plan %s
column7: OTHER_GROUPS was not included as part of the specified top-plan. Each top plan must include the built-in consumer group OTHER_GROUPS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create a plan directive with the argument GROUP_OR_SUBPLAN being OTHER_GROUPS somewhere in the top-plan.

column6: resource plan %s is involved in a loop in top-plan %s
column7: A loop was discovered while validating a top-plan.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the plans that have the specified plan as a GROUP_OR_SUBPLAN, and remove the plan directive that causes the loop.

column6: resource plan %s is currently active and cannot be deleted
column7: An attempt was made to delete an active plan in the pending area. No changes can be made to active plans.
column8: From Oracle doc: Delete the plan when it is not in use.

column6: plan/consumer_group %s referred to by another plan and cannot be deleted
column7: An attempt was made to delete a plan or consumer group that is referred to by another plan.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove all plan directives that have the plan or consumer group as GROUP_OR_SUBPLAN; then delete the plan or consumer group.

column6: validation of pending area failed
column7: Invalid changes were attempted in the pending area.
column8: From Oracle doc: See documentation and the error messages that follow this one.

column6: all leaves of top-plan %s must be consumer groups
column7: An attempt was made to create or modify the specified top-plan but it has some plans as leaves.
column8: From Oracle doc: To identify which plans and/or plan directives need to be modified, look at all plans that have no plan directives. Then, alter the top-plan so that all its leaves are consumer groups.

column6: number of children for plan %s exceeds %s
column7: An attempt was made to create or modify the specified plan, but the plan has more than 32 children.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the specified plan points to no more than 32 distinct nodes.

column6: cannot create plan directive from %s to %s
column7: An attempt was made to create a plan directive from a plan to itself.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the arguments PLAN and GROUP_OR_SUBPLAN to procedure CREATE_PLAN_DIRECTIVE of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER are different.

column6: plan or consumer group %s is mandatory and cannot be deleted or modified
column7: An attempt was made to delete or modify the specified mandatory plan or consumer group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to delete or modify mandatory plans and consumer groups.

column6: no top-plans found in the pending area
column7: The VALIDATE_PENDING_AREA procedure found that either the intended top-plan(s) are involved in a loop or there are no top-plans.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check all edges going from a subplan to the intended top-plan. Make sure the top plan does not have any plan referring to it.

column6: plan/consumer_group %s is part of more than one top-plan
column7: An attempt was made to delete a subtree that includes a plan or consumer group that is part of more than one top-plan as part of procedure DELETE_PLAN_CASCADE or package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER. Such a plan or consumer group cannot be deleted.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the ancestors of the plan or consumer group and make sure it is only part of the top-plan that includes the subtree being deleted.

column6: too many errors during validation
column7: The number of errors detected during validation is too high.
column8: From Oracle doc: Perform the necessary actions to remove some errors, and retry validation.

column6: some resource plans are not part of any top-plan
column7: An attempt was made to create or modify some plans in the pending area that are not part of any top-plan.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove these plans are try validation again.

column6: %s and %s must be mandatory to create a mandatory plan directive
column7: An attempt was made to create a mandatory plan directive where either PLAN or GROUP_OR_SUBPLAN or both were not mandatory.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-create these objects as mandatory and then create the plan directive.

column6: user %s does not exist or is not logged on
column7: An invalid user name was specified as argument to procedure SET_INITIAL_CONSUMER_GROUP of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER or SWITCH_CONSUMER_GROUP_FOR_USER of package DBMS_SYSTEM or the specified user was not logged on.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid user name.

column6: session id %s and serial# %s do not exist
column7: Invalid session id and serial# were specified as arguments to procedure SWITCH_CONSUMER_GROUP_FOR_SESS of package DBMS_SYSTEM.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify valid values from the view V$SESSION.

column6: cannot set the initial consumer group to %s
column7: An attempt was made to set the initial consumer group of a user to OTHER_GROUPS.
column8: From Oracle doc: OTHER_GROUPS is for the resource manager's internal use. Specify another consumer group.

column6: cannot switch group to %s
column7: An attempt was made to switch the consumer group of a user or a session to OTHER_GROUPS.
column8: From Oracle doc: OTHER_GROUPS is for the resource manager's internal use. Specify another consumer group.

column6: cannot grant/revoke switch privilege for %s
column7: An attempt was made to grant or revoke the privilege to switch to OTHER_GROUPS.
column8: From Oracle doc: OTHER_GROUPS is for the resource manager's internal use. Specify another consumer group.

column6: invalid privilege name specified
column7: An invalid privilege name was specified as an argument to procedure GRANT_SYSTEM_PRIVILEGE or REVOKE_SYSTEM_PRIVILEGE of package DBMS_RESOURCE_MANAGER_PRIVS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid privilege name.

column6: user %s does not have privilege to switch to consumer group %s
column7: An attempt was made to set the initial consumer group of the specified user but the user does not have the privilege to switch to that group.
column8: From Oracle doc: Grant the privilege to switch to the consumer group to the user and then set the initial group.

column6: data cartridge error%s
column7: An error has occurred in a data cartridge external procedure. This message will be followed by a second message giving more details about the data cartridge error.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the Oracle8i Data Cartridge Developer's Guide for an explanation of the second error message.

column6: NAMED keyword is invalid in CREATE JAVA CLASS
column7: A NAMED keyword was specified in the CREATE JAVA CLASS statement. NAMED keywords are valid only in CREATE JAVA SOURCE or RESOURCE statements.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the NAMED keyword from the CREATE JAVA CLASS statement.

column6: invalid or missing Java source, class, or resource name
column7: The required name for a Java source, class, or resource was invalid or missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid name.

column6: NAMED keyword required in CREATE JAVA RESOURCE
column7: The name for a Java resource was not specified. The name must be specified with the NAMED keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid name with the NAMED keyword.

column6: SCHEMA keyword not valid with NAMED keyword
column7: SCHEMA and NAMED keywords were used together in the same CREATE JAVA command, but only one may be used in a CREATE JAVA command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove either the NAMED or the SCHEMA keyword.

column6: invalid or missing schema name
column7: The required schema name was invalid or missing.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a valid schema name.

column6: AS keyword is invalid in CREATE JAVA CLASS or RESOURCE
column7: The AS keyword was used in CREATE JAVA CLASS or RESOURCE. The AS keyword is valid only in CREATE JAVA SOURCE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the USING keyword in CREATE JAVA CLASS or RESOURCE.

column6: invalid query derived from USING clause
column7: The USING clause did not form a valid query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the USING clause.

column6: query derived from USING clause found zero or many rows
column7: The USING clause defined a query that either did not return any values, or returned more than one value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the USING clause.

column6: query derived from USING clause did not select a value of type %s
column7: The USING clause did not form a query that selects a value of the type specified by the term following the USING keyword.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the USING clause.

column6: incorrectly formed Java binary class definition
column7: An attempt was made to create a Java class using data expected to be in binary (Java .class) format. The data was found not to be in this format, or to be incorrectly formed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the definition data.

column6: name, %s.%s, already used by an existing object
column7: A CREATE JAVA command attempted to create a source, class, or resource object with a name that is already in use.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the existing object that is using the desired name, or use a different name for the new object.

column6: could not resolve Java class
column7: A CREATE AND RESOLVE NOFORCE JAVA CLASS command specified definition data that could not be resolved, or resolution failed for some referenced class.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the NOFORCE option or remove impediments to resolution.

column6: incorrectly formed name resolver specification
column7: A name resolver was not specified in the required form: (( name_pattern , schema_name) ...).
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the specification.

column6: referenced class name too long
column7: An attempt was made to import a .class file containing a class name of length greater than number. The .class file could not be imported because the referenced class name was too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Shorten the referenced class name in the .class file.

column6: class name contains illegal character
column7: An attempt was made to import a .class file containing a character that cannot be converted to the server character set. The .class file could not be imported because of the illegal character.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the illegal character in the .class file.

column6: exit called from Java code with status %s
column7: Java code included a call to java.lang.Runtime.exitInternal.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not include this call unless non-local exit is desired.

column6: Aurora assertion failure: %s
column7: An internal error occurred in the Aurora module.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: recursive resolution failed for a referenced class
column7: An attempt to resolve a referenced class failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Review the errors for referenced classes and complete the necessary actions to correct them.

column6: name %s resolved to an object in schema %s that is not a Java class
column7: A referenced name was resolved to an object that is not a Java class.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust name resolver or add missing Java class.

column6: name %s resolved via a synonym in schema %s to a class with a different name
column7: A referenced name was resolved to a synonym, which translated to a class whose name does not match the referenced name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust name resolver or add missing Java class.

column6: name %s resolved to a class in schema %s that could not be accessed
column7: An attempt to access a referenced class failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust authorizations or name resolution.

column6: referenced name %s could not be found
column7: Name resolution failed to find an object with the indicated name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust name resolver or add missing Java class.

column6: authorization error for referenced name %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to resolve a class that is not authorized to use the indicated referenced class.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust authorizations or name resolution.

column6: authorization error for unknown referenced name
column7: An attempt was made to resolve a class that is not authorized to use a referenced class. The name of the referenced class could not be determined.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust authorizations or name resolution.

column6: wrong types of arguments in call to '%s'
column7: A method was called with argument(s) of incompatible type(s).
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust caller.

column6: referenced name is too long: '%s'
column7: An attempt was made to create a class that references a name longer than 4000 characters. The class could not be created because the name is too long.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust the definition.

column6: created Java class %s"%s"
column7: An informational message, not an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: created Java source %s"%s"
column7: An informational message, not an error.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: invalid Java call in trigger %s
column7: The Java method specified in trigger does not exist or cannot be called as used.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust trigger definition.

column6: invalid function or method call %s in trigger %s
column7: The function or method specified in Java trigger call expression could not be resolved.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust trigger definition.

column6: could not create shortened name for %s
column7: Insert into shortened name translation table failed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Retry the insert.

column6: no method %s in class %s
column7: An attempt was made to execute a non-existent method in a Java class.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust the call or create the specified method.

column6: Java call terminated by uncaught Java exception: %s
column7: A Java exception or error was signaled and could not be resolved by the Java code.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify Java code, if this behavior is not intended.

column6: attempt to overwrite class or resource %s while defining or compiling %s.%s
column7: A class or resource defined by a SQLJ source conflicted with an existing object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove existing object, or modify SQLJ source.

column6: referenced object %s.%s could not be resolved
column7: Name resolution determined that the indicated object is referenced but could not be resolved.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct name resolver or address resolution problems in the referenced class, or correct compilation problems in its source.

column6: source requires recompilation
column7: The reason the current class object was invalid is recorded with the source object from which it was compiled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Inspect errors in the source object and take the necessary corrective actions.

column6: badly formed source: %s
column7: An attempt was made to create a Java source object with text that could not be parsed adequately to determine the class(es) defined by it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct errors in source.

column6: class or resource cannot be created or dropped directly
column7: An attempt was made to create or drop a Java class or resource that is known to result from compilation of an existing Java source object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Act on the class or resource by acting on the source, or change the source so that it no longer defines the class or resource.

column6: Java not installed
column7: An attempt was made to use a Java command when Java is not installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Install Java, or do not use the command.

column6: Java system classes already installed
column7: An attempt was made to use the CREATE JAVA SYSTEM command in a database where the Java system classes already are installed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use CREATE OR REPLACE JAVA SYSTEM.

column6: class %s does not exist
column7: Java method execution failed to find a class with the indicated name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the name or add the missing Java class.

column6: class %s.%s could not be resolved
column7: An attempt was made to execute a method in a Java class that had not been previously and cannot now be compiled or resolved successfully.
column8: From Oracle doc: Adjust the call or make the class resolvable.

column6: class %s already defined by source %s
column7: An attempt was made to create a Java source object that would define a class that is already defined by a different Java source object.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either drop the old source or modify the new source.

column6: Java command %s not yet implemented
column7: An attempt was made to use a Java command that is not yet implemented.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use the command.

column6: invalid type
column7: The type argument in a call to a Java export or import command did not have a recognized value.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value.

column6: badly formed class: %s
column7: An attempt was made to create a Java class object with bytecodes that were rejected by the Java verifier.
column8: From Oracle doc: It is possible that an attempt was made to create the Java class from a damaged class file, in which case the CREATE should be reattempted with a correct class file. It is also possible that the message is the result of using "-" in the resolver so that the verifier could not check the correctness of some code. In that case, the class needs to be created with a resolver.

column6: badly formed resource: %s
column7: An attempt was made to create a Java resource object with data that was rejected by the Java verifier.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the data.

column6: Java system class not available: %s
column7: An attempt was made to use a command that requires a Java system class that was not yet present or was invalid.
column8: From Oracle doc: Load the system classes, or do not use the command.

column6: Java system class reported: %s
column7: A command that uses a Java system class was aborted due to an error reported by the Java system class.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the error that was reported.

column6: class %s.%s has changed, Java session state cleared
column7: A class in use by the current session was redefined or dropped, invalidating the current Java session state and requiring that it be cleared.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: Java session state cleared
column7: The Java state in the current session became inconsistent and was cleared.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: could not convert %s to Unicode
column7: A string in the database character set could not be converted to Unicode, as required for use by Java.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the string.

column6: verification warning: %s
column7: An attempt was made to create a Java class object with bytecodes that caused the Java verifier to issue a warning.
column8: From Oracle doc: It is possible that the Java class was created from a damaged class file, in which case the CREATE should be reattempted with a correct class file. It is also possible that the message is the result of using "-" in the resolver so that the verifier could not check the correctness of some code. In that case, the class needs to be created with a resolver.

column6: class in use: %s.%s
column7: An attempt was made to modify a Java class that is in use in the current call.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the code in use in this call.

column6: unhandled Java out of memory condition
column7: The session encountered an out of memory condition in Java from which it could not recover. Java session state was cleared.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: Java source, class or resource is not allowed here
column7: A Java source, class, or resource was specified in an inappropriate place in a statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the name is correct or remove it.

column6: unable to connect to Cluster Manager
column7: Connect to the Cluster Manager (CM) failed or timed out.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the CM was started. If the CM was not started, start it and then retry the database startup. If the CM died or is not responding, check the Oracle and CM trace files for errors.

column6: error occurred in Cluster Group Service operation
column7: An unexpected error occurred while performing a CGS operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the LMON process is still active. Also, check the Oracle LMON trace files for errors.

column6: error occurred in DLM operation
column7: An unexpected error occurred while performing a DLM operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check Oracle trace files for errors.

column6: cannot specify ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT in 8.1.5 or earlier release
column7: The ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT parameter was specified when one of the instances in the cluster was running Oracle 8.1.5 or an earlier release.
column8: From Oracle doc: Restart the instance without specifying the ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT parameter. Or, upgrade all instances to Oracle 8.1.6 or later release and then specify the parameter.

column6: ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT is %s but needs to be %s to be compatible
column7: The value of the ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT parameter must be the same in all Oracle Parallel Server instances.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your initialization parameter files in all instances and ensure that the ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT parameter has the same value. Then restart the instance.

column6: incorrect value %s for parameter ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT
column7: The ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT parameter must be set to 1 in a two node active/standby parallel server configuration or to a value that is greater than or equal to the total number of instances if a standby instance is not needed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your initialization parameter files and correct the value of the ACTIVE_INSTANCE_COUNT parameter. If you are configuring a two node active/standby parallel server, set this value to 1. Otherwise, do not specify any value for the parameter.

column6: invalid name for operator
column7: The name specified for the operator is incorrect.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a correct name for the operator.

column6: missing RETURN keyword
column7: The RETURN keyword has not been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the RETURN keyword or check the SQL statement.

column6: missing CONTEXT keyword
column7: The CONTEXT keyword has not been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the CONTEXT keyword or check the SQL statement.

column6: missing ANCILLARY keyword
column7: The ANCILLARY keyword has not been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the ANCILLARY keyword or check the SQL statement.

column6: missing DATA keyword
column7: The DATA keyword has not been specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the DATA keyword or check the SQL statement.

column6: missing COLUMN keyword
column7: Keyword COLUMN is expected.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either specify the COLUMN keyword or specify another option.

column6: specified binding does not exist
column7: The operator binding which has been specified does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the operator binding that has been specified does exist.

column6: specified operator does not exist
column7: The operator which has been specified does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the operator that has been specified does exist.

column6: specified primary operator binding does not exist
column7: The specified binding for the primary operator does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Ensure that the specified binding for the primary operator exists.

column6: cannot drop an operator with dependent objects
column7: The operator which is being dropped has some dependent objects.
column8: From Oracle doc: Either drop the dependent objects first and then issue the DROP OPERATOR command or specify the FORCE option with DROP OPERATOR.

column6: inadequate operator privileges
column7: The user does not have the appropriate privileges to perform the specified operation on the operator.
column8: From Oracle doc: Grant the appropriate privileges to the user and then reissue the statement.

column6: missing STATISTICS keyword
column7: This is not a valid option with the ASSOCIATE command.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify STATISTICS keyword after the ASSOCIATE command.

column6: incorrect object name specified
column7: The specified name is not a valid name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct name of the object with for which an association needs to be defined.

column6: non-supported object type with associate statement
