column7: There is no space to write to the file. Its size is at the maximum limit.
column8: From Oracle doc: If you can, increase the limit.

column6: OCIFileOpen: Cannot create the file or cannot open in the requested mode
column7: The create flag was specified in OCIFileOpen such that the file was to be created. But unable to do so. Or the file already exists and the permissions on it does not allow the file to be opened in the requested open mode.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check whether the user has permissions to create the specified file or if the file exists whether the permissions on it allow the requested open mode.

column6: Unable to access the file
column7: The function was unable to access the existing the file.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check if the user has the required permissions on the file.

column6: A system error occurred during the OCIFile function call
column7: A system error occurred while executing the OCIFile function.
column8: From Oracle doc: Investigate and solve the system error.

column6: The OCIFile context is not initialzed
column7: The function OCIFileInit need to be called before calling any other OCIFile function to initialize the OCIFile context.
column8: From Oracle doc: Call the function OCIFileInit need to be called before calling any other OCIFile function.

column6: The thread safety initialization failed
column7: The call to SlgInit failed in OCIFileInit.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: invalid type given for an argument
column7: There is an argument with an invalid type in the argument list.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the correct type wrapper for the argument.

column6: invalid format code used in the format %s
column7: There is an invalid format code in the format string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the invalid format code with a valid one.

column6: invalid flag used in a format specification
column7: There is an invalid flag in a format specification.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the invalid flag with a valid one.

column6: duplicate flag used in a format specification
column7: There is a duplicate flag in a format specification.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the duplicate flag.

column6: invalid argument index used in a format code
column7: Zero or negative argument index or index not following (.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the invalid argument index with a valid one.

column6: argument index is too large
column7: An argument index exceeds actual number of arguments supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix format string or pass additional arguments.

column6: integer in argument index is not immediately followed by )
column7: Missing closing parenthesis in argument index.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the format specification.

column6: invalid precision specifier
column7: Period in format specification not followed by valid format.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the invalid precision specifier with a valid one.

column6: invalid field width specifier
column7: Invalid field width supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Replace the invalid field width with a valid one.

column6: argument type not compatible with a format code
column7: Bad argument type given for a format code.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make format and arguments be compatible.

column6: output too large to fit in the buffer
column7: The buffer is not large enough to hold the entire output string.
column8: From Oracle doc: Fix the buffer size and length passed in.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: missing argument list
column7: No argument list supplied.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the argument list to have at least OCIFormatEnd in it.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: reserved for future use
column7: This message is reserved for future use.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action required.

column6: Wrong NLS item was passed into OCINlsGetInfo()
column7: The item is not supported NLS item.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the item number passed to OCINlsGetInfo().

column6: Unable to load NLS data object
column7: It may be caused by invalid NLS environment setting.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check your NLS environment setting such as ORA_NLS33.

column6: NULL pointer to OCIMsgh was passed to OCIMsg function
column7: The NULL pointer was passed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the value of the OCIMsgh pointer.

column6: Cannot open mesage file
column7: The message may not exist in your system.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the message for the given product and facility.

column6: summary does not exist
column7: A non-existent summary name was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the summary name.

column6: container table already in use by other summary
column7: Another summary is already using this table as a container table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Select another table or snapshot as the container table for this summary.

column6: dimension does not exist
column7: The dimension named in a dimension DDL statement does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the dimension name.

column6: illegal dimension level name
column7: A level name in a dimension DDL statement did not conform to SQL identifier rules.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use a level name that begins with a letter, consists of only letters, digits, and underscores and contains no more than 30 characters.

column6: JOIN KEY clause references a level not in this hierarchy
column7: The level name specified with the REFERENCES portion of a JOIN KEY clause in a dimension DDL statement does not reference a level in the hierarchy that contains the JOIN KEY clause.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the level name.

column6: no child for specified JOIN KEY
column7: The level specified in the REFERENCES portion of a JOIN KEY clause in a dimension DDL statement does not have a child level.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the level name referenced in the JOIN KEY clause. If the referenced level is the first level in the hierarchy, you need not and must not specify a JOIN KEY clause.

column6: multiple JOIN KEY clauses specified for the same parent level
column7: More than one JOIN KEY clause was specified for a given parent level in a dimension hierarchy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Match up each JOIN KEY clause with the level it references in the hierarchy. Eliminate the redundant JOIN KEY clause.

column6: illegal dimension hierachy name
column7: An illegal dimension hierarchy name was specified in a dimension DDL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the name begins with a letter, contains only letters, digits and underscore and contains no more than 30 characters. If you qualify the name with the owner name, make sure the owner name conforms with the requirements for an owner name on your system.

column6: illegal dimension attribute name
column7: An illegal dimension attribute name was specified in a dimension DDL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the name begins with a letter, contains only letters, digits and underscore and contains no more than 30 characters. If you qualify the name with the owner name, make sure the owner name conforms with the requirements for an owner name on your system.

column6: illegal dimension name
column7: An illegal dimension name was specified in a dimension DDL statement.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the name begins with a letter, contains only letters, digits and underscore and contains no more than 30 characters. If you qualify the name with the owner name, make sure the owner name conforms with the requirements for an owner name on your system.

column6: dropped level has references
column7: An attempt was made to drop a level using the default or RESTRICT option in a dimension while references to that level remain in the dimension. References can occur in hierarchies and attributes within the dimension.
column8: From Oracle doc: First remove any references to the level prior to dropping it, or specify the CASCADE option with the DROP LEVEL clause.

column6: referenced level is not defined in this dimension
column7: A reference to a level not defined within the dimension was found.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the level name.

column6: level name is not unique within this dimension
column7: Two or more levels were defined with the same name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the level names.

column6: number of child cols different from number of parent level cols
column7: The number of child columns specified in a JOIN KEY clause is not the same as the number of columns in the specified parent level.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the child columns and the columns in the definition of the referenced parent level and correct the discrepancy.

column6: circular dimension hierarchy
column7: A circularity was found the dimension hierarchy.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the hierarchy for a level name that occurs more than once.

column6: hierarchy name must be unique within a dimension
column7: The same name was used for more than one hierarchy in a dimension.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the hierarchy name.

column6: a table name is required to qualify the column specification
column7: A table name was omitted in a column specification where the column must be qualified by the table name.
column8: From Oracle doc: Qualify the column with the table name.

column6: ADD and DROP cannot both be specified
column7: One or more ADD clauses were found in the same ALTER DIMENSION statement with one or more DROP clauses.
column8: From Oracle doc: Separate your ADD operations into one ALTER DIMENSION statement and your DROP operations into another.

column6: specified dimension hierarchy does not exist
column7: A hierarchy name was encountered that is not defined within the dimension.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the hierarchy name.

column6: specified dimension attribute does not exist
column7: An attribute name was encountered that is not defined within the dimension.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the attribute name spelling.

column6: query rewrite does not currently support this expression
column7: A complex expression was specified that is not currently supported by query rewrite.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reduce the complexity of the expression.

column6: inconsistent numeric precision or %s length
column7: The SELECT expression was of a different numeric precision or string length than the corresponding container column. Therefore, query rewrite cannot guarantee results that are identical to the results obtained with the un-rewritten query.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the precision or string length difference, specify the WITH REDUCED PRECISION option, or disable the REWRITE option on the materialized view.

column6: expression not supported for query rewrite
column7: The select clause referenced UID, USER, ROWNUM, SYSDATE, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, MAXVALUE, a sequence number, a bind variable, correlation variable, a set result, a trigger return variable, a parallel table queue column, collection iterator, and so on.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the offending expression or disable the REWRITE option on the materialized view.

column6: Query rewrite not allowed on SYS relations
column7: A SYS relation was referenced in the select clause for a materialized view with query rewrite enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the reference to the SYS relation from the select clause or disable the REWRITE option on the materialized view.

column6: materialized view container does not exist
column7: A DROP TABLE command was issued directly against the materialized view container table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Use the DROP MATERIALIZED VIEW command to clean up the residual metadata for the materialized view. Then use the CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW statement to re-create the materialized view. Thereafter, use the DROP MATERIALIZED VIEW command rather than the DROP TABLE command to drop a materialized view.

column6: the specified refresh method is not supported in this context
column7: The refresh method that was specified is not currently supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a different refresh method or change the context to enable support of the chosen refresh method.

column6: this PL/SQL function cannot be supported for query rewrite
column7: The statement referenced a PL/SQL function that is not marked DETERMINISTIC.
column8:
From Oracle doc: Perform one of the following actions: 

Remove the use of the PL/SQL function. 

Mark the PL/SQL function as DETERMINISTIC. 

Disable the REWRITE option on the materialized view. 

The function should be marked DETERMINISTIC only if it always returns the same result value for any given set of input argument values, regardless of any database state or session state. Do not mark the function as DETERMINISTIC if it has any meaningful side-effects.

column6: summary and materialized view are not in same schema
column7: An internal error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: Query rewrite is not supported on SYS materialized views
column7: An attempt was made to enable the REWRITE option on a materialized view in the SYS schema.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the materialized view in a different schema or disable the REWRITE option.

column6: REF not supported with query rewrite
column7: The statement contained a REF operator. Repeatable behavior cannot be guaranteed with the REF operator. Therefore, query rewrite cannot support the REF operator.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the reference to the REF operator or disable the REWRITE option on the materialized view.

column6: unrecognized %s type
column7: An internal error occurred.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: dimension column cannot be a sequence
column7: The dimension statement referenced a column that is a sequence.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the reference to the sequence.

column6: columns in a dimension column list must be in the same relation
column7: The dimension statement contained a column list where the columns are not all from the same relation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the list of columns using only columns from a single relation.

column6: this level has the same set of columns as another
column7: The level definition contained the same set of columns as another level.
column8: From Oracle doc: Eliminate the redundant level definition.

column6: left relation in the JOIN KEY clause cannot be same as right
column7: The relation of the child columns on the left side of the JOIN KEY clause was the same as that of the parent level on the right side.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove the JOIN KEY clause. It is not required or allowed when the child and the parent are in the same relation.

column6: child JOIN KEY columns not in same relation as child level
column7: The relation of the child columns on the left side of the JOIN KEY clause differed from that of that child level.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the correct child columns in the JOIN KEY clause.

column6: a JOIN KEY clause is required
column7: A JOIN KEY clause was omitted in a dimension statement. A JOIN KEY clause is required when the child level and the parent level are not in the same relation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify a JOIN KEY clause to indicate how the relation of the child level joins to the relation of the parent level.

column6: ATTRIBUTE cannot determine column in a different relation
column7: An ATTRIBUTE clause in a dimension statement specified a determined column on the right that is in a different relation than that of the level on the left.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify attributes only for those dimension levels that functionally determine other columns within the same relation.

column6: maximum number of columns is 32
column7: A list of columns was specified using more than 32 columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Specify the list using no more than 32 columns.

column6: set operators are not supported in this context
column7: A set operator such as UNION, UNION ALL, INTERSECT, or MINUS was encountered in an unsupported context, such as in a materialized view definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-specify the expression to avoid the use of set operators.

column6: column cannot define a level in more than one dimension
column7: A column was used in the definition of a level after it had already been used to define a level in a different dimension.
column8: From Oracle doc: Reorganize dimension levels and hierarchies into a single dimension such that no column is used to define levels in different dimensions. There is no limit on the number of levels or hierarchies you can place in a dimension. A column can be used to define any number of levels provided all such levels are in the same dimension and provided no two levels contain identical sets of columns.

column6: fine grain access policy conflicts with materialized view
column7: A fine grain access control procedure has applied a non-null policy to the query for the materialized view.
column8: From Oracle doc: In order for the materialized view to work correctly, any fine grain access control procedure in effect for the query must return a null policy when the materialized view is being created or refreshed. This may be done by ensuring that the usernames for the creator, owner, and invoker of refresh procedures for the materialized view all receive a null policy by the user-written fine grain access control procedures.

column6: object data types are not supported in this context
column7: An object data type was encountered in an unsupported context, such as in a materialized view definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Re-specify the expression to avoid the use of objects.

column6: list does not contain any valid summaries
column7: List is empty or does not contain the names of existing summaries.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the list of names passed to refresh contains the name of at least one existing summary object

column6: refresh method must be ANY or INCREMENTAL or FORCE_FULL, not %s
column7: An invalid refresh method was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the refresh method is one of 'ANY' or 'INCREMENTAL' or 'FORCE_FULL'.

column6: summary '%s.%s' is in INVALID state
column7: The summary is in INVALID state and cannot be refreshed.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: '%s.%s' is not a summary
column7: There is no such summary, therefore it cannot be refreshed.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify the correct name of the summary.

column6: refresh method must be one of FC?AN, not '%s'
column7: An invalid refresh method was specified.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that the refresh method is one of 'FC?AN'.

column6: job_queue_processes must be non-zero in order to refresh summaries
column7: The server must be started with parameter JOB_QUEUE_PROCESSES greater than zero.
column8: From Oracle doc: Correct the value of JOB_QUEUE_PROCESSES and restart the server instance.

column6: unable to open named pipe '%s'
column7: The refresh process was unable to open a named pipe to the job queue process usually because of insufficient system resources. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: all job queue processes have stopped running
column7: All of the job queue processes used by refresh have stopped for some reason. At least one job queue process must be running in order to refresh summaries. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: unable to access named pipe '%s'
column7: The refresh process was unable to access a named pipe to the job queue process after it successfully opened the pipe. This usually indicates an internal or operating system error condition. This is an internal error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: refresh of '%s.%s' failed because of %s
column7: The refresh job queue process encountered an error and is reporting it. The accompanying text of the message indicates cause of the error.
column8: From Oracle doc: Varies, depending upon the reported cause.

column6: refresh_after_errors was TRUE, and one or more errors occurred
column7: One or more errors occurred during a refresh of multiple summaries.
column8: From Oracle doc: The NUMBER_OF_FAILURES parameter returns the count of how many failures occurred. The trace logs for each refresh operation describe the each individual failure in more detail.

column6: internal error
column7: An internal error was detected by the summary refresh subsystem, and aborted the refresh operation.
column8: From Oracle doc: Contact Oracle Customer Support.

column6: cannot compute AVG(X), VARIANCE(X) or STDDEV(X), without COUNT(X) or SUM(X)
column7: Incremental refresh of summaries requires a COUNT(X) column in order to incrementally refresh AVG(X). It requires both SUM(X) and COUNT(X) columns in order to in refresh STDDEV(X) or VARIANCE(X).
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the required columns are part of the summary definition if incremental refresh capability is desired.

column6: summary contains AVG without corresponding COUNT
column7: Incremental refresh of summaries with AVG(X) requires a COUNT(X) column to be included in the summary definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the required columns are part of the summary definition if incremental refresh capability is desired.

column6: summary contains STDDEV without corresponding SUM & COUNT
column7: Incremental refresh of summaries with STDDEV(X) requires COUNT(X) and SUM(X) columns to be included in the summary definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the required columns are part of the summary definition if incremental refresh capability is desired.

column6: summary contains VARIANCE without corresponding SUM & COUNT
column7: Incremental refresh of summaries with VARIANCE(X) requires COUNT(X) and SUM(X) columns to be included in the summary definition.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the required columns are part of the summary definition if incremental refresh capability is desired.

column6: '%s.%s' cannot be refreshed because of insufficient privilege
column7: The user lacks one or more permissions that are required in order to refresh summaries.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that the user is granted all required privileges.

column6: '%s.%s' cannot be refreshed because of unmnanaged NOT NULL columns in container
column7: The container object for the summary contains one or more unmanaged columns do not allow nulls, and which do not specify a default value for those columns.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure that default values are specified for all NOT NULL columns that are not part of the summary definition.

column6: '%s.%s' cannot be refreshed because the refresh mask is %s
column7: An attempt was made to incrementally refresh a summary that is not incrementally refreshable.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to incrementally refresh the summary; use full refresh instead.

column6: '%s.%s' cannot be refreshed because the refresh method is NONE
column7: An attempt was made to refresh a summary whose refresh method is NONE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Summaries whose refresh method is NONE (NEVER REFRESH) cannot be refreshed. Alter the summary to change the default refresh method from NONE to some other value.

column6: '%s.%s' cannot be refreshed because it is marked UNUSABLE
column7: An attempt was made to refresh a summary which is UNUSABLE.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine why the summary is UNUSABLE, re-enable it, and retry the refresh.

column6: '%s.%s' cannot be refreshed because it is marked DISABLED
column7: An attempt was made to refresh a summary which is DISABLED.
column8: From Oracle doc: Determine why the summary is DISABLED, re-enable it, and retry the refresh.

column6: unsupported operator: %s
column7: An attempt was made to refresh a summary containing an unsupported operator.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that all columns of the summary contain expressions that are refreshable.

column6: '%s' is not a detail table of any summary
column7: The list of tables passed to REFRESH_DEPENDENT contains at least one invalid table name. That table is not a detail table of any summary and is therefore an invalid input to REFRESH_DEPENDENT.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify the correct name of all tables in the list.

column6: no summaries exist
column7: A call was made to REFRESH_ALL_MVIEWS, but no summaries exist. At least one summary must exist before calling REFRESH_ALL_MVIEWS.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create one or more summaries.

column6: feature not enabled: %s
column7: The specified feature is not enabled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to use this feature.

column6: PLAN_TABLE does not exist in the user's schema
column7: Estimate_Summary_Size uses Oracle SQL "EXPLAIN PLAN" command to estimate cardinality of the specified select-clause. This requires a table called the PLAN_TABLE in the user's schema. For more information, refer to Oracle8i SQL Reference.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the PLAN_TABLE as described for EXPLAIN PLAN. On most systems a script UTLXPLAN.SQL will create this table.

column6: The input select_clause is incorrectly specified
column7: The input select-clause parameter to Estimate_Summary_Size is incorrectly specified and cannot be compiled.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the syntax of the select-clause.

column6: Specified dimension does not exist
column7: The specified dimension to be verified does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Check the spelling of the dimension name.

column6: Summary Advisor error%s
column7: An error has occurred in the Summary Advisor package. This message will be followed by a second message giving more details about the nature of the error.
column8: From Oracle doc: See the Summary Advisor documentation for an explanation of the second error message.

column6: DISTINCT option not allowed with GROUP BY CUBE or ROLLUP
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: GROUPING function only supported with GROUP BY CUBE or ROLLUP
column7: No description available.
column8: From Oracle doc: No action defined.

column6: database open triggers and server error triggers cannot have BEFORE type
column7: An attempt was made to create a trigger that fires before the database is open or before server errors, but these types of triggers are not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to create a trigger that fires before the database is open or before server errors.

column6: instance shutdown triggers cannot have AFTER type
column7: An attempt was made to create a trigger that fires after an instance shutdown, but this type of trigger is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to create a trigger that fires after an instance shutdown.

column6: system triggers cannot have INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE as triggering events
column7: An attempt was made to create a system trigger with INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE triggering events, but this type of trigger is not supported because a system trigger does not have a base table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to create a system trigger with INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE triggering events.

column6: system triggers cannot have a REFERENCING clause
column7: An attempt was made to use a REFERENCING clause with a system trigger, but this type of trigger is not supported because a system triggers does not have a base table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use a REFERENCING clause with a system trigger.

column6: system triggers cannot have a FOR EACH ROW clause
column7: An attempt was made to use a FOR EACH ROW clause with a system trigger, but this type of trigger is not supported because a system triggers does not have a base table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not use a FOR EACH ROW clause with a system trigger.

column6: system triggers should not reference a column in a WHEN clause
column7: An attempt was made to use a WHEN clause to reference a column with a system trigger, but this type of trigger is not supported because a system trigger does not have a base table.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the WHEN clause to an appropriate clause.

column6: system triggers cannot be based on tables or views
column7: An attempt was made to base a system trigger on a table or a view.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the type of the trigger is compatible with the base object.

column6: normal triggers cannot be based on a schema or a database
column7: An attempt was made to base a normal trigger on a schema or a database, but normal triggers can be based only on tables or views.
column8: From Oracle doc: Make sure the type of the trigger is compatible with the base object.

column6: client logon triggers cannot have BEFORE type
column7: An attempt was made to create a trigger that fires before logon. This type of trigger is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to create a trigger that fires before logon.

column6: client logoff triggers cannot have AFTER type
column7: An attempt was made to create a trigger that fires after logoff. This type of trigger is not supported.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to create a trigger that fires after logoff.

column6: system triggers cannot be defined on the schema of SYS user
column7: An attempt was made to define a system trigger on the schema of SYS user. This type of trigger is not supported currently.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not attempt to create a system trigger defined on the schema of SYS user.

column6: invalid DDL operation in system triggers
column7: An attempt was made to perform an invalid DDL operation in a system trigger. Most DDL operations currently are not supported in system triggers. The only currently supported DDL operations are table operations and ALTER?COMPILE operations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Remove invalid DDL operations in system triggers.

column6: cannot modify %s.%s more than once in a transaction
column7: An attempt was made to modify an object more than once in a transaction. This error is usually caused by a DDL statement that fires a system trigger that tries to modify the same object. It can also happen when an attempt is made to perform more than one DDL operation on a queue table in the same transaction without issuing a commit between operations.
column8: From Oracle doc: Do not create system triggers that might modify an already modified object. Also, do not specify more than one DDL operation on a queue table in the same transaction.

column6: cannot create system triggers of INSTEAD OF type
column7: Only BEFORE or AFTER triggers can be created on system events.
column8: From Oracle doc: Change the trigger type to BEFORE or AFTER.

column6: system trigger cannot modify tablespace being made read only
column7: A beofre trigger tries to modify a tablespace which is being made READ ONLY as the part of DDL oepration.
column8: From Oracle doc: Modify the trigger to avoid modifications to the objects in the same tablespace as the one which is being made read only, or use autonomous transactions to commit modifications.

column6: index depends on a package/function spec/body which is not valid
column7: The functional indexes depend on some invalid/non-existent package/function specification/body.
column8: From Oracle doc: Verify that all the package/functions which the index depends on exist and are valid.

column6: The index depends on a package/type body which does not exist
column7: The functional indexes depend on a package/type body which does not exist.
column8: From Oracle doc: Create the package/type body.

column6: The package/procedure/function cannot be changed
column7: The package/procedure/function is deterministic and some object depends on it.
column8: From Oracle doc: Drop the other object which depends on the package/function/procedure you are trying to change.

column6: The function is not deterministic
column7: The function on which the index is defined is not deterministic.
column8: From Oracle doc: Mark the function deterministic.

column6: function-based index %s.%s is disabled

column6: Performance degradation of process instance %s due to failed locality optimization.
column7: Due to an invalid configuration (relation of number of CPUs, system boards and process instances) or hardware failure, it is not possible to perform the locality optimization for process instance %s. This will result in significant performance degradation of this process instance.
column8: For clearing of this invalid configuration it is recommended to consult Technical Service. If this alarm appears only for one or few process instances of one process group, it is likely that one or more CPUs have failed in the system or have been taken offline. Verify the status of the CPUs and replace failed CPUs or take offline CPUs online. If this alarm appears for all process instances of one process group, typically, there is a misconfiguration regarding the number of CPUs, the number of system boards and the number of process instances (not conform to TPD). Make sure that the number of CPUs in the system is a whole-number multiple of the number of process instances and that there are at least as many process instances as system boards. Other configurations are not supported by the feature 'locality optimization'. Note: On multi-core CPUs the term 'CPU' refers to one core of the CPU. On CPUs with CMT (chip multi-threading) it refers to one hardware thread of one core.

column6: Wrong filer id %s (in logical directory %s, expected %s).
column7:
The mentioned logical directory is polled for new campus batch orders.
 It is located on a filer. All farms connected to a campus DB should 
 also be connected to a single filer. When executing orders it was 
 detected that this farm node is connected to a different filer (by 
 comparing its unique filer id with the expected value).
column8:
Please check if the same filer is mounted for the mentioned logical
 directory on all farm nodes belonging to the campus. If the filer id
 is missing it can be re-created by executing a restart of the 
 application processes as described in the Installation and 
 Configuration Guide.

column6: Log type %s has reached fill level 1 (%s percent).
column7:
Log messages of the Unified Platform are stored in a local repository
 until they are collected by the Log Management Application of the
 Unified Commander EMS.
 There is a log type specific maximum number of messages being stored in
 the repository. If the repository is filled up to this level the oldest
 log messages are deleted to store further entries. This results in log
 messages being lost.
 This alarm is generated if the configured fill level 1 is reached for a
 log type. Further alarms are sent if fill level 2 is reached and when
 the maximum fill level is exceeded.
column8:
Please use the Log Management Application of the Unified Commander EMS to
 export these log entries to external storage space.

column6: Log type %s has reached fill level 2 (%s percent).
column7:
Log messages of the Unified Platform are stored in a local repository
 until they are collected by the Log Management Application of the
 Unified Commander EMS.
 There is a log type specific maximum number of messages being stored in
 the repository. If the repository is filled up to this level the oldest
 log messages are deleted to store further entries. This results in log
 messages being lost.
 This alarm is generated if the configured fill level 2 is reached for a
 log type. A further alarm is sent when the maximum fill level is exceeded.
column8:
Please use the Log Management Application of the Unified Commander EMS to
 export these log entries to external storage space.

column6: Log type %s has reached the maximum fill level (%s percent). Data is lost!
column7:
Log messages of the Unified Platform are stored in a local repository
 until they are collected by the Log Management Application of the
 Unified Commander EMS. There is a log type specific maximum number of
 messages being stored in the repository.
 The repository now is filled up. The oldest log messages are being deleted
 to store further entries. These deleted log messages are lost.
column8:
Please use the Log Management Application of the Unified Commander EMS to
 export these log entries to external storage space.

column6: Log type %s has sunken below fill level 2 (%s percent).
column7:
Log messages of the Unified Platform are stored in a local repository
 until they are collected by the Log Management Application of the
 Unified Commander EMS.
 There is a log type specific maximum number of messages being stored in
 the repository. If the repository is filled up to this level the oldest
 log messages are deleted to store further entries. This results in log
 messages being lost.
 An alarm had been generated because the configured fill level 2 had been
 reached for the mentioned log type. But now the repository fill level has
 sunken below fill level 2 again.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Log type %s has sunken below fill level 1 (%s percent).
column7:
Log messages of the Unified Platform are stored in a local repository
 until they are collected by the Log Management Application of the
 Unified Commander EMS.
 There is a log type specific maximum number of messages being stored in
 the repository. If the repository is filled up to this level the oldest
 log messages are deleted to store further entries. This results in log
 messages being lost.
 An alarm had been generated because the configured fill level 1 had been
 reached for the mentioned log type. But now the repository fill level has
 sunken below this warning level again.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Log type %s has sunken below the maximum fill level (%s percent).
column7:
Log messages of the Unified Platform are stored in a local repository
 until they are collected by the Log Management Application of the
 Unified Commander EMS.
 There is a log type specific maximum number of messages being stored in
 the repository. The repository had been filled up to this level and the
 oldest log messages had been deleted to store further entries.
 But now the fill level has sunken below the maximum and log messages are
 no longer deleted.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Limit ID %s has reached %s %% of %s.

 If need be, please contact the Vendor Service staff.

column6: Limit ID %s is below %s %% of %s.

column8: No action necessary.

column6: Limitation of limit ID %s under-runs its TrafficGrant.
column7:
The traffic load reduction for limit ID %s on node %s
 necessitates to under-run its configured TrafficGrant value.
 The current CPU load exceeds the specified threshold limit
 of %s %%.
column8:
In case the alarm situation does frequently occur one has
 to ascertain the reason why the processor load lies ongoing
 at the configured maximum capacity.
 Also verify the configured traffic grant values and the
 priorities for their feasibility resp. plausibility.
 If need be, please contact the Vendor Service staff.

column6: TrafficGrant capacity of limit ID %s is provided again.
column7:
The traffic grant capacity value of limit ID %s
 on node %s is provided again. The specified CPU
 load threshold of %s %% is kept.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Campus license limit %s has reached %s %% of %s.
column7:
The campus traffic rate has exceeded the minor threshold of 
 the license limit. If the rate reaches the license limit the
 traffic will be blocked.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Campus license limit %s is below %s %% of %s.
column7:
The campus traffic is below the minor 
 license limit again.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Campus license limit %s has reached %s %% of %s.
column7:
The campus traffic has exceeded the major threshold of the 
 license limit. If the traffic rate reaches the license 
 limit, incoming traffic will be blocked, leading to call 
 failures.
column8:
Please purchase additional license capacity if more traffic
 shall be handled.

column6: Campus license limit %s is below %s %% of %s.
column7:
The campus traffic rate is below the major threshold

column8: No action necessary.

column8: No action necessary.

column6: Campus license limit %s has reached %s %% of %s.
column7:
The campus traffic has exceeded the license limit.
 Incoming traffic in top of the license limit will be

column8:
Please purchase additional license capacity if more traffic

column6: Campus license limit %s is below %s %% of %s.
column7:
The campus traffic rate is below the license limit

column8: No action necessary.

column6: User '%s' has been locked.
column7:
Locked users are not allowed to log in.
 The mentioned user has been locked because the threshold for faulty logins
 has been reached. Further logins will fail until the user is unlocked
 again.
column8:
The user may be unlocked by a privileged user through an administrative
 action in the user management access function of the appropriate
 application or in the Unified Platform Local User Management GUI.

column6: User '%s' has been unlocked.
column7:
The mentioned user has been unlocked through an administrative action.
 Login is now possible again.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: OS and/ or FTAC properties of user '%s' have been recovered.
column7:
UMF users may be assigned OS login accounts or FTAC profiles. These OS
 and/ or FTAC properties of the mentioned user have been recovered.
 This happens if the OS account or FTAC profile have been deleted by direct
 administration on OS level.
 The rights of the reconstructed OS account/ FTAC profile have been reset
 to a default minimum. The previous settings of the OS account or FTAC
 profile are lost. The user has been locked also.
column8:
Take an administrative action to repeat the configuration of the user's OS
 account/ FTAC profile and to unlock the user.
 This must be done by a privileged user in the user management access
 function of the appropriate application or in the Unified Platform Local User
 Management GUI.

column6: Vendor/ network operator '%s' has been locked temporarily.
column7:
The mentioned user is not allowed to log in for the configured time
 (default 10 min). The lock has been applied because the threshold for
 faulty logins has been reached.
 This user is a customer with business organization type vendor or network
 operator. Such privileged users will only be locked temporarily.
column8: No action necessary.

column6:
Overload condition detected: overload protection for ticket import has been 
 activated.
column7:
Ticket files from remote systems are transfered to local directories for
 further processing. This ticket import is currently exceeding the
 processing capacity of the local system and the file system has filled up
 to a critical usage limit (%s percent).
 The ticket import directories have been locked to avoid further transfer
 of ticket files. This means that transfers from remote systems probably
 fail at the moment.
 If the file system usage sinks below %s percent the
 ticket file transfer will be unblocked automatically.
column8:
The transfer of new ticket files originating from remote systems should
 be interrupted. It may be continued when this alarm is reset.

column6: Overload condition passed. Ticket import has been unblocked.
column7:
The diskspace usage of the file system used for importing ticket files has
 reached an uncritical level again (below %s percent). The ticket import
 directories have been unlocked.
column8: The transfer of ticket files from remote systems may be continued now.

column6: An FTAC profile user with duplicated transfer admission has been found.
column7:
The FTAC Profile of the user %s has a transfer admission duplicated and it 
 is locked. This can occur if another user uses the same password.
column8:
The owner of the the locked FTAC profile must login in at Unified Platform Local User
 Management GUI and change its password.

column6: Password of user '%s' will expire in %s days.
column7:
The password of the user of shown domain will expire in some days. 
 It should be changed by the user.  If an OS user is associated with 
 this user (e.g. if this is a Batch user), login will be disabled for 
 that when the password expires.
column8: The user should change his password using product interfaces.

column6: Password change is no longer necessary for user '%s'.
column7: Password change is no longer necessary for the user.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Password of user '%s' has expired.
column7:
The password of the user of shown domain has expired. It must be 
 changed by the user during next login. If an OS user is associated 
 with this user (e.g. if this is a Batch user), login has been 
 disabled for that.
column8: The user should change his password using product interfaces.

column6: Password change is no longer necessary for user '%s'.
column7: Password change is no longer necessary for the user.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Missing keys for use case '%s' (within %s days for %s applications).
column7:
Secure system operation requires activated key data for the
 Key Management Function (KMG) use case mentioned. The system is
 configured to find needed key data in the KMG repository. Currently for
 some of these KMG applications or KMG keysets key data is not available or will be
 missing (due to expiration) within the mentioned number of days.
column8:
Provide the system with the needed keys. Correction of this situation is
 supported by the Key Management Batch (KMB) operation 'queryKeyAvailability',
 the KMB client support tooling and KeyManagement GUI. Please consult the manual
 'ADMN:Security Management' for descriptions of KMG use case specific
 procedures to resolve the problem.

column6: Key data now available for use case '%s'.
column7: All needed keys of the use case '%s' have been activated.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: Untested keys in use case '%s' (within %s days for %s applications).
column7:
Untested key data will be activated for the KMG use case mentioned for
 certain KMG applications. Tested key data is or has been previously
 available. Usage of untested key data may result in partial system
 outage. At the latest, within the number of days mentioned, untested
 key data for this use case will be activated for the number of
 applications mentioned because the activation period of tested key
 sets ends.
column8:
Execute the key data testing procedure with the Key Management
 command line interface (KMG CLI) tool. Please consult the Security
 Management manual for further information.

column6: Tested key data now available for use case '%s'.
column7: Tested key data is available in all applications of use case '%s'.
column8: No action necessary.

column6: License file with serialNbr %s expires in %s days.
column7:
Certain system functionality is only available if properly licensed from
 the software vendor. Software licenses may expire in part or completely.
 The currently activated license contains license items that will
 expire within the mentioned number of days. The protected system
 functionality then will not be available any further.
column8:
The state and contents of the system software license can be checked
 with the 'AdvKmgTool' Key Management command line tool. A new or extended
 software license may be purchased from the software vendor.

column6: Software license expiration has been resolved.
column7:
The complete or partial expiration of the software license has been
 resolved. None of the license items will expire within the supervised
 period of time.
column8: No action necessary.

column8: If there was a software installation activity within the last 24 hours then this can be expected. Otherwise please check the differences in the log file carefully.

column6: PCS terminated as initialization failed: %s
column7: PCS detected a fatal failure during initialization.i.e, before it has reported its successfully initialization to the TSP, PCS process stopped. This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#50) on PCS startup.Since a PCS process is automatically re-started few times,the alarm is repeated possibly
column8: If the alarm is caused by an invalid value of a PCS configuration parameter (for name and valid values, see variable part of alarm text), try to use the configuration management to set the parameter to a valid value and restart the process via process management.Otherwise, contace the PCS service

column6: PCS initialized with severe functional restriction: %s
column7: PCS detected a non-fatal failure during initialization.i.e, before it has reported its successful initialization to the TSP. PCS process did not stop. This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#50) on PCS startup.
column8: If the alarm is caused by an invalid value of a PCS configuration parameter (for name and valid values, see variable part of alarm text), try to use the configuration management to set the parameter to a valid value and restart the process via process management.Otherwise, contace the PCS service

column6: PCS initialized with functional restriction: %s
column7: PCS detected a non-fatal failure during initialization.i.e, before it has reported its successful initialization to the TSP. PCS process did not stop. This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#50) on PCS startup.
column8: If the alarm is caused by an invalid value of a PCS configuration parameter (for name and valid values, see variable part of alarm text), try to use the configuration management to set the parameter to a valid value and restart the process via process management.Otherwise, contace the PCS service

column6: PCS terminated due to failure: %s
column7: PCS detected a fatal failure.PCS process stopped.This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#50) on PCS startup. Since a PCS process is automatically re-started few times, the alarm can be repeated
column8: Contact the PCS service

column6: PCS working with severe functional restriction: %s

column6: PCS overload control: Load level of %s increased to ABOVE_NORMAL
column7: The load level of a certain PCS resource increased to ABOVE_NORMAL.On this level and above, tracing is switch off(except error tracing).This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#58) when the load level decreases to NORMAL
column8: If the alarm frequently occurs or is not cleared automatically after a short time, reduce load.e.g, message rate on affected external interface, or ask the PCS service for a PCS variant with higher capacity

column6: PCS overload control: Load level of %s increased to HIGH
column7: The load level of a certain PCS resource increased to HIGH.On this level and above, tracing is switch off(except error tracing), and incoming requests for creating or modifying session are rejected. This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#58 or #59) when the load level of the same resource decreases to ABOVE_NORMAL or below
column8: If the alarm frequently occurs or is not cleared automatically after a short time, reduce load.e.g, message rate on affected external interface, or ask the PCS service for a PCS variant with higher capacity

column6: PCS overload control: Load level of %s increased to CRITICAL
column7: The load level of a certain PCS resource increased to CRITICAL.On this level and above, tracing is switch off(except error tracing), and incoming requests for creating or modifying session are rejected. This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#58, #59 or #60) when the load level of the same resource decreases to HIGH or below
column8: If the alarm frequently occurs or is not cleared automatically after a short time, reduce load.e.g, message rate on affected external interface, or ask the PCS service for a PCS variant with higher capacity

column6: PCS overload control: Load level of %s increased to VERY_CRITICAL
column7: The load level of a certain PCS resource increased to VERY_CRITICAL.On this level and above, tracing is switch off(except error tracing), and incoming requests for creating or modifying session are rejected. This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#58, #59, #60 or #61) when the load level of the same resource decreases to CRITICAL or below
column8: If the alarm frequently occurs or is not cleared automatically after a short time, reduce load.e.g, message rate on affected external interface, or ask the PCS service for a PCS variant with higher capacity

column6: PCS %s limit reached: %s
column7: A PCS resource was exhausted temporarily. This alarm is cleared automatically by a clearing event(#62) when a sufficient portion of the resource is available again
column8: If this alarm frequently occurs or is not cleared automatically after a short time, reduce load, e.g., message rate on affected external interfaces, or ask the PCS service for a PCS variant with higher capacity

column6: Context data will be lost on PCS stop. Enable onlineMigrationEnabled to avoid.
column7: The PCS/Core/sessionDataSurviveShutdown configuration parameter has been set to RtpFalse. This means that the context(session data) of the PCS process will be deleted when the process will stop
column8: If you want that the context (session data) of the PCS process is saved and will be available on re-start of the PCS process, set the PCS/Core/onlineMigrationEnabled configuration parameter to RtpTrue via configuration management

column6: PCS rejected %s from %s: %s
column7: PCS reject a connection request from a peer, an initial message of a connection(e.g. a Diameter Capability Exchange Request or a COPS Client Open), or an initial message of a connectionless association from a peer. This alarm is automatically cleared by a clearing event(#66) when a connection or connectionless association to the same peer is successfully established(this includes a successfully initial message exchange on application level.e,g Diameter capability exchange or first Radius Request and Response)
column8: See info in alarm text. In particular, if it indicates a PCS Manager configuration issue, check that configuration

column6: PCS lost %s to %s: %s
column7: PCS detected that an established connection or connectionless association to a peer is no longer available.This alarm is automatically cleared by a clearing event(#66) when a new connection or connectionless association to the same peer is successfully established(this includes a successfully initial message exchange on application level.e,g Diameter capability exchange or first Radius Request and Response)
column8: See info in alarm text

column6: PCS terminated %s to %s:  %s

column8: See info in alarm text
